<body background="/esoup/gif/a137.jpg" text="#FFFFFF" link="#00FFFF" vlink="#FF80FF">
<h1 align=center><a name="Teachers and Staff"><U>Electric Soup</U> Teachers and Staff as Writers</a></h1>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/twilight.jpg" align=right width=218 height=147>Pieces in this Volume Include:</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Master's"><STRONG>Master's Thesis</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Elizabeth Downing</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Discovery"><STRONG>Discovery</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Catherine Jensen</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Milkweed"><STRONG>Milkweed</STRONG></a><STRONG> by John Smith</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Daedulus's payment"><STRONG>Daedalus' Payment</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Florence McGinn</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#My Trusty Steed"><STRONG>My Trusty Steed (Green Monte Carlo)</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dan VanAntwerp</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#The Good Rose"><STRONG>The Good Rose</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Jeannie Gobillot</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv3toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 3 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<pre><a name="Master's"><STRONG>Editor's Note:  Creative writing is of great importance to our </STRONG></a><STRONG>
teachers and staff, but their writing is not confined to the 
creative area. Teachers and staff explore the area of academic 
writing, too.  In this issue, in addition to poetry, we present 
for you an intriguing excerpt from a master's thesis.  
</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Elizabeth Downing is an English teacher and a Chinese language 
teacher at HCRHS.  Her master's thesis prepared for Columbia 
University was an original translation of a segment of a Buddhist 
sutra in four chuan from Chinese into English.  Ms. Downing 
utilized the Visesacintibrahma pariprccha which was translated 
from Sanskrit into Chinese by Kumarajiva in 402 A.D.  The 
following material is excerpted from Ms. Downing's thesis work; 
these intriguing, brief excerpts from her in-depth, scholarly 
study and translation work introduce Kumarajiva as well as 
influences upon the formation of Tibetan Lamanism.  

</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     Kumarajiva (344-413 A.D.) was born in Serindia where there
were both Indian and Chinese influences.  He is counted in the
Madhyamika tradition as descending directly from Magarjuna, the
founder of the sect.  He received his education in Northern India. 
Initially he studied Hinayana texts, but he was converted to
Mahayana after a lecture by Suryasoma, a renowned Mahayana
scholar.  By the time he was forty, he had become a famous
Mahayana teacher in his own right. 
     In 383, a Chinese expeditionary force seized Kumarajiva and
carried him away as captive.  He was held at the Later Liang Court
for almost twenty years studying Chinese.  When the Later Chin
conquered Liang in 401, he was welcomed into the court.  He spent
the rest of his life in Ch'ang-an teaching his disciples and 
translating texts.  He is credited with translating more than 100 
titles . . . 
     Historically, Tibet has had two, major Buddhist influences, 
the Indian Madhyamika and the Chinese Ch'an.  In addition to these 
two Buddhist influences, the native Bon-po Shamanism played a large
part in the formation of Tibetan Lamanism.  The first Buddhist
temples were built in Tibet during the reign of Songtsen Gampo d.
A.D. 649, who also founded Lhasa and established the official 
Tibetan alphabet . . . 
     Songtsen Gampo's marriage to both a Chinese and a Nepalese
Buddhist woman served to increase national patronage of Buddhism. 
Both women were devout Buddhists and encouraged the development
of Buddhism in Tibet.  Buddhism thrived in the mid 7th century in
Tibet, but it suffered a setback later in the century when a 
smallpox epidemic broke out, and the Chinese wife of Songtsen 
Gampo was one of the victims.  Her death was interpreted as an 
omen that Chinese Buddhism was inauspicious, and it was 
subsequently suppressed . . . 
     Sino-Tibetan relations were symbolically renewed once again
by the marriage of the Tibetan King Ki-li-nou-si-long to the 
Chinese princess Chin Ch'eng in 740 . . . There is controversy 
about the lineage of the princess who was sent to Tibet, and 
exactly which Tibetan king she married, but it is agreed that she 
married a Tibetan king, bore him a son, and died in 739 A.D.  
     It was during the reign of her son, Khri-sron-Ide-bcan that 
the Council of Lhasa was held.  Conflict between Ch'an and 
Madhyamika teachings led to this official debate at Sam-ye, the 
first Buddhist monastery of Tibet.  The king ordered the debates 
and summoned an official representative from each of the schools.  
Kamalsila represented the Indian Madhyamika school   He was a 
native of India, and one of the major figures of Madhyamkia 
Buddhism at that time . . . 
     The Indian Buddhist contingent headed by Kamlsila was
proclaimed the victor and Chinese Buddhism was banned in Tibet. 
One of the texts most often cited in the course of the debates was 
the Visecacintibrahma pariprcca, a Madhyamika text concerned with
methods of attaining Buddha-hood and other points essential to the
difference between Madhyamika and Ch'an ideology.  </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     According to Ms. Downing's manuscript, the pivotal role of 
the Buddhist sutra, Visesacintribrahma pariprccha in The Council 
of Lhasa's official debate intrigued her.  Her interest in its 
dramatic influences became one of her reasons for  its selection 
as the topic of her thesis and her work upon its translation.  
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<pre><center><a name="Discovery"><STRONG>Discovery </STRONG></a><STRONG>
by Catherine Jensen, English Teacher 
               </STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>               
               I've found some sound, 
               With pen in hand 
               and men on mind with flowers, 
               words jump down, thoughts rise. 
               While I stand in bed I see 
               what's happening to me. 
               I'm showering in movement, 
               watching evolution shake an echo 
               in my head.  I signal to those people. 
               They have leapt into the picture 
               of the words I'm writing down
               about chrysanthemums 
               and jumping men 
               and sound.  
                        </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><center><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>M</STRONG><a name="Milkweed"><STRONG>ilkweed
</STRONG></a><STRONG>by John Smith, English Teacher</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I picked a milkweed plant from a field alongside the highway 
stuck it in an old vinegar bottle on my kitchen table, and waited 
for one of the fruits to shrivel, dry, and split open 
so I could count how many seeds, piled like match heads with silk
sticks, 
were packed inside a single pod. 
I watched the slit widened from the base of the shells 
haphazardly stacked at the top of the stalk, 
and spread to the tip of each capsule. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>It was the slowest opening I ever witnessed, the softest shedding.
Whenever someone walked by 
or undid a window anywhere in the house, 
the white hairs would begin trembling, 
peel from the gray pouch, and tumble on the breeze. 
I lost count, but there were over a hundred and fifty seeds
and it took days for one casing to empty.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I brought the milkweed to school.
I wanted to know who, among the passing between bells,
would notice a plant bottled in the doorway 
and not be able to help but stop for a second, risk being tardy, 
just to stroke the silk tuft with a fingertip, 
maybe even pinch a brown-headed seed 
from a pod by the white strands of hair, 
then dangle it in front pursed lips 
as if whistling a secret while making a wish.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I wanted to know how long it would take for the hallway to fill 
with feathery spheres
and a whole school of heads turn to watch dozens of frayed
parachutes float -- 
no, bob above them like wild promises. 
I wanted everyone to dip and weave like the silk-threaded seeds 
rushed between scissoring legs, 
caught up and spun by a sudden draft, 
twirling around all four walls, and careening off the milky-green 
tiles on the way to physics or geometry. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>What s there to wish for if not that a hallway of fluorescent 
lighting and fiber optics 
quietly converts into a snowy  field? 
What learning s worth chasing more, as it swerves in and out of the
lockers, 
than the one we can clasp in our hands? 
How far have we come if we aren't struck downy and transported by
the world around us,
if we can t stop sheltering the seeds planted inside and open our 
lives to the wind; 
spark into class late, but blazing, or better yet, turn at the 
first exit sign we find, 
burst through the fire doors into the outside, and climb the sky? </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<pre><center><a name="Daedulus's payment"><STRONG>Daedalus' Payment</STRONG></a><STRONG>
Written by Florence McGinn, English Teacher</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>          In Pieter Brueghel the Elder's painting, Landscape with
          Fall of Icarus, young Icarus plummets into the sea within
          sight of land .
          </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                   
                 Brueghel painted gouged eye socket truth.  
                 Boyish Icarus, wrapped in a garment
                 of father-built wings and feathers, 
                 broke journeyed silence only twice.  
                 Once, with a cry of genetic exuberance 
                 echoing out from above slow motion clouds.  
                 Second, in a glittering, final song 
                 honed on wisdom's bare knife edge.
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Boyhood's fall came within sight of land.  
                 Rose flesh lips were damp with cloud-taste 
                 when ocean's deep belly split 
                 in brief welcome.  Icarus vanished  
                 with plowed fields skimming 
                 across sun-dimmed retinas.
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Daedalus' toes must have scraped 
                 in screaming curl against leather sandals 
                 already pressed in secure glory 
                 against cropped grass and sandy earth.
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Daedalus' soaring, sky vault vision
                 tilted earthward following a human 
                 cormorant's dive like basalt flint 
                 sheering air and white-capped water.
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Victory is forever divided. 
                 Fullness builds on another's 
                 emptiness.  Standing in harvest gold
                 beckons winter's pallored cold.
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Old Daedalus, didn't you always know
                 the gods would exact raw payment?                 </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<pre><center><a name="My Trusty Steed"><STRONG>My Trusty Steed (Green Monte Carlo) </STRONG></a><STRONG>
by Dan VanAntwerp, English Teacher 
              </STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Through the icy, wet morning 
                 I expect you 
                 To carry me . . . 
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 In spite of
                 Your doors, which 
                 Neigh shrilly, 
                 Reminding of your countless journeys, 
                 And the ghostly outlines on the windshield, 
                 Marking your stops along the way.  
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Giving you no credit for 
                 Your lima-bean carpet, 
                 Mucky with rainy Mondays, 
                 Bristling with the sandy grit 
                 of Forgotten Summers, 
                 </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                 Or the lingering staleness 
                 Of While Owls and Marlboros, 
                 Smelling of the countless 
                 Red lights and logjams 
                 You waited out, 
                 Fuming impatient white smoke 
                 Like a proud stallion 
                 . . . To my desperate destination
                 Once more.                  </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<pre><center><a name="The Good Rose"><STRONG>The Good Rose</STRONG></a><STRONG> <img src="/esoup/gif/goodrose.jpg" align=right width=102 height=46>
Written by Jeannie Gobillot 
</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Whispers of spring, gentle and
chaste. 
Warm, musty earth, dew lies
suspended, 
Pausing -- a time to embrace. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Shears in my pants, I head for
my roses. 
Molding, charging, nurturing,
pruning. 
Delicious agony -- what to trim! </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Vines thriving, richness. 
Looking ahead to blushing blooms, 
Blazing moons on fire -- yellow, gold, pink 
Hodgepodge of colors. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Velvet leaves, thorns ready to bite. 
Angel Face, Comanche, Friendship, Mikado, 
Here's Peace, Love, Honor, Cherish. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Hoe the earth, reflect, meditate, 
To give is to gain, 
To love, often labor. 
To sweat, to create! </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>My roses flourish, maturing and glowing. 
Humbled, I toil with my brother 
Whose ashes lie under that soil.  </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Teachers and Staff"><STRONG>Return to Teachers and Staff Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
