<h1 align=center><a name="short stories"><STRONG><U>Electric Soup</U></STRONG><STRONG> Short Stories</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
</STRONG></h1>
<p align=center><STRONG><br>
&quot;A book should serve as an ax <br>
for the frozen sea within us.&quot; <br>
Franz Kafka</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/aarbry.jpg" align=left width=248 height=168>Pieces in this volume include</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#heart of"><STRONG>Heart of the Neocromancer</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dan DiMicco </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#wolf"><STRONG>Wolf</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Brooke Hennessey </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><br>
<br>
<img src="/esoup/gif/pr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h2><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/danpipe.jpg" align=right width=221 height=197></STRONG><a name="heart of"><STRONG><br>
<br>
Heart of the Necromancer</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
 by Dan DiMicco -<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h2>
<pre><STRONG>     The twilight of the hour was showing through the land. 
There was a stillness about everything. Everything seemed out of 
place--the trees, the foliage, and the warrior. The panting grew 
louder, the footsteps harder and the air wetter.
     The warrior was clad in the shreds of a dirt-covered robe. 
Her rags were barely hanging onto her back. She had been whipped by
her captor many times.
     The dense fog that covered the ground swirled around her. 
She was lost in a place she did not understand. She turned her 
head to see if it was following her, but there was nothing in back 
of her.
     The warrior turned around to face a cloaked figure dressed in
black. She studied her adversary closely, to find a weakness, but 
there were none. She could not tell who he was, or what he was. 
All she could see was an evil glint in his eye.
     The cloaked figure moved his hand in a deliberate gesture. 
The warrior collapsed to the ground. Her eyes glowed a fiery red. 
Her long flowing hair began to shrivel up around her neck. Her 
skin began to boil and welts formed on her body.
     The cloaked figure crackled, &quot;Goodbye, Heart of the Warrior.&quot;
     She moaned, &quot;I . . . will never . . . die.&quot;
     With her last words, she fell to the ground, her body now red
and shriveled. A great warrior was dead. The air began to dance
around the cloaked figure's head. The trees gained life back into
them. His job was done - for now. There were still others he had 
to eradicate.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     Far from the eternal resting place of the warrior,  another
one like her was resting at a tavern.  His armor was carefully 
polished and attended to.  His plate mail bore the insignia of a 
cross with two swords Xed around it, the symbol of a Zenith Warrior.
His sword at his side was like no other.  It had no stain of ever 
being used.  The handle of the sword was perfectly carved for his 
hand.  The gleam of .the sword would catch every thief's eyes.  Yet
one of that art would not dare to touch it.
     Another woman across the bar had the same insignia on her
necklace.  She was very young looking and had the eyes of a master
sorceress.  She was dressed in brightly covered robes.  She only 
had one weapon, a quarter staff.  It, too, was crafted for her use.
     In a flash of an eye, each warrior collapsed to the ground. 
They began to shake and quiver like the one warrior who died before
them.
     In unison they screamed, &quot;I . . . will never . . . die.&quot;
     At that instant, their eyes were red with revenge and horror.  
For a moment, their souls were linked with the fallen warrior.  The
tavern had died while looking at the two.  Everyone was staring,
wondering what to do.  
     One lone drinker commented, &quot;Let them die.&quot;
     After what seemed like an eternity for the two warriors, they
got up.  The man got up slowly, quivering with every heartbeat.  
The woman got up quicker, her actions like those of a cat.
     He slowly made his way over to the other warrior, intrigued by
their link.  Was she one?  Or was she merely trying to deceive him?</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     &quot;Hello, my lady.  I saw you in agony, as I was.  I thought I 
was the last Zenith, but now I am not so sure.  My name is Celestial
Hawk.&quot;
     &quot;Hello, sir.   I, too thought I was the last one alive.  I 
guess we are never alone.  My name is Magena.&quot;
     Celestial Hawk carefully studied Magena.  She was a very
powerful sorceress.  She had bags of unknown contents, robes of
bright colors and amulets swung about her neck.  She was beautiful,
everything about her led Celestial Hawk to believe she was the
ultimate sorceress.  One necklace caught his attention.  She 
noticed his eyes and brought the necklace from her bosom.  It was 
the symbol of the Zenith.
     Celestial Hawk carefully places his hand upon the amulet.  It
glowed a like the sun and his hand began to feel warm.  The Zenith
symbol on his armor glowed in response.  They both were one of a
kind.  Each with the same quest - to destroy the black mage.
     He spoke carefully, &quot;I believe one of us has fallen.  Do you
know who did this?&quot;
     &quot;I felt the power of a masterful wizard.  Possibly our eternal
enemy.&quot;
     &quot;I was afraid of this.  I do not think I am ready to face this
challenge.  But I can no longer wait.  The others must be avenged.&quot;
     &quot;What do you mean you're not ready?  And that you can no
longer wait?  We must work together.&quot;
     Celestial Hawk mumbled, &quot;Hmm... you may be correct, but for
now, let's get some sleep.  We have an arduous journey before us.&quot;
     The two of them went out of the tavern and looked around. 
The town was barren at night;  all the lights were turned low in 
the shops.  The only other place open besides the tavern was an 
inn.  It was too dark for them to see the name or the condition of 
the inn. They paid for two separate rooms and went off to bed.  
They each drifted into a sleep with the thoughts of what was to 
lie ahead.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#short stories"><STRONG>Return to Short Stories Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/pr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h2><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/brooke.jpg" align=middle width=201 height=153></STRONG><a name="wolf"><STRONG>Wolf</STRONG></a><STRONG> - by Brooke Hennessy -<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h2>
<pre><STRONG>     Cananjui is half-wolf and half dog.  He is beautiful in every 
sense of the word.  Death-black eyes wrapped in ice, yet soft and 
comforting.  His soul is the best thing about him, always alive, 
forgiving, and just like Cananjui. 
     Cananjui is very independent, for a half-breed that I call my
pet, anyway.  He lives off sheep from my ranch in Montana.  I don't
mind really.  Ours is always an exchange.  Sheep for protection, no
matter what kind.  Cananjui would always protect me to the best of
his abilities. 
     Cananjui sleeps on the other side of a perimeter fence
surrounding the ranch, always looking into the forest.  My loving 
cat, George, started sleeping and riding around on Cananjui's back 
when he was about two.  They're the best of friends, separated 
only when Cananjui goes into the forest with his brother, the Wolf.  
     I found Cananjui in a winter storm that could choke a polar
bear.  He lay just inside the perimeter fence snuggled next to his 
dead mother's body.  This spot would mark a series of events to 
come -- the farthest northeastern spot on the ranch, where the 
fence meets in a corner, near an ancient maple tree. 
     She was a wolf, but I could tell by Cananjui's full face, long
tail, and wide chest that he had domesticated blood in his veins.  
For months I fed Cananjui, for he would not hunt, but he was too 
young to hunt anyway.  He never played with other pups on the ranch,
keeping to himself, that is, until George came along. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     One day, about four years after I adopted Cananjui, a wolf
pack attempted to crash through the perimeter fence in the old
northeast corner where Cananjui's mother is buried.  Cananjui
jumped in front of their path, a half-breed with no experience in
violent matters.  The wolves attacked with no regret or thought 
to the situation -- it was just their way, and they felt that they 
had to defend themselves.  Cananjui knew he didn't have a chance 
and using the trick I had foreseen as being valuable to him, he 
played dead.  The pack turned their backs ready to return to the 
forest, disinterested with my ranch and the sheep it held. 
     As I watched, Cananjui quietly stalked the leader, then flew
through the air, his jaws locking around the wolf neck.  This wolf 
was buried near to Cananjui's mother, and eventually his son, Canon,
would be buried near the old maple tree, too.  I think that 
Cananjui's mother would have been proud. 
     The wolves howled at Cananjui, inducting him in as the new
leader of their pack.  Cananjui calmly turned around and walked
home to greet George, who was just arriving back at the ranch from 
a trip to the veterinarian.  
     The wolves returned every night, just past sunset.  They would
howl and howl until Cananjui would finally place George gently
inside the fence and trot off to be with his wolves for the night. 
Cananjui was my dog, yet he belonged to the wolf pack.  He 
protected me, George, and my ranch.  Still, the wolves were his 
true family, soulmates, regardless of his half-breed status. 
     Every morning just before dawn, Cananjui would crawl under
the fence, place George on his back with gentle yet powerful teeth,
and walk the length of the perimeter fence, like on a patrol.  
George and Cananjui almost seemed to talk to each other, like 
silent friends, who already knew what they had to say to one 
another. 
     Once, near the end, in spring, Cananjui brought a female wolf
back to the ranch.  She stayed only for a week, and I was sure 
that she had been impregnated.  George was acting strange, and 
for weeks after the female left, he stayed on my bed, basking in 
my solitary affection.  Those nights, Cananjui would abandon his 
pack earlier and come stand about twenty feet from my bedroom 
window.  He would stay there until I left the house to do the 
morning chores, then disappear until the next morning.  Finally, 
came the morning that both Cananjui and I had been hoping for.  As 
I opened the door to leave to do chores, George ran out in front of
me and leapt onto Cananjui's back.  Obviously, George was ready to 
forgive and forget, and Cananjui seemed even more relieved than I 
was.  
     George was not permitted to be out of Cananjui's sight for a
week.  George, however, never slept anywhere but in my bed from
then on. 
     The female wolf, whom I had named Canoka, returned that
fall, after her springtime mating.  She brought another male wolf,
named Cretydon, son of the wolf that Cananjui had killed.  It 
seemed that there was going to be a fight, for love and leadership.
Canoka sat near George under the great maple tree in the 
northeastern corner of the ranch, where the perimeter fence met in 
a corner where Cretydon's father and Cananjui's mother are buried. 
     George ran from the sight of Canoka, up into the great maple,
on a low branch near a squirrel.  He crouched and waited. 
     Canoka seemed to be in pain, and I looked at her firmly,
willing my mind to see her troubles.  Suddenly, I realized that 
she had started her hour of travail. 
     Cretydon lunged at Cananjui, straight at his throat.  Cananjui
now knew what he did not when Cretydon's father was killed.  He
knew how to fight, hunt, and that young wolves were often fools. 
     Cananjui whipped around, sweeping dirt into Cretydon's face
with his large tail.  Cananjui turned again and was taken by 
surprise when the wind was knocked out of him, and he was staring 
up at the sky.  
     Cretydon started to growl, walking slowly, menacingly toward
Cananjui.  Just as he bent to Cananjui's throat, George flew from 
his place on the great maple tree, onto Cretydon's head, shredding 
his eyes with well-sharpened claws.  Cretydon turned in circles 
many times, still intoxicated with adrenaline from the fight.  He 
yearned for death, to smell the carcass of the first wolf he would 
kill.  Cretydon, now blind, staggered for a moment, and then, with 
full confidence, lunged at his final target. 
     Canoka is buried next to Cananjui's mother, nearly fifteen 
feet from where Cretydon lies in the ground.  Cananjui had killed
Cretydon so quickly that I had thought, rather foolishly, that he 
had died from the eye wounds that George had inflicted.  If not for
the blood lining Cananjui's mouth, I would have documented that 
George had murdered Cretydon. 
     Canoka's cubs were saved by me, four beautiful boys, half-
breeds, yes, but still wolves at heart.  When Cananjui dies, the 
eldest brother will become leader of the pack.  His name is 
Cheyenne, and he is destined to be great friends with George's son,
and they will come to remind me of the relationship between George 
and Cananjui. 
     The other cubs have left the ranch.  Cananjui brought a
female, whom I have name Wily, the next morning to take the cubs to
the pack and to raise as her own. 
     George remains Cananjui's friend to this day.  Cananjui does
not care that George unwittingly killed Canoka, only remembering
that George saved his life from Cretydon.  George still sleeps 
with me every night.  Just after sunset, George, Cananjui, and 
Cheyenne walk the perimeter fence, on patrol.   Cananjui delivers 
George to me, and he trots off into the night with his son.  </STRONG></pre>
