<h1><a name="philosophical essays"><U>Electric Soup</U> Philosophical Essays</a></h1>
<p><STRONG>I would write one true sentence <br>
<img src="/esoup/gif/robi.jpg" align=right width=281 height=222>and then go on from there.<br>
--Ernest Hemingway</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#celts "><STRONG>Celts and Christians</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Christine Pasun </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#what causes civilization"><STRONG>What Causes Civilization, What Makes a Person Civilized?</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Thor Solberg</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG>                                   --Robi Mookerjee,
					 Freelance Art Director</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/rd_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></pre>
<h3><a name="celts "><STRONG>Celts and Christians </STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Christine Pasun </STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     In Europe around the seventh and eighth century B.C., there
was a group of highly religious barbarians called the Celts.  Their
territory was stretched from the British Isles to Turkey.  Even 
though they were referred to as barbarians, they had a great amount
of good qualities.  They were close to nature, believed in an 
afterlife, treated women equally, and were great artisans.  When 
the Christians came, most notably St. Patrick, the Celts were 
forced to abandon their beliefs and adopt new ones.  The Christians
disrupted the life of the ancient Celts and made them lose harmony 
between themselves and nature.  They were in touch with the earth 
and, therefore, better off before they were forced to convert.
     The Celts were able to spread into Gaul, the Iberian Peninsula,
north Italy, the Balkans, Asia Minor, Britain, Scotland, Wales and
Ireland.  They also settled in Italy, France, Germany, and
Switzerland. In Ireland, as well as the rest of the Celtic 
dominated areas, the tribes were &quot;not unified politically but...by 
culture and language&quot; (Embassy 1). One of the earliest tribes were 
the Hallstatt Celts.  They were able to create weapons and 
household instruments from iron instead of bronze, which made them 
last longer.  In Anne Ross' </STRONG><STRONG><U>Man, Myth and Magic</U></STRONG><STRONG>, it's stated that 
&quot;new skills in horse rearing and management..., combined with 
better weapons and perhaps innovations in methods of warfare, 
helped the Hallstatt warriors to establish supremacy over a wide 
area&quot; (439).  Other groups, besides the Hallstatts, were also able 
to dominate large areas. Even though this is true, &quot;in the end most 
of the Celts were conquered by the well organized legions of Rome, 
and later by the fury of the Franks, Alamanni and other Germanic 
groups as well as the Anglo-Saxons&quot; (Hamblin 6).   Sometimes seen as 
&quot;big, tall, hairy types who loved wine and war, seemed happy and 
hardy enough to sleep on the ground, and scared the daylights out of 
anybody not that tough&quot;(Hamblin 2), it's hard to believe that the 
Celts were very religious.
     Nature and religion were closely intertwined in the Celtic 
society.  The Celts were in touch with the earth, referring to the
female and the male half as the Great Mother and the Horned God
respectively. They named their months after trees, and were able to
use the sun and stars to plan their years (Conway 82-83).  Dora
Hamblin in the Smithsonian states that &quot;rather than copying nature
and life, they [the ancient Celts] interpreted it&quot; (3).  This shows
that they understood what was around them, and adjusted so it fit 
into their life.  The Druids, who performed most of the religious
ceremonies, used oak and mistletoe as an important part of their
rituals.  It is said that &quot;the word Druid itself may be related to 
daur, the Celtic word for oak tree&quot; (Littleton 1).  Many of their 
gods and goddesses were believed to control different parts of the 
natural world.  One example is the goddess Flidais.  She was goddess
of the forests, woodlands, and other wild things.  She was also a 
shape-shifter, and rode in a chariot drawn by deer (Conway 110).  
The Christians didn't believe in having any more than one almighty 
God and, therefore, attempted to convert the Celts from polytheism 
to monotheism.  It was hard for the Celts to get rid of all their 
many gods and goddesses and believe only one supreme being 
controlled everything.  Many of them weren't able to, and they 
still harbored the idols inside their homes even after they 
&quot;converted&quot; to Christianity.
     The Celts harbored an afterlife belief that was very different
from the Christian's.  Heaven and Hell didn't exist to the Celts. 
Unlike other religions &quot;the otherworld of the Celts, was a world of
magic rather than a world of formal doctrine and inflexible deities;
a world which mattered in everyday life rather than at religious 
feasts and periodical rituals alone; a world not of gloom but of 
gaiety&quot; (Ross 444). There wasn't any form of purgatory, as in 
Christians beliefs, because they didn't believe that you were 
punished after you died.  Pigs, or boars, were one of the favorite 
foods of the Celts, and their love of this is reflected in part of 
the otherworld feast.  It is said that the feast is &quot;sustained by 
magical pigs which, no matter how often they are cooked and eaten, 
are whole and alive again the next day, ready for the next feast&quot; 
(Ross 443).  There was also belief in reincarnation and 
transmigration, returning as an animal or plant.  When they died, 
they were buried in tombs with many possessions believed to be 
needed in the next world. 
     Near the town of Hallstatt (named for the Hallstatt Celts) in
upper Austria, diggers uncovered a gigantic cemetery.  In the tombs
there were many things a person might need when going into a new
world.  There was jewelry, clothing, beds, weapons, carts, and
miniature boats (Hamblin, 3).  Anne Ross tells that &quot;the burials 
were elaborate, being under a mound, in a wooden chamber usually 
made of oak.  They were furnished with richly decorated weapons and
personal ornaments, many of them bearing symbols which we
know...had a religious significance&quot; (439).  Christians believe in 
the phrase 'you can't take it with you' after you died because they
believe that Heaven has everything you want, and since Hell is 
punishment, you don't have to worry about getting any extras.  
     Celtic women didn't have to worry about equality as much as
Christian women did.  In many Christian religions, women were
thought of as possessions instead of equals.   Women weren't able 
to hold important positions, such as priests, they were only able 
to be nuns. The Celtic equivalent of priests were Druids, but there
was a female order like Druids called Dryads.  The Dryads were 
believed to be in existence before the Druids, originally a part of
the very old goddess religion (Conway 77).  In Celtic society there
were &quot;reports of flaxen-haired females who brandished swords and fought
besides their men&quot; (Hamblin 4).  The Christian crusades, men were 
the only ones who were supposed to fight.  Women were supposed to 
stay at home and tend to all the stereotypical housewife chores, 
fighting was the man's job.   Being allowed, and being able, to fight 
weren't the only ways that the Celtic women felt equality.  The Celts 
held family to be of great importance so women held power over men 
because of their ability to bare children.  One act that was 
encouraged was sexual promiscuity which the Christians tried to 
discontinue.  During Mai (May) the Celts honored the Great Mother 
and the Horned God of the woodlands by freely practicing sex.  They
wore green to honor the Great Mother at this time. In hopes that 
people, especially women, would stop this sexual promiscuity, 
Christians started, in vain, calling green an unlucky color.  
Virginity wasn't valued, and sexual activities were often encouraged
among the ancient Celts (Conway 83).
     Ancient Celts were master metal smiths, and craftsmen.  Their
most popular work includes complex, linear, intertwining symbols
that were sometimes used to deter the &quot;evil eye&quot;.  They were able 
turn everyday objects like swords, metal-embossed drinking vessels,
and decorative caldrons into works of art.  They also had their 
jewelry which included &quot;intricate fiblea, ornamental garment pins, 
often adroitly crafted into plant and animal forms.  Women wore 
rings, and wrist and ankle bracelets, and men sometimes sported 
heavy worked necklaces called torques, of bronze, silver or gold.&quot; 
(Hamblin 3)  In the Bible it says that God didn't allow jewelry or 
ornamentation of any type because that was a sign of pagan beliefs. 
The Christians probably tried to dissuade the Celts from wearing 
jewelry, but their efforts were probably didn't pan out.  The Celts
also carved stones with magical writing and figures, but Christians 
attempted to deface them by carving  religious figures, like the 
three wise men, to cover them.  As Dora Hamblin points out they 
also &quot;developed scythes for harvesting hay and the iron plowshare, 
invented the rotary flour mill and a sort of wheeled harvesting 
machine, [and] iron rims for chariot wheels&quot; (3).  They also invented 
a way to mine salt, which was very precious, by burrowing deep under 
the deposits and then mining their way back up to the surface.  They 
only used this difficult method when the surface conditions made it 
too dangerous for surface mining.
     The Celts mostly used oral tradition to pass on stories or
beliefs, so not much was written down.  Another reason is stated by
D.J. Conway.
	  &quot;St. Patrick personally burned almost 180
	  Irish books written in the Celtic language. 
	  This set an example for Christian zealots
	  who destroyed every piece of Druidic
	  literature they could find.  Christian
	  monk-scribes, for some unknown reason,
	  felt compelled to record the Celtic myths,
	  even while missionaries determinedly
	  stamped out belief in the ancient gods and
	  goddesses.&quot; (77)
If it wasn't for the monk-scribes probably all of 
the literature would be gone.  The Celts used an alphabet called 
the &quot;Ogham&quot;(pronounced owam), but they also used Greek frequently. 
After the Christians came in they forcibly replaced Ogham with 
Latin.  The Celts had knowledge of three languages and it is likely
that they wrote down their history and many of their legends 
(Conway 76).  One of the greatest contributions made by the Celts 
was the story of King Arthur of the Round table and Camelot.  The 
Celtic story was probably changed a little to make it more 
appealing.  No one wanted to hear a tale of &quot;some rude Celtic 
warrior&quot; but would rather have a tale of the &quot;chivalric head of a 
band of noble knights&quot; (Hamblin 6). Nobody knows if Arthur really 
lived but &quot;he was the greatest contribution the Celts made to 
world literature&quot; (Hamblin 6).
     The Christians may have tried to contribute to the betterment
of the world but ended up almost making a culture and religion
disappear by forcing conversion. The Celts were also known for
human and animal sacrafices, which is strictly forbidden in
Christianity.  The Celts at least had some agreements on what goes
into forming a society and religion.  Some points are the belief 
in a supreme power, belief in something occurring after death, and 
having a system of beliefs.  The ancient Celts would probably have 
been better off, and maybe have been able to form a country if the
Christians didn't come and Christianize everyone.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                       Works Cited
			     </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                             
Conway, D.J. Celtic Magic. St. Paul, Minnesota:Llewellyn, 1994</STRONG></pre>
