	1-3. Abstracted in  Countries of the world.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Hamblin, Dora Jane. &quot;Once Maligned, Celts Are Now Touted as the
	First Europeans.&quot;   Smithsonian, May, 1993, pp 118-125. 
	Replicated on SIRS &quot;Renaissance&quot;.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Littleton, Scott. &quot;Druids.&quot; The New Grolier Multimedia
	Encyclopedia, 1994.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Ross, Anne. &quot;Celts.&quot; Man, Myth and Magic (1970), Vol. 4, 437-444\
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#philosophical essays"><STRONG>Return to Philosophical Essays Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/rd_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></pre>
<h3><a name="what causes civilization"><STRONG>What Causes Civilization, What Makes a Person Civilized?</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
By Thor Solberg<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>   Throughout history, certain places referred to as civilized
have always existed.  Since the first use of the word, people have 
always wanted to live as a part of a civilization.  It was all 
Gilligan, Skipper, Ginger, and every other castaway on Gilligan's 
Island ever wanted. Although many definitions are associated with 
the word, civilized is a term, according to the American Heritage 
Dictionary by Houghlin Mifflin, which means &quot;to be efficient while 
polite or cultured;refined.&quot;
      A refined, efficient, cultured and polite society is not
constructed overnight.  Many factors, over time, together create a
civilized society.  Man has many needs and wants that are all vital
parts in the formation of a civilization.  The civilized man is 
not only a curious man, but also he is always wanting to know more,
always hungry for more knowledge.
     Man has a need to know the ways of the world; to be cultured. 
Occasionally, you will see a Dukes of Hazard loving &quot;redneck,&quot; who
still thinks the South won the Civil War.  This same person also 
wants nothing to do with any other place but his couch.   More 
often, people want to have knowledge about other places the world 
has to offer.  A more cultured person would much rather eat Italian 
food one day then try French food the next day and so on.  A less 
cultured person, however, would rather eat a grilled cheese sandwich
every day.  A cultured person always wants to extend themselves 
beyond their &quot;comfort zone&quot;; they want to take risks, travel to 
new places, try new things, make new acquaintances, and strive to 
understand the processes of other societies.   They, with their new
found information, feel the need to become more refined.  This 
leads to a need for the finer things in life, such as beauty.
     Beauty comes in many forms; it can be a piece of music or
perhaps a painting.  A painting for example, is not beautiful 
because it resembles to something lifelike, but for deeper reasons.
  It is easy for a refined man to see that a painting is a form of 
expression, and he will try to see the artist's deeper meaning.  
Another part of refinement, is being polite.  Someone who says 
&quot;excuse me,&quot; as opposed to &quot;move&quot; or &quot;outa my way,&quot; is without 
question much more polite.  This is much more refined, which makes 
it much more civilized.  Someone who is not polite is like a 
caveman dragging his woman into his cave, whereas  a person who is 
suave like James Bond is polite.  A refined and cultured person 
will also show sophistication.
     Yet sophistication is not an easy thing to explain.  This can 
be put into an equation by saying that cultured plus refined equals
sophistication.  In the above paragraph, I talked about James Bond 
as polite; he is also an example of a sophisticated man.  His many
worldly travels have made him cultured.   These travels lead to his
being refined and polite.  These are the effects that cause a man 
to be considered civilized.  
     Of course, for a civilized man to become efficient, something
must happen.  Man cannot become efficient on his own; part of
efficiency is working together.  A lack of cooperation is what lead
to the fall of the Roman Empire.  The empire became too large and 
it was not efficient.  People, noticing that the government was 
failing them, attempted to fix things themselves.  This lack of 
cooperation between citizens was the bane of the Roman Empire.  
All members of civilized societies must cooperate with others in 
the society, or nothing will ever get accomplished.  
     In order for man to join in the accomplishing of a common
goal, such as in a society, communication is a necessity.  Without 
a way for people to communicate with others in the society, the 
whole society would come crashing down.   That is not very 
civilized, so people make sure to communicate through many 
different methods. There are many methods of communication, such as
talking or sign language.  The more efficient the lines of 
communication, the more advanced the civilization.  This leads to 
the final piece needed to put together the puzzle of the civilized 
society, and it is simply, efficiency.
     Efficiency is very important because it is a way to get
everything done faster and easier.  Wars, an unavoidable part of 
any civilization, are won and lost on efficiency and technology.  
Although technology is not part of the definition of civilized, 
it should be.  It was the need for efficiency that lead to the 
creation of technology.  After all, anything that serves a purpose 
or makes something easier, or more efficient, is technology.   
When life is easier, it leaves the society more apt to do things 
for the betterment of that society.
     Man's need to be cultured leads to a need to have beauty, and
these together cause man to become sophisticated.  Being
sophisticated leads to man needing to cooperate with each other
toward a common goal.  The goal is efficiency.  These are simple
causes that when put together cause man and eventually a society to
become civilized.  In studying any society from the beginning of 
time until today, one will find all of the above factors present. 
     </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#philosophical essays"><STRONG>Return to Philosophical Essays Main Menu</STRONG></a><br>
