<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/poon.jpg" align=left width=169 height=172>                   </STRONG></pre>
<h3><a name="Grievances"><STRONG>Grievances</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Stephen Poon -<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>   Two-hundred, fifty-six dollars and thirty-four cents and a 
small dent - only monetary and physical harms.  The least and most 
irrelevant on my list of grievances.  But the worst was the stare 
of fallacy from all, and nothing for me but to stare back at myself.
	Their idle comforts told me it was a freak incident.  The 
fault of a patch of black, hungry, evil ice. But it s hard to point
 my finger at a frozen pool of rain when lives were at risk.  Not 
the safety of some nameless face but the blood of a friend.  Their 
bruises from the impact of metal, their pain from the shattered 
glass cutting into their skin, and my horror from their screams, 
their parents  screams, and my screams.  All too much guilt for a 
sound mind to rationalize.
	Luckily, the impact was nothing.  Only a smack from reality,
knocking me down from the pedestal of driving's bliss into another 
statistic.  A good laugh for them, a recurring nightmare for me.
	A photograph stapled to the inside of my eyelids: the 
incoming taillights gleaming redder than any stop sign ever could. 
Closer.  The break pedal no longer to be differentiated from the 
my foot.  Still closer.  The worried cries of my passenger drowned 
out by the screaming radio only increased the silence of my terror.
All happening too fast.  Too much time for a frightened mind.
	I ll walk next time.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/bl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG>
</pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/muir2.jpg" align=right width=143 height=211></STRONG><a name="Guardian"><STRONG>Guardian</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Ryan Muir -<br>
<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>   Looking up as they walked along, most people, 
as they passed beneath, only caught glimpses.  Although 
they looked often, only its position was noticed. 
Seeming to be so high in the air as to actually touch 
the heavens, most people didn't notice its cold, hard, 
face.  They could only guess at its smile, not knowing 
it to be twisted into an ironic and saddened thing.  
Most people didn't see how the light reflected 
perfectly off its smooth and polished white surface.  
Most people didn't care.
	Sometimes when a bird came down from its tiresome flight, 
perching a while on the shoulder to catch its breath, it would 
notice.  The white,unblemished surface only seemed to be entire. 
Sometimes if the bird would squint just right, it could make out 
the imperfection.  Down from that face of scorn and contempt, 
starting from those eyes of pity and deep sadness, ran two lines.  
Two crevices, as if a stream of molten lava had erupted from them, 
pouring forth and leaving only their scars behind as a reminder.  
But the bird, just having lit on the shoulder to rest, would
only notice these things in passing; for it was only a bird, not to
be bothered when those eyes weren't staring at and judging him.
	Every day and night, every hour of guardianship, the 
unnoticed saw.  It saw a black woman get beaten and mugged.  It 
saw countless drug deals on nameless street corners.  Once it even 
saw the president.  Those eyes saw everything.  So cold, so hard, 
so unrelenting, and yet so sad.  Most people didn't notice.  Most 
people didn't care.  And the bird finally has flown away.
		   </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/bl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG>
</pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/nancy.jpg" align=middle width=186 height=174></STRONG><a name="Burning Love"><STRONG>Burning Love</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Nancy Pawlick -<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Fire's burning.  Hot, intense flame, going higher, growing stronger.
The more you add to it, the bigger it grows.  Feeding the fire.  
Like watering a bush of fiery, red roses, fire grows.  It's like 
love, true love, when the more you put into it, the more you get 
back and the longer it lasts.
		   </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Fire has its dangerous side, too.  It can be damaging just as love 
can be.  Like water, you can drown.  It can hurt, it can burn, just
like the unwanted words from someone you love.  It's a feeling of 
being powerless and unwanted.  Like the harsh, pounding water 
that  puts the fire out, it can wash out the passion you have to
leave you with a dead emptiness.
		   </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>You must be careful not to play with fire.  Make sure the matches 
don't end up in the wrong hands, and don't let it get out of control.
		   </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/bl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG>
<STRONG>                  </STRONG></pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/tom.jpg" align=right width=256 height=192></STRONG><a name="Jesus Statue"><STRONG>The Jesus Statue</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Tom O'Connor <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>   Jesus was a statue, and he cast a shadow on the church.  His
molded features and slender fingers, a typical depiction of the 
resurrection.  But the lights from above were shining down, 
painting shadow pictures on the wall, and the statue kept the 
light away from what was behind it. And there, shadow arms were
straightened into sticks. And a dark body, long and gaunt, into 
two trees, two arms, legs, nails.  Two stories.
	And behind me, a young mother was busy disciplining her 
young son.  Telling him that the Bible wasn't a toy, shaking her 
hands into fists, finally causing the child to turn his cheek to 
her again, and then again.  More stories.
	My sister dyed her hair a different color today. Something 
new, because how often is what we're given good enough?  I can 
still see it though.  Silent.  Hiding quietly beneath the latest 
fad.  It cannot be washed away.  It is waiting, on her forehead, 
in a little girl smile.  It is now just a shadow of what once was, 
and now is just a memory, a story.
	I love my sister.  I've never thought otherwise, but what 
is it that keeps me from touching her?  What is it that stops the 
hug in my heart during peace-time, couldn't even touch her hand.  
So I asked God today for just the strength to hold my sister and 
tell her as much.  
	Jesus was a man, and every man casts a shadow.  There is a 
shadow inside the little boy behind me, beneath my sister's hair.  
In my heart.              </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/bl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gernay.jpg" align=middle width=179 height=211></STRONG></h3>
<h3><a name="Mood Swings of a River"><STRONG>Mood Swings of A River</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Ryan Gernay </STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>
	The river flows calmly and peacefully.  It greets its
surroundings with a warm hello.  The trout who inhabit this
river have a fairly easy time climbing upstream against the
gentle current of flowing water.  The reflection of the bright 
sunlight on the water causes it to appear to be sparkling,
and it adds to its aspect of friendliness and serenity.
	Then your mother comes home to find the house a mess.  
Dishes are stacked in the sink, the newspaper is strewn about on 
the floor, and paw prints are embedded in the sacred carpet in the 
living room.  The sparkle in her eyes dims down so low you know it's
not even there anymore. The current of the river becomes stronger, 
and tiny whitecaps begin to take shape.  Waves begin slapping the
unsuspecting  boulder faces which block their path.
	Your mother rushes upstairs to see the bathroom covered in 
a deluge of toothpaste.  The water is now surging forth at great 
speeds.  The trout are fighting a losing battle to get upstream.
	All the beds in the house have yet to be made, and she has 
finally reached the end of her rope.  The path of the river comes 
to an end and has no place to go but down. Water cascades over the 
side of the mountain and lands abruptly in the lagoon which has 
been waiting for it.
	She runs outside onto the patio to find her husband waiting 
for her at a candlelit table.  The path of the river proceeds from 
the lagoon and continues on its smooth course once again, the 
sparkles from the sun radiating on its surface.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/bl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/terrizzi.jpg" align=left width=194 height=116></STRONG><a name="Brewing Storm"><STRONG>A Brewing Storm</STRONG></a><STRONG> - Jessica Terrizzi -<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Fluffy white balls control precipitation and move swiftly across 
the serene blue sky.  Being pushed by forceful winds.  Unable to 
choose their own direction. Shaped, by various influences of 
nature.  No control over its form. 

Cute innocent creatures, the future of tomorrow, travel aimlessly 
down a common pathway. Manipulated by the dreams and images of the 
world.  Unable to express personal feelings or dream true dreams. 
No control over its form. 
 
Often, the soft cotton balls in the sky become aggravated with the 
temperamental winds.  Unified by determination, they unite to form 
an unbreakable chain.  As one, they plant themselves firmly in the
sky.  Together, the wind is powerless over them.  A ritual, during 
which built up tension and anger is released, occurs.

The younger generation has ideas which greatly vary from present 
day perceptions.  Adolescents are socially shunned fron the current
mainstream society.  Together, united as one, the youth will begin
a ritual.  

As frustrated clouds release their tension, the pushy wind steps 
down off its high pedestal. 
 
As silent demonstrations are held, the powerful leaders begin to 
feel their sturdily planted feet tremble.  An uproar is about the 
occur.  With interest now heightened, the hushed world begins to 
hear, with clarity, the once muffled sounds of its youth.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/whball.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Free Writes"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
