<h1><a name="collaborative short stories"><STRONG>Electric Soup Collaborative Short Stories</STRONG></a></h1>
<p align=center><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/mime.jpg" align=baseline width=186 height=169></STRONG></p>
<p align=center><STRONG>Miriam Pare: Collaborative Short Stories Editor</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Pieces in this volume include:</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Mars Federal Colony, Part 4"><STRONG>Mars Federal Colony</STRONG></a><STRONG>, Part 4: New Continuation by Lucy Robertson on original short 
story begun by Ryan McNamara with previous episodes added by Mike Fitch and Pat<br>
Clark.<br>
</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Mall Madness, Part 5"><STRONG>Mall Madness</STRONG></a><STRONG>, Part 5: New Continuation by Laura Kuznicki on original short story begun 
by Miriam Pare with previous episodes added by Nicole Baker, Meghan Bissett, and Laura 
Kuznicki.</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><img src="/esoup/gif/rd_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></pre>
<h3 align=center><a name="Mars Federal Colony, Part 4"><STRONG>Mars Federal Colony, Part 4<br>
</STRONG></a><STRONG>New continuation by Lucy Robertson</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     Lunging across the room and slamming on the intercom,
Andrews yelled, &quot;Armstrong, what's going on up there!!&quot;
     The captain's voice echoed across the panicked bridge, but
Commander Armstrong continued giving her original orders. 
&quot;Jeffries, take us off navigational control, and try to steer us 
out of the beam!  Ensign, figure out why this thing didn't show up 
before!! Go to red alert!&quot;  Only after the alarms sounded did she 
turn her attention back to the intercom and the Captain.
     &quot;Captain Andrews, sir, we appear to be trapped in some kind
of tractor beam, enemy vessel unknown.&quot;  The ship lurched to the
right as Lieutenant Jeffries engaged the starboard engines. 
&quot;Captain?  Captain!&quot;  There was no response.  &quot;Of course,&quot; she
muttered and ran to a computer.
     She disengaged the locks on the bridge doors, engaged
automatically during red alert, scant seconds before the captain
walked through, still pulling on his jacket.
     &quot;Report!&quot; he demanded as he strode towards another console.
     &quot;Sir,&quot; she began, approaching him and eyeing the display
screen, &quot;we are caught in a tractor beam from an unregistered vessel
and are attempting to free ourselves.&quot;  Just then the ship lurched 
to the left  but without further affect.  Jeffries grimaced and 
tried again.
     &quot;You don't appear to be having much success.  Why didn't
you inform me there was another ship in the area?&quot;
     &quot;It did not appear on our sensors until the beam was engaged. 
Ensign Torik, do you have an answer yet?&quot;
     &quot;Still working on it, Commander.&quot;
     Andrews frowned and advanced on the frantic Jeffries. 
&quot;Lieutenant, any progress?&quot; he asked in a calm voice.
     &quot;Just a minute, Sir,&quot; Jeffries rapped out, then threw the ship
to the side once more.  This time the motion did not stop, and they
shifted towards the side of the beam.
     &quot;Good work, Lieutenant.  Now keep it up.&quot;
     &quot;Aye, Sir!&quot;  Jeffries continued punching in directions as the
captain moved to stand behind Ensign Torik.
     &quot;Ensign, if you can't tell me who that is, can you at least 
tell me what it is?&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir--No, Sir.  The vessel does not appear to fit any
known, standard formats.&quot;
     The ship moved again, and Armstrong called out, &quot;Captain,
we're almost out of it!&quot;
     Andrews turned back to the expectant ensign.  &quot;Ready our
weapons.  As soon as we're out from under her, I want you to target
her aft engines and fire two missiles.  Understood?&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir!&quot;
     Captain Andrews moved over to stand beside the commander.
     &quot;What do you think, Sir?&quot;  Does this have something to do
with the colony?&quot; she asked carefully. 
     &quot;Most likely, Commander.  Most likely.&quot;
     Several seconds after, Jeffries slammed the ship into reverse,
and the hull creaked as it was ripped from the tractor beam.  
Andrews counted to three, then shouted, &quot;Now, Ensign!  Fire!!!&quot;
     Two missiles tore into the engines of the enemy ship, and with
a flash of light, the sensors went blank.
     Silence fell on the bridge for several seconds, until Andrews
spoke.  &quot;Torik, what just happened?&quot;
     Startled, the ensign lifted his hands back to the console and
checked his data.  &quot;Sir, our missiles made contact, and then--the 
ship just vanished.&quot;
     &quot;Just vanished?&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir.  That's the best I can tell you.  One second it was
there, and the next... Who knows.&quot;
     Andrews frowned and turned towards the Commander. 
&quot;Well, Armstrong, do you think we could have destroyed it?  With
only two missiles, meant to disable it?&quot;
     Slowly she shook her head.  &quot;Very doubtful, Captain.  In fact,
I'd expect to see our visitors again.&quot;
     &quot;Mind your tongue, Commander,&quot; warned Andrews, eyeing
the still nervous crew.  &quot;As it stands right now, we'll assume they
escaped.  Send an emergency message to Earth HQ--I want them to
know everything we've encountered so far.  Keep sending updates
every half hour.  We can't take any chances of being cut off.&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir.&quot;
     &quot;Jeffries!&quot; the Captain called.  &quot;Nice job.&quot;    The lieutenant
grinned and relaxed.
     &quot;Now, return to our original course--we'll continue on towards
the colony.  We've still got a mission to complete and paychecks to
earn.  And I want every one of you to relax.&quot;  He turned his gaze 
to the rest of the bridge crew.  &quot;No use tiring yourself out with 
worry.  If anything else happens, you'll know soon enough.&quot;
     Andrews turned to Armstrong.  &quot;Commander, have there been
any more developments in that message we keep receiving?&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir!  I meant to tell you as soon as you woke up.  If 
you'll follow me to the communications room . . . &quot;  She preceded 
him down the corridor, until they reached the brightly lit chamber.
     &quot;All of the pieces we couldn't decipher before?  They repeated
at regular intervals, and the computer started to put them together.
I think we've made enough to safely say it's one long message.  
Here-- see what you make of this.&quot;  She thrust a printout at him.
     His eyes widened as he read, his mind easily filling the gaps 
of the transmission.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>          UNIDENTIFIED VESSEL,--------VESS--PLEASE
IDENTIFY--------IDENTIFY      YOURSELF, OR-------FIRED UPON.  HALT
YOUR ADVANCE, DO-----CLOSER OR     YOU WILL--------TROYED. 
UNIDENTI-------YOU COPY?  DO YOU READ---N BACK    NOW!  TURN
BACK NOW!------WILL BE DESTROYED----NIDENTIFIED VESSEL,-------
     ---VESS, PLEASE IDENTIFY. . .
     </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     Armstrong looked up at his face, startled when he crumpled
the page.  &quot;What do you think?&quot;
     Grimly, he lowered the wad of paper.  &quot;I'd say it was the
colony warning somebody off.&quot;
     &quot;Our new friends?&quot;
     &quot;It looks that way, doesn't it?  And is this message is still
being repeated....  We've assumed that their communications were 
damaged in some way, yet they haven't been repaired yet.  That 
means no one is capable of repairing it.&quot;
     &quot;Or even alive to repair it,&quot; Armstrong murmured, grasping
his idea.  
     &quot;Right.  We can also assume that the colony fired on this
unidentified vessel, using the same weapons we just used, probably
with the same effect.&quot;
     They looked at each other, then up at the wall monitors
displaying the message.
     &quot;Should we keep going?&quot; she asked nervously.
     &quot;We have to know for sure.  I'd keep this conversation between
us for right now--we don't need to panic the crew.  But make sure 
you send our theory to Earth.  Forget about the next scheduled
transmission--I want it sent now!&quot;
     &quot;Yes, Sir!&quot;
     He ran his hands through his dark hair in frustration.  &quot;I'll 
go look over the colony's weapons--see what they might have used. 
Maybe it'll help us if we run into 'them' again.  Notify me at the
slightest change in status.&quot;  He brusquely turned and stalked back 
to his chamber, leaving her alone in the communications room.
     &quot;Aye, Sir,&quot; Commander Armstrong whispered.
     Several hours later, the Captain's pacing was interrupted by
the same bright light.  Immediately afterwards the ship was jerked 
to the side, and an explosion followed, knocking him, half-
conscious, to the ground.  When he finally regained his feet, he 
flipped on the intercom and called the bridge for a damage report. 
There was no response--he feared the worst. . .      
</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     What do you think happens next?  Contribute your ideas in
story form!
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#collaborative short stories"><STRONG>Return to Collaborative Short Stories Main Menu.</STRONG></a></p>
