<h1 align=center><a name="Alumnae"><STRONG><U>Electric Soup</U></STRONG><STRONG> Alumnae</STRONG></a></h1>
<p align=center><STRONG>I think I grow tensions <br>
like flowers <br>
in a wood where <br>
nobody goes. <br>
from Robert Creeley's &quot;The Flower&quot; </STRONG></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/pond.jpg" align=left width=320 height=240>                              </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#she-wolf"><STRONG>She Wolf</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Pat Sewak</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#rain never dreams of trees"><STRONG>rain never dreams of trees</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dara Badiak</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#rhythm of tomorrow"><STRONG>Rhythm of Tomorrow</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Michelle Lee Reeves</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="she-wolf"><STRONG>She-Wolf, Part 2</STRONG></a><STRONG>-- by Pat Sewak </STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>                                
	    In Part I of this saga by alumnae Pat Sewak, you
	    met a warrior named Lupus and the female warrior,
	    Octavia.  Octavia senses the wolf potential in Lupus
	    as she reveals her ability to shift form.  Lupus
	    initially remains wary, but Octavia wins his
	    involvement.  Read on as the tale of Octavia and
	    Lupus continues.   
					</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     Hours later, Octavia lay on the ground her head resting 
on her paws.  She looked at Lupus as he lay next to her, his tail 
curled around his hind quarters.  His fur was black, deep and rich
in its shade, and she knew that no normal man would ever be able to
spot this particular wolf at night.  His coat blended exquisitely 
well with the shadows.  Not that you have anything to fear from men,
oh, my dark one, she thought as she admired the bulky lines of his 
form.  You are magnificent, my rouge.  How many others of our kind 
have I run across, hoping to find a mate, yet only to find those 
who have corrupted their blood lines, and whose deficient seed 
produced no cubs.  But you, my Lupus, you, I think, will be 
different.  Nay, I know thee will be different, for I do believe 
that you are not exactly of my people, but of a different breed.  
Even now I know there will be cubs, a litter of young ones filled 
with your strength and vitality.  
     Lupus opened his eyes and buried his snout into the russet
colored fur that covered Octavia's neck.  She made a small sound in
her throat that was almost a purr.  Lupus rose off his belly onto 
his paws and shook out his fur.  Then he turned around and looked 
at Octavia. 
     She was fairly big, perhaps two and a half feet high at the
shoulder.  She was sleek and lean, much like her human form.  Her
fur was short and bristly and red in hue, reminding Lupus of the
flames of a fire.  Her eyes were still the same brilliant blue; 
however,they no longer smoldered, but they seemed to glow with a 
gentle warmth.  She walked towards him, and as is the way among 
wolves, she offered him her throat. 
     Lupus, instead of taking her throat and biting down on it to
show his dominance over her, slid his muzzle under her throat and
gently lifted her head back up.  Octavia turned and looked at Lupus,
her eyes wide.  The large black wolf only shook his head from side 
to side. 
     Octavia shuddered and began to change.  It was Lupus' turn to
watch wide eyed.  There was a sound like bones breaking, tendons
snapping, skin being stretched, as Octavia's entire form began to
remold itself.  Her paws became thinner and lengthened into fingers. 
Her muzzle became part of her face again, ears shifted back to 
human proportions and location.  Her fur receded within her flesh 
until all that was left was her long, tangled locks.  Then it was 
over. 
     Octavia rose to her feet.  Lupus shook himself again, and he
shifted form.  Where Octavia's entire body broke itself apart and
reformed the pieces into the desired shape, Lupus' body merely
became blurry.  There was no snap or crackle of rending bones or
flesh, merely a soft pop and whoosh.  His form unblurred and where
once a pony sized wolf stood, Lupus now stood erect. 
     &quot;What are you?&quot; Lupus asked. 
     &quot;I think I should be asking that question,&quot; Octavia replied. 
&quot;But, by the Silver Goddess, a man such as you I've never known.  I
am of the People of the Moon, a Child of the Wild.  I am what men
call a lycanthrope, a werewolf.&quot; 
     Lupus mulled this over as he stared at the stars.  Octavia came
over to him, wrapped her arms about him as she said, &quot;Lupus, come
with me.  I do not know exactly what you are, but I do know that I
could be happy with you for the rest of the time Artemis gives to me. 
Any pack would be honored to have such a warrior as you as a
member.  In fact, there are very few packs that you could not lead. 
We could roam across the continent, you and I.  What say you, my
dark one?  Will thou come with me?&quot; 
     Lupus sighed and turned around, gently grasping her chin in
his hand.  &quot;Octavia, all my life I have known no other like myself, and
now you tell me there is an entire race of people, who can change 
theirform between wolf and man.  I have known no woman like 
yourself.  I would be most honored to accept your offer . . . &quot;                                                     
	&quot;Good,&quot;  Octavia said as she reached up to kiss Lupus.  He
very gently pushed her away, again shaking his head. 
     &quot;You did not let me finish.  I would be most honored to accept
your offer, if I was able.  Sadly, I cannot.&quot;  Octavia's head 
lowered, and Lupus could tell by the shudder that ran through her 
that she was crestfallen by his reply.  &quot;I cannot go with you, 
wherever it is you wish to go.  I must stay with Nephilim.  This is
my sworn duty.  I gave my word of honor to Merlin that I would look
after the little runt. However, if you are able to, and as long as 
he doesn't mind, you are welcome to travel with us for as long as 
you like.&quot;  Lupus said, lifting her head up with his thumb and index
finger. 
     Octavia's eyes were bright.  Her lower lip trembled as two 
tears rolled down the sides of her face.  She shut her eyes and 
slowly shook her head from side to side. 
     &quot;No, I . . . I . . . I . . . can't go with you.  Even though 
my heart cries out that I should.  Every fiber of my being shouts 
at me to take your offer and your hand in my own and trod whatever 
paths your destiny bids you follow; I cannot.  Just as you have a 
duty and a vow to keep, so do I.  I am a Mage-hunter -- sworn to 
seek out those who weave magic and end their weaving forever.  
I must go my own way.  Our paths must part here, for anyone who 
grew up in the great Merlin's company must know many a mage, and I 
would not willingly slay any of your kin.  I must go and pray that 
our paths never cross again, oh, my dark one.&quot;  Octavia turned away
and began gathering her things up. 
     Lupus stood and watched her.  He walked over to her sword
and drew it from the earth.  He wiped the dirt from the blade.  He
approached her as she was buckling the last strap of her 
breastplate.  He held the sword out to her. 
     Octavia looked at him, took the sword from his hands, and
placed it in its scabbard.  She then gathered him to her with one 
arm and kissed him fiercely.  Again, she broke away from him and 
walked swiftly to her horse.  She mounted it with a graceful leap. 
She tossed him the  sheathed Spatha, and said, &quot;Here, take this as 
a token of my love for thee, for it will guard you while I cannot. 
Remember me, Lupus of the dark eyes, for I will remember you . . . 
always.&quot;  With this, Octavia wheeled her horse about and rode off 
into the early morning shadows.
     Lupus stood there for a long time.  He held the sheathed sword
in his left hand, watching the spot where he had last seen her.  
He let out a great sight and shook his head.  He half unsheathed 
the Spatha, gazing down at the runes inscribed on the blade.  A 
single tear fell from Lupus' cheek to splash upon the cold steel.  
His tear ran over the runes, which read: 
	     THE NAME OF THIS BLADE IS WYRMBANE.
     &quot;Sometimes, Neph, I wish I had never met you.  If you only
knew the sacrifices I make for you!  What I give up for you!  You 
and Merlin are the only family I've ever known, and I do not renege
on my word, but Odin take me for a fool if that wasn't the 
greatest woman I've ever met.&quot; 
     &quot;Lupus, shut up.  I'm trying to sleep,&quot;  Nephilim mumbled as
he rolled over.  &quot;Besides, she had red hair.  Your destiny lies 
with a black haired woman.&quot;  Nephilim started snoring softly again. 
     It was a long time before Lupus moved.  He finally slid the
blade back into the scabbard and returned to his spot by the tree,
waiting for the sun to rise, waiting for sleep to take him into 
her dark embrace. 

</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG>Did you enjoy the characters of Lupus and Octavia? Are you<br>
intrigued about Nephilim and his cryptic remarks? As readers, we<br>
can only hope that Patrick Sewak will sit down soon at his<br>
keyboard and continue this fine fantasy tale. <br>
<br>
<br>
<img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Alumnae"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/raintree.jpg" align=right width=320 height=240></p>
<h3><a name="rain never dreams of trees"><STRONG>rain never dreams of trees</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Dara Badiak <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>in this dry time
leaves hang limp as cloth from branches 
entire trees turn downward 
because they have given up on the sky 
they are worn out from so long 
begging for rain with palms raised </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>rain never asks for trees 
it does not care that salty tongues of root 
	are in love with it 
or even that they hate it when it doesn't 
	come 
it simply falls because that's what it wants to do </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>rain never dreams of trees when it sleeps 
but trees would tear themselves from the soil if they could 
and crawl miles in search of it 
ripping roots and dragging worms 
every wood fiber aching for its cold kisses </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>and trees die quietly for want of rain, now 
as clouds full of it drift silently away 
because the rain needs nothing as it wanders 
and it isn't even lonely 
with the whole earth, or nowhere, as its home </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Alumnae"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="rhythm of tomorrow"><STRONG>Rhythm of Tomorrow</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Michelle Lee Reeves <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Here we are but for a moment, 
At once so close, and then we drift apart. 
But always, ALWAYS, let us be connected, 
For without you, a part of me is lost. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Our rich heritage dictates the rhythm of tomorrow. 
We pass our values on to our children 
And let them adapt these to their own, 
So that each reunion will have a unique quality. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Perhaps many years pass between them, 
But once we're together again, time loses its meaning, 
And the lost days seem like moments 
On the calendar of life. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>We were meant to be together. 
Nothing can destroy our bonds. 
They're tied together by yesterday's memories 
Which are always revived when we meet. </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/orangeba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Alumnae"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
