<h1 align=center><a name="Community of Writers"><STRONG>Electric Soup Community of Writers</STRONG></a></h1>
<pre></pre>
<p><STRONG>Between my finger and my thumb<br>
The squat pen rests <br>
I'll dig with it<br>
Irish poet, Seamus Heaney<br>
<img src="/esoup/gif/laurak3.jpg" align=right width=243 height=185></STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#October Song"><STRONG>October Song, 1992</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Lissa Richardson </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Only Symphony"><STRONG>The Only Symphony</STRONG></a><STRONG> by John Smith </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#sylvia"><STRONG>Sylvia</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Jeannie Gobillot </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#once in a lifetime"><STRONG>Once in a Lifetime</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dan VanAntwerp </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Lessons"><STRONG>Lessons</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Florence McGinn</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11> </STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="October Song"><STRONG>October Song, 1992<br>
</STRONG></a><STRONG>by Lissa Richardson<br>
Ms. Richardson is a guidance counselor,who taught <br>
English for many years at HCRHS.<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>       This September, I stopped teaching.
       Now I have an office with no windows,
       And air conditioning,
       My own phone number,
       And sad gratitude for the peace.
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       But out in the world beyond my office
       My double rises up
       To teach my classes.
       It looks like me--doesn't know quite what to do with its
       hair,
       Seldom irons its clothes.
       My students are fooled.
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       Their sweet, open faces turn to the teacher,
       Twenty five expectant moons on a
       Hard horizon of desks.
       They whisper,  &quot;Teach us.  Tell us the secrets.&quot;
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       Which is what I could never do.
       I lost too many,
       To boredom and daydreams,
       To sunshine and snow.
       I lost suicides who shot themselves or ate poison pills or
         jumped from high places,
       I lost murderers--of strangers, of mothers--
       And miniature drunkards living up to the family promise.
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       I lost until I knew that I could not lose even one more 
       And salvage myself.
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       But this wonderful Monster Teacher
       Ascends in my room already flexed for the task,
       Wizard tongue to reach every ear, unending energy to call
       each mind
       Into the mystery.
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       So, I leave her there, hair electric and muscles singing,
       Telling all for which I had no language.
       And I will stay here in this unnatural room,
       Grateful, YES, And grieving helplessly for the 
       Twenty years of lost children
       And for the twenty years ahead without them.
       </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a><STRONG> </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/smith.jpg" align=left width=182 height=211></STRONG></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="Only Symphony"><STRONG>The Only Symphony</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by John Smith, English teacher <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>       Who among us, even now as I speak,  
       isn't falling, whether it be from the edge 
       of her seat; or standing, somehow inside
            himself
       at all times, who doesn't feel his heart 
            sink like a stone 
       through the soles of his feet?  I should 
            say plunge. 
       Or maybe I have it all wrong, should have 
            said who 
       among us, even now as I speak, isn't rising? 
       Whether scaling the clouds like mountains 
       or winging our way through a dream, 
       who cannot feel her heart rocket 
       or his hopes lift from the weight of the world, 
       drift into grace?  I have been watching the leaves 
       do their annual leaving.  I have been thinking of twirling 
       like an umbrella turned inside out.  Do you know what I
       mean? 
       Hold your hand up above your head as a waiter would 
       balancing an invisible tray and then spiral it down to the
       table. 
       Do you feel the lock of your wrist get in the way? 
       Do you have any idea what it is that you're serving? 
       Have you ever considered your life's like an escalator 
       levitating from level to level; or an elevator, always
       departing 
       as well as arriving; each ceiling, another floor; every 
       floor, a ceiling? 
       But I drift, don't I?  I was talking about the leaves, 
       the way they swirl when they fall.  I was dipping and rising. 
       I was swaying the way some leaves cradle the air 
       to the left, to the right like gentle pendulums, 
       like children riding the slowest swings in the world, 
       like brooms sweeping what's right and what's left into one
       motion, 
       like the ebb and flow of the ocean, or the hands of a
       maestro 
       conducting the only symphony we know.
            </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11>       </STRONG></pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gobillot.jpg" align=right width=168 height=214></STRONG></h3>
<h3><a name="sylvia"><STRONG>Sylvia</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Jeannie Gobillot<br>
Mrs. Gobillot is secretary to Principal Linda Batz<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>       
       Sylvia walked on feet of light 
       An angel touching all our lives. 
       A sorority in sisterhood 
       We protected our own. 
       Soldiers, we two were 
       Fighting for our loved ones' lives. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       We sat close in a sunlit room
       And whispered warm words. 
       She bent over the chair 
       That cradled my brother. 
       &quot;Mel, how wonderful to see you still!&quot; 
       Her soft hair floated down from above 
       And gently caressed his sweet face. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       &quot;Oh, forgive me, dear. 
       I didn't mean to let it fall on you!&quot; 
       A tear appeared; then more 
       Gliding down Mel's cheeks. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       Without a grimace or a quiver, 
       Softly, like a prayer, 
       &quot;Sylvia, your hair is like warm sunlight. 
       Let it fall everywhere.&quot; 
       The words drifted like petals from his lips. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       And we three sat together, 
       Hands gripping each other's tight. 
       Two sighted people, one not. 
       All crying for the warm sunlight
       That was soon to disappear.
       </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG>
<STRONG>       </STRONG></pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/vanantw.jpg" align=left width=173 height=209></STRONG></h3>
<h3><a name="once in a lifetime"><STRONG>Once in a Lifetime</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Dan Van Antwerp, English teacher <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>       A heavy snow fell
       Between 
       Then and now. 
       Afraid of losing my way, 
       I focused on the light
       ahead, 
       Pausing only to turn
       back for a 
       moment. 
       Soon, 
       a  thick blanket 
       covered the way 
       from which I came.
       The childlike footprints 
       only ghostly outlines, 
       traced 
       in the snow. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       A few weeks ago, 
       I found myself 
       in the middle of 
       another frosted night, 
       a night on which 
       the young pines 
       struggled, 
       beautiful yet helpless 
       against the weight 
       of the glistening, 
       glassy splinters of ice. 
       I ran and laughed 
       with my poodle, 
       gliding over the surface 
       and enjoying our 
       first snow together. 
       As I watched the 
       delicious smoke 
       from my cigar 
       trail away, 
         
       I saw 
       the falling snowflakes 
       opening up like 
       little parachutes, 
       and I felt closer 
       to the heavens 
       than I every had before, 
       because I had landed 
       here. 
       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>       
       </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gr_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11> </STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/mcginn.jpg" align=right width=194 height=181></STRONG><a name="Lessons"><STRONG>Lessons</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Florence McGinn, English teacher <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>I</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The vole, bent awkwardly between the claws 
of my neighbor s cat, shakes without pride.  
The silent vole flails when even to breathe 
bleeds its pulsating pain across feline fur.   </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Without moving body or extended paw, 
the golden cat lifts its head with a preoccupied ease.  
I recall that I watched yesterday as this laxly muscled, 
purring bundle was being carried to the family car 
in the brusquely affectionate arms of a child. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I feel the vole's heart caving in, but the claws 
fully contain its continued thrashing.  I approach, 
and the cat lays back its ears.  I watch the cat's fur
momentarily rise and fall back into place as I pause.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>For a long moment, my will urges the kill.  I wish
the vole its moment of death.  But the cat waits, 
waits past the time of reason into the pause of pleasure,
and I feel anger s bile fill my mouth.  Muscles tense, 
and I lift my book to heave it at the cat. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>There is a tiny eruption of blood when clawed knives
slash the vole s body as its dripping, spastic limbs
are tossed into the air.  The broken ruin lands 
at my feet as I shudder and jump back. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>With no acknowledgment of reason or emotion, 
the cat picks up the supple flesh and turns for home.
</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>II</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I let go of dreams in the morning shower s steaming heat.
In front of an unscreened expanse of kitchen window, 
I coax thoughts of the day s routine into the perspective
of downy woodpecker s rhythmic pecking on seeded suet.
I watch finches flutter over the bit of fur and broken skull
under the crabapple tree.  Those remnants like the wrinkled, 
scattered petals of roses too long past their time of blooming 
are all that the cat has left of yesterday s vole.  One finch lands
and pecks quickly at the fur.  Its head tilts as it picks up a 
broken piece of bone I had not seen until then.  With a lift 
of wings, it drops the small, finished splendor of vole spirit. 
I rise and press my hands against the glass to see if there 
is a pattern of boundaries, a message of infinity, 
left in the air between the departing finch
and the scattered design of vole intentions.
</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>III
</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Sunset shadows deepen like an arc of darkness 
spreading its blinding sheen across vision's depth.
Perspectives shift from black ebony to soft pewter
in the thin light of a rising, ancient moon.
Night s texture is given spreading substance
by the horned owl s throaty voice.  I follow
its call into the woods to the dark base of a tree
that fingertips remember as a shagbark hickory.
In the amplified clarity of silence, I sense
the tufted, shadow form in the trunk s cleft.
A white throat shimmers in the slow movement
of a rotating head, and I hold my breath.
The owl s yellow eyes are open like a child s eyes 
struck with wonder, senses filled with hunger.
Its eyes meet mine, and I strive to memorize
how the moon dilates over its liquid surface,
how the moon glows with a cat s feral vision. </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
</body>

