<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv4toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 4 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></pre>
<pre><center><a name="Empress of the Night"><STRONG>Empress of The Night</STRONG></a><STRONG>
by Dan DiMicco</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Writing for young readers is a unique and challenging craft.  
Writers and illustrators for young audiences know that 
sophisticated techniques, rhythms, and images need to be woven in 
an especially imaginative manner to capture young imaginations and 
simultaneously to interest adult readers.  This piece by a 
high school writer entrances within the world of imagery which 
appeals to both young and old.
<img src="/esoup/gif/outofrch.jpg" align=right width=153 height=199></STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The great empress of the night
     Slowly stalking her prey</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Flawless in every way
     She waits as the wind tackles the night</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Without warning the beast of beauty     
     Soars through the air</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Graceful
Magnificent Splendor
Lethal</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The empress flies graciously with the wind              --Robi Mookerjee
     Lightning descends upon the prey                    </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Death now becomes her
     She is the empress of the Night.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="Gamble Bug"><STRONG>Gamble Bug</STRONG></a></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>by  Chris Carmona
Chris is a sixth grader at Readington School.</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>          
I like to gamble here and there, 
Spend it all at once, I shall not dare. 
How I love the sound of those dice being rolled! 
If I could buy gambling, consider it sold.
I love the sound of the breath-taking slots. 
I get so tense, I pull my hair into knots. 
Some people say I got bit by a gamble bug. 
I dare not have a disease like that, like a drug. 
When I gamble, I don't know if it's night or day. 
All I know is to gamble and play. 
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="Valentine's Day for Vets"><STRONG>Valentine's Day for Vets</STRONG></a></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>By Antonnella Carannante
Antonnella is a fifth grader at Robert Hunter.
</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>V eterans
A ll American
L et freedom ring
E verywhere    
N ow
T ime has passed
I want to thank you
N ow and always
E veryday
S tay with us</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG>D ay and night<br>
A lways remembered<br>
Y ou are in our hearts<br>
</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="My Bedtime Buddy"><STRONG>My Bedtime Buddy</STRONG></a></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>by Natasha Emelianov
Natasha is a second grader at Robert Hunter.</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                       
     I have a bedtime buddy.  His name is Berry and I got
him at a garage sale.  I also bought his cousins at a  garage
sale.
     Barry is grey and he has a pink bow around his neck. 
I like him most because he is soft and fluffy and I can play
with him whenever I want to.  Our favorite game is
Detective.  But do you know why he is my bedtime buddy? 
Because he helps me fall asleep.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="The Sun"><STRONG>The Sun</STRONG></a><STRONG>
by  Raffeale Illiano
Raffeale is a second grader at Robert Hunter.
</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>The sun is hot </STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>I like it a lot.</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>The sun makes the flowers grow</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><center><STRONG>I like it so!
     </STRONG></center></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG></STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="The Rain"><STRONG>The Rain</STRONG></a><STRONG> 
by  Noha Amin
Noha is a second grader at Robert Hunter.
</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Without rain 
People would die,
Without rain
There would be no life
Up in the sky.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="The Forgotten Hat"><STRONG>The Forgotten Hat</STRONG></a><STRONG>
By Charlyn Nevarez
Charlyn is a third grader from Robert Hunter.</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>                It was a Friday in January and I woke up at 8:00.  
I was upset because I was going to miss the school bus.  I had
ten minutes to get dressed and to get to the bus stop.  But it
was so late that my mother had to take me to school.
     When I got to school I saw everyone in my class with a
hat on.
     &quot;Oh, no! It's Hat Day!  I forgot my hat because I was
in a rush this morning.  What am I going to do?&quot;  I said to
myself.
     I asked my teacher if I could call my mom so that she
could bring my hat.  She told me yes.  I was hoping my mom
was home.  I called but my mom didn't answer.  I left a
message on the answering machine.
     I felt sad that my mom wasn't home and hoped she
would get the message.  I waited and waited and finally gave
up because it was almost lunch time.
     All of a sudden, I saw my mom in the doorway with
my hat.  I was so happy to see her.  Now I was going to
celebrate Hat Day!

</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="My Heroes"><STRONG>My Heroes</STRONG></a><STRONG>
By Michael Mancino
Michael is a fourth grader at Robert Hunter.
</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     To me, a hero is a person that loves you, cares for you
and is nice.  Mom and Dad love me, care for me, and are
nice to me, too.
     Sometimes if my mom is not home, my dad and I play
football or basketball.
     One day, I was playing golf with my friends.  I got hit
with a golf club and two of my teeth came out.  I lost a tooth
on the ground.  Then my Mom and Dad took me to the
hospital.  They held my hand when I got my stitches.  If they
didn't bring me to the hospital, my chin would be infected.
     My Mom and Dad are my heroes because they play
with me when they have time, take me places where I have to
go, and they take good care of me.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#Top"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></p>
<pre><center><a name="I Think"><STRONG>I Think</STRONG></a><STRONG>
By Chris Carmona, a 6th grader at Readington School</STRONG></center></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I think I see you, but I don't know
I think I'm walking, but I can't go
I think I'm looking, but I can't see
I'm moving my leg, but I can't feel my knee
I think I'm crying, but I can't see my tears
I think I have them, but I can't feel my ears
I think I know you, but I don't remember
I think it's August, but it might be September
I think I know them, but I can't hear the band
I think I'm writing, but I can't feel my hand
</STRONG></pre>
