<h1 align=center><a name="short stories"><STRONG>Electric Soup</STRONG></a><STRONG> Short Stories</STRONG></h1>
<pre><center><img src="/esoup/gif/pondhaze.jpg" align=bottom width=310 height=90></center></pre>
<p><STRONG>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#neocromancer,2"><STRONG>Heart of the Necromancer, Part 2</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dan DiMicco </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#swollen"><STRONG>Swollen on the Fourth of July</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Bill Henderson</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv5toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 5 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/wh_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/danfall.jpg" align=right width=194 height=212></STRONG><a name="neocromancer,2"><STRONG>Heart of the Necromancer, Part 2</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dan DiMicco<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     The next morning they went outside to 
see the town.  Everything was busy; street 
vendors and farmers' wagons littered the street.  
One wagon particularly caught their attention.  
The wagon was exquisitely decorated with 
colored fabric and paper. Celestial Hawk
quickly approached the vendor.
     With an unusual accent the vendor 
asked.  &quot;Why, hello, good fella.  What may 
I do for you this lovely morning?&quot;    
     &quot;I'd like to see what you have on sale.&quot;
     &quot;I think I know what you would be interested in.  Here's an 
amulet that I just found the other day.&quot;
     The vendor pulled out a sparkling amulet.  The insignia 
immediately got Celestial Hawk and Magenas' attention.  It was the 
sign of the Zenith.
     Celestial Hawk bellowed out, &quot;Where did you get this?!?!?!&quot;
     His hand came up to the neck of the vendor.  Celestial Hawk's 
eyes grew read with fury.  Magena put her arm in his line of attack.  
     The vendor quivered out, &quot;I don't know... I just found it in 
the forest, not too far from here.  Put me down!&quot;
     &quot;If you are lying, I will come back and snap your neck!&quot;
      Red-faced and angry, Celestial Hawk threw the vendor on the 
ground.  Celestial Hawk then slowly walked to a nearby wall and 
propped himself against it.  Tears began to slide down his cheek. 
Magena went up to him, but he only pushed her away.  After 
wallowing in self pity for a couple of minutes, he apologized to her.  
     &quot;I'm sorry,&quot; he softly whispered, &quot;I shouldn't have reacted 
that way.&quot;
     &quot;That's ok, we all have hard times.  How about we go to the 
forest and find out what happened to her?&quot;
     &quot;How are we going to get there?  It takes about a day by 
horseback.&quot;
     &quot;Well, I suggest we start walking or find a horse!&quot;
     After an hour of searching around town, they managed to find a 
horse that they could use.  They had to, however, buy it for one 
hundred gold coins.  It was the last of the money Celestial Hawk had.
     They slowly trotted out of town on their new horse.  After a 
few hours of riding, Magena complained of a sore rump.   After 
resting, an eerie wind blew over them.  Celestial Hawk felt the
presence of pure evil.
     After searching around an open clearing in the forest, they 
came upon a body.  Worms and maggots had gotten to the body before 
they did.  The flesh was rotted beyond recognition and the skin on 
the skull was worn away.  
     &quot;My god - what on this world...,&quot; Magenta cried.
     Celestial Hawk just looked down on the corpse to see if it 
was their lost warrior.  Maggots crawled in and out of the skull.  
He carefully pushed them away, a Zenith symbol appeared on the 
crown.  It was she.  He bent down to touch the body.  It broke
at his touch.  A shrill scream echoed through the air.
     &quot;What was...?&quot;
     &quot;I don't know, Celestial.&quot;
      Celestial Hawk bent down and touched the crumbling carcass.  
Once again, a shrill voice echoed through the forest.  
     &quot;Her spirit must not be at rest. We must avenge her,&quot; 
Celestial Hawk bluntly stated.
     &quot;How can you be so - distant?  She was one of us!  You have no
emotion!  What is wrong with you?  Are you not a Zenith?&quot; 
screamed Magena.
     &quot;I've seen too many dead bodies, too much killing, 
slaughtering . . . &quot;
     &quot;I think that voice is trying to tell us something, that 
shrill scream - a direction . . . &quot;
     Magena bent down and touched the body.  Th voice again howled.
She did it again, and they were able to tell the direction of the 
scream.
     &quot;Let's head that way - where the voice is coming from,&quot; 
Celestial Hawk mumbled.
     Celestial Hawk and Magena began to head toward the darker 
section of the forest.  Winds howled through the trees.  With its 
bitter touch, the warriors grew tired.  Trees began to bend and 
fold around each other, weeping, crying out to the wind.  The forest
displayed a true evil mien.  After traveling for endless hours, 
they stopped to rest.  Every way they turned, there was evil.
     &quot;Where are we, Celestial Hawk?,&quot; Magena asked.
     &quot;I do not know, but wherever we are, there is more evil than 
I have ever seen.  I have only heard stories about a place of this 
evil.&quot;
     &quot;What about those stories?&quot;
     &quot;Well, I don't remember much, and I don't care to remember 
them.  An evil necromancer used to use black magic to torture and 
kill animals, people, everything.  Eventually, he turned insane. 
Everything that he saw brought an end to sanity.  The dark magic 
began to control him, instead of him controlling it.  There was a 
time that his soul could be spared, but now he no longer has one.  
He only has the souls of those he killed.&quot;
     &quot;My god... &quot;
     &quot;Hopefully, we will not have to face him, and maybe there is 
someone else.  But for now, we should rest.  This place certainly 
isn't a nice place to sleep, but we'll have to.  I can take the 
first watch,&quot; Celestial Hawk ordered.
     &quot;Ok, let's get the camp set up.&quot;
				   </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>           Readers have indicated a strong interest in the 
		&quot;Heart of the Necromancer&quot;tale.   Hopefully, 
		the saga will continue!
  </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/purbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#short stories"><STRONG>Return to Short Stories Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/wh_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="swollen"><STRONG>Swollen On the Fourth of July</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
 By Bill Henderson<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>
     Dolichovespula Arenaria -- commonly known as the
  yellowjacket, is a small black insect, 17-18mm in length (
  0.7 inches), with yellow markings on the head, thorax, and
  bands on the abdomen.  The yellowjacket is very
  aggressive, and despite its diminutive appearance, is able to
  inflict great pain upon creatures thousands of times its size
  with a single sting.  These are all facts which I have known
  for quite some time now.  How did I learn them?  Well, I
  was taught them first hand.  In fact, I was taught by a tiny
  black and yellow teacher with six legs and wings.  
     It was July 4th, 1995, and I was expecting a typical
  Independence Day at my grandparents' house, playing
  volleyball and eating hot dogs.  It's not as exciting as it
  sounds.  I am usually designated the job of watching the
  little kids to make sure that they don't hurt themselves, and
  I never really get a chance to enjoy myself.  After I'd
  showered and dressed that morning, I meandered clumsily
  into the kitchen, where my mother was just hanging up the
  phone.
     &quot;Guess what?&quot; she asked, not actually expecting me
  to guess.  &quot;There's not going to be a family picnic this
  year.&quot;
     I was overcome with a sense of freedom, and I was
  already beginning to plan out my day in my head as my
  mother continued, &quot;Instead, I'm going to drop you off at
  my parents' house, and you're going to help them put up
  the fence around their pool.&quot;  She could see the look of
  discontent slide onto my face, and before I could protest,
  she said, &quot;I'm sure they'll pay you twenty dollars if you
  help them.&quot;
     I had been beaten.  She had hit my main weakness
  and rendered me completely defenseless.  I then realized
  that the sooner I helped them with their fence, the quicker
  I'd be able to get twenty bucks and go home.  I glanced
  down at my bare feet and decided to slip on some
  moccasins. Going to get my socks would have wasted
  precious seconds that could later be used for staring at my
  newly earned money. 
     I stepped outside into the balmy summer air and
  swiftly entered the car where my mother soon joined me.  I
  sat back and relaxed, dreaming contentedly of the
  imminent elderly gold mine.
     Before I knew it, we were pulling into my
  grandparents' driveway in front of their pleasant abode in
  sunny Southhampton, Pennsylvania.  As I stepped out of
  the commodiously air-conditioned car, I cringed in
  response to the drastic climate change.  The air was soggy
  and sweat-inducing and instantly gave me an
  uncomfortable feeling as though I had just wet not only my
  pants, but my entire body.  
     I began quickly to long for the comfort of air-
  conditioning and started across the lawn towards the front
  door.  I noticed that the grass underfoot was beginning to
  turn a pale yellow from lack of water.  Yards everywhere
  suffered from the terrible drought that summer, and this
  one was not an exception.  
     I looked up from the lawn to realize that I had
  reached the comfort of the front porch.  I lunged forward,
  eager to grasp the aluminum handle which would lead me
  inside to the wonderful air-conditioned haven of my
  grandparents' kitchen when, suddenly, I was assaulted by a
  rather discourteous bee.  
     &quot;God, I hate these stupid bees!&quot; I cried, violently
  swatting at my bantam assailant.  My crude strategy was
  effective as the bee speedily fled my flailing hand.  Finally, I
  opened the door and entered the house.  My mother
  followed a few steps behind me, and together we traversed
  the short hallway to the kitchen where my grandmother
  and grandfather spend the day working on crossword
  puzzles and drinking coffee, respectively.  
     My grandmother generally has a rather difficult
  time actually hearing other people.  As a consequence of
  this minor disability, my mom and I were virtually on top
  of her by the time she realized we had arrived.  
     &quot;Oh!&quot; she yelled, emerging suddenly from the
  newspaper and its half-finished crossword, &quot;I didn't even
  hear you come in.&quot;</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>      I glanced at my mother and knew instantly that the
  single phrase running through her mind at that moment
  was, &quot;Isn't that a surprise!&quot; but instead she just said,
  &quot;Where's Daddy?&quot;
     &quot;He's out back,&quot; my grandmother replied, gesturing
  to the yard behind the house.  &quot;He's getting ready to set up
  the fence.&quot;
     My mother eyed the wooden clock above the
  telephone and turned back to me, saying, &quot;It's about 11:30
  now, so I'll go shopping for a little while, and I'll be back to
  get you at about one.&quot;      
     &quot;Ok, whatever,&quot; I replied without comprehending
  what she had said.  My mind was wandering towards more
  important topics -- for example, finishing this fence so that
  I could get out with my 20 bucks ASAP.  
     As my mom walked out the door, my grandmother
  instantaneously offered, &quot;Would you like a Pepsi or
  something to eat?&quot;  Though she's purely Irish, she's one of
  those grandmas that displays the typically Italian trait of
  offering you a lot of food all the time.  This is probably due
  to the fact that she's been married to an Italian for more
  than forty years and has gotten used to having to live up to
  his feeding expectations.  
     &quot;No, thanks.  I'm fine,&quot; I responded, glaring out the
  back window.  She could tell I wanted to get out and start
  working.  Little did she know, I wasn't actually eager to
  help -- I just wanted to get it over with.  She asked if I was
  ready to go out back.  I nodded, and followed her out the
  white aluminum door onto the back patio.
     My grandparents' back yard is exactly the kind of
  place that you'd like to be on any day in the summer.  The
  grass there didn't seem to be having as tough a season as
  the grass out front, and it was evident that whoever they
  were paying to take care of it was doing a good job.  There
  are four or five large trees which provide a comfortable
  refuge if you need to get away from the sun, and the whole
  yard is surrounded by a humble brown fence.  As my eyes
  drifted across the landscape, I noticed my grandfather
  readying the white metal safety fence to be set up around
  the pool.  I approached him and we met with the customary
  handshake.  
     &quot;How are ya?&quot; he asked, wiping the sweat from his
  tanned brow.
     &quot;I'm fine,&quot; I responded. &quot;How about you?&quot;
     &quot;I'm friggin' tired.  It's hot out here,&quot; he said.  He's
  not the kind of grandfather who generally makes a huge
  effort to be a good example to his grandchildren.
     I watched him as he wiped his sweating forehead
  again and asked, &quot;How long have you been out here?  You
  look exhausted.&quot;
     He shrugged and said, &quot;About 5 minutes.&quot;  Right
  then I knew that this fence thing was going to be a rather
  difficult task.  My grandmother made her way over to the
  pool, and we decided that we should get started so that we
  could get out of the sun as quickly as humanly (or elderly)
  possible.    
     Putting up the fence wasn't all that bad, and for a
  while it went pretty smoothly.  We'd set it up in sections,
  picking it up onto the side of the above-ground pool and
  then fastening the screws and washers.  We got two sections
  up and were almost finished with the third when it started
  to go down hill.  The fence was bent, and I couldn't fit my
  fingers between it and the side of the pool in order to
  tighten the screw.  My grandmother decided to give it a try
  seeing as how her fingers are smaller than mine.  This
  turned out to be a big mistake.
     She leaned over the small shrubs that line the
  outside of the pool and reached around the fence. 
  Suddenly, I saw her arm jerk away as she lost her grip on
  the screw and attempted to catch it.  Unfortunately, she
  was unsuccessful, and the screw plummeted into the bush
  underneath her.  
     She looked down at the little bush, then over to my
  grandfather and said to him, &quot;Frank, we need another
  screw.  I dropped that one.&quot;
     &quot;I know you dropped it,&quot; he returned. &quot;Just pick it
  up.&quot;  
     Following my grandfather's words of wisdom, she
  bent down to retrieve the fallen screw.  She reached
  forward to the small shrub and inserted her hand into it. 
  All of a sudden, she yelped and withdrew her arm from the
  bush.  Before I could react, I felt a sharp pain in my left
  ankle, and I cried out as well.  I instinctively looked down
  to the source of the discomfort and saw my tiny assailant
  clinging to me and repeatedly thrusting his pointed rear
  into my ankle.  I swiped my hand in the direction of the
  bee, removing him from my ankle, and fled the area where
  I had been attacked.  
     Everything calmed down as quickly as it had begun,
  and as soon as I stopped thinking about getting away from
  the yellowjackets, I started to feel a motherload of pain in
  my throbbing ankle.  I dashed up the steps to the pool,
  threw off my moccasin, and plunged my left leg into the
  cold water of the pool so quickly that my grandparents
  temporarily lost track of me.  When they realized where I
  had gone, they immediately began the grandparently act of
  finding out whether or not I was going to die.
     I was suddenly bombarded with a barrage of
  questions regarding my well being.  
     &quot;Are you ok?&quot;
     &quot;Does your foot hurt?  Are you in pain?&quot;
     &quot;Are you all right?&quot;
     &quot;Don't worry, it's nothing big.  I'll be fine,&quot; I
  assured them.  I'd been stung before and didn't have any
  major problems, so why should I have them now.  I looked
  through the crystal clear pool water at my ailing ankle, and
  a small red circle caught my eye, where the stinger had
  pierced my skin.  I then glanced over at my grandparents
  and noticed a similar mark on my grandmother's arm.
     &quot;Did you get stung, too?&quot; I asked.
     &quot;Yeah, but I'm fine,&quot; she answered.   &quot;I'm just
  concerned about you because it's my fault that you got
  stung.&quot; 
     I was in the middle of assuring her that it was no
  one's fault when my grandfather took credit for the mishap. 
  &quot;You wouldn't have picked it up if I didn't tell you to,&quot; he
  said.  The two argued about whose fault it was for a couple
  of minutes and then decided to go inside so that she could
  put some ice on her arm and help to ease my sting, too.  I
  told them that I was just going to stay outside and soak my
  foot in the pool for a while, and we'd could finish the fence
  later.
     As I sat there in the blistering heat, soaking my foot
  and waiting for my mom to get back, I scratched my arm
  and thought about the day.   I realized that we didn't finish
  the fence, and I might not get any money.  Then, I
  scratched my thigh.  Suddenly, I was uncontrollably
  scratching my entire body.  I thought that maybe they had
  too much chlorine in the pool and it was giving me a rash,
  or something, so I got up and hopped across the yard to the
  back door. 
     I went into the house and sat down in the living
  room.  I remained on the couch for quite a few minutes, but
  the itching did not cease.  The pain in my ankle didn't stop
  either.  Finally,  I put the two irritations together and
  realized that the itching was probably due to the sting. 
  This perplexed me because the only adverse effect that a
  bee sting had ever had on me before was the pain.  
     My grandmother entered the living room and asked
  if I wanted some ice for my ankle.  I looked down at it and
  noticed a welt about the size of a quarter forming around
  the little red circle.  &quot;Please,&quot; I said.  &quot;it'll probably help
  the swelling.&quot;  She left for the kitchen to get the icepack,
  and I sat scratching myself until she returned.  I applied the
  chilly item to my sting and sat silently on the couch.
     After another 10 or 15 minutes, my mom got back
  and was rather surprised to see two thirds of the household
  wearing icepacks.  We told her the whole story, and she
  gave me the same wellness interrogation that my
  grandparents had given me after the incident.  
     She looked me over to see if I was ok and
  commented, &quot;Your lips look swollen.&quot;
     &quot;Maybe it's the lighting,&quot; I suggested, but upon
  moving to the kitchen where the lighting was better, the
  swelling of my lips was unchanged.  My mother then
  examined my ankle, and decided that we should get going
  so that we could pick up some Benadryl  to ease up my
  swelling.
     We said our good-byes and left for the car, without
  the twenty bucks I had longed for.  On the way home, the
  itching and swelling worsened, and some interesting red
  welts appeared in various parts of my body.  We stopped at
  a 7-11 and picked up some Benadryl , which eventually
  helped my symptoms.  By the time we arrived back at our
  house, the swollen area on my ankle was about the size of
  half a kiwi.  
     Though the red welts and itching went away, my
  ankle continued to inflate over the rest of that day.  In fact,
  I wasn't even able to get on my shoe in order to go out that
  night.  We had plans to go to the movies and were afraid
  that they would be ruined by the strict &quot;no shirt, no shoes,
  no service&quot; policy.  However, I used the pair of moccasins
  that I had worn earlier that day, and my foot was able to fit
  into them with only minor problems.  
     The trip to the theater that night was an extremely
  uncomfortable one, mainly because of my bulging left foot. 
  The fact that the movie was Batman Forever certainly
  didn't help the situation.  By the time the picture was over,
  I couldn't walk, and my foot was actually overflowing from
  the moccasin.  It was then that I began to question whether
  I was allergic to bee stings.  
     The next day, my doctor began to question along
  that line as well.  We gave him a visit that morning because
  I still couldn't walk and secondarily because my foot was
  the size of a VCR.  He told me to come back in a month and
  have a series of amusing tests done to determine whether or
  not I was extremely allergic to stinging insects.  
     I took his advice and returned the next month.  This
  was not a fun visit.  I received many injections and other
  painful analyses which determined that on the whole, if it
  stings, I'm very allergic to it.  
     As a result of my allergies, I now must be constantly
  armed with a syringe and various pills during the entire
  &quot;bee season.&quot;  I urge you to take this advice -- treat insects
  with respect.  They may be small, but man, they can really
  make you swell.
  </STRONG></pre>
