<body background="/esoup/gif/a026.jpg" text="#FF80FF" link="#FFFF00" vlink="#00FF00">
<h1 align=center><a name="free writing"><STRONG>Electric Soup</STRONG></a><STRONG> Free Writing</STRONG></h1>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/pond.jpg" align=right width=229 height=164>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#ellie"><STRONG>Ellie</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Melissa Gurba </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#tongue"><STRONG>Tongue</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Christina Swan </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#tongue"><STRONG>Living Music</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Shannon Ingoglia </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv5toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 5 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gurba.jpg" align=left width=205 height=188></STRONG><a name="ellie"><STRONG>Ellie</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- by Melissa Gurba<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     She watches behind transparent shades of 
pewter as time passes and days move on.  Irony 
exists in the fact that, in reality, she cannot 
see me.  Her heat-seeking, v-shaped tongue 
suppresses against the flat surface of the glass, 
just as any warm-blooded, warm-hearted mammal 
wanders past her.  Beneath interlocking squares 
of mesh and metal, luminescent spheres of fire 
call out for attention.  A glance down into her 
world renders boredom; hence, one is left to 
believe she relies not on instinct alone but the one
who watches over her.  Without limbs to walk with, to reach out and
grasp with, she slithers ever so gently with a sense of acumen.  
Her inability to produce sufficient amounts of melanin leave her
colorless. . .in a way.  Pearly shades of pink-hued undertones and
stripes like rays of sunshine reveal internal organs that almost
protrude through her tightly-packed scales and into my palms. 
Voluntary muscle composes the majority of her worm-like
structure; whereas, freely, she chooses how and which way to twist
and twine throughout my eight phalanges.  My thumbs, which are
squeezed with any slight movement, function hand- in-hand with
her posterior end as both ventral and dorsal sides spiral about. 
Apparently, security is at ease now because she maintains
continence.  Outside of these compassionate hands 
she would be left to fend for herself and rely on instinct alone for
survival purposes.  No one would be near to rescue her from
predators in the wild longing to snatch her up in an instant. 
Therefore, one can only ponder if, in essence, she  will ever come
to appreciate the tender touch of a human hand because had she
ever been given the chance to truly be free, only then would we
know which she preferred. 
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#free writing"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/swan.jpg" align=left width=212 height=266></STRONG><a name="tongue"><STRONG>Tongue</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- by Christina Swan</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     What if someone came up to you and cut off 
your tongue?  Not a word spoken. Their actions 
making sure that you can't say anything.  No 
wait, stop!  You can't do that! But it's already 
been done.  You frantically look around for your 
tongue.  You spot it in the corner, kicked out 
of the way.  It's alive!  Spasmodically jumping 
off the floor like a fish out of water.  Maybe 
there's still time.  I know I can save it.  I 
can pack it in ice and take it to the hospital, 
and they can sew it back on.  With the leeches 
sucking the blood away,  I know I have time.
     You bend down and carefully pick up your 
tongue, realizing that there is really nothing 
that you can do.  For God's sake, someone cut 
your tongue off!  No one can put a tongue back on!  Your perfect, pink, 
sensitive, tongue.  One of the most important things you have is your 
ongue.  It allows you to taste the most beautiful tastes in the world.  
It allows you to explore the most desirable thing you can get your 
mouth on.  It allows you to communicate with someone 100,000 miles 
away from you.  Your tongue  allows you to speak your mind, voice your
opinion, pronounce letters, help you sing a song, kiss someone you 
love, make obscene gestures. Your tongue allows you to choke if you 
are having a seizure.  It allows you to taste the most revolting taste
you could imagine.  It allows you to feel excruciating pain if your 
pearly whites decide to plot against your taste buds.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#free writing"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yl_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/ingoglia.jpg" align=left width=173 height=167></STRONG><a name="living music"><STRONG>Living Music</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- by Shannon Ingoglia <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     There is music in any thing.  The way you 
talk is music.  As well as the way you move, 
breathe.  In your eyes and hair is music. Even 
the way you always look at me as if you don t 
quite think I'm real, that is music as well.  
And perhaps I m not real, but only the music 
knows for sure.  Because everything that is 
has its own music.  I can sit here and look 
at your eyes.  Not into them, for I only want 
to go so deep.  But I can look at your eyes and feel their
rhythm.  The dark, rich brown creates its own music as they burn
that color right into my mind.  And even as our relationship wavers
between what it will be and what it is, it creates such beautiful 
melodies that I find myself in a trance.  Sometimes I just sit and 
listen to our music and wonder if you can hear it, too.  It isn't 
very loud, but it is perfect.  Your confusion is obvious to me
as I listen to your part of the song, and I feel the frustration in
the chords.  It isn't as if you need to tell me; the music is 
enough.  Although I wish to help you, my heart longs to sing with 
those lovely melodies.  Our relationship can only say so much.  If 
you really wanted to understand it, you could just listen to the 
music. But it almost seems as if you don t want to.  Is it easier 
to wander in confusion?  Pleading, dark eyes have a dangerous song 
to sing. Perhaps it would be better to shut the song out, for it 
seems to be getting us nowhere.  But there would only be another 
song somewhere else.  The music is inevitable.  Just listen and 
try to understand.  For me.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/grenbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#free writing"><STRONG>Return to Free Writes Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
