<h1 align=center><a name="alumnae writing"><STRONG>Electric Soup</STRONG></a><STRONG> Alumnae Writing</STRONG></h1>
<pre></pre>
<pre><STRONG>--Kristina Sutphen and Nicole
   Baker, Alumnae Editors</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/alumnaed.jpg" align=left width=219 height=199>Pieces in this volume include: </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#pinhole"><STRONG>Pinhole in Never</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Tom Swift </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#gravity"><STRONG>gravity</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Dara Badiak </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#anticipation"><STRONG>Anticipation</STRONG></a><STRONG> by Michelle Lee Reeves</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv5toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 5 Main Menu<br>
</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
<br>
</STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/pondover.jpg" align=right width=220 height=181></STRONG><a name="pinhole"><STRONG>Pinhole in Never</STRONG></a></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Standing there in my never
I looked across its span
the deep and abiding maybe 
of me.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I said there to the nowhere never
that never again would I venture
never again take the leap
never chance to reap.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>While molding this never into my world
I left a lilliputian crack in my circumference
the sharpest sliver of a star
which is random.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>And you, with your heart pressed thin
slipped and fell
through the pinhole in my hide of never
and you said,</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>All these nevers, never again.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>           Tom Swift</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#alumnae writing"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Writing Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="gravity"><STRONG>gravity</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Dara Badiak<br>
Alumnae of class of 1995</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>there are satellites so large
they dance in a double orbit with their hopeless cycles
two bodies pulling and pushing in tidal surges
sucking with hungry gravitational mouths
moving in distorted circles through the silent vacuum</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>as they spin through their hopeless cycles
they slowly draw one another in 
knowing the consequences of getting too close
always turning aside at the last instant
and passing by one another in the cold night</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>each one has to keep circling
even when it can feel its rock, its oceans, its liquid metal core
pulled toward the other
even when all it wants to do is surrender
stop spinning and dancing away
fall inward, grow fingers and lips and a tongue, ignite
and never have to worry about geometry and distances again</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#alumnae writing"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Writing Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/cy_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11> </STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="anticipation"><STRONG>Anticipation</STRONG></a></h3>
<pre><STRONG>I cannot live on faith alone
That you will return to me, my love
And while the nights grow darker still,
My voice carries a note of frigidity
(Is it only my voice?)
For in these infinite hours of longing,
I have begun to shrink into myself,
While you are off cavorting with a stranger,
My heart dares not to ask where you have been.
	       </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>               by Michelle Reeves</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/yellowba.gif" align=bottom width=14 height=14></STRONG><a href="#alumnae writing"><STRONG>Return to Alumnae Writing Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
