<p><STRONG>Return to </STRONG><a href="esv5toc.html"><STRONG>Volume 5 Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<pre><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11><STRONG> </STRONG></pre>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/vanantw.jpg" align=left width=173 height=209></STRONG><a name="harvest"><STRONG>Harvest</STRONG></a><STRONG> --- by Dan VanAntwerp</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>I found music,
And discovered
What it was,
To burn on stage,
mind spinning thrillingly
beyond control,
adrenaline rushing
my brain
and crushing my
consciousness
as I
squeeze the last howling, roaring
gasp
of electric agony
from a Fender Telecaster.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Or to feel the wah-wah,
Washing away 
All symptoms of adulthood,
To be newly baptized
in the torrents
of rhythm,</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Or, for just a razor slice
of time
to be back,
magically,
jamming in the basement
of Ted's house,
naively believing
we had the stuff
to be
on someone else's radio.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>When I found music,
I suddenly discovered
a screaming, wailing,
demon voice
with which to 
chase away
the awkward agonies
of my timid adolescence.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>And now, 
as rock dreams
fade away
into the bottom of a briefcase,
I realize
that just three chords
can contain more magic
than I ever
dreamed
when I would 
fall asleep 
in my old bedroom,
guitar in hand,
blistered fingers
caked with blood,
and Neil Young
on the radio,
lulling me to sleep
with
Hey, Hey, My, My
Rock and Roll
Can Never Die.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/redbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11><STRONG> </STRONG></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/gobil2.jpg" align=right width=219 height=228></STRONG><a name="suitcase"><STRONG>THE SUITCASE</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- by Jeannie Gobillot </STRONG></p>
<pre><STRONG>The suitcase, half packed
Shiny, yet scratched
Nicks, rough edges worn smooth
Lining torn, pockets stretched</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Push aside jammed tears,
Tuck all grief away,
Look for joy of living.
Seasons merge in between
Good times to store.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The suitcase, half packed
or, perhaps, half empty?
Will the lid slam?  Or
Will it close gently?</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/redbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11><STRONG> </STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/livech.jpg" align=left width=225 height=173></STRONG><a name="for 20 years "><STRONG>For Twenty Years You've Opened Every Day</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- <br>
by John Livecchi<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>How many times as I
turned that corner
in the Acropolis Museum
could I feel you tugging at me?</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>You held me transfixed
my eyes feasting on the light;
and once, when the guard had tired of chaperoning us
I reached out because we were alone.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>It wasn't marble I touched.
It was as if in one moment
a merciful hand from the past found me.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>In that instant I knew
I couldn't meet another day
without your presence.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Remember how many layers they wrapped you in
to guard fragile plaster;
or how they stamped &quot;MUSEUM COPY&quot;
all over that great cocoon?</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>When I finally had you home,
before anything else,
I had to find a place for you
so our conversation could continue.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>And now, 
in another museum,
I turn another corner
knowing you are there;
sensing it before my eyes venerate you</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The crowd around dutifully studies,
intent on learning who made you
and what the style of your garment suggests
and where the archaeologists found you.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Experts call you pensive, mourning
Citing time, subject, location
as if your clues were external.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>But they have never regarded you as I have,
like a lover always searching,
even from this distance,
in every contour,
to find an invitation to go on.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>From the first day
I understood:
you simply read 
words we cannot see.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>And what others term sadness
is the inner smile
that comes from knowing 
which words will stop a goddess
and bow her head.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/redbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><img src="/esoup/gif/or_bar.gif" align=bottom width=640 height=11><STRONG> </STRONG></p>
<h3><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/mcginn2.jpg" align=right width=92 height=138></STRONG><a name="delivering death"><STRONG>Delivering Death</STRONG></a><STRONG> -- by Florence McGinn<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Summer whisks fingers 
translucent with shimmering heat
across the blue whirr of dragonfly wings.  
Algae floats thickly upon pond water
like long hair twisted into knots of scum.
Two does step into mud, lower their heads, 
and alternately drink and snort.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>It is a sound, almost human, 
in an inhuman time 
of humid weight and fiery air.  </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The buzz of gnats and black flies,
loud like a wheezing engine, 
draws me away from the pond edge. </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Insects swarm and rise above
the farm road s ditch and coarse weeds.
A young rabbit, its back legs torn and twisted,</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>lies visible from the road.  As I stare, it lifts
its head, eyes covered with flies, and cries 
a thin, high wail.  I shudder and back away.  </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>When I find the large rock and lift its weight
with both hands, I flinch.  I want to offer 
comfort and can only bring release.  </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I cannot go near.  I find instead a thick stick. 
I plan only one, swift stroke, but I swing 
and slam five, maybe six, times.  It is hard</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>to stop.  I run and heave the stick deep 
into the still pond.  I keep on running 
from the dead rabbit and from myself.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/redbull.gif" align=bottom width=18 height=18></STRONG><a href="#Community of Writers"><STRONG>Return to Community of Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
