<h3><a name="I am"><STRONG>I Am</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Chris Carmona<br>
Chris is a sixth grader at Readington School.</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>I am a crazy guy who loves baseball.
I wonder why I always talk about baseball.
I hear Hank Aaron's seven-hundred sixteenth home run.
I see Babe Ruth in my dreams.
I want a $4,000,000 contract like Barry Bonds.
I am a crazy guy who loves baseball.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I pretend I'm watching the World Series in the Goodyear blimp.
I feel like I need baseball to survive.
I touch the glove that Willie Mays used.
I worry that players will just play baseball for the money.
I cry for those who hate baseball.
I am a crazy guy who loves baseball.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I understand the meaning of baseball.
I say baseball will always be the best.
I dream about baseball's great meaning.
I try not to miss a Frank Thomas homer.
I hope Frank Thomas gets triple crowned.
I am a crazy guy who loves baseball.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="clouds"><STRONG>The Clouds</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Natasha Emelianov<br>
Natasha is a second grader at Robert Hunter.</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>Little Clouds, little clouds
You are like pillows in the sky
When the rain comes, you go bye, bye.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="my favorite toy"><STRONG>My Favorite Toy</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Raffaele Illiano<br>
Raffaele is a second grader at Robert Hunter.</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     One day I went to Jamesway and bought a fire truck.  
Then I went to my Mom and Dad's pizzeria to play with it.
     The fire truck was red and had a fireman.  It also had a 
ladder that went up and down.  I put the ladder up and the fireman 
on the ladder and pretended there was a fire.
     I play with my fire truck after school and like to pretend I 
am a fireman.  Sometimes, I put the siren on.  It's loud and has a 
red light.
     The fire truck is the best toy in the world because it makes 
me happy and lets me pretend I'm a fireman.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="detour"><STRONG>A Detour On the Way to Camp Bernie<br>
</STRONG></a><STRONG>by Antonella Carannante<br>
Antonella is a 5th grader at Robert Hunter.</STRONG></h3>
<pre></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     The day finally came.  Our fifth grade class was getting ready
to go on a trip to Camp Bernie.  It was a rainy day.  We got on the
bus and started going.  The bus had to take a detour because there
was construction on the road.
     Maria, Samantha and I were playing travel games.  Suddenly,
we were thrown to the side of the bus when the bus driver lost
control of the wheel.  It was slippery and the bus skidded into the
woods.  Everybody was screaming as the bus fell in  hole.  &quot;Help,
help!&quot; I screamed.  All of the kids panicked.  Then we were floating
and rotating in space.  After a while, we landed on a planet and we
felt safe because the bus was standing still.  
     The planet was different from Earth.  There were gray and
yellow trees and red grass.  We saw no people and no buildings. 
All of a sudden, these blue and purple strange creatures appeared. 
They were about two feet tall with long droopy ears.  We were
trying to get away from them because they were banging on the
windows of the bus.  The bus driver started driving away.  &quot;Wow!&quot;
I thought.  They must have been going 60 miles per hour because
the bus driver was going 50 miles per hour and they got past us.  
     The bus started going slower until it stopped.  The bus driver
was shouting, &quot;I RAN OUT OF GAS!&quot;  Everyone started screaming.  
The creatures began attacking the bus.  They broke the glass and 
tried to get in.  I thought I was going to pass out and I
began to sweat.  Suddenly, I found myself sitting on my bed in the
dark.  I took a deep breath and went back to sleep.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="untitled"><STRONG>Untitled</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
by Alyssa Sussman<br>
Alyssa attends Far Hills Country Day School.</STRONG></h3>
<h3></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     From my standpoint I can see
     The craze behind those icy eyes
     You realize not the pain to me 
     Caused by the silence I despise</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     I feel the breeze's frosty breath
     Upon my neck so late at night
     He whispers horrid psalms of death 
     I listen and my face grows white</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     Emerges from blackness the silver of knife
     Then howling echoes through the place
     That's drowning in the essence of the absence of life
     I do not watch, I hide my face</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     The pines converse, the moonlight glares
     They urge me off their property
     I'm flaming with guilt but no one cares
     Won't someone come to rescue me?
     </STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>     I can not cope; I'm in a daze
     This wasn't something I could plan
     I'm smothered with a mass of haze
     I can't believe I've killed a man.
</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="journey"><STRONG>The Journey</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Jessica Merkel Keller<br>
Jessica attends Far Hills Country Day School.<br>
<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>I must travel far far away
Where nobody knows my name.
There I can rebuild from the ground.
There I will have a new life where I will be free.
I must lay the foundation of my hopes and dreams.
I need to run by night.
Soon my color will not matter.
The night will show the drinking gourd.
I will follow it north.
When the dawn comes my journey will cease
only to start again.
White and black only make mocha.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="what has happened here"><STRONG>&quot;What Has Happened Here?&quot;</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by George Fountoulakis<br>
George attends Far Hills Country Day School. <br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>A flare
A glare
A spark upon the air
Like lightning, thunder upon the sky of bare
And there I sat, staring at the flares and the glare
Thinking of things that happened there.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>I closed my eyes, completely unaware
A scream
Like a gunshot
And then I thought...
A shuffling of feet,
A jostling crowd.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The screams increased
The crowd aware
Everyone seemed scared,
What could it be
Whatever could have happened
But I still thought...</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Abruptly the screams ended,
Leaving an empty feeling in the air
Everything was bare
The cameras flash
But then again it all stopped
And I still thought...</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>The silence stood
As it should
And hovered in the air
The screams had died,
I asked myself,
&quot;What has happened here?&quot;</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="face of"><STRONG>THE FACE OF THE FLOORFELANG</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
Work for young writers created by Ryan Miller, 11th grader<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>The face of the
floorfelang
Is the scariest thing you'll see
Long twisted teeth, mandibles of death
And from him you will flee</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>Glowing red eyes on the back of his head
There are four if you want to know
And a giant wart-covered nose on his skull
From which a river of boogers flow</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>From each of his ears grow long blue hair
If you get real close you can count two
But the worst thing about the Floorfelang
Is that he is right behind you!</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="excitement"><STRONG>Excitement</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Matt DiGiandomenico and Jonathan Sasor<br>
Matt and Jonathan are in sixth grade <br>
at East Amwell Township School.<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>     When excitement comes......
	  you can't sit still
	  ready to explode
	  you feel like screaming
	  happiness is overwhelming
	  confusion and amazement take over
	  terrified of what will happen next
     When excitement comes, you never know what to expect.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="discovery"><STRONG>Discovery</STRONG></a><STRONG><br>
by Jessica King and Jackie Luster<br>
Jessica and Jackie are both eighth graders <br>
at Reading Fleming Middle School<br>
</STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>The awkwardness of the unknown startles my thoughts.
Wondering where I might go next, wanting to know where,
	where is.
My path is misleading,
Its unexpected winding is perilous.
Though the wind pushes me towards its mouth, I argue.
For I have been there before, and to explore is my new fantasy.
I must take the risk to travel the darkness of the unknown.
The awkwardness of the unknown no longer startles me.
I am aware.
And awakened . . . </STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/barfrac1.gif" align=bottom width=555 height=17></STRONG></p>
<h3><a name="inner sources renga"><STRONG>Inner Sources</STRONG></a><STRONG> <br>
A renga is a Japanese form of linked poetry. This linked poem<br>
examining the roots of creativity was created by student workshop<br>
participants at the 1996 Writer's Day of the Hunterdon Teen Arts<br>
Festival. </STRONG></h3>
<pre><STRONG>(Danica Rue, Reading Fleming Middle School)
     The brightness of the outside 
     Doesn't show the darkness of 
	  the inside.
     Deep inside my thoughts comes my
	  dreams and fears.
     A million thoughts waiting to become words.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Anna Ichel, Round Valley Middle School)
     A far off place where ideas and    
     Stories come to life.
     Where everything is impossibly perfect.
     A light shines through from this place
     And a story is born.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Matt DiGiandomenico, East Amwell School)
     My creativity comes from      
     Something I may see 
	  or read about.
     I usually have an interest 
	  in the topic I write about.  
     I m not exactly sure 
     Where it comes from.
     I just imagine it.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Nitasha Bansal, Reading Fleming Middle School)
     Dark, deep               
     A seemingly endless pit
     Emotions swirl and are swept away
     By the raging sea
     Ideas are struggling
     Desperate to be freed
     Down there
     WITHIN

(Jessa Conant, Voorhees High School)
     From feelings            
     From people who make me happy
     From people who hurt me
     From all the deep thinking and 
     Exaggerated things I think of 
     That no one cares about but me.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Liz Upchurch, Voorhees High School)
     My source for creativity           
     I was always alone growing up 
     I had a lot of time to think and reflect 
     Almost everything I think or do or feel 
     Stems back to that time.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Jonathan Sasor, East Amwell School)
     My creativity comes from                
     Imagination.  Anything I can 
     Think up may be something to write about.
     I'll think up an ordinary thing 
     And turn it into something
     Extraordinary</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(John Grimaldi)
     I have no definite sources for creative                
     Writing.  When I write creatively, 
     My sources emanate from 
     The world around me.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Barbara Witmer, Reading Middle School)
     My sources come from my dreams          
     And my family.
     It comes from animals and their behavior.
     Anything that comes to my mind that
     I think will be interesting.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Jessica King, Reading Fleming Middle School)
     My eyes enclose what I see         
     My nose what I smell
     My mouth what I taste
     My ears what I hear
     And my heart, mind, and soul open up
     And release me in words.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Jackie Luster, Reading Fleming Middle School)
     From my soul and heart        
     My mind
     My language
     My sense -- the touch of my hand to a pen
     My body
     My face
     My emotions
     My expressions
     Especially my hands.</STRONG></pre>
<pre><STRONG>(Dale Langley, Reading Fleming Middle School)
     My creativity comes from being     
     With others.  My family, friends, 
     And the people I babysit all make me
     Happy or sad or angry.
     I think about the outdoors--
     The sky and clouds, 
     The trees and the hills.
     I feel at peace when 
     I think about these things.
     I create.</STRONG></pre>
<p><STRONG><img src="/esoup/gif/balloon2.gif" align=bottom width=32 height=32></STRONG><a href="#young writers"><STRONG>Return to Young Writers Main Menu</STRONG></a></p>
