<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=25%><IMG SRC="door.jpg" HEIGHT=148 WIDTH=136 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>

<TD width=3%></TD>

<TD width=47%><IMG SRC="aboutesp.jpg" HEIGHT=144 WIDTH=234 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>

<TD width=25%><IMG SRC="door.jpg" HEIGHT=148 WIDTH=136 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>ELECTRIC SOUP</B>, Hunterdon Central Regional High School's cyber-mag,
is developed based upon a belief in the energy and importance of words.
This literary magazine project utilizes technology to deliver electronic
impact to words, and <U>Electric Soup</U> has received a 1996 NJ Best Educational
Practices Award. Its student editors are active writers, who have published
in print literary magazines, presented a workshop for Hunterdon Teen Arts,
organized a Teen Arts Open Mike Poetry Reading, participated in school
and public poetry readings, and presented portions of the cyber-mag on
WCVH, FM 90.5. Poet Adrienne Rich writes that &quot;The words are purposes./The
words are maps.&quot; Join us as we embark upon a conversation of language
and imagination striding upon a path of inner exploration and universal
quest. </P>

<P>Only a few, rare copies of <B>ELECTRIC SOUP</B> are available in print
form, for <B>ELECTRIC SOUP</B> is a cyber-mag with the built-in immediacy
of electronic delivery. Modern and exciting access methods to <B>ELECTRIC
SOUP</B> are given to our readers. A colorful graphics version can be read
on the HCRHS network system from computers throughout our high school.
A World Wide Web version of <B>ELECTRIC SOUP</B> is on the Internet as
part of the high school's Internet site. To connect directly to the cybermag's
web location, use <A HREF="http://www.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us/esoup/welcome.html">http://www.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us/esoup/welcome.html
</A>for quick access. To learn more, contact Florence McGinn, John Smith,
or Catherine Lent at HCRHS, 84 Route 31, Flemington, NJ 08822 or at internet
addressses: <A HREF="mailto:fmcginn@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us">fmcginn@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us</A>
</P>

<P>OR <A HREF="mailto:jsmith@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us">jsmith@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us
</A>OR <A HREF="mailto:clent@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us">clent@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us</A>.
</P>

<P><B>Red anger, boiling rage, </B></P>

<P><B>Pain, sorrow, fear </B></P>

<P><B>All are channeled as electricity </B></P>

<P><B>through the wire of my pen </B></P>

<P><B>to the appliance of the word . . . </B></P>

<P><B>Lauren Crotsley</B> </P>

<P><B>READ ABOUT THE DIFFERENT FEATURE SECTIONS</B> </P>

<P><B>OF<U> ELECTRIC SOUP'S</U> STUDENT EDITORS!</B> </P>

<P><B>To be a poet of life, though artists seldom realize it, is the <I>summum</I>.
To breathe out more than one breathes in. </B></P>

<P><B><I>Henry Miller</I></B> </P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>STUDENT POETRY</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B>Hello, you have reached the free verse poetry section
of <U>Electric Soup</U>. The editors, Jenn Schneiderman, Jaeme Griffin,
Carolyn Chun, and Shannon Ingoglia are not available right now, but please,
feel free to submit any piece of writing which looks, screams, feels, smells,
or tastes like free verse poetry ( use your own discretion). Please make
your submissions electronically if you can. Submit each poem under a separate
electronic file name or in dark type that can be scanned.</B> </TD>

<TD width=5%.</td></TD>

<TD width=25%><IMG SRC="poetry1.jpg" HEIGHT=102 WIDTH=245 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Thanks! We'll be waiting to read your work!</B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>MAGNETIC, LINKED, AND FORM POETRY</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="magnet2.jpg" HEIGHT=135 WIDTH=252 ALIGN=LEFT></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Welcome to a new section of <U>Electric Soup</U>! Get
with a friend, get with a group, do it by yourself! All you need are magnets
and something they'll stick to. Okay. What is magnetic poetry? Here's how
to do it: </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>l. If you write individually, just dig through the magnets
until you find the words you want. No words other than what's on the magnets!
</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>2. If you're with a group, you can alternate words, lines,
and stanzas. Do whatever you want to create poetry with a theme or a nonsensical
poem. Have fun! </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>We are also looking for form poetry. Examples are haiku
(5,7,5 or within the haiku spirit), limericks (a,a,b,b,a), or tankas. We
are interested in all form poetry including creative rhyme pieces, sonnets,
concrete poems, or villanelles. </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Editors Jarrett Basedow, Ryan Gernay, Alison Quairoli, and Lisa Santowasso</B>
</P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>THE ALUMNAE SECTION</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><B>Words can become a way of life. Leaving school need not
sever the writer from words and creativity, for school can be a wide doorway
opening upon a lifelong path of imaginative thought and beautiful language.
The Irish poet, Seamus Heaney wrote that &quot;Between my finger and my
thumb/The squat pen rests/I'll dig with it.&quot; We invite you to read
the evocative work of alumnae writers, who have been willing to search
for words and to bring those words forth in visible form. </B></TD>

<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="alumni1.jpg" HEIGHT=123 WIDTH=180 ALIGN=CENTER></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Editors Kristina Sutphen, Nicole Baker, and Meghan Bissett</B> </P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>COMMUNITY OF WRITERS </B></P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=1%></TD>

<TD width=40%><BR>
<B>Poet Sandra McPherson a joy and a power in <BR>
trying to understand <BR>
through by using the <BR>
and images and the <BR>
of language.&quot; It is with </B></TD>

<TD width=5%><IMG SRC="commun1.jpg" HEIGHT=124 WIDTH=220 ALIGN=LEFT></TD>

<TD width=50%><BR>
<B>tells us, &quot;There is <BR>
writing . . . You're <BR>
what you're living <BR>
tools of words <BR>
beautiful inner structure <BR>
pleasure and a belief in </B></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD width=1%></TD>

<TD colspan=3><B>the writing process that the adults in our community and
our world make themselves available as role models for student writers.
</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>The poet, Claribel Alegria, writes that &quot;Poetry is
like bread -- everybody shares it.&quot; Family, staff, teachers, writers
in our community, writers in or out of our country are invited to submit
material. Sharing the words infuses writing experiences with interactivity
and life. The power of inclusiveness and a shared exploration of words
provide foundations for true writing experiences. </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Editors Kimberly Krug, and Jill Luster</B> </P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>FREE WRITES</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=5%><IMG SRC="freewri1.jpg" HEIGHT=132 WIDTH=222 ALIGN=LEFT></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>The genres of writing are as varied and diverse as the
manifold cultures of this world. Many of these different styles, such as
the limerick and the haiku, are rigidly structured. But sometimes, a writer
will feel the urge to put his or her thoughts down on paper without having
to worry about following a specific formula. This is the essence of a free
write, whose very </B></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD colspan=3><B>name implies its unregulated style. Its spontaneous nature
has been defined by Natalie Goldberg in her <U>Writing Down the Bones</U>
and <U>Wild Mind</U>.</B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Characteristically, a free write is brief, only one or
two pages long. It is often descriptive, an emotionally charged piece that
transports the reader into the writer's mind and psyche. Although conflict
is usually inherent, the presence of characters is frequently absent. Rather,
the struggle is, in many cases, internal, such as a disturbing memory,
an important experience, or a sudden enlightenment.</B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>So now, you are invited to sit back and delve into the
work of the authors featured in this section. Let their words swell around
you, allow their emotions and struggles to become tangible, for then, you
will have truly captured the spirit of the free write.</B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Editors Kate Lynch, Erin Schneiderman, and Meenu Sanwal </B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>COLLABORATIVE SHORT STORIES</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>WELCOME and PLEASE SUBMIT. YOU have to send continuous
work for there to be collaborations. Submissions should consist of around
250 words. Make your stories energetic and imaginative, but keep your stories
clean. What are Collaborations? Collaborations are a section of </B></TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="collab1.jpg" HEIGHT=135 WIDTH=178 ALIGN=LEFT></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD colspan=3><B>the magazine set aside for &quot;Pass Around Stories.&quot;
That means that one person starts the story and submits it. Then other
people read and think, <I>This should really happen next</I>, so they send
in the next part of the story. Someone else reads what the last person
wrote, writes something new, and submits the next part, and it's an endless
circle. Our goal is to have several stories going at once. Thanks for taking
a minute to read this, and if you have any ideas or suggestions, please,
write to us. Submit anything at any time, just submit! Just remember --
WE NEED YOU! </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Miami Pare, Sara Walsman, and Kira Kohrherr, Collaborations Feature
Editors</B> </P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>PHILOSOPHICAL ESSAYS</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Many philosophers have written about things such as Morality,
Rights, Freedom, Government, and even God. Whether you are familiar with
philosophy or not, this is a forum in which you can voice your opinions.
This does not mean that it is an editorial section. Editorials tend to
get case specific, and that is not what we are looking for. Instead, we
would like to see essays addressing a general thesis and expanding upon
that thesis. For instance you might want to write an essay about a proof
for or against God (or any other religious deity). Or you might want to
write about a certain moral that you think society should hold in high
regard. </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Submission pieces should be in essay form . You should
make your arguments through analysis, not general statements without proof.
The essays will not be chosen on the viewpoint presented, but rather on
the content. Please, have no qualms about your position on any given issue;
if we all agreed, the world would be very dull. For further information
concerning this section, or even for ideas, feel free to contact us.</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Philosophical Essays Editor, Sarah Hornstein</B> </P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>SHORT STORIES</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Give your imagination a chance to stretch with lively
characters and exciting plot lines. We're interested in short stories of
every genre. What we want to see is the well-written tale or narrative.
Length is not of great importance. Send your short stories as well as stories
of length to Bryan Littel, Dan DeLorenzo, and Rob Wavra, ELECTRIC SOUP'S
Short Stories Editors. If we decide to print a long piece, we may print
it in episodes. The important thing is to send us your imaginative short
story work! </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>YOUNG WRITERS</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Hey! It's Chris Mc Nutt, Kim Collins, and Dorit Radzin,
Young Writers Editors for <U>Electric Soup</U>. Writing creatively when
you are young is an important part of any creative process -- and it's
fun! That's the most important part of writing at any level -- being creative
and having fun! So get out your pen and paper. Start writing about anything
you feel -- a dream, your best friend, your shoes. You have no limits.
Your work can be as long or as short as you wish. Your submission can be
a poem, a short story, a play -- whatever you want it to be. Have fun writing,
use your imagination, and send your work to us for possible publication.
</B>
<P></td</tr></P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Won't it be neat to see your name in print? Even if one
of your pieces doesn't get published, don't feel badly! Just keep on sending
us new work. Read some of our young writer's work now! Maybe it'll give
you some ideas. We're looking forward to reading your work and seeing what
you can do with your imagination! </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>LETTERS TO THE EDITOR IN CHIEF OF <U>ELECTRIC SOUP</U></B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>ELECTRIC SOUP is based upon a belief in a broad, living,
active writing process. Such a process does not occur in a vacuum, and
our writers and the magazine staff are interested in your feedback. We
invite you to use this feature to send us your responses and ideas! Send
to <A HREF="mailto:cdymek@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us">cdymek@star.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us</A>.</B>
</TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="cdymek1.jpg" HEIGHT=147 WIDTH=237 ALIGN=LEFT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Editor in Chief <A HREF="http://www.cableview-online.com/~cdymek">Chris
Dymek </A></B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>PHOTOART </B></P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="photog1.jpg" HEIGHT=145 WIDTH=227></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Have you ever seen the perfect picture that really captures
the essence of a moment? Is it in your own photography or art collection?
If so, we need submissions here at the Photart section of <U>Electric Soup</U>.
We are interested in photography and art by anyone at all! There will be
some cooperation between us and the new Photography Club</B></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD colspan=3><B>run by Brandon Wall. We will work to coordinate photography
and literature. Soooo, if you're interested, get in touch with Melissa
Gurba, Robyn King, or Alex Radus, and get your art on line! </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>COLLAGE EDITOR </B></P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>In this occasional feature of ELECTRIC SOUP, Frank Dumbreski,
explores words and images as metaphor. He works to combine the powerful,
connotative qualities of the written word and the visual impact of images
into an interpretative, electronic collage. </B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" algin="left" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72></P>

<P><B>ADMINISTRATIVE EDITORS</B> </P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=15%><IMG SRC="admin1.jpg" HEIGHT=116 WIDTH=162></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Are you interested in helping in the details of magazine
publicity? Join Administrative Editors Anita Kulkarni and Tara Machusak
in the advertising, communications, and publicity details of the electronic
magazine. Your ideas and help can become an active part of ELECTRIC SOUP!
</B></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="deer.jpg" HEIGHT=44 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>TECHNICAL EDITORS </B></P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=80%><B>Working closely with Editor-in-Chief Chris Dymek on the
technical aspects of the multiple formats of ELECTRIC SOUP is challenging.
Technical Supervisory Editor Dan DiMicco works with Technical Editors,
Rob Setzer, Zak Klase, and J.R. Rusnak, to solve technical glitches and
to support and implement the electronic delivery of this cyber- magazine.
If you are interested in technology and electronic publishing, consider
working with <U>Electric Soup</U>.</B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B><I>The poet, Li-Young Lee, writes, &quot;it had something to do with
love . . . &quot; which is what we believe underlies the powerful work
<U>Electric Soup</U> encounters. </I></B></P>

<P><B>&quot;But I being poor, have </B></P>

<P><B>only my dreams </B></P>

<P><B>I have spread my dreams </B></P>

<P><B>under your feet</B> </P>

<P><B>Tread softly because you </B></P>

<P><B>tread on my dreams.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B><I>W.B. Yeats from &quot;He Wishes for the Cloths of Heaven&quot;</I></B>
</P>

