<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Electric Soup"></A><B>Electric Soup Alumnae</B></H1>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=60%><B>Pieces in this Volume Include:</B> 
<P><A HREF="#My Crucible"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#My Crucible">My
Crucible</A> by Tom Swift</B></P>

<P><A HREF="#Climbing Mountains"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#Climbing Mountains">Climbing
Mountains</A> by Matt Kuznicki</B></P>

<P><A HREF="#P E A N U T B U T T E R OR J E L L Y"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#P E A N U T B U T T E R O R J E L L Y">PEANUT
BUTTER&nbsp; OR&nbsp; JELLY</A> </B></P>

<UL>
<P><B>by Ryan Muir</B></P>
</UL>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="esv6toc.html">Volume 6 Main&nbsp;Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=40%><IMG SRC="flower85.jpg" HEIGHT=144 WIDTH=216></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="bar4.gif" HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=528></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=50%><A NAME="My Crucible"></A><B>My Crucible</B> </TD>

<TD width=45%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=40%><B><I>By Tom Swift</I></B> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</TD>

<TD width=55%><IMG SRC="eyes.jpg" HEIGHT=107 WIDTH=250></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=5%></TD>

<TD WIDTH=75%>I'm screaming, <BR>
<BR>
tearing out my eyes, <BR>
<BR>
pulling off this skin, <BR>
<BR>
crying to break free. <BR>
<BR>
Your fire is searing me, <BR>
<BR>
you boil my brain, <BR>
<BR>
consume my soul, <BR>
<BR>
with your need. <BR>
<BR>
Scorched you wait, <BR>
<BR>
melting in your crucible <BR>
<BR>
no rain to cool <BR>
<BR>
just tears from me. <BR>
<BR>
</TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><A HREF="#Electric Soup"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A>Return
to <A HREF="#Electric Soup">Main Menu</A> </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="bar4.gif" HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=528></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><A NAME="Climbing Mountains"></A><B>Climbing Mountains</B>
</TD>

<TD width=20%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=50%><IMG SRC="glacier1.jpg" HEIGHT=144 WIDTH=189></TD>

<TD width=45%><B><I>By Matt Kuznicki</I></B> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>was once confined to the same realm <BR>
<BR>
as dreams and wings; standing atop <BR>
<BR>
peaks she screams and squeals with delight, <BR>
<BR>
jokes about making love <BR>
<BR>
and catching frostbite. She spreads her arms <BR>
to encompass and embrace this entire scene <BR>
<BR>
wanting it to fall into <BR>
<BR>
the ridges in her skin, leave a picture <BR>
<BR>
among the goosebumps <BR>
<BR>
for her to remember. <BR>
<BR>
The emotions surging through <BR>
<BR>
her accepting body thrust her <BR>
<BR>
first one direction, then another; <BR>
<BR>
from accepting everything <BR>
<BR>
to stunned apathy while looking down. <BR>
<BR>
In later nights she will look about <BR>
<BR>
the aging apartment her high school crush <BR>
<BR>
and she have struggled to hold onto. <BR>
<BR>
She will be certain of devotion <BR>
<BR>
and touch him no longer. <BR>
<BR>
Her heart belongs to the clouds. <BR>
<BR>
</TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><A HREF="#Electric Soup"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A>Return
to <A HREF="#Electric Soup">Main Menu</A></TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%></TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="bar4.gif" HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=528></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="P E A N U T B U T T E R O R J E L L Y"></A><B>PEANUT
BUTTER OR JELLY?</B> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I>By Ryan Muir </I></B></TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="muir.jpg" HEIGHT=125 WIDTH=133></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%></TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><B><I>Ryan is attending Trenton State College this fall.</I></B>
</TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>Life is plagued with difficult decisions. From the last minute
decision made at 2 a.m. about which assignment to complete, to the slightly
more significant decision of which college to attend, the process of choosing
surrounds our lives, day in and day out. In all of the countless decisions
that we ever will make, there is one that stands out from the rest. This
momentous choice is something that everyone has to make for himself, without
the help of friends and family. This road that you choose, most likely
you will follow until the end of your days. Yes, the sticky question is
that of which is the better, peanut butter or jelly? </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>Inside of everybody's head lurks childhood memories of mother-made
peanut butter and jelly sandwiches. For many people, these sandwiches played
an integral part in helping them to grow and achieve happiness, providing
the substance that is so essential to life. But one side of the bread always
seemed a little bit better than the flip side. This could be because it
stuck to the wall longer when winged at high speeds from across the room
or simply because it was more pleasing to the taste buds. Many different
reasons exist as to why someone would like peanut butter or jelly more.
</TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>Taste preference will ultimately determine the decision of
peanut butter over jelly or vice-versa. Jelly is an extremely sugary substance
that is pleasing to eat. It is available in many different flavors to suit
individual taste: strawberry, cherry, grape, etc... you get the idea. This
allows the eater of jelly to pick the flavor that is right for him or her.
Peanut butter has a pleasing taste, and although it, too, is sweet, it
does not have nearly the amount of sugar that jelly has, which may or may
not be your thing. While available in different textures: smooth or chunky,
peanut butter is only available in one flavor, that of peanuts. </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>When deciding which is the better, texture must also be taken
into consideration. The texture of peanut butter is thick and sticky. This
allows for good gripping on any surface: bread, walls, people. Also, if
the peanut butter gets accidentally turned upside down, none will spill
out of the canister or fall from your food. The texture of jam is also
sticky, but it is not nearly as thick as peanut butter. It will still stick
to things pretty well, but if turned upside down, some seepage might occur,
so watch out! </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>One issue that might be important in the decision making
process, especially for all of the health conscious people out there, is
that of fat, calorie, and protein content. In one serving of peanut butter,
there are 16 grams of fat. This is 4 more grams in one tablespoon of peanut
butter than in an entire bar Crunch bar or Hershey's bar. It also contains
200 calories, 140 which are from fat. Its saving grace is that it contains
6 grams of protein. In one serving of jelly, there is no fat, 40 calories,
and no protein. It is obvious that for the weight conscious person, jelly
would be the way to go. </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>When making the decision about which of the spreads is right
for you, versatility must also be considered. Besides the actual peanut
butter and jelly sandwiches, how else can these items be used? To answer
that question, we must look at them individually. Some of the known uses
for peanut butter are for celery sticks, cookies, and candy bars. Peanut
butter can also be used to remove sticky substances from hair, (such as
gum) and this is always a plus. Jelly is mostly used for toast and crepes,
and it does not have the ability to remove sticky things from hair. Both
of these substances are typically not eaten by themselves. Peanut butter
is too thick and clogging to eat in large amounts by itself, and if it
were attempted to do so, serious harm to the eater might result. Jelly
is typically not eaten by itself because people can only take so much of
its obscenely high sugar content. If you enjoy heaping amounts of sugar,
then, please, disregard the prior statement. </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>The last issue, for all of you hungry yet frugal people out
there, is that of cost. Just like any food, a person can spend any amount
they wish on either peanut butter or jelly by going into some speciality
shop and buying the &quot;world's finest&quot; spread. But on the average,
a one pound container, about 16 servings, of peanut butter runs around
$1.60, which is double the $0.80 required for a one pound and 16 serving
size of jelly. </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%>Once all of these above facts, plus countless others that
pertain only to you, are taken into consideration, only then can the final
decision be made. The question of peanut butter or jelly may seem trivial
to some cynical folk, but it plays an important part in out lives. It helps
us to distinguish our true identities and to find out who we really are.
If more people would take the time to find out the answers to questions
such as these, then the world would be a much better place to live. </TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><A HREF="#Electric Soup"><IMG SRC="whball.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A>Return
to <A HREF="#Electric Soup">Main Menu</A></TD>

<TD width=20%></td.</tr></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

