<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Electric Soup Collaborative"></A><B>Electric
Soup Collaborative </B></H1>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><B>Short Stories</B></H1>

<P><B>Volume 6 contains the following selections:</B></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=65%>
<UL>
<P><A HREF="#Mars Federal Colony"><IMG SRC="redbull.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#Mars Federal Colony">Mars
Federal Colony</A> by Alex Radus </B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<P><A HREF="#Mall"><IMG SRC="redbull.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#Mall">Mall
Madness</A></B> <B>Continued by Dan DiMicco </B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<P><A HREF="#The Fifty-third Street"><IMG SRC="redbull.gif" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=18></A><B><A HREF="#The Fifty-third Street">The
Fifty-third Street Bar</A></B> <B>Created by Dan DiMicco and Zak Klase</B></P>
</UL>

<P><B>Click here to&nbsp;Return to the <A HREF="esv6toc.html">Volume 6
Main Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=35%><IMG SRC="ocean2.jpg" HEIGHT=218 WIDTH=304> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=20%><IMG SRC="redmars.jpg" HEIGHT=184 WIDTH=244></TD>

<TD width=75%><A NAME="Mars Federal Colony"></A><B>Mars Federal Colony
</B>
<P><B><I>Part 6, Continued by Alex Radus</I> </B></P>

<P><B>Original story created by Ryan McNamara; previous episodes added
by Mike Fitch, Pat Clark, Lucy Robertson, and Topher Taylor. </B></P>

<P><B>Mars Federal Colony has been altered slightly, thanks to the creativity
of Alex Radus. </B></P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Lieutenant John Mitchell was afraid. He had only been afraid once
before in his life, as far as he could remember. When he was eight, his
older brother took him hiking in the woods near their house. He was attracted
to an area simply by a gut reaction. There was nothing special about this
clump of overgrown moss and shrubs against the rock face, but it was a
visceral feeling eight-year-olds are not very adept in. Almost hypnotically,
he made his way to the shrubbery. His older brother did not seem to share
his enthusiasm and, being an older brother, proceeded to make fun of the
strange way in which his younger sibling approached the rocks. He brushed
the shrubs away to reveal a dank cave, black as the creek that trickled
out of it and back into the rocks. </B></P>

<P><B>Not even exchanging glances, the brothers made their way into the
cave. By now the older Mitchell was as entranced as the younger. The darkness
enveloped them quickly. The musty smell reminded John of his grandmother's
basement with her coal furnace, dirty concrete walls, and jars of pickles,
tomato sauce, and who knows what. As they crept farther into the cave,
the fear crept farther into them. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Mom's going to worry if we aren't back soon,&quot; said David,
the older of the two. &quot;We might as well start heading back. It's just
a cave.&quot; But John would have none of it as he listened to his brother's
voice echoing around him. They had told their mother they would be back
by dusk - and it was only 4:30. John was delighted to feel the water slowly
permeate his shoes and rest between his toes. It was so cold! </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Just a little farther, David,&quot; replied John. &quot;We've
got plenty of time.&quot; So onward they trekked, bumping, bruising, and
scratching, and they finally saw light. They made their way towards the
illumination and were astounded by what they saw. A huge cavern illuminated
by a single shaft of light down the middle of the room and landing on a
podium of rock. The podium was on a small island of rock surrounded by
a moat of water for which there seemed no source. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;This must be just below the hill behind the school,&quot; David
said in awe. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;You could fit two football fields in here!&quot; said John
enthusiastically. He began to make his way towards the center of the room.
The ceiling loomed forty feet above his head. An immense sound slammed
into the side of John's head. It sounded like a thousand hands clapping
at once - like a huge wave rolling into the shore. John looked up towards
the sound. &quot;The ceiling is collapsing!&quot; he shouted to his brother.
They made their way, stumbling towards the cave entrance where they stopped,
perplexed. Had the ceiling been collapsing some- thing surely would have
hit them by now. They turned around slowly. What they saw next neither
of them have been able to sufficiently explain. </B></P>

<P><B>A wave of black swooped down from the ceiling and circled in a deadly
column and folded back on itself before shooting toward the brothers. They
made a narrow escape as they plunged themselves into the opening, barely
missing the onslaught of thousands of bats. </B></P>

<P><B>A musty smell suffocated John as it swarmed around him. He and his
brother clamored back up the wet rock as fast as adrenaline would allow.
In seconds the stinking creatures were on them, engulfing, asphyxiating,
making it impossible to move. Claustrophobia buried the brothers in its
hot grasp as the wings batted against their heads and sticky fur slashed
past their skin. </B></P>

<P><B>Finally, the brothers made it out through the dense canopy closing
off the cave. The bats did not follow them out. John and David could not
even hear the swishing and squeaking of the thousands of bats that seconds
ago covered them. It was as though the creatures never existed. John felt
as if the cave led to another planet or dimension. The bats seemed so hungry...
</B></P>

<P><B>Sitting in the storage closet, Lieutenant John Mitchell was afraid
again. He had seen his superior officer impaled with an axe. He had heard
the grisly fate of Captain Andrews. He remembered the hunger of the bats
and now he felt that same cold. He felt something warm and furry brush
past his ear and he jumped. It turned out only to be a hanging mop. But
for a second there he thought . . . </B></P>

<P><B>What will happen next? </B></P>

<P><B>Was that really only a mop that brushed past John Mitchell's ear?
</B></P>

<P><B>You can create the next episode and <A HREF="http://www.cableview-online.com/esoup/fup.html">submit</A>
to <U>Electric Soup!</U> </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Collaborative">Collaborative Short
Stories Menu</A></B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Mall"></A><B>Mall Madness</B> 
<P><B><I>Final Episode</I> </B></P>

<P><B><I>Continued by Dan DiMicco</I> </B></P>

<P><B>Original story created by Miriam Pare; previous episodes contributed
by Nicole Baker, Meghan Bissett, Laura Kuznicki (2 episodes), and Desiree
Carmona. </B></P>

<P><B>After Sam and Mary turned the corner, their hearts stopped. The silence
in the mall was deafening. All that could be heard was the ringing in their
ears. A dark figure loomed over them, shadowing all light. They could only
make out two shoes at the bottom. </B></P>

<P><B>The figure spoke, &quot;Welcome to the mall.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>The two teenagers were speechless. For the first time in their short
lives, they saw nothing. Nothing in their futures, nothing in their deaths.
</B></P>

<P><B>&quot;NEVER!&quot; Sam hollered, the veins in his throat poking through
his skin. </B></P>

<P><B>The figure jumped and grabbed the two teens in one horrendous move.
Sam and Mary were helpless to stop the figure's grip. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Why are you doing this to us?&quot; Mary pleaded helplessly.
</B></P>

<P><B>&quot;You'll NEVER get away with this!&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>The figure stood there, his own heart beating faster. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Shut up you little twerps; you and your clich&eacute;s are
ticking me off!&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>Sam ferociously attacked the figure, clawing, kicking, raving in
all directions. The little kid in him was beginning to show nicely. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Let us go, you big bully!&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Shut up.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>The figure took the two kids into another dark spot in the mall.
Sam read the letters on the shop, &quot;Wild Bill's Fish and Game Hunting
Shop.&quot; What an interesting store... I wonder what they have in there...
</B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Why are you taking us here??? What are you going to do? WHY?
HELP!!! MOMMY!&quot; Mary pleaded, and started sucking her thumb. She was
obviously regressing back into her childhood. </B></P>

<P><B>The doors to the store opened as they approached. The fishing lures
caught the attention of Sam. I should buy those, he thought, they catch
my attention. They must get the fishes! Sam's eyes slowly began to drift
around in all directions. Nothing else interesting caught his eyes, other
than the guns on the far wall. If only I could get to those guns! </B></P>

<P><B>Mary, however, was still trapped in her childhood, and she began
to cry even more. All of a sudden, loud noises went off all around them.
Wild blasts of light, smoke and tear gas broke loose. Men in black ran
in the entrances, and flew through windows. A very large man came flying
in through the roof of the mall. The letters on his black outfit read,
&quot;SPLAT.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>Thinking quickly, Sam used this time to entertain the figure. &quot;Why,
those are wonderful shoes you have on! Where did you get them? At the shoe
store at the other end of the mall? How much did they cost?&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Shut up.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>In a mad dash, the figure ran for the guns. However, since his shoes
did not fit correctly, he fell face down. The figure began to curse, and
scream all the profanities in the <U>Oxford Dictionary</U>. After he got
up, his costume fell off, and he appeared to look like a normal man. His
face, however, was still a little distorted. After a closer look at the
figure, Sam concluded that he was a disgruntled postal worker. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Help us! Help us! This big man killed our friends and kidnapped
us! Help!&quot; Mary was still having some problems. </B></P>

<P><B>The rest of the SPLAT team broke through the mall and went after
the man. The tear gas the SPLAT team threw in the building was very flammable,
especially when mixed with chemicals from the local Agway. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Stay away from me! I didn't do anything! I didn't kill the
kids! It was the voices in my head!&quot; Wild shots rang out in the air;
sparks flew, and gas ignited. The mall went up like Waco! </B></P>

<P><B>After the clean up, witnesses swore the last thing they could hear,
was shouting. They could only make out part of it. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;I would have gotten away with it, if it weren't for you pesky
ki...&quot; </B></P>

<P><B><I>The End</I>. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Mall Madness&quot; has been discontinued. </B></P>

<P><B>It is now replaced with &quot;The Fifty-third Street Bar&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Collaborative">Collaborative Short
Stories Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=60%><A NAME="The Fifty-third Street"></A><B>The Fifty-third Street
Bar </B>
<P><B>Part I, Created by Dan DiMicco and Zak Klase </B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="spacscen.jpg" HEIGHT=137 WIDTH=330> </P>

<P><B>The air was cold and bitter. Fragrant smoke flowed through the autumn
air. Cars traveling down the road left an exhaust trail in the cold evening.
Street lamps glittered, casting their yellow beams downward. Artificial
sun could not light this dark place. </B></P>

<P><B>One such beam gleamed upon the 53rd Street Bar. The outside lights
were comparable to the street lamps. The windows were lit to anyone willing
to enter. </B></P>

<P><B>Sylvan Garrison was one of these few people. Alone and shy, he was
not happy. Women dancers moved in time with the music. Sylvan sat nursing
his drink. He had come to make some friends but wasn't having any luck.
</B></P>

<P><B>Maureen Poppy sauntered in the door, flowed up to the bar and ordered
her usual. &quot;New guy in town, ever seen him before,&quot; said the
bartender gesturing at Sylvan. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;I'll show him a good time,&quot; winked Maureen. </B></P>

<P><B>Her sly grace became her, and she slithered to the chair beside the
lonely Sylvan. The dancer flung an article of clothing towards Sylvan.
As it passed him, he flinched at the evil garment. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Ehehe, relax. It's only a bra.&quot; Maureen took a long sip
from her champagne. </B></P>

<P><B>Winston Weich slid into the bar. He slowly walked to a bar stool,
away from everyone else, and sat down. The bartender gav him some of his
finest chardonnay. He slowly began to drink away his problems and his memories.
</B></P>

<P><B>Reverend Murphy wandered into the bar and stopped dead in his tracks.
</B></P>

<P><B>&quot;My Good God!&quot; he exclaimed. &quot;A den of sinful pleasures!&quot;
He quickly walked straight to the bar and beckoned the bartender. &quot;Could
I hang up these posters for my revivial meeting?&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>The bartender slowly answered the good reverend with a discreet glass
of J.D. </B></P>

<P><B><I>What will happen next? Will the reverend be pulled into a life
of sin? Will Sylvan's life be changed forever? You can create the next
episode and submit it to <U>Electric Soup</U>! </I></B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Collaborative">Collaborative Short
Stories Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

