<P><IMG SRC="cy_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Dreams Exist to be Conquered"></A><B>Dreams Exist
to be Conquered </B>
<P><B>by Jessica Terrizzi </B></P>

<P><B>Sharp and clear the dreams of the young and always framed in gold...
</B></P>

<P><B>Vision, the projected power of the mind, builds a better world for
each generation. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;TENNESSEE GAS TRANSMISSION COMPANY,&quot; <U>Time</U>, May
12, 1958 </B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="terrizzi.jpg" HEIGHT=116 WIDTH=194> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=65%><B><I>&quot;When I grow up, I'm going to be an astronaut
and be the first to walk on Mars,&quot; stated the second grade girl. She
was outside with her friends during school recess. It was a beautiful,
sunny day, and they were dreaming about their future. </I></B>
<P><B><I>A couple of boys ran by and overheard their friends talking. Stopping
abruptly, they skipped back to join in the conversation. &quot;Wow,&quot;
interrupted one boy, &quot;that's really neat. But I'm going to create
the fastest space ship so we can travel past Mars before we get too old.
Maybe you can be an astronaut for my shuttle.&quot;</I> </B></P>

<P><B><I>&quot;Maybe! That would be really cool,&quot; excitedly replied
the girl.</I> </B></P>

<P><B><I>The students continued their discussion into the classroom and
asked their teacher, Mrs. Star, what she wanted to be when she was their
age. She got the class settled down and rambled off numerous different
dreams she had when she was younger. Some of them were funny, and others
were intriguing. Concluding her childhood fantasies, she explained how
her dream of teaching became a reality. The children learned how important
it is to dream, and think creatively. They realized that the career they
chose--the dream(s), in the sense of aspirations/goals, they pursued--would
be their contribution(s) to the the world. </I></B></P>

<P><B>Too often, as age increases, this valuable lesson becomes buried
under numerous phone numbers and strict schedules in a complicated maze
located under the skull. Filled with important facts and haunting errands,
the mind constantly confronts things needing to be accomplished. Obstacles
are endless and wide smooth paths are rarely experienced. </B></P>

<P><B>In youth, however, the mind, the body, and the soul roam freely along
roads with wide shoulders. Each day, an exciting adventure begins as new
items are discovered, untraveled paths are walked, and imaginations are
utilized. In time, however, the experiences encountered during life shade
opinions, views, and perceptions different colors. Greatly influenced by
the practical world, one's imagination becomes restricted with responsibility.
Opportunity increases throughout one's life, but inescapable obligations
tend to intensify with age. Unfortunately, tentative prospects may not
enable present requirements to be fulfilled. As a result, restrictions
are inadvertently placed upon the public. Dreams once sworn by have suddenly
disappeared behind thick gray clouds of limitations filled with burdening
conditions. An occurrence similar to this, demonstrates that life has lost
meaning and transformed into a boring routine. </B></P>

<P><B>Life should be anything but a boring routine. Adventures, risks,
laughs, love, happiness, sorrow, and other sensations exist to make life
a roller coaster loaded with peaks, valleys, and unexpected turns. Chasing
one's true dream(s) allows each individual's life roller coaster to stand
apart from the rest. </B></P>

<P><B>Throughout life, dreams are naturally refined, changed, and interpreted
differently. Nevertheless, dreams should always be within one's sight.
They are necessary aspects of life which aid in the evolution of our continually
developing world. Technology, medical advancements, different teaching
techniques, new age thinking, and various other ways of life in the 90's
all began as dreams. The mind, constantly thinking, instantaneously forms
opinions, that are accompanied by images and ideas, based upon the present
situation. It is essential to explore the imaginative section of the mind.
As a thorough search is underway, the mind and its power, will be observed
with awe. At first glance, the amazing sight cannot be seen, however closer
examination confirms its beauty; a colorful kaleidoscope full of spectacular
dreams, goals, and aspirations, waiting to be recognized, to be achieved,
and to be utilized for tomorrow. </B></P>

<P><B>Recognition is a key element when striving to attain a goal. It is
important to pinpoint exactly what dream is going to be conquered. Some
regard this to be a complete waste of time. In their mind, dreams are simply
fantasies, an escape from reality. If this were true, we would still be
carving stories in stone. Many had to pursue wild dreams in order for today's
world to be a modern society. </B></P>

<P><B>Dreams must not be thought of as unrealistic fantasies, simply wasting
time when considered or, even worse, pursued. Determination and dedication
to your true goal will enable you to succeed through all your endeavors.
If you believe that your dream will come true by sleeping on the hammock
and creating pictures in the clouds, you're dreaming. No one will serve
your dreams to you on a golden platter, but by working, many will be able
to see your golden platters filled with personal accomplishments. Remember,
no one will do anything for you, especially if you aren't willing to do
it for yourself. </B></P>

<P><B>Everyone must realize that each person has a unique gift to contribute
to this world. There are no exceptions to this statement, only one requirement;
it comes from your heart. This condition ensures that the contribution
is meaningful to each individual. A sense of humble pride and accomplishment
will be experienced when you initialize the world with your unique gift.
Many times, these priceless gifts lie within your goals. Talents are discovered
as we steadily trudge along the rugged tracks of life. </B></P>

<P><B>Besides discovering hidden talents along the path of life, a change
of heart may manifest itself. The highway of life has many exits. Pick
and choose according to desire. Always be cognizant of the consequences.
Remember it's natural for people's areas of interest to change from time
to time. Even when drastic transition doesn't transpire, one's goals usually
undergo adjustment. They are refined many times before realistic ideals
are uncovered. After this phase, the first steps toward success are taken.
</B></P>

<P><B>Often, perceptions concerning the accomplishment of goals appear
closer than reality. They jump a few times with hopes of confiscating their
dream. After a few attempts fail, the need for support becomes obvious
and basic ground work begins. A solid foundation beneath our feet is steadily
built before setting up the ladder towards success. As this sturdy base
is slowly built, some may try to discourage you by belittling your efforts
and minimizing your progress. It is also important to remember that luck
and/or heritage have nothing to do with personal goals. Dreams lie within,
along with determination. Devotion determines your future. Therefore, you
control your fate, not luck, heritage or any other factor. </B></P>

<P><B>Dreams create options for your destiny; they are the shadows of our
future. They are perfect outlines missing a few minor details. As in Peter
Pan, it is first necessary to locate your shadow. Then, you must aggressively
capture it. Next, the obtained shadow must become your prisoner. Coincidentally
forgetting your handcuffs, you are forced to attach your accomplishment
permanently with a needle and thread. Finally, after having the shadow
secured, you can begin to utilize it. With this new addition to your existence,
a new adventure, maybe to Never Neverland, will begin. </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Philosophical Essays
Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="cy_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Prison or Penthouse?"></A><B><TT>Prison or Penthouse?</TT>
</B>
<P><B><TT>by Ryan Gernay </TT></B></P>

<P><B><TT>In the 1970's, many believed prisoners deserved a rehabilitation
program to set them on the right track once they re-entered into society.
Today, however, the minds of the people have changed dramatically. They
now feel prisoners should lead a life of isolation. They feel the job of
the prisons is to separate the criminals from the rest of society. What
has changed so many minds over the past two and half decades? The common
answer is that prisons are too lenient, and criminals are unafraid of being
thrown in jail. If prisons truly are a correctional facility, then the
public has a right to worry because those who walk out of out unaffected
by their &quot;bad experience&quot; are ready to commit another crime.</TT>
</B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="gernay.jpg" HEIGHT=211 WIDTH=179> </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B><TT>Many people may be asking the question, &quot;Why
wouldn't someone be afraid of being thrown in jail?&quot; There is one
simple answer: luxury. Most prisoners have more luxuries in their jailhouses
than most hard-working Americans. Inmates have access to body-building
equipment, televisions, radios, and reading materials. The federal court
required North Carolina to equip thirteen prisons with a set of drums,
three guitars, and five Frisbees. At one Massachusetts facility, prisoners
were served prime rib dinners. It is these luxuries which deny criminals
the persuasion they need to convince them that crime doesn't pay.</TT>
</B>
<P><B><TT>It may not seem as obvious, but aside from the luxuries of the
jail cells, prisoners are also granted working luxuries. In fact, not all
prisoners are even forced to work. According to the Bureau of Justice Statistics,
91% of all prisoners work in the federal system, and only 70% work in the
state. Those who are exempt include the medically or mentally unfit and
those who can't be trusted to work without harming another inmate (Lacayo
33). The average prisoner workweek is only thirty-four and a half hours.
Criminals had relatively little work to do, and the remainder of their
time was occupied by leisure activities. Quoted in Sarah Glazer's essay
&quot;Can Prisons Rehabilitate Criminals,&quot; George Bush indicated a
tough stance on criminal behavior. </TT></B></P>

<P><B><TT>A common-sense approach to crime means that if we're going to
affect people's behavior, we must have a criminal-justice system in which
there is an expectation that if you commit a crime, you will be caught;
and if caught, you will be prosecuted; and if convicted, you will do the
time. For far too long, a privileged class of violent and repeat offenders
have calculated that crime really does pay--that our criminal-justice system
is a crapshoot where the risks are worth the rewards. Well, it's time we
change the odds--and up the stakes enormously (Glazer 430).</TT> </B></P>

<P><B><TT>It may have been this paragraph-long speech that gave other politicians
as well as prison officials the incentive to take action.</TT> </B></P>

<P><B><TT>Joe Arpaio of Maricopa County, Arizona banned all TV stations
as well as pornographic magazines. The inmates' leisure time now includes
one of the following: CNN, old Disney films, or reruns of Newt Gingrich's
10-part course on revitalizing American civilization. In Richard Lacayo's
&quot;Prisons: The Real Hard Cell&quot; essay, Arpaio said, &quot;I want
to make this place so unpleasant that they won't even think about doing
something that could bring them back. I want them to suffer&quot; (Lacayo
31). This is a view supported by the majority of Americans. </TT></B></P>

<P><B><TT>Senator Phil Gramm of Texas believes inmates should be forced
to work more than the required thirty-four hours each week. He's pushing
to make the prisoner workweek seventy hours; a total of ten hours each
day. This amendment is well supported by the people. Whenever Gramm makes
a campaign stop, the crowd cheers, &quot;We've got to stop building prisons
like Holiday Inns&quot; (Lacayo 31).</TT> </B></P>

<P><B><TT>As part of the Republican-sponsored anti-crime bill, a new amendment
has been added which will try to deny luxurious living conditions in federal
prisons. If this amendment is allowed to enter the final version of the
bill, it would forbid such things as premium cable channels and R- or X-
rated movies. Representative Dick Zimmer of New Jersey, the above bill's
sponsor, is trying to create a law that would deny federal prison money
if the states did not ban such things as in-cell TVs and coffee makers,
body-building equipment, and any food better than that served to U.S. soldiers
(Lacayo 31).</TT> </B></P>

<P><B><TT>Prison wardens and guards say taking away the leisure activities
and luxuries of the prisoners would be a big mistake. Since they're the
ones who must live with the the convicts at close range, they think the
inmates need the variety of activities to choose from because it keeps
them busy and reduces the risk of a prison riot erupting. Thomas McKinney
of the Alfred Hughes state prison unit in Gatesville, Texas said in Lacayo's
&quot;Prisons: The Real Hard Cell&quot; essay, &quot;To ban such things
as TV and recreation would take away one of our best management tools&quot;
(Lacayo 32).</TT> </B></P>

<P><B><TT>Will the prisons ever run the way the people feel they should:
to separate the criminals from the rest of society, make them suffer, and
teach them how to live a normal life? Probably not if the constitution
has anything to say about it. But the voices of the people are getting
louder and stronger. They tried giving the prisoners a fair chance to prove
themselves in the past through the rehabilitation programs. But some prisoners
proved themselves to be incapable of change. Now the people just want to
turn the tables on the criminals who inhabit their cities. They want them
to suffer and lead lives of hard work and isolation. But that goal may
prove to be a failure if prison leniency continues strongly into the future.</TT>
</B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Philosophical Essays
Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="cy_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="The Prozac Addiction"></A><B>The Prozac Addiction
</B>
<P><B>by Lisa Routel </B></P>

<P><B>It has been called the &quot;pills of pills&quot;- a green and white
capsule that was introduced in 1988 and has become one of the ten best-selling
drugs in the world. Prozac offers nothing less than self-transformation,
turning self-doubt into confidence, increasing energy, improving one's
social skills. However, the sacrifice of this scientific advancement is
the loss of individuality. </B></P>

<P><B>There's no denying it, Prozac is remarkable. Prozac has positive
results in treating major mental illnesses from psychotic depression to
eating disorders to schizophrenia. It works by altering the biochemistry
of a single neurotransmitter, serotonin. Normally, brain cells that produce
serotonin quickly reabsorb the chemical and deactivate it, clearing the
pathway for the next chemical signal. Prozac interferes with that reabsorption
process, making more serotonin available in the brain ( Jaret 396). Prozac
has the power to give social confidence to the timid, make the sensitive
brash, lend the introvert the social skills of a salesman. Dr. Peter Kramer,
psychiatrist and author of Listening to Prozac, prescribed Prozac to many
of his patients. He began to see a clear picture of how poorly patients
fared when they were inhibited (Kramer 15). The realization of how our
culture favors one interpersonal style was obvious. </B></P>

<P><B>However, is it ethical to choose which traits we value and which
we choose to suppress? &quot;No,&quot; says Chris Dymyk, who has seen the
disasterous effects of Prozac. He recalls how he once knew of a friend's
brother, who turned violent when on the medication, and threatened to kill
his whole family. Dymyk also feels Prozac &quot;stifles individuality.&quot;
In Dr. Kramer's book, <U>Listening to Prozac</U>, he shares a story about
one of his patients, a man named Sam. He was an architect, who was suffering
from a bout of melancholy. Even though his wife disapproved of it, Sam
had an interest in pornography. As he reached forty, Sam fell into a bout
of depression set off by the death of his parents. Sam was soon prescribed
an antidepressant; it worked only partially, leaving him able to function
at work but left him with a constant feeling of vulnerability. </B></P>

<P><B>Soon, it was revealed with further sessions with Dr. Kramer, Sam
recalled having been an obsessed child. This obsessive quality faded as
he entered adulthood and focused on his career. When Sam's depression failed
to respond to the medication, Dr. Kramer thought about the hints of his
history of something resembling obsessive compulsive disorder. Prozac,
at the time a new antidepressant, was thought to have the potential to
ameliorate compulsiveness. The change that came was remarkable. Sam not
only recovered from his depression, he declared himself &quot;better than
well.&quot; He felt more vitally alive. Sam had fewer rough edges. He experienced
this change as a loss. The style he had nurtured and defended for years
now seemed not a part of him but an illness. Sam was convinced that his
interest in pornography had been a physiological obsession. Sam had allowed
Prozac not only to cure the episode of depression, but also to tell him
how he was to be constituted. </B></P>

<P><B>Prozac's power to alleviate depression, shyness, and hypersensitivity
is beneficial, however, only in the severest of cases. The indiscriminate
use of Prozac runs our culture into the risk of covering itself in a veil
of monotony. Dr. Peter Kramer foresees the social implications involved:
&quot;We cannot escape entirely the fear that a drug that makes people
optimistic and confident will rob them of the morally beneficial effects
of melancholy and angst&quot; (Nichols 37). </B></P>

<P><B>However, many doctors appear too liberal with their prescriptions.
&quot;If a patient comes to me feeling unhappy or out of sorts, why not
try Prozac?&quot; as one leading psychiatrist put it. &quot;It's not going
to do them any harm, and it just might help&quot;(Jaret 397). Even a prominent
researcher was bemoaning the fact that Prozac takes several weeks to become
effective, and he looks forward to the day when a quick-acting version
is available (Jaret 396). </B></P>

<P><B>There is an aura of mystery that surrounds Prozac. Neuroscientists
still can't identify all of its effects. Unfortunately, Prozac may present
serious side-effects that are still unknown. Prozac's long-term effects
might not be known for decades. &quot;I'm very concerned about Prozac,&quot;
says Dr. Brandes, who reported in 1992 that rats and mice with artificially
induced cancer showed an increased rate of tumor growth when they were
given Prozac (Nichols 37). </B></P>

<P><B>Altogether, Prozac has proven to be a medical breakthrough-- eliminating
severe bouts of depression and other chronic mental illnesses. However,
I feel Dr. Kramer stated it perfectly when he wrote that sometimes &quot;you
take Prozac to treat a symptom, and it transforms your sense of self &quot;
(Nichols 39). All I know is, in the future, I don't want to be walking
in a crowd, surrounded by a sea of faces, and realizing each face is the
same. </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Philosophical Essays
Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

