<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="A Castle's Room"></A><B>A Castle's Room</B> 
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;No one ever discovers the depths of his own loneliness.&quot;<I>Georges
Bernanos</I> </B></P>

<P><B>The field was empty, less the afflicted sapling. A small, warped
tree, striving to live in the center of a barren, creatureless plain. Every
other tree had fallen at the whim of flesh, except that one. It had been
decided that even though it'd be alone, being so small, it wasn't worth
the effort. Tufts of ill-placed leaves adorned the branches in a mesmerizing
pattern. Surrounded by low grasses, it was visible for miles on the flat
plain, but from the tower it was the lone green spot on a sea of burnt
browns. </B></P>

<P><B>As the sun rose, its rays bent and reflected at strange angles. The
rays of warmth rippled through the swirling blue glass, a lone pane. Circular
and framed in iron, it was the only source of light. </B></P>

<P><B>A drop of water fell from the cold gray stone of the ceiling and
ran down my nose, leaving a moist trail. As it hit the floor, it shattered
like crystal, sending rays of distorted light reeling. For a glimmer of
a second, the room was bathed in sunlight. The small components, bound
to the floor by an unseen force, surveyed my nothingness. </B></P>

<P><B>The gray stones formed a solid wall that stretched for a full revolution
around me. Dank and empty, I had no one with whom to share my captivity,
less my little liquid friend. As I glanced he had evaporated leaving only
a mark behind as his epitaph. I pleaded with a god I knew well for my time
to leave this world and wished I could flow through the shattered walls,
but I could not fall through <I>these</I> cracks. </B></P>

<P><B>As night fell, even the warmth left me. Skin cold and damp, I was
being consumed by sheets of fire, the walls of my internal hell. I begged
for someone to melt away with, someone to share this isolation. </B></P>

<P><B>-Robert Wavra- </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=10%><IMG SRC="winter2.jpg" HEIGHT=166 WIDTH=185></TD>

<TD width=85%><A NAME="The River"></A><B>The River</B> 
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>The river flows with the current, carving its path. The seasons come
and go as they always do. </B></P>

<P><B>The wind gradually begins to bring bitter coldness from the north.
Life underneath the current is submerged in ice, gasping for the last drop
of air. The water remains frozen, hard as a rock.</B></P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=20%></TD>

<TD width=75%><B>Gradually, the ice begins to melt, and it is able to flow
freely once again. However, with this change the charcoal clouds that invade
the sky carry torment. As the water falls, the current gains momentum.
The water jostles and twists and turns. As the floor churns endlessly,
like the eye of a hurricane, the brown ugliness turns over and over. Ugliness
that would seem to go on forever.</B> 
<P><B>That was not the end of it.</B></P>

<P><B>The water calmed and gently lapped onto the shore, the black, lush
soil of the woods. The tiger lilies bloomed. Each petal coyly opening,
absorbing the radiant energy. A beam of sunlight trickled down from the
sky, shining on the river.</B></P>

<P><B>- Lisa Santowasso-</B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gifF" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Slow Growth"></A><B>Slow Growth</B> 
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>Falling and hitting, churning and bubbling, the water tips over the
edge to its destination below. I sit on a smooth grey rock and dangle my
feet into icy water that rushes to me from fifty feet above and tickles
neurons and pressure points. </B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="falls2.jpg" HEIGHT=227 WIDTH=151></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B>Around me cool lush trees block out harsh rays. They cast
shadows which seem to carry the chirps and snippets of bird talk, crickets
in harmony. I lie down and calmly breathe. The absence of light coats my
body with a slick grey that I can't wash away, can't even peel away. I
try to drift elsewhere, ignoring the shadows, focusing on my breath. Sucking
air swiftly with a whisper through my nostrils. The tight coppery smell
of the crackling water, sifting through the air reminding me... </B>
<P><B>not of rebirth but of the steely thickness dripping into streams
and veins- cold hospital floors where everything echoes. Everything frees
(my thoughts, words, motions), and it hurts to try and understand, so I
. . . </B></P>

<P><B>feel at peace. Everything loosens, and I can think with a clarity
that is new to me, but it feels old and familiar. And I accept this because
I am getting older even if my wrinkles aren't abundantly visible. If I
were younger, I would want time to slow down, so I could jump and play
on the rocks forever, not heeding my mother's call to &quot;be careful&quot;
and not falling over the rocks to an almost inevitable death because I
. . . </B></P>

<P><B>didn't understand that maybe I would be the last one left running
through those hospital halls, building DNA structures out of blocks, praying
with Bert and Ernie for a cure--wondering why I couldn't see . . . </B></P>

<P><B>the fish (her). </B></P>

<P><B>And then when I got into double digits I wanted time to speed up,
so I could be older and do everything like the &quot;big kids&quot; because
they never got lost in the woods. . . they never got lost in the tubes
or the elevators, lifting you upward to the sky or downward to a place
where I can only see her through the plastic bag she sits in (oh, I can't
remember the terminology because I'm so young, so young that my hands are
still so tiny and I can't reach the door handle), and I see her chest rise,
fall, rise, fall,. . .rise--slowly breathing different air --not the air
of the forest where... </B></P>

<P><B>I sit on the smooth grey rock and realize life and time are working
hand in hand because they both seem so unfair and refuse to be manipulated.
</B></P>

<P><B>-Kira Kohrherr - </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=75%><A NAME="Over the"></A><B>Over the Edge</B> 
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;Hand in hand, I walk through the mall with my girlfriend. It
was a lazy afternoon, and we were quite bored. I, in my infinite wisdom,
was struck with the brilliant idea of exploring the array of specialty
shops and department stores clumped together in everyone's favorite marvel
of modern shopping convenience-the mall. </B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=20%><IMG SRC="climb.jpg" HEIGHT=239 WIDTH=160></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B>We strolled along at a lethargic pace when, suddenly,
my arm was yanked with an unexpected ferocity. Before I realized what was
the matter, I passed under the sign which entitled my doom-Bath and Body
Works. This palace of hygiene haunts the dreams of every man ever to make
an entertaining experience of shopping. The ominous flow of the words off
the lips causes grown men to shiver in fear. I was truly petrified. </B>
<P><B>I thought to myself, Okay, you're a big guy. You can handle this.
It's just a stupid, feminine store. </B></P>

<P><B>Oh, how wrong one pitiful person can be. Smack! I'm slammed in the
face with the force of a Mack truck. Fruits and berries tear away at the
intricate patchwork of my sanity. My nostrils are on fire. The multitude
of scents presently entering my unsuspecting nose pushes me to the brink
of olfactory eruption. ''Look, it's blueberry bodywash,&quot; she marvels
as I grasp for a whiff of the uncorrupted oxygen necessary for life. &quot;Ooohh,
peach moisturizer. I love how my legs feel after I put this on.&quot; How
can she stand this odorous hell as it eats away at my weakening brain.
&quot;Oh, my god, lavender bubble bath. I can't wait to get home and hop
into the tub.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;No! Help me, dear lord! I can't take it anymore! God have mercy!&quot;
</B></P>

<P><B>There I told you the stupid story again. Now <I>please</I> loosen
this damn jacket.&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>- Dan DeLorenzo - </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="The Fires of Passion"></A><B>The Fires of Passion
</B>
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>His passion spits at me. Tongues flaring wildly about, raging and
out of control. He dances; moods so dynamic, constantly changing. Peaceful
and serene, as much as one can imagine. Until, swiftly, the earth's breath
carries him under her wing, illuminating and capturing the essence of the
night in his smoldering gray eyes. In the next instant, anger spouts upward,
erupting fiercely to a wild conclusion, warming me and sending a glow to
caress my skin. His eyes burn bright in mine. I close my eyes and inhale
his scent and smile. </B></P>

<P><B>-Alison Quairoli - </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="pr_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Ad Astra Per Aspera"></A><B>Ad Astra Per Aspera
</B>
<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>I was tired and it was late; already for some minutes I had been
bathed in that delicious warm numbness that sweeps over one in relaxation
of muscles long tense and strained from a day s rigors, but I could not
sleep. The insomnia was familiar, and I felt it creep up and envelop me
like a constricting gag, restraining me from the peace of losing myself
in blissful slumber. Though I was but a mere child of ten, I knew sleeplessness
as well as the contours of the bed in which I lay, but that made it no
less disconcerting. </B></P>

<P><B>Finally, unable to keep my eyes closed any longer, I unveiled them
to the pitch darkness hanging over my room, a cloak of deepest royal purple.
I cannot pretend that the dark did not frighten me; although I had, of
course, performed the routine ceremony of checking under my bed before
retiring, some innate part of me deep within whispered; black rumors brought
terror flooding through every nerve of my body. My limbs tensed tight as
a ready bowstring, and in that moment of sickening fear, I knew that Morpheus
had truly abandoned me this night. </B></P>

<P><B>I could not remain there, lying still in the stifling blackness with
Heaven-only-knew-what sort of malignant creature advancing upon me. So,
with a gasp, I finally sprang from my prison and ran to the window. </B></P>

<P><B>Thick, blue curtains separated me from the summer night sky beyond,
but I drew them back quickly and threw open the glass pane with a trembling
hand. Before me, the sky stretched endlessly onwards, and my eyes roved
rapidly as I searched its surface frantically for some ray of hope. It
was a cloudy night, however, and there was nothing above but ebony clouds
racing in a light breeze. My throat constricted; the oppressive gloom pressed
in on me from above, from below, from all around, and I felt as though
I would scream... </B></P>

<P><B>Suddenly, for a mere moment, a gap opened in the clouds on high to
reveal one bright, glittering star, whose rays fell upon me as balm upon
a wound. Like a diamond in a sea of velvet it was, myriad rays streaming
from its facets onto my upturned face, imparting to me in that fraction
of a second the calm and serenity of unimaginable age, knowledge, and wisdom.
</B></P>

<P><B>In another moment, it was gone, the black clouds closing over that
one, tiny hole in Heaven as the Red Sea closed over the head of the Egyptians.
But my fright was gone as well, banished like Arcita from Theseus and Athens,
and I smiled into the darkness that had so recently evoked a grimace of
horror. </B></P>

<P><B>Closing the window and the curtains, I turned back to my bed, fatigue
abruptly washing over me. Confining prison had become a welcome haven,
and I clambered eagerly into the waiting embrace of the crisp, clean sheets.
Just before I drifted off into slumber, however, I remembered a Bible verse
so often quoted by my mother and father - &quot;A light shines in the darkness,
and the darkness has not overcome it.&quot; Smiling again, I rolled over
and let myself go down into the lightless realms of sleep. Ad astra per
aspera, indeed. </B></P>

<P><B>-Katie Lynch- </B></P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Free Writes Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

