<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="Electric Soup Community"></A><B>Electric Soup
Short Stories</B></H1>

<CENTER><P><B>Volume 6 contains the following selections: </B></P></CENTER>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=40%><A HREF="#Getaway"><IMG SRC="brlittel.jpg" HEIGHT=139 WIDTH=148></A></TD>

<TD width=60%>
<UL>
<P><A HREF="#Getaway"><IMG SRC="yellowba.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14></A><B><A HREF="#Getaway">Getaway</A>
by Laura Kuznicki</B></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<P><A HREF="#Drive-By"><IMG SRC="yellowba.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14></A><B><A HREF="#Drive-By">Drive-By</A>
by Helen&nbsp;McWilliams</B></P>
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Click here to&nbsp;Return to the <A HREF="esv6toc.html">Volume 6
Main Menu</A> </B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="or_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Getaway"></A><B>Getaway</B> 
<P><B>By Laura Kuznicki</B> </P>

<P><B>The tires screeched around the turn in the road. Sirens blaring could
be heard miles away. The pressure was on as the getaway car sped away.
People on the street were frantically screaming as they tried to recall
the face of the masked man.</B> </P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="highway2.jpg" HEIGHT=114 WIDTH=204></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B>Charlie and Ed had been best friends since the second
grade. Now they were twenty-three-year-olds and still as immature as they
had been then. Behind the wheel was Charlie, a young, handsome man, though
not very bright. Ed sat in the passenger seat, huddled in a small mass,
air puffing in and out of his lungs at a quickening pace.</B> 
<P><B>&quot;Drive faster, you idiot! You're gonna get us caught!&quot;
Ed was letting the horror in his voice show through. &quot;I knew this
was a bad idea. Why I am doing this?&quot; Ed mumbled as Charlie pressed
down on the gas pedal, and the acceleration was felt. &quot;Ah, now that's
more like it.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>The bright, sunny day slowly turned into a dark, mischievous night.
The chase had been on for five hours, and Charlie's station wagon was running
out of fuel. Charlie knew that it would be over soon, and that they would
be in a great deal of trouble. The police car behind the old, beat-up car
was still shining its bright lights into their window. The loud siren was
pounding in the young mens' heads. This would be a day that they would
never forget.</B> </P>

<P><B>Charlie's mind was in a raw mass of confusion. He knew what he was
doing was wrong, even though he had not done the crime himself. He would
be an accessory when they were found, and that would be just as bad as
doing it himself. Guilt swept over his entire body until he began to quiver.
His hands shook with fear and the car sped out of control.</B> </P>

<P><B>Ed gripped the stolen money in his sweaty hands and prayed that his
pitiful life would be spared. <I>What would my mother think if she were
still alive?</I> Ed thought. The idea swept through his mind with tremendous
pain. <I>It's all over now. My life is over.</I> One single tear ran down
Ed's face. He knew what he had to do. </B></P>

<P><B>The spinning station wagon flung itself into the middle of the road
at a speed that was unimaginable. The police stopped their patrol car and
quickly hopped out. The wagon came to a halt with a loud smash. Ed's and
Charlies' seemingly lifeless bodies were thrown through the windshield
onto the soft spring grass. The chase was over.</B> </P>

<P><B>Emergency vehicles raced into the scene. It was unknown whether or
not Ed and Charlie were still alive. The bodies were loaded into the ambulance,
and it was determined that Ed had died. Charlie was barely holding on.
They reached the hospital in a matter of minutes. Charlie would eventually
be all right.</B> </P>

<P><B>Weeks later, Charlie had almost totally recovered. He still had to
go through physical therapy, but all his wounds had healed. It was the
day that Charlie was going to be able to go home from the hospital when
he saw the silver-badged men come into his room. &quot;Are you Charles
Edensmer?&quot; they inquired.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Yes, sir.&quot; Charlie answered. Fear built up inside of him.</B>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;Well, I am afraid that you are being charged with the robbery
of Sunny County Bank, young man. Do you deny this charge?&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;I only drove the car, sir.&quot; said Charlie.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Did you take part in this crime?&quot; the officer asked Charlie.</B>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;Yes, sir, I did.&quot; he replied.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Then you have the right to remain silent. Anything you say
can and will be used against you in the court of law.&quot; The handcuffs
were placed on Charlie, and he was taken away.</B> </P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Short Story Menu</A></B></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="or_bar.gif" HEIGHT=11 WIDTH=640></P>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><A NAME="Drive-By"></A><B>Drive-By </B>
<P><B>By Helen McWilliams</B> </P>

<P><BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><B>We kept driving. And driving still. Hoping and waiting and hoping
some more. Courtney was trying to fill a void, and I was trying to understand
if the void needed filling. The car was wet with exhaustion. It had been
hours... or days.</B> </P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%><IMG SRC="oneway2.jpg" HEIGHT=114 WIDTH=204></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD width=5%></TD>

<TD width=65%><B>Courtney started humming. It was a nondescript, bored
hum, most likely never having been labeled a tune in its short life. The
initially endearing hum grew incessant. I gritted my teeth and sighed through
my nose. None of the pressure dissipated in the deep sigh. The humming
continued, eventually blending with the roar of the jalopy's motor. I closed
my eyes, relaxed, leaned against the seat. Everything was dank outside.
Trees and wet leaves and mud. I would have liked to swim in the humidity.
Courtney Courtney Courtney. The sound of the word rolled around my brain
cavity and echoed. Courtney Courtney Courtney.</B> 
<P><B>I had been single for two weeks. Mmmm. It was quiet, but comforting.
The nerves, the confusion, the excitement... all alleviated for the time-being.
Still, I had loved him once. Thoroughly. Letting him in felt right. Suddenly
my stomach turned itself inside out. Knowing I was free was like knowing
my name: familiar, but unfortunate.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;This is all getting sort of monotonous, isn't it Phoenix?&quot;
she asked me. I ignored her. &quot;Isn't it? Didn't we pass that tree already?&quot;
I sort of smiled and shook my head. The road was still brown, but the pebbles
were beginning to get thicker, metamorphosing into rocks. And then boulders
and finally... mud. Courtney began to giggle. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;My tires are really gonna get pissed at me for this one, Pheen.&quot;
I debated questioning the moodiness of her tires. I decided to let it pass.
Bump bump bump... roooolllll. My stomach felt like a nuclear waste dump.
Bump bump bump... roooollll. Bump bump bump... rooolll. The irregularity
of the road was unusually regular. </B></P>

<P><B>The sun beat down against my forehead, which started to melt. I could
actually feel my skin softening, liquefying, and dripping off the tip of
my nose. Turning to Courtney, I waited to see the look of revulsion on
her face. She just smiled complacently. Apparently she hadn't noticed.
I smiled to myself.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Do you feel like you're melting or is it just me?&quot; I pondered
aloud.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;You're hot? I can put the air conditioning on if you want,&quot;
she replied, gently pressing the small button labeled &quot;AC&quot; next
to the cigarette lighter.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;That's nice, thanks.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Why didn't you say something before? I'm sorry,&quot; she apologized
for not sensing my disomfort. Courtney is like that. Courtney lives in
my ribcage sometimes.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;No, don't worry about it. I'm not actually hot.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;But you said--&quot; Courtney stopped short, knowing me well
enough to understand that even if I <I>tried</I> to explain it to her,
I would get nowhere.</B> </P>

<P><B>Liking the air conditioner, watching the vents rotate like eyeballs.
Cool air across my face, now my neck, now my collarbones, now my face...
All the places he had loved me. All the places he had inhabited and made
his. All the places he had discovered and charted.</B> </P>

<P><B>I said his name aloud, slowly, letting it <I>sliiiiide </I>off of
my tongue like diseased water. The kind that quenches your thirst right
before it kills you.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;What did you say?&quot; Courtney asked softly, with aged Merlot
in her voice.</B> </P>

<P><B>I repeated his name. I even said his middle name. The name felt like
an ice-pick, but sounded something like light rain against sand.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;What about him?&quot; she questioned, fearing any answer.</B>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;Oh nothing. I just felt like saying his name,&quot; I returned
cheerfully. She knew false cheeriness. She regarded me out of the corner
of her eye. Hell, it was true, mostly. I did feel like saying his name.
I also felt like maybe he'd appear in the backseat like a genie if I said
it nicely enough. I needed him to pop up out of nowhere, call me his Baby
and tell me things would be good. He'd take a detour to the local Super
Stop &amp; Shop. We would buy cereal (Frosted Flakes or Fruity Pebbles
maybe) and eat it with our fists. Sugar grinding against our teeth, we
would laugh at nothing. And everything. And nothing again.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Yeah? You sure?&quot; she vocalized her doubt.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Hell's yeah.&quot; I don't know where we had picked up that
phrase. Hell's yeah. It was similar to &quot;word.&quot; White girls in
the suburbs don't say Hell's yeah. We said Hell's yeah on a daily basis.
Hell's yeah.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Hey Phoenix, do you want to talk about things with... you know...?&quot;
Yes I knew. But it was more than I wanted to know. So I ignored her and
it was all calm in my heart again.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Feel like stopping?&quot; Courtney asked too loudly. What a
dumb question. Feel like stopping? I felt like starting. I felt like I
had never been. I felt like I had never even seen the kind of people who
had started in the past. Stopping was so out of the question. Sooooo out
of the question.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Put on your windshield wipers,&quot; I commanded.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;It's not raining,&quot; Courtney argued. It wasn't. &quot;It's
clear out.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;I know, I just--&quot; My thoughts interrupted my sentence.
I wanted the hypnotism of the windshield wipers. I wanted the constant
swish to comfort me. I wanted some constancy. I wanted something I could
predict. Life left me confused.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;How hard do you think it would be to become a hermit?&quot;
I asked loudly. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Professionally?&quot; </B></P>

<P><B>I giggled too quickly. &quot;Yeah.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>Courtney thought for a moment. &quot;I dunno. Pretty easy I guess.
Whadya' really need to be a hermit? Cabin, woods, wild animals--&quot;</B>
</P>

<P><B>&quot;What are the animals for?&quot; I interrupted.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;They're, you know, hunt and kill?&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;I don't hunt.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;You could learn,&quot; she encouraged.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;I don't kill.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>That course of conversation sort of sank into the false wood paneling
enclosing the station wagon. I wondered silently how long it would take
to learn which berries were edible and which were poisonous. Nuts and berries;
isn't that what one survives on in the woods? I didn't remember ever having
seen wild nuts in my life. Seeds, maybe. Nuts, never.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;So he's really got you freaking out, huh?&quot; Courtney asked
quietly.</B> </P>

<P><B>I pulled a blueberry bagel out of the cooler and started chewing
on it carefully. The blueberries just tasted right. I thought about how
nice it would be to live on blueberries for a few years. But I'd miss the
bagel part.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;I mean,&quot; she continued, &quot;You're not doing too well
are you?&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>Apparently my attempt to silence her by eating a blueberry bagel
was fruitless. So I rolled down the window.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Pheen, the A/C is on,&quot; she told me.</B> </P>

<P><B>I opened the door.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;Pheen!&quot; Courtney cried, slamming on the breaks. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;I dropped something,&quot; I told her. </B></P>

<P><B>&quot;Jesus Christ! I hope it was pretty damn important to risk your
life over retrieving. What did you drop?&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>Hum. Rattle. Bump. Roll. Swish.</B> </P>

<P><B>&quot;My guard.&quot;</B> </P>

<P><B>Return to <A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">Short Story Menu</A></B><A HREF="#Electric Soup Community">
</A></P>
</TD>

<TD width=30%></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

