Date: Tuesday, 31-Dec-96 22:38:09 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<u><h3><u>Hypothesis</u></h3></u>
The third step in the Scientific Method is to make an educated guess at the solution.  This is called the hypothesis, since it is a reasonable solution based on knowledge and judgement rather than on ignorance and superstition.
<a href="labs3.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br>
<a href="test.html"><h5>Go to 
Next Step</h5></a><br>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-39</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA003-000024-B009-223</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://scratchy.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us:80/science/test.html 205.247.5.34 19961231223814 text/html 2582
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tuesday, 31-Dec-96 22:38:18 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<u><h2><u><center>Test (Experiment)</center></u></h2>

It is now time to test your hypothesis.  The experiment must be thought out ahead of time to obtain all the necessary materials.  The test must be done with accurate notes, so other people can reproduce the same experiment in the same conditions.  Each experiment must contain two procedures:  One procedure must contain  <a href="#control">CONTROL</a>and one must contain a <a href="#variable">VARIABLE</a>.  Furthermore, there must be a <a href="#Number">SUFFICIENT NUMBER OF EXPERIMENTAL ORGANISMS</a>, <a href="#repeat">REPETITION</a>, and Careful Observations.  

<a href="labs3.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a>
<a href="conclude.html"><h5>Go to 
Next Step</h5></a><hr>



<a name="control"></a>
<h3><b>CONTROL</b></h3>
This is something that every valid experiment must contain.  In two procedures, the procedures are identical, until, at one point, a <a href="#variable"> VARIABLE </a>
is introduced.  The procedure with the variable is the one involving the experiment.  The procedure without the variable is called control.

<a href="test.html"><h5>Continue Reading</h5></a><br>


<a name="variable"></a>
<h3><b>VARIABLE</b></h3>

A variable is anything that changes.In the two procedures, this is the procedure with the change.  However, there can only be <b>one</b> variable, otherwise, the test is invalid.  If this was not the case, you wouldn't know if the results were because of the variable or whether ir was altered by something else.  You must always be on the lookout for extraneous variable (i.e., the temperature, humidity, placement of your tools, and other things you would ordinarily not pay attention to)

<a href="test.html"><h5>Continue Reading</h5></a><br>



<a name="Number"></a> 
<h3><b>SUFFICIENT NUMBER OF ORGANISMS</b></h3>
Large numbers of organisms should be used so that variables such as disease and individual differences may be ruled out.  Also, mathematically speaking, the more organisms, the better the accuracy.  Also, do not be quick to assume that works on some animals will work on humans.  The results may be completely different.

<a href="test.html"><h5>Continue Reading</h5></a><br>

<a name="repeat"></a>
<b><h3>REPETITION</h3></b>
An experiment must be repeated many times to assure its reliability.  If it is not repeated, you can not be sure if the experiment is valid or if it was just a fluke.

<a href="test.html"><h5>Continue Reading</h5></a><br>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-40</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA003-000024-B009-232</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://scratchy.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us:80/science/conclude.html 205.247.5.34 19961231223825 text/html 584
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tuesday, 31-Dec-96 22:38:30 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<u><h3><u>Conclusion</u></h3></u>
After careful evaluations of your results, you must answer one question:  Was my hypothesis correct?  Even if you have proved your hypothesis false, it does not necessarily mean it is wrong.  In your experiment, you may have uncovered a new hypothesis.  Remember though, a good conclusion often leads to another hypothesis.
<a href="labs3.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a>
<a href="terms.html"><h5>Go to 
Scientific Terms</h5></a>

