<body>

<h2 align=center><b>Weight</b></h2>

<p>This is the amount of force that gravity exerts on an object. This means
that, depending upon the <img src="gif/denver2.gif" height=200 width=200 align=right>amount
of gravity at a given location, the weight of an object varies. The larger
a heavenly body is, the more gravity it exerts, and, consequently, the
more something weights. For example, if you weight 100 pounds on Earth,
you would weight 20 pounds on the moon and 2800 pounds on the sun. Altitude
also plays an important role in weight. The greater the altitude, the less
something weighs. So, if you want to &quot;lose weight&quot;, go to Colorado!
You may ask how scientists (and people everywhere) avoid getting different
measurements depending upon their location. If one scientist weighed an
object in Colorado and one weighed the same object in the Sahara Desert,
their answers would be totally different. The solution to this problem
is <a href="mass.html">MASS</a>. </p>

<h5><a href="weight.html">Go Back to Weight, Mass, and Density
<br></a><a href="mass.html">Go to Mass
<br></a><a href="density.html">Go to Density
<br></a><a href="basics.html">Go Back to the Basics</a></h5>

</body>
</html>
