<b><h2><center>Conduction</center></h2></b>

In conduction (conduct meaning "to lead"), the molecules must touch.  When molecules are "bumped", they begin to mave fater, thus "bumping" the molecules next to them.  The process is much like a chain reaction spreading the heat throughout the object.  This is much like when you put a <a href="#example">Nail in a Flame</a><br>
<a href="transfer.html"><h5>Go to Top of
Heat Transfer</h5></a>
<a href="conins.html"><h5>Go to Conductors/Insulators</h5></a><hr>




<a name="example"><u><b><h3>Example:  A Nail in a Flame</h3></b></a></u>

If you were to hold the end of a nail in a flame, the heat would move up to your hand by means of conduction.  The molecules in part of the nail in the flame begin the bounce around faster.  Soon, the molecules bump into one another, forming a chain reaction.  The molecules at the end of the nail (in the flame) conduct the heat upwards, towards your hand.






