<b><h2><center>Convection</center></h2></b>
With convection, the molecules of a heated gas or liquid actually move from one place to another.  This is best explained through an example; <a href="#stove">The Stove</a>
<a href="transfer.html"><h5>Go to Top of
Heat Transfer</h5></a>
<!--<a href="radidate.html"><h5>Go to Radiation</h5></a><hr>
-->
<a name="stove"><u><b><h3>Example:  The Stove</h3></b></a></u>

Suppose you had a stove in the middle of a large room.  Through <a href= "conduct.html"> conduction</a>, the heat passes through the walls of the stove and out into the air of the room.  This air expands.  The cold air near the windows weighs more than the hot air (remember; hot air rises and cool air sinks).  Consequently, this cooler, heavier air sinks to the floor, forcing the air aroundt he stove to move towards the ceiling.  As more hot air comes out of the stove, the cooler air continues to push it towards the ceiling, thus continuing the cycle.






</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-60</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA003-000024-B010-86</DOCOLDNO>
