<b><h2><center>Radiation</center></h2></b>

To get heat through radiation, a hot object must give out radiant heat.  As an object becomes hotter and hotter, it gives out more and more radiant energy.  It travels in a straight line through space.  However, this energy is not true heat.  Only when this radiant energy strikes certain materials that can absorb it does it turn into heat.  The radiant energy sets the molecules of that material into rapid motion, thus transfering heat.  In radiation, no molecules are need to transfer the heat.  It is a lot like our <a href="#sun">SUN</a><br>
<a href="transfer.html"><h5>Go to Top of
Heat Transfer</h5></a><hr>

<a name="sun"><u><b><h3>Example:  The Sun</h3></b></a></u>

If you recall, the sun is 93 million miles away.  In this empty space, there are no molecules.  However, we still receive heat from the sun; we would die without it.  The radiant energy (the sun) travels in a straight line through space and hits our Earth.  However, this radiant energy is not true heat.  For, if it were, the tops of the mountians would be hot as they're closer to the sun than the hot deserts.  In fact, the air isn't warmed much by the sun.  The sun can also travel through glass without affecting it (ever bask in the warmth of the sun spilling through the window; you're hot, yet the window pane is cold?).  This is because both air and glass do not absorb much radiant energy.  You can only feel the heat when the radiant energy is absorbed by a material, is changed into heat energy, then sets the molecules of the material moving faster and then, finally, the material gets warmer.  What a complicated sun we have!






</DOC>
