<h2><b><center>Definitions and Conclusions</center></b></h2>
<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="bpoint.html"><h5>Go Back the Boiling Point</h5></a></u></center><hr>

<h4><center>What is the boiling point and how can it be altered?</center><br></h4>

According to Funk and Wagnall's Dictionary, the boiling point is "The temperature at which a liquid boils; at normal atmospheric pressure, the boiling point of water is 212 degrees Fahrenheit or 100 degrees Celcius".  However, because all thermometers are different, in the classroom, we said that, since water can't go higher than its boiling point, we would define it as the temperature at which the thermometer would go no higher in that solution.  

It is also important to know that boiling point of water does NOT change unless you alter the water in some way.  For instance, if you add salt, the boiling point will be affected, but, if you only deny it oxygen, it will not be affected.  You must physically change the water.


