<h1 align=center><b>Salt</b></h1>

<center><p><u><img src="gif/smile.gif" border=0 height=34 width=35></p></center>

<h5 align=center><a href="bpoint.html">Go Back the Boiling Point</a></h5>

<center><p></u><img src="gif/chemist.gif" border=0 height=200 width=200 align=right>
<hr></p></center>

<h3 align=center><i>What is the effect of salt on the boiling point of
water?</i> 
<br></h3>

<p>Ever wonder why your grandmother would always put salt in the pot before
cooking spaghetti? 
<br>
<br>Well, after conducting an experiment, we found that salt actually raised
the boiling point of water. We mixed up two solutions; one had 150mL of
plain tap water, another had 150mL of plain tap water mixed with 25g of
salt. The solution with salt took 5 minutes and 8 seconds to boil. Its
boiling point was 109 degress Celcius. The beaker without the salt took
5 minutes to boil. Its boiling point was 106 degrees Celcius. Though with
salt it takes more time to reach a boil, the increased temperature allows
things (such as spaghetti) to cook faster. 
<br><img src="gif/boiling.gif" border=0 height=200 width=200 align=right></p>

