<h2><b><center>Reduced Air Pressure</center></b></h2>
<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="bpoint.html"><h5>Go Back the Boiling Point</h5></a></u></center><hr>

<h4><center>What effect does reducing the air pressure have on the boiling point of water?</center><br></h4>

Since water boils at approximentally 100 degrees Celcius, at "normal atmorspheric pressure", what would happen if you greatly reduced that pressure?<br><br>

Through an experiment which involoved monitoring the temperature of water in a beaker (all the while sucking air out of the bell jar it was contained it), we obtained our results:  When you reduce the air pressure, water can boil at a lowered temperature.  Though we had not altered or heated the water in any way, after we reduced the air pressure, it began to boil at its original temperature (25 degrees Celcius).  Thus, we concluded that, becuase the water was not at "normal atmospheric pressure", it would boil at a lower temperature. 


