<h1><u><center>Batholiths</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="intrude.html"><h5>Go Back to Intrusive Vulcanism</h5></a></u></center><hr>

Beneath the earth's surface lays many pools of molten rock 
<a href="#magma"> (Magma) </a>.  As cracks make their way down to these pools, magma <a href="#intrude">Intrudes</a>and squeezes in between the layers of rock.  This molten rock lie so far beneath the surface that it takes a long time to cool.  Consequently, large amounts of granite form.<br>
Over time, batholiths may become exposed due to erosion.  <br>
Smaller batholiths are called <a href="stock.html">Stocks</a>.<br> 
Many of the world's mountain ranges have batholiths as their cores.  Some examples are the Coast Range of British  Columbia, the Sierra Nevadas, and the Rocky Mountains.<br>
<a href="lacc.html">To Laccoliths</a><br> 
<a href="dike.html">To Dikes</a><br>
<a href="sill.html">To Sills</a><br>  
<a href="stock.html">To Stocks</a><br> 
<a href="bath.html">To Top of Batholiths</a><hr>

<a name="magma"></a>
<b><h3>Magma</h3></b>
This is the molten rock material within the earth.<br>
<a href="bath.html">Continue Reading</a><br><br>

<a name="intrude"></a>
<b><h3>Intrude</h3></b>
This means to push upward.<br>
<a href="bath.html">Continue Reading</a><br><br>


