<h1><u><center>Laccoliths</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="intrude.html"><h5>Go Back to Intrusive Vulcanism</h5></a></u></center><hr>

These are mushroom-shaped intursions of magma between rock layers.  Since it is difficult for the magma to make its way between the laters, it pushes the overlying rock into domes.  <br>
As a result, dome-shaped mountains on the surface form.  The Henry Mountains of Utah and the Orange Mountains of New Jersey are two such examples.  <br>
Laccoliths, like batholiths, are made up of granite or diorite rock.  Both types produce large crystals because the magma takes so long to cool.<br>

