<h1><u><center>Earthquakes and Volcanoes:  Location</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="earthgen.html"><h5>Go Back to General Information on Earthquakes</h5></a></u></center><hr>

<h3>Ever notice that, where there's an earthquake, there's usually a volcano?  For instance, Southern California has earthquakes, and nearby Northern California, Washington and Oregon have volcaoes.  Why is this?</h3>

This is because volcano and earthquake activity is related; both are formed because of plate activity and unrest.  Often times, plates near each other move different ways, and therefore have different types of boundaries.<br>

<a href="eandv.html">To Top of Earthquakes and Volcanoes:  Location</a><br>
<a href="earthgen.html">To General Information on Earthquakes</a><br>


