<h1 align=center><u>San Francisco</u></h1>

<center><p><u><img src="gif/smile.gif" border=0 height=34 width=35></p></center>

<h5 align=center><a href="earthgen.html">Go Back to General Information
on Earthquakes</a></h5>

<center><p></u><img src="gif/calif2.gif" height=200 width=300 align=right>
<hr></p></center>

<h2 align=center><b>The City that Waits to Die</b></h2>

<p>Why is San Francisco called this? It is for a variety of reasons. Once,
in 1906, the city experienced an earthquake measuring 8.3 on the <a href="richter.html">Richter
Scale</a> which left 3,000 people dead. It also caused a 270 mile-long
segment of the fault to jump 21 feet in just a few seconds. Since then,
the fault has been relatively inactive; indeed, it seems to be locked.
You see, San Francisco's real problem is not actual earthquakes; it's the
lack of small ones. If small ones occurred, then the tension would gradually
ease on the two plates and we wouldn't be waiting for the &quot;Big One&quot;.

<br>
<br>To add to the city's problem, a lot of the government-run facilities
are located directly on the fault line (see <a href="property.html">Property</a>).

<br>
<br><a href="eandv.html">To Top of San Francisco
<br></a><a href="earthgen.html">To General Information on Earthquakes</a>
<br></p>

</body>
</html>
