<h1><u><center>Shallow, Medium, and Deep Focus Earthquakes</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="earthgen.html"><h5>Go Back to General Information on Earthquakes</h5></a></u></center><hr>

<h3>There are three types of earthquakes:  
<ul>
<LI><a href="#shallow">Shallow Focus</a>
<LI><a href="#med">Medium Focus</a>
<LI><a href="#deep">Deep Focus</a><hr></h3></ul>

<a name="shallow">
<b><h2>Shallow Focus Earthquakes</h2></b>
The majority of earthquakes are shallow-focus.  They occur along ocean ridge systems and transform boundaries.  They are long, but close to the surface.  For example, one may be 450 miles long, yet only 25 miles deep.<br>
<a href="#med">Go to Medium Focus</a><br>
<a href="#deep">Go to Deep Focus</a><br>
<a href="focus.html">Return to top of Menu</a><br>

<a name="med">
<b><h2>Medium Focus Earthquakes</h2></b>
Medium Focus Earthquakes are of moderate length and moderate depth.  An average one would be 320 miles long and 300 miles deep.  They occur along transform and divergent boundaries.<br>
<a href="#deep">Go to Deep Focus</a><br>
<a href="#shallow">Go to Shallow Focus</a><br>
<a href="focus.html">Return to top of Menu</a>
<br>

<a name="deep">
<b><h2>Deep Focus Earthquakes</h2></b>
Deep Focus Earthquakes are the most disasterous ones.  They are short in length, yet very deep (An example is 50 miles long, 650 miles deep).  Oceanic trenches are associated with these type of earthquakes.  They also occur along subduction zones.<br>
<a href="#shallow">Go to Shallow Focus</a><br>
<a href="#med">Go to Medium Focus</a><br>
<a href="focus.html">Return to top of Menu</a>
<br>
</DOC>
