<h1><u><center>The Richter Scale</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="earthgen.html"><h5>Go Back to General Information on Earthquakes</h5></a></u></center><hr>

The Richter Scale was invented by a man named Charles Richter in 1935.  He devised this system of measuring quakes because he was tired of journalists asking him to compare the earthquakes.  The Richter Scale uses a seismograph to measure <a href="seismic.html">seismic waves</a>.<br><br>

Now, scientists have abandoned the Richter Scale and have gone to using the Moment-Magnitude Scale.  Essentially, this is determined by multiplying the area of a fault's rupture surface by the distance the earth moves along the fault.<br>
<a href="sanfran.html"><h5>Continue Reading about San Francisco</h5></a><br><br>

The Scale and how the numbers compare:
<h5>Note:  each number is 10 times as powerful as it goes up each number
</h5>
<OL>
<LI>Felt by instruments only
<LI>Felt by sensitive people and sensitive animals (10 times #1)
<LI>Felt by many people--feels like a passing truck (100 times #1)
<LI>Felt by everyone; pictures fall off the wall (1,000 times #1)
<LI>Damage--may cause weak walls to crack and fall (10,000 times #1)
<LI>A destuctive earthquake in populated areas; falling smokestacks, etc. (100,000 times #1)
<LI>A major earthquake causing serious damage (1,000,000 times #1)
<LI>A disaster--a great earthquake that produces total destruction to nearby communities {1906 in San Francisco--8.3} (10,000,000 times #1)
<LI>Libson, Portugal had the highest ever in 1775 at 8.9.  Who knows? (100,000,000 times #1)</UL>


<a href="richter.html">Go to Top of Richter Scale</a><br>
<a href="earthgen.html">Go Back to General Information on Earthquakes</a>
</DOC>
