<h1><u><center>The Sun's Rays</center></u></h1>

<center><u><IMG SRC="gif/smile.gif"><a href="season.html"><h5>Go Back to Seasons</h5></a></u></center><hr>


<h2><i>As the sun shines on the earth, it produces two kinds of rays:</i></h2>
<UL><LI><a href="#direct"><h3>Direct Rays</h3></a>
<LI><a href="#indirect"><h3>Indirect Rays</h3></a></ul><br>
<a href="axis.html"><h5>Go Back to the Earth's Tilted Axis</a>
<a href="season.html"><h5>Go Back to Seasons</h5></a><br><hr>

<a name="direct"></a>
<b><h3>Direct Rays</h3></b> 
These rays are those that strike the earth's surface at a 90 degree angle.  These are the hottest rays; they strike wherever the earth is closest to the sun.  Due to the inclination of its axis, this place constantly changes.  On December 21, this is the Tropic of Capricorn; on March 21, this is the Equator; on June 21, this is the Tropic of Cancer; and, on September 22, this is the Equator once again (see <a href="rotate.html">Revolution</a>).  <br>
<a href="#indirect">Go to Indirect Rays</a><br>
<a href="rays.html">Go back to the Sun's Rays</a><br><br>


<a name="indirect"></a>
<b><h3>Indirect Rays</h3></b> 
These are rays  which strike the earth at diminishing angles, such as at the poles.  They strike above the Tropic of Cancer and below the Tropic of Capricorn.    <br>
<a href="#direct">Go to Direct Rays</a><br>
<a href="rays.html">Go back to the Sun's Rays</a><br>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-83</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA003-000024-B010-412</DOCOLDNO>
