<body>

<h1 align=center><u>The Four Seasons</u></h1>

<center><p><u><img src="gif/smile.gif" border=0 height=34 width=35></p></center>

<h5 align=center><a href="season.html">Go Back to Seasons</a></h5>

<center><p></u>
<hr></p></center>

<h3>Once every year, the earth experiences four seasons:</h3>

<ul>
<li><a href="#winter">Winter</a> </li>

<li><a href="#spring">Spring</a> </li>

<li><a href="#summer">Summer</a> </li>

<li><a href="#fall">Autumn</a></li>
</ul>

<h5><a href="season.html">Go Back to Seasons</a></h5>

<p>
<hr><a name="winter"></a><img src="gif/snow_cpl.gif" border=0 height=200 width=200 align=right></p>

<h2><b>Winter</b></h2>

<p>Called the Winter Solstice, December 21 is the first day of winter in
the Northern Hemisphere. Since the Southern Hemisphere is closer to the
sun, the <a href="rays.html">direct rays </a>are striking the Tropic of
Capricorn, and therefore, they experience warm weather. Consequently, since
the Northern Hemisphere is tilted away from the sun, the direct rays are
not striking on the Tropic of Cancer and they experience cool weather.

<br>
<br></p>

<h3><img src="gif/snow296.gif" height=200 width=200 align=left>On the winter
solstice:</h3>

<ol>
<li>The direct rays are as far south as they go; the Tropic of Capricorn
</li>

<li>The North Pole is in the middle of a 6-month period of darkness </li>

<li>The South Pole is in the middle of a 6-month period of light </li>

<li>It is the shortest day in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>The sun rises south of east and sets south of west </li>

<li>Winter begins in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>Summer begins in the Southern Hemisphere</li>
</ol>

<h5><a href="#spring">To Spring 
<br></a><a href="#summer">To Summer 
<br></a><a href="#fall">To autumn</a> 
<br></h5>

<h2><a name="spring"></a><b>Spring</b><img src="gif/suny_cpl.gif" height=200 width=200 align=right></h2>

<p>As the revolution continues, the direct rays gradually shift upward,
resting on the equator on March 21. This marks the first day of spring,
or the vernal equinox. On this day, there are exactly twelve hours of daylight
and twelve hours of darkness. The earth and the sun are 93,000,000 million
miles apart. 
<br>
<br></p>

<h3><img src="gif/rain064.gif" height=200 width=200 align=left>On the vernal
equinox:</h3>

<ol>
<li>The direct rays are at the equator </li>

<li>Six months of daylight begin at the North Pole </li>

<li>Six months of darkness begin at the South Pole </li>

<li>Twelve hours of daylight and twelve hours of darkness all over the
earth </li>

<li>The sun rises due east and sets due west </li>

<li>Spring begins in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>Autumn begins in the Southern Hemisphere</li>
</ol>

<h5><a href="#summer">To Summer 
<br></a><a href="#fall">To autumn 
<br></a><a href="#winter">To Winter</a> 
<br></h5>

<h2><a name="summer"></a><b>Summer</b><img src="gif/sun062.gif" height=200 width=200 align=right></h2>

<p>As the earth continues to revolve around the sun, the direct rays continue
to move upward. On June 21, on the summer solstice, the direct rays are
as north as they go; the Tropic of Cancer (the earth has reached the aphelion
and is coming back closer to the sun). 
<br>
<br></p>

<h3>On the summer solstice:</h3>

<ol>
<li>The direct rays are as far north as they go; the Tropic of Cancer </li>

<li>The North Pole is in the middle of a six-month period of light </li>

<li>The South Pole is in the middle of a six-month period of darkness </li>

<li>It is the longest day of the year in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>The sun rises north of east and sets north of west </li>

<li>Summer begins in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>Winter begins in the Southern Hemisphere</li>
</ol>

<h5><a href="#fall">To Autumn 
<br></a><a href="#winter">To Winter 
<br></a><a href="#spring">To Spring</a> 
<br></h5>

<h2><a name="fall"></a><img src="gif/wind_cpl.gif" height=200 width=200 align=right><b>Autumn</b></h2>

<p>The direct rays are now begining their descent downward. On September
22, they stop on the equator, the date of the autumnal equinox. Like spring,
there are exactly twelve hours of both daylight and darkness and the two
bodies are 93,000,000 miles apart. 
<br>
<br></p>

<h3>On the Autumnal Equinox:</h3>

<ol>
<li>The direct rays are at the equator </li>

<li>Six months of darkness begin at the North Pole </li>

<li>Six months of light begin at the South Pole </li>

<li>Twelve hours of darkness and twelve hours of light all over the earth
</li>

<li>The sun rises due east and sets due west </li>

<li>Autumn begins in the Northern Hemisphere </li>

<li>Spring begins in the Southern Hemisphere</li>
</ol>

<h5><a href="#winter">To Winter 
<br></a><a href="#spring">To Spring 
<br></a><a href="#summer">To Summer 
<br></a><a href="season.html">To Top of the Four Seasons 
<br></h5>

</body>
</html>
