<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Bryozoa</b></u></h2>

<h3><u>Or Moss Animal</u></h3>

<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>
<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Bryozoas are similar to corals because they are marine animals that live only in colonies.
They resemble seaweed, or may form hard shelled, moss like mounds on rocks.  
Bryozoas have encrusting, branching, or fan-like growth.  The bryozoan skeleton 
consists of hundreds of small boxes arranged along branches or over the surface of structures.  Bryozoas have a cluster
of tentacles that trap small particles of food.  <br><br>

Each colony is made up of microscopic
beings called zooids.  The zooids have box like or tube shaped bodies.  
Some of the colonies consisted of simple chain-like series of tubes.
But they could also be leaf-like, fan-like, or ball-shaped.  Most Bryozoas are
found in limestone rocks from the Ordovician period. 
 <a href="bryo.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>
 
<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u></h3></u>
<dd>Bryozoans lived on the sea bed, where sand and mud were deposited.  Most are found worldwide in water
from shallow ponds to deep oceans.  They were not able to
escape burial, even when alive, since they lacked the ability to move.  All colonies of Bryozoas form networks
on water plants.  </h4>
 <a href="bryo.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br>
 
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-87</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA003-000024-B011-58</DOCOLDNO>
