<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Mollusk</b></u></h2>

<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>

<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u></h3></u>
<dd><h4>Mollusks are soft bodied animals with no bones.  Most have a hard external shell to
protect their bodies.  Some have no shells and others have an internal shell.  The shell structure varies
from coiled to symmetrical bivalves.    
The mollusk phylum is the second largest in the animal kingdom.  This phylum includes snails, slugs, clams, oysters,
squids, and octopuses.  Mollusks are common as fossils.<br><br>



There are three main groups of mollusks (these are the groups the freshmen will study).  They are:

<UL>
<LI>Gastropods (snails)
<LI>Pelecypods (clams)
<LI>Cephalopods (nautillus, octopus, and squids)
</UL>

<h3><u>Gastropods</u></h3>

Gastropods first appeared in the early Cambrian.  They adapted themselved to life in 
the sea, fresh water, and on land.  Gastropods carries a shell on its back, when there is
danger they retreat into the safety of its shell.  They have a single,
coiled shell (but some are cone-shaped), and their body has a 
well defined head, eyes, and a large muscular foot.  They also have a mouth, and tentacles.  
Only the gastropods have adapted to a terrestrial mode of life.  

<h3><u>Pelecypods</u></h3>

Pelecypods are bivalved mollusks.  Bivalves first appeared in the early 
Ordovician and although their two-valved shell has restricted their evolution they were successful since 
the beginning of the Triassic.  Most are marine animals but some live in fresh water, they may be
attached, burrow into the bottom, or creep about by their hatchet-shaped foot.  Scallops are free-swimming.
Oysters, mussels, and clams are living types.  Pelecypods valves are equal in size and mirror images of each
other.  These mollusks have no head or teeth and they get food and oxygen through a siphon.  
Many fossils are found as casts and molds.  Pelecypods first appeared in the Ordovician Period,
they are common in rocks of the Paleozoic, Mesozoic, and Cenozoic.

<h3><u>Cephalopods</u></h3>

Cephalopods are the most advanced class of mollusks.
Cephalopods have their shells external, internal, or none at all.  They are living forms and
 have well-developed head with large eyes, a well-formed brain, and tentacles.
They first appeared in the Ordovician.  The early nautiloids had a variety of shell shapes.  Another 
group of cephalopods, the ammonoids, came in the early Devonian.  They had a rather simple structure.
Fossils forms have well-developed shells.  Most common fossils forms are from the Mesozoic Period.  Cephalopods
are also useful in helpong to date rocks.<br><br>

Modern representatives of mollusks are octopus, squid, and cuttlefish.  Modern cephalopods 
have internal shells completely covered by soft parts.
<a href="moll.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>



<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u></h3></u>
<dd>Most are marine but some live in
fresh-water, and some live on land.  Some are free-swimming but most are bottom dwellers.  All mollusks
must keep their bodies moist to stay alive.  </h4>
<a href="moll.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>

</DOC>
