<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Coelenterates</b></u></h2>
<h3><u>"Hollow Intestine"</u></h3>

<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>
<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Coelenterates are simple aquatic animals including corals, sea anemones, sea pens and fans, the tiny 
hydra, and the extinct stromatoporoids.  They are usually soft bodied marine animals.  
The body of coelenterates has a radical symmetry.  Their bodies are sac-like and have at least two layers of cells 
which form the body wall.  The outer layer is the body covering and the inner layer lines the digestive cavity.  Some
have more layers of a stiff, jellylike substance to support the animal.  The body is shaped like a cylinder, bell, or
umbrella and has a single opening surrounded by tentacles.<br><br>

They lack hard parts, so they rarely form fossils.  One group, the Anthozoa, grow external stony skeletons that is
fossilized.
<a href="coele.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>


<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u></h3></u>
<dd><h4>Coelenterates usually live in the sea, most living in colonies.  The coelenterates can swim about
freely or be attached to the sea bottom.<br><br>

The corals, the most prominent of the coelenterates, grow together in colonies 
that are made up of individual corals whose skeletons 
are attached to each other.  Corals are important rock builders, since tropical islands are partly coral limestone. 
Reef-building corals live in an equatorial belt of warm, shallow water.  
They don't grow on muddy bottoms.  Coelenterates were found in the Arctic and Antarctic, 
which indicates that climatic conditions were different from the present.     <br><br>

Coelenterates indicate climatic conditions which were very different from the present.  They are found from 
the Pre-Cambrian Era to the Present.</h4>
<a href="coele.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br>




</DOC>
