<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Arthropods</b></u></h2>

<h3><u>"Jointed Foot"</u></h3>

<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>
<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Arthropods have segmented bodies, paired, jointed limbs, and a hard external 
covering, with flexible joints.  The legs are used as sucking organs or sense organs, jaws, or weapons of
defense.  The outside shell of the arthropods is made of a stiff material named chitin. 
There are seven groups of arthropods.  They are:
<UL>
Spiders<br>
Ticks<br>
Millipedes and Centipedes<br>
Lobsters<br>
Crabs<br>
Barnacles<br>
Insects<br>
</UL>

The four most important classes of arthropods are:
<UL>
<LI>Trilobites
<LI>Crustaceans
<LI>Chelicerates
<LI>Insects
</UL>

The class the freshmen will study is the <a href="trilo.html"><b>trilobites</a>.</h4>
<a href="arthr.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>

<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u></h3></u>
<dd><h4>Arthropods are a sucessful phylum of invertebrates and one of the most
abundant animals on earth.  Arthropods can exist on land, in fresh and salt water, and in the air.
You can probably find arthropods anywhere that life exists.  However only a few groups of arthropods
are commonly found as fossils.<br><br>

Arthropods first appeared in the Cambrian Period.  The trilobites, a group of arthropods, were abundant during this
time.  The only group of arthropods that is now extinct is the trilobites.<br><br>
<a href="arthr.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>



</DOC>
