<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Echinoderms</b></u></h2>
<h3><u>"Spiny Skin"</u></h3>


<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>
<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Echinoderms or "spiny-skins" are a phylum of marine animals.  These are complex animals, 
that are coverd with plates or spines.  Many fossil echinoderms had a long, flexible jointed
stem.  This stem hooked them to the sea floor to to another object.  But most forms are
unattached and move freely over the sea floor. <br><br>

As adults, echinoderms have bodies that have radial symmetry (body parts are arranged around a center
like spokes on a wheel).  Their bodies are divided into five sections with the mouth at the center.  Many tiny tube like
structures, called tube feet, project from the body.  The tube feet allow the echinoderms to move, breathe, feed, and
sense.  As larva, the echinoderms have bilateral symmetry.<br><br>

This phylum has eight common classes.
<UL>
Crinoid<br>
Asteroid<br>
Ophiuroid<br>
Holothurioid<br>
Echinoid<br>
Edrioasteroid<br>
Cystoid<br>
Blastoid
</UL>

Some examples of echinoderms are:
<OL>
<LI>Sea Urchins
<LI>Starfish
<LI>Sea Cucumbers
<LI>Brittlestars
<LI>Sea Lilies
</OL>

One of the more popular echinoderms is the criniod.  Freshmen will go into more detail with the
crinoind than any of the other classes.<br><br>

<h3><u>Criniod</u></h3>

Crinoids are called sea-lilies but are animals not plants. 
Criniods are from the Ordovician to the Recent.  Found in Paleozoic rocks, a complete crinoid is very rare.
Today crinoids are rare and are confined to the deeper parts of the ocean.  
They are flower-like echinoderms, which are also often beautiful colors
that grow in colonies on the sea floor.  Some forms were free-swimming but most were fixed by a stem.   
<a href="echin.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>



<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u></h3></u>
<dd>Echinoderms lived in deeper parts of the ocean during the Paleozoic Era.  They reproduce by laying eggs that
develop into larva.  The larva swims freely during its early stages.  The larva then sinks and attaches to the ocean bottom
as it changes into an adult.</h4>
<a href="echin.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>

</DOC>
