<h2><u><b>Fossil:  Brachiopods</b></u></h2>
<h3><u>"Armed Foot"</u></h3>

<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#appear">Appearance</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#conditions">Conditions Found In</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#function">How They Function and Live</a><br>
<b><img align= top src="gif/grenbull.gif" ALT="* ">   <a href="#articulates">Articulates</a><br>
<hr>

<dl>
<a name="appear"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Appearance:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Brachiopods are divided into two groups.  They are inarticulates (no hinge) and articulates (hinged valves).  The freshmen will
only study the articulates.<br><br>

Brachiopods are marine animals with soft bodies covered by shells (made of two parts or valves).  Each shell is bilaterally symmetrical
(symmetrical up and down, not left and right).<br><br>

A brachiopod body has four parts.  They are:
<OL>
<LI><u>The mantle</u>-sheet whose two halves fold over the rest of the body, makes the shell and encloses the body and the
internal organs.
<LI><u>Brachia/lophore</u>-outside the body but inside the mantle.  Two long coiled arms which have rows of small
tentacles on the edge.  Each tentacle has tiny hair like cilia attached to them for trapping food.
<LI><u>Internal organs</u>-muscles, digestive tract, nerves, and glands.
<LI><u>Stalk or pedicle</u>-fleshy projection between valves.  Is long and flexible, attaches owner to solid objects.
</OL>


Brachiopods are usually small, no greater than one inch.  But some grow to four inches or more.  Some have smooth shells but 
most have ribbed shells.  They are used as food in some places.<br><br></h4>
<a href="brach.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>

<dl>
<a name="conditions"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Conditions Found In:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Brachiopods were found in rocks from the early Cambrian period to the present.  They are an important fossil group.  Most
of the 30,000 known fossil species come from rocks of the Paleozoic era.  Brachiopods don't like to be seen.  They stay 
inconspicuous.  The earliest brachiopods lived in colder waters, not far from active glaciers.  Today they are restricted to 
the tropic.</h4>
</dl>
<a href="brach.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br>

<dl>
<a name="function"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>How They Function and Live:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Adult brachiopods mainly lived attached to an object on the sea floor by their pedicle.  But they begin
life as free-swimming.  Brachiopods feed by filtering tiny sea organims into their 
lophophore (create a current of sea organisms and gathers food).</h4>

<a href="brach.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br></dl>

<dl>
<a name="articulates"></a>
<dt><u><h3><u>Articulates:</u><h3></u>
<dd><h4>Articulates have shells that are hinged by teeth on one shell and sockets on the other.  Thus keeping the shells
in line.  Their shells are make mainly from calcium carbonate, and have a thin outer layer and thicker inner layer.
Articulates were seen in the Cambrian Age but were not in abundance until the Devonian
Age.</h4>

<a href="brach.html"><h5>Go to 
Top of Menu</h5></a><br>
