<h5><u><IMG SRC="Gif/Smile.gif"><a href="fossil5.html">Go to 
Stops Made Menu</h5></a></u>


<center><h2><u><b>Buttsville Terminal Moraine</b></u></h2></center>

<h4>When arriving at the Buttsville Terminal Moraine, students are asked to locate this stop
on their New Jersey Map.  <br><br>

They will then have to list three characteristics of the small hill seen at this location:
<h5><OL>
A.  There are all different kinds of rocks.<br>
B.  All the rocks are rounded off.<br>
C.  The rocks are all different sizes (Since they are all sizes this shows that a river didn't flow through this area.  A
river would sort the rocks into equal sizes, but a glacier wouldn't sort the rocks.  This leads us to believe that 
a glacier once passed through here.).
</OL></h5>

Students have to define what a <u>moraine</u> and a <u>terminal moraine</u> are.<br>
<h5>Moraine-a boundary line of a glacier.<br>
Terminal Moraine-last boundary line of a glacier.</h5>

Some of the question asked in the booklet are:
<OL>
<LI>How many years ago was there a glacier at Buttsville?
<h5>Answer:  10,000 years ago</h5>
<LI>How many ice sheets have covered parts of North America?
<h5>Answer:  Three (scientists believe that there were three different ice ages, one for each glacier)</h5>
<LI>How thick were the great continental glaciers?
<h5>Answer:  A couple thousand feet</h5>
</h4>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-94</DOCNO>
