<h5><u><IMG SRC="Gif/Smile.gif"><a href="fossil5.html">Go to 
Stops Made Menu</h5></a></u>

<center><h2><u><b>Delaware Water Gap</b></u></h2></center>
<h4>
Once at the Delaware Water Gap, students will have to locate this stop on their New Jersey Map.<br><br>

Students will then be asked some questions.  Some examples of these questions are:<br>  
<OL>
<LI>What made the Gap in the mountain?
<h5>Answer:  The mountains were pushing up while the river stayed the same (cutting away at the rock of the
mountain), wind eroded the top of the mountain to form the V shape.</h5>
<LI>What did not make the Gap?
<h5>Answer:  Glaciers didn't make the Gap.  They couldn't since glaciers are 10,000 feet high, mountains aren't.
If a glacier came through, it would just cover the mountain not make a gap.</h5>
<LI>Briefly outline how the Gap was formed.
<h5>Answer:  
<UL>
A.  The river (staying the same, cutting away), the mountain (pushing up).<br>
B.  Mountain uplifted by convection currents pushing.<br>
C.  The tops of the mountain started to erode.<br>
</UL> </h5>
<LI>What geologic name is given to the pile of loose rock found at the bottom of the cliff?
<h5>Answer:  Talus slope-make of rocks fallen down.</h5>
</h4>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B40-95</DOCNO>
