<h5><u><IMG SRC="Gif/Smile.gif"><a href="fossil5.html">Go to 
Stops Made Menu</h5></a></u>

<center><u><b><h2>Stroudsburg Fossil Site</h2></b></u></center>

<h4>Students will have to locate this stop on their New Jersey Map.<br><br>

They will also have to answer some questions in their booklet.  These questions are:<br><br>

<OL>
A.  What class of rock is found here (Igneous, Sedimentary, or Metamorphic)?
<h5>Answer:  Sedimentary</h5>
B.  What must have covered this area at one time?  How do you know?
<h5>Answer:  An ocean must have covered this land at one time.  We know this because all the fossils
found here are shell and coral.  Since shells and coral only live in the ocean, than this must have
been an ocean.</h5>
C.  What type of fossil is most common here?
<h5>Answer:  Anthozoa (shells)</h5>
</OL>
Students have to collect as many different kinds of fossils that they can.  In order to pass
the fossils unit students have to collect five of the eight classes.  Back at school students have
to clean and identify the fossils they collect.  They will also be graded on their collections.</h4>
</DOC>
