<h5><u><IMG SRC="Gif/Smile.gif"><a href="arthr.html">Go to 
Arthropods</h5></a></u>

<center><h3><u><b>Trilobites "three lobes"</b></u></h3></center>
<hr>


<h4>Trilobites are one of the earliest marine arthropods,  found in the Cambrian 
to the Permian Period.  They lived in the sea, but they are now extinct.<br><br>

Trilobites were common three-lobed marine arthropods, most being less than four inches long.  The body of the
trilobite had three main parts:  the head, thorax (body), and tail.  
They had a soft shell that covered most of their body.   Two groves extending down the back of the
body divided it into three lobes.  Each lobe was divided into many segments, each having its own pair
of legs.  From front to back, the body has a number of arranged segments.  A pair of jointed legs grew from each side
of these segments.  They have a head, body, and a tail.<br><br>

When they grew larger, trilobites molted their armor (like a snake sheds its skin). 
Trilobites could also roll up into a ball.  This was done to protect the animal's soft underside.
Trilobites were probably bottom-feeding scavengers and predators.<br><br>
 


When you find a trilobite as a fossil they are usually found in parts rather than as a
whole.  However, during the Fossil Field Trip, if a student finds a whole trilobite fossil, 
the teacher will reward them somehow.  
They are one of the most popular and priced fossil.  Some are used as jewlery.<br><br>


</h4>
</DOC>
<DOC>
