<HEAD>
<TITLE>CHCH-TV's History</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/history.gif"></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="founder.htm">Our Founder , Kenneth D. Soble</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="proghili.htm">Hilites Of 40 Years</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="house.htm">Our "Old House"</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="owners.htm">Who Has Owned Us?</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="proghis.htm">Programs We've Aired</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="awards.htm">Awards Won At CHCH</A></LI>
</UL>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR></CENTER>

<P> On March 30, 1953, a licence application was approved for a
local consortium consisting of Maple Leaf Broadcasting, controlled by
Kenneth Soble, Wentworth Broadcasting, and Southam Press (owners of The
Hamilton Spectator).  Shortly thereafter, Theatre Properties Hamilton
joined the consortium.

<P>On June 7, 1954, at 8:00 p.m., "Lucky Channel 11" began transmitting to
the public as a privately owned affiliate of the CBC network.  The opening
show was a two-hour production telling the story of the city of Hamilton. 
One of the many "new" attractions about CHCH was the tower, a single pipe rising 540
feet from the top of Hamilton mountain, eight miles from the station. 
Invented by G. Bruce MacKimmie, the tower was called a "wavestack
antenna".  Another big attraction for viewers on June 7, 1954, was the
"weather window".  Toronto viewers were accustomed to watching the
weather mapped out on a blackboard.  Now viewers could watch weatherman
John Dickins stand behind a glass window, and with a crayon, mark in the
various systems and weather information on the back of the glass --
writing backwards all the time.

<P>CHCH also had a television
camera apparatus which was the first of its kind in Canada.  It was an
"electro-zoom" gadget .  The station boasted a special effects
generator, which allowed the viewer to look at the screen and see the
announcer in one part of it and, for example, a news film in the rest.  
As well, CHCH had the biggest studio in Canada -- the Hamilton Forum, a
200 foot x 95 foot arena owned by Ken Soble.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../general/aboutch.htm"><IMG SRC="../images/leftarro.gif" border=0 ALT="Left Arrow Icon"><BR><B>All About CHCH</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="/"><IMG SRC="../images/home.gif" border=0 ALT="Home Page Icon"><BR><B>CHCH Home Page</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="mailto:webmaster@chch.wic.ca"><IMG SRC="../images/mail.gif" border=0 ALT="Mail Icon"><BR><B>webmaster@chch.wic.ca</B></A></TH></TD>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<I>Updated: March 6, 1996</I> 
</CENTER>
</BODY>


</HTML>
