<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon On-Line</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER>
<img src="../../images/noon_on.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="The News At Noon On-Line">
</CENTER>



<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, January 2, 1997</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Economy Lookahead   
    <li>PEI Bridge          
    <li>Ferries Resume      
    <li>BC Weather          
    <li>West Coast Wrap     
    <li>Weird Weather       
    <li>Polar Bears 97      
    <li>Sydney Polar Death  
    <li>Puppy Rescued       
    <li>Hamilton Babies     
    <li>Hardy Dead          
    <li>Kiddie Porn         
    <li>Dubai Documents     
    <li>Toronto Murder      
    <li>Niagara Fatal       
    <li>Body Inn            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Economy Lookahead</b><p>
We all hope for the best at the start of a new year ... but this year it appears, there may actually be some sound economic evidence on which Canadians can pin their hopes. For the first time in nearly a decade, economic forecasters are almost unanimously upbeat; saying the conditions are ripe for a return to prosperity, and lower unemployment, across Canada. 
<hr>
<b>PEI Bridge</b><p>
The maritime region of Canada has often seen some of the toughest economic conditions in Canada. But this year may be different. Aggressive policies by provincial governments, combined with generally better economic conditions, are spurring new development, and optimism. But one of the biggest spurs to economic growth on the east coast, is a concrete serpent more than 20 kilometers long. 
<hr>
<b>Ferries Resume</b><p>
Travellers in the maritimes will still be forced to rely on the ferries to trips to Newfoundland however. That service resumed this morning, after hurricane force winds over the Northumberland Straight, forced the ferries to shut down over New Years. Travellers trapped on one ferry were treated to a free meal, and party favours by a sympathetic crew.
<hr>
<b>BC Weather</b><p>
The bill for some of the worst weather in the history of British Columbia ... could top more than 200-million dollars. Heavy snow collapsed many buildings, including scores of commercial greenhouses, used by the province's multi-million dollar flower industry. And following the snow, came warm temperatures and heavy rain bringing floodwaters ... which will make the holiday season of 1996, one to remember in B.C.
<hr>
<b>West Coast Wrap</b><p>
And the same weather system that has battered B.C. has wreacked havoc up and down the west coast of North America; from Washington state, to California.
<hr>
<b>Weird Weather</b><p>
Meanwhile in Europe ... record breaking cold from Moscow to Madrid ... has claimed 140 lives in the last week. One of the latest victims; a French resident of Normandy, who tried to walk home in minus 15 degree temperatures; when his car wouldn't start.
<hr>
<b>Polar Bears 97</b><p>
It probably began as a hardy Canadian cure for the inevitable New Year's Day hangover. But whatever sparked the tradition of diving into the frigid waters of the great lakes on New Years Day; has now spawned a host of frosty frolicking, not only designed for fun, but for charity as well. Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>Spectators huddled for warmth in their cars, parked along Hamilton's beachfront.  Even the dogs were bundled against the cold.  But the arctic air, and frigid waters of Lake Ontario still enticed dozens of hardy dippers.  <br>Just enough time for a few Kodak moments, and one last warm embrace. Then, into the swim of things.  <br>Of course proper attire is mandatory.  Also mandatory... post-swim analysis .  <br>Eleven years ago, just five people took the plunge from this side of the lake.  This year, more than three-hundred rushed in, to raise money for a good cause.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Sydney Polar Death</b><p>
Many say the human body was not built for such abuse ... and unfortunately; almost every year there is at least one case to prove them right. This year, in Sydney Nova Scotia; a 65 year old member of the local polar bear club, suffered a heart attack and died, after a plunge in minus seven degree temperatures. Authorities say, Bill Jamieson was one of 29 people who braved the waters of Sydney Harbour. After the event, Jamieson dressed in his truck, and began to drive to a local fire hall, but the collapsed behind the wheel and died, a short time later.
<hr>
<b>Puppy Rescued</b><p>
Rescue workers in Thorold report a happy conclusion in their efforts to rescue a dalmation puppy ... that fell some thirty metres down the ventilation pipe; from an old septic system... on the property of Tony and Kathy Bowman. The puppy was a Christmas gift to the couple's young children; and had gone astray from the family home.<br>  A quick search drew the family to the sound of the yelping puppy at the bottom of the pipe.<br>  It took firefighters and Humane Society officials five hours to rescue "Duke" from his subterranean prison.<br>  Although frightened, "Duke" is fine; and dog-gone lucky, to be alive.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Babies</b><p>
They were not the first Canadians born in the New Year ... <br>  But two babies born in separate hospitals arrived at virtually the same moment ... to make them the first new residents of Hamilton, for 1997.<br>  At St. Josephs Hospital, Dominic Scibetta .... the son of Josee and Joseph Scibetta, weighed in at seven pounds, eight ounces ... arriving five minutes after midnight.<br>   At the same moment, on Hamilton mountain ... Nolan Robert Charles Thomas; made his way into the world ... almost 36 hours after mother Dawn Berry, had been induced to labour. Doctors had been concerned about the baby's health, and Nolan was born almost three weeks ahead of schedule... weighing five pounds, eight ounces. Happily, both mom and baby, are doing just fine.
<hr>
<b>Hardy Dead</b><p>
Funeral services will be held saturday morning, in toronto, for internationally known Canadian composer, Hagood Hardy. Hardy succumbed to cancer in a Hamilton hospital yesterday. He was 59.<br>  The three time Juno Award winner was best known for his melodic instrumental "The Homecoming,".... originally written for a tea commercial. <br>  He also composed film and TV scores, including "Anne of Green Gables."<br> Hardy started in Toronto's jazz clubs in the 1950's, and also performed for a time with jazz great George Shearing.
<hr>
<b>Kiddie Porn</b><p>
A former defence department scientist facing child pornography charges appeared briefly in an Ottawa court today.<br> His case was set over until January 30th at the request of the defence.<br> 46 year old Blair Evans of Gloucester, Ontario was arrested last month, after the OPP seized more than 20-thousand computer files containing child pornography, from a defence department office. Evans is charged with making, possessing and distributing child pornography, via the Internet.
<hr>
<b>Dubai Documents</b><p>
New evidence in the "Maersk Dubai" case indicates that Canadian authorities had to make it up as they went along.<br>  Briefing notes to Canada's justice minister from the mounted police show that Ottawa ... at first ... said it had no jurisdiction in the case.<br>  Six Taiwanese container ship officers are facing an extradition hearing, after charges that they threw three Romanian stowaways overboard, to their deaths, on the high seas.<br>  Because the incident took place in international waters, federal ports police at first said, there was nothing they could do.<br>  The mounties then stepped in, re-interviewed the witnesses, and laid charges ... while Canada hastily wrote an administrative agreement with Romania ... that would allow the RCMP to board the ship, and search for evidence in the case.
<hr>
<b>Toronto Murder</b><p>
A York University student has been charged with second degree murder, after the stabbing death of a German man; in Canada for only a few hours. Metro homicide detectives were called to a rooming house in North York where they found the body of 55-year-old Helmuth Volkmann of Germany. Police say he had been stabbed to death. The suspect is Volkmann's son, 25-year-old Krister Volkmann, who came to Canada last fall to attend university. A German newspaper reports that the senior Volkmann had come to Canada to rescue his son from what he believed to be a cult.<br>  His son was arraigned on the murder charge and remanded in custody in a Toronto court, this morning.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Fatal</b><p>
A British tourist died in this accident; in Niagara on the Lake. 33 year old Anne Denise Coventry of London England, was a passenger in a mini-van which collided with a car, and then struck a utility pole.<br>  She was thrown from the vehicle ...which then rolled over, and landed on top of her.<br>  Her husband, 34 year-old Edward Coventry and their two young children suffered minor injuries.
<hr>
<b>Body Inn</b><p>
Fire claimed the life of a 72 year old woman, in a New Year's day fire at a St. Catharine's hotel. Foul play is not suspected in the death of Cecile Dumais, whose body was pulled from the flames and smoke that engulfed room 6 of the Crossroads Motor Inn. Firefighters quickly extinguished the blaze. Careless smoking is the suspected cause.













