<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News On-Line</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<P>

<CENTER>
<img src="../../images/first_on.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line">
</CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, January 2, 1997</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Crumbling Sewers    
    <li>Teacher Charged     
    <li>Niagara Bomb        
    <li>Niagara Fatal       
    <li>Body Inn            
    <li>Flu Bug             
    <li>Dalmation Rescue    
    <li>JAG                 
    <li>Polar Bear Swim     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Crumbling Sewers</b><p>
Hamilton- Wentworth residents may be flushed with pride, having just concluded a year that featured Hamilton's Sesquicentennial, the privatization of Hamilton airport, and the Grey Cup bash.<br>  But unless the region gets its financial house in order, taxpayers may not be able to flush much else.<br> In a bluntly-worded report, regional staff warn politicians that they have been penny-wise and pound-foolish.<br> As a result, Hamilton- Wentworth's roads, sewers and waterworks are crumbling.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br> Caught between a provincial government bent on slashing subsidies, and taxpayers who demand no increases, Hamilton- Wentworth politicians have responded by cutting capital spending by 70-million dollars during the 1990's.  More and more of what's left is spent on special projects, and less and less on what the region's already got... things like roads, sewers and water mains. Councillors now have a choice. They can raise taxes to improve maintenance of essential services, or cancel special projects.  <br>To contain the overflow, Hamilton- Wentworth has built a series of giant CSO tanks, that temporarily store sewage overflows until the treatment plant is able to to handle the excess. Councillor Wilson fears future tanks could wind up on the special project hit list. If something has to go, he'd rather see cancellation of the Red Hill Creek Expressway.  <br>Either way politicians can pay now, or pay much more later. Staff point out it costs at least five times more to replace services, than to maintain and repair what you've already got.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Teacher Charged</b><p>
A Hamilton teacher faces charges after a former student claims he was molested for a two year period, starting in 1972. At the time, police say the male complainant was a 10 year old student at Earl Kitchener School in Hamilton.<br>  He claims the incidents occured while he helped out after school.<br>  48 year old Edward Ward is charged with buggery, gross indecency and indecent assault.<br>  The case is now being handled by Hamilton Wentworth's major crimes unit.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Bomb</b><p>
Police used a water cannon to disable an apparent pipe-bomb in Niagara Falls.<br> The device, with a timer attached, was found outside a home on Armoury St., New Year's Eve.  About 20 neighboring homes were evacuated.<br> Officers used a water cannon to blow apart the package holding the device, then detonated it safely.<br> They're still trying to figure out who planted the bomb, and why.
<hr>
<b>Niagara fatal</b><p>
A British tourist died in this accident; in Niagara on the Lake. 33 year old Anne Denise Coventry of London England, was a passenger in a mini-van which collided with a car, and then struck a utility pole.<br> She was thrown from the vehicle ...which then rolled over, and landed on top of her.<br>  Her husband, 34 year-old Edward Coventry and their two young children suffered minor injuries.
<hr>
<b>Body Inn</b><p>
Foul play is not suspected in the death of a woman in a St. Catharines hotel yesterday. This after the body of 72-year-old Cecile Dumais was pulled from flames and smoke that engulfed room 6 of the Crossroads Motor Inn. Firefighters quickly extinguished the blaze. Careless smoking is the suspected cause.
<hr>
<b>Flu Bug</b><p>
Much of Ontario is in the grip of the grippe.<br> Thousands of people suffering from the influenza-a virus have swamped hospitals and clinics.<br> Hamilton doctor Kathleen Walker says the epidemic is turning doctors' offices into "viral pits."<br> Symptoms -- which last about a week -- include fever, sore throat, cough, fatigue and aches and pains.<br> Children sometimes develop vomiting.<br> Walker says there's not much physicians can do but let the bug run its course.<br> The elderly and very young particularly those who have had respiratory infections  are particularly vulnerable.
<hr>
<b>Dalmation Rescue</b><p>
Cruella De Vil wasn't involved but a dalmation puppy in Tholold got the scare of his life last night.<br>  Duke, a seven week old, deaf dalmation pup fell head first into a narrow ventilation pipe.<br>  As Lauran Sabourin reports, Duke was trapped inside the pipe for five hours before firefighters were able to pull him out..
<i><br>  For five hours firefighters frantically made one attempt after another to dislodge tiny Duke the dalmation from a backyard septic tank ventilation pipe. <br>  Bathy Bowman had let Duke outside around six o'clock just for a minute. When she says the ground just sucked him up..<br>  She didn't even realize the hole was there.. <br>  Oxygen was pumped into the hole in an attempt to keep the pup alive. <br>  Three times the pup was snared ..three times he fell back down the 30 foot pipe. <br>  Finally firefigters got a 30 foot rod. attached a noose to it. and was able to lasoo the dog's tail. <br>  Shivering..coated with mud, Duke was wrapped up in blankets and rushed to an animal hospital.<br>  He went into shock at the hospital and nearly died.  <br>  This morning Duke was still worn out.  He was curled up at home with his sister Peanut.<br>  Today his owners seem to be more shaken up by Duke's ordeal than he is.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>JAG</b><p>
The military drama "JAG" comes to the CHCH program lineup beginning Friday night.<br> The show, which drew roller coaster ratings after being shuffled around various nights last season, has taken on new life following a U.S. network switch.<br> Alex Reynolds reports that Canadian actor David James Elliott plays the lead.
<i> <br>  "JAG" is military-speak for Judge Advocate General's Corps, the elite cadre of naval officers trained as investigators and lawyers.<br>  After some tinkering by the producers, the show has a new look. <br>  <br>  Timely plots infuse the show with energy and realism....sexual harassment, AIDS and gays in the military.... there's also focus on the personal interplay between the two characters, who work side by side, and not one in front of the other. <br>  "JAG" officers investigate... prosecute.... defend.<br>  The elements are in place for gripping tales.<br>  "JAG" has found a home Friday nights on CHCH-TV.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Polar Bear Swim</b><p>
Oakville's Burloak Bears Polar Bear Club has raised five thousand dollars for World Vision Canada to help Rwandan orphans.<br> This at yesterday's traditional New Year's Polar Bear Dip... at which more than 200 braved the icy waters of Lake Ontario. There was a minimum donation of fifteen dollars for each of the dippers... and a loonie apiece from the more than 2500 spectators who showed up.








 <P>


<CENTER><A HREF="../../intouch/"><IMG SRC="../../images/intchbd2.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER =0 ALT="In Touch: Answering The Call"></A></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../news/"><IMG SRC="../../images/leftarro.gif" border=0 ALT="Left Arrow Icon"><BR><B>The News Page</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../../images/blank.gif"></TD>
