<HEAD>

<TITLE>Our Founder, Ken Soble</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG HEIGHT=133 WIDTH=529 SRC="../images/ksoble.gif" ALT="Ken Soble Photo"></CENTER>
   

<P>Kenneth D. Soble, founder of CHCH, was a revered giant in
the broadcast industry and an effective leader in urban renewal.  He was
a man of great vision, daring, and determination, who was respected
professionally and personally by everyone.  His career was comprised of
a long list of firsts which included the pioneering of: Canada's first
audience-participation radio broadcast, private television's first
regular reports from Parliament Hill, Canada's first on-the-spot  sports
broadcast, and the first broadcast for crippled children from Toronto's
Maple Leaf Gardens.  Soble was also instrumental bringing about
invaluable recognition for Canadians by having Leopold Stokowski arrange
and play Canadian music in Canada at Carnegie.

<P> Ken Soble gave
some of the biggest names in show business their start, for example, 
Oscar Peterson purchased his first piano with prize money won on the Ken
Soble Amateur Hour; people like Joyce Davidson, Gordie Tapp and the Four
Lads can trace their success back to Soble.      He was one of the key
figures in developing Broadcast News Ltd., the radio and television news
service affiliate of the Canadian Press.

<P> He also served for
many years on the board of the Canadian Association of Broadcasters. 
Kenneth D. Soble was born June 12, 1911, in Toronto.  At the age of 16,
he entered broadcasting at a Toronto radio station by giving a ride to a
young woman in need of transportation -- Jane Gray, Canada's first
female broadcaster .  Shortly after, he created the country's first
amateur show, The Ken Soble Amateur Hour, a radio broadcast that began
during the Depression in 1931.

<P> In 1936, at the age of 25, Ken
Soble came to Hamilton to manage radio station CHML.  Eight years later,
Soble learned that CHML was for sale and mortgaging everything he owned,
bought it.  In 1953 his television licence application, with equal
partnership with Wentworth Broadcasting and Southam, was approved.  In
1961, he pulled away from the CBC Network making CHCH Canada's only
independent station.

<P>Soble always managed to shock other
broadcasters.  In October of 1966, in association with Power Corp. of
Canada Ltd., he presented to the Board of Broadcast Governors a proposal
for a 97- station nation-wide television network to be fed by an
all-Canadian space satellite.  He and his partners could have the system
up and running before any other country in the world.   At the time of his death, no
formal application had been made.

<P>  Kenneth D. Soble entered the public housing field in
1960.  He was the first chairman of  Hamilton's urban renewal committee,
a position he held until his death in 1966.  His leadership in this
field was so impressive, that he was invited by the Ontario government
to head its proposed advisory committee.  He was a dynamic force within
the community.   He originated the Hamilton Dream Home campaign in 1950
to raise money for Winnipeg flood victims.

<P>Soble served on such
organizations as The Hamilton United Appeal, the Hamilton Art Gallery,
the Masonic Order, the Hamilton Health Association, the Primrose Club,
the B'nai Brith and the Hamilton Club.  He was an active member of the
Beth Jacob Synagogue.  In 1962 he was honored with a human relations
award from the Canadian Council of Christians and Jews.  Soble was
national chairman of the United Israel Appeal.  He was a member of the
conference planning Canada's centennial, a member of the Board of
Governors of McMaster University and a governor of the Hamilton Tiger
Cats Football Club.

<P> Repeatedly, Ken Soble was heard to say, "I
don't really have any talent of my own, unless it's a knack for finding
good people to run my businesses, and then leaving them alone.  Each
time I go into a new business, I leave my old one to the manager, and
I'm embarrassed by how successful it becomes."  According to Jack
Miller, radio and TV editor of the Hamilton Spectator at the time of Ken
Soble's death, that statement was the only repeated statement Soble ever
made -- that he couldn't back up.

<P>His "knack for finding good
people to run his businesses" proved to be true long after his death. 
His widow, Frances Soble, succeeded him first, as the head of one of
Canada's largest broadcasting empires.  Her position was then passed
along to two individuals Kenneth Soble placed in high regard -- Sydney
James Bibby, followed by Douglas C. Gale.

<P>Kenneth D. Soble
died on December 16, 1966, at the age of 55.<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
