<HEAD>

<TITLE>CHCH Production & Technical Highlights Page</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/11s.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>CHCH-TV Highlights</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<H2>CHCH-TV Production Highlights</H2>
<UL>
<LI>NHL Hockey</LI>
<LI>Pippin</LI>
<LI>Paul Williams And His Ladies</LI>
<LI>The Palace</LI>
<LI>Red Skelton</LI>
<LI>Crystal Gale</LI>
<LI>CFL Football (for Ralmar - American Market)</LI>
<LI>Roger Whittaker In Concert</LI>
<LI>Opera Hamilton Productions</LI>
<LI>Smith & Smith</LI>
<LI>The Comedy Mill</LI>
<LI>The Red Green Show</LI>
<LI>The Second City Live</LI>
</UL>

<P>In 1993 CHCH opened a new frontier in the broadcast industry with the interactive special, 
"The Abduction of Kristen French."</P>


<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<H2>CHCH-TV Technical Highlights</H2>

<UL>
<LI>1993 - CHCH continues to be an innovator on the Canadian television
scene.  A new state-of-the-art news broadcast centre and a
microwave/fibre optics network is put in place.</LI>

<LI>1984 - CHCH-TV's new facilities completed and the Southam House
refurbished to its former elegance.</LI>

<LI>1982 - Studio "A", CHCH's main studio (1954 - 1961), demolished to
make way for new "superstation" -- new master control, production
facilities, offices. CHCH seen nationwide on satellite as part of the
Cancom package available to cable subscribers.</LI>

<LI> 1981 - the Sony 1-inch VTR machines go on-line, continuing the
move to smaller, lighter equipment.  As well, 3/4" VCR's go into service.</LI>

<LI>1979 - the Ikegami EFP camera adds to the flexibility of remote
production.  It heralds the move to lighter, smaller, tape format recording.</LI>

<LI>1978 - brings the arrival of the Supercruiser and a new era in
CHCH's remote production capability -- advanced switcher, 16 track
audio, new videograph.</LI>

<LI>1977 - the purchase of a "slo mo" machine enhances sporting event
playbacks and adds to the stations special effects capabilities. </LI>

<LI>1972 - new Bosch Fernseh cameras contribute to state-of-the-art
production at the Telecentre. </LI>

<LI>1971 - an electronic character generator brings immediacy and
flexibility to CHCH's television graphics.  A Ward-Beck production
audioboard is also installed at the Telecentre adding dimension to
musical productions.</LI>

<LI> 1969 - Courier highway bus purchased and converted into a
monochrome remote production unit. </LI>

<LI>1967 - marked the delivery of the Ultracruiser and Marconi Mark VII
colour cameras.</LI>

<LI>1966 - Kenneth D. Soble spearheads a revolutionary proposal for a
third Canadian television network with signals to be distributed by
satellite (satellite still in infancy at this time).  Proposal halted
due to Kenneth Soble's death during the Fall of that year.</LI>   

<LI>1960 - Niagara Television spent $400,000 creating the Telecentre
Studio (King Street).</LI></UL><P>    


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="history.htm"><IMG SRC="../images/leftarro.gif" border=0 ALT="Left Arrow Icon"><BR><B>CHCH History</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
