<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CHCH's Home</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG HEIGHT=105 WIDTH=529 SRC="../images/our_home.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" ALT="CHCH-TV's Old Building"></CENTER>

<CENTER><H2>&quot;Mansion On Nob Hill Unlikely Home For Television Station&quot;</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P>The main offices of CHCH-TV were and still are housed in an unlikely
setting for a television station -- a stately 1840's mansion.  It was
built by John Bickle, an early Hamilton druggist, who named the
residence Pinehurst.  Following his death in 1875, the home became known
as Bishophurst and was occupied by Bishop Thomas Brock Fuller, the first
bishop of the newly created Diocese of Niagara.   It later became the
property of publishing pioneer William Southam, publisher of The
Hamilton Spectator.

<P> When William Southam died in 1932, the
residence was taken over by the Cawesco Club and used as a boarding
house and social centre for single male university graduates who had
come to Hamilton to be trained for management positions at Westinghouse.

<P> Following World War II, the house was transformed into the
headquarters for CJSH-FM, a radio station owned by the Hamilton
Spectator.  In 1953, CHCH began to occupy the house as part of its
facilities.

<P>When CHCH went on air, the grand old cut-stone home
housed CJSH-FM radio as well as the newly converted broadcasting
facility.   A Spectator delivery truck garage was located at the rear of
the house.  The new television station was equipped by RCA, acclaimed to
be among the best equipment in North America during that era.  The
reconverted garage at the rear of the house served for a time as CHCH's
main studio, complementing the TV studio set up at the Telecentre, the
old Kenmore Theatre, located a few blocks away.

<P>Until 1984, CHCH operated out of a collection of old buildings, including the 1840's
Georgian-style mansion. The designated historic site played a major role
in the construction and design of a new low-rise, high-tech facility
that would be linked with the house and bring operations under one roof.
In the end, the elegance of  Pinehurst-Bishophurst was completely
refurbished to its former grandeur.


<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="history.htm"><IMG SRC="../images/leftarro.gif" border=0 ALT="Left Arrow Icon"><BR><B>CHCH History</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="/"><IMG SRC="../images/home.gif" border=0 ALT="Home Page Icon"><BR><B>CHCH Home Page</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="mailto:webmaster@chch.wic.ca"><IMG SRC="../images/mail.gif" border=0 ALT="Mail Icon"><BR><B>webmaster@chch.wic.ca</B></A></TH></TD>
