<HEAD>
<TITLE>Turning Back The Dial...</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/bkgd.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/11s.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Turning Back The Dial...</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<P>In the 1990's, CHCH has maintained its television programming
savvy, offering a well balanced schedule to its viewers -- news, sports,
comedy, drama and prestigious seasonal specials.  However, in the
inaugural days of television programming, news was not one of the key
players like it is today.  Musical entertainment was the order of the
day.  Following is a look back at a variety of some old CHCH favourites:

<UL>
<LI>The Ken Soble Amateur Show, which began in radio in 1931 and
went on to become a weekly television show in 1954.  It became one of
the longest running shows in Canadian Broadcast history.</LI> 

<LI>Tiny Talent Time, equally enduring, showcased aspiring singers, dancers,
baton twirlers and other hopefuls who were under the age of 12 (on-air
35 years - last broadcast 1992).</LI>

<LI>Family Theatre</LI>

<LI>OHA Hockey Coverage from the Hamilton Forum proved to be a forerunner of 
Wednesday Night NHL telecasts following the Toronto Maple Leafs.</LI>

<LI>Don Messer's Jubilee</LI>

<LI>Party Game, hosted by Bill Walker with regular players Dinah
Christie, Billy Van and Jack Duffy.</LI>

<LI>The Hilarious House of Frightenstein, starring Billy Van and Vincent Price.</LI>

<LI>Parents trusted popular children's shows like Randy Dandy,
Cap'n Andy, Grandpa Schnitzel, Miss Nancy and Uncle Bill to regularly
entertain their children.</LI>

<LI>Cherington -  the show where everyone called in to talk with the man they loved to
hate -- Tom Cherington

<LI>Polka Party, Jamboree, Grand Union, Summer Jamboree, Saturday Night Jamboree, 
Mickey A Go-Go, Music Go Round, Club 11 Dance Party, The Sonins, Jane Gray, 
Roy Ward Dickson Game Shows, Father Meehan, Ein Prosit, Ryan's Fancy, the Harry Hibbs Show and
George Hamilton IV were also on the list of local vintage programs.</LI>

<LI>Other popular CHCH programmes included: Secrets From the Kitchen,
Pasquale's Kitchen Express, New Faces, Ben Wicks, Sketches Of Our Town,
The Palace with Jack Jones, and the long-running interview talk show,
Mid-Day, hosted by current news anchor Dan McLean.</LI>

<LI>Soap Box - hosted by "Mr. Soaps" himself, Vic Cummings</LI>

<LI>Dayscene and On The Scene with Wendy Brunelle</LI>

<LI>Don Cherry's Grapevine</LI>
<LI>Smith And Smith, The Comedy Mill, The Red Green Show</LI>
<LI>Ben Guyatt's roving Comedy Club.</LI><P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<TABLE COLSPACE=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../general/aboutch.htm"><IMG SRC="../images/leftarro.gif" border=0 ALT="Left Arrow Icon"><BR><B>All About CHCH</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="/"><IMG SRC="../images/home.gif" border=0 ALT="Home Page Icon"><BR><B>CHCH Home Page</B></A></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="../images/blank.gif"></TD>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="mailto:webmaster@chch.wic.ca"><IMG SRC="../images/mail.gif" border=0 ALT="Mail Icon"><BR><B>webmaster@chch.wic.ca</B></A></TH></TD>
