<HEAD>
<TITLE>EXTRA: The News and Entertainment Magazine on CHCH-TV</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/program.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<CENTER><H1>EXTRA: The News and Entertainment Magazine</H1>


<H1><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H1>

</CENTER>

<P>
&quot;EXTRA&quot; is <I>your</I> half-hour daily entertainment
news magazine show, airing weekdays Monday to Friday (5:00 p.m.
- 5:30 p.m.).
<P>


The successful magazine series EXTRA is living up to its name by giving viewers something EXTRA. More than just entertainment news, more than just pop culture stories, EXTRA is combining the excitement of Hollywood with the drama of the real world to deliver breaking and topical news from around the globe. 
EXTRA has spent the past several months revamping and refocusing to evolve from a purely entertainment magazine to a broader, popular news series, covering a wide array of stories about celebrities, music, fashion, politics, business, health, everyday heroes and ordinary people doing EXTRAordinary things. 

<P>

EXTRA has built a strong news gathering operation comprised of highly regarded journalists, writers, and producers who travel throughout the country -- and around the world -- to go where the stories take them so they can bring them to EXTRA's viewers. 

<P>

The series is anchored by award-winning and seasoned broadcast journalists Brad Goode and Libby Weaver, and supported by a team of highly respected and talented correspondents including Lauren Sanchez, David Rose, Phil Shuman and Wendy Walsh. 

<P>

EXTRA's strength in front of the camera is matched by enormous power behind-the-scenes. In February, award-winning news producer David Friend (who has been with EXTRA since its inception) was named executive producer and was given the mandate to use his strong news expertise to change the show's philosophy, direction, and style of coverage. 

<P>

Friend restructured and reorganized the senior news staff, shifting the emphasis away from entertainment and towards pop culture. He recruited two senior supervising news producers, with exceptionally strong news backgrounds. Gloria McDonough-Taub (former executive producer of the number-one rated 11:00 p.m. newscast in the number-one market -- New York's "Eyewitness News" on WABC-TV) heads up the news and features unit, while Eugene Young (most recently executive producer of the 11:00 newscast on KCBS-TV in Los Angeles) is in charge of broadcasts. In addition, EXTRA has completely transformed its New York office into a comprehensive news bureau. 

<P>

And, as a Time Telepictures Production, EXTRA benefits from the enormous resources of Time Inc.'s publications (including Time, People, Entertainment Weekly, Life, and Sports Illustrated). The EXTRA staff works closely with the editors, reporters, and researchers from the publications in identifying, developing, and reporting a broad range of stories. 

<P>

All of this adds up to EXTRA's new status as a broadcast journalistic powerhouse. 

<P>

EXTRA, which offers half-hour editions every weekday and an original hour-long weekend installment, is seen in more than 90% of the country, including clearances in major market affiliates in prime access and key latenight time periods. In the top-ten markets, EXTRA is seen on WNBC (New York), KNBC (Los Angeles), WMAQ (Chicago), WCAU (Philadelphia), KPIX (San Francisco), WCVB (Boston), WJLA (Washington, D.C.), KTVT (Dallas), WJBK (Detroit) and WAGA (Atlanta). 

<P>

EXTRA, a Time Telepictures Production, is distributed by Warner Bros. Domestic Television Distribution. 

<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 
<H3>EXTRA: The News and Entertainment Magazine <I>on the WEB</I>:</H3>

<P>
<A HREF="http://www.extratv.com">EXTRA: The News and Entertainment Magazine Web Site</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.knbc4la.com/NBCshows/extra_.html">The EXTRA Entertainment Flash from KNBC Burbank, CA.</A>
</CENTER>
