<HEAD>
<TITLE>Connie Smith Biography</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<IMG SRC="../../images/connie.gif">

<B>Connie Smith</B> has been with <B>CHCH</B> since 1976 and over
the years has become one of the most solid and recognizable personalities
on Channel 11.<BR>

<P>
Raised in Burlington, Connie graduated from Mohawk College with
a diploma in Communication Arts - majoring in Broadcast Journalism.
She landed her first job at CKOC Radio in Hamilton in 1973. The
following year, Connie made the move to Toronto, becoming a &quot;Good
News Reporter&quot; at CFRB. Then, it was off to television! From
1974 - 76 she worked in the newsroom at CKVR in Barrie, holding
positions as a general assignment reporter, weather broadcaster,
back-up anchor and host of the series, <I>Third Degree</I>.<BR>

<P>
In many ways, Connie's arrival at <B>CHCH</B> in 1976 made history
in the station's newsroom. She became the first weather person
at <B>CHCH</B>, and went on to become the first female anchor
of the weekday news and first <B>CHCH</B> anchorperson to have
a baby.<BR>

<P>
Connie co-anchored <I>Newsroom 11 Today</I> at 5:30 p.m. with
Dan McLean from 1988 to September of 1992. She also launched the
noon news show, <I>Newsroom 11 Mid-Day</I> in 1988 with Tom Cherington
and continued co-anchoring that news package until September 1992.
<BR>

<P>
In September 1992, Connie anchored and produced the <I>Evening
News</I> at 6:30 p.m. Since September of 1993, Connie has produced
and co-anchored the <I>News at Noon</I> and <I>The</I> <I>Golden
Horseshoe Report</I> at 5:30 p.m., the latter was renamed <I>First
Edition</I> in January 1994.<BR>

<P>
Aside from her duties within the News Department, Connie donates
her time to many charitable causes. She is currently Honourary
Chair of Second Stage Housing, which provides emergency interim
shelter for abused women and their families. She is also co-host,
once again, for the Annual Mother's Day Telethon for the Chedoke-McMaster
Children's Hospital on <B>CHCH-TV</B>. In 1995 Connie won the
first ever Community Spirit Award from The Lung Association for
serving back to back terms as Honourary Chair of the Christmas
Seal Campaign and her on-going support. She has also served as
Co-Honourary Chair of the Hamilton Aids Network Wellness Centre
Fundraising Campaign and Honorary Chair of the M.S. Society Carnation
Campaign. In addition to these functions, Connie supports fundraisers
for the &quot;Y&quot; and The Heart and Stoke Foundation, speaks
to schools, church and community organizations about the role
of television journalism and moderates and emcees community events
and discussions about community issues.

<P>
In her spare time, Connie enjoys being with her young son, Calvin
Christopher, reading, and travelling. <BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="mailto:anchors@chch.wic.ca">Send Connie Smith a message here.</A></CENTER><P>
