<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Matt Hayes Biography</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<IMG SRC="../../images/matt.gif">

<P> MATT HAYES was born in Hamilton, Ontario, in 1958.  He attended
Father Loftus school in Ancaster,  St. Mary's high school in Hamilton,
followed by Mohawk College, where he graduated in 1981 in the field  of
Television Broadcasting.

<P> In June of Matt's graduating year, he
secured a job at CHEX-TV in Peterborough.  Six months later, he was
working at CHCH as a news reporter.  Three years after that, Matt began
his illustrious career as the  station's unpredictable, good-natured
weatherman.

<P> In addition to his famous roving weather reports on
CHCH, Matt also gained recognition as host of the  station's past weekly
variety show, "New Faces," as well as the half-hour TV special,
"Hollywood Hayes  On Assignment."

<P> Matt's singing talent allowed
him to record five songs and videos with Hamilton's
singer/songwriter/recording artist Jim Witter under the name The Weather
Boys.  Two of the songs, "The Weather Shuffle" and "Gotta Be Snow For
Christmas," received air-play on local radio stations with  proceeds
from the records being donated to the Jimmy Lomax Operation Santa Claus
Fund.

<P> Matt has also appeared in a number of Hamilton Players'
Guild productions, receiving a Best Supporting Actor  Award in 1986 for
his role of Ben Silverman in "The Sunshine Boys."  He has been featured
in numerous  television and radio commercials; and worked for almost two
years as a radio host on CHML.  Currently,  Matt co-hosts the morning
show, "Sunni and Hayes," on Hamilton's K-Lite-FM.

<P> When not
appearing on television or radio or lecturing at Mohawk College, Matt
gives generously of his  time to several local charities.  He is the
1994 Honourary Chairman for the Super Cities Walk for Multiple 
Sclerosis and Honourary Chairman for the Ontario Juvenile Diabetes
Foundation.</P><P> Matt is married to Patti and both are proud parents
of daughter, Kyra.
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P>
