<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ken Welch Biography</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../images/bkgd.jpg">
<IMG SRC="../../images/ken.gif">

<P>CHCH-TV's
quick-witted sports anchor and reporter KEN WELCH was born in Toronto in
1954.   Although his family resided in Tweed, followed by Bramalea, it
was in Belleville, Ontario, where Ken  completed his elementary
education, and obtained his high school diploma.  After a two year
sojourn at  Kingston's Queen's University, Ken transferred to Carleton
University in Ottawa, where he graduated with  a Bachelor of Arts Degree
in History.

<P> Ken Welch's broadcast career began in 1981, at
Newmarket radio station, CKAN.   In August, 1982, he  made the switch to
CFOS Radio, Owen Sound, where he took on the duties of news and sports
reporter, as  well as that of host for a weekly sports phone-in show. 
Word soon spread about Ken's personable nature  and innate sports
reporting talent, and by 1984, he was working at CHYM/CKGL Radio in
Kitchener as sports director.

<P>Recognizing Ken's capabilities, CHCH-TV hired him in October, 1985,
as writer, producer, and anchor  for the weekend sportscasts .  Since
1988, Ken has applied those same skills to CHCH-TV's Final Edition
newscasts, weeknights.  In addition to those responsibilities, Ken has
been the host and sideline reporter for University Football  Game of the
Week (1989 to present); for four years he hosted, wrote, and co-produced
a weekly Canadian  Football League show, CFL Journal (1988-91).  As
well, Ken has provided reports from the sites of five  Grey Cup
Championship games; and co-hosted the Save the Ti-Cats Telethon (1989).

<P>Outside the sports world, Ken generously gives of his time to youth
oriented endeavours, e.g., he regularly  visits  local schools as part
of "Literacy" and "Learn To Read" Weeks; participates in CHCH-TV's
annual  Mother's Day Telethon to benefit the Children's Hospital at
Chedoke-McMaster; and he was the  Honourary Chairman of the 1995 Big
Brother's Bowlathon of Hamilton-Wentworth, Burlington.

<P> Never at a loss for words, Ken's command of the English language has made him a
popular figure on the  speakers' circuit.  He has emceed banquets and
delivered after-dinner speeches all over southern Ontario,  in
Nashville, Tennessee and even in New Orleans, Louisiana.

<P>Ken and his wife, Laura, are the proud parents of one beautiful child, Michael.<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="mailto:anchors@chch.wic.ca">Send Ken Welch a message here.</A></CENTER><P>
