<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 12/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, December 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Specialists Protest 
    <li>Bernardo Attacked   
    <li>CAI Hargrove     
    <li>Pearson Severance   
    <li>Main St. Flood      
    <li>UI Stats            
    <li>GM Layoffs St Kits  
    <li>Fewer Pols          
    <li>Halton - GTA
    <li>Sailing Death       
    <li>Grenade - Ancaster    
    <li>Car Lease Language  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Specialists Protest</b><p>
Surgeons across the province have taken the day off, in a continuing protest by doctors, against the Harris government.  Only emergency patients will receive treatment, and specialists across the province are being urged to shut their doors in a one day protest next week. While doctors continue to edge closer to a full-blown strike; the Ontario Medical Association says, it believes a settlement with the province could come, this weekend. 
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Attacked</b><p>
Convicted sex-killer Paul Bernardo has been attacked by another inmate at the Kingston Penitentiary.<br>  Corrections officials say the incident occurred as Bernardo was being escorted back to his cell this morning after taking a shower.<br>  Another inmate outside his cell stepped up and punched Bernardo in the face.<br>  Bernardo suffered a cut on his cheek and a swollen eye.<br>  The unidentified inmate has been placed in segregation.
<hr>
<b>CAI Hargrove</b><p>
As 37-hundred members of the Canadian Autoworkers Union prepare to vote on a contract designed to save Canadian Airlines ... their national president is slamming the deal, and continuing efforts to renegotiate. Buzz Hargrove is calling on the federal government to pump more money into the restructuring plan... and re-instate regulatory controls over Canadian skies.<br> 
<i> <br>   The president of the Canadian Autoworkers wants federal government to step in to save Canadian Airlines.<br>  Buzz Hargrove is still smarting over  Ottawa's order forcing the holdout union to vote on a rescue package for Canadian.<br> But so far, the autoworker's leadership has refused to tell its 37 hundred members to vote against the restructuring plan. <br>Yesterday... Hargrove was beseiged by members who want to vote on the package which contains a sliding scale of pay cuts.<br>  But this British Columbia union leader says most Canadian employees feel the government has sold them out.<br>  The union says Canadian's problems are caused by cutthroat competition with Air Canada.<br>  It wants Ottawa to re-regulate the industry.<br>  But the transport minister says reregulation won't fly.<br>   Meanwhile.. Hargrove says the the fight over Canadian has gotten personal.<br>  His former wife's address and phone number have been posted on the Internet.<br>  There have been bomb threats..and tires slashed.  All this is happening as Canadian's 16 thousand workers begin voting on the restructuring plan.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Pearson Severance</b><p>
Meanwhile; 500 employees at Pearson Airport are enjoying a federal windfall of nearly 10-thousand dollars each. That's the average amount paid out in severance benefits to the airport workers ... even though none of them has lost their jobs. In fact, they haven't been out of work for even so much as a day. The federal government paid out nearly five million dollars to the workers, however, because the airport was turned over to a local airport authority and officially, they are no longer civil servants.
<hr>
<b>Main St. Flood</b><p>
Regional crews mopping up a wet mess in central Hamilton this morning.<br>  A water main broke on Main Street at Grant during this morning's rush hour, spewing water several blocks away.<br>  A road construction crew had been working nearby just before the break.<br>  A spokeswoman with Hamilton Wentworth's Sewer and Water Department says there have been several complaints of flooding by nearby residents and businesses.
<hr>
<b>UI Stats</b><p>
The economy may be improving, but the unemployment rate, isn't. Statscan says, the national jobless rate edged upwards in November ... to a worrisome ten percent ... the worst performance in three months.<br>  In Ontario, unemployment climbed by two-tenths of a percent, to 9.3. But Newfoundland, Nova Scotia, Saskatchewan, Alberta, and B.C. all reported slight improvement.<br>  Locally, Hamilton's jobless rate rose slightly to 7.3 percent... still one of the lowest rates in Canada. Kitchener- Waterloo also reported a small increase in unemployment ... while Toronto held steady, and improvement was reported, in the Niagara Peninsula, and London.
<hr>
<b>GM Layoffs St Kits</b><p>
 33 workers at General Motors in St. Catharines, have one week left on the job. They will be laid off, December 15th; as the plant cuts production of its v-6 engines, and winds down its foundry operations. 88 more workers will will be laid off, March 1st.
<hr>
<b>Fewer Pols</b><p>
Ontario will do without 27 MPPs, come the next provincial election. The Harris government kept a campaign promise, and cut the number of provincial politicians from 130, to 103. New ridings will match existing federal boundaries. The province says the move will save, 11-million dollars a year.
<hr>
<b>Halton - GTA</b><p>
 David Crombie's 'who does what panel', will tell the province what to do with Toronto, this morning; calling for a super-city; and the establishment of a greater Toronto region, stretching from Burlington to Clarington ... and north from Lake Ontario to Bradford. What will that mean for the region of Halton? Deborah Walker reports:
<i> <br>The "who does what" panel resurrects some of the recommendations of the Golden Report, endorsing the GTA-wide provision of services, and the elimination of overlapping layers of municipal government. But unlike Golden, the panel also looked at municipal government beyond the borders of the GTA.  <br>As a member of the "who does what" panel, Cooke won't comment on specific recommendations until they're released to the public.  <br>The chairman of Halton Region supports change, but only if it's change for the better.  <br>The mayor of Burlington wants more details before he comments on the recommendations. But Terry Cooke warns it's too late for Burlington to reconsider throwing its lot in with Hamilton- Wentworth.  <br>The recommendations of the "who does what" panel are just that.  It's up to the Ontario government to decide whether to accept them.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Sailing Death</b><p>
Australian authorities have abandoned the search for an 18 year old Fonthill resident, missing, and presumed drowned, after a freak accident on board a sailboat, off the north coast of Australia.<br>  Derek Zavitz was part of a student adventure program; and was sailing on board the Concordia, when the ship's battery exploded, and apparently threw him overboard. His body has not yet been recovered. A memorial service for Zavitz is planned for tomorrow, in Wainfleet.
<hr>
<b>Grenade - Ancaster</b><p>
Nine year old Barron Thompson's show and tell subject, turned out to be a show stopper, in Ancaster, yesterday. Thompson was on his way home when he pulled a hand-grenade from his back pack on board the school bus. A startled driver, who did not know that the grenade was inactive; stopped the bus, and evacuated the students. Police bomb squad officers moved in to take the device away. That left Thompson to explain to his father, how the souvenir he had picked up at a sportsman's show; had suddenly disappeared.
<hr>
<b>Car Lease Language</b><p>
The cost of car-buying is driving many consumers down the road less travelled.<br>  Leasing, is becoming more popular than ever ... even though car lease contracts are more confusing than federal tax rules. But provincial regulators are hoping to take the mystery, frustration and danger out of leasing with some plain language ... as Lauran Sabourin reports.
<i><br>  Shopping for a new car can be an intimidating experience.<br>  Should they buy ..should they lease..what's it all going to cost ...<br>  Leasing started to become more popular as cars became more expensive.<br>  People couldn't deal with the sticker shock.<br>  The lower monthly payments were more palatable..<br>  But with leasing had its problems.<br>   People knew what their monthly payment was.<br>  But often weren't told what the residual value of the vehicle would be. <br>  But there should be no surprises now.<br>  Effective January 1st 1997 car dealers will be required to fully disclose what a vehicle costs a consumer.<br>  Taxes, mileage, down payments, responsibilities. <br>  Every thing will be laid on the line.<br>  Now dealers won't be able to simply tell customers what they want to hear.<br>  They'll have to put everything down on paper.</i>









