<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 12/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, December 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Hargrove Newser     
    <li>Doc Dispute         
    <li>Strike Clash        
    <li>Workfare            
    <li>Students - Fumes      
    <li>Christmas Ride      
    <li>Pot House           
    <li>Native Dispute      
    <li>Paris Canadian      
    <li>Simpson Latest      
    <li>Jenny Jones         
    <li>Ghali UN            
    <li>Tiny Tim Funeral    
    <li>Bobbitt Minister    
    <li>Nicholson Star      
    <li>Billboard Awards    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hargrove Newser</b><p>
Buzz Hargrove says the union will keep on trying.   <br>   The head of the Canadian Auto Workers Union called a news conference in Toronto today to restate the union's case for more government help for Canadian Airlines International. Hargrove says the union will use at least the balance of the day to try to get the federal government to move on the issue of re-regulating the industry. It will also try to negotiate some of the issues with the company. Hargrove says he's in contact with the federal labor minister's office, the federal transport minister, B.C. premier Glen Clark and Canadian Airlines president Kevin Benson. Earlier today, Hargrove ruled out a court challenge to the federal decision ordering the union to allow its members to vote on the company's wage-reduction package.
<hr>
<b>Doc Dispute</b><p>
The battle between Queens Park and the province's doctors is heating up again. Despite optimism on the part of the Ontario Medical Association that a deal is close, many general surgeons are closing their offices on Friday and now the Specialist Coalition of Ontario is calling for a provincewide closure of all specialist offices, beginning next Friday. But the coalition is refusing to call it a strike. Coalition vice-chairman Dr. William Hughes says patients expecting to see a specialist December 13th will be rescheduled. But he maintains emergency services will be provided.
<hr>
<b>Strike Clash</b><p>
Videotaped evidence from the spring riot at Queen's Park contradicts OPP claims that striking civil servants used picket signs as weapons. A confidential report on the March 18th incident reveals that one picket was hit in the head by an OPP sergeant -- then hit by another officer as he fell. The 114-page report on allegations made by Stephen Giles was delivered yesterday to OPP commissioner Thomas O'Grady. The OPP has 30 days to decide whether to take disciplinary action.
<hr>
<b>Workfare</b><p>
If the province approves it, Hamilton- Wentworth's workfare program could be up and running by the middle of next month. Initially, only new welfare applicants will have to sign up for workfare. Another six-thousand people who are already collecting benefits will be gradually phased into the program. Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>Only a handful of Hamilton- Wentworth regional councillors object to the workfare program adopted by council this week.  <br>Anyone who's eligible, and refuses to participate in workfare, can have their benefits cut off.  <br>For the first four months, recipients have to conduct a job search.  After that, they'll have three options... register with a job placement agency, sign up for a retraining program, or work for a non-profit group as a volunteer. That's something many welfare recipients are already doing.  <br>Schuster says the workfare program won't cost Hamilton- Wentworth Region a cent, and it's expected to produce a five per cent drop in the welfare caseload by next year.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Students - Fumes</b><p>
Authorities still don't know the source of nauseating fumes at a Hamilton high school yesterday. Thirty students and staff at Sir Winston Churchill Secondary School were taken to hospital after being overcome. Dozens of people reported coughing, headaches, sore throats, nausea and burning eyes. The school was checked for natural gas but nothing unusual showed up.
<hr>
<b>Christmas Ride</b><p>
With Christmas just 20 days away, Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are kicking off their annual holiday ride programs.<br>  Ride lanes will be set up every day throughout the region to help reduce drinking and driving.<br>  Last holiday season, there were 33 collisions involving drunk drivers, including 2 fatalities.<br>  In the first week of Ontario's strict new driving suspensions for impaired driving, 4 people in Hamilton Wentworth have lost their licences for 90 days.<br>  Carol Redmond, whose husband was killed by a drunk driver 3 years ago, had a sobering message at the ride kickoff this morning.
<hr>
<b>Pot House</b><p>
Quite the surprise for police checking out a house break-in overnight.<br>  A neighbour had called after seeing two men run from the back of the house with two garbage bags.<br>  When police went inside to investigate, they found marijuana leaves spread out on a table and a hydroponic growing system with several marijuana plants in the basement.<br>  31 year old Matthew Gordon Kelly of Hamilton faces a number of narcotics charges.
<hr>
<b>Native Dispute</b><p>
A dispute that closed a school on the Six Nations Reserve near Brantford has been resolved. Natives used their vehicles to blockade the school for four days to protest the actions of a teacher they say was insensitive to native language and customs. They say the teacher reprimanded two boys for speaking the Cayuga language in a gym class. The protest ended yesterday when a Six Nations Band Council decided to sent a resolution demanding the removal of the teacher to the Federal Indian Affairs Department.
<hr>
<b>Paris Canadian</b><p>
A Victoria man is preparing to fly to Paris to join his injured son, who lost his bride to a terrorist attack on Tuesday. Newlyweds Frank Stonebanks and Helen Viel were on a Paris commuter train that was bombed. Roger Stonebanks says his 30-year-old son's injuries are not life-threatening and he expects to leave the intensive-care unit today.
<hr>
<b>Simpson Latest</b><p>
The judge in the OJ Simpson civil trial has allowed testimony banned at his criminal trial. A battered women's counselor told jurors yesterday that a woman named Nicole called to say she was being stalked by her ex-husband. The counselor said the call came in just days before Nicole Brown and her friend Ron Goldman were murdered. Simpson is being sued by the families of the victims for wrongful death.
<hr>
<b>Jenny Jones</b><p>
A man who killed a gay admirer who revealed the crush on a "Jenny Jones Show" taping has been sentenced to 25 to 50 years in prison. Jonathan Schmitz was convicted last month of second-degree murder in the shooting death of Scott Amedure. During the trial, witnesses said Schmitz believed he was going on the show in March 1995 to meet a female secret admirer. Amedure was shot three days after the taping. The show never aired, but was played in court during trial.
<hr>
<b>Ghali UN</b><p>
Boutros Boutros-Ghali has "temporarily" suspended his candidacy for another five-year term as UN chief. That opens the door for other Africans to vie for his job. But Boutros-Ghali insists he's still in the race, adding more confusion to the bizarre proceedings. Boutros-Ghali's term expires December 31st. Diplomats say the 74-year-old Egyptian is prepared to withdraw in light of an American veto against his re-election. They say he doesn't want to be blamed by Africans for denying the continent another five-year term by staying in the race. At the same time, they say he doesn't want to let down his backers. No other candidate has been nominated yet.
<hr>
<b>Tiny Tim Funeral</b><p>
Tiny Tim has been laid to rest the way he would have wanted it -- with a ukulele on his chest surrounded by tulips. About 400 people showed up for his funeral in Minneapolis yesterday. A fan placed six rose-colored tulips in Tiny Tim's casket, and someone had placed a stuffed white rabbit in as well. Tiny Tim died Saturday night of a heart attack suffered just as he was performing his signature song, "Tiptoe Thru' the Tulips."
<hr>
<b>Bobbitt Minister</b><p>
And they say the lord works in mysterious ways, but this one has many people baffled. Remember John Bobbitt -- the guy who gained notoriety three years ago after his wife cut off his penis? Well it's now Reverend Bobbitt. He says he's been ordained a minister in, where else...Las Vegas. Bobbitt has done a lot of things since the impromptu amputation, including an adult movie and a jail stint for assaulting his fiancee.
<hr>
<b>Nicholson Star</b><p>
Its "Jack Nicholson Day" in Hollywood! The honorary mayor of Hollywood, Johnny Grant made the announcement to commemorate the two time Oscar winner getting a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. Nicholson is the proud recipient of the Hollywood chamber of commerce's 2,077th star. You can find it at 6925 Hollywood Boulevard in front of Mann's Chinese Theater.
<hr>
<b>Billboard Awards</b><p>
Madonna has made her first public appearance since becoming a mother. She was on hand in Las Vegas last night at the Billboard Music Awards, where she won the artist achievement prize. It was also a big night for Alanis Morissette of Ottawa. She won the artist of the year award. Mariah Carey was a double winner.









