<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 29, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Eves Statement      
    <li>Docs                
    <li>Labour - Sudbury      
    <li>Casino Spinoffs     
    <li>Drinking & Driving  
    <li>Liberal Leadership  
    <li>CAI Latest          
    <li>Flamboro Merger     
    <li>Canal Body          
    <li>Coats for Kids      
    <li>Frechette           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Eves Statement</b><p>
We're doing better than we thought we would ... but three billion more, in provincial budget cuts ... are coming.  That's the word from Ontario finance minister Ernie Eaves. But Eaves was not prepared to detail his plans ... when he delivered an economic statement to the province at Queen's Park. Instead the finance minister focused on the deficit, and government success in bringing it 40 per cent below what it was, when the Tories came to power.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Docs</b><p>
Ontario's doctors are stepping up the pressure in their efforts to resist provincial government budgets cuts to the health care sector. General surgeons announced that they will stop treating all but cancer and emergency patients, beginning next Friday.<br> Meanwhile, most physicians in Mississauga took the day off today, in protest over government plans to cap their salaries, and force new doctors to work in underserviced areas.
<hr>
<b>Labour - Sudbury</b><p>
While the doctors continue their protest against the Harris government ... organized labour is having some trouble keeping the momentum going.<br> Labour leaders in Sudbury have now rejected plans for a 'days of protest' rally in their city, scheduled for February.<br> Steelworkers in the nickle city say the demonstrations have failed to get the government to change its course on program and budget cuts. And the District Labour Council says ... February is no time to take to the streets ... in Sudbury.
<hr>
<b>Casino Spinoffs</b><p>
While it may seem that Ontario's economy is still very sluggish ... you'd have a tough time proving it, in Niagara Falls.<br> The honeymoon city is gushing with excitement and activity with the grand opening of the Niagara Falls Casino just over a week away.<br> As Lauran Sabourin reports businesses are cashing in on a multi-million dollar jackpot of economic spinoffs.
<i><br>  Casino Niagara is still a muddy construction site.<br>  A site that within the last year has employed three thousand construction workers.<br>  Eighty million dollars has been spent on construction materials alone.<br>  But construction isn't the only industry that has come out a winner.<br>  Local retail businesses are cashing in big on the casino.<br>  Beatties Stationary is supplying all of the office materials at Casino Niagara. <br>  Six hundred thousand is being spent on office related tools and supplies.  <br>  At Cataract Ice in the falls they're packing and stacking bags in preparation for all of the casino parties. <br>  Restaurant managers are looking at hiring more staff to feed hungry gamblers.. <br>  Even the mood on economically depressed Queen Street is changing..<br>  Where the businesses go from here no one is sure.<br>  But with six million people spending 650 million dollars a year at the casino,  many business operators at looking at grabbing even a small piece of that action.. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Drinking & Driving</b><p>
It also got more expensive to drink, and drive. as of midnight ... the province began to enforce new penalties that will provide an automatic 90 day licence suspension for anyone caught exceeding the legal blood alchol limit, behind the wheel. At least four people have been charged already, in Kitchener, Toronto, and Owen Sound. No one has yet been charged, in Hamilton-Wentworth.
<hr>
<b>Liberal Leadership</b><p>
Provincial Liberals begin their leadership convention ... facing off at Maple Leaf Gardens in Toronto, today. Seven candidates are seeking to replace out-going leader Lyn McLeod ... and the odds on favourite is former food bank director, and rookie Toronto MPP ... Gerard Kennedy.  
<hr>
<b>CAI Latest</b><p>
Blame it on Buzz Hargrove. The CAW president is being characterized as the villain ... in the drama surrounding the potential collapse of Canadian Airlines.<br> Hargrove stormed out of a meeting with federal transport minister David Anderson last night; claiming Anderson had nothing to offer but the same old lecture, on the financial state of Canadian.<br> Hargrove's union is the last hold-out in a plan to bail out the financially strapped airline. The CAW objects to a proposed five percent pay cut, and will not allow its 32-hundred members to vote on the restructuring plan. Hargrove wants Ottawa to kick in more money. The federal government says, it has gone as far as it can, to save Canadian. Airline officials now say however, that Hargrove's union may not matter. They believe with five other unions already on board, creditors will now accept the restructuring plan for Canadian.
<hr>
<b>Flamboro Merger</b><p>
Residents of Flamborough turned out by the dozen last night ... to show their opposition to the Hamilton-Wentworth super-city plan.<br> Flamborough mayor Ted McMeekin says, he wants to bring in a new mediator, and renegotiate the current deal, with a little more sensitivity to public input.<br>  Ian Dovey reports.
<i><br>  There have been few issues that have sparked the public's attention as the proposed supercity concept in Hamilton Wentworth.<br>  Mayor Ted McMeekin says it's time to reneogiate. <br>    A supercity that includes Flamborough is a sensitive issue for residents here, but still people came out to this public meeting to voice their distaste. <br>    The meeting also attracted this councillor from Dundas, a community that also opposes a megacity. <br>    A citizens group has started a petition against the supercity.<br>  Organizers hope the signatures end up on municipal affairs minister Al Leaches desk. <br>    </i>
<hr>
<b>Canal Body</b><p>
Police have now identified the body of a woman pulled from the Welland Canal in St. Catharines, yesterday. 46 year old Elita Johnson died, when her car left the road and plunged into the frigid waters just after one o'clock yesterday. Witnesses say they could hear the woman screaming, but could only watch helplessly as the car quickly sank in the canal. It took St. Lawrence Seaway divers 20 minutes to find the victim, and pull her from the car. Attempts to revive her in hospital, were futile. An autopsy will be conducted, today.
<hr>
<b>Coats for Kids</b><p>
A heart warming story being played out across Hamilton Wentworth today.<br>  This as hundreds of kids pick up donated winter clothing collected by regional police.<br>  Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  This is the second winter kids from across Hamilton Wentworth will be kept a little warmer thanks to community donations.  The warm a heart campaign, organized by Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police, has been collecting warm coats, boots, hats and mitts for the last several weeks.  <br>  This year, people have donated three times as much as last winter.  <br>  While the clothing is meant to warm little bodies across the region this winter, handing them out seems to warm the hearts of those involved.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Frechette</b><p>
Olympic synchronized swimming medalist Sylvie Frechette ... is embarking on a new career.<br>  Frechette will join the internationally reknowned Cirque du Soleil ... to develop and star in a new 'water show' ... to be presented as a regular attraction of the new Bellagio Hotel, in Las Vegas. Both the show, and the hotel will open in the spring, of 1998.








