<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 28, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>CAI Unions        
    <li>Cardiac Wait        
    <li>No Mini Budget      
    <li>St. Liz Inquest 6   
    <li>Bell Cancer         
    <li>Bell Warning        
    <li>Nuke Plant Licence  
    <li>Murder Charge       
    <li>Scarf Bandit        
    <li>Gun Law             
    <li>Fireworks Explosion 
    <li>Zaire Canada        
    <li>Bouchard Mission    
    <li>Crash - Genie         
    <li>Jagged Little Pill  
    <li>Ancaster / Broadway   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>CAI Unions</b><p>
The deadline for a deal between Canadian Airlines and its six unions has been pushed back one week.  <br> Airline president Kevin Benson says he's confident he'll have a deal by then. Benson challenged two of the carrier's six unions to put a restructuring proposal to their members for a vote. CUPE, representing flight attendants, and the CAW, representing terminal staff, consider a pay cut unacceptable. CUPE president Benson said he's confident pressure from other unions will persuade CUPE and the CAW to put the deal to a vote. He also said he's going ahead with restructuring talks with the four unions that are on-side.
<hr>
<b>Cardiac Wait</b><p>
While one of this country's major air carriers continues on financial life support,  waiting lists for non-emergency heart surgery in Ontario have reached an all-time high.<br> Some cardiologists believe that a crisis is developing.<br> A group which monitors waiting lists says there are more than 15-hundred people waiting for non-emergency bypass surgery.<br> The Cardiac Care Network says the median waiting time is 70 days, but some folk are waiting as long as four months.<br> Patients needing emergency surgery do get immediate care.<br> The growth in waiting lists comes eight months after the province spent 16-million dollars to improve cardiac services.<br> The money was to fund more than 14-hundred bypass operations with the goal of cutting the waiting list by one-third.
<hr>
<b>No Mini Budget</b><p>
Finance minister Ernie Eves delivers an economic statement today and premier Mike Harris says it will offer a rosy view.<br> He says the numbers will show Ontario is "ahead of schedule" in cutting spending and reducing the province's 8.7 billion-dollar deficit.<br> But the update won't include the information municipalities, hospitals, school boards and post-secondary institutions are looking for.<br> The premier says funding information for the province's transfer partners won't come until next month at the earliest.<br> Liberal finance critic Gerry Phillips says it's going to be "a window dressing statement " that won't tell people how the tories plan to balance Ontario's books.
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Inquest 6</b><p>
More disturbing testimony at the coroner's inquest into deaths at a Hamilton seniors home. The jury heard that a resident of St. Elizabeth Villa jumped to his death from an upper floor window. But, when his body was discovered, police weren't even called. Dwight Ryan reports.
<i><br>  Members of the jury had a first hand look at St. Elizabeth Villa ..touring the facility they have heard so much about in recent weeks.<br>  The coroner's inquest is investigating five deaths at the villa..five of more than forty in just over a year.  <br>  Earlier in the day jury members heard dramatic testimony about the suicide of an elderly villa resident not long ago.  The man's crumpled body was found outside the building shortly after ten o'clock in the evening. <br>  RNA Sherry Farrell said Sister Maria was flustered and asked her to call a doctor.  Armed with a flashlight the sister and Farrell saw that the man, surrounded by blood, was obviously dead.<br>  Further investigation showed that he had removed his screen and jumped from an upper floor window.<br>   It was the doctor who called the coroner and police.  Later the angry officer said if anything like that happened again, to call 911 immediately.<br>  The suicide story was just one of many that put the villa's management in a bad light.<br>  Former health care aide Linda Bonnoly told coroner Bill Lucas and jury members that she was repeatedly yelled at by Sister Maria.  It was her way or not at all.<br>  She detailed instances of sour milk being sent to the residents and fresh cereal poured over stale cereal.  Damp sheets being returned from the laundry. Improvising when supplies such as bed pads and diapers weren't available. <br>  When the investigation into St. Elizabeth Villa began, staff members were asked to write letters to the medical officer of health defending the facility.<br>  Linda Connoly refused.  A couple of weeks later she quit.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Bell Cancer</b><p>
An expert says the high rate of cancer among workers at a Bell Canada office in Hamilton is coincidence. Dr. Gilles Theriault, an epidemiologist at McGill University in Montreal, says further testing would be useless. Eight cases of cancer have been confirmed among 50 workers on one floor of the Bell Canada Centre, including five breast cancers. In September, the workers moved from the third floor to the seventh. Tests of air quality, electromagnetic and radiation emissions were done, but nothing unusual was found. Bell Canada is setting up a cancer surveillance program for workers who were on the third floor.
<hr>
<b>Bell Warning</b><p>
And a warning from Bell Canada today about a new phone scam.<br> Urgent messages are being left on voice mail concerning accidents, deaths or prize winnings.<br> The recepient is asked to call back a number beginning with 8-0-9.<br> What they aren't told is the number originates from the Caribbean, and that the call could cost you as much as 100 dollars.
<hr>
<b>Nuke Plant Licence</b><p>
Canada's oldest nuclear-power plant finds out today how much faith regulators have in it.<br> The Pickering facility just east of Toronto is expected to get an unusually short six-month licence renewal, not the standard two-year renewal Hydro wants. A shorter term would be a rebuke for a litany of safety and staff problems.<br> The Atomic Energy Control Board is holding a public hearing in Oshawa today before ruling on the plant's application for a new licence.
<hr>
<b>Murder Charge</b><p>
Niagara Region police have made an arrest in connection with a shooting death earlier this month in Fort Erie.<br> The body of Fred Grondin was found lying beside a van on the shoulder of Highway 3 November 7th.<br> Charged with first-degree murder is 30-year-old Patrick O'Connor of Fort Erie.<br> He is to appear in a St. Catharines court Friday morning.
<hr>
<b>Scarf Bandit</b><p>
Police in Hamilton believe they may have nabbed the "scarf bandit".<br> Over the past few weeks, several stores and submarine shops on Hamilton mountain have been robbed by a suspect wearing a scarf across his face.<br> Yesterday, police arrested a suspect after a Bargain Shop on Fennell Avenue was robbed by a man wearing a scarf and matching the description from similar robberies.<br> 21 year old Kurt Gray of Hamilton is charged with robbery in the Bargain Shop hit.<br> Police are continuing their investigation.
<hr>
<b>Gun Law</b><p>
Justice minister Allan Rock has tabled new regulations that accompany the gun-control bill passed almost a year ago. As Ian Dovey reports, the major provision calls for a person to be notified if a spouse or ex-spouse applies for a gun permit.<br>
The person notified would then have a chance to wave a red flag.                 <I><br>  Ottawa says buying a firearm will under the proposed regulations be straightforward and practical.<br>  The new process will be much like a credit card purchase.<br>  The swipe of a license and registration card will verify that the buyer is authroized to buy the gun and that the store is authorized to sell it. <br>    Beginning in 1998 everyone who owns a gun will have to have a license.<br>  The five year license will range from 10 to 80 dollars depending on the weapon.<br>  Regarding the storage of weapons... non restricted firearms will have to be stored unloaded, locked or deactivated in a separate location from the ammunition.<br>  Restricted or prohibited weapons must be stored in the same fashion but with a trigger lock in a locked case or cabinet.<br>  Rock says the existing permit to transport firearms will replaced with simpler rules.<br>  The anti gun lobby supports Ottawa's initiatives. <br>    Rock says the regualtions will apply to aboriginal peoples as well, but enforced with respect for the aboriginal way of life.<br>  Ontario along with Alberta, Manitoba, Saskatchewan and the territories say they will not enforce the registry.<br>  </I>
<hr>
<b>Fireworks Explosion</b><p>
Peruvian police say six people are dead and at least seven people are seriously injured from a fireworks factory explosion in a Lima shantytown.<br> The police say a spark apparently started the deadly blaze which was still burning Wednesday evening. Police officer Hector Grados says all the injured people have been taken to hospitals.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Canada</b><p>
Foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy says 15 countries have agreed to a multinational mission to help Rwandan refugees in central Africa.<br> Axworthy says while diplomatic efforts to get the mission off the ground have been frustrating, he feels things are moving now.<br> He says details of the force will be worked out under United Nations rules tomorrow.<br> He says the force will be occupied with setting up relief headquarters in Uganda, reconnaissance to identify areas of need and co-ordination of delivery of aid packages.
<hr>
<b>Bouchard Mission</b><p>
He may not be a team player, but Quebec premier Lucien Bouchard has decided to join the Team Canada Trade Mission to Asia in January.<br> Taking part will be prime minister Chretien, all the premiers, the leaders of the two territories, and representatives of 300 companies. Bouchard's decision is a break from the policy of his predecessor, Jacques Parizeau.<br>  He did not take part in the last two trade missions, to China in 1994 and to India last year.
<hr>
<b>Crash - Genie</b><p>
It was a big night for controversial movie director David Cronenberg last night. Banned in some countries, Cronenberg's film "Crash" won the most Genie awards -- but not best picture. Cronenberg's notorious blend of sex and car collisions won him the Genie for best director -- one of five genies that went to "Crash."<br> The best picture award went to John Greyson's "Lilies."
<hr>
<b>Jagged Little Pill</b><p>
Alanis Morissette's "Jagged Little Pill" appears to be the juggernaut of the 90's. The Recording Industry Association of America reports the album has sold 14-million copies, averaging sales of one-million a month. That's enough to make it one of the three best-selling albums of the 90's, up there with Hootie and the Blowfish's "Cracked Rear View" and the soundtrack to "The Bodyguard."
<hr>
<b>Ancaster / Broadway</b><p>
The Ancaster Arts Council goes broadway once again with its fourth annual community musical.<br> "The Magic of Broadway," with a cast of over 60, taps into the blockbuster shows ...."Phantom" ...."Evita".... "Les Miz" ...."Guys and Dolls"....and "West Side Story" among others.<br> Proceeds from ticket sales are donated to community programs.<br> "The Magic of Broadway" runs tonight through Saturday at the Ancaster High School auditorium.








