<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 27, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Supercity Update    
    <li>St. Liz Inquest 5   
    <li>Drunk Driving       
    <li>Latimer Appeal      
    <li>Baby - Shot           
    <li>Ross Appeal         
    <li>Auditor Report      
    <li>OJ Simpson          
    <li>Air Bag Dead        
    <li>Crash Video         
    <li>Canadian Air        
    <li>Cancer Connection   
    <li>Election Law        
    <li>Phone Hike          
    <li>Opera Hamilton      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Supercity Update</b><p>
Some say it's just another stalling tactic. Others say it's an essential delay to allow more public consultation. <br>   Either way, Hamilton city council voted last night to wait two more weeks before making a final decision on the proposal to merge Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities into one supercity. Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>Several members of Hamilton city council came to the meeting ready to vote, especially because municipal jobs are on the line.  <br>Even some who oppose the plan, are anxious to get on with the vote.  <br>In the end, council voted to delay the final vote for two more weeks.  </i>
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Inquest 5</b><p>
Dining room food routinely recycled. Mouldy juice bottles often refilled ...just some of the disturbing testimony coming out of a coroner's inquest looking into deaths at a a Hamilton home for seniors. Dwight Ryan has more.
<i><br>  Letitia Jones worked as a health care aide at St. Elizabeth Villa for three years.<br>     During that time, she testified she repeatedlay witnessed incidents of poor patient care.<br>  She told the jury that Sister Elizabeth often refilled milk bags from a bottle.  And that on one occasion curdled milk was served on porridge.  Health care aides refused to serve it to the residents and gave them toast instead.<br>   She said orange juice bottles with black around the edges and mould inside would be refilled.<br>  Soup bowls from the dining room would routinely be emptied back into the pot.<br>   Jones went on to say that Sister Elizabeth mixed mashed potatoes with her bare hands.   And that Louis, a resident who helped in the kitchen would peel carrots, potatoes and onions with his bare hands, despite having an infected finger. <br>  Inquest counsel Angela Paparella asked Letitia Jones if she had ever spoken to Sister Elizabeth about the incidents.  No, she replied, I was scared of her, she yelled at me a couple of times. <br>  In earlier testimony, registered practical nurse Debbie Smith told jury members that Sister Elizabeth had scolded her for calling an ambulance after an elderly woman had fallen and injured her back.<br>  RPN's weren't to call for help without following the correct protocol.<br>  Smith however returned to St. Elizabeth Villa after working in Mississauga for a month.  When the probe into allegations of poor care began, Smith wrote to medical officer of health and the media defending the Villa.<br>  Jury members will tour St. Elizabeth Villa Wednesday afternoon.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Drunk Driving</b><p>
A crackdown on drunk drivers begins later this week, just in time for the Christmas party season. Starting Friday, those who are caught drinking and driving in the province will automatically lose their licences for 90 days. Transportation minister Al Palladini says the new administrative driver's licence suspension program won't totally eliminate drunk driving, but says it will go a long way towards getting drunk drivers off the road. Palladini says he expects up to 200 drivers will lose their licences this weekend alone.
<hr>
<b>Latimer Appeal</b><p>
The Supreme Court of Canada today heard an appeal of Robert Latimer's second-degree murder conviction but reserved judgement. The Wilkie, Saskatchewan farmer wants his confession to killing his daughter thrown out, arguing police violated his constitutional rights. Latimer told police in 1993 he killed his 12-year-old daughter with carbon monoxide to end her suffering from cerebral palsy.<br>   He was given a life sentence in 1994.
<hr>
<b>Baby - Shot</b><p>
Elsewhere in an Ottawa-area courthouse a woman accused of attempting to murder her unborn child goes on trial today. Brenda Drummond is accused of shooting her fetus two days before the boy was born at her townhouse in Carleton Place. Lawyer Lawrence Greenspon will argue that because the infant was in the womb, he was not legally a human being and therefore, there is no victim.
<hr>
<b>Ross Appeal</b><p>
The crown intends to retry the former chief psychologist of the Grandview Training School for Girls on sex-related charges. 63 year-old Dr. Robert Ross was found not guilty of six charges of sexual abuse November 1st, but a Kitchener jury could not agree on 11 other counts. Ross, a criminology professor at the University of Ottawa, originally faced 19 charges ranging from rape to breach of trust.
<hr>
<b>Auditor Report</b><p>
Canada's auditor general warns the public is being put at risk by the prison release program. Denis Desautels says gaps in communication between federal and provincial authorities are letting dangerous criminals loose among the public. In his final report of the year, Desautels says public safety is being compromised by a lack of information sharing on prisoners who are released back into society.
<hr>
<b>OJ Simpson</b><p>
OJ Simpson's wrongful death civil trial is breaking for the American Thanksgiving weekend.  Simpson left the stand yesterday after three days of tough questioning by lawyers for the victims' families. His own lawyer opted not to cross-examine Simpson, but to bring him back when the defence presents its case.
<hr>
<b>Air Bag Dead</b><p>
It was just a minor fender-bender -- but it resulted in the death of a one-year-old girl who was decapitated by an air bag. Police in Boise, Idaho, say the accident in a parking lot triggered the passenger-side air bag in the car being driven by the girl's mother. Air bags have been blamed in the deaths of more than 30 American children in low-speed crashes.
<hr>
<b>Crash Video</b><p>
The final moments of an ill-fated Ethiopian Airliner were captured on video.  A South African couple on their honeymoon in the Comoros Islands witnessed the crash on Saturday  as they sunbathed on the beach and recorded the disaster. At least 120 people died in the crash. The Boeing aircraft was hijacked on a flight from Addis Ababa to the Kenyan capital of Nairobi, and the pilot was ordered to fly to Australia. It crashed just offshore from the tourist beach as onlookers watched in horror.
<hr>
<b>Canadian Air</b><p>
A flurry of last-ditch efforts to keep Canadian Airlines alive is nearing a midnight deadline. The airline wants to know by tonight whether workers will agree to a rescue plan that involves 10-per-cent pay cuts. Two unions say they won't go along with the pay cuts. As far as government support goes, Alberta has expressed its willingness to help, but Ottawa still hasn't.
<hr>
<b>Cancer Connection</b><p>
There's a new service up and running now across Ontario to help cancer patients deal with their disease and its treatment.<br>  Through "Cancer Connection", patients or their caregivers are matched up anonymously with a cancer survivor who's been through a similiar experience.<br>  Their contact is by phone, with the Canadian Cancer Society picking up the tab for any long distance charges.  
<br>  If you have cancer and want to hear from someone who shares your experience, or if you're a cancer survivor who'd like to help, you can call "Cancer Connection" toll free at 1-800-263-6750.
<hr>
<b>Election Law</b><p>
Pending senate approval, the next federal election campaign will be shorter and cheaper than in years past. The commons has given final approval to amendments to the Elections Act that would include setting up a permanent voters' list, eliminating the need for enumerators. A campaign could last as little as 36 days, and polls would close at roughly the same time across the country.
<hr>
<b>Phone Hike</b><p>
Local phone bills are on the rise for three-million Bell Canada customers.  The CRTC has approved a rate increase for customers in small- and medium-sized towns in Ontario and Quebec. Rates will rise next month by up to four-dollars.  In return, rural customers will have access to digital services, like call-waiting, late next year.
<hr>
<b>Opera Hamilton</b><p>
An operatic leading light is headlining in Hamilton this week.<br>  He's the internationally acclaimed baritone Allan Monk.<br>  The Calgary native, a regular with the Metropolitan Opera for thirty years, has performed in Hamilton on many occasions....this time in the Opera Hamilton production of Mozart's "Cosi Fan Tutte."           <br>  Performances of "Cosi Fan Tutte" continue Thursday and Saturday at Hamilton Place.








