<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 26, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Doctor Protest      
    <li>Witmer WCB          
    <li>Rent Study          
    <li>Supercity Forum     
    <li>Ont. Immigration    
    <li>Babysitter Killed   
    <li>Karla Parole        
    <li>Simpson Tuesday     
    <li>Sands Blown         
    <li>Candy Stamp         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Doctor Protest</b><p>
Starting next Monday, it may be hard trying to get an after-hours appointment with your family doctor. That's the day thousands of Ontario's doctors are being asked by the Coalition of Family Physicians to stop booking evening and weekend appointments. The move means more after-hours clinics will likely close their doors. It is the latest escalation in the dispute between doctors and the province over cutbacks to the health-care system. On November 8th, many doctors stopped taking on new patients and some surgeons have refused to book elective surgeries.
<hr>
<b>Witmer WCB</b><p>
The provincial government will cut benefits to injured workers under legislation to be introduced today. The proposed law, to replace the Workers Compensation Act, would slash benefits by five percentage points to 85 per cent of pre-injury earnings. Labor minister Elizabeth Witmer says the aim is to make the system more cost effective. New Brunswick, Nova Scotia and Newfoundland have cut benefits to injured workers in recent years. The law would also make people return to work earlier and tighten eligibility rules.
<hr>
<b>Rent Study</b><p>
A private research study suggests that a growing number of people who rent rather than own their own home, may be forced on the streets, because of the Harris government's loosening of rent controls. The study indicates a growing number of people are having trouble making the rent.
<hr>
<b>Supercity Forum</b><p>
A public meeting on the concept of a supercity in Hamilton Wentworth drew a less than enthusiastic response from residents of Hamilton last night. The city hall meeting attracted fifty people. And of that number less than half expressed an opinion.  Some of those present had already been involved with the municipal reform process... four people said they were in favour of a supercity, 14 were opposed. Many of them wanted a referendum. Hamilton city council will likely vote on the new single tier structure at a special council meeting on Friday, although some expect fireworks in the council chambers tonight over the megacity proposal at the city's regularly scheduled meeting.
<hr>
<b>Ont. Immigration</b><p>
A federal study confirms that Ontario gets the lion's share of immigrants to Canada.<br>   More than half the 1.5-million immigrants who arrived in the past six years settled in Ontario -- most of them in Toronto. British Columbia was the second favorite arrival spot, taking in 20 per cent of immigrants, while Quebec absorbed 12 per cent. Virtually none went to Saskatchewan and only two per cent went to the atlantic provinces.
<hr>
<b>Babysitter Killed</b><p>
Winnipeg police say an eight-year-old boy who shot and killed his 13-year-old babysitter is too young to be charged. But his parents aren't. Possible charges include unsafe storage of firearms, possession of a prohibited weapon or causing death by criminal negligence. Police say the shooting of the 13-year-old girl by her eight-year-old cousin was no accident. Crystal Ducharme was babysitting the boy Saturday when police say they got into a fight. They say the boy fired a shotgun at Ducharme as she hid behind a bathroom door -- killing her.
<hr>
<b>Karla Parole</b><p>
In spite of being eligible for day parole on January 6th, Karla Homolka has shown no signs of wanting to get out of prison.<br>  Homolka is serving a 12-year sentence in Kingston's prison for women after being convicted of helping her former husband, Paul Bernardo, kill two teenaged girls. Parole board officials say they have not been contacted by Homolka. They say if she does approach them, it would be at least five months before her application would come up for a hearing. Another important date for Homolka is july 6th, 1997, when she will have completed one third of her manslaughter sentence in the deaths of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy. Under the law she will be automatically eligible for full parole and an automatic parole board hearing at that time -- unless she waives her right to the hearing.
<hr>
<b>Simpson Tuesday</b><p>
The judge in OJ Simpson's civil trial is expected to dismiss a juror today for alleged misconduct. Meantime, Simpson will take the stand again. Yesterday, he denied owning Italian shoes like those he's shown wearing in a 1993 picture. 
<hr>
<b>Sands Blown</b><p>
Talk about going out with a bang. A Las Vegas landmark, the 44-year-old Sands Hotel was demolished this morning to make way for a two billion-dollar resort. This was the third major casino to be destroyed in the past four years. The Sands once showcased the world's leading entertainers.  It was the glamorous playground of top entertainers such as Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr., Joey Bishop and Peter Lawford, who collectively became known as the Rat Pack.
<hr>
<b>Candy Stamp</b><p>
Here's an update on a story we told you about yesterday.  John Candy's family says it's too soon to honor the comedian with a stamp.<br>   Lawyer Patrick Duco, who represents the family, says they were honored by the proposal from Canada Post but the family feels his children are still too young. Candy, a founding member of SCTV, was to be one of three Canadian-born Hollywood stars to be honored in a stamp series. But when news leaked, members of Candy's family told Canada Post they hadn't been consulted and wanted the stamp killed. The crown corporation has agreed. Candy, a native of Newmarket, Ontario, died of a heart attack March 4th, 1994. He was 43.








