<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 25, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>First Snow          
    <li>Grey Cup Winner
    <li>Foster Newser       
    <li>Bouchard Results    
    <li>Quebec - Terrorist    
    <li>Simpson Monday      
    <li>Apec Meeting        
    <li>Ethiopia Update     
    <li>Canadian Airlines   
    <li>Manpower Survey     
    <li>Candy Stamp         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>First Snow</b><p>
Old man winter has returned to the golden horseshoe early this year. It wasn't a blizzard but light snow began falling yesterday and didn't let up until the wee hours this morning. Accumulations of a couple of inches are fairly common, and the white stuff will stick around, with more on the way. Cold temperatures and flurries are on tap for most of the week. Salters and sanders were on the job keeping highways and main thorourfares clear, but many sidestreets are still snowcovered, or slushy. Driving conditions led to a number of accidents on area roads, although no serious injuries have been reported. While it was a gentle reminder winter is on the way, many Hamiltonians were caught off guard when they woke up this morning.
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup Winner</b><p>
Doug Flutie conquered blowing snow, swirling winds and the CFL's top defence to lead Toronto to an exciting 43-37 Grey Cup victory over Edmonton. Flutie was 22 of 35 for 302 yards. He also rushed for a game high 98 yards and a touchdown.  He was named top player of the game. Kicking was a decisive factor in the Argonauts' Grey Cup win over the Eskimos. The Argos' Mike Vanderjagt was five-for-five on field-goal attempts, while Edmonton's Sean Fleming went 0-for-3. Vanderjagt was picked top Canadian in the Grey Cup. 
<hr>
<b>Foster Newser</b><p>
A man cleared of being a savage sexual predator is accusing police of browbeating him into an early morning confession. 23 year-old Jeremy Foster, of Thornhill, says he got nothing to eat and was denied sleep after his arrest. He was taken in at 9 p-m on November 16th, and finally confessed the next morning at eight o'clock. He says he decided that was the only way he was going to get to see a lawyer. Foster was accused of two knifepoint sexual assaults and held in custody for almost a week until he was cleared by DNA tests.
<hr>
<b>Bouchard Results</b><p>
Quebec premier Lucien Bouchard walked out of a three-day policy convention with a mandate to give the Parti Quebecois a new look. After receiving a less than resounding leadership mandate, Bouchard insisted his party is going to change. Hardliners went to the meeting wanting a return to unilingual french commercial signs. But that motion was rejected, and Bouchard demanded a more tolerant approach would pave the way to a sovereigntist win in the next referendum.
<hr>
<b>Quebec - Terrorist</b><p>
 Meanwhile,  there are reports the Quebec government has a former FLQ terrorist in its midst. The Montreal Gazette reports Gaeten Desrosiers is an associate deputy minister in the department responsible for greater Montreal. In 1967, Desrosiers testified that a year earlier, he delivered the bomb to a shoe factory that killed a 64-year-old woman. The Gazette says two years ago, the Parti Quebecois put Desrosiers on a three-year contract -- at 91-thousand dollars a year.
<hr>
<b>Simpson Monday</b><p>
OJ Simpson returns to the stand today at his civil trial in Santa Monica, California. On Friday, he answered scores of questions about his fights with Nicole Simpson, and denied killing her and her friend. Today, plaintiff lawyer Daniel Petrocelli is expected to grill Simpson on what he was doing during and around the time of the murders. 
<hr>
<b>Apec Meeting</b><p>
It accounts for 40 per cent of global trade, and this morning, Apec leaders vowed to make the pacific rim region a giant free-trade zone. Prime minister Chretien sat down with 17 other world leaders in the Philippines for a pacific rim economic summit. Their communique promises the nations will take concrete steps toward transforming the region into the world's largest free-trade zone by the year 2020.
<hr>
<b>Ethiopia Update</b><p>
A section of the Ethiopian Airlines plane that crashed Saturday in the Indian Ocean was hauled onto the beach today. As the chunk of fuselage was brought ashore, bodies could be seen dangling from the seats they were strapped into. The hijacked plane ran out of fuel off the coast of East Africa and ditched into the sea. Only 52 of the 175 passengers and crew survived.
<hr>
<b>Canadian Airlines</b><p>
Transport minister David Anderson will head up restructuring talks today with Canadian Airlines in Richmond, B.C. Anderson has said Ottawa would consider helping the cash-strapped carrier if it reaches an agreement with its unions to save itself. The airline says it needs its 16-thousand employees to take a 10-per-cent wage cut to avoid bankruptcy.
<hr>
<b>Manpower Survey</b><p>
There may be some good news on the employment front in Canada. Manpower Temporary Services polled 16-hundred Canadian businesses on their hiring plans for the first three months of next year. Sixty-eight per cent expect to keep staff levels even, while 14 per cent plan to hire employees. However, another 14 per cent admit jobs will be cut.
<hr>
<b>Candy Stamp</b><p>
Johnny LaRue would be proud. Canada Post will deliver "Candy" next year. The late John Candy will be featured on a 1997 postage stamp honoring Canadian-born Hollywood stars. The Toronto-born actor-comedian died in March 1994 at the age of 43.








