<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 22, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Bus Vote            
    <li>Meningitis Shots    
    <li>Back to Basics      
    <li>Jobs Recut          
    <li>Boater Search       
    <li>Mahaffy Split      
    <li>Simpson 
    <li>Aussie Sentenced    
    <li>Yeltsin Out         
    <li>Teresa In           
    <li>JFK Film            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bus Vote</b><p>
The buses could be rolling in Hamilton in time for Grey Cup Sunday. The city's transit workers are voting on a tentative agreement today. More than 600 drivers, mechanics and inspectors have been on strike since last weekend, in a contract dispute that centres on job security. They've been without a contract since March.  A marathon bargaining session produced results yesterday with the announcement of the tentative pact. Aside from the out of towners looking for transit to the big game on Sunday, some 60 thousand daily users of public transit in the Hamilton region will be looking to board the buses that have been idled all week.
<hr>
<b>Meningitis Shots</b><p>
 Some 16 hundred Hamilton high school students will get the point today...not in classroom studies, but via the business end of a hypodermic needle. The St. Thomas More teenagers will be immunized against meningitis because regional health authorities now realize that two students who became ill earlier this month did indeed both have the same vaccine preventable strain of meningitis. Shots will also be given to children attending a day care centre attached to the school. Health officials say Grey Cup visitors have nothing to fear, because the general public is not at risk.
<hr>
<b>Back to Casics</b><p>
Ontario's education minister is promising to reform the province's elementary school system. And John Snobelen says the emphasis will be on the basics -- reading, writing, spelling, grammar, math, science, geography and Canadian history. The first phase of a new curriculum is to be implemented next September, with the rest brought in over the next five years. Provincewide testing is also on the way, as are standard report cards. Snobelen vows to improve the quality of education in Ontario and to make the system more accountable to parents.
<hr>
<b>Jobs Recut</b><p>
Meanwhile, many young people in school today are fearful about their futures. They wonder if there is a job for them waiting in the Canadian workforce. Schools are having to prepare your children for what lies ahead.
<hr>
<b>Boater Search</b><p>
A search resumed today for two boaters who were reported missing late Thursday after they set out on the Niagara River from Chippawa. Police said the 66-year-old man and 15-year-old boy had planned a short trip in a 4.5-metre aluminum boat. No names were released. A search late Thursday by volunteers from the Chippawa division of the Niagara Falls Fire Department failed to turn up any clues. The New York State Parks Police, U.S. Coast Guard, Niagara Region Police and a helicopter from CFB Trenton were also called in for the search.
<hr>
<b>Mahaffy Split</b><p>
The parents of one of Paul Bernardo's murder victims are separating, saying the strain of losing their daughter has been too much to handle.  Debbie Mahaffy says she and her husband Dan are ending their marriage after five years of trying to cope with the torture death of 14-year-old Leslie.  The Burlington girl and 15-year-old Kristen French were murdered by Bernardo and his ex-wife Karla Homolka.
<hr>
<b>Simpson </b><p>
OJ Simpson today will finally get to tell his story -- from the witness stand.  For the first time, Simpson will offer a Santa Monica jury his answers to such key questions as what was he doing during the June 1994 murders of his ex-wife and her friend, and how he cut his hands. 
<hr>
<b>Aussie Sentenced</b><p>
A judge in Australia handed down 35 life terms to a man who pleaded guilty to murdering 35 people last April. During his trial, 29-year-old Martin Bryant was described as sane, but with a severe personality disorder. The judge ordered that Bryant never be eligible for parole. The shooting rampage occurred at a tourist spot in Tasmania.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Out</b><p>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin has left a Moscow-area clinic to continue recovering in a government rest home. Wearing a fur hat and long dark coat, Yeltsin waved cheerfully as he took a limo ride to Barvikha Sanatorium. The 65-year-old leader is said to be making steady progress after his November 5th quintuple bypass. Doctors have warned him against taking things too fast.
<hr>
<b>Teresa In</b><p>
Mother Teresa is back in the hospital for an irregular heart beat. Doctors in Calcutta says she was admitted today with acute left-ventricular failure and is in stable condition. Her doctor says the 86-year old Nobel Peace Laureate is comfortable, conscious, and breathing on her own. Mother Teresa was in hospital twice earlier this year, for malaria, irregular heart beat and respiratory problems.
<hr>
<b>JFK Film</b><p>
A never-seen-before film of John Kennedy's last days 33 years ago is now public. It shows the former U.S. president and his wife being mobbed by Texas well-wishers the day before he was killed in Dallas. The film was filmed by a Kennedy aide. It shows the Kennedys driving down streets in an open convertible and people running up to shake hands and pat the president's back. The film runs out just moments before the 1963 shooting in Dallas. The pictures were released by the review board looking into Kennedy's assassination. One analyst says they are interesting for what they reveal about security at the time.








