<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 21, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Bus Deal            
    <li>Festival Closures   
    <li>403 Lane Closure    
    <li>Kenilworth Open     
    <li>Derry Death         
    <li>Bernardo Aid        
    <li>Glancaster - Booze  
    <li>Cops Cleared        
    <li>School Ruling       
    <li>Native Commish      
    <li>Tobacco Update      
    <li>Boxing Day          
    <li>Rent Control        
    <li>Rico Explosion      
    <li>Fire Update         
    <li>Chunnel Fire        
    <li>Britain Subway      
    <li>Math Update         
    <li>QM School          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bus Deal</b><p>
The slowdown in steeltown could be over before the Argos and the Esks take the field for the Grey Cup showdown.  After more than 16 hours of mediated talks at the Burlington Holiday Inn, a tentative contract was hammered out this morning between striking Hamilton Street Railway drivers and mechanics and the region. Talks continue to try to find a settlement for the hsr's inside workers who also are on strike. The five day old job action has shut down bus service for some 60 thousand regular public transit users in the Hamilton Wentworth region. Local 107 of the Amalgamated Transit Union will vote on the deal tomorrow, they could be back behind the wheel on Saturday.
<hr>
<b>Festival Closures</b><p>
And just a reminder that with all the Grey Cup festivities taking place in Hamilton,  a section of the downtown core has been shut down, right through the weekend.<br>  King Street is closed from James to Bay Streets for the Grey Cup festival. And it won't re-open until 3 o'clock Monday morning.<br>  McNab Street is also closed to accomodate another tent for the festival.
<hr>
<b>403 Lane Closure</b><p>
And Grey Cup organizers have a bone to pick with the Ministry of Transportation.<br> Anybody coming into Hamilton from out of town for any of the festivities will likely be treated to traffic backups due to lane restrictions on Highway 403 between the Highway 6 north cutoff and the Main Street East ramp. Transport ministry crews are busy putting up concrete barriers and high mast lighting, upgrading pavement, and repairing bridges and guard rails.<br> The bottleneck will be there until next summer, and Grey Cup officials are wondering out loud why a project this size couldn't have been postponed for a few days.
<hr>
<b>Kenilworth Open</b><p>
But there is some good news for motorists in Hamilton.  After being closed since last Tuesday, the down bound lanes of the Kenilworth Access were re-opened this morning.  The main mountain access in the city of Hamilton has been under construction after a retaining wall gave way.<br> The up bound lanes should be cleared for traffic later in the day.
<hr>
<b>Derry Death</b><p>
One person is dead after a car slid under a tractor-trailer and burst into flames outside of Milton.<br> The truck had been carrying a load of seat-belts to the Ford plant in Oakville when it collided with the car at Trafalgar and Derry Roads.<br> The resulting fire engulfed both vehicles.<br> The body of the car's driver was trapped inside the smoldering wreck. The victim's identity has not been released.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Aid</b><p>
Paul Bernardo has been told he can't get legal aid for his appeal.<br> But officials with Ontario's legal aid program won't say why his request was rejected.<br> Bernardo has been attempting to appeal his convictions for first-degree murder, sexual assault and other crimes in the deaths of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy. The legal aid money would have paid for Bernardo's lawyer and research for his case. Bernardo has now applied for an "inmate appeal," which doesn't require a lawyer and doesn't take place before a full court.
<hr>
<b>Glancaster - Booze</b><p>
A stolen tractor trailor loaded with rye whisky has been found, empty, in Mount Hope.<br> The rig had been reported stolen from Simcoe Tuesday night.<br> Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police found the trailor, abandoned on Airport Road.<br> Anyone with information on the stolen booze is asked to call Crime Stoppers.
<hr>
<b>Cops Cleared</b><p>
Niagara Regional Police officers have been cleared of any wrongdoing in the death of a man found hanging in his cell.<br> The special investigations unit has wrapped up its probe into the death of Donald Yacura.<br> He was arrested last March 27th, and had to be treated for a gash to his head after struggling with officers.<br> Yacura was placed in a holding cell in Grimsby, but later moved to a St. Catharines lockup.
<hr>
<b>School Ruling</b><p>
A group of religious minorities has lost a 10-year fight to receive provincial funding for their schools.<br> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled against them today.<br> The case was brought by the Ontario Alliance of Christian Schools, the Canadian Jewish Congress and a multi-faith coalition.<br> They had argued that freedom of religion includes the right of parents to educate their children according to their beliefs.
<hr>
<b>Native Commish</b><p>
The Royal Commission on Aboriginal Affairs says aboriginals need a new deal, including new lands and real self-government.<br> Otherwise, it warns native people might turn to violence.<br> The five-volume report, put together at a cost of 52-million dollars and two years past its deadline, warns aboriginals have made it clear they will no longer sit quietly by.<br> It says some leaders feel violence could come from ignoring long-held grievances.<br> The commission calls for an extra-two billion dollars to be added to the six billion spent annually by the federal and provincial governments to improve housing, health an employment.<br> The commission also calls for an aboriginal parliament.
<hr>
<b>Tobacco Update</b><p>
Federal health minister David Dingwall has changed his mind -- and won't table his anti-tobacco bill today.<br>   He says it still needs some work. There are suggestions dingwall was pressured by Quebec MP's who met with sports and cultural groups fearful of losing their tobacco company sponsorship.
<hr>
<b>Boxing Day</b><p>
The province has taken steps to legalize store openings the day after Christmas. A retailing association predicts most merchants are likely to take advantage of the new rule.<br> However, the province's top labor group condemns the move as another blow to working people under the Tory government.<br> The Ontario Federation of Labor, says if the government had its way, people would work on Christmas Day, too.<br> Under the proposed law, workers could refuse to work Boxing Day.
<hr>
<b>Rent Control</b><p>
The Ontario government tables its rent-control legislation today.<br> It will make it easier for landlords to raise rents that are below market value. Housing minister Al Leach says current rules have led to a near-freeze in rental-housing construction.<br> Critics complain the new rules will lead to dramatically higher rents.
<hr>
<b>Rico Explosion</b><p>
Turning to international news.  An explosion at a suburban shoe store in Puerto Rico killed at least 15 people and injured 50 today. Police said leaking natural gas may have been the cause. The early morning explosion destroyed much of a six-storey building housing the store, leaving a tangle of concrete and steel beams.<br> Firefighters searched through the rubble for other victims and police sealed off the site. Nearby buildings also were damaged.
<hr>
<b>Fire Update</b><p>
At least 39 people were killed and 80 injured in the worst fire to hit Hong Kong in almost four decades.<br> Most victims were found between the 13th and 15th floors of the 16-storey downtown high rise.<br> One firefighter died after falling into an elevator shaft.<br> The blaze burned for 21 hours before firefighters were able to bring it under control today.
<hr>
<b>Chunnel Fire</b><p>
The fire-damaged Channel Tunnel reopened for limited business after Monday's fire on a truck transporter train.<br> The folks who run the Chunnel have given the green light for six freight trains to traverse the tunnel every 90 minutes.<br> Passenger and shuttle trains carrying cars and their passengers might be rolling again before the end of the week.<br> There's no indication of when shuttle trains carrying cargo trucks might resume service.
<hr>
<b>Britain Subway</b><p>
London's Subway system was paralysed by a power failure for two-and-a-half hours.<br> Thousands of passengers were stranded in tunnels and stations last night.<br> Once power was restored just after midnight, trains pulled into the next station where passengers disembarked.<br> Most had to find their way home by other means because most public transit shuts down overnight.<br> Central London was packed with bewildered tourists and residents faced with long waits for buses and taxis.
<hr>
<b>Math Update</b><p>
Back home, education minister John Snobelen says math and science classes in Ontario are boring.<br> He says that's part of the reason why Ontario grade 7 and 8 students received average scores in an international study of math and science testing.<br> Alberta and B.C. scored much higher than Ontario in both categories.<br> Snobelen says Ontario students are "part of the Nintendo generation," and it's about time they were educated with the proper tools.
<hr>
<b>QM School</b><p>
It was a evening of celebration and dedication at Queen Mary School in Hamilton last night. With the cutting of the ribbon Queen Mary School was officially reopened.<br> The original school was built in 1913.<br> Two years ago the old school was demolished to make room for the new facility. Parents, staff and students packed the school's gymnasium last night for the ceremony that included elected and non elected school board officials.<br> Taking in the special event was 91-year-old Helen Mepham who attended Queen Mary School when it opened 83 years ago.<br> Helen Mepham's three great granddaughters are now students at Queen Mary School.








