<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 20, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Transit Recut       
    <li>Festival Closures   
    <li>Supercity Region    
    <li>Fire Master Plan    
    <li>Tobacco Tax         
    <li>Plane Collision     
    <li>Hong Kong Fire      
    <li>Yeltsin Pics        
    <li>Canada - Zaire        
    <li>Haiti - Canada        
    <li>Mini-Vans           
    <li>Pam Lee Divorce     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Transit Recut</b><p>
Public transit users in Hamilton Wentworth are sitting on pins and needles today. This as mediated talks go on in the four day old transit strike, which has crippled bus service in the region.  <br> 600 bus drivers, inspectors and mechanics with the Hamilton Street Railway walked off the job on the weekend. Union members rejected the company's final offer, which included a $1,000 signing bonus and a partial pension payment holiday. Job security remains the stumbling block. Both sides seem to agree that if those talks in Burlington today don't bring some quick results, this strike could be a long one. That has led to the suggestion that perhaps the HSR might be better off, in private hands. And some public transporation analysts say that is the way of the future in many communities.
<hr>
<b>Festival Closures</b><p>
And to add to the traffic problems in Hamilton, a section of the downtown core will be shut down, starting tomorrow for Grey Cup weekend.<br>  King Street will be closed from James to Bay Streets for the Grey Cup festival.<br>  The closure begins at 10 o'clock tomorrow morning, and continues until 3 o'clock Monday morning.<br>  McNab Street will also be closed to accomodate another tent for the festival.
<hr>
<b>Supercity Region</b><p>
There's a chance the citizens of Hamilton Wentworth might be given a say in the supercity deal amalgamating Hamilton and the five outlying communites. Last night Hamilton Wentworth Regional council agreed to debate the merits of holding a region wide referendum. That discussion will take place in two weeks. Flamborough and Dundas oppose the supercity concept. The mayor of Flamborough senses support for the deal is falling apart.
<hr>
<b>Fire Master Plan</b><p>
Hamilton firefighters are concerned that further funding cuts could put city residents at risk.<br>  Mike Murphy reports the firefighters are warning that some money could be saved...but at the cost of lives.
<i><br>  So many firefighters turned out to sound the alarm over potential budget cuts ...they had to find a bigger room.<br>  Then...the firefighters warned a committee of Hamilton council that major cuts in service and manpower could be disastrous.<br>  Their concerns surround Hamilton's master fire plan.<br>  A plan that lays out potential scenerios which could see up to 60 of 440 firefighters lose their jobs..and budget cuts of up to 3 million dollars<br>  Already the city has downsized the fire department. There are fewer vehicles on the road.<br>  And fewer firefighters to pull trapped motorists out of cars.<br>  This alderman says he'll fight any further cuts.<br>  The new fire master plan will be hotly debated when it comes back to the politicians for action early next month<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Tobacco Tax</b><p>
It's going to cost more to buy a pack of cigarettes. CTV News reports the federal government will unveil legislation tomorrow that would boost federal tobacco taxes by 60 cents a carton. And it says five provinces -- Ontario, Quebec and the maritimes -- are prepared to follow suit. That would raise the cost by 15 cents a pack in those provinces, and seven-and-a-half cents everywhere else. Meanwhile, smoking in a home with young children has been equated to child abuse. An Ontario Medical Association report suggests the government should consider banning tobacco use in homes where pregnant women or young children are present.
<hr>
<b>Plane Collision</b><p>
Turning to international news, investigators are studying a fiery runway collision in Illinois that killed all 14 people aboard the two planes involved. The crash occurred when a United Express commuter flight landing at the airport struck a smaller plane that was taking off. The commuter flight was carrying two crew and 10 passengers, and the smaller plane had two people on board.
<hr>
<b>Hong Kong Fire</b><p>
Scores of people were injured when fire broke out in a building in a densely-populated district of Hong Kong today. Ambulances took 68 people to hospital after the blaze broke out in a 16-storey commercial and office building. Flames erupted in the lower floors but spread quickly via the elevator shaft to sweep through to the top three floors. There's no word on fatalities but people were seen clinging to windows and then falling. Helicopters were called in to pluck a number of fire victims from the upper floors and roof of the flame ravaged structure.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Pics</b><p>
Russian state television broadcast the first images of president Boris Yeltsin today, since his heart operation earlier this month. Yeltsin was shown smiling and walking alongside his wife, Naina, daughter Tatyana and granddaughter, Masha, in the Kremlin central hospital garden, where he is recovering from his multiple heart-bypass operation on November 5.  Yeltsin could be transferred on Thursday or Friday to his official rest home just west of Moscow. Since Mr. Yeltsin's quintuple heart-bypass operation the Kremlin has stressed that the Russian leader is recovering better than expected. However his address to the nation that was to have made last Friday was postponed.
<hr>
<b>Canada - Zaire</b><p>
Rwanda says foreign soldiers are not wanted or needed in central Africa. That is putting the future of any Canadian-led international mission in doubt. Countries involved in the rescue effort will hold several meetings this week to debate whether to send over a military force. Aid agencies insist the mission should go ahead. They say that while one-half-million refugees have returned home to Rwanda, there are still one-half-million more in Zaire in need of help. An advance team of Canadian soldiers remains in Uganda, with nothing to do as they await the results of the diplomatic meetings.
<hr>
<b>Haiti - Canada</b><p>
Canada will likely stay in Haiti longer than planned -- again. For the second time, Canada is expected to extend its peacekeeping and training mission beyond November 30th. Haiti's president hopes the U.N. will stay through July. Canada has 700 soldiers and 100 mounties in Haiti helping to reform its legislative and justice systems.
<hr>
<b>Mini - Vans</b><p>
If you're considering buying a minivan you might want to consider this information.  The Ford Windstar minivan outperformed eight competitors in protecting occupants in crash tests. The tests were done by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety in the U.S.  The poorest performer was the Pontiac Trans Sport, with its massive collapse of the passenger compartment. The Institute says minivans generally have good on-the-road crash experience, being large and usually driven by low-risk drivers.
<hr>
<b>Pam Lee Divorce</b><p>
It's splitsville for B.C. native Pamela Anderson Lee and Tommy Lee. The "Baywatch" star filed for divorce from her rocker husband yesterday in Los Angeles, citing irreconcilable differences. The Lees, who have each others' names tattooed on their ring fingers, married 21 months ago after a four-day courtship.  They have a five-month-old son.  Tommy Lee was previously married to actress Heather Locklear. 








