<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 19, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Transit Tuesday     
    <li>Leach re: Supercity 
    <li>Dundas Says No      
    <li>P.E.I. Elex         
    <li>Inflation Rate      
    <li>Bankruptcies        
    <li>Help Wanted         
    <li>Weeping Icon        
    <li>Video Gambling      
    <li>Chunnel Fire        
    <li>U.S. Zaire          
    <li>Ghali Vote          
    <li>Pope Castro         
    <li>Israel Beating      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Transit Tuesday</b><p>
An attempt to kick-start stalled talks between transit workers and Hamilton Wentworth regional officials is underway.   It's day three of the transit strike with time ticking away before thousands of people pour into steeltown for the Grey Cup. More than 600 bus drivers, inspectors and mechanics with the Hamilton Street Railway walked off the job on the weekend. Union members voted yesterday against accepting the company's final offer, which included a $1,000 signing bonus and a partial pension payment holiday. Job security remains the stumbling block. Meanwhile, the Hamilton Grey Cup Committee is doing some damage control. With the championship Canadian Football League game set for Sunday, the committee is stressing that it's business as usual and has arranged for five park-and-ride locations throughout the city. A private company will provide the service and the union has agreed not to disrupt it.
<hr>
<b>Leach re: Supercity</b><p>
Look out Ontario ... the supercity is likely the way of the future ... Hamilton- Wentworth Region's proposal for becoming a supercity was given thumbs up by the provincial government yesterday.<br> Municipal affairs minister Al Leach has announced his endorsesment of the plan which was brokered through provincial mediator Gardner Church. He also wants all councils involved to complete deliberations on the plan quickly so that the new structure can be in place for the 1997 elections.
<hr>
<b>Dundas Says No</b><p>
But instead of moving towards unanimity, the town of Dundas is actively working to ensure it's not part of a supercity in Hamilton Wentworth. An ad campaign will help spread the anti-super city message and a call for a referendum is likely to be presented to regional council tonight. As Ian Dovey reports last night Dundas council voted unamimously against the mega municipal concept and to advise the province of its desire to remain an independent town.                                     
<I><br>  It's not the first time Dundas has threatened to withdraw from the region,  as this copy of an 1859 separation bylaw infront of Dundas Town Hall states. <br>There wasn't much to discuss, the vote was unamimous Dundas wants to remain distinct and independent from any unified municipal structure. <br>    Mayor Addison has been a strong critic to the process that lead to unified government concept for Hamilton Wentworth telling his council and the public it the least democratic he's ever witnessed.<br>   The mayor had no problems gaining councils support to go it alone. <br>   Addison says he'll now try to persuade the other outlying councils to do the same. <br>    </I>
<hr>
<b>P.E.I. elex</b><p>
While Dundas was saying no to amalgation, Prince Edward Island voters were rejecting their government. There's no such thing as "Milligan's Island" anymore. PEI premier Keith Milligan and his Liberals have been swept from power. Pat Binns' Tories won yesterday's election, taking 18 of 27 seats for a majority government.
<hr>
<b>Inflation Rate</b><p>
Higher energy and food prices pushed last month's inflation rate to its highest level since November 1995.<br>   Statistics Canada says year-over-year inflation climbed to 1.8 per cent, up from the 1.5 per cent rate for September.<br>   Costs were also higher for new vehicles, post-secondary education and telephone service. But homeowners spent considerably less on mortgage interest rates.
<hr>
<b>Bankruptcies</b><p>
More disturbing economic news. Bankruptcies among consumers and businesses continued at record pace in September. There were 69-thousand failures in the first nine months of the year, up more than 20 per cent from the previous high of 57-thousand in the same period of 1995. Ontario and Quebec consumers were hard hit in September, each with 26-hundred failures.
<hr>
<b>Help Wanted</b><p>
It wasn't supposed to be this way. The economy is growing but more Canadians are either out of work or worried about keeping the job they now have. Many Canadians are wondering where have all the jobs gone?
<hr>
<b>Weeping Icon</b><p>
The jury is still out on whether it's a miracle, but Toronto police say there's no evidence of fraud in claims of a weeping icon in a tiny church.<br> Detective Arthur Locker says there's no proof of any financial gain by those involved with a Greek orthodox church in suburban East York.<br> The icon, a copy of a 12 hundred-year-old painting of the Virgin Mary, allegedly began weeping last August.<br> Large amounts of cash were donated when reports of the icon became public.<br> Fears were raised when it was discovered that the church pastor was excommunicated for once working in a brothel.
<hr>
<b>Video Gambling</b><p>
Ontario has become the ninth province to legalize video lottery gambling. The Conservative government passed legislation yesterday to allow 20-thousand machines at racetracks and permanent charity casino sites, on a trial basis. The government, which says it is devoted to curbing profiteering from illegal gambling devices, is expected to rake in between 300- to 400-million dollars a year.
<hr>
<b>Chunnel Fire</b><p>
Turning to international news.  A fire deep inside the tunnel that runs beneath the English Channel has left 34 people injured, most with smoke inhalation. The blaze broke out last night onboard a truck being hauled on a freight shuttle using the tunnel, better known as the Chunnel. The fire scene was about 20 kilometres from the French end of the 51-kilometre-long tunnel. The tunnel has been shut down because of the fire and it is not known when it will re-open.
<hr>
<b>U.S. Zaire</b><p>
The future of the Canadian led aid mission to Zaire remains in doubt. This after the Clinton administration announced plans to scale back its plans to send a large military force to Central Africa. American officials say the administration is still considering whether to send a smaller contingent of troops to aid relief efforts along the border of Zaire and Rwanda. Military planners and diplomats from more than one-dozen nations, including Canada, will meet Thursday in Stuttgart, Germany to discuss their options.
<hr>
<b>Ghali Vote</b><p>
The United Nations says the United States has vetoed a second term for Boutros Boutros-Ghali as U.N. secretary general. All 14 other security council members voted for a resolution recommending the 74-year-old Egyptian diplomat for election by the general assembly. The veto may open the way for other candidates to enter the race for a five-year term as secretary-general beginning January 1, 1997.
<hr>
<b>Pope Castro</b><p>
Pope John Paul has accepted Fidel Castro's invitation to visit Cuba. The two met at the Vatican this morning. It was the first encounter between the two men. Before the meeting, the Cuban leader said he was bringing the Pope a message of friendship. Cuba is the only Latin American country the Pope has not visited. A date for the papal visit has not been set.
<hr>
<b>Israel Beating</b><p>
Israel's border police arrested two officers after they were caught on video beating and kicking a group of Palestinians. The video shows the troops apparently unaware of an amateur Palestinian cameraman nearby as they attacked the six arab men. One officer kicked a man in the head and the footage also shows the Israelis apparently forcing the Palestinians to do push-ups. a passerby who stops to ask questions is smacked in the face.








<P>
