<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 18, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>HSR Strike 
    <li>Snowstorm           
    <li>Zaire Update        
    <li>Mars Probe Crash    
    <li>Russian Explosion   
    <li>Children Shot       
    <li>Vanderkley Sentenced
    <li>Memory Drug         
    <li>Christmas Shopping  
    <li>Christmas Dolls     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>HSR Strike </b><p>
Thousands of people who depend on public transit in Hamilton Wentworth were left to their own devices this morning, as the work week began with no bus service.  <br> The 525 member workforce walked off the job on the weekend... and no new talks to settle the dispute have been scheduled.    As Dwight Ryan reports, regional counsellors and striking workers are both being briefed at this hour on why the strike began.  
<i><br>  The sixty thousand people who rely on public transit in Hamilton were on their own as the work weeek began.<br>  Negotiations between the Amalgamated Transit Workers Union and the HSR's 525 drivers broke off in the early hours of Sunday morning.<br>  Regional chairman Terry Cooke says they were close to an agreement.  <br>    Cooke is now briefing all regional counsellors on the strike, the first in Hamilton since 1982.<br>  A news conference is scheduled to follow.   <br>      Striking HSR wokers in the meantime are at this hour being briefed by the union leadership.<br>  As the strike moves through its second full day, no new talks are scheduled.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Snowstorm</b><p>
At least the weather is fine for walking to work today in Southern Ontario. Pity those who have to travel the Trans-Canada Highway between Kenora and Winnipeg.<br> An intense storm battering the American midwest right up to northwestern Ontario has brought heavy snow and freezing rain to the area. In Kenora, OPP Constable Rob Kobayashi says the amount of snow took them by surprise with more than 70 centimetres falling in the past 24 hours. The Trans-Canada was closed this morning, it should be reopened shortly. No flights are going in or out of Winnipeg's airport and city streets there are clogged with stuck cars. As many as three people died from shovelling snow in Winnipeg.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Update</b><p>
The homecoming of hundreds of thousands of Rwandan refugees from Zaire is prompting a rethinking of an international relief mission. Commander Lieutenant-General Maurice Baril thinks the mission should proceed for the sake of the refugees still in Zaire. He has invited all participating military leaders to meet in Germany later this week to discuss how to proceed with the multinational effort. Baril left Ottawa for Africa last night.
<hr>
<b>Mars Probe Crash</b><p>
They're breathing a sigh of relief down under. Fears that Russia's failed Mars space probe would crash in Australia evaporated last night when pieces of the spacecraft fell into the southern Pacific Ocean west of Chile.  Officials had been concerned about possible nuclear contamination.
<hr>
<b>Russian Explosion</b><p>
The death toll from a weekend explosion at a military block of flats in Russia's southern Dagestan region has risen to more than 40. Officials expect the toll to surpass 50. Eight people are in hospital and about a dozen others are still missing and feared buried in the rubble. Rescuers believe there is a chance of finding some of them alive. The Itar-Tass news agency says the blast might have been gangland revenge over a crackdown on arms and smuggling.
<hr>
<b>Children Shot</b><p>
Police in Laurens, South Carolina are looking for a man after his wife found their four children shot to death in their beds. The victims are a 16-year-old girl and her three brothers, ages 10, 13 and 14 -- and they may have been dead several days. Reports say the mother, Bertha Satterwhite, left the home earlier in the week because of marital problems.
<hr>
<b>Vanderkley Sentenced</b><p>
A Niagara Falls man has been sentenced to three months in jail after killing a police officer in a hit and run mishap last April. This morning 68 year old Frank Vanderkley was sentenced in a St. Catharines Court, and also ordered not to drive for another year and half. Vanderkley struck and killed veteran OPP officer Mike Goula, who was helping another officer with a traffic accident when he was struck by the side of the road in Niagara Falls.
<hr>
<b>Memory Drug</b><p>
There's a new drug that has been shown to restore memory in healthy older men.  American scientists are hoping the drug can do the same for people with alzheimer's. They plan to begin testing it on alzheimer's patients next year.
<hr>
<b>Christmas Shopping</b><p>
And just in case you forgot, there is just over a month until Christmas. And the Retail Council of Canada is expecting a good holiday season. Council vice-president Jill Birch says a survey of store owners suggests they expect sales this year to be better than last year.  Most major stores are decorated for the season and the holiday buying binge has begun.
<hr>
<b>Christmas Dolls</b><p>
Have any of your christmas shopping done yet?<br>  Well often it's not a store-bought gift that's the best idea, but one hand-made with love.<br>  Annette Hamm tells us the story of an elderly Stoney Creek woman who's been busy all year getting ready to spread a few smiles this Christmas.
<i> <br>  The sewing machine is rarely idle at Bea McPherson's Stoney Creek apartment.<br>  88 year old McPherson spends most of the year working her magic for this time of year.<br>  Ahe's putting the finishing touches on a spare bedroom full of dolls hoping for new homes this Christmas.<br>  Bea estimates she's refurbished thousands of second hand dolls since 1941, when her husband asked her to send some Canadian dolls overseas.<br>  Now she does donates her dolls to local charities.  <br>  Picking up remnants throughout the year, with the help of her friend Kathleen Cortolucci, Bea fixes up one doll at a time.   <br>  Each one is given special attention in the hopes it will become someones special doll.  <br>  Bea McPherson's dolls will be available at the Christmas Bazaar at Stoney Creek United Church this Saturday.<br>  </i>








<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

