<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 15, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>HSR Strike          
    <li>Crowd Control       
    <li>Retaining Wall Down 
    <li>Postal Problems     
    <li>Days of Action      
    <li>Serial Rapist       
    <li>Bernardo Cell       
    <li>Meningococcal       
    <li>Smoking Rates Up    
    <li>Zaire Update        
    <li>Linehan             
</ul>
<hr>
<b>HSR Strike</b><p>
If you use public transit in Hamilton, you might want to start looking for another way to get around town.  A provincial mediator has called Hamilton Street Railway bosses and the drivers' union back to the bargaining table today for a last ditch effort at averting a region wide transit strike. Contract talks broke off Wednesday night with bus drivers and maintenance workers poised to pick up the picket signs. Shutting down the busses in Hamilton Wentworth could create havoc for Grey Cup organizers, school boards and businesses. Education officials are already scrambling to come up with contingency plans for thousands of students who use public transit to get to classes. HSR drivers last hit the bricks in June of 1982, staying off the job for 92 days.
<hr>
<b>Crowd Control</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police also gearing up for Grey Cup.<br>  Fearing, but not expecting the worse, a special crowd management squad of 40 officers has been preparing for the game and its festivities since January.<br>  Annette Hamm reports.
<i> <br>  The 93 riot in Montreal after the Canadiens won the Stanley Cup.<br>  It's exactly the kind of situation police don't want to see happen in Hamilton Grey Cup weekend.<br>  And this is their insurance.  <br>  Since January, forty officers have been practicing hard tactical manoueuvres, preparing for the very worst Grey Cup weekend may have to offer.  <br>  Police don't know exactly what size crowd they'll be dealing with, but insist they won't be on hand to intimidate them.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Retaining Wall Down</b><p>
Fears for public safety on a Hamilton mountain access now seem well founded.<br>  By this morning, a retaining wall on the Kenilworth access was leaning at a 45 degree angle.<br>  Officials shut down the access Tuesday night after they noticed a buckle in the wall.<br>  A Hamilton firm has started demolishing the wall.<br>  Once it's down, engineers will examine the foundation to find out why the wall failed.<br>  The access is expected to be reopened next Thursday.
<hr>
<b>Postal Problems</b><p>
We could see some mail disruptions early next month. The Canadian Union of Postal Workers is planning a day of protest, to show their anger over Canada Post's withdrawal from the junk mail business. CUPW president Darrell Tingley says Ottawa's order to stop door-to-door flyer delivery will mean the firing of 10-thousand workers.
<hr>
<b>Days of Action</b><p>
Sudbury will be the next target of Labor's Days of Protest. That word comes from CUPE Ontario leader, Sid Ryan. Yesterday Ryan also said North Bay, the riding of Premier Mike Harris, should also be hit before next summer. Union leaders and social activists will meet in Toronto on November 26th. They will discuss future protest plans and ryan says he'll push for Sudbury to be hit as early as February. He also said Thunder Bay and Windsor should also be targets.
<hr>
<b>Serial Rapist</b><p>
Toronto-area police are on the hunt for a savage rapist who struck for a fourth time yesterday. But the latest victim, in her 20's, managed to fend off her attacker by fighting back in the Dufferin-Steeles area. Police say the woman was spun around and thrown to the ground, but was not sexually assaulted. The attack occurred near the scene of the first assault on Sunday. Police say yesterday's victim was threatened with a knife and that the suspect's description matches the rapist sought in the other attacks. All of the attacks occurred within the past five days within an eight kilometre radius.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Cell</b><p>
Officials at Kingston Penitentiary have removed the plexiglass shield around the door of Paul Bernardo's jail cell. The shield was installed after inmates pelted the convicted Ontario sex killer with human waste. But prison officials have taken it down so Bernardo can benefit from heating and ventilation during the winter. Plexiglass will remain around his sleeping area.
<hr>
<b>Meningococcal</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth health officials are keeping a close watch on the student population of a city high school. Authorities are investigating the occurence of meningococcal disease among grade 11 students at St. Thomas Moore High School. A teenaged girl was admitted to St. Joseph's Hospital earlier this week and a male student, suspected of having the disease was admitted to McMaster Medical Centre on Wednesday. There is no apparent link between the two but those in close contact with the two teens are being treated with medication and area health care professionals are on notice. Meningococcal disease is a serious but rare infection which occurs in the blood or lining of the brain.
<hr>
<b>Smoking Rates Up</b><p>
Ontario's chief medical officer says smoking is making a come back -- and it's causing a health "crisis." Dr. Richard Schabas  says governments must take tough action to butt out the crisis, especially among teens.  
<hr>
<b>Zaire Update</b><p>
Tens of thousands of Rwandan refugees are trekking through the eastern Zaire town of Goma towards Rwanda today. There are possibly 100-thousand of them, and they may be headed for home. The exodus from two sprawling camps at Mugunga follows heavy fighting between Zairian rebels and Hutu fighters who had controlled the camps. The retreat of the Hutu fighters allowed the refugees to leave the camps. This could be good news for the planned international relief mission, as it could reduce the risk of military intervention. Meanwhile, the U.N. Security Council meets today to decide whether to authorize a multinational relief mission to help refugees in Zaire. The Canadian-led effort could involve 20-thousand troops from more than one-dozen countries, although the length of its mandate is still up for debate. Defence minister Doug Young says the bill for a six-month mission could hit 100-million dollars -- about one-tenth of his department's budget.
<hr>
<b>Linehan</b><p>
The lives of showbusiness celebrities are an open book, and it seems public interest is focused more on inner secrets rather than their outer image.<br> Brian Linehan has built a career meeting with screen names and emphasizing their positive strengths.<br> Alex Reynolds interviews the man who talks to the stars.
<i> <br>  The Hamilton native combines a photographic memory with meticulous preparation... movie names responding with amazement to little known facts Linehan reveals during sessions.<br>  But it isn't always easy. <br>  Linehan will be back on the home screen with a weekly series beginning in January.<br>  A kick-off special is set for Saturday night on chch-tv.<br>  </i>








<P>
