<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 14, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Fire Kills Kids     
    <li>Children Report     
    <li>Parents Kill        
    <li>Villa Inquest       
    <li>Quebec Judge        
    <li>Docs Dicipline      
    <li>Heart Drug          
    <li>Zaire Troops        
    <li>Haiti Canada        
    <li>St. Pete's Riot     
    <li>India Update        
    <li>Emergency Landing   
    <li>Church Speaks       
    <li>Gallery of Dist.    
    <li>Jackson Marries     
    <li>Monkees Reunite     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Fire Kills Kids</b><p>
The Ontario Fire Marshall continues to look for answers in a Brantford fire that killed two toddlers.   <br> The bodies of three-year-old Samantha Dixon and her two-year-old sister Natalie were found huddled under a bed in an upstairs bedroom yesterday. They were trapped by flames that engulfed their home. Police say the girls' mother noticed smoke in the house and managed to escape next door with her nine-month-old daughter copelyn. But Muriel Dixon was overcome by smoke and flames when she tried to rescue her other daughters.
<hr>
<b>Children Report</b><p>
The Canadian Council on Social Development warns that poverty threatens the health of more than one-million children. And there are dire warnings that the problem will worsen as governments cut funding for social programs.
<hr>
<b>Parents Kill</b><p>
Neighbors said he was a model father. Every morning, Bernard Halpin would help Andrea, his 35-year-old mentally handicapped daughter, into his car and buy her breakfast at a McDonald's Restaurant.<br> But that routine was shattered yesterday when the 75 year old retiree shot Andrea and then took his own life.<br> It's the second such shocking incident in Montreal in two weeks. Last week six-year-old Charles Antoine Blais, an autistic child was drowned in a bathtub. The boy's mother has been charged with first-degree murder.
<hr>
<b>Villa Inquest</b><p>
A former nurse says staff at a Hamilton retirement home created an atmosphere of fear.<br> A coroner's jury was read a letter written by the home's former nursing director in which she describes a long list of alleged abuse and "substandard" care.<br> Helen Demchuk's letter led to the inquest into five of 42 deaths at St. Elizabeth Villa from January 1994 to April of 1995.<br> She wrote it in October 1994 after being fired.<br> Among other things, it accuses staff of sedating new residents and placing others in restraints.<br> It also says residents were abused to the point that one suffered a broken elbow and another received cuts and bruises on his head. The inquest continues today.
<hr>
<b>Quebec Judge</b><p>
A newly-named Quebec judge and former FLQ sympathizer says he's stepping down from the bench temporarily.<br> Richard Therrien was convicted 25 years ago of hiding terrorists involved in the kidnapping and murder of Quebec labor minister Pierre Laporte.<br> Quebec Liberals say Quebec justice minister Paul Bezin should resign for allowing therrien's appointment. But Bezin insists he only learned of it last week, and has complained to the province's Judicial Council and Bar Association.
<hr>
<b>Docs Dicipline</b><p>
The Harris government has failed to stop a protest by Ontario's doctors.<br> The governing body for the doctors has turned down a request by the health minister to discipline physicians who refuse to treat new patients.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Heart Drug</b><p>
Doctors may soon be prescribing something other than an aspirin a day for heart and stroke patients. A Canadian team headed by researchers at Hamilton Civic Hospitals, tested the new blood thinner -- called Clopidogrel, it reduces the risk of new heart attacks and strokes by one-third, compared with one-quarter for aspirin with milder side effects.  One drawback though -- it'll cost more than aspirin.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Troops</b><p>
Canada sends its first group of soldiers to Zaire today, to lay the groundwork for saving one-million starving refugees.<br> More than two dozen countries have pledged their support and troops for a Canadian-led humanitarian mission.<br> The remainder of Canada's 15-hundred-troop commitment, and those from other countries, won't deploy until after the U.N. security council sanctions the mission.<br> Meanwhile, an American army medical, engineering and security team has arrived and is already in the Rwandan capital, Kigali to assess the situation for a possible large-scale deployment of American personnel.<br> The team, lead by Major General Edward P. Smith, will be based at the U.S. embassy in Kigali and will carry out assessments for material and personnel to open a humanitarian corridor to aid the hundreds of thousands of refugees that have fled recent fighting.
<hr>
<b>Haiti Canada</b><p>
Haiti is asking the U.N. to extend its peacekeeping mission through July.<br> President Rene Preval says Haiti's new police force needs more training, and says it can't be done by November 30th.<br> Twelve-hundred U.N. troops and 300 U.N. civilian police -- mostly Canadian soldiers and mounties -- are in Haiti.<br> The mission has already been extended once.
<hr>
<b>St. Pete's Riot</b><p>
Police in St. Petersburg, Florida say the streets are quiet now. But last night violence erupted after a grand jury cleared a white police officer in a fatal shooting of a black motorist that led to rioting last month.  Two officers received minor gunshot wounds and seven other people were hurt in the unrest overnight.
<hr>
<b>India Update</b><p>
Speculation on the cause of a mid-air disaster that killed 349 people in India is focusing on pilot error.<br> India has launched an official inquiry into yesterday's crash in which a Saudi jumbo jet was smashed by a Kazak cargo plane.<br> Controllers had warned the pilots shortly before the crash to watch out for the other plane.<br> Authorities say the windshield of the Kazakh plane was largely intact, indicating it was not a head-on crash.
<hr>
<b>Emergency Landing</b><p>
It was nail bitting time for eleven passengers on board a U.S. Air flight from Pittsburgh to Hamilton last night.<br> Just before eleven last night the pilot radioed the tower saying he had a problem with his landing gear.<br> The twin engine prop circled the airport several times so that emergency crews to get into position.<br> The aircraft landed safely with all three landing gear down. There were no injuries.
<hr>
<b>Church Speaks</b><p>
The man who brokered a deal to turn Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities into one supercity, insists he has no idea what the province intends to do with it.<br>  Gardner Church spoke this morning to a joint breakfast meeting of the Hamilton and District Chamber of Commerce, and the Hamilton Construction Association.<br>  Earlier this week, Church suggested the supercity deal will go ahead, with or without local council approval.<br>  Today, he stressed his job as mediator has ended, and it's now up to the province to decide how to proceed.
<hr>
<b>Gallery of Dist.</b><p>
Hamilton took time last night to honour some of the people who have made significant lifelong contributions to the steel city.<br> In this, Hamilton's Sesquicentennial year, seven names were added to the Gallery of Distinction.<br> Included in this year's list were former Tigercat owner David Braley, former McMaster University president, Alvin Lee, Firan Corporation founder, Morgan Firestone, businessman Chester Waxman, and Grey Cup 96 co-chair, Marnie Paikin. The gallery posthumously honoured painter Frank Panabaker, and the reverend John Bonomi.
<hr>
<b>Jackson Marries</b><p>
Entertainer Michael Jackson has married again. A news release from his production company, MJJ Productions, says Jackson married Debbie Rowe, the woman carrying his child, in Sydney, Australia this morning. Jackson has known Rowe for 15 years. She works for the doctor who treated him for his skin condition, vitiligo. Rowe is reported to be due to give birth to Jackson's baby in February.
<hr>
<b>Monkees Reunite</b><p>
You're going to be seeing a lot of the Monkees lately -- all four of them. Their new album, "Justus," is about to be released and marks the return of Mike Nesmith. They'll also play together live for the first time in years at a record release party in West Hollywood, California, next Wednesday. They're also celebrating their 30th anniversary, and the Disney Channel will air a Monkees special in January. And, the Monkees could be hitting the big screen again soon. Their publicist confirms that a film deal is in the works.









<P>
