<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 13, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Blaze Recut         
    <li>Thorold Fire        
    <li>QEW Crash           
    <li>Kenilworth Access   
    <li>Doc Decision        
    <li>TTC Sues            
    <li>Supercity - Council   
    <li>India Crash         
    <li>Mexico Explosion    
    <li>Zaire Relief        
    <li>Immigration         
    <li>Peru Quake          
    <li>Who Does What       
    <li>Villa Inquest       
    <li>White Rose Robbery  
    <li>Drug Sting          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Blaze Recut</b><p>
A house fire in Dundas last evening has claimed the life of a woman.   46 year old Debbie Trafford was pulled from the top floor of a Govenor's Road house soon after firefighters arrived. It is the second fire related death in the valley town in two years, and firefighters are still trying to determine a cause.
<hr>
<b>Thorold Fire</b><p>
 A 72-year-old Thorold woman has succumb to her wounds after being rescued from a house fire. The woman was taken by air ambulance to hospital in Hamilton last night with serious burns to 90 per cent of her body. The fire was contained to a washroom on the lower level of the Cowan Drive home. The cause remains under investigation.
<hr>
<b>QEW Crash</b><p>
Traffic was snarled on the Queen Elizabeth Way at Grimsby for all of the morning commuter rush. A tractor trailer jack-knifed in the Hamilton-bound lanes at Casablanca Boulevard.<br> The westbound lanes were closed and eastbound traffic was reduced to one lane. Despite the rush hour traffic headaches, there were no serious injuries as a result.
<hr>
<b>Kenilworth Access</b><p>
And while one road worry cleared up this morning on the QEW, Hamilton drivers face a week-long hassle on a key mountain access.<br> Last night, the partial collapse of a primary retaining wall forced the closure of the Kenilworth Access.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  This morning, this was about the only traffic moving on Hamilton's Kenilworth Access.<br>  Last night, road crews decided to shut down the mountain access after finding a large buckle in a retaining wall.<br>  Because of the danger of the wall falling down, councillor Terry Anderson, who chairs Hamilton Wentworth's Transportation Services Committee, expects it could be some time before the access reopens.  <br>  The closure created a few traffic tieups at the bottom of the access this morning, mainly by drivers who didn't realize they could get up or down the mountain this way.<br>  Danny Schebesch is a engineering consultant who worked on repairing the neighbouring Sherman Cut back in the 1980's.<br>  He expects similiar remedial action will be needed here.  <br>  It's believed a slow leak from a 40 year old water system on top of the mountain may have caused the crack.<br>  City officials are meeting all day to figure out the best way to repair it.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Doc Decision</b><p>
The College of Physicians and Surgeons decides today on a government request to punish doctors who refuse new patients. Health minister Jim Wilson wants the college to amend its regulations to expand the definition of professional misconduct. If Wilson has his way, even doctors who simply urge others to boycott new patients could be punished. The push to penalize doctors has outraged many physicians involved in the anti-government protest.
<hr>
<b>TTC Sues</b><p>
The Toronto Transit Commission is suing labor leader Sid Ryan for the 1.7-million dollars it lost on the Toronto Days of Action protest last month. The TTC cites the CUPE boss and two other labor organizers in the suit. Ryan calls the lawsuit a joke. He says the real villain is premier Mike Harris, whose cuts have taken millions of dollars out of the transportation system.
<hr>
<b>Supercity - Council</b><p>
 Fireworks in Hamilton last night as some city councillors accused the mayor of trying to pull an end run around council, in the supercity debate: they were angry that a caucus of five council members signed a deal with other Hamilton Wentworth municipalities to drop the region and form a supercity, in closed talks last week.  When the smoke cleared; councillors agreed to put the supercity memorandum of agreement on the next regular council agenda November 26th, for a full debate.
<hr>
<b>India Crash</b><p>
Turning to international news.  The black box flight recorders have been recovered from both planes involved in a fiery crash over India. A Saudi Airways jumbo jet had just left New Delhi when it collided with a Russian-built cargo plane coming in for landing. The crash scattered wreckage and the bodies of about 350 people over a wide area of farmland. No word on the cause of the crash.
<hr>
<b>Mexico Explosion</b><p>
Two people have died of burns suffered in an inferno that has raged for more than three days just outside Mexico City. At least 13 other people were hurt, several critically, in Monday's explosion and fire at a fuel depot. Towering columns of flame continue to light up Mexico City's skyline as thick black smoke billows high into the air. More than five-thousand people have been evacuated.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Relief</b><p>
Prime minister Chretien is challenging world leaders to get off their duffs and do something to help one-million starving refugees in Central Africa. He wants an international military force to ensure food and medicine get into war-torn Zaire. Chretien says he's frustrated by the lack of action, so he's called 16 world leaders himself, and got the support of 10 of them. Canada is willing to lead the mission and send 15-hundred troops to Zaire.
<hr>
<b>Immigration</b><p>
Immigration minister Lucienne Robillard says she has tried to balance compassion with security in clearing a huge backlog of refugees. She has announced plans to grant landed immigrant status to more than 75-hundred Somalis and Afghans over the next four years. They have been stuck in legal limbo because their war-wracked countries could not provide them with any documents to prove who they are. Robillard says to win landed status, the refugees must be in Canada for at least five years, and show they have been good citizens with no criminal records.
<hr>
<b>Peru Quake</b><p>
Many residents in Southern Peru are living outdoors after a powerful earthquake rocked the region. As many as 15 people were killed and 700 people injured when the 6.4 magnitude quake struck. Many homes and buildings are in ruins. Forty to 60 miners remain trapped in an isolated gold mine in the Andes mountains.
<hr>
<b>Who Does What</b><p>
Back home,  the so-called "who does what" panel is recommending the Ontario government pay a bigger share of the cost of education.<br>   Panel chairman David Crombie is recommending that school boards focus their attention on activities that relate directly to students in the classroom. Crombie says that means business functions, like school construction and transportation, can be left to municipalities. The panel is also recommending that the number of school boards be reduced with boards having the same boundaries as counties and regional governments. Meanwhile,  the Association of Municipalities is applauding a recommendation that municipal governments get more control over police services. The panel says municipalities should set police budgets and appoint members of police-services boards. But the association is holding its breath over a suggestion that all municipalities be required to pay for policing.
<hr>
<b>Villa Inquest</b><p>
An inquest into the deaths of nursing home residents in Hamilton has been told there were problems at the St. Elizabeth Villa. The coroner's jury heard yesterday that 42 residents died in just over a year. Former regional coroner Dr. Bonita Porter testified she began an investigation in April 1995 after complaints about food, nursing care, and the use of restraints. The inquest is looking into the deaths of five residents at the home. Porter was the first witness to testify, and said that while reviewing medical charts, she noticed a pattern of problems. Those included problems with admission criteria, monitoring care, availability of resources and residents' injuries.
<hr>
<b>White Rose Robbery</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police investigating a robbery at the White Rose Nursery outlet on Upper James Street this morning.<br> Details are still coming in ...but it appears that two suspects wearing ski masks and brandishing handguns entered the store around 8:30 this morning and demanded cash.<br> The two fled with a third suspect in a green Ford Mystique.<br>   The license plate of the getaway car had been covered with plastic.<br>   We'll have an update at 5:30.
<hr>
<b>Drug Sting</b><p>
Teenagers and drugs...  despite the many campaigns over the years to tell teenagers to just say no to drugs.. they still do it ... and there are still those who happily sell drugs to teenagers.. as Jamie West reports, Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are turning up the heat on drug pushers and users in hopes of getting the anti-drug message through to young people.
<i><br>  9am and the Hamilton Wentworth High Enforcement Action Team are getting ready...<br> The six member team changes it's focuss every few months...they've already made a big dent in car thefts,  kept loitering youths off the streets, and are now conducting daily undercover surveillance of 10 high schools, trying to put a damper on drug use...<br>  Education is a big component of the programme,...<br>  So far over 25 arrests...for possesion and trafficking...<br>  And word is getting around that the heat is definitely on...<br>  Marijuana is the drug of choice followed by hasish oil and LSD.<br>  The numbers say less than 5% of students are users on a regular basis, but the percentage of first timers is way up...<br>  Even being where you're not supposed to be will get you in trouble with this team...<br>  Continuing identification arrests, prosecution and effective followup are proving to the community that heat means business.<br>  </i>









<P>
