<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 12, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Doc Protest         
    <li>QEW Rollover        
    <li>Zaire Canada        
    <li>Planes Crash        
    <li>Mexico Explosion    
    <li>U.S. Snow           
    <li>Video Vote          
    <li>GM Strike           
    <li>Marvin Caplan       
    <li>Jenny Verdict       
    <li>Morissette          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Doc Protest</b><p>
The doctors' protest is spreading. <br> Ontario's 450 general surgeons have stopped booking new operations as part of the job action against the Harris government. Doctors are battling with the province over a clawback on their earnings and the right of new doctors to practice where they want. The surgeons say they will perform procedures that were booked before November 8th. But they say they will be joining obstetricians and other specialists by not taking on any new patients. The head of the Association of General Surgeons of Ontario says all elective surgery in Ontario could be shut down within a month.
<hr>
<b>QEW Rollover</b><p>
Motorists on the Queen Elizabeth Way found it a lot less stressful during this morning's rush hour. This after one of Canada's busiest highways was closed for more than half a day.<br> All lanes of the QEW through Burlington were reopened just in time for the morning rush hour.<br> The highway was closed at Burloak Drive around one o'clock yesterday afternoon when a tractor-trailer carrying gasoline flipped onto its side. About one-thousand litres of the truck's 50-thousand-litre load spilled forcing the closure of the busy highway and bringing traffic to a standstill for most of the afternoon and evening, and creating a major traffic headache right into the wee hours of this morning. The tanker truck was moved from the side of the road around 4:30 this morning. Luckily no one was injured.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Canada</b><p>
Canada has offered to lead a multinational force to help end the refugee crisis in eastern Zaire.<br> U.N. secretary general Boutros Boutros-Ghali confirms Canada is ready to command the force in Zaire and he hopes the U.S. offers logistical support. Boutros Ghali says the size of a force has not been set but experts are speculating between 10-thousand to 12-thousand troops will be needed. 
<hr>
<b>Planes Crash</b><p>
Two planes have collided in flight near New Delhi.<br> Reports say there were no survivors among the 350 people aboard the aircraft.<br> The planes involved were a Saudi Airways 7-47 jumbo jet and a smaller passenger plane from Kazakhstan.<br> The scene of the disaster is a village about 60-kilometres west of New Delhi.
<hr>
<b>Mexico Explosion</b><p>
Hundreds of firefighters are battling to contain a huge blaze at a fuel storage facility just outside Mexico City.<br> Towering flames lit up the night sky nearly 12 hours after a giant storage tank exploded.<br> At least 11 people were hurt and thousands were forced from their homes.<br> Flames rose high in the sky after the initial blast yesterday sparked a fire that quickly spread to a second storage tank.
<hr>
<b>U.S. Snow</b><p>
The threat of heavy snowsqualls has eased across most of southwestern and central Ontario -- except in the Goderich area.<br> About 35 centimetres of lake-effect snow has fallen in the Huron and the southern Grey-Bruce region during the past 24 hours.<br> Forecasters say another 15 centimetres could fall in the area today.<br> That's not the case south of the border. Frigid air feeding off the great lakes has dumped more than 60 centimetres of snow from Wisconsin to New York. The hard-hit Cleveland area already has about 60 centimetres and forecasters expect another 50 today.<br> The snow storm has closed schools, blacked out tens of thousands of homes, and forced communities to open temporary shelters.<br> So far, the pre-winter blast is blamed for eight deaths in Wisconsin and one in Ohio -- most of them traffic related.
<hr>
<b>Video Vote</b><p>
A controversial sex-education video has spawned a new material-review policy, at the Wentworth Board of Education. An animated video that some parents complained was too graphic, prompted the board last night to approved a ten-point program; that will allow school councils the opportunity to view, and approve sex-education videos that may be deemed controversial, by board staff. The new policy was approved by a 6-4 margin ... and was widely applauded, by parents attending the board meeting.
<hr>
<b>GM Strike</b><p>
Strikes against General Motors in Canada and the United States will likely cost the automaker at least 650 million dollars U.S. after taxes in the fourth quarter.<br> GM lowered its fourth-quarter production forecast by 151-thousand vehicles to 1.17 million because of the strikes.<br> Meanwhile, General Motors says strikers who occupied an Oshawa plant for several hours last month did extensive damage.<br> The Canadian Auto Workers Union denies that.<br> The automaker says it doesn't have an exact figure but suggests the repair bill will run into the thousands of dollars.<br> GM spokesman Stew Low says the damage includes tampering with brakes to tractor trailers, severing of hydraulic and pneumatic hoses, and ripped wire doors.<br> About 125 striking workers stormed the plant and occupied it for five hours on October 16th to stop the company from removing machinery.
<hr>
<b>Marvin Caplan</b><p>
Uptown style in a downtown location; was the trade mark of Marvin Caplan, for nearly two decades.<br> The retailer, and Hamilton alderman made a statement with both his wardrobe, and his views on city politics.<br> Later this week; half of that equation, will disappear, as Caplan closes his retail outlet, for the last time.<br> The clothing store that made his name is, he says, a victim of both changing consumer shopping patterns, and the city's failure to react more quickly to the deterioration of the downtown core. Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>They're liquidating the inventory at Marvin Caplan Gentlemen's Apparel.  They're also liquidating three full-time jobs, several part-time positions, and an eighteen-year-old business.  The company's president, who's also a Hamilton alderman, says he can't afford to keep losing money while the city dickers over what to do about the downtown.  And he wishes the city would simply let its staff do the job they're paid to do.  <br>Caplan says the city merely needs to create the conditions necessary to allow business to thrive.  The businesses themselves will do the rest.  <br>And Hess Village is not the only high point. Caplan points out the International Village, and James Street North and South are thriving, proving it's premature to sound the death knell for the downtown core. </i>
<hr>
<b>Jenny Verdict</b><p>
Jonathan Schmitz, who admitted shooting a gay acquaintance after the man revealed a crush on him during a taping of the Jenny Jones Show, was found guilty today of second-degree murder. Schmitz was charged with fatally shooting Scott Amedure in March 1995 after the two were taped for a Jenny Hones show segment on same-sex crushes.
<hr>
<b>Morissette</b><p>
Rocker Alanis Morissette has made Canadian recording history. She's the first Canadian to hit the magic "double-diamond" mark of two-million sales for a single album, "Jagged Little Pill." Released in June, 1995, the album has produced four consecutive top 10 singles and a trophy case full of Junos and Grammys. The 22-year old Ottawa native is also the first artist of the 90's to hit the two-million mark in Canada and the first since Michael Jackson's "Thriller" album in 1982.<br> The only other members of the Canadian "double-diamond' club are Fleetwood Mac's "Rumors," "Led Zeppelin 4," "The Wall" by Pink Floyd and Meat Loaf's "Bat Out of Hell."










<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

