<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 11, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Remembrance Day     
    <li>Zaire Update        
    <li>Algerian Bomb       
    <li>Russian Bomb        
    <li>Cyclone Update      
    <li>Doc Update          
    <li>Ford Vote           
    <li>Labor Storm         
    <li>Minivan Bumpers     
    <li>Toronto Murder      
    <li>Box Office          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Remembrance Day</b><p>
At the 11th hour, of this the 11th day, of the 11th month, Canadians took a moment to remember.  <br>  Today is Remembrance Day, a day to remember Canadians who gave up their lives in past wars allowing us to reap the legacy of their sacrifices in a free world. Ceremonies were held across the country, to the refrain of the last post.
<hr>
<b>Zaire Update</b><p>
While we in Canada enjoy a life free of war, the same cannot be said of millions around the world.  A mission to get relief to the huge crowds of refugees in eastern Zaire is set to begin today. A U.N. official says assessment teams and some emergency aid are to enter Zaire from Rwandan border towns. They'll lay the groundwork for the arrival of truckloads of badly needed food and medicine. Fighting during the past month has sent more than one-million refugees scattering without food or water.
<hr>
<b>Algerian Bomb</b><p>
The shadow of terrorism continues to plague many countries around the world.  A car bomb exploded in an Algiers suburb Sunday, killing at least 15 people. A few hours later, a second bomb exploded.<br> Both explosions could be heard throughout most of the Algerian capital.<br> Officials say the first bomb went off near a coach parked by a school.<br> Hospital sources say 15 people were killed, four of them children, and at least 30 others were wounded -- some of them also youngsters.<br> No one claimed responsibility for the bombings, but suspicion centres on muslim militants waging an insurgency against the government.
<hr>
<b>Russian Bomb</b><p>
Russia has set up special police teams to track down the gangland bombers who killed at least 12 mourners at a Moscow cemetery. Yesterday's massacre has been blamed on criminal groups linked to Afghan war veterans' groups. It has shocked a nation where mafia killings have become commonplace in Russia's post-communism chaos. The Moscow prosecutor's office says the attack is being investigated as "terrorism."
<hr>
<b>Cyclone Update</b><p>
 While manmade tragedy continues to claim lives, mother nature is capable of inflicting her wrath in terrible catastrophies. Officials say the death toll from a cyclone that swept through southeast India last week may reach two-thousand. The search continues for about one-thousand fishermen, who were working at sea where the cyclone hit on Wednesday. Hopes are fading as hundreds of bodies wash ashore. The cyclone destroyed houses, livestock and crops in a prime agricultural area of the country.
<hr>
<b>Doc Update</b><p>
Ontario's doctors are turning up the pressure in their battle with the province. Doctors are angry with provincial clawbacks on their earnings and a plan by the Harris government to force doctors to work in underserviced areas. Yesterday, two after-hours children's clinics in Toronto closed their doors, forcing parents to take their kids to hospital emergency rooms. Dr. Paul Friedman of the Coalition of Family Physicians says he doesn't agree with such closures, but says if the government doesn't back down, more closures might be unavoidable. He says if the government follows through on its total fee reduction, what is happening today will be "small potatoes" compared to what will happen next February and March as the fiscal year ends. Talks between the Ontario Medical Association and the province continue this week.
<hr>
<b>Ford Vote</b><p>
It's a clean sweep for the Canadian auto workers. Workers voted almost unanimously in favor of new three-year deal with Ford yesterday. The deal tracks those hammered out earlier with Chrysler and G.M. CAW head Buzz Hargrove says bargaining this year with the big three shows that if workers unite, they can get ahead in a climate of downsizing and concessions. The three-year deal puts restrictions on contracting out and hikes wages by about 10 per cent.
<hr>
<b>Labor Storm</b><p>
Meanwhile, the level of time lost due to labor unrest in the first half of this year reached levels not seen since 1990. That suggests a long period of labor calm has given way to stormy workplace relations.<br>   A stronger economy, global competitive pressure, labor-law changes and the erosion of the social safety net have unleashed a new militancy among unions.<br>   At the same time, companies are more resolved to take the unions on.<br>   Figures show just over one-10th of one per cent of all work time was lost to strikes or lockouts involving more than 500 workers between January and June.<br>   That's roughly four times the level of the past two years, although still well below the almost half per cent level in 1976.
<hr>
<b>Minivan Bumpers</b><p>
It appears that most minivan bumpers don't do much to prevent big damage in low-speed impact crashes. The U.S. Insurance Institute for Highway Safety crashed nine popular vans into barriers at eight kilometres an hour.  All fared poorly.  The 1996 Honda Odyssey sustained the least amount of damage -- at about 474 dollars per crash -- while the Ford Aerostar had the most at 14-hundred per crash.
<hr>
<b>Toronto Murder</b><p>
Police are asking for the help in identifying Toronto's 49th murder victim of the year.<br> The man aged between 60 and 70 was found in a recycling bin at the rear of an apartment building on Adelaide Street near Niagara Street on Saturday morning.<br> He'd been beaten on the head.
<hr>
<b>Box Office</b><p>
"Ransom", starring oscar-winning heartthrob Mel Gibson, has knocked Shakespeare from atop the North American box office. The film about a father who turns the tables on his son's kidnappers took in an estimated 35-million dollars U.S. in its debut weekend. "Romeo and Juliet" was second, bringing in 8.8-million dollars, followed by Queen Latifah's "Set it Off."









<P>
