<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 8, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Hamilton One Tier   
    <li>Unemployment        
    <li>Bank Rate           
    <li>Doc Protest         
    <li>OFL Protest Follow
    <li>HSR Update       
    <li>Machete Murder      
    <li>Harnick Break-in    
    <li>Homolka Parole      
    <li>Teachers Vote       
    <li>Halton School Update
    <li>Rock Guns           
    <li>Gun Bust            
    <li>TWA Missile         
    <li>Nigeria Crash       
    <li>India Cyclone       
    <li>Sex Scandal         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton One Tier</b><p>
A deal has been reached between Hamilton and her suburban neighbours which could see the creation of a new supercity.  Bleary-eyed municipal politicians met into the wee hours of this morning with provincial mediator Gardner Church, and finally came up with an agreement which almost everyone could live with. Deborah Walker was there for the twelve-and-a- half hour marathon session, and has this report.
<i><br>For the first seven hours, they staked out their positions, conferring in corridors... or closeting themselves away from others outside their own municipality. Gradually, all the suburban politicians congregated in one room, with occasional emissaries from Hamilton dispatched from the floor above. By midnight, everyone re-assembled for a last-ditch effort at reconciling their differences.  <br>But an hour later, the deal-making nearly collapsed, as Dundas and Flamborough walked out on the talks.  The rest soldiered on, and at four-thirty this morning, they reached an historic agreement.  <br>Under the proposal, Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities will disappear, replaced by one, as yet un-named municipality, governed by one local council, with less than half the current number of politicians.  The former suburbs will retain their historic names, and have the choice of setting up community councils, to deal with local issues.  <br>In exchange for giving up their boundaries, the former suburbs will have the same number of seats on the new council as Hamilton has.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Unemployment</b><p>
Canada has returned to double-digit unemployment. The jobless rate hit ten per cent last month, up from 9.9 per cent in September. The economy created 42-thousand jobs in October -- but that wasn't enough to offset a rising number of job hunters. Some industries that had been putting Canadians back to work suddenly backtracked and cut payrolls, including manufacturing, transportation and communications. The biggest source of new jobs last month -- farming and construction.
<hr>
<b>Bank Rate</b><p>
The good news on the economic front is that the major banks are cutting interest rates yet again. Both the Bank of Nova Scotia and the Toronto-Dominion Bank led the way this morning chopping one-quarter of a percentage point from their prime rate. The new prime will be 4.75 per cent, effective Tuesday. The announcements came minutes after the Bank of Canada cut its key lending rate. The new central bank rate is 3.25 per cent. The central bank has been cutting rates steadily to offset the dollar's rising strength on the exchange market and the stimulate the economy.
<hr>
<b>Doc Protest</b><p>
Talks between the province and Ontario's doctors have resumed in spite of the start of a job action by many physicians.<br>   Doctors have said they would begin turning away new non-emergency patients today if an agreement wasn't reached with the province. A move, meanwhile, by health minister Jim Wilson to limit the withdrawal of services has infuriated doctors. In a toughly worded letter to the College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario, Wilson said work stoppages should lead to sanctions. Dr. Murray Miller of the Specialist Coalition of Ontario says Wilson's bullying tactics have undermined the negotiations. Miller says the doctors in his group won't negotiate with a gun to their head.
<hr>
<b>OFL Protest Follow</b><p>
Unions appear to be divided over day of protest tactics. More than a dozen unions say they'll no longer help shut down Ontario cities to protest the Harris government's cost-cutting policies. After meeting with the Ontario Federation of Labor to discuss last month's Toronto protest, the power workers' union and 12 others issued a news release saying it makes more sense to go the political route. While labor leaders insist there's no division in the ranks. It appears the prospects for another citywide shutdown is remote.
<hr>
<b>HSR Update</b><p>
A mediator will try next week to avert a strike that could bring Hamilton busses to a halt during Grey Cup week. Hamilton Street Railway bus drivers have set a November seventeenth strike deadline. Union leaders say members have no intention of accepting concessions. But Hamilton- Wentworth Region faces the possibility of another seven-million dollar cut from the province. And at least one councillor believes the failure to accept concessions now, could ultimately lead to the death of the HSR.
<hr>
<b>Machete Murder</b><p>
A Hamilton man who plead guilty to second degree murder in the death of his wife will not be eligible for parole for 15 years.<br>  Mr. Justice John Cavarzan, in sentencing 53 year old Carmelo Reyes, described the machete attack as an act of "appalling and unspeakable cruelty".<br>  47 year old Alba Fuentes-Reyes died after being struck by a van and struck repeatedly with a machete.<br>  Before his sentencing, Carmelo Reyes broke down momentarily, weeping while admitting he was wrong and was willing for pay for what he did.
<hr>
<b>Harnick Break-in</b><p>
Attorney general Charles Harnick dropped a bombshell in the legislature yesterday when he announced police were investigating two New Democrat MPP's.<br> Harnick says his ministry has asked the police to open a criminal investigation of Shelley Martel and Peter Kormos for an alleged break-in at the province's new family support plan office.<br> Kormos and Martel went there yesterday morning to try to expose problems.<br> Opposition politicians are accusing harnick of "shocking" intimidation and of acting as judge and jury.
<hr>
<b>Homolka Parole</b><p>
The Ontario government is looking to block Karla Homolka's parole from the Kingston Prison for Women. The Toronto Star says solicitor-general Bob Runciman and attorney-general Charles Harnick will intervene with the National Parole Board in the case.<br> Homolka is serving a 12-year sentence for manslaughter in the deaths of two teenagers, but will be eligible to apply for day passes in January, and for full parole in July.<br> But a source says both cabinet ministers have no intention of letting her get out.
<hr>
<b>Teachers Vote</b><p>
Secondary school teachers voting today on the Hamilton Board of Education's last offer.<br> They're also taking a strike vote.<br> Both votes are being supervised by the education relations commission.<br> That's the provincial body overseeing teacher-board negotiations.<br> Should the teachers vote in favour of a strike, they'll be in a legal position to do so five days after giving the board notice.<br> Ballots will be counted this afternoon, and we hope to have results for you on First Edition at 5:30 pm.
<hr>
<b>Halton School Update</b><p>
Groups opposed to school closures in the Halton Region are joining forces to pressure trustees to keep them open.<br> Six schools are scheduled to close, but the groups say its not the answer.<br> Dwight Ryan reports from Burlington.
<i> <br>  The children are singing in the gym at Lakeshore Public School in Burlington.<br>  They've been making music for generations at one of the city's oldest schools.  <br>    The board is facing a 24 million dollar shortfall.<br>  Parent groups from all six schools are joining forces to fight the cuts.<br>  They believe school closures are not the answer.   <br>    And so with a well organized campaign they are trying to convince trustees to vote against closures.   <br>       Sstill, the director of education believes closures are the answer.   <br>      Parent groups will have the opportunity to voice their opinions in communtiy meetings.<br>  A final answer from the board will come before Christmas.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Rock Guns</b><p>
Justice minister Allan Rock is said to be on the verge of releasing the new national firearms regulations. MP's studying the new rules say they've been told they'll be handed down November 20th. The regulations deal with the licensing of all gun owners and registering of all firearms. Regulations -- as opposed to laws -- are implemented directly by cabinet and don't require approval of parliament.
<hr>
<b>Gun Bust</b><p>
A joint forces investigation involving RCMP, OPP and police in Hull, Quebec and Hamilton Wentworth has broken a gun running ring.<br>  Six of the nine guns seized, including a .50 calibre handgun, had been stolen from a Hamilton area home this summer.<br>  37 year old Bruce Gerald Maher of Hamilton was arrested last night, and charged with 25 weapon offenses.<br>  More arrests are expected.
<hr>
<b>TWA Missile</b><p>
Turning to international news,  veteran U.S. newsman Pierre Salinger says he will hand over a mysterious document to the FBI. He says it proves the U.S. navy accidentally shot down TWA flight 800 in July off Long Island during a missile test. Both the navy and FBI heatedly denied Salinger's charge. However, the FBI received dozens of calls from people claiming to have seen a missile at the time of the explosion. All 230 people on board the plane were killed.
<hr>
<b>Nigeria Crash</b><p>
A Nigerian Boeing 727 airliner missing since Thursday has crashed killing all 141 people on board. The plane was flying from the southeastern oil city of Port Harcourt to Lagos with 132 passengers and nine crew members. Airport sources said several foreigners were on board, possibly oil company executives.
<hr>
<b>India Cyclone</b><p>
Planes and helicopters are scrambling to drop food and medicine to half a million people stranded by flood waters in India. A cyclone lashed the southeastern coast Wednesday night, killing at least one thousand people -- a toll officials say is certain to rise. State officials say 15-hundred people are missing, including dozens of fishermen working in the Bay of Bengal. More than 10-thousand homes were destroyed.
<hr>
<b>Sex Scandal</b><p>
A sex scandal has rocked the U.S. army. An army captain and two sergeants face charges of raping or sexually harassing more than two dozen female trainees. The alleged incidents took place at the Army Ordnance Centre in Maryland. Other service officials said the case could get worse and that some 500 female recruits and former recruits had already been questioned.








