<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 7, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Hospital Cuts       
    <li>Ortho Docs          
    <li>Chlorine Water      
    <li>Van Shooting        
    <li>Burton Search       
    <li>Kids Breakfast      
    <li>Gambling Crackdown  
    <li>Truck Safety        
    <li>Ford Settles        
    <li>Australia Massacre  
    <li>Yeltsin Better      
    <li>Candu China         
    <li>Alien Smuggling     
    <li>Dying Mom Sentenced 
    <li>SCTV                
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hospital Cuts</b><p>
There's a report that Ontario is about to lose one-fifth of its acute-care hospital beds.  <br>  The Toronto Star says the Health Services Restructuring Commission plans to eliminate 48-hundred of the province's 24-thousand acute-care beds. Those beds are the ones used for for everything from surgery to childbirth and emergencies. It's the first time the commission has confirmed plans to reduce hospital capacity beyond the nine-thousand beds already closed in recent years. Commission chairman Duncan Sinclair says no hospital is exempt from cost cutting. Health minister Jim Wilson has said he intends to chop 1.3-billion dollars from the health-care system in three years. Sinclair says the commission will be able to cut more than that.
<hr>
<b>Ortho Docs</b><p>
More trouble for Ontario's beleaguered health care system. Ontario's orthopedic surgeons will start refusing most new patients tomorrow. It's part of a protest against the Tory government's failure to meet doctors' demands. The Ontario Orthopedic Association called for the long-threatened job action in a memo faxed to its 298 members yesterday. The group says there's been no progress at talks with the province and it's useless to wait any longer.<br>   The association says elective surgery such as hip and knee replacement shouldn't be cancelled, and emergency problems should be treated. The OMA rejected a tentative deal with the province last week after a vote by members but put off job action as long as talks continue.
<hr>
<b>Chlorine Water</b><p>
Still with health news,  a new study suggests that chlorine-treated drinking water could be killing people. In studying five-thousand Ontario residents, Health Canada suggests chlorinated water causes more than 500 cases of cancer and 140 deaths each year. It concludes the reaction of chlorine with decaying organic material creates carcinogenic byproducts known as T-H-M's in the water. Researchers think those cause bladder and colon cancers.
<hr>
<b>Van Shooting</b><p>
Niagara Regional Police are investigating a fatal shooting. A body was found along the side of Highway Three near Fort Erie around 5:30 this morning. Reports from the scene suggest a man was found shot to death beside a delivery van. Police aren't saying much more as they continue their investigation.
<hr>
<b>Burton Search</b><p>
 About a dozen Hamilton Wentworth police officers spent the morning looking for clues in the disappearance of a Stoney Creek woman.  41 year old Kathryn Burton disappeared October 3rd. Police say she is unemployed and was depressed around the time of her disappearance.<br> A neighbour reported Burton missing from her apartment where she lived by herself. If you think you've seen Kathryn Burton, please call Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police at 546-4925.
<hr>
<b>Kids Breakfast</b><p>
Premier Mike Harris has found himself in a food fight.  He says it isn't unemployment or welfare cuts that are leaving kids with empty tummies.  The premier announced a school breakfast program yesterday. The eight million-dollar initiative will support 400 breakfast plans to be introduced across the province by the end of the school year. He shrugged off suggestions that his government's cuts to civil-service jobs and welfare rates might have something to do with kids' being hungry and that has critics fuming.
<hr>
<b>Gambling Crackdown</b><p>
Just days before legalizing 20-thousand video lottery machines, the Ontario government is cracking down on illegal ones. Police estimate about 15-thousand illegal machines are in use across the province. Solicitor General Bob Runciman says organized crime has a hand in most of them. The OPP will hire an extra 29 officers to deal exclusively with gaming investigations.<br>   In addition, eight Toronto police officers, four crown attorneys and up to five technical experts will be dedicated to fighting illegal video gambling. Critics argue that legalizing some machines will only compound what is already a serious problem.
<hr>
<b>Truck Safety</b><p>
And Queens Park isn't gambling on road safety. It's cracking down on companies that operate unsafe trucks. Legislation to be tabled today will give the registrar of motor vehicles the power to penalize companies who operate unsafe rigs. Safety records of firms will be made public, exposing those with a history of violations to insurance companies and customers. There will also be new provisions to allow the registrar to refuse new licences.
<hr>
<b>Ford Settles</b><p>
Ford of Canada workers vote on a new tentative contract this weekend. Ford and its union struck the deal yesterday, hours before a strike deadline. The CAW is recommending members accept the pact, which shadows ones made with chrysler and G.M. The deal contains wage increases and limits on outsourcing.
<hr>
<b>Australia Massacre</b><p>
Turning to international news,  an unsettling scene today in court in Hobart, Australia.  The man who killed 35 people last April changed his plea to guilty to all 72 charges he faced in the Port Arthur shooting massacre.  But Martin Bryant laughed during his entire court appearance. He's certain to spend the rest of his life behind bars. The only question is whether it'll be in prison or a mental institution.
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Better</b><p>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin is walking again. But he's been advised to stay another 24 hours in the Moscow hospital where he had open heart surgery this week. Doctors made the recommendation despite a request by Yeltsin to move to another clinic to convalesce. They say all signs are that the 65-year-old president's condition is normal after such an operation.
<hr>
<b>Candu China</b><p>
The federal government may water down environmental regulations to help complete the four billion-dollar Candu reactor sale to China. Reports say prime minister Chretien doesn't want an environmental review to delay the project. Under the rules, Canadian-funded projects that don't face environmental assessment in the recipient country must undergo one in Canada. The Candu sale has also come under attack because of China's human rights record and its active nuclear weapons program. It's suspected the prime minister wants to make the signing ceremony the centrepiece of his visit to China later this month.
<hr>
<b>Alien Smuggling</b><p>
Hundreds of illegal Asian immigrants have been pouring into the United States over the last two years ... through a doorway cut in Canada. The RCMP made a dozen arrests ... four in Ontario ... to close that doorway, and end one of the most lucrative and despicable smuggling operations, in North America. 
<hr>
<b>Dying Mom Sentenced</b><p>
The final chapter has been written in a sad story in Toronto. A woman who claimed to be on the brink of death and the victim of a purse-snatching has been sentenced to three years probation. Donna Mercier says all she really wanted last April was medication for her painful kidney condition. But she ended up telling police she'd been robbed of 150 dollars and was dying of cancer.  Her tale drew national public sympathy and 100-thousand dollars in donations.
<hr>
<b>SCTV</b><p>
Last week we spoke with the author of a new biography on the late John Candy. It seems canadians can't get enough of memories of the SCTV comedy troupe. Hamilton's own Dave Thomas has a new book out about the years he spent creating one of Canada's funniest video exports.


<P>
