<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Clinton Wins        
    <li>Yeltsin Update      
    <li>Mortgage Update     
    <li>Smokies Protest     
    <li>Deadly Fire         
    <li>Doc Talks           
    <li>Ford Settles???     
    <li>Reserve Smokes      
    <li>Restructure         
    <li>Gambling Survey     
    <li>Success at Shaw     
    <li>Macarena Madness    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Clinton Wins</b><p>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has easily won a second term in office.   <br>  He's the first Democratic president to be re-elected since Franklin Roosevelt six decades ago. But Republicans will keep control of congress. Clinton says by splitting the balance of power in Washington, Americans are saying they want all parties to work together to "get the job done." 
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Update</b><p>
Russian president Boris Yeltsin is back in charge.<br> He reclaimed his presidential powers just 24 hours after a seven-hour heart-bypass operation.<br> Yeltsin had transferred power to prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin before surgery.<br> His lead surgeon initially thought it would be a couple of days before Yeltsin could regain charge of the country.<br> Doctors performed five bypasses on Yeltsin.
<hr>
<b>Mortgage Update</b><p>
The cost of borrowing to buy a home, already at some of the lowest levels in 30 years, has fallen a little more.<br> Royal Bank kicked off another round of cuts today, chopping up to a quarter point off existing rates. Effective tomorrow, a five-year mortgage at the Royal falls to 6.95 from 7.20.<br> The six-month rate drops to five per cent from 5.20.<br> Falling interest rates have paved the way for the latest cuts.
<hr>
<b>Smokies Protest</b><p>
Firefighters would like to see the government's proposed fire protection and prevention act go up in smoke.<br> Thousands of them are at a rally outside Queen's Park today to protest the legislation to regulate municipal fire departments.<br> The bill allows firefighters to work up to 48 hours a week, bars them from striking, and permits key personnel to be excluded from the union.<br> The Ontario Professional Firefighters Association says the legislation puts the safety of firefighters in jeopardy.
<hr>
<b>Deadly Fire</b><p>
A four-year old boy has died of burns hours after a fire in downtown Toronto.<br> The boy was taken to hospital with burns to about 90 per cent of his body. His mother, and three firefighters suffered burns as well.<br> None of their injuries are life threatening.<br> The fire apparently began in the basement of a townhouse in Toronto's Chinatown Tuesday afternoon. Its cause is still under investigation.
<hr>
<b>Doc Talks</b><p>
There are two days to go before thousands of disgruntled Ontario doctors start shutting their doors to new patients.<br> The government and the Ontario Medical Association are trying to resolve disputes over billing, malpractice insurance, and how to serve underserviced areas.<br> A new wrinkle is a failure by doctors to sustain a united front.<br> Some obstetricians stopped taking new patients months ago, some family doctors followed suit last Friday, but most are waiting until this Friday.
<hr>
<b>Ford Settles???</b><p>
It appears a tentative contract has been reached at Ford of Canada.<br> A union official at Ford's assembly plant in St. Thomas, Ontario, confirmed the deal to a London radio station.<br> The official, who didn't want to be named, says members of the Canadian Auto Workers are being told not to consider an early walkout because a deal has been struck.<br> CAW president Buzz Hargrove has been saying for days the two sides are close.<br> Ford was facing a strike dealine of 7 p-m this evening.
<hr>
<b>Reserve Smokes</b><p>
Operations at one of the largest employers on the Six Nations Reserve are touch and go.<br> This after charges were laid against 9 founding members of Grand River Enterprises.<br> 32 people work at the cigarette manufacturing plant.<br> The RCMP claim the plant has illegally manufactured and sold cigarettes without a federal licence since it opened in 1994.<br> The Six Nations Band Council called a meeting this morning to support the members charged.
<hr>
<b>Restructure</b><p>
Some are calling it Meech Lake... and it kind of looks like it, right down to the open bar.   A provincially appointed mediator called together political delegations from every municipality in Hamilton Wentworth Region for a closed door meeting at a downtown Hamilton hotel last night.<br> When regional chairman Terry Cooke arrived, he was appalled to find a fully-stocked bar in the meeting room.<br> Knowing the discussions would require clear heads, Cooke ordered the bar removed, and the meeting began.<br> Politicians are trying to find the common ground necessary to carry them to a united vision on restructuring local government. ...the mediator has forbidden politicians from talking to reporters as long as there is hope they can reach a compromise.
<hr>
<b>Gambling Survey</b><p>
The Ontario government appears to be backing away from a plan to introduce video lottery machines in licensed restaurants and bars.<br> The issue was debated in the legislature yesterday without a final vote.<br> Afterwards, premier Mike Harris said they are still looking at introducing the VLTs into controlled locations where there is already gambling, such as racetracks and charity casinos. Meanwhile, Ontario's Liberals say a majority of people are opposed to video gambling in the province.
<hr>
<b>Success at Shaw</b><p>
It's a record-breaking year so far for the Shaw Festival in Niagara on the Lake.<br> Revenues have already hit 9.2 million dollars, surpassing last year's high by more than 160-thousand dollars. Paid attendance has reached 282-thousand-643, or 75 per cent of capacity.<br> Agatha Christie's, "The Hollow" has been such a success it is held over until November 24th.
<hr>
<b>Macarena Madness</b><p>
All "macarena" all the time -- well, at least for a day-and-a-half.<br> New radio station KUJ in Walla Walla, Washington kicked off its launch Sunday with an all-"macarena" format, playing the dance song for 36 straight hours.  The county's emergency dispatch centre even called the station to ask if its disk jockey had died.


<P>
