<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Yeltsin Heart       
    <li>U.S. Elexn.          
    <li>Bhutto Fired        
    <li>Ford Talks          
    <li>Doc Deal            
    <li>Burton St. Arson    
    <li>Reyes Verdict       
    <li>Missing Woman       
    <li>H.W. Restructure     
    <li>Kissing Judge       
    <li>Roux Commons        
    <li>Philip at Fair      
    <li>Hamilton Smoking    
    <li>Jackson Baby        
    <li>Mars Mission        
    <li>Cold Myths          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Yeltsin Heart</b><p>
Russia is currently in the hands of prime minister Victor Chernomyrdin.<br> That's because president Boris Yeltsin has successfully undergone open heart surgery.  <br> Yeltsin has spent the past six weeks preparing for the bypass operation. He's expected to reclaim his powers as soon as possible after the surgery.<br> 
<hr>
<b>U.S. Elexn.</b><p>
South of the border Bob Dole is leading the U.S. presidential election -- so far. The first presidential votes of 1996 were cast early today morning in two tiny new hampshire towns.<br> In combined results from the towns, Dole had 31 votes to 20 for president Clinton and five for Ross Perot.<br> Despite those results the United States headed for the polls today with all signs pointing to a triumph for president Bill Clinton and the end of the trail for old soldier Bob Dole. But the opinion surveys that unanimously forecast re-election for democrat Clinton also suggest that grudging voters might hinder him with another republican congress.
<hr>
<b>Bhutto Fired</b><p>
Pakistan's president has called for new elections to replace the prime minister and her government.<br> The president sacked prime minister Benazir Bhutto and her government, accusing her of rampant corruption.<br> Soldiers are on guard outside Bhutto's residence.<br> A party spokesman says her phone lines have been cut, and only her family is being allowed to see her.<br> The spokesman also says Bhutto's husband has been arrested, along with 20 other party members.
<hr>
<b>Ford Talks</b><p>
Ford Canada workers could hear about a new contract agreement with the nation's second-biggest automaker today.<br> Ford has decided to "track the pattern" established at Chrysler and GM and has agreed to restrictions on outsourcing.<br> It has also offered a six per cent wage hike over three years.<br> CAW leader Buzz Hargrove says a deal is "within reach."
<hr>
<b>Doc Deal</b><p>
It's back to the bargaining table today for negotiators for the government and Ontario's doctors.<br> Last week, representatives of Ontario's 20-thousand doctors soundly rejected a proposed settlement in their dispute with the province.<br> The Ontario Medical Association had said it would accept most of the provisions, including reduced salary clawbacks and increased malpractice funding.<br> But the association balked at conditions that would force new doctors into underserviced areas.
<hr>
<b>Burton St. Arson</b><p>
Investigators on the scene again today at a suspected arson in Hamilton's north end.<br> Just a month ago, police say a fire was deliberately set at the vacant Burton Street Markethon Flea Market.<br> Then last night witnesses say they a couple of teenagers running from the building just before flames shot out the second floor window.<br> Damage in this latest fire is estimated at 30-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Reyes Verdict</b><p>
A Hamilton man who hacked his wife to death with a machete was convicted Monday of second-degree murder.<br> 53 year old Carmelo Reyes, pleaded guilty to a crime that crown attorney Denis Allan described as ``unbelievable brutality in a public place.''<br> Court was told that in early December 1994, Alba Fuentes-Reyes was struck down by a van driven by her estranged husband and then slashed to death in front of her home. She died from severe head injuries.<br> Several people rushed to defend the 47-year-old mother of four.<br> The prosecution and defence jointly asked that reyes be given a life sentence with no chance of parole for at least 15 years. He is scheduled to be sentenced Friday.<br> One of the men who tried to help Alba Fuentes-Reyes has been nominated for an award with the Carnegie Hero Fund out of Pennsylvia.<br> Alexander Lee, a student at Western University, was treated for 26 stitches after he tried to stop the attack.
<hr>
<b>Missing Woman</b><p>
Police need help in locating a Stoney Creek woman, missing for more than a month now.<br> 41 year old Kathryn Burton was last seen October 3rd.<br> Police say she is unemployed and was depressed around the time of her disappearance.<br> A neighbour reported Burton missing from her apartment.<br> If you think you've seen Kathryn Burton, please call Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police at 546-4925.
<hr>
<b>H.W. Restructure</b><p>
There will be no meeting of regional council in Hamilton Wentworth as per usual tonight...<br> The regional chairman has cancelled the meeting...  so that politicians can push ahead with talks aimed at streamlining local government.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>One suburban mayor describes Gardner Church favourably as a man in a hurry.  Evidently, Church has found reason to continue. Regional business will grind to a temporary halt with the cancellation of Tuesday night's council meeting. Instead, each of Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities will send a delegation to another round of negotiations, under the guidance of Church.  And there's probably good reason for political co-operation. Hamilton- Wentworth councillors are no doubt aware of the provincial government's proposal to merge Toronto's six municipalities into one super-city. But as long as Gardner Church is still on the job, Ontario's municipal affairs minister says it's premature to think about imposing the super-city model on Hamilton- Wentworth.  <br>Leach says he expects a progress report from Church by the end of the week.  At that point, the two will decide how best to proceed. </i>
<hr>
<b>Kissing Judge</b><p>
The Ontario Court of Appeal says a lower court exceeded its jurisdiction before removing judge Walter Hryciuk from the bench in 1993.<br> Hryciuk was dismissed for kissing and making lewd remarks to female prosecutors.<br> The appeal court ruled that justice Jean MacFarland had a "narrow mandate to conduct an inquiry" based on complaints from two crown attorneys and no one else.<br> MacFarland went on to hear evidence from three other women who complained of similar behavior before dismissing Hryciuk.
<hr>
<b>Roux Commons</b><p>
The Chretien government is ignoring opposition calls for the firing of Quebec's lieutenant governor for Nazi sympathies during the second world war.<br> Cabinet ministers feel that Jean-louis Roux's politics of 1942 took place a long time ago.<br> But Montreal Liberal MP Sheila Finestone isn't as forgiving.<br> She says she was disgusted at Roux's interview in a French news magazine, and wants him to apologize.
<hr>
<b>Philip at Fair</b><p>
There is royalty in our midst. Prince Philip is in Toronto for a two-day visit. He was greeted by bagpipes last night as he entered a gala party to benefit the World Wildlife Fund -- his favorite charity. He's also in the city for the Royal Winter Agricultural Fair. He'll hand out his own Duke of Edinburgh Youth Achievement Awards to 100 young Ontarians and wrap up the day with a celebrity dinner.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Smoking</b><p>
With the number of smoking bans coming our way, we've heard plenty of complaints about how such bans will hurt business at restaurants.<br>  Now comes a survey from the Hamilton Wentworth Public Health Department that claims the opposite.<br>  Annette Hamm explains.
<i><br>  It's just an estimate, but Hamilton Wentworth's healthy lifestyles branch says a smoking ban will bring in at least 685-thousand dollars to the region's hospitality industry.<br>  The numbers come from average restaurant receipts and a random telephone survey of smokers and non smokers.<br> That phone poll showed 27 per cent of Hamilton Wentworth residents smoke.  <br>  The region's telephone survey found 69 percent of restaurant customers who asked for non smoking seating found it unacceptable.<br>  Just over a third have left restaurants because they couldn't get a seat in the non smoking section.<br>  And 26 per cent have left restaurants because the smoke bothered them.<br>  The public health department will be meeting with Hamilton Wentworth municipalities later this month to come up with a draft bylaw to go smoke free by the year 2-thousand.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Jackson Baby</b><p>
It turns out that the tabloid rumor about Michael Jackson having a baby is true. Jackson's publicist, Christine Holevas, confirms that longtime friend Debbie Rowe will have his child next year. Jackson says in a statement that having a little one "is my dream come true."<br> Holevas denies reports that Rowe was artificially inseminated and that she's being paid 528-thousand dollars to have the baby. The statement from Jackson also asks for privacy for him and the mother-to-be.
<hr>
<b>Mars Mission</b><p>
Where once we earthlings concentrated on getting to the moon, our attention is now centered on the red planet. Even before scientists raised the possibility of life on mars, NASA had been planning to probe the surface of our mysterious galatic neighbour.
<hr>
<b>Cold Myths</b><p>
Welcome to the cold season. If you've noticed everyone seems to be fighting the sniffles these days, you're not alone. But what medications help? And which ones don't? 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

