<HEAD>

<TITLE>The News At Noon: 11/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/noon_arch.gif" width=400 height=56 border=0 alt="CHCH News At Noon On-Line Archive"></CENTER>

<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 4, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Porn Bust           
    <li>Lumberyard Fire     
    <li>Fergus Murder       
    <li>Domestic Courts     
    <li>Police Warning 
    <li>Ford Update         
    <li>OHA Conference    
    <li>Grit Poll           
    <li>Prez Poll           
    <li>Refugees - Zaire      
    <li>lt. Gov. Nazi       
    <li>Copps Flags         
    <li>Unity Cycle         
    <li>Jackson Baby        
    <li>Box Office          
    <li>Elvis Auction       
    <li>Sinatra Hospital    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Porn Bust</b><p>
Ontario Provincial Police say they think they've made the largest bust of child pornography ever in Canada.   <br>     The OPP's anti-pornography squad has seized 20-thousand computer files containing photos and video clips of child pornography. Police describe the nature of the material as "shocking." 22 year-old Trevor Davis of Kirkland Lake has been charged with several offences concerning the making, possession and distribution of child pornography. He's scheduled to appear in court in Kirkland Lake November 18th. The investigation in Ontario followed an FBI probe. Several people in California have been arrested after police linked them with a group called the Orchid Club.
<hr>
<b>Lumberyard Fire</b><p>
The Ontario Fire Marshall has been called in to investigate a Tapleytown lumberyard blaze.<br> The inferno erupted at Davey Lumber and Building Supplies late yesterday afternoon with smoke and flames quickly spreading to a storage shed. As many as 40-firefighters, mostly volunteers, were called out to the scene... and extra tankers were brought in from Grimsby and Glanbrook. One firefighter was injured, but not seriously, battling the flames.
<hr>
<b>Fergus Murder</b><p>
A 52-year-old Fergus man appears in court today in connection with the shooting death of his estranged wife.<br> Gordon Ray Abbott was arrested Saturday afternoon and charged with first-degree murder.<br> Forty-year-old Patricia Abbot of nearby Fergus was shot several times with a small calibre weapon when she went for lunch from her job as a legal secretary.
<hr>
<b>Domestic Courts</b><p>
The province will open two new courts next year dedicated to dealing with domestic assaults.<br> The government has announced 140-thousand dollars in funding.<br> The courts are scheduled to open in January and will have specialized teams of prosecutors, police, abuse intervention experts and counsellors.<br> Police will be expected to collect more evidence to allow for convictions if a victim won't testify.<br> That would include 911 tapes, audio and video tapes of the initial victim statements, and photographs of the victims and the crime scenes.
<hr>
<b>Police Warning </b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth police are urging doctors who perform abortions to be cautious in the wake of the anniversary of two shootings of Canadian gynecologists.<br> 63-year old Dr. Hugh Short was hit in the arm by a sniper's bullet last year as he sat with his wife in their Ancaster home.<br> Short who has yet to return to work was on the second floor of his home when a shot was fired from a ravine behind his house.<br> The shooting happened two days after the first anniversary of a Vancouver abortion doctor's near fatal wounding by a sniper. Police won't give details about added security measures being taken in Hamilton.
<hr>
<b>Ford Update</b><p>
The Canadian Auto Workers union is expecting a "good economic offer" from Ford of Canada today following a weekend of negotiations. Ford should be ready to table its first contract offer in a bid to avert a strike Wednesday. Auto workers president Buzz Hargrove says Ford is still dealing with local union issues, as both sides work towards the deadline.
<hr>
<b>OHA Conference</b><p>
The Ontario Hospital Association wants the Harris government to move more quickly to close or merge hospitals.<br> The association begins its annual convention today in Toronto with the message that the restructuring process is at risk. It wants to know by June which facilities will be closed rather than waiting for the health care restructuring commission to finish its work in 1999. Association president David Mackinnon says hospitals need time to adjust. He also says the government's plan to spend 167-million dollars a year to help surviving hospitals with renovations and new equipment isn't enough.
<hr>
<b>Grit Poll</b><p>
The honeymoon isn't over for the federal Liberals. An Angus Reid-Southam News poll indicates the Chretien grits still enjoy the support of 52 per cent of decided voters. Reform is up to 14 per cent, the Tories are down to 13, the Bloc Quebecois has 12 per cent, while the NDP stands at nine. In Quebec, the poll suggests the Bloc Quebecois has 46 per cent of decided voter support, six points more than the Liberals.
<hr>
<b>Prez Poll</b><p>
Meanwhile, south of the border, it's the final day of the U.S. presidential campaign. President Clinton will spend the day in New Hampshire. Republican challenger Bob Dole was in Phoenix Arizona this morning. Labouring with laryngitis he kept up his tirade against Clinton ethics in a last ditch attempt to sway the American public. It may do him no good though. The latest CBS poll out today indicates the Dole-Kemp ticket is still way behind president Clinton and vice president Al Gore. Third party hopeful Ross Perot is trailing badly.
<hr>
<b>Refugees - Zaire</b><p>
Tutsi rebels in eastern Zaire have declared a ceasefire to allow for repatriation of refugees who want to return to Rwanda.  A spokesman says the ceasefire will be in effect for at least three weeks so international relief workers can evacuate refugees to their native country. However, he says the fighting will resume if Zairian troops fail to respect the ceasefire. Battles between Tutsi rebels and Zairian troops flared last month, scattering more than one million refugees.
<hr>
<b>lt. Gov. Nazi</b><p>
Quebec's lieutenant governor has admitted to wearing a nazi symbol during the second world war. In the French news magazine l'actualite, Jean-louis Roux admits wearing swastikas during the war. He also participated in an anti-semitic demonstration in Montreal in 1942 in which the windows of stores with foreign-sounding names were smashed. But he's also quoted as saying that in France after the war, he could see the devastation "caused by nationalist ambitions" and changed his tune. A militant Quebec sovereignty group has sent a telegram to the Queen calling for Roux's dismissal.
<hr>
<b>Copps Flags</b><p>
Heritage minister Sheila Copps says her national flag giveaway will cost taxpayers far less than she first predicted. The government has delivered more than 683-thousand free flags since last February. Copps had expected the tab would be 23-million dollars, but now, it looks like it will come in eight-million under budget. Reform MPs have trashed the flag program as a waste of money, yet at least nine of them have called to get some.
<hr>
<b>Unity Cycle</b><p>
What have you done for your country lately, beside paying your taxes? A Hamilton man believes that each of us needs to do something to bring Canada closer together ... and he wants us to get it done before the turn of the century.<br> As Jamie West reports Mr. Intensity is planning to cycle where no one has cycled before...
<i><br>  Tthis was perhaps Canada's most passionate moment last year in Montreal on the eve of the Quebec Referendum ...<br>  An outpouring of Canadian unity ...<br>  A sign says this man, that Canadians can get fired up when push comes to shove...he should know.. he and his son were there ...<br>  Chris Roberston's gift is a 6,520 kilometre cycling journey called "To the Top Canada" launching March first...<br>  A similar ride is already underway by a man from Fort McMurray travelling across Canada, and their message as they stop in dozens of cities and towns will be similar.<br>  That every Canadian has their own unique gift and in response to the priviledge of living in Canada every Canadian should try to carry out their own personal good deed project to make Canada better than when we found it.<br>  By being the first person to cycle that far north... Robertson hopes to show Canadians that despite the challenges, they too can overcome ... and make Canada a better country .. <br>  For more information you can call Chris at (905) 387 0721. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Jackson Baby</b><p>
A British tabloid says Michael Jackson's nurse has conceived a baby boy by the rock star through artificial insemination.<br>   The "News of the World" says the child is due in February. It quotes Debbie Rowe as saying she's known Jackson for 15 years and is being paid 528-thousand dollars to have the baby. The newspaper also says the infant, shown on a scan to be a boy, will be named Michael Jackson Junior.
<hr>
<b>Box Office</b><p>
Moviegoers are in love with "William Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet."  The modern telling of the tragic love story was the weekend's number-one film. Industry sources say Romeo and Juliet sold an estimated 11.6-million dollars worth of tickets. "Sleepers" falls to number-two after two weeks on top. Jon Lovizt's "High School High" is third, followed by Bill Murray's pachyderm comedy, "Larger Than Life" and the killer lion adventure, "The Ghost and the Darkness."
<hr>
<b>Elvis Auction</b><p>
No blue suede shoes, but there was plenty of polyester on hand in Los Angeles at an auction of Elvis Presley items. The total take yesterday was just under a half-million dollars U.S. an opal and diamond ring brought more than 25-thousand dollars, while Elvis's "Thunderbird" stage cape sold for 50-thousand.
<hr>
<b>Sinatra Hospital</b><p>
Legendary entertainer Frank Sinatra isn't being released from the hospital, just yet.  He was admitted to Cedars Sinai Medical Centre in Los Angeles Friday for what was expected to be a weekend stay. But doctors yesterday decided to keep him in for a few more days. The 80-year-old star is being treated for a pinched nerve. A hospital spokesman says Sinatra is doing quite well -- but is uncomfortable because of the nerve. The hospital and Sinatra's publicist are denying a report he's being treated for pneumonia and possible heart trouble.


<P>
