<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 12/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, December 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Cities - Reaction
    <li>UI Stats            
    <li>Casino Niagara      
    <li>GM Layoffs St Kits  
    <li>Main St. Flood      
    <li>Bernardo Attacked   
    <li>Pot Bust            
    <li>Crack & Cash        
    <li>Sailing Death       
    <li>Grenade - Ancaster    
    <li>Massacre Vigil      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Cities - Reaction</b><p>
Halton Region will cease to exist, and Hamilton- Wentworth will become a supercity, if Ontario's influential "who does what" panel has its way. <br> The panel forwarded a series of recommendations on municipal government reform to the province today.
<br>  If adopted, GTA cities like Burlington would gain more local clout.<br>  But towns like Dundas and Flamborough would lose their battle against amalgamation.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br> As expected, the who does what panel suggests scrapping all five regional governments in the greater Toronto area, replacing them with a GTA board to co-ordinate services.  It's part of a stretegy to streamline local governments throughout Ontario.  <br>Suburban GTA municipalities like Burlington would gain power under the Crombie plan, a prospect that pleases the city's mayor.  <br>The Crombie panel also urges the province to move quickly on the Hamilton- Wentworth supercity proposal, a suggestion that puzzles supercity opponents.  They figure what's good for the GTA, is good for Hamilton- Wentworth.  </i>
<hr>
<b>UI  Stats</b><p>
 Job losses are expected as a result of this latest push to reform and streamline municipal government. And this latest push comes as unemployment creeps higher across Canada. According to November figures, it's up to 10 per cent now, the highest in three months.<br>  In Ontario, the jobless rate is up to 9.3 per cent.<br>  Hamilton, at 7.3 percent is still one of the lowest rates in the country and Niagara reports some improvement.
<hr>
<b>Casino Niagara</b><p>
It was hoped that what's being called Niagara Falls' second wonder would help stimulate the local economy.<br>  Casino Niagara is set to open its doors to the public on Monday.<br>  But the media was given a sneak preview today and it makes a storybook first impression.
<hr>
<b>GM Layoffs St Kits</b><p>
The news isn't good for 33 workers in Niagara.  They're GM in St. Catharines and they have one week left on the job. They will be laid off, December 15th; as the plant cuts production of its v-6 engines, and winds down its foundry operations. 88 more workers will will be laid off, March 1st.
<hr>
<b>Main St. Flood</b><p>
It's been a busy day on the job for regional workers in Hamilton. They've been investigating numerous complaints of flooding at homes and businesses in central Hamilton after a water main broke during this morning's rush hour. It sent water spewing for blocks.<br>  A road construction crew had been working nearby just before the break at Main and Grant Avenue.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Attacked</b><p>
Convicted sex-killer Paul Bernardo was attacked by another inmate at the Kingston Penitentiary today.<br> Corrections officials say it happened when Bernardo was being escorted back to his cell this morning after taking a shower.  Another inmate outside his cell stepped up and punched Bernardo in the face.  Bernardo suffered a cut on his cheek and a swollen eye.  The unidentified inmate has been placed in segregation.
<hr>
<b>Pot Bust</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth drug officers with help from the east end heat team and tips from Crime Stoppers have put an end to a budding marijuana growing operation.<br>  Late this afternoon our camera's were on hand to capture the arrest of one suspect as drug officers executed a search warrant on a farm house at 363 Mud Street near Tapleytown Road.<br>  Police found 50 marijuana seedlings with a street value of about 40-thousand dollars. Police say the operation was just getting started and that two suspects will be facing charges of cultivating marijuana for the purpose of trafficking and possesion of stolen property.<br>  Regional police have put an end to 62 hydroponic operations in the last year, that's up from about half a dozen five years ago...
<hr>
<b>Crack & Cash</b><p>
Police have seized more than 18-thousand dollars in cash and drugs after stopping a vehicle in east Hamilton. They found several small packages of cocaine and crack and 15-thousand dollars in cash after a subsequent search of a Stoney Creek home.<br> Charged with having proceeds of crime and possession of narcotics for trafficking is 31 year old Marijuan Vlasic of Stoney Creek.<br> 32 year old Jack Ring of Hamilton also charged with narcotics possession for trafficking.
<hr>
<b>Sailing Death</b><p>
The search has been called off the search for an 18 year old Fonthill resident, missing, and presumed drowned in a freak accident off the north coast of Australia.<br> Derek Zavitz was part of a student adventure program; and was sailing on board the Concordia, when the ship's battery exploded, and apparently threw him overboard. His body has not yet been recovered. A memorial service for Zavitz is planned for tomorrow, in Wainfleet.
<hr>
<b>Grenade - Ancaster</b><p>
It was a show and tell project he'll never forget. Nine year old Barron Thompson of Ancaster was on his way home when he pulled a hand-grenade from his back pack on board the school bus. A startled driver, who did not know that the grenade was inactive; stopped the bus, and evacuated the students. Police bomb squad officers moved in to take the device away. That left Thompson to explain to his father, how the souvenir he had picked up at a sportsman's show; had suddenly disappeared.
<hr>
<b>Massacre Vigil</b><p>
At this hour at Hamilton City Hall, and city hall's across the country, an annual vigil is underway to remember the 14 women gunned down by Marc Lepine at the Ecole Polytechnique in Montreal, seven years ago.  In Hamilton, the vigil marched from city hall to the YWCA on Macnab Street. Donations to Canada's National Day of Remembrance and Action on Violence Against Women go to help fund anti violence programs.





<P>
