<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 12/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, December 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Halton - G.T.A.     
    <li>Students - Fumes      
    <li>Pot House           
    <li>Christmas Ride      
    <li>Car Lease Language  
    <li>Chanakuh Light      
    <li>X-mas Trees Cut     
    <li>Troy Sing           
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Halton - G.T.A.</b><p>
The Ontario government's "who does what" panel is poised to release recommendations for sweeping changes in the way the province's municipalities are governed. <br>  Reports published today suggest the panel wants to create a greater Toronto area commission to deliver services now provided by regional governments.
<br>  But its recommendations will also affect municipalities well beyond the borders of the GTA.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>The "who does what" panel resurrects some of the recommendations of the Golden Report, endorsing the GTA-wide provision of services, and the elimination of overlapping layers of municipal government. But unlike Golden, the panel also looked at municipal government beyond the borders of the GTA.  <br>As a member of the "who does what" panel, Cooke won't comment on specific recommendations until they're released to the public.  <br>The chairman of Halton Region supports change, but only if it's change for the better.  <br>The mayor of Burlington wants more details before he comments on the recommendations. But Terry Cooke warns it's too late for Burlington to reconsider throwing its lot in with Hamilton- Wentworth.  <br>The recommendations of the "who does what" panel are just that.  It's up to the Ontario government to decide whether to accept them.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Students - Fumes</b><p>
Authorities still don't know the source of nauseating fumes at a Hamilton high school yesterday. Thirty students and staff at Sir Winston Churchill Secondary School were taken to hospital after being overcome. Dozens of people reported coughing, headaches, sore throats, nausea and burning eyes. The school was checked for natural gas but nothing unusual showed up.
<hr>
<b>Pot House</b><p>
Hamilton police have made an arrest after what began as a suspected house break-in at this Macallum Street house last summer.<br>  A neighbour had called after seeing two men run from the back of the house with two garbage bags.<br>  When police went inside to investigate, they found marijuana leaves spread out on a table and a hydroponic growing system with several marijuana plants in the basement.<br>  31 year old Matthew Gordon Kelly of hamilton now faces a string of narcotics charges.
<hr>
<b>Christmas Ride</b><p>
If you consider getting behind the wheel of a car after cosnuming too muc alcohol, beware: the annual holiday Ride program is underway.<br>  Ride lanes will be set up every day throughout the region to help reduce drinking and driving.<br>  Last holiday season, there were 33 collisions involving drunk drivers, including 2 fatalities.<br>  In the first week of Ontario's strict new driving suspensions for impaired driving, 4 people in Hamilton Wentworth have lost their licences for 90 days.<br>  Carol Redmond, whose husband was killed by a drunk driver 3 years ago, had a sobering message at the Ride kickoff this morning.
<hr>
<b>Car Lease Language</b><p>
The government is trying to take any mystery out of automobile leasing contracts.<br>  This morning Ontario consumer minister David Tsubouchi along with his federal counterpart and the Ontario Auto Dealers Association unveiled what is called the plain language auto lease agreement.<br>  A document that will tell consumers exactly where their money is going.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  Shopping for a new car can be an intimidating experience.<br>  Should they buy ..should they lease..what's it all going to cost ...<br>  Leasing started to become more popular as cars became more expensive.<br>  People couldn't deal with the sticker shock.<br>  The lower monthly payments were more palatable..<br>  But with leasing had its problems.<br>   People knew what their monthly payment was.<br>  But often weren't told what the residual value of the vehicle would be. <br>  But there should be no surprises now.<br>  Effective January 1st 1997 car dealers will be required to fully disclose what a vehicle costs a consumer.<br>  Taxes, mileage, down payments, responsibilities. <br>  Every thing will be laid on the line.<br>  Now dealers won't be able to simply tell customers what they want to hear.<br>  They'll have to put everything down on paper.</i>
<hr>
<b>Chanakuh Light</b><p>
Sundown tonight marked the beginning of chanuka, the annual festival of lights on the Jewish calendar. In a ceremony this afternoon at Hamilton City Hall the first chanuka candle was lit by children of the Hamilton Hebrew Academy. The festival lasts eight days and commemmorates the Hebrew victory over Syrians more than two thousand years ago but with only enough sacred oil to light the menorah in the temple for one day. Thanks to the miracle of the lights, however the oil lasted eight days and that is why today the menorah is lit candle by candle each night of chanuka.
<hr>
<b>X-mas Trees Cut</b><p>
It's no longer a question of fake or real, with a trend toward more nostalgic yuletides past, it's also parking lot or cut-your-own. <br>    With twenty days left until christmas, we sent Matt Hayes out to the wilds of Lynden in search of that perfect christmas tree.
<i><br>  Hubert will knows what he's doing he's been growing Christmas trees since 1966.  Will specializes in white spruce ...the only seasonal tree that is native to Ontario.  It takes 8 years and a lot of tender loving care to bring these trees to maturity.  There are plenty to choose from at his Lynden based farm and will believes more people are choosing real over artficial.<br>  Cut your own is meant to be a complete family Christmas experience.  Being a media man on the move I had to hurry things along. Nothing like a little fresh country air and some exercise the next three weeks are crucial at the Will farm and others like it. I proved to be an inspiration to Hubert will and his family ...an example of what cut your own is really all about.<br>  Now that we have the tree a few simple instructions from the expert.<br>  That's our day on the farm we leave with a reasonably priced tree of 16 dollars a great family experince and only a slight back ache.  What do you expect from a city boy. </i>
<hr>
<b>Troy Sing</b><p>
Finally tonight, it's become a modern-day Christmas tradition in the community of Troy, northeast of Brantford. <br>   And now every year at this time, big city meets small town when some divine inspiration from Toronto, comes to town. Alex Reynolds reports.
<i> <br>  Four years ago, the Grant African Methodist Episcopal Church Choristers were invited to celebrate the restoration of Troy's 19th century United Church. <br>  The congregation's upbeat response to that spring concert sparked the annual yule visit.<br>  An innovation for this fourth anniversary sing ....a choir-within- a-choir. <br>  With seven "witness" members composing original material, the concert choir has a life of its own, blending contemporary with traditional spirituals and gospel. <br>  Troy Church will be filled with joyful sounds Friday and Saturday...as "Witness" presents three concerts.<br>  </i>





<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

