<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 12/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, December 4, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Students - Fumes      
    <li>Six Nations School  
    <li>Oakwood School      
    <li>Crime Paralyzed     
    <li>Bryden - Y.O.A.     
    <li>Workfare            
    <li>CUPW - Copps        
    <li>Lake Erie Mill         
    <li>Hamilton Booze      
    <li>Ancaster Toy Drive  
    <li>Stolen Cop Car      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Students - Fumes</b><p>
Emergency officials are scratching their heads tonight over something in the air at a Hamilton high school.
<br>  32 students and staff members at Sir Winston Churchill were taken to various hospitals over the noon hour after they were overcome by something unidentifiable.<br>  Whatever it was it had the greatest effect on staff and students near the main office before spreading to the second and third floors.<br>  The principal of the school says the substance was odorless and tasteless.<br>  900 students had to be evacuated for about an hour before the unknown substance dissipated. <br>    
<hr>
<b>Six Nations School</b><p>
The federal Department of Indian Affairs is being asked to re-assign an Ohsweken teacher.<br>  Parents say the non-native teacher is physically and emotionally abusing her elementary students and they want her gone.<br>  And, as Dwight Ryan reports, they have blockaded the school to get their point across.
<i><br>  Its a question of culture according to these parents of students at I.L. Yhomas School in Ohsweken. <br>  And they're seeking support for their cause by circulating a petition.<br>  For five days now they have blocked the entrance to the Cayuga Language Immersion School.<br>  As a result, the school has been closed.<br>  At issue a teacher who the parents say not only grabbed a child so violently that she suffered bruises, but also ejected two youngsters for speaking their native language.   <br>    Once all councillors have signed the resolution, it will be forwarded to the federal department of indian affairs. Chief Wellington Staats believes they'll act on it.  <br>      Parents meanwhile are prepared to let the school open, but only if the teacher is re-assigned.   <br>      A decision from Indian Affairs is expected Thursday.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Oakwood School</b><p>
And an inner city Oakville school slated for possbile closure by the Halton Board of Education is fighting back.<br> Students from kindergarten to grade five at the small school staged an assembly this morning to let trustees know how much they need Oakwood to stay open.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  The principal at Oakwood Public School in Oakville feels the small number of students, only 189, may be a reason it's been slated for closure by the Halton Region Board of Education.  <br>  Surrounded by apartment complexes, it's as close as you can get to an inner city school in Oakville.<br>  If it's closed, Oakwoods kindergarten to grade five students would have to be bussed to the next closest schools.<br>  The chair of Oakwood's council feels that would unfairly split up a very unique school community.  <br>  The students themselves wanted to hold this assembly, showing school trustees why they'd like to stay together as a learning group.<br>  Under the pressure of provincial cutbacks, the Halton Board of Education is expected to announce the fate of Oakwood on December 19th.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Crime Paralyzed</b><p>
Two teens including one who allegedly fired the gun that paralyzed a Dundas convenience store clerk appeared in Hamilton court today.<br> The pair were part of group of four who held up Farah's Food Mart last August.<br> Charges of attempted murder were laid against the guy who police believe fired the gun.<br> The violence charges were automatically transferred to adult court but the accused is appealing to have the case returned to youth court.<br> That hearing is set for January 23rd.<br> Meanwhile a 15 year old involved in the botched robbery has been sentenced to 18 months in custody.<br> The victim, Khaled Mujber remains in a rehab hospital paralyzed below the waist with limited used of his arms.
<hr>
<b>Bryden - Y.O.A.</b><p>
Meanwhile, Hamilton Wentworth MP John Bryden presented a petition to parliament today demanding changes to the Young Offenders Act.<br>  The petition was signed by 22 thousand canadians.<br>  The public has been screaming for the politicians to hand stiffer sentences to teenage violent offenders.
<hr>
<b>Workfare</b><p>
If the province approves it, Hamilton- Wentworth's Workfare program could be up and running by the middle of next month.<br>  Initially, only new welfare applicants will have to sign up for workfare.<br>  Another six-thousand people who are already collecting benefits will be gradually phased into the program.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br> Only a handful of Hamilton- Wentworth regional councillors object to the workfare program adopted by council this week.  <br>Anyone who's eligible, and refuses to participate in workfare, can have their benefits cut off.  <br>For the first four months, recipients have to conduct a job search.  After that, they'll have three options... register with a job placement agency, sign up for a retraining program, or work for a non-profit group as a volunteer. That's something many welfare recipients are already doing.  <br>Schuster says the workfare program won't cost Hamilton- Wentworth region a cent, and it's expected to produce a five per cent drop in the welfare caseload by next year.  </i>
<hr>
<b>CUPW - Copps</b><p>
A group of angry postal employees occupied Hamilton East MP Sheila Copps' office this afternoon.<br>  The group is upset over the government's decision to get out of the unaddressed admail business.<br>  Ten thousand people deliver admail across the country.<br>  Their jobs will be terminated by the end of the year.
<hr>
<b>Lake Erie Mill</b><p>
A major power failure at its shot strip mill has forced a shutdown at Stelco's Lake Erie Works.  The roughing mill will be closed for 11 days.  An electrical problem  with a six-thousand horsepower drive motor is to blame.  Stelco says it hopes any losses will be partially offset by insurance.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Booze</b><p>
 Hamilton- Wenworth regional council has decided residents here should not be able to stock up on Christmas spirit over the next three Sundays. <br>  That's the kind you find in a bottle.  This is the latest in a growing list of regions to say thanks but no thanks to the LCBO offer. Ian Dovey reports.                              
<I><br>  31 LCBO and beer stores in Hamilton Wentworth will not be open on the three Sunday's leading up to Christmas and New Years.<br>  By a vote of 16 to ten regional councillors overturned a recommendation to accept the Sunday openings.<br>  On the issue of drinking and driving councillor Frank D'Amico won the support of council. <br>    But it was opposed for other reasons. <br>    The LCBO loses 750 million dollars a year from contraband booze and for that reason other councillors supported the Sunday openings. <br>     </I>
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Toy Drive</b><p>
Ancaster firefighters will be giving Santa a boost this Saturday with their annual toy drive. <br> Toys or cash will be accepted on behalf of the Neighbour to Neighbour program.  Just look for the fire trucks at the Zehrs Walmart and K-Mart parking lots in Ancaster between 10am and 2pm.  Last year the firefighters collected more than 600 toys and three thousand dollars during their one day campaign.
<hr>
<b>Stolen Cop Car</b><p>
Finally tonight, one of those embarassing moments for Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police overnight.<br> Someone snuck into a parking lot full of cruisers at the central station and stole one ....the unmarked vehicle was found abandoned this morning on Lake Avenue North in Hamilton... with the front seats burned, the door locks broken and the ignition punched out.<br> The car is an administrative vehicle used for police training.<br> Police are still investigating.





