<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 29, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Fire - Homeless       
    <li>Canal Body          
    <li>Vanscoy Deal Nixed  
    <li>Grey Cup Survey     
    <li>Flamboro Merger     
    <li>Liberals - Hamilton   
    <li>McNichol Park       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Fire - Homeless</b><p>
Less than a month before Christmas, 13 people find themselves homeless tonight after their Thorold apartment building was gutted by fire. <br> One man was rushed to hospital suffering smoke inhalation.
<br>   And a number of cats and one dog were killed in the blaze.<br> Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  The emergency call came in about 6:30 this morning.<br>  When firefighters arrived on the scene thick smoke and flames were pouring from the upper floor of a the building at 4 Ormond Street South.<br>  An apartment building that has 11 units.<br>  Everybody inside was led out safely thanks in part to two passersby who started banging on apartment doors. <br>  It was difficult blaze to put out. <br>  Some residents escaped with little more than a beer bottle in their hand. <br>  This afternoon John Daley had to start rebuilding his life piece by piece with the help of social service agencies. <br>  John and the other tenants are collecting clothes. odds and ends.<br>  Now they have to search for another roof to put over their heads.<br>  The relief effort is being organized at Thorold City Hall.<br>  Any items you would like to donate to the fire victims can be dropped off at Thorold City Hall on Carleton Street or at the Thorold Community Cares office in the basement of City hall. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Canal Body</b><p>
Police have now identified the body of a woman pulled from the Welland Canal in St. Catharines, yesterday. 46 year old Elita Johnson died, when her car left the road and plunged into the frigid waters just after one o'clock yesterday. Witnesses say they could hear the woman screaming, but could only watch helplessly as the car quickly sank in the canal. It took St. Lawrence Seaway divers 20 minutes to find the victim, and pull her from the car. Attempts to revive her in hospital, were futile. An autopsy will be conducted, today.
<hr>
<b>Vanscoy Deal Nixed</b><p>
The deal with the devil part two may be dead. Karen Vanscoy, the mother of a teen shot dead last September has won a review of a plea-bargain agreement with the young man accused of killing her daughter.  The 17-year-old's court appearance scheduled for monday has been postponed. Mrs. vanscoy had protested to the crown after learning of a possible plea reduction to manslaughter with the recommendation of a two-year sentence.  She had compared that to the so-called deal with the devil that saw Karla Homolka sentenced for manslaughter in the deaths of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy in exchange for testifying against her ex-husband Paul Bernardo.
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup Survey</b><p>
The official numbers aren't in yet on the Grey Cup festivities of last week, but as Jamie West reports... an unofficial survey conducted by some area high school students reveals that most revellers dropped their cash between James and Bay Streets...
<i><br>  Bob O'Conner turned the Grey Cup into a class project...<br>  He was the guy in the 1929 football helmet partying with the westerners...<br>  Bob's class of grade 12 travel and tourism students  surveyed hundreds of participants and local businesses.<br> Their figures show that most partiers were male, university educated, 26-40 years old and earned an average of 60-thousand dollars a year.<br>  Most spent about 200 bucks on food...mostly the fast variety. And about 350 dollars on booze.<br>  Many registers in Jackson Square just didn't ring up massive sales ...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Flamboro Merger</b><p>
The mayor of Flamborough, Ted McMeekin wants to renegotiate the deal struck to turn Hamilton- Wentworth into a super city. His comments came at a public forum in Rockton last night.  Reporter Ian Dovey was there.
<i><br>  There have been few issues that have sparked the public's attention as the proposed supercity concept in Hamilton Wentworth.<br>  Mayor Ted McMeekin says it's time to reneogiate. <br>    A supercity that includes Flamborough is a sensitive issue for residents here, but still people came out to this public meeting to voice their distaste. <br>    The meeting also attracted this councillor from Dundas, a community that also opposes a megacity. <br>    A citizens group has started a petition against the supercity.<br>  Organizers hope the signatures end up on municipal affairs minister Al Leaches desk. <br>    </i>
<hr>
<b>Liberals - Hamilton</b><p>
Ontario Liberals are hoping to restructure their party's fortunes with the election of a new leader this weekend. 
<hr>
<b>McNichol Park</b><p>
The "Friends of McNichol Park" in Burlington have won a land mark court decision against the city of Burlington. A panel of three judges has ruled that the city violated its own zoning by-law when it issued a building permit for the construction of Wellness House... a facility for the aged... on part of the park.





<P>
