<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 28, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Canal Body          
    <li>Murder Charge       
    <li>"Gun" Incident      
    <li>Scarf Bandit        
    <li>St. Liz Villa 7     
    <li>Bell Cancer         
    <li>Our Place Newser    
    <li>Ancaster / Broadway   
    <li>Santa Letters       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>canal body</b><p>
Police in St. Catharines are investigating the death of a woman whose car plunged into the Welland Canal this afternoon.
<br> The accident happened on Government Road near Lock Two in the city's north end.  Witnesses say they watched helplessly as the Dodge Neon drove into the water.<br> The woman was rushed to hospital after having been in the water for up to 25-minutes.<br> But she apparently drowned before rescuers could reach her.<br> Police are not sure why the car left the road although there was some light snow on the road at the time.  The victims's identity has not been released.
<hr>
<b>Murder Charge</b><p>
There's been an arrest in connection with a shooting death earlier this month in Fort Erie.<br> The body of Fred Grondin was found lying beside a van on the shoulder of Highway 3 November 7th.<br> Niagara police have charged 30-year-old Patrick O'Connor of Fort Erie with first degree murder.<br> He is to appear in a St. Catharines court Friday morning.
<hr>
<b>"Gun" Incident</b><p>
A dramatic scene on the west Hamilton mountain over the noon hour, after a passerby spotted three males with what appeared to be a handgun enter the Westcliffe Mall. <br> Police responded within minutes and took the trio into custody after they emerged from the mall and got into a car. They found a gun in a gym bag. But it later turned out the gun, complete with an authentic-looking clip, was just a toy.  The three were subsequently released.  Police say they were following normal procedure when investigating a suspicious incident. Four youths are being sought after a robbery in the area over the weekend.
<hr>
<b>Scarf Bandit</b><p>
Police in Hamilton believe they may have nabbed the "scarf bandit".<br> Over the past few weeks, several stores and submarine shops on Hamilton mountain have been robbed by a suspect wearing a scarf across his face.<br> Yesterday, police arrested a suspect after a Bargain Shop on Fennell Avenue was robbed by a man wearing a scarf and matching the description from similar robberies.<br> 21 year old Kurt Gray of Hamilton is charged with robbery in the Bargain Shop hit.<br> Police are continuing their investigation.
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Villa 7</b><p>
The Hamilton Region's medical officer of health is set to meet with legal officials concerning allegations of poor treatment of the residents of St. Elizabeth Villa.<br>  Testimony this week at an inquest into five deaths at the villa deserves further attention according to Sr. Marilyn James.<br>  And, as Dwight Ryan reports, Dr. James told jury members today that St. Elizabeth Villa should never have been licensed in the first place.  <br>  <I>          <br> Dr. Marilyn James says St. Elizabeth Villa is licensed to operate as a second level lodging home, but is functioning poorly as an unlicensed nursing home. <br> The region's medical officer of health told jury members at the inquest into five deaths at the villa, that the facility should never have been licensed in the first place. <br> An investigation by the Hamilton Wentworth Regional Health Department showed that nearly half of the villa's residents required care greater than that of a lodging home.<br>  But, the villa's staff had neither the training nor the supervision required for such care.<br>  The regions chief doctor told jury members that the St. Elizabeth Villa in 1994 had a mortality rate of more than 27 percent. Suggesting that one's chance of dying was more than one in four and that the villa was not a place to go and live.<br>  She added residents of palliative care units have a greater chance of surviving.<br>  Pushed by the villa's lawyer Christopher Ashby, Dr. James held her ground saying something was going on in 1994 at St. Elizabeth Villa that was knocking them off.<br>  She admitted frustration saying lodging homes in Hamilton are subject to a city bylaw..a bylaw that in turn is enforced by the region.<br>  Dr. James believes the residents of lodging homes deserve better treatment and should be covered province-wide by Ontario legislation.<br>  Queen's Park is expected to be watching this inquest carefully with the jury's recommendations having province-wide implications.<br> </I>
<hr>
<b>Bell Cancer</b><p>
That high rate of cancer among workers at a Bell Canada office in Hamilton is apparently just coincidence.<br> Dr. Gilles Theriault, an epidemiologist at McGill University in Montreal, says further testing would be useless.<br> Eight cases of cancer have been confirmed among 50 workers on one floor of the Bell Canada Centre, including five breast cancers.<br> In September, the workers moved from the third floor to the seventh.<br> Tests of air quality, electromagnetic and radiation emissions were done, but nothing unusual was found.<br> Bell Canada is setting up a cancer surveillance program for workers who were on the third floor.
<hr>
<b>Our Place Newser</b><p>
The sign outside "Our Place Tavern" on Beach Road says come party with us.<br> But nobody came to the Grey Cup party, not even the regulars.<br> Everyone, it seems partied downtown and at the beer gardens near Ivor Wynne Stadium on game day leaving many east end taverns owners fuming.
<hr>
<b>Ancaster / Broadway</b><p>
The Ancaster Arts Council goes broadway once again with its fourth annual community musical. "The Magic of Broadway," with a cast of over 60, taps into the blockbuster shows "Phantom".."Evita" ..Les Miz"."Guys and Solls" ....and "West Side Story" among others. Proceeds from ticket sales are donated to community programs. "The Magic of Broadway" runs tonight through Saturday at the Ancaster High School auditorium.
<hr>
<b>Santa Letters</b><p>
Canada Post opened its doors to students from Regina Mundi School today. The grade 2 students hand delivered thier Santa mail to the Stoney Creek processing plant. The highlight of the trip was an opportunity to speak to the big guy himself in a special conference call from the North Pole.  These kids had plenty on their minds.   If you have a letter to Santa adress it to Santa Claus, North Pole, H0H 0H0. Don't forget to include a return address and postal code.





<P>
