<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 27, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Health Workers      
    <li>St. Liz Inquest 6   
    <li>Vanscoy Plea        
    <li>Mountain Robber     
    <li>Supercity 
    <li>Motts Boycott       
    <li>Opera Hamilton      
    <li>Decew Stone         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Health Workers</b><p>
Some 4000 CUPE employees in the Hamilton Wentworth healthcare system commenced a job action today.  They want you to know who they are ...and how important they are to the quality of your healthcare..
<br> As Jamie West reports...the so called "invisible" hospital workers want a fair shake ...
<i><br>  If these specific people weren't here to prepare your in hospital meal would it affect your healthcare ...the Canadian Union of Public Employees, thinks so...<br>  They've just launched a public information campaign called "The Faces of Health Care" to make people aware of the 4000 invisible faces in Hamilton healthcare...<br> Employees like housekeepers, food service people, registered practical nurses.<br> Some of whom are being replaced by private companies ..<br>  They earn an average of 26-thousand dollars a year.<br>  And find it absurd that they should have to take an 18 percent cut ...while doctors are sneezing at a 7 percent hike.<br>  And they're not against taking their message fully to the streets...<br>  Union leader Sid Ryan says two more days of action protests are on the books ...<br>  Sudbury in February...<br>  Thunder Bay in April...<br>  Both cities have seen the government force closure of hospitals.<br>  </i>
<br>  there's no official word on when any layoffs might take effect, but it's possible that notices could be sent out early in the new year.
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Inquest 6</b><p>
A coroner's jury heard today that a resident of St. Elizabeth Villa jumped to his death from an upper floor window.<br>  But, when his body was discovered, police weren't even called.<br>  Dwight Ryan is covering the inquest and has this report..  <br>  
<i><br>  Members of the jury had a first hand look at St. Elizabeth Villa ..touring the facility they have heard so much about in recent weeks.<br>  The coroner's inquest is investigating five deaths at the villa..five of more than forty in just over a year.  <br>  Earlier in the day jury members heard dramatic testimony about the suicide of an elderly villa resident not long ago.  The man's crumpled body was found outside the building shortly after ten o'clock in the evening. <br>  RNA Sherry Farrell said Sister Maria was flustered and asked her to call a doctor.  Armed with a flashlight the sister and Farrell saw that the man, surrounded by blood, was obviously dead.<br>  Further investigation showed that he had removed his screen and jumped from an upper floor window.<br>   It was the doctor who called the coroner and police.  Later the angry officer said if anything like that happened again, to call 911 immediately.<br>  The suicide story was just one of many that put the villa's management in a bad light.<br>  Former health care aide Linda Connoly told coroner Bill Lucas and jury members that she was repeatedly yelled at by Sister Maria.  It was her way or not at all.<br>  She detailed instances of sour milk being sent to the residents and fresh cereal poured over stale cereal.  Damp sheets being returned from the laundry. Improvising when supplies such as bed pads and diapers weren't available. <br>  When the investigation into St. Elizabeth Villa began, staff members were asked to write letters to the Medical Officer of Health defending the facility.<br>  Linda Connoly refused.  A couple of weeks later she quit.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Vanscoy Plea</b><p>
The deal with the devil, part 2?  That's how a St. Catharines woman describes a possible plea bargain deal between the crown and her daughter's accused killer.<br> Karen Vascoy, 14-year-old daughter Jasmine was shot in the head with a stolen gun in her home in September, has learned that the 17-year-old charged with second degree murder would plead guilty to a lesser charge of manslaughter.<br> She's sent a letter of protest to crown attorney Ray Houlahan.<br> Both Houlahan and the accused's lawyer George Walker were party to the original so-called deal with the devil, which saw Karla Homolka testify against her ex-husband Paul Bernardo in the murders of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy.
<hr>
<b>Mountain Robber</b><p>
Seems there could be a busy robber at work on Hamilton mountain these days.<br> His latest hit ... the Biway store on Concession Street.<br> He tried, unsuccessfully, to hold up the store yesterday, then bolted from his getaway cab after hearing his description broadcast on the taxi's radio.<br> Police looking for a black male in his mid-20's about 5-6 or 5-8, weighing 180 pounds.<br> They suspect he may be responsible for string of robberies at stores and sub shops in the area.
<hr>
<b>Supercity</b><p>
It's been 23 years so what difference will a few more days make? That was the issue at Hamilton city council last night as they decided not to decide just yet on restructuring Hamilton- Wentworth Region into a super city. Deborah Walker reports.                     
<i> <br>Several members of Hamilton city council came to the meeting ready to vote, especially because municipal jobs are on the line.  Even some who oppose the plan, are anxious to get on with the vote.  <br>In the end, council voted to delay the final vote for two more weeks.</i>
<br>
The Hamilton city council tally now stands at nine for and 8 against the supercity plan. That's not expected to change.
<hr>
<b>Motts Boycott</b><p>
The United Food and Commercial Workers union wants you to hold the Clamato juice next time you make a caesar.<br> While the label boasts the drink is "Canada's original" tomato-clam cocktail, the union says that hasn't stopped Mott's from shifting production to the U.S. and now it's calling for a consumer boycott.<br> The Mott's move south wipes out 165 jobs at the company's plant in St. Catharines.<br> Mott's says it was forced to make the move to remain competitive.
<hr>
<b>Opera Hamilton</b><p>
Internationally acclaimed baritone Allan Monk is back on stage at Hamilton Place this week.<br> The Calgary native, a regular with the Metropolitan Opera for thirty years,  is performing in the Opera Hamilton production of Mozart's "Cosi Fan Tutte."         <br>  Performances of "Cosi Fan Tutte" continue Thursday and Saturday at Hamilton Place.
<hr>
<b>Decew Stone</b><p>
And finally tonight, restorers of this century old flour mill in St. Catharines are giving vistors a chance to taste a bit of history.<br> The friends of the Morning Star Mill have four hundred pounds of stone-ground flour to give away.<br> They'll open the mill, which is on Decew Road, on Saturday from two until four.<br> Make sure you bring your own container.<br> The Morning Star Mill is the only water-powered mill in the Niagra region. It was built in 1872 and restored just a few years ago.





<P>
