<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 26, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>St. Liz Inquest 5   
    <li>Pool Fight          
    <li>Karla Parole        
    <li>Supercity Forum 
    <li>Pelham Herald       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Train Dismantled    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>st. liz inquest 5</b><p>
Dining room food routinely recylced and mouldy juice bottles often refilled. Dramatic testimony today at the coroner's inquest into the deaths of five people at a Hamilton home for seniors. It came from a former employee of St. Elizabeth Villa.

<br>   Dwight Ryan was at the inquest and has this report.  <br>  
<i><br>  Letitia Jones worked as a health care aide at St. Elizabeth Villa for three years.<br>     During that time, she testified she repeatedlay witnessed incidents of poor patient care.<br>  She told the jury that Sister Elizabeth often refilled milk bags from a bottle.  And that on one occasion curdled milk was served on porridge.  Health care aides refused to serve it to the residents and gave them toast instead.<br>   She said orange juice bottles with black around the edges and mould inside would be refilled.<br>  Soup bowls from the dining room would routinely be emptied back into the pot.<br>   Jones went on to say that Sister Elizabeth mixed mashed potatoes with her bare hands.   And that Louis, a resident who helped in the kitchen would peel carrots, potatoes and onions with his bare hands, despite having an infected finger. <br>  Inquest counsel Angela Paparella asked Letitia Jones if she had ever spoken to Sister Elizabeth about the incidents.  No, she replied, I was scared of her, she yelled at me a couple of times. <br>  In earlier testimony, registered practical nurse Debbie Smith told jury members that Sister Elizabeth had scolded her for calling an ambulance after an elderly woman had fallen and injured her back.<br>  RPN's weren't to call for help without following the correct protocol.<br>  Smith however returned to St. Elizabeth Villa after working in Mississauga for a month.  When the probe into allegations of poor care began, Smith wrote to medical officer of health and the media defending the villa.<br>  Jury members will tour St. Elizabeth Villa Wednesday afternoon.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Pool Fight</b><p>
A brawl at a downtown Hamilton bar has cost a 29 year old hamilton man his sight.<br>  Police say a fight broke out at the Artizan Diner between four men betting on a pool game.<br>  The 29 year old was robbed and had his eye stabbed with a beer bottle, and a 35 year old Hamilton man received bumps and bruises to his head after being hit with a pool ball.<br>  21 year old Joseph Edward Campbell and 21 year old Christopher William Boylan, both of Hamilton, face a number of charges tonight in that attack.
<hr>
<b>Karla Parole</b><p>
Karla Homolka doesn't appear anxious to get out of jail. She's eligible for day parole on January 6th, but   parole board officials say they haven't heard from her yet. If she does approach them, it would be at least five months before her application would come up for a hearing.<br>  Homolka is serving a 12-year sentence in Kingston's prison for women for her role in the murders of Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy. By July 6th, she will have completed one third of her manslaughter sentence and will be automatically eligible for full parole and an automatic parole board hearing, unless she waives her right to the hearing.
<hr>
<b>Supercity Forum </b><p>
The first attempt to engage the citizens of Hamilton in a public debate on the supercity proposal failed to draw a significant turnout last night.  As a result, when Hamilton city council meets in two hours from now, it's expected to defer a final vote on political restructuring in Hamilton- Wentworth. 
<hr>
<b>Pelham Herald</b><p>
It's not big government they're battling in Pelham, but big business. A piece of history will be lost when the Pelham Herald Weekly newspaper closes it's doors December 31st.<br>  The shutdown is being called another casualty of the Conrad Black push for profits.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  For forty years the Pelham Herald has been keeping the residents of Fonthill and surrounding area informed on what is happening in their community.<br>  Flipping through the pages of the archives stored in the basement reporter Carolyn Mullin readily recognizes familiar faces.<br>  Publisher Martha Cepuch has called the Herald home for 17 years.<br>  Once it closes its doors she feels the community will lose part of its voice.<br>  And another paper has been positioning itself to takeover the Pelham market.<br>  The Welland Tribune which is owned by Conrad Black is not a union shop. <br>  The Pelham Herald which is owned by Southam and controlled by Conrad Black is a union shop.<br>  And even though the Herald is a profitable weekly the union feels this is another case of Black trying to flee the union. <br>  Dave Hall started this paper 40 years ago.  And he was shocked when he learned that the familiar storefront office will be closed. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stocks climb to new record highs today.<br>  Bank of Montreal reports a record profit of more than a billion dollars in 1996.<br>  Atomic Energy of Canada signs a 4-billion dollar contract to build two nuclear reactors in China.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Train Dismantled</b><p>
You might call it an underground railway. Located in the basement of the Delta Bingo Hall the Bay City Railway is about to go off track.  The location will soon be a grocery store and as quick as you can say bingo Bay City is being derailed.  More from Matt Hayes.
<i><br>  Delta area residents are happy.  In the new year they'll have a neighbourhood grocery store at this location for the first time in about 20 years. The Delta Bingo is moving up town to the old Kresge's building pending approval from the city and the Ontario Gaming Commission.<br>  They're also happy.  As for the Bay City Railway ...they're about to be derailed.  The Model Engineer Society has called the basement of the current Delta Bingo home for the last 16 years but they're world of miniatures is coming to an end.<br>  Its taken years to create this kind of detail.  And there was more in construction...<br>  Now they're talking demolition.<br>  A new 4000 square foot location is being sought...but that won't prevent the passion for this 22 member club from grinding to a halt.   An open house during Christmas week will provide the last run for this rail community.  After that the trains come off the tracks. Despite the setbacks the club has lasted 48 years. And somewhere the Bay City Railway will roll again. </i>





<P>
