<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 25, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Grey Cup Follow      
    <li>Cup Finances        
    <li>Munitions Fire      
    <li>Mounties - Deaths     
    <li>Bus Passes Refund   
    <li>New Saltfleet High  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup Follow</b><p>
What a morning after. The showdown in steeltown is now history.<br>    What some feel will be the last ever Grey Cup is being hailed as an extraordinary success by just about everyone involved.<br>  Tens of thousands of people travelled to Hamilton for the CFL championship and left the steel city with nothing but good things to say about their hosts.<br>  Dwight Ryan has the story.. <br>  
<i><br>  The showdown in steeltown will go down as one of the best Grey Cups ever.<br>  Spectacular football.. <br>  And spectacular hospitality.. <br>  Hamilton was at its best hosting guests from one end of the country to the other.   <br>    Rooms at the Royal Connaught Hotel were booked solid almost a year ago.<br>    The situation was similar at the downtown Sheraton and the Ramada Inn.  <br>  And despite the partying, just one twelve-hour suspension from nine thousand ride checks  <br>  And now the massive task of dismantling the 1996 Grey Cup is underway.   <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cup Finances</b><p>
While the clean-up continues, the counting begins.<br>  There's no question the turn-out was huge, both for the game and the four day festival.<br>  But was it enough for Hamilton's Grey Cup organizers to turn a profit?<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>One day after the game, Grey Cup merchandise is selling at bargain prices.  And after week's of frantic activity, all's quiet in the Grey Cup office.  Time to clear up lose ends...and trade a few momentoes.  <br>The first chunk of Grey Cup profits will go to the CFL. Anything left will help pay off the five-million dollar municipal loan.  And even if the City of Hamilton were to lose a few hundred-thousand dollars, it won't worry mayor Bob Morrow.  <br>If profits exceed the five-million dollar investment, the money will be split between the city and the region.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Munitions Fire</b><p>
Firefighters are still on the scene of a stubborn apartment house blaze in Port Colborne.<br>  The fire at the Fraser Street home is believed to have started when two men put a smoldering couch up against the house.<br>  There are unconfirmed reports that there is a quantity of weapons and ammunition inside the building.<br>  There are no injuries.<br>  The blaze is still under investigation.
<hr>
<b>Mounties - Deaths</b><p>
The RCMP has been called in to investigate two boating deaths on the Upper Niagara River last week.<br>  Police discovered bags of liquor and cigarettes when the boat and one of the bodies were found.<br>   They want the Mounties to find out whether the goods had anything to do with the boating accident.<br>   The body of 66-year-old Baron Sciortino of Niagara Falls was pulled from the water last Friday. Fifteen-year-old Terry Baxter of St. Catharines is missing and presumed drowned.
<hr>
<b>Bus Passes Refund</b><p>
Hamilton Street Railway is giving a 26-dollar credit toward adult bus passes for December to those holding November bus passes. That's to make up for the week during which busses did not run due to a strike. Special monthly pass holders will receive a 19-dollar credit. In both cases, though, you'll have to hand in your November pass when you buy December's. If you're not going to buy a December pass, you can use November's up until december sixth.
<hr>
<b>New Saltfleet High</b><p>
Stoney Creek has a new jewel in its crown tonight. A brand new 20 million dollar high school. It's the new Saltfleet District Secondary School and it was officially opened at 4 o'clock this afternoon. It's a 21st centruy place of learning complete with classrooms equipped to handle computers and it's the only high school in Canada with an astronomy observatory. No telescope yet ...that's all part of a major fundraiser.  The new Saltfleet on Highland Road West was designed to accommodate a growing population on the mountain and replaces the old Saltfleet High located on Grays Road.  It has an enrollment of 11-hundred students.





<P>
