<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 22, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Cup Ticket Sales    
    <li>East vs. West       
    <li>H.S.R. Vote         
    <li>Cops Cup            
    <li>Road Closure        
    <li>Meningitis Shots    
    <li>Niagara Boaters     
    <li>Missing Person      
    <li>St. Joes Layoffs    
    <li>Parade Map          
    <li>Game Map            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Cup Ticket Sales</b><p>
In just over 48 hours from now, the Edmonton Eskimoes and the Toronto Argonauts will meet at Ivor Wynne Stadium. And it's all about this: the Grey Cup.  Normally living a quiet existance inside the football Hall of Fame a few blocks away, it's been enjoying a busy social life lately.
<br>Is it the league? Is it the price? Or is it just the procrastination of Argo fans in southern Ontario? No one knows for sure; but a full 20 percent of the seats in the stands ... are still open for fans looking for tickets to Grey Cup '96. Scot Urquhart has that story:
<i><br>  In fact, there are thousands of seats going begging for the big game, less than 48 hours from kickoff. How many seats? <br>  Eight thousand tickets were left unsold ... when George McGow went to get his tickets ... was he surprised? <br>  But eight thousand empty seats for the national championship? That would be an embarrassing flop: <br>  And that's what the Grey Cup committee is hoping for too: <br>  But in Gretzky's bar in Toronto, that excitement is not enough to compensate ... for a ticket price that exceeds a hundred dollars:  <br>  These from Ottawa however, are apparently a heartier, well-heeled bunch: <br>  But is that event enough to sell the Canadian game, or have fans given up? <br>  But will that confidence be borne out, by the fans, in the stands? <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>East vs. West</b><p>
A quieter start to Grey Cup festivities in downtown Hamilton today.<br>  But once last night's cobwebs were cleared round two got rolling.<br>  As Jamie West reports word on the street is that when it comes to partying the west is the best...
<i><br> Ah the formality and majesty of the pipes...a sound you'd almost expect to connect to the slightly more subdued eastern fan...<br>  But this...this is definitely the west...party pros at their best...<br>  Western party animals are taking over...<br>  And another thing... what is it about guys in fur coats...<br>  Did he say "97 ...I guess he's having a real good time..<br>  And as far as east vs west goes ...who cares, we'll call it a draw...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>H.S.R. Vote</b><p>
We are expecting the results anytime on the HSR vote. It means Hamilton buses could be rolling in time for Grey Cup Sunday. The city's transit workers are voted on a tentative agreement today. More than 600 drivers, mechanics and inspectors have been on strike since last weekend, in a contract dispute that centres on job security. They've been without a contract since March.  A marathon bargaining session produced results yesterday with the announcement of the tentative pact. Aside from the out of towners looking for transit to the big game on Sunday, some 60 thousand daily users of public transit in the Hamilton region will be looking to board the buses that have been idled all week.
<hr>
<b>Cops Cup</b><p>
A fairly well behaved crowd at the first night of Grey Cup Festivities last night.<br>  Police say they laid only 3 liquor arrests last night, and didn't make any drunk driving arrests after stopping more than 25-hundred vehicles in ride programs.<br>  Police say they'll have 350 to 400 officers deployed across the region at the peak of the weekend's party.
<hr>
<b>Road Closure</b><p>
Recapping the downtown core road closures on now through the weekend.  King Street remains closed from James to Bay and MacNab Street is closed between Main and King.  Stay with us for Sunday's road closures around Ivor Wynne Stadium and tomoroww's parade route.  
<hr>
<b>Meningitis Shots</b><p>
 16 hundred Hamilton high school students were vaccinated against meningitus today. Regional health authorities now say St. Thomas More students who became ill earlier this month did indeed both have the same vaccine preventable strain of meningitis. Shots were also to be administered to children attending a day care centre attached to the school. Health officials say Grey Cup visitors have nothing to fear, because the general public is not at risk.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Boaters</b><p>
A man's body has been found in the Niagara River in the search for two missing boaters.  An aluminun boat carrying the boaters failed to return to Chippawa after a trip on the upper Niagara River yesterday. Around 11 o'clock this monring, the body of a 66-year-old man was located in a boat in the section of the river above the horseshoe falls. A 15-year-old boy is still missing.
<hr>
<b>Missing Person</b><p>
Police in Hamilton want your help in their search for a missing man. 40-year-old Luis Medeiros is mentally challenged. He was last seen when he left home at noon yesterday. He's described as white, 5-5, 130 pounds, slim build with short brown hair. He was wearing a bomber jacket and a black baseball cap. If you know where he might be, call police.
<hr>
<b>St. Joes Layoffs</b><p>
St. Joseph's Hospital is cutting 32 full time and 8 part time support staff jobs as of next may. The workers were given the required six months notice today. But hospital spokesman Hugh Greenwood says St. Joe's is hoping to use early retirment and buy-outs to take care of most of those workers.
<hr>
<b>Parade Map</b><p>
Tomorrow's Grey Cup/Santa Claus parade starts at 2 o'clock.  The route takes us from York Boulevard up Queen Street to Main...along Main to John....down John to King ....then north on Bay St.  Again start time, 2 o'clock, and don't forget to bring along canned goods and non-perishables, kinettes will be accepting donations along the parade route.
<hr>
<b>Game Map</b><p>
And looking ahead to game day on Sunday.  Road closures in the vicinity of  Ivor Wynn Stadium: Melrose and Balsam will be closed between King and Barton. Beechwood and Cannon will be closed between Melrose and Balsam.




<P>
