<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 21, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Grey Cup 
    <li>Festival Closures   
    <li>H.S.R. Deal         
    <li>Mac Donation        
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Derry Death         
    <li>Glancaster - Booze  
    <li>Cops Cleared        
    <li>Bernardo Aid        
    <li>QM School          
    <li>Parade Tree         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup</b><p>
Good evening, from the Sheraton Hamilton Hotel, headquarters for Grey Cup 96. It's been 24 years since Hamilton has played host to the Canadian classic. <br>  This Sunday at Ivor Wynne Stadium, the Toronto Argonauts take on the Edmonton Eskimoes in the 84th battle for Earl Grey's Cup. But the partying is already underway.
<br> As east meets west, the street barriers have gone up and provincial barriers have come down.<br> As Jamie West reports...the spirit of fun mixed with football came fast beginning this morning.
<i><br>  Western hospitality arrived to satisfy a fierce eastern hunger...<br>  And that's no lie...look at the line up...<br>  Downtown was buzzing with excitement long before noon...<br>  Joe Short from Baltimore would give anything to see the cup again ...<br>  Inside the convention centre the legends luncheon packed them in...<br>  Tony Gabriel with two rings to his credits remembers this phenominal play in '76...with 19 seconds left to win it over the Green Riders...<br>  And theres Grey Cup 96 currency now in circulation...<br>  Over at Chedoke McMaster Hospitals the Calgary Grey Cup Committee entertained to the delight of dozens of sick youngsters.<br>  This is obviously the spirit of the west easterners have heard about. <br>  And this is only day one... the party continues right through Sunday.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Festival Closures</b><p>
And once again the downtown core road closures now in effect through 3 o'clock Monday morning:<br> King Street from James to Bay.<br> McNab Street is also closed between Main and King, all part of the Grey Cup street festival.
<hr>
<b>H.S.R. Deal</b><p>
And if you just don't want to go anywhere near your car this Grey Cup weekend ... some good news ... Hamilton's bus strike may be over, by tomorrow morning: more on that from Scot Urquhart.
<i><br>  The mood on the picket line is considerably lighter ... now that a tentative deal is in the works for drivers and mechanics at the HSR. But there is still some unfinished business. Some 70 inside workers, represented by this man, are trying to complete a deal of their own: <br>  Job security, particularly as it concerns the possible privitization of the HSR: <br>  As long as the inside workers remain without a deal ... the pickets will stay up, and the buses will remain silent. How long will that take? <br>  And so with luck, there could be bus service this Grey Cup weekend, after all. </i>
<hr>
<b>Mac Donation</b><p>
A financial boost today from the DeGroote family of Laidlaw fame for Mac's new university centre ... a complex that will centralize all student services under one roof. Mac president Peter George and student union president Geoff Ritchie joined the DeGroote sons, Michael Junior and Gary in cutting a cake to commemorate the occasion. The four million dollar donation is the largest ever received by Mac, excluding bequests... and it brings the total amount raised toward the project to 12 million dollars. Total cost is expected to be almost 19- million.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
After a long string of setting new record highs, stock prices paused today as investors took some profits.<br>  Since the Seagram Company introduced its Tropicana Fruit Juices in Canada, it has captured more than half of the Canadian market share with opportunity for more growth.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Derry Death</b><p>
One person died this morning when a car slid under a tractor-trailer and burst into flames outside of Milton. Ironically, the truck had been carrying a load of seat-belts to the Ford plant in Oakville when it collided with the car at Trafalgar and Derry Roads.<br> The resulting fire engulfed both vehicles.<br> The body of the car's driver was trapped inside the smoldering wreck. The victim's identity has not been released.
<hr>
<b>Glancaster - Booze</b><p>
A stolen tractor trailor loaded with rye whiskey has been found, empty, in Mount Hope.<br> The rig had been reported stolen from Simcoe Tuesday night.<br> Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police found the trailor, abandoned on Airport Road.<br> Anyone with information on the stolen booze is asked to call Crime Stoppers.
<hr>
<b>Cops Cleared</b><p>
Niagara Regional Police have been cleared of wrongdoing in the death of a man found hanging in his cell.<br> the special investigations unit has wrapped up its probe into the death of Donald Yacura.<br> Arrested last March, he was treated for a gash to his head after struggling with officers.<br> Yacura was placed in a holding cell in Grimsby, but later moved to a St. Catharines lockup.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Aid</b><p>
Paul Bernardo has been told he can't get legal aid for his appeal.<br> But officials won't say why.<br> Bernardo has been attempting to appeal his convictions in the sex slayings of teens Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy. The legal aid money would have paid for his lawyer and research for his case. Bernardo has now applied for an "inmate appeal," which doesn't require a lawyer and doesn't take place before a full court.
<hr>
<b>QM School</b><p>
Hamilton's historic Queen Mary School has officially reopened. It happened with much pmomp and ceremony last night.<br> The original school, built in 1913 was demolished two years ago.  Parents, staff and students packed the gym for the ceremony. On hand, was 91-year-old Helen Mepham who attended Queen Mary School when it opened 83 years ago. Today Helen's three great granddaughters are Queen Mary students.
<hr>
<b>Parade Tree</b><p>
A large blue spruce will be among the floats Saturday's Grey Cup parade.<br> The 55 foot tree was moved this morning from it's Hamilton mountain Empress Avenue home.<br> The gigantic fir has been growing in Jim and Janice Scott's front yard for the past 35 years.<br> But it had gotten too big, so the Scotts decided to donate the tree to the CHML Christmas Tree of Hope. After the parade, it will tower over the corner of King and James.




<P>
