<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 20, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>H.S.R. Mediation    
    <li>403 Lane Closure    
    <li>Festival Closures   
    <li>Kenilworth Reopen   
    <li>Supercity Region    
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Mac Microscope      
    <li>Flush & Shut 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>H.S.R. Mediation</b><p>
On the eve of one the biggest parties Hamilton has ever thrown, a slim chance remains tonight of getting the city's transit system moving in time for the Grey Cup. <br> Mediation talks continue at this hour to try to end the four day old strike by drivers and mechanics at the Hamilton Street Railway.... and both sides admit, this could be a crucial turning point.
<br> They suggest that a settlement will either come quickly ... or the talks will collapse and the strike will drag on for at least another month. Scot Urquhart has the details:
<i><br>  Early morning on the picket line, and the mood is not optimistic. A half page ad in the newspaper outlining the region's final offer ... is angrily dismissed as propaganda ... payed for with tax dollars: <br>  Cheeseman says, his members have offered to maintain the status quo, and extend the current collective agreement for two years, rather than go with the offer outlined in the paper. Something he says, is rotten on Wentworth Street: <br>  What's obviously missing at the moment... are the buses. That's bad news for senior citizens at Mohawk Gardens; who are having to find other ways to get around: <br>  And the Board of Education says 11-hundred public system students are on their own for at least the next two weeks .... but so far, they've had few complaints.  On the other hand, the strike is good news, for businessmen like Blue Line Cab owner, Tony Rizzuto: <br>  As the two sides in the dispute gather for mediation at a Burlington hotel; there is word from the Canadian Urban Transit Association that the cost to run the HSR... is one of the highest in the province. Even the TTC; which is a far bigger and more complex system ... is cheaper to run ... and London Transit ... which serves roughly the same number of customers ... spends only a third of what the HSR does, for administration. Does that mean the HSR is top heavy? Or poorly managed? <br>  So how long will this strike last? Who knows? But this cannot be a good sign: <br>  The HSR is already handing out refunds for November bus pass holders ... at this temporary office on Catharine Street. And sources tell us that union executives have laid plans to keep their pickets in place for at least another four weeks. But as in all strikes; depending on what happens at the bargaining table, all of that could change, overnight. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>403 Lane Closure</b><p>
And also just in time for Grey Cup, expect more traffic problems just outside the city on Highway 403 between the Highway 6 north cutoff and the Main Street East ramp. Transport ministry crews are busy putting up concrete barriers and high mast lighting, upgrading pavement, and repairing bridges and guard rails. The bottleneck will be there until late next summer.
<hr>
<b>Festival Closures</b><p>
These are the Grey Cup festival road closures that will take effect tomorrow morning at 10 through until 3 a.m. Monday: <br>  King Street from James to Bay.<br>  And MacNab Street between Main and King, where another tent will be located. Throughout the rest of the week we'll update you on the Grey Cup parade route and game day closures.
<hr>
<b>Kenilworth Reopen</b><p>
After being closed since last Tuesday, the Kenilworth Access will re-open tomorrow.<br>  Crews are putting the finishing touches on the access today, back-filling behind a cracked retaining wall and finishing up the curb and paving around it.<br>  Hamilton Wentworth's senior director of roads, Ted Gill, tells us the access should reopen sometime after tomorrow morning's rush hour, but before the afternoon drive home.
<hr>
<b>Supercity Region</b><p>
There's a chance the plan to amalgamate Hamilton and the five outlying suburban municipalities that now make up Hamilton-Wenworth could go to the people for a vote. Last night regional council agreed to debate the merits of holding a region wide referendum.<br> That discussion will take place in two weeks.<br> Flamborough and Dundas oppose the supercity concept.<br> The mayor of Flamborough senses support for the deal is falling apart.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Low inflation with Canadian interest rates edging lower encouraged investors to move more money into stocks today breaking new record highs.<br>  Shares of Philip Environmental are soaring after U.S. analysts rate Philip shares as a strong buy. <br> 
<hr>
<b>Mac Microscope</b><p>
There is spaceage beacon sending out a signal from inside a tiny basement lab at Hamilton's McMaster University. <br>  It's attracting a lot of attention and money from the local scientific and industrial community and as Jamie West tells us...it's already being seen throughout the world...
<i><br>  A definite reason to celebrate... this is what scientist's have been waiting for.<br>  A scanning electron microscope that sees samples the way they've never been seen before ...like this spacy looking ion exchange bead that to the naked eye is half a millimetre in size.<br>  No more having to dry out or freeze samples to view... <br>  Instead for the first time technicians can get a new moving view of what happens to samples of metals, ceramics, concrete, paper, foods and microgels used in drug delivery. <br>  The 633-thousand dollar microscope is one of only a handful worldwide, and was unveiled officially to local industry, government and students at a special seminar ...industry believes the tool will lead to new products...<br>  The microscope came through a grant from the Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council and will be shared Waterloo, Guelph, Western, U of T and Ryerson. Revenue will be generated from research by private industry.<br>  The aquisition cements McMaster's standing as the leading electron microscopy centre in Canada. </i>
<hr>
<b>Flush & Shut </b><p>
Finally tonight, just when you thought you'd have to throw your husband out, along comes a device to save your marriage. <br>    It's a gadget that Thomas Crapper probably wished he'd thought of when he invested the porcelain commode.<br>  It's called the "Flush & Shut".  Its a special lever that puts the lid down every time you flush the toilet.<br>  The device is being demonstrated at the Seaway Mall in Welland.



<P>
