<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 19, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Dundas Says No      
    <li>Private Transit     
    <li>Fire Master Plan    
    <li>Pharmacy Awards     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Dundas Says No</b><p>
The region of Hamilton- Wentworth debates its future tonight. <br> When council meets within a couple of hours from now, it will consider its course of action on the road to becoming a super city.<br>
But instead of moving towards unanimity, the town of Dundas is actively working to ensure it's not part of a supercity in Hamilton Wentworth. An ad campaign will help spread the anti-super city message and a call for a referendum is likely to be presented to regional council tonight. As Ian Dovey reports last night Dundas council voted unamimously against the mega municipal concept and to advise the province of its desire to remain an independent town.                                     
<I><br>  It's not the first time Dundas has threatened to withdraw from the region,  as this copy of an 1859 separation bylaw infront of Dundas Town Hall states. <br>There wasn't much to discuss, the vote was unamimous Dundas wants to remain distinct and independent from any unified municipal structure. <br>    Mayor Addison has been a strong critic to the process that lead to unified government concept for Hamilton Wentworth telling his council and the public it the least democratic he's ever witnessed.<br>   The mayor had no problems gaining councils support to go it alone. <br>   Addison says he'll now try to persuade the other outlying councils to do the same. <br>    </I>

<hr>
<b>Private Transit</b><p>
The two sides in the HSR dispute hope that a provincial mediator will help them bring a quick end, to the three day transit strike in Hamilton. But behind the scenes there are stories of bad blood between the two sides; and a suggestion that perhaps the HSR might be better off, in private hands. 
<hr>
<b>Fire Master Plan</b><p>
Hamilton firefighters are warning the city that further cuts could put residents at risk.<br>  As Mike Murphy reports the firefighters say the city may save some money...but it could cost lives.
<i><br>  So many firefighters turned out to sound the alarm over potential budget cuts ...they had to find a bigger room.<br>  Then...the firefighters warned a committee of Hamilton council that major cuts in service and manpower could be disastrous.<br>  Their concerns surround Hamilton's master fire plan.<br>  A plan that lays out potential scenerios which could see up to 60 of 440 firefighters lose their jobs..and budget cuts of up to 3 million dollars<br>  Already the city has downsized the fire department. There are fewer vehicles on the road.<br>  And fewer firefighters to pull trapped motorists out of cars.<br>  This alderman says he'll fight any further cuts.<br>  The new fire master plan will be hotly debated when it comes back to the politicians for action early next month.</i>
<hr>
<b>Pharmacy Awards</b><p>
A Hamilton pharmacist has been recognized for bringing his drug store down to the people. <br> His innovative design ideas recognize a shift towards patients having to take more responsibility for their own healthcare as government funding decreases ...<br>  Jamie West explains...
<i><br>  So Hilton Silberg brought his Day Nite Pharmacy down to street level...<br>  A number of innovations have won him a national award of excellence for design...<br>  Among them hands free telephones...<br>  Shy about family planning, drug interaction or even itching? no problem...<br>  A number of counselling areas have been built that range from public to semi-private to very private ...<br>  The pharmacy's old computer system and counter have been donated to Mohawk College's pharmacy assistant program. A valuable donation that will be built into a fake full service pharmacy.<br>   Silberg believes with more governent cutbacks to healthcare.. patients are going to be treating themselves more often and that will create a need for a closer relationship between patients and pharmacists.<br>  </i>



<P>
