<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 18, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>HSR Strike       
    <li>Leach Re: Supercity 
    <li>Hospital Needs      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Suspicious Package? 
    <li>Vanderkley Sentenced
    <li>Christmas Dolls     
    <li>Thief Back          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>HSR Strike</b><p>
For the first time in 14 years, bus drivers with the Hamilton Street Railway are walking the picket line. <br>  Marathon talks over the weekend collapsed early Sunday morning ...just hours after the union strike deadline.
<i><br>  With the buses idle and the picket lines up, the situation politicians wanted the least has become a reality.<br>  For the first time in fourteen years, drivers with the Hamilton Street Railway are on strike.<br>  Regional chairman Terry Cooke briefed politicians on the situation this morning.<br>  Cooke says he was certain that marathon talks on the weekend were heading toward a settlement.  Cash awards in lieu of benefit reductions and reduced pension contributions were settled.   <br>      And the regional chairman denies reports of a hallway deal late Saturday night that would have led to an agreement.   <br>     Details of the regions' offer will go into newspaper ads tomorrow.<br>  But most union members had the opportunity to vote on it today.<br>  Under provincial law, they must if its a final offer.<br>  Union head Kim Cheeseman says the region forced them into a strike.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Leach Re: Supercity</b><p>
Hamilton- Wentworth Region took another step toward becoming a supercity today.<br> Municipal affairs minister Al Leach has announced his endorsesment of the plan, brokered ten days ago through provincial mediator Gardner Church. He also wants all councils involved to complete deliberations on the plan quickly so that the new structure can be in place for the 1997 elections.<br> As for Dundas and Flamborough, the two dissenting municipalities,              last week, Flamborough indicated it would opt out of a supercity. As for Dundas, that council meets tonight, along with Glanbrook and Ancaster. After a stormy debate last week, regional council put the matter off until next week.
<hr>
<b>Hospital Needs</b><p>
The Niagara District Health Council is doing some restructuring of its own these days.<br> The council is looking at how much it can cut before the province's restructuring commission comes in and does it for them.<br> It's released a report warning that within five years Niagara residents are going to have access to fewer hospital beds and fewer hospitals.<br> Lauran Sabourin has more.
<i><br>  During its eight month review the groups involved in drawing up this report asked themselves three key questions. <br>  What are the trends?><br>  What can be done outside the hospital? <br>  What the needs of Niagara residents in the year 2001.? <br>  What the restructuring committee found is that Niagara could do with fewer acute care beds, fewer chronic care beds, but a significant increase in rehab beds. <br>  All told it would mean that the peninsula would have about 5 percent fewer hospital beds in five years. <br>  In the future those people giving care will be doing it more on an outpatient basis.<br>  Caring for fewer people admitted into the hospital for more than a day.</i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Low interest rates gave investors enough incentive to buy more stocks today sending Canadian share prices to their 59th record high of the year.<br> Analysts expect Canadian share prices to move even higher. <br> 
<hr>
<b>Suspicious Package?</b><p>
The Hamilton Regional Police bomb squard responded to a call at the James Street Armouries this afternoon ... after a suspicious package was spotted in a baby carriage, in the court-yard of the facility. The call forced police to close James Street for over an hour; while the package was retrieved by a police robot.<br> Police blew the box open with a water cannon ... and found nothing.
<hr>
<b>Vanderkley Sentenced</b><p>
A Niagara Falls man has been sentenced to three months in jail after killing a police officer in a hit and run last April. This morning 68 year old Frank Vanderkley was sentenced in a St. Catharines court, and also ordered not to drive for another year and half.<br> Vanderkley struck and killed veteran OPP officer Mike Goula, who was helping another officer with a traffic accident when he was struck by the side of the road in Niagara Falls.
<hr>
<b>Christmas Dolls</b><p>
Have you started your Christmas shopping?  If not, reporter Annette Hamm has a suggestion if you're looking for something very special.  She has the story of a Stoney Creek senior who's been busy all year hand-making her creations with needle, thread and a lot of love.
<i><br>  The sewing machine is rarely idle at Bea McPherson's Stoney Creek apartment.<br>  88 year old McPherson spends most of the year working her magic for this time of year.<br>  She's putting the finishing touches on a spare bedroom full of dolls hoping for new homes this Christmas.<br>  Bea estimates she's refurbished thousands of second hand dolls since 1941, when her husband asked her to send some Canadian dolls overseas.<br>  Now she does donates her dolls to local charities.  <br>  Picking up remnants throughout the year, with the help of her friend Kathleen Cortolucci, Bea fixes up one doll at a time.  <br>  Each one is given special attention in the hopes it will become someones special doll.  <br>  Bea McPherson's dolls will be available at the Christmas Bazaar at Stoney Creek United Church this Saturday.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Thief Back</b><p>
Finally tonight, an update on a crime story we brought you on Halloween.<br> A suspect had smacked his skull while running from Tabby's Variety with a plastic bag over his head.<br> Last night, police say the same suspect returned to the store, this time to buy something.<br> A clerk recognized him, though, and held him for police.<br> 34 year old Shawn Gray of Hamilton is charged with robbery.



<P>
