<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 15, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Restructure War     
    <li>HSR - Grey Cup    
    <li>Crowd Control       
    <li>Grey Cup Volunteers 
    <li>Escaped Custody     
    <li>Barnesdale Fire     
    <li>Retaining Wall Down 
    <li>Bus Banner          
    <li>Lakeport Buy        
    <li>Linehan             
    <li>Library Windfall    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>restructure war</b><p>
The deputy mayor of Flamborough wants his municipality to go it alone, if a Hamilton- Wentworth Region becomes a supercity. <br>  Dave Braden is bitterly disappointed with an agreement that he says has little to do with good government, and everything to do with political ambition.
<br>  And he adds he feels betrayed by both the provincially- appointed mediator, and Hamilton- Wentworth's regional chairman.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>The deputy mayor of Flamborough says politians who negotiated municipal government reform were bullied by the empty threat of provincial intervention, and duped by provincial mediator Gardner Church.  <br>But Braden feels equally betrayed by the regional chairman.  Braden hopes taxpayers will revolt against the supercity concept, and if it goes through, he wants Flamborough set free.  <br>Tory Toni Skarica, whose riding includes Ancaster, Dundas and Flamborough, has reservations about the deal. <br> But Liberal Dominic Agostino favours the agreement, as long as local councils have the final say on whether it comes to pass.  <br>Ontario municipal affairs minister Al Leach has promised to make a statement on the supercity plan on Monday. </i>
<hr>
<b>HSR - Grey Cup</b><p>
Will the Hamilton Street Railway face a strike tomorrow at midnight?<br> Reporter Jamie West says both sides are optimistic that a settlement will come through...
<i><br>  Keeping the buses rolling is what both sides want...<br>  The region has tabled what it calls it's final offer...<br>  The union is seeking terms identical to their last contract. They gathered at the Royal Connaught just before heading into negotiations...<br>  Mediated by Bob Pryor...<br>  They've accused the HSR of trying to strip their pensions...<br>  The HSR will save money through the elimination of some benefits and the reduced pension contributions by employees.<br>  The last HSR strike was in 1982 and lasted 92 days. The union has been in a strike position since june 2nd. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Crowd Control</b><p>
Regional police have their contingency plans for the Grey Cup too. Fearing, but not expecting the worst, a special crowd management squad of 40 Hamilton- Wentworth officers has been preparing for the game and its festivities since January.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i> <br>  The 93 riot in Montreal after the Canadiens won the Stanley Cup.<br>  It's exactly the kind of situation police don't want to see happen in Hamilton Grey Cup weekend.<br>  And this is their insurance.  <br>  Since January, forty officers have been practicing hard tactical manoueuvres, preparing for the very worst Grey Cup weekend may have to offer.  <br>  Police don't know exactly what size crowd they'll be dealing with, but insist they won't be on hand to intimidate them.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Grey Cup Volunteers</b><p>
And the volunteers are ready.  It was wardrobe call at the Hamilton Convention Centre last night. Some 1300 volunteers began suiting up with Grey Cup hats and jackets.  <br>Most are from the Hamilton Wentworth Region, but some are from as far away as north bay.
<hr>
<b>Escaped Custody</b><p>
He was to be picked up on a breach of recognizance, but now a Hamilton man is wanted for escaping custody.<br> This after a suspect bolted while being escorted to a police cruiser last night in Hamilton.<br> A warrant has now been issued for the arrest of 31 year old John Daniel O'Callaghan of Hamilton.
<hr>
<b>Barnesdale Fire</b><p>
Fire resulted in a narrow escape for a Hamilton man... he was taking a shower when the blaze erupted in his 3rd floor apartment in a fourplex at 51 Barnesdale North. He climbed from a window onto the roof. Neither he nor the six others who occupy the building were injured. Careless smoking is the suspected cause. Damage is estimated at 40- thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Retaining Wall Down</b><p>
The wall came tumbling down today. At one point that buckling retaining wall identified earlier this week along Hamilton's Kenilworth Access appeared ready to topple, leaning at a 45 degree angle this morning. A Hamilton firm has started demolishing the wall.<br>  Once it's down, engineers will examine the foundation to find out why the wall failed.<br>  Officials shut down the access Tuesday night. It's expected to be reopened next Thursday.
<hr>
<b>Bus Banner</b><p>
It you're travelling the roadways of St. Catharines in a few weeks, watch for some winning spirit.<br> St. Francis Secondary School has won a school spirit banner contest.<br>  Today some 300 students signed the banner which will be featured on the side of a St. Catharines Transit bus for a month.
<hr>
<b>Lakeport Buy</b><p>
The future is bright for Hamilton based Lakeport Brewery.<br>  Company founder and president Bill Sharpe, along with his vice-president of finance have acquired the 90 percent of the company owned by Cott Corporation.<br>  The future of the company was in doubt for some time after Cott announced it wished to sell off its interest.<br>  In order to finance the 17 million dollar deal, Sharpe sold the brewing rights of several popular beers to Molson Breweries.<br>  Still, Sharpe says all jobs will be saved as he introduces new products starting in January.
<hr>
<b>Linehan</b><p>
Hamilton native Brian Linehan has built a career out of his unique chats with Hollywood celebrities. <br>  This Saturday marks his return to the steel city with a special premiere edition of a weekly show beginning on CHCH-TV in January. Alex Reynolds interviews the man who interviews the stars.
<i> <br>  The Hamilton native combines a photographic memory with meticulous preparation... movie names responding with amazement to little known facts Linehan reveals during sessions.<br>  But it isn't always easy. <br>  Linehan will be back on the home screen with a weekly series beginning in January.<br>  A kick-off special is set for Saturday night on CHCH-TV.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Library Windfall</b><p>
After decades of borrowing from the Hamilton Public Library ... Ed and Connie Dowler decided, they would give something back. The well known Hamilton residents died within days of each other ... earlier this year and today all proceeds of their estate were officially turned over to the library... a bequest of some 350-thousand dollars. The generous gift will be used to begin an endowment fund at the library; and income generated will be directed to the upkeep and improvement of bookmobile services... a particular favourite of Ed Dowler.



<P>
