<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 14, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Church - Restructure  
    <li>Biz Backs Reform    
    <li>Meningococcal       
    <li>Joe Brant - Elderly 
    <li>St. Liz Villa 3     
    <li>Heart Drug          
    <li>Smoking             
    <li>Doctor Charged      
    <li>Fire Kills Kids     
    <li>Emergency Landing   
    <li>Stelpipe Pickets    
    <li>Overflow Tank       
    <li>Gallery of Dist.    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Church - Restructure</b><p>
They're flexing their muscle. Local councils who have something to say about the plan to convert Hamilton- Wentworth into a super city.  And today, the man who brokered the deal said the province, though determined to streamline local government, may listen.<br>    Gardner Church was addressing a joint meeting of the Hamilton and District Chamber of Commerce, and the Hamilton Construction Association.
<br>  His remarks are at odds with comments he made earlier this week, suggesting the merger is a done deal, despite growing resistance to the idea from local councils.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>If Hamilton- Wentworth politicians embrace the supercity deal reached last week, Gardner Church says they'll become the first to provide one-stop shopping for all government services.  And he says instant access to those services is critically important to small businesses, the current leaders in Canadian job creation.  <br>But some local councils reject the supercity concept outright, while others are having second thoughts. Earlier this week, Church suggested it's too late for councils to undo the deal.  Today, he stressed he's no longer an active player in Hamilton- Wentworth's struggle with government reform, and has no inside knowledge of what the province plans to do.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Biz Backs Reform</b><p>
Meanwhile, a group of Hamilton-area business executives endorse the idea of streamlining local government, although not necessarily the specific agreement signed last week.<br>  Individuals respresenting businesses, big and small, plan to take out ads in the Hamilton Spectator and the region's weekly newspapers, applauding political leaders for taking a first step towards government reform.
<hr>
<b>Meningococcal</b><p>
Parents of St. Thomas More Secondary students are reading notices tonight from the public health department. They're investigating the occurence of meningococcal disease among grade 11 students at the Hamilton high school. A teenaged girl was admitted to St. Joseph's Hospital earlier this week and a male student, suspected of having the disease was admitted to McMaster Medical Centre last night.  There is no apparent link between the two but those in close contact with the two teens are being treated with a prophylactic medication and area health care professionals are on notice. Meningococcal disease is a serious but rare infection which occurs in the blood or lining of the brain.
<hr>
<b>Joe Brant - Elderly</b><p>
A Burlington family is outraged that Joseph Brant Memorial Hospital has billed their 93 year old mother nearly 9-thousand dollars after she refused to be transferred to a nursing home.<br> As Jamie West reports... the hospital blames bed shortages and funding cuts for their policy...
<i><br>  Pat Morris says she's happy that her 93-year old mother Catherine Duffy is now being cared for in Mt Nemo Lodge about 10 minutes from her home...<br>   Joseph Brant Hospital orginally wanted the family to sign a paper agreeing to have her mother placed in a home up to an hour's drive away. Pat flatly refused...<br>  About 86-hundred dollars...all tolled.<br> And some bad attitude to boot ...<br>  The hospital says it needs the space for acute care patients...<br>  It's already down 60 beds 80 jobs and will cut another 4 million from it's operating budget to please the province. The daily cost of a hospital bed is between 4 and 5 hundred dollars compared to about 60 dollars in a nursing home.<br>  This Toronto based health lawyer says it's illegal for hospitals to bill patients...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Villa 3</b><p>
A coroner's jury today heard the intricate details concerning long term care for the elderly.<br> Form after form was recited to the jury as the inquest probed the deaths of five people at Hamilton's St. Elizabeth Villa seniors' residence.<br> Dwight Ryan has the story..  
<i><br>  In all, 42 deaths occurred at St. Elizabeth Villa between January of 1994 and March of 1995.<br>  This inquest, before Niagara Regional Coroner Bill Lucas is looking into five of those deaths.<br>  Much of Thursday's testimony centred on the placement of those in need in long term care facilities of all sorts.<br>  St. Elizabeth's Villa is licensed as a 2nd level lodging home..not a nursing home. Despite that, public health officials felt many of the residents required more care than the home provided.<br>  Joyce Cahill who is a placement co-ordinator told jury members that even when doctors recognize the need for further care, its the family who is ultimately responsible for the well-being of their relatives.<br>  Two of the deaths in question were residents who doctors said shouldn't have been in the villa. But, at the request of their families, both remained there until the end.<br>  Miss Cahill told the inquest that second level lodging homes do have the right to say take them home, but she's never seen that happen.<br>  Adding, they're too humane.<br>  The inquest, which is scheduled to last more than a month will resume Friday morning.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Heart Drug</b><p>
It was an apirin a day but doctors may soon be prescribing a new drug for heart and stroke patients. A Canadian team headed by researchers at Hamilton Civic Hospitals has tested the blood thinner -- called clopidogrel, it reduces the risk of new heart attacks and strokes by one-third, compared with one-quarter for aspirin with milder side effects. It'll likely cost a little more though.
<hr>
<b>Smoking</b><p>
Ontario's top public health official is warning of an epidemic of heart disease and lung cancer because we're losing the war on tobacco. Dr. Richard Shabus says after years of decline, tobacco use by teens has shot up 20 per cent in the past two years.  He blames lower taxes and slick promotions.
<hr>
<b>Doctor Charged</b><p>
A doctor who practices in Hamilton faces twelve counts of sexual assault.<br> 55 year old Dr. Lam Dam Nguyen of Mississauga was charged after a woman complained she had been assaulted over the period of a year. Police say the complainant is not one of his patients.
<hr>
<b>Fire Kills Kids</b><p>
Still no word on the cause of yesterday's tragic fire that killed two Brantford toddlers.<br> The bodies of three-year-old Samantha Dixon and her two-year-old sister Natalie were found huddled under a bed in an upstairs bedroom. Police say the girls' mother, Muriel, noticed smoke in the house and managed to escape next door with her nine-month-old daughter Copelyn. But she was overcome by smoke and flames when she tried to rescue her other daughters. The First Baptist Church of Brantford is accepting food and clothing donations for the family and the Bank of Nova Scotia has set up a fund at all of its Ontario branches.  It's transit number 90852, account number 0067385.
<hr>
<b>Emergency Landing</b><p>
In the end there were no injuries but some terrifying moments for eleven passengers on board a U.S. Air flight from Pittsburgh to Hamilton last night.<br> Just before eleven o'clock the pilot radioed the tower saying he had a problem with his landing gear.<br> The twin engine prop circled the airport several times to allow emergency crews to get into position.<br> The aircraft managed to land safely with all landing gear down in tact.
<hr>
<b>Stelpipe Pickets</b><p>
A few tense moments high atop Stelco Tower today. Striking Stelpipe workers gathered on the 24th floor of the building and then locked the elevators for about an hour. When asked to leave they took their protest outside blocking traffic on King Street for a short time. The four hundred workers from the Page Hersey Plant in Welland have been off the job since November 1st. They want better pension packages and increased wages. The workers say they have not had a raise in nine years.
<hr>
<b>Overflow Tank</b><p>
Hamilton West MP Stan Keyes joined regional chairman Terry Cooke and Hamilton mayor Bob Morrow to celebrate the completion of a major construction project at King and Main Streets. The 25 million dollar overflow tank project, funded by all three levels of government will reduce storm water overflow. It will also improve the water quality in Chedoke Creek and Cootes Paradise.
<hr>
<b>Gallery of Dist.</b><p>
Hamilton took time last night to honour some of the people who have made significant lifelong contributions to the steel city.<br> In this, Hamilton's Sesquicentennial year, seven names were added to the Gallery of Distinction: congratulations to former Tigercat owner David Braley, former McMaster University president, Alvin Lee, Firan Corporation founder, Morgan Firestone, businessman Chester Waxman, and Grey Cup 96 co-chair, Marnie Paikin. The gallery posthumously honoured painter Frank Panabaker, and the reverend John Bonomi. <br>   And a distinctive individual at CHCH-TV was also honoured last night at the Annual Spirit of Style Fashion Show for the Lung Association. Community Relations Manager Denise Dickie was presented the community spirit award for her support over the years. 



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

