<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 13, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Fire Kills Kids     
    <li>Deadly Blaze        
    <li>Thorold Fire        
    <li>Quebec St. Fire     
    <li>St. Liz Villa 2     
    <li>QEW Crash           
    <li>Kenilworth Access   
    <li>White Rose Robbery  
    <li>Casino Date         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>fire kills kids</b><p>
Four deaths in four fires in the last 24 hours have the Ontario Fire Marshall's Office clambering to find out why. <br> The November ice and cold were factors in fighting the blazes but were they factors in the causes?
<br> In the latest, two children have perished in a house fire in Brantford this afternoon.<br> Over come by smoke and flames two young girls aged 4 and three died in a house fire in Brantford's core area.<br>  The Brantford fire department received the call from an occupant of the house just before one o'clock this afternoon.<br>  When firefighters arrived at 27 Durham the two storey clapboard home was fully involved.<br>  The platoon chief says they had to battle the flames before they could attempt any rescue.<br>  The two girls were found in an upstairs bedroom.<br> The house has been completely gutted.
<hr>
<b>Deadly Blaze</b><p>
This time last night, reporter Ian Dovey was on the scene of another. It was the second fatal fire in two years in the valley town of Dundas. And it claimed the life of 46-year-old Debbie Trafford.
<hr>
<b>Thorold Fire</b><p>
A 72-year-old Thorold woman was rescued from a fire in her home, only to die of her injuries. She was taken by air ambulance to hospital in Hamilton last night with serious burns to 90 per cent of her body. The fire was contained to a washroom on the lower level of the cowan drive home. The cause remains under investigation.
<hr>
<b>Quebec St. Fire</b><p>
And yet another blaze... this one minus serious injuries although one firefighter ended up in hospital with a cinder in his eye. It was on Quebec Street in Hamilton... it started in the living room couch ... careless smoking is the suspected cause. The first and second floors were completely gutted. Damage is estimated at 70-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Villa 2</b><p>
Meanwhile, efforts continue in the search for what lead to the deaths of five residents of a Hamilton retirement home. The director of nursing for the Hamilton Wentworth Region admitted to a coroner's inquest that her officials found little evidence to support allegations of substandard care at St. Elizabeth Villa.  Dwight Ryan reports.   
<i><br>  St. Elizabeth Villa is the largest facility of its type in the Hamilton Wentworth Region.<br>  The inquest is investigating the deaths of five people at the second level lodging home between January of 1994 and March of 1995. Although the probe is into just five deaths, 42 residents died during that period. <br>   Officials were alerted when the former nursing director of the villa wrote a letter to the board then the health department detailing alleged problems.<br>  On the stand, the region's nursing director said many of Helen Demchuk's allegations seemed serious and worthy of further investigation. <br>  Vicky Woodcox identified them as abuse, inappropriate handling of food, including recycling leftovers, management style, staffing, resident transfer techniques, infection control and emergency procedures.<br>  Public health officials began an immediate investigation.<br>  Later working with a villa consultant, public health nurses felt that the facility was violating a local bylaw in that many of the residents required more care than their license allowed.<br>  But Wilcox told the inquest that her officials found no evidence whatsover of the stronger allegations contained in the letter that started it all.<br>  No evidence of abuse, no evidence of recycling food or inefficient infection control.<br>  She added that St. Elizabeth Villa officials acted immediately when the region's public health department sent an order to comply following their initial probe.<br>  The inquest, is expected to last more than a month.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>QEW Crash</b><p>
It was a slow ride to work for commuters in Niagara today. A tractor trailer jack-knifed in the Hamilton-bound lanes at Casablanca Boulevard. The westbound lanes were closed and eastbound traffic was reduced to one lane. Despite the rush hour traffic headaches, there were no serious injuries as a result.
<hr>
<b>Kenilworth Access</b><p>
It's going to be week until things are back to normal on a key Hamilton mountain access.<br>  Last night, the partial collapse of a primary retaining wall forced the closure of the Kenilworth Access.<br>  
<hr>
<b>White Rose Robbery</b><p>
A few moments of terror for customers of the White Rose Nursery on Hamilton mountain this morning. Two gunmen burst into the store ... ordered everyone to the floor ... and emptied the safe. They escaped in a blue Mercury Mystique .... driven by a third suspect. Police say the three men are white males in their late twenties. The two gunmen wore ski masks ... the driver; however, was clean cut, had black hair, and a slim build. Anyone with information on the hold-up, is asked to call mountain detectives, or Crime Stoppers.
<hr>
<b>Casino Date</b><p>
Niagara gamblers hoping for a lucky break will get their chance December 9th.<br> Casino Niagara made the announcement this morning at the Skyline Brock Hotel.<br> The casino is expected to attract about six million people a year to Niagara Falls.<br> The building will have a total of 96 thousand sqare feet of gaming space which includes three thousand slot machines and 123 gaming tables.<br> It will also have a premium players club for the high rollers.<br> The casino will employ about three thousand people.



<P>
