<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 12, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>St. Liz Inquest 1   
    <li>Nochar Demo         
    <li>Police Services     
    <li>Bill 84 - St. Kitts   
    <li>Drug Sting          
    <li>Video Vote          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>St. Liz Inquest 1</b><p>
Two years ago the city of Hamilton cited a retirement home for violations ranging from recycling food, to failing to arrange proper care for residents whose needs exceeded those normally provided by a second-level lodging home.  Today an inquest opened into five deaths at Saint Elizabeth's Villa on Hamilton mountain.<br> A coroner testified she investigated the deaths of forty-two residents that occured over a sixteen-month period in 1994 and 1995.
<br>  She chose five of those deaths because she felt they were representative of possible problems at the villa.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br> St. Elizabeth's Villa is one of the largest of Hamilton's eighty-nine second level lodging homes. There is no provincial legislation to regulate such homes.  But St. Elizabeth's does have a license, issued by the city of Hamilton.  Dean Barrow is a senior city license inspector.  He testified he inspected St. Elizabeth's in November 1994, after receiving a complaint from the villa's former nursing director.  Barrow says he was impressed with the facility, finding it modern and clean and in compliance with all aspects of the second-level lodging home bylaw.  <br>The violations included recycling rood, delayed response to medical emergencies, the admission of residents who may have needed a higher level of medical care than the home could provide, and the failure to transfer residents whose health had deteriorated.  Barrow says all the deficiencies were corrected in two months, and no charges were ever laid.  But a month-and-a-half later, former regional coroner Doctor Bonita Porter was contacted by Hamilton- Wentworth's Medical Officer of Health, who expressed concern about mortality rates at St. Elizabeth's.  Doctor Porter launched her own investigation into forty-two deaths at the villa, and found a number of areas of concern... concerns like nutrition, whether St. Elizabeth's had enough personnel to provide adequate care to its residents, and whether some of those residents might have been better off in a nursing home.  Doctor Porter hopes the five deaths singled out for this inquest will help illustrate whether or not those concerns are justified.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Nochar Demo</b><p>
Containing a gasoline spill safely is a time consuming process.  Anyone stranded on the QEW yesteday knows just how long it takes. But a new line of chemical products may be about to change that. Matt Hayes was on hand for todays demonstration that proved very timely.
<i><br>  Yesterdays tanker rollover was a nightmare for motorists. The QEW at Burloak was closed for more than 15 hours. The bulk of that time spent cleaning up spilled gasoline. Its one day later ...not far from the accident scene.  These people represent firefighting spill control and waste management services. They're here at the Petro Canada refinery in Oakville to see if their's a better way. Nochar Canada is using this demonstration to unveil a new line of fire and environmental protection products.<br>  In light of yesterdays accident the demonstration couldn't be more timely.  Sher says his product is perfect for tackling spills like this one.<br>  This turtle pool contains gasoline.  Once the Nochar chemical is applied it goes from gas to goo. Easier to cleanup and transport.  Other demonstrations show how fire retardants can slow the burning process.  The boxes that have them chemical applied smoulder but don't burn. As for the second set of boxes.  From fire to spills. New technology may not prevent accidents like this one yesterday but could go a long way to making the cleanup quicker and safer. </i>
<hr>
<b>Police Services</b><p>
The Tory government's who does what panel has handed down its recommendations when it comes to emergency services.  Among them, that local councils set policing budgets to make the system more accountable to the taxpayer. The panel also suggests municipalities appoint police services board members, instead of the province, making the process more open to public input.
<hr>
<b>Bill 84 - St. Kitts</b><p>
In its cost-cutting mission, the Harris government is also aiming at the province's professional firefighters. The firefighters accuse the government pushing through legislation that will allow municipalities to cut costs at the expense of people's lives. Lauran Sabourin has that story.
<i><br>  This is the contentious legislation. Bill 84.<br>  The problems the province's professional firefighters have with Bill 84 is that it diminishes their right to negotiate hours of work.<br>  It allows the hiring of part time firefighters.<br>  And it gives the municipality the option of privatizing the firefighting service.<br>  All of these changes are designed to save money...<br>  But going so fare as to privative the fire service is something that the mayor of St. Catharines rejects. <br>  Professional firefighters spend about 40 percent of their time fighting fires.<br>  The remaining time is spent on other kinds of calls. Extricating people from wrecked vehicles.<br> Trying to resusitate heart attack victims.<br>  Assisting is high angle rescues. <br>  Most people in St. Catharines remember the seeing pictures of firefighters plucking frightened workers off a narrow ledge on the Garden City Skyway after their scaffold collapsed. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Drug Sting</b><p>
It may be cold outside but that's not keeping schoolyard drug users and traffickers from plying their trade. <br> And as Jamie West reports tonight... Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are turning up the heat in efforts to get the anti-drug message through to teenagers...
<i><br>  9am and the Hamilton Wentworth High Enforcement Action Team are getting ready...<br> The six member team changes it's focus every few months...they've already made a big dent in car thefts,  kept loitering youths off the streets, and are now conducting daily undercover surveillance of 10 high schools, trying to put a damper on drug use...<br>  Education is a big component of the programme,...<br>  So far over 25 arrests...for possesion and trafficking...<br>  And word is getting around that the heat is definitely on...<br>  Marijuana is the drug of choice followed by hasish oil and L.S.D.<br>  The numbers say less than 5% of students are users on a regular basis, but the percentage of first timers is way up...<br>  Even being where you're not supposed to be will get you in trouble with this team...<br>  Identification arrests, prosecution and effective followup are proving to the community that heat means business.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Video Vote</b><p>
Finally tonight, an update now on a story we brought you a few weeks ago, about the controversial animated sex-education video, that some parents claimed was too graphic. Last night, the Wentworth Board of Education approved by a 6-4 margin, a new material-review policy. The ten-point program will allow school councils the opportunity to view, and approve sex-education videos that may be deemed controversial, by board staff.



<P>
