<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Monday, November 11, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Truck Rollover 
    <li>Hamilton Cenotaph   
    <li>Niag. Cenotaph      
    <li>Cadets Vigil        
    <li>St. Creek Fire      
    <li>Marvin Caplan       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Remembrance - Schools 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Truck Rollover </b><p>
It's a nightmare on the 403 highway this hour.  It's been closed in both directions at Burloak Drive since early this afternoon when a tanker carrying gasoline flipped over, spilling it's load. Clean-up operations are continuing but it look like the highway will remain closed for some time yet.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Cenotaph</b><p>
Traffic a little lighter today with the November the 11th holiday.<br> Hundreds packed downtown cenotaphs across the country to remember the 100-thousand Canadians who lost their lives so than we could live in freedom today.  At Gore Park in Hamilton, veterans, politicians and students alike gathered for a re-dedication of the cenotaph. Dedicated orginally to honour our first world war heroes, as of the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month, 1996, Hamilton's war memorial now officially commemorates those who died in valour in world war two and korea.
<hr>
<b>Niag. Cenotaph</b><p>
At the St. Catharines cenotaph, a double blast from a Howitzer gun launched Remembrance Day services. It was sunny but cold as some 500 people, of all ages stood silently with heads vowed as our thoughts turned to the ultimate sacrifices made by so many, so long ago.
<hr>
<b>Cadets Vigil</b><p>
Services began last night for members of the Royal Canadian Sea Cadet corps renown, of St. Catharines and for Stoney Creek's 713 air cadet squadron.  These young people decided to do something special for this year's November the 11th. They stood guard at the town cenotaph from 5 o'clock yesterday afternoon until 11 o'clock this morning.
<hr>
<b>St. Creek Fire</b><p>
A Stoney Creek family won't forget this Remembrance Day.<br> They've lost everything in a fire, including some Chistmas gifts. An investigator with the Ontario Fire Marshall's Office spent much of today sifting through the ashes of their barton street east home.<br> By the time Stoney Creek firefighters arrived on the scene last night, it was totally engulfed in flames.<br> The three people who live there, a mother and her two sons were out of town for the weekend.<br> Damage is set at 130-thousand dollars.  A neighbour, Ann Tebow is accepting donations on behalf of the family.  The two boys are aged 4 and 17.  The family has been left with only the clothing on their backs.
<hr>
<b>Marvin Caplan</b><p>
Efforts to revitalize downtown Hamilton are too little, too late for one well-known retailer.<br> Marvin Caplan Gentlemen's Apparel will close by the end of the year, a victim of both changing consumer shopping patterns, and the city's failure to react more quickly to the deterioration of the downtown core.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>They're liquidating the inventory at Marvin Caplan Gentlemen's Apparel.  They're also liquidating three full-time jobs, several part-time positions, and an eighteen-year-old business.  The company's president, who's also a Hamilton alderman, says he can't afford to keep losing money while the city dickers over what to do about the downtown.  And he wishes the city would simply let its staff do the job they're paid to do.  <br>Caplan says the city merely needs to create the conditions necessary to allow business to thrive.  The businesses themselves will do the rest.  <br>And Hess Village is not the only high point. Caplan points out the International Village, and James Street North and South are thriving, proving it's premature to sound the death knell for the downtown core. </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian banks and government offices were closed for Rememberence Day.<br>  Howevever stocks markets were opened and stock prices surged to new record highs again in Toronto and New York.<br> Some market watchers believe interest rates can still edge lower.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Remembrance - Schools</b><p>
Time heals all wounds... that old saying may be true when it comes to the body.., but many men and women that served know too well that the same cannot always be said for one's emotions. <br>  The memories for most are still as vivid as the events that created them. As Jamie West reports...some young Hamiltonians are helping to preserve those memories...
<i><br>  Two ceremonies, one in song... one in silence ... both recognizing Canadian freedom and the sacrifice it took to preserve it.<br>  Fifty-one years since the end of World War Two. Eight lifetimes for many of the students at George R. Allan School... <br>  At St. John the Baptist School ...a tulip garden has been planted. <br>  To them Officer Bob is a crossing guard... but the pride is taking root.</i>



<P>
