<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Friday, November 8, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Hamilton One Tier   
    <li>Dundas / Flamborough  
    <li>Teachers Vote       
    <li>Van Shooting        
    <li>Machete Sentence    
    <li>Inquest Goes        
    <li>Rick Hansen         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton One Tier</b><p>
After more than two decades, municipal government as we know it in Hamilton- Wentworth is about to disappear.  Bleary-eyed municipal politicians met into the wee hours of this morning with provincial mediator Gardner Church, and finally came up with an agreement which almost everyone could live with.
<br>  We have special reports tonight beginning with Deborah Walker who was there for the twelve-and-a- half hour marathon session, and has this report.
<i> <br>For the first seven hours, they staked out their positions, conferring in corridors... or closeting themselves away from others outside their own municipality. Gradually, all the suburban politicians congregated in one room, with occasional emissaries from Hamilton dispatched from the floor above. By midnight, everyone re-assembled for a last-ditch effort at reconciling their differences.  <br>But an hour later, the deal-making nearly collapsed, as Dundas and Flamborough walked out on the talks.  <br>The rest soldiered on, and at four-thirty this morning, they reached an historic agreement.  <br>Under the proposal, Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities will disappear, replaced by one, as yet un-named municipality, governed by one local council, with less than half the current number of politicians.  The former suburbs will retain their historic names, and have the choice of setting up community councils, to deal with local issues.  <br>In exchange for giving up their boundaries, the former suburbs will have the same number of seats on the new council as Hamilton has.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Dundas / Flamborough</b><p>
The new arrangement reflects the view of 85 percent of Hamilton Wentworth's residents.  But, as Deborah reported, two communities were thumbs down on the deal.  Dwight Ryan has their story..  
<i><br>  When the historic document was signed  some signatures were notably absent.<br>  Delegates from Dundas and Flamborough left in the middle of the night saying they could no longer take part in the process.<br>  Mediator Gardner Church respected their view saying their departure was magnificently civilized.  <br>  Flamborough mayor Ted McMeekin favours the deal and stayed till the end. But his two colleagues walked.<br>  Today a weary mayor McMeekin said he still likes the new arrangement.  <br>  The new supercity, with or without Dundas and Flamborugh comes into effect on January 1st, 1998.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Teachers Vote</b><p>
Whatever happens to school boards in the future, today, secondary teachers voted overwhelmingly to reject the Hamilton Public School Board's last offer.<br> They also voted 86-percent in favour of strike action.<br> Both votes were supervised by the Education Relations Commission, the provincial body overseeing teacher-board negotiations. the high school teachers will be in a legal position five days after giving the board notice.
<hr>
<b>Van Shooting</b><p>
Police in Niagara have relased the name of the murder victim found shot to death early yesterday morning in Fort Erie. He is 48-year-old Frederick Steven Grondin of Port Colborne.  Police say Grondin was last seen leaving the Donut Diner on Garrison Road in Fort Erie at about 5:15 yesterday morning. His body was found at the side of Highway Three about 15 minutes later. Between midnight and 4 a.m., he had been at the Plaice Restaurant Charity Casino. Police want to speak to anyone who saw Grondin in the 24 hours before he died... they also want to speak to the driver of a white pick up truck with dual wheels that was apparently at the scene where the body was discovered before police arrived.
<hr>
<b>Machete Sentence</b><p>
A Hamilton man who admitted to murdering his wife will not be eligible for parole for 15 years.<br>  Mr. Justice John Cavarzan, in sentencing 53 year old Carmelo Reyes, described the machete attack as an act of "appalling and unspeakable cruelty".<br>  47 year old Alba Fuentes-Reyes died after being struck by a van and struck repeatedly with a machete.<br>  Before his sentencing, Carmelo Reyes broke down momentarily, admitting he was wrong and was willing for pay for what he had done.
<hr>
<b>Inquest Goes</b><p>
An Ontario divisional court judge has rejected a bid by Hamilton's St. Elizabeth Villa to derail a coroner's inquest into the deaths of five residents last year. Judge John O'Driscoll called the application "vexatious, frivilous and entirely without merit". The inquest will proceed as scheduled, starting Tuesday. The villa claims the deaths were the result of natural causes and that the coroner plans to use the probe to push for changes in municpal bylaws that control how retirements homes are run.
<hr>
<b>Rick Hansen</b><p>
Finally tonight, Canadian hero Rick Hansen, was in Hamilton last night, as guest speaker at a fundraising dinner hosted by our own Paul Hendrick.<br> It's been ten years since his two year, 33-country Man in Motion tour came through Hamilton.<br> Hansen's 40-thousand kilometre trek raised more than 16-million dollars for spinal cord research.


<P>
