<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Thursday, November 7, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Fort Erie Murder    
    <li>Halton Fatal        
    <li>Burton Search       
    <li>Restructure Deadline
    <li>HSR Update       
    <li>Halton School Update
    <li>Noranda Closure
    <li>Seaway Jobs         
    <li>Guilty Poll         
    <li>Workers Museum      
    <li>Xmas Seal Launch    
    <li>Dunnigan - Davoe      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>fort erie murder</b><p>
Fort Erie has recorded its second murder in three weeks. <br>  This morning a man was found shot to death on highway three just outside of town.
 <br> Police are not yet releasing the victim's identity. But he is believed to be from Port Colborne.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  About 5:30 this morning residents who live in the area of Laur Road and Highway Three in Fort Erie were awakened by a series of shotgun blasts.<br>  A man who didn't want to be identified described what he he saw.<br>  At the same time a woman driving by called 911 when he say the body of a man on the shoulder of the road. <br>  It was a man in his 40's. He had been hit by a shotgun blast to the head. <br>  Detectives from the major crime unit and identification officers spent hours this morning gathering evidence.  Examining the body. Collecting items including spent shotgun shells from the scene.<br>  Residents who heard the blasts also say they saw a pickup truck speed away from the scene.<br>  It headed west on Highway Whree and then turned south down Stone Mill Road. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Halton Fatal</b><p>
"Very serious" is the way police in Halton describe the injuries to the driver of a mini-van that collided with a gravel truck on Ford Drive in Oakville near the auto plant today. They say that both vehicles were travelling in the same direction at the time... and are at a loss to explain why the mishap occurred. The truck driver was uninjured.
<hr>
<b>Burton Search</b><p>
Police in Hamilton Wentworth stepping up efforts in the search for a missing Stoney Creek woman. 41 year old Kathryn Burton disappeared October 3rd.<br> Police say she is unemployed and was depressed around the time of her disappearance.<br> A neighbour reported Burton missing from her apartment where she lived by herself.<br> If you know anything about the whereabouts of Kathryn Burton, you're asked to call police.
<hr>
<b>Restructure Deadline</b><p>
Tonight is a make-or-break night for Hamilton- Wentworth politicians, trying to agree on how to re-design local government in the region.<br>  As councillors prepared to meet behind closed doors for a third straight night tonight, a provincially- appointed mediator said it would only take a matter of hours to announce whether they'd reached concensus, or an impasse.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br> They're burning the candle at both ends... carrying on regional business by day, then bargaining over the future of Hamilton- Wentworth until midnight each night.  The regional chairman says as long as they're still talking, there's still hope.  <br>If there's any concensus, details will be released to the public. If there's an impasse, Church will head straight to Queen's Park and report to Ontario's municipal affairs minister. Whichever alternative comes to pass, the discussions that produce it remain locked behind closed doors.  </i>
<hr>
<b>HSR Update</b><p>
A mediator will try next week to avert a strike the could bring Hamilton busses to a halt during Grey Cup week.<br> Hamilton Street Railway bus drivers have set a November seventeenth strike deadline.<br> Union leaders say members have no intention of accepting concessions.<br> But Hamilton- Wentworth Region faces the possibility of another seven-million dollar cut from the province.<br> And at least one councillor believes the failure to accept concessions now, could ultimately lead to the death of the HSR.
<hr>
<b>Halton School Update</b><p>
Groups opposed to school closures in the Halton Region are joining forces to pressure trustees to keep them open.<br>  Six schools are scheduled to close, but the groups say its not the answer.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports from burlington.
<i> <br>     The children are singing in the gym at Lakeshore Public School in Burlington.<br>  They've been making music for generations at one of the city's oldest schools.  <br>    The board is facing a 24 million dollar shortfall.<br>  Parent groups from all six schools are joining forces to fight the cuts.<br>  They believe school closures are not the answer.   <br>  And so with a well organized campaign they are trying to convince trustees to vote against closures.   <br>       Still, the director of education believes closures are the answer.   <br>      Parent groups will have the opportunity to voice their opinions in communtiy meetings.<br>  A final answer from the board will come before Christmas.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Noranda Closure</b><p>
More than 200 employees at Fraserpapers may be looking for work if the company can't find a buyer for its Thorold mill.<br>  Mounting losses are promping the sale at the specialty papers mill.<br>  The mill only produces about half its capacity for specialty papers. It will take a multi million dollar capital investment to make the operation competitive.<br>  If a buyer isn't found by the end of January the mill will likely close.
<hr>
<b>Seaway Jobs</b><p>
Meanwhile no major job losses expected in Niagara when the St. Lawrence Seaway is turned over to a consortium in the new year. Seaway chief Glendon Stewart admits some local jobs could disappear and others might be contracted out.<br> But he says for the most part operations will remain the same.<br> The seaway employs 355 full-time employees in the Niagara Region with a payroll of 20 million dollars.
<hr>
<b>Guilty Poll</b><p>
All around the world, too many of us feel guilty about tour pleasures in life and that could make us sick. A survey conducted by associates for research into the science of enjoyment, or arise, questioned 4-thousand people about such indulgences as smoking, chocolate, drinking and lack of exercise and found we're plagued by guilt. Australaian were the most remorseful with 27 per cent showing angst about their indulgence; the Dutch feel the least guilt, at 13 per cent. Stress, arise believes, can undermine the positive benefits of enjoyment which can protect the immune system. The organization just warns of the dangers of overinulgence.
<hr>
<b>Workers Museum</b><p>
It's been in and out of the news for decades, and now another chapter is about to be written in the history of Hamilton's old Custom House.  After eight years, workers are putting the finishing touches to the Ontario Workers Arts and Heritage Museum, set to open tomorrow in the landmark northend building.<br>  Annette Hamm reports.
<i> <br>  There's a lot of work still to be done at the Ontario Workers Arts and Heritage Centre in north Hamilton.<br>  The floors need to be cleaned.  The elevator for disabled visitors has to be installed.<br>  But it's frenzied work like this that the centre is built on.<br>  It's the only museum of its kind in Canada designed to honour the everyday labourer.  <br>  Among the first displays, what a 1930's working class household would have looked like.<br>  An exhibit by Carole Conde and Karl Beveridge on the strike of 46 is still being set up.<br>  And upstairs there'll be a resource centre for labour.<br>  The building itself, Hamilton's old Custom House, is steeped in labour tradition.  <br>  The Ontario Workers Arts and Heritage Centre opens to the public Friday afternoon at 5:30.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Xmas Seal Launch</b><p>
Matt Hayes found himself in a sticky situation today. The Lung Association decided to have a little fun at the launch of their Christmas Seal Campaign.  Three teams pasted local celebreties with the christmas stamps in a three minute contest in the Spectator cafeteria. Spec columnist Wade Hemsworth and his team "The Airbags" won the competion. The Lung Association hopes you'll use your christmas seals on letters and packages instead this holiday season.
<hr>
<b>Dunnigan - Davoe</b><p>
Finally tonight, a few weeks ago we brought you the story of Justin Devoe, the little Hamilton boy battling brain cancer, with his mom Charlene at his side. Today, Justin gained another supporter, Ticat Matt Dunnigan dropped by the cancer centre at Henderson Hospital, while Justin was ungergoing his daily radiation treatment and presented him with a team sweater. Friends of the family have setup a fund to help pay some of the bills for Justin. All CIBC branches from Toronto to Niagara are accepting donations on the family's behalf.


<P>
