<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Wednesday, November 6, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>

<ul>
    <li>Hamilton - Charity  
    <li>Wesley Centre       
    <li>Ford Settles 
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Welland Scissors    
    <li>Domestic Assault    
    <li>Downtown Breakins   
    <li>MADD- Grey Cup  
    <li>Kids go to Work     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton - Charity</b><p>
We begin tonight with a good news story. <br> When it comes to giving to charity, the people of Hamilton- Wentworth have a lot to be proud of.
<br> Figures released by Statistics Canada indicate we are among the most benevolent in the country.<br> Dwight Ryan has the story.  
<i><br>  Canadians as a whole donated three and a half billion dollars to charities in 1995...that's up three percent from the year before.<br>  Seniors were the most generous, averaging 910 dollars, well above the national average of 650 dollars.<br>  The median donation, that which half were higher and half lower was 150 dollars.<br>  Surprisingly the highest median amount was St. John's Newfoundland at 220 dollars a person.  Next was Saskatoon Saskatchewan at 210 dollars followed by Hamilton at 200 dollars.  St. John New Brunswick and Windsor, Ontario were tied with Hamilton.  <br>  Whether its supporting the United Way, a hospital or just buying Girl Guide cookies, the people of Hamilton Wentworth take pride in the fact they are amongst the most generous in the country.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Wesley Centre</b><p>
The legal existence of a Hamilton drop-in centre, that sometimes shelters more than a hundred homeless people a night, has been questioned by staff at Hamilton City Hall.<br> Neighbourhood complaints about the centre prompted city staff to issue an "order to comply" against Wesley Urban Ministries.<br> But at a meeting today, staff conceded the city simply has no bylaw to control the location and operation of drop-in centres.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>It's lunch-time at Wesley Urban Ministries in Hamilton.  Up to two hundred people will stop in for a hot meal.  But neighbours are complaining about another Wesley Urban Ministries program... a drop-in centre for street people that's open from midnight to noon. The complaints are numerous enough that Hamilton city staff have questioned Wesley's right to operate the centre under its present zoning conditions.  <br>Allan says it's reached the point where anything that goes wrong in the Wesley neighbourhood is blamed on clients at the drop-in centre.  <br>After hearing an appeal from Wesley Urban Ministries, Hamilton aldermen learned there is no bylaw on the books governing the existence of drop-in centres. They've directed city staff to study the possibility of enacting one.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Ford Settles </b><p>
Autoworkers in Canada can breathe a collective sigh of relief tonight. They reached a tentative agreement with Ford just hours ahead of the union's strike deadline.  If ratified, the deal wraps up bargaining with the big three carmakers.  
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Falling interest rates fueled yet another record high close on the Toronto Stock Exchange today.<br> Canadian banks announced another cut in mortgage rates pulling borrowing costs down to 35-year lows.<br> A new Stoney Creek company plans to hire more people as it trys to keep up with the demand for its unique portable fence.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Welland Scissors</b><p>
A Welland man has been charged following a savage domestic dispute attack.<br> Thirty-six-year- old Linda Even was suffered scissor wounds to her forehead, arms, hands and thighs last night.<br> A man, who fled after the attack, was found by a police canine unit, with self-inflicted wounds.<br> Thirty-eight- year-old Paul Mercier, the woman's former common law husband, is charged with attempted murder.
<hr>
<b>Domestic Assault</b><p>
A Hamilton woman was taken to hospital with several cuts and bruises, and her common law husband arrested after a domestic assault early this morning in downtown Hamilton.<br> Police had to force their way into an apartment after someone called saying they saw the woman being forced down a flight of stairs and into the unit.<br> 24 year old James Mann is charged with forcible confinement and assault level two.
<hr>
<b>Downtown Breakins</b><p>
Four people in custody after a pair of break-ins at downtown Hamilton stores overnight.<br> Police nabbed three men running from "Discount Sellers" on King Street East.<br> 20 year old Kelly Frederick Charles of Toronto, and two 15 year olds from Hamilton are charged with break and enter with intent.<br> In the second break-in, an officer on patrol noticed a window shattered at "Unique Hair Design" on James Street, then spotted a man inside.<br> 31 year old Joseph Arnold Carter, of no fixed address is charged with break enter and theft.
<hr>
<b>MADD- Grey Cup</b><p>
Mothers Against Drunk Driving is warning Grey Cup revellers to take it easy during the Hamilton celebrations.<br>  At a news conference this morning at Ivor Wynne Stadium, representives of MADD kicked off their annual red ribbon campaign against drinking and driving.<br>  Alcohol plays a role each year in the Grey Cup celebrations, and the anti-drunk driving group is reminding partiers to act responsibly.  <br>  
<hr>
<b>Kids go to Work</b><p>
Across the nation today, grade nine students went to work.<br> No...there isn't a labour shortage ..just an opportunity for young people to spend one day in the work world with a parent, relative or friend. <br> All day we've had a number of young people learning about television news, and one in particular seems to have caught on pretty well...<br> Jamie West has the story...
<i><br>  This is Kelly, my cousin, she's fourteen and just like many of her friends, hasn't given much thought to what career path to follow....<br>  Today...however she'll give news reporting a try ...<br>  The newsroom veterans were happy to mix and mingle with a number of youngsters paired up with various members of the CHCH TV news team.<br>  But once the introductions were out of the way it was time to get to work... <br>   Our first stop was in Hamilton's industrial core, Dofasco, where Phil Smith spent the day teaching his daughter about the intricacies of being a production engineer in the coke ovens...<br>  Next stop the Hamilton Wentworth Roman Catholic Seperate School Coard.<br>  Michael Davidson like thousands of grade nine students in 6 provinces has spent the day with his dad superintendant of finance Tony Davidson...<br>  The three year old program has grown in popularity with educators and businesse alike, ...<br>  Now back to Kelly she learned about deadlines...<br>  How to manage her time...<br>  Get the interviews write the story...<br>  And then work with perhaps the most important members of the team the editors. And finally how to get the story to air.<br>  </i>


<P>
