<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><img src="../../../images/first_arch.gif" width=400 height=55 border=0 alt="First Edition News On-Line Archive"></CENTER>


<CENTER>
<H1>Tuesday, November 5, 1996</H1>
</CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>H.W. Restructure 
    <li>Niagara Restructure?
    <li>Welfare / Transit 
    <li>Brantford PUC
    <li>Reyes Verdict       
    <li>Missing Woman       
    <li>Burton St. Arson    
    <li>St. Elizabeth       
    <li>Flasher             
    <li>Bogus Bucks Niagara 
    <li>Success at Shaw     
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Hamilton Smoking    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>H.W. Restructure </b><p>
The face of local government in Hamilton- Wentworth could change significantly if a meeting underway in Hamilton at this hour produces results.
<br>  Provincially appointed mediator Gardiner Church has called together political delegations from every municipality in the region for a closed door meeting at a downtown Hamilton hotel. They're trying to find the common ground necessary to carry them to a united vision on restructuring local government. <br>The mediator has forbidden politicians from talking to reporters as long as there is hope they can reach a compromise.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Restructure?</b><p>
Meanwhile in the peninsula politicians are balking at the idea of a Niagara supercity.<br>  Twenty five years ago 26 towns in the Niagara amalgamated to form 12 municipalities and Niagara Region.<br>  And as Lauran Sabourin reports the feeling is that's enough change for now.
<i><br>  Niagara regional politicians started talking seriously about cost cutting last December.<br>  A committee was struck to look at ways where the region and municipalities could possibly save money. <br>  They were looking at sharing services. But one of the ideas that came up was that Niagara's 12 municipalities should be amalgamated into one huge city of Niagara.<br>  Niagara regional councillor Peter Partington chaired that municipal reform committee.<br>  He doesn't see the supercity option working in the peninsula.<br>  The 370 thousand people who live in Niagara have a strong affinity to their own town.<br> St. Catharines, Niagara Falls, Welland and the smaller communities all have their own identities. <br>  Even Niagara's regional chairman Brian Merrett isn't pushing for a one tiered regional government or city called Niagara.<br>  He realizes that Niagara is different from Toronto, different from Hamilton. Where community identity is very strong.<br>  The region has been looking forward.<br>  The Kitchen Report completed in 1989 had a vision for the year 2000. In his conclusions the author Harry Kitchen saw region wide government as a more efficient option. <br>  Pushing toward a Niagara supercity would only meet resistance right now.<br>  The region itself is 25 years old.<br>  As a political entity its still young.<br>  It's an idea that wouldn't work right now.<br>  But nobody's ruling out the larger city in the future.</i>
<hr>
<b>Welfare / Transit </b><p>
Municipalities, including Hamilton- Wentworth, will have to pay the full cost of public tranist, sewer and water services, if the Ontario government accepts the latest recommendations of its "who does what" commission.<br> In exchange, the province would foot the full bill for children's aid societies, and shelters for abused women.<br> Currently, the province pays half the cost of running the Hamilton Street Railway, down from seventy-five per cent just two years ago.   <br>  The region would also have to pick up the capital costs of buying new busses, a cost that is currently shared fifty-fifty with the province.
<hr>
<b>Brantford PUC</b><p>
A shake-up in Brantford.  City council there is moving ahead with plans to take-over management of the public utilities commission, in hopes of saving close to a million dollars a year in duplication of services.  The amalgamation is seen as the only way to deal with a total of nine million dollars in provincial cuts in recent years. Mayor Chris Friel says most of the PUC's 168 employees will not be affected. 14 senior management jobs will go though.<br> Commission chairman Ted Oliver  is hinting at fighting the plan.
<hr>
<b>Reyes Verdict</b><p>
A Hamilton man will be sentenced Friday after admitting to hacking his wife to death with a machete.<br> 53 year old Carmelo Reyes, pleaded guilty to a crime that crown attorney Denis Allan described as ``unbelievable brutality in a public place.''<br> In early December 1994, Alba Fuentes-Reyes was struck down by a van driven by her estranged husband and then slashed to death in front of her home.<br> The prosecution and defence jointly asked for a life sentence with no chance of parole for at least 15 years.<br> Several people rushed to defend the 47-year-old mother of four.<br> University student Alexander Lee, was treated for 26 stitches after he tried to stop the attack. He's been nominated for an award from the Carnegie Hero Fund out of Pennsylvia.
<hr>
<b>Missing Woman</b><p>
Police need help in locating a Stoney Creek woman, missing for more than a month now.<br> 41 year old Kathryn Burton was last seen October 3rd.<br> Police say she is unemployed and was depressed around the time of her disappearance.<br> A neighbour reported Burton missing from her apartment.<br> If you think you've seen Kathryn Burton, please call Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police at 546-4925.
<hr>
<b>Burton St. Arson</b><p>
Fire officials investigating another suspected arson in Hamilton's north end. Last month, police say a fire was deliberately set at the vacant Burton Street Markethon Flea Market.<br> Then last night witnesses say they saw a couple of teenagers running from the building just before flames shot out the second floor window.<br> Damage in this latest fire is estimated at 30-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>St. Elizabeth</b><p>
The owners of a Hamilton retirement home are going to court to try to stop an inquest into the deaths of five residents.  The inquest, called last March is scheduled to begin next week. St. Elizabeth Villa claims the deaths were the result of natural causes and the coroner hopes to use the probe to push for changes in municpal bylaws that control how retirements homes are run.
<hr>
<b>Flasher</b><p>
Police in St. Catharines are looking for a sex deviant. So far he has not harmed anyone.<br> Women who have encountered the man say he exposes himself and makes sexually suggestive comments, but doesn't try to touch them.<br> In the latest incident a woman says the man walked toward her wearing no pants or underwear.<br> He has also been seen driving a small red car that might have a baby seat in the back.<br> He is described as in his mid 30's with brown hair.<br> Police are warning women to be cautious if they are out at night.
<hr>
<b>Bogus Bucks Niagara</b><p>
A former nursing home manager from St. Catharines will be sentenced January 20th after pleading guilty in a funny money scheme.<br> Niagara regional and 10 other police services were involved in the investigation that turned up more than half-a-million dollars in the bogus dough.<br> Mary Grant made the money with the help of a high-tech copier.<br> An associate is already serving three-and- one-half years.<br> Grant's son Myles was sentenced to eight months.<br> He is also charged with planting a phony bomb at St. Catharines General Hospital October 3rd.
<hr>
<b>Success at Shaw</b><p>
It's been the real thing at the Shaw Festival in Niagara-on-the-Lake.<br>  and lots of it. So far revenues have hit a record-breaking 9.2 million dollars, surpassing last year's high by more than 160-thousand dollars.<br> Agatha Christie's, "The Hollow" has been such a success it is held over until November 24th.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
The party in Canadian financial markets grew wilder today with the dollar surging above 75 cents U.S.<br>  Interest yields paid on 30 year government bonds fell to their lowest level ever.<br>  Stocks smashed through new record highs led by more exraordinary gains in Canadian bank shares.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Smoking</b><p>
Could a smoking ban in restaurants actually increase business? <br> A new survey compiled by the Hamilton- Wentworth Public Health Unit seems to indicate just that.<br>  Annette Hamm explains.
<i><br>  It's just an estimate, but Hamilton Wentworth's healthy lifestyles branch says a smoking ban will bring in at least 685-thousand dollars to the region's hospitality industry.<br>  The numbers come from average restaurant receipts and a random telephone survey of smokers and non smokers.<br> That phone poll showed 27 per cent of Hamilton Wentworth residents smoke.  <br>  The region's telephone survey found 69 percent of restaurant customers who asked for non smoking seating found it unacceptable.<br>  Just over a third have left restaurants because they couldn't get a seat in the non smoking section.<br>  And 26 per cent have left restaurants because the smoke bothered them.<br>  The public health department will be meeting with Hamilton Wentworth municipalities later this month to come up with a draft bylaw to go smoke free by the year 2-thousand.<br>  </i>


<P>
