<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, November 4, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>













<ul>
    <li>Climate Change      
    <li>H.W. Restructure     
    <li>Hospital Pickets    
    <li>Porno Bust          
    <li>Fergus Murder       
    <li>Police Warning   
    <li>Senior Drivers      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Heart Matters       
    <li>Veteran's Week      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Climate Change</b><p>
It's been a chilly November but some Canadian scientists are worried it's getting too warm. <br> They've launched a study on the impact of global warming on the golden horseshoe.
<BR>They say the temperatures of the great lakes are rising, the water levels are falling and there in an increasing cloud of rain and smog blanketing southern Ontario.<br> Lauran Sabourin reports on day one of a two day conference on global warming in Toronto.
<i><br>  Floods, droughts, heat waves, scientists have no dought that global warming actually exists. <br>  This summer's flooding in Quebec is a event that scientists are looking at closely.<br>  The experts can't say with certainty that global warming contributed to the flooding conditions.<br>  But they are looking for weather patterns that point in that direction. <br>  Over the next two days environmentalists scientists, members of the insurance industry are meeting in Toronto to discuss what they can do to mitigate the impact of global warming on the golden horseshoe. <br>  Scientists in Canada are already seeing the impact of global warming in the north west part of the country.<br>  They predict that if the temperature of the earth continues to rise a few degrees the impact will be devastating.<br>  Not only will future generaations struggle simply t maintain a viable source of food in Canada.<br>  Future generations will struggle simply to survive. </i>
<hr>
<b>H.W. Restructure</b><p>
There is a changing political climate evolving in Hamilton- Wentworth. The regional chairman has cancelled tomorrow night's council meeting, so politicians can push ahead with talks aimed at streamlining local government.<br> A provincially- appointed mediator met individually with representatives of all six municipal councils on the weekend.<br>  Tomorrow, he'll bring all six together for another round of talks.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.<br>
<i> One suburban mayor describes Gardner Church favourably as a man in a hurry.  <BR>Evidently, Church has found reason to continue. Regional business will grind to a temporary halt with the cancellation of Tuesday night's council meeting. Instead, each of Hamilton- Wentworth's six municipalities will send a delegation to another round of negotiations, under the guidance of Church.  And there's probably good reason for political co-operation. Hamilton- Wentworth councillors are no doubt aware of the provincial government's proposal to merge Toronto's six municipalities into one super-city. But as long as Gardner Church is still on the job, Ontario's municipal affairs minister says it's premature to think about imposing the super-city model on Hamilton- Wentworth.  <BR>Leach says he expects a progress report from Church by the end of the week.  At that point, the two will decide how best to proceed. </i>
<hr>
<b>Hospital Pickets</b><p>
There was a picket outside Chedoke Hospital on Hamilton mountain today to protest the results of a changing hospital structure: contracting out housekeeping services. Their union claims that workers were threatened with disciplinary action if they participated in today's demonstration and that they've been replaced by minimum wage workers employed by contractor Marriott Incorporated. A CUPE national rep says that patient care will suffer as a result.
<hr>
<b>Porno Bust</b><p>
Police say they are shocked over the nature of computer child pornography seized in a major bust in northern Ontario, possibly the largest ever in North America. OPP seized 20-thousand computer files. A Kirkland Lake man has been charged. 
<hr>
<b>Fergus Murder</b><p>
A 52-year-old Fergus man appeared in court today, charged with the first-degree murder of his estranged wife.<br> Gordon Ray Abbott was arrested Saturday afternoon without incident.<br> Forty-year-old Patricia Abbot was shot several times with a small calibre weapon when she went home for lunch from her job as a legal secretary, October 23rd.
<hr>
<b>Police Warning </b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth police are urging doctors who perform abortions to be cautious in the wake of the anniversary of two shootings of Canadian gynecologists.<br> 63-year old Dr. Hugh Short was hit in the arm by a sniper's bullet last year as he sat with his wife in their Ancaster home. The bullet that struck short, who has yet to return to work, was fired from a ravine behind his house. It happened two days after the first anniversary of a Vancouver abortion doctor's near fatal wounding by a sniper. Police in Hamilton- Wentworth have implemented additional security measures but are not offering any details.
<hr>
<b>Senior Drivers</b><p>
For seniors over 80, it was an annual worry.<br> Now the Ontario government has replaced the mandatory drivers test with a group education session every two years. As Annette Hamm reports, transportation minister Al Palladini says the new program will help keep seniors mobile, and our roads safe.<br> 
<i>> For the past three years, 83 year old Joe Shepherd has had to take a driver's examination to prove his skills are up to speed.<br>  While he says the test hasn't been stressful for him, it is for many seniors.<br>  It's hoped this class will put an end to that.<br>  These seniors are part of the first driver education session in Ontario, interupted for a P.R. appearance by the two ministers responsible for the program.  <br>  Every two years now, drivers 80 years and over will take a vision and knowledge test, part of a 90 minute group session focussing on issues facing older drivers.  <br>  Transportation minister Al Palladini expects only about ten percent of the drivers who take the new session will have to take a road test.<br>  His ministry is also looking at introducing sessions for drivers under 80.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
With the anticipation of yet another reduction in Canadian interest rates, investors shifted more money into blue chip Canadian stocks today.<br>  The value of shares in Toronto rose to the 51st record of they year.<br> <hr>
<b>Heart Matters</b><p>
Heart attacks are growing in numbers...and as the baby boom generation turns grey those numbers will likely double or triple current rates. <br> The Hamilton Public Health Unit has been reaching out to heart attack victims with a support program called "Heart Matters".  As Jamie West reports, it's helping dozens of people to regain their confidence...
<i><br>  That's why they meet every month at St. Joeseph's Health Centre...<br>  They're all victims of heart attacks... <br>  But it's other common experiences they've come to share...<br>   In the case of Audrey Hickling she didn't suffer the heart attack, but suffers the consequences of her husband Doug's....<br>  But Doug has risen to regain his life and he credits the heart matters program ...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Veteran's Week</b><p>
Finally tonight, Jean Chretien has declared this week, Veteran's Week in Canada. <br> In Hamilton, the downtown Veteran's Affairs offices opened it's doors to host an informal open house.<br> Veteran's and their families, legion members, schools and the general public were welcomed in to revisit the stories of glory and sacrifice that Canadian soldiers made during decades of confict throughout the world.<br> Of great concern to veteran's this year is that many of Canada's young people have forgotton or have little knowledge of Canada's contribution to the preservation of freedom...


