<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 11/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, November 1, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>














<ul>
    <li>Mac Fundraising     
    <li>Violence Concludes  
    <li>Stelpipe Strike     
    <li>Cop Relatives       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Principal on Roof   
    <li>Cape Breton Choir   
    <li>Neil Young          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Mac Fundraising</b><p>
A Hamilton MP is screaming for legislation today, that makes charities more financially accountable to the public. <br> Hamilton Wentworth Liberal MP, John Bryden is claiming that in many cases less than 30 percent of money raised gets used as donors intended.

<br> Among the examples he sites --- Hamilton's Chedoke McMaster Hospitals Foundation.... Jamie West has the story...
<i><br>  Stop the music says John Bryden less than half that amount actually goes to patient care furthermore...the majority of the cash has been paying for the costs of the telethon and lately the 818-thousand dollar severance package given to Chedoke McMaster's former CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman .. <br>  Although Bryden took his figures from a 1994 tax return filed by the hospital, the foundation insists Bryden's accounting is way off and less than 25 cents on the dollar goes to cover administration costs...<br>  Bryden is sticking to his guns and insists new legislation is long overdue to ensure better accountability...<br>  After their fixed costs the foundation says the money they raise only goes to patients...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Violence Concludes</b><p>
There was no budget for this. in fact the rule was, these solutions couldn't cost a dime. But tonight, 100 citizens of Hamilton- Wentworth have a new mission. Educators, doctors, nurses, councillors, students and broadcasters who have each agreed to take on a project to help stop violence in their communities.                         Among the commitments by CHCH-TV at the conference: to set up a public stakeholers consultation process, including an advisory committee focusing on standards for our news and sports and we will work to improve our news coverage to promote a better understanding of the causes and effects of violence.
<i><br>  Two days of talking, defining identifying specific issues,  devising, refining, specific practical do-able actions.  The end result, a lot of paper to be recycled and a grassroots collaborative plan these 100 citizen delegates believe can help create a more positive environment in our schools, our streets, our homes, an environment that will help end the cycle of violence, the experts say is perpetuated by images and sounds like these.  <BR>A student media relations committee to promote positive achievements by our young people for others to emulate.... nutrition programs in schools to curb the problems caused by empty stomachs, improved access to recreation for at risk youth, and more training for coaches, community councils to bring nieghbourhoods together.  Could the solutions be so simple. It may take months or even years to implement all the actions committed to this week but this group says just give it a chance.</i>
<hr>
<b>Stelpipe Strike</b><p>
Four hundred workers at Stelpipe's Page Hersey plant in Welland are walking the picket line this evening.<br> They're contract expired at midnight.<br> And as Lauran Sabourin reports the key issue in this dispute is money.
<i><br>  They gathered for an informal rally in front of the Stelpipe plant gate this morning.<br>  Four hundred plant employees in a legal strike position walked off the job at midnight. <br>  They're looking for a better pension package.<br>  A package that gives them parity with other Stelco divisions.<br>  They're looking for a wage increase.<br>  Stelpipe's Page Hersey plant produces half inch to 16 inch pipe for oil and gas transmission and other industrial uses.<br>  The company's third quarter report for 1996 says that Stelpipe has shown a 25 percent increase in sales over the previous quarter.<br>  Ammunition the union is using to bolter it's position that the company can afford to pay them more. <br>  In a statement released today Stelpipe simply acknowledged there was a strike. But said little else..<br>  The union memebers sense this strike may be a long one.<br>  The company issued a notice saying that the members insurance policy had expired. <br>  The last strike at Stelpipe was in 1987. That lasted for three and half months.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cop Relatives</b><p>
Last night we told you how Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police were looking for relatives of two officers who died on duty in the 1920's.<br> Friends and family of both men have now come forward.<br> Constable Reg Pryor died in 1921 when he swerved on his motorcycle to avoid a pedestrian in downtown Hamilton.<br> In 1929, Constable Fred Raynes died when a streetcar hit his motorcycle.<br> Police wanted those close to the men to be present when they honour both constables at a date to be announced.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Foreign investors are in love with Canada and right now they can't buy enough Canadian dollars.<br>  The loonie is on the threshold of breaking through 75 cents U.S.<br>  That is allowing Canadian interest rates to drop further.  
<hr>
<b>Principal on Roof</b><p>
Students at a private school in Burlington sent their principal through the roof today.<br> Bob Euesden promised students at Park Academy that if they'd raise 15-thousand dollars for the school, he'd spend a day on the roof.<br> Well, the students reached their goal, and Mr. Euesden spent a chilly day perched on top of Park Academy.<br> More than 180 students participated in a family day and walkathon earlier in the school year, raising 15-thousand, 9-hundred dollars.<br> The money will go towards the school's budget.
<hr>
<b>Cape Breton Choir</b><p>
Cape Breton's world renowned "Men of the Deeps" went deep into Dofasco's shipping yards today for an inprompteau performance.<br> Dofasco is sponsoring the choir's performance at Hamilton Place Saturday night.<br> That show is completely sold out, so the "Men of the Deeps" stopped by the steel company's shipping yard to to belt out a few bars.<br> Members of the choir are all working or retired coal miners from Cape Breton who joined to preserve the rich folklore of that island's mining communities.
<hr>
<b>Neil Young</b><p>
There were plenty of slick tricks, and musical treats as Canadian rock n roll icon Neil Young and his band Crazy Horse rolled into steeltown's Copps Coliseum with a Halloween concert last night. A somewhat disappointing audience of about eight-thousand attended. But those who traded Halloween for Young had no regrets.  


<P>
