<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/31/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, October 31, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>













<ul>
    <li>Violence conf.      
    <li>Health Corp         
    <li>Redland Fini        
    <li>Ancaster Fire       
    <li>Ancaster Crash      
    <li>Truck Accident      
    <li>Masked Robber       
    <li>Bricks Follow       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>1920's Cops         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Violence Conf.</b><p>
There was a declaration of war in Hamilton today, a war on violence. But the battles will be peaceful ones, fought at the neighbourhood level using dialogue as ammunition.  
<br> A two-day conference called Stop the Violence opened in Hamilton today, to develop a plan of action at the neighbourhood level to reduce violence in our schools, our homes, and our streets. And these ordinary citizens are doing it with no more money and no new laws.                                 <br> Some examples of the actions conference participants are considering: in schools, more parental involvement, nutrition programs, protecting early childhood education and teaching media literacy. In sports, promoting positive adult role models, improved training for coaches, rewarding participants, other than winner. In public safety and security: expanding community-based policing, a violence education program for parents, and an advisory group to help CHCH-TV guide programming standards.  Tomorrow conference participants will refine and evaluate a plan of action and CHCH-TV will be there for the results.
<hr>
<b>Health Corp</b><p>
A new era in health care is officially underway in Hamilton.<br> The new Hamilton Health Sciences Corporation held it's first board meeting after the Hamilton Civics and Chedoke McMaster Hospitals merged earlier this month.<br> As Jamie West reports...public accountability and openess will be a priority.
<i><br>  These new board members are getting the nickle tour of Henderson General Hospital one of four facilities they will now help to govern...<br>  The board is comprised of 26  members including 6 each from the Civics and Chedoke McMaster.  Other members include regional chairman Terry Cooke and Hamilton mayor Bob Morrow. Hamilton city council is asking for two additional members to better ensure public accountability... <br>  A number of housekeeping items were on the first agenda of board of trustees including the appointment of a new chief of staff.<br>  He will be Dr. William Shragge a respected cardiac surgeon.<br>  The merged hospital's new CEO Dr. Scott Rowand says patients will benefit from the merger.<br>  Another more contentious item the board is dedaling with behind closed doors is the matter of severances and salaries. Word is a new policy is being hashed out that will prevent a repeat of the controversy that plagued Chedoke McMaster Hospitals recently over the 818-thousand dollar severance shelled out to former CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Redland Fini</b><p>
They're toasting their health in Greensville tonight. A ten year battle against a landfill site has ended in victory.<br> The provincial government officially declared today that the Redland Quarry proposal was dead.<br> Dwight Ryan was there for the announcement.
<i><br>  It was a community nightmare. Redland Quarries hoped to turn this defunct mine this site into 26 million tonnes of industrial waste.<br>  Residents were assured there would be no environmental problems.<br>  But,  after 140 days of municipal and environmental assessment hearings,  it was decided the dump wouldn't go ahead.<br>   The community celebration was short lived as Redland Quarries appealed to the provincial cabinet.  Now it was time for an answer.  <br>  Local MPP Tony Skarica campaigned against the dump.   <br>    The man who led the fight against the dump was delighted..yet conciliatory.   <br>    And for once someone (albeit) in disguise, held a sign praising the Mike Harris government.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Fire</b><p>
An early morning fire in rural Ancaster has gutted a farmhouse. Fire fighters say the home on Powerline Road was totally engulfed in flame when they arrived on the scene shortly after five this morning. There was no one in the house, and the cause is under investigation.<br> Damage is listed at more than 150 thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Crash</b><p>
While fighting that blaze, Ancaster fire officials were called to a multi-vehicle crash on Highway Two, at Shavers Road. It resulted in a number of minor injuries, and firefighters had to use the jaws of life to pry one victim from his car.<br> Ambulance crews then rushed him to hospital for emergency treatment of serious but not life-threatening injuries.
<hr>
<b>Truck Accident</b><p>
A dump truck driver is lucky to be alive after his truck rammed into the back of a transport on the QEW in Niagara Falls this afternoon.<br> The driver had to be extricated from the crushed cab.  He suffered serious leg injuries.<br> The driver of the transport was treated for cuts to his face.<br> The QEW at Sand Plant Hill was closed for about an hour.<br> Niagara Falls bound traffic was being diverted onto Highway 405. The accident is still under investigation.
<hr>
<b>Masked Robber</b><p>
A warning to trick or treaters tonight not to run with masks on their head.<br> A robbery suspect in Hamilton did just that last night, and ended up falling on his face.<br> He was running away from the Tabby Variety in downtown Hamilton, where he had tried, unsuccessfully to grab some cash with a plastic bag over his head.
<hr>
<b>Bricks Follow</b><p>
City inspectors in Hamilton will be examining all high rise buildings in with brick facades like the one that collapsed Tuesday, sending 50 tons of bricks crashing down on the street below. Luckily no one was hurt. The construction technique is rarely seen anymore, but city officials are not sure how many buildings share the design, and want to determine if there are any potential safety concerns.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stock prices roared to their 50th record high close so far this year.<br>  Stocks were propelled higher by falling interest yields on government bonds. Despite falling interest rates, the Canadian dollar strengthened to its strongest level in a year.  
<hr>
<b>1920's Cops</b><p>
Finally tonight, Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police want to honour two of their own, but need some help.<br> They're trying to get the names of two constables, both killed in the 1920's, added to the police memorial in Ottawa for officers killed while serving their community.<br> Now they need help locating the officers relatives.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  Before the use of patrol cars in the 1950's, motorcycles were the vehicle of choice for Hamilton police.<br>  But helmets were unheard of.<br>  29 year old constable Reg Pryor died in 1921 when he swerved on his motorcycle to avoid a pedestrian at King and Sanford in downtown Hamilton.<br>  Four years later, a streetcar hit the motorcycle ridden by 31 year old constable Fred Raynes.<br>  Both officers were honoured with police funerals, but Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police have no records of the incidents.  <br>  When constables Pryor and Raynes are honoured, police would like their relatives to be present.<br>  They're hoping anyone with information will call the central police station at 546-4707.<br>  </i>



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

