<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, October 30, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>












<ul>
    <li>Winds/Accident      
    <li>Bricks Follow        
    <li>Mountain Fire       
    <li>Turned in Kid       
    <li>Beach Robbery       
    <li>NHL Again           
    <li>Hamilton Medical    
    <li>Chedoke Petition    
    <li>Dofasco 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Winds/Accident</b><p>
A storm packing 100 kilometer winds has hit much of the province of Ontario.  In northern regions, salters and sanders are battling ice and snow. In the golden horseshoe it's winds gusting to 100-kilometers an hour that have proven fatal.
<br>
Three people were killed in a two-vehicle collision in Thorold when a car entered an intersection that was missing a stop sign. The accident occurred at Merrittville Highway and Holland Road.<br>   Police say the car was hit broadside by a dump truck, killing the three occupants.<br>   The two occupants of the truck were taken to hospital with injuries that are described as non-life threatening.<br>   Police say they aren't sure if the winds blew the sign away or it was stolen.<br>  In downtown Hamilton the gusts have created an extremely dangerous situation.<br>  Pains of glass from some highrise office towers have lossened, some have even blown out sending them crashing to the street below.<br>  Throughout the province power lines and trees have been downed and motorists are being urged to be extremely careful.<br>  Even though the high winds are expected to die down overnight a high wind warning from the Ontario Provincial Police remains in effect for the Burlington Skyway Bridge and the Garden City Bridge in St. catharines.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Bricks Follow</b><p>
The high winds making clean-up efforts difficult at the site of the 13 storey apartment building downtown Hamilton that lost the bricks off one side yesterday.<br> Engineers and architects spent the day removing the rest of the facade and checking inside the apartments involved.  The property ownrs are waiting for the results of an engineering report looking into the cause.<br> In the meantime, the city building department has determined there is no structural damage or danger to any tenants.
<hr>
<b>Mountain Fire</b><p>
Fire officials were to sift through the ashes of an overnight blaze at a new home under construction on the east Hamilton mountain. They're trying to determine how the fire was sparked but they think it was the work of an arsonist.<br> No one was hurt, but damage extensive with estimates  at upwards of 300-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Turned in Kid</b><p>
Checking the police file now, a pair of Dundas grandparents decided the law should handle their 14 year old grandson.<br> They found marijuana and a pair of ninja throwing stars in the boy's possession and marched him into the Dundas Police Station last night, where the teen was charged with possesion of marijuana and possession of a probibited weapon.
<hr>
<b>Beach Robbery</b><p>
A man's been charged with robbery after an unusual confrontation on Hamilton's beach front.<br> Police say the suspect pulled up beside another vehicle in the parking lot of Hutch's Restaurant, and started yelling at the driver about his driving habits.<br> He then reached into the car and took off with the victim's glasses and cell phone.<br> Charged is 48 year old Zenon Gluckowski of Hamilton.
<hr>
<b>NHL Again</b><p>
The city of Hamilton will put its assets where its mouth is in its efforts to lure an NHL team here. Last night, city council gave its entertainment branch the go-ahead to bid for a team, and agreed to use city assets to prove it's good for 75-million dollars. Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <br>Hamilton Spectator publisher Pat Collins handed city council a cheque for 100-thousand dollars, money that will be delivered to the NHL in New York City Friday, as part of Hamilton's application for an expansion team.  And the bid will be submitted by HECFI, the city corporation that runs Copps Coliseum, Hamilton Place and the Convention Centre.  <br>And the city of Hamilton will promise to deliver the money needed to pay the franchise fee.  <br>If Hamilton beats the odds, and is actually awarded an expansion team, mayor Bob Morrow is certain the city can unload it.  If not, Hamilton taxpayers will own the team, and HECFI will run it.  <br>But before any of this can happen, Hamilton must petition the province to change the legislation that created HECFI, and currently prohibits HECFI from owning any property, including a hockey team.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Medical</b><p>
Ontario doctors are putting together a bid of their own right now, a last minute offer to their leadership aimed at avoiding a mass withdrawal of services on Friday.<br> The new offer could give health minister Jim Wilson a way out of a dilemma.<br> His ministry faces the prospect of shelling out millions of dollars for contingency plans if the doctors withdraw their services.<br> Jamie West reports that most Hamilton and Halton doctors say no one's life will be jeopardized...
<i><br> Sticking it to them...that's how doctors especially young interns in Ontario feel about a tentative deal reached between the Ministry of Health and the Ontario Medical Association...<br>  Under the agreement not yet ratified...many new Ontario doctors could be forced to work in underserved parts of northern and southern Ontario ...<br>  A group within the OMA is now racing toward a last minute committment by the government to keep negotiating in exchange for a recommendation to it's members to hold off on Friday's job action. Dr. David Wismer an orthopeadic surgeon say's the government's original refusal to recognize the OMA as a negotiating body has delayed a meeting of minds.<br>  Many doctors are threatening to refuse new patients, to withdraw from hospital service and to cancel all but emergency surgeries.<br>  Meanwhile the OMA is still sorting out the results of polling on the tentative agreement in Toronto...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Chedoke Petition</b><p>
A 3-hundred- and-5 name petition, calling for a public inquiry into the brain injury program at Hamilton's Chedoke-McMaster Hospital, is now in the hands of the Ministry of Health.<br> MPP Toni Scarica accepted the petition this morning in Hamilton, and was to present it this afternoon at Queen's Park.<br> Wendy Littlejohn, alleges her son Timothy was abused while enrolled in the program.<br> She wants some answers.
<hr>
<b>Dofasco </b><p>
Dofasco of Hamilton today reported a profit of more than 50 million dollars in this year's third quarter.<br>  At the same time the company unveiled its new electric arc furnace mini mill that began operating in Hamilton last month.<br>   President John Mayberry also announced Dofasco will spend 14 million dollars to build a tube mill in Hamilton that will make high pressure tubing for the auto industry.




<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

