<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, October 29, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>











<ul>
    <li>Building Collapse   
    <li>Flag Dispute        
    <li>Female Bandit       
    <li>Computer Theft      
    <li>Ancaster B & E      
    <li>Bawdy House         
    <li>Homicide I.D.       
    <li>Awards Night        
    <li>Linc - Race         
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Building Collapse</b><p>
Some Hamilton residents will be spending the night in temporary quarters while officials secure their homes.   It's a mystery that began this morning when a deafening crash rocked the downtown core, sending residents and business people scurrying into the streets, wondering what had happened?
<BR> At this hour, there is still no explanation for the possible cause of the collapse of most of the brick facade on one wall of a 13-storey downtown Hamilton apartment building. As Anthony Pooley reports tonight thankfully, no one was hurt by the falling brick.
<i><br>  It happened without warning and for no apparent reason ... most of the clay brick facade over a concrete wall of this apartment building at Forest and John Streets simply fell off, as tenants inside felt tremors and heard noise consistent with a minor earthquake. Fortunately, it started at the bottom and fell stragiht down limiting the spread of debris to the roof over the building's underground garage... with some spillage out onto John Street. Surprisingly, no one was hurt... and no vehicles were damaged. Even so, crews will clean up the debris by hand as part of standard rescue procedure ... even though there is virtually no likelihood that anyone was buried by the bricks. <br>  The structure is 25-years old and that was the original brick work. The building is well maintained. Engineers couldn't explain why the wall's brick veneer collapsed... and neither can the building owner's property manager. <br>  Meanwhile, this block of John Street will remain closed for the time being... while work continues to remove the remaining danger hovering above. Tenants who were evacuated are to be allowed to return... since the building real concrete wall remains intact and structurally sound.</i>
<hr>
<b>Flag Dispute</b><p>
In Brantford, another home is at the centre of a controversy tonight. And it has a Brantford woman more determined than ever to fly her Canadian flag outside her townhouse.<br> The single mom says its in honour of her grandfather.  But condo residents says its a disgrace..and that its only there to support a C.B. radio antenna.<br> Dwight Ryan has a report on the Brantford flag flap.  <br>  
<i>Tens of thousands of Canadians travelled across Canada to show their support for national unity.<br>  Just days before the Quebec Eeferendum, the show of national pride was nothing short of phenomenal.<br>  At the centre of that pride was the Canadian flag.   <br>    This is the flag, mounted outside the three story residence of Sue Saraceni.<br>  Condo rules however say no structures outside.   <br>  But Sue says she put it up legally.  <br>  Not good enough says neighbour Ede Simmons-Karolyi.   <br>    In Ottawa, local MP Jane Stewart tried to stay clear of the conflict, but..   <br>  Still condo residents say Sue's flag was put up to comouflage a C.B. radio antenna thats messing up their cable t.v. and cordless phones.<br>  The flag's out the front now, the antenna protrudes through a bedroom window.     </i>
<hr>
<b>Female Bandit</b><p>
An eighteen-year -old girl appeared in a Milton courtroom this afternoon charged with five counts of robbery. Her arrest yesterday follows a month-long investigation into a string of bank robberies in Milton. Halton police struck "target team" to try to catch a female suspect wanted in connection with seven robberies.<br> Yesterday's arrest of Lorraine Esther Chicoine of Brampton followed a robbery at a Toronto Dominion branch on Main St. in Milton staked out by police as a likely target.<br> The suspect was apprehended by target team members as she tried to enter a vehicle.
<hr>
<b>Computer Theft</b><p>
Halton police are hoping this surveillance video will bring about the arrest of two computer thieves smashing their way into a Brighton Road business in Oakville.<br> The culprits made off with a Macintosh computer central processing unit worth more than two thousand dollars.<br> Halton police hope that someone may be able to identify these individuals.<br> If you can help call the Halton Regional Police break and enter squad at 825-4747 extension 2216, or Crime Stoppers at 825-8477, that's 825-tips.
<hr>
<b>Ancaster B & E</b><p>
A rude awakening for an Ancaster father last night.<br> After hearing noises in his son's room he found three teens ransacking the place.<br> They fled, but one left behind a knapsack with his name in it.<br> A 15 year old Ancaster boy has been charged with break and enter with intent.<br> Further investigation revealed the same teen was also involved in a house entry the night before.<br> He's charged with break and enter in that incident.
<hr>
<b>Bawdy House</b><p>
A Hamilton couple facing charges after a nearly three month long investigation in Stoney Creek.<br> Police say undercover officers were offered sexual services for a fee at a King St. West, Stoney Creek address during that time.<br> After executing a search warrant, they've charged 50 year old Cheryl Lees and 51 year old Phil Lees with keeping a common bawdy house.
<hr>
<b>Homicide I.D.</b><p>
An autopsy has revealed that a Fort Erie homicide victim died of multiple stab wounds to the heart.  The body of 43 year-old Maurice Chin was found inside a Cherrywood Avenue residence Saturday.   Chin was the father of five who had been employed as an independent broker for a courier service. Police say Chin was an acquaintence of the man charged with his murder, 33-year-old Daniel Norman Schell of Crystal Beach. Schell is to appear in court in St. Catharines, Thursday.
<hr>
<b>Awards Night</b><p>
Eleven people who risked their lives to help others were recognized at a special ceremony at Hamilton city hall last night.<br> The Hamilton Safety Council awarded eight civilians, two police officers and a firefighter.<br> Each individual was honoured with a plaque with their name inscribed and a brief description of their selfless act.<br> The recipients were Brian O'Donnell, Mike Joy, Denise Leonard, Sophie Sporbeck, Nick Procailo, Mary Spilchuk, Michael Bowker, Barbara Jean Shaver and her husband Steven, Dan Reid and his sons Michael and John, and Matthew Horyn.
<hr>
<b>Linc - Race</b><p>
Another prestige appointment for the honourable Lincoln Alexander.<br> Prime minister Jean Chretien today appointed the former Hamilton West M.P. as chairman of the Canadian Race Relations Foundation.<br> Mr. Alexander has held a number of government posts and was Ontario Lieutenant Governor from 1985 to 1991.<br> The recipient of many awards and honours, Mr. Alexander is a companion of the Order of Canada and a member of the Order of Ontario.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Almost 100 different companies from across Hamilton Wentworth are represented at Business Expo "96" at the Hamilton Convention Centre. The region's new business information network is also featured at the show. <br> 



<P>
