<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/28/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, October 28, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>











<ul>
    <li>N.H.L. Update       
    <li>Church - Restructure  
    <li>Youth Chase         
    <li>Westdale Grabber    
    <li>BC Escapee          
    <li>Liberal Convention  
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>N.H.L. Update</b><p>
The city of Hamilton is once again going after an NHL franchise.<br>  The deadline for bids, in what could be the last league expansion, is this Friday.<br>  And Hamilton will be there with a one hundred thousand dollar application fee and the promise of 75 million dollars if the team is awarded.<br>  Dwight Ryan has the story.  
<i><br>  People in the steel city love NHL hockey.  Not only that, Hamilton has, in Copps Coliseum, one of the finest venues for professional hockey in North America.<br>  So officials here are not giving up on their bid to get a team.<br>  The Hamilton Spectator has offered a hundred thousand dollars U.S. for the application fee. The bid goes in Friday in New York and officials say they're ready.    <br>    HECFI, the group that oversees the city's entertainment facilities will present its report to city councillors Tuesday night.<br>  With expected unanimous approval, the application will go to the NHL in New York on Friday.   <br>    The National Hockey League is expected to award four new franchises when they meet in Phoenix in December.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Church - Restructure</b><p>
A provincially- appointed mediator says it will take only a matter of days to decide if Hamilton- Wentworth politicians are willing to try to end their deadlock over municipal government reform.<br>  Gardner Church arrived in Hamilton today, and immediately began soliciting opinions from politicians, cab drivers, even people he met on the street.<br>  He wants the broadest view possible of what's right and what's wrong with our various layers of municipal government.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.<BR>
<i> Gardner Church won't waste time in Hamilton- Wentworth, if he encounters political inflexibility on the issue of reforming local government.  <BR>That kick will be delivered by Queen's Park, and a government disinterested in the long-time provincial practice of bailing out inefficient municipalities. Church says he does sense Hamilton- Wentworth politicians are willing to at least explore opportunities for reform.  <BR>Just don't expect Church to keep an open mind.  He says an open mind is like a vacant mind, and he has definite views on the need for local governments to be accountable, and cost-conscious. </i>
<hr>
<b>Youth Chase</b><p>
Checking the police file tonight, a stolen car with five teenagers inside crashed on Hamilton mountain this morning during a police chase.<br>  The car reached speeds of 70 km an hour, then hit a median after an officer tried to pull them over.<br>  All five bolted from the car after the crash, but were eventually nabbed.<br>  The 17 year old driver is charged with dangerous driving and possession over five-thousand dollars.<br>  Police say a 12 year old boy, two girls aged 13 and 14 and a 15 year old boy inside the car had all been reported missing by their families.
<hr>
<b>Westdale Grabber</b><p>
Police in west Hamilton on the lookout for a man wanted for fondling two 21 year old female McMaster University students.<br> In both cases, the description of the suspect matches. The suspect is described as a short, middle aged man who smokes and walks with a hunch.<br>  The latest incident occured late last night, and another student was grabbed three weekends ago.
<hr>
<b>BC Escapee</b><p>
And an escapee from British Columbia's electronic monitoring program is back in custody after a fight in Hamilton.<br>    32 year old Mark Culp of no fixed address faces a number of charges, including assault with a weapon and possession of burglary tools. Two women and a man confronted another man as he was trying to break into a car over the weekend. The suspect turned a screwdriver on them during the fight, then ran away, right in the direction of an oncoming police officer.
<hr>
<b>Liberal Convention</b><p>
The federal Liberal's four-day policy convention in Ottawa closed with a pep rally for an election. The prime minister told delegates he could call the vote any time during the next two years. But senior Liberals expect he'll most likely call it next year.<br>   The two-thousand delegates produced only one surprise over the weekend -- they backed a non-binding resolution to legalize support doctor-assisted suicide. Chretien admitted it's a delicate issue that won't be resolved swiftly.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
As expected, the Bank of Canada lowered the trend setting bank rate by a quarter of a percentage point today.<br>   Canadian chartered banks will cut their prime rates by the same amount to a 40-year low of five per cent, effective tomorrow.   



<P>
