<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, October 25, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Toronto Protest       
    <li>Protest - Hamilton  
    <li>School Closures     
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Booze Bust          
    <li>St. Kitts Fire      
    <li>Catholics - 2000    
    <li>Jennya Leaves       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Toronto Protest</b><p>
Day one is done. Labour and social groups tried to shut-down Canada's largest city.  They say they did it. But premier Harris wonders just what was accomplished. 
<hr>
<b>Protest - Hamilton</b><p>
Two busloads of Hamilton steelworkers left early this morning to take part in the protest. They stopped first at S.A. Armstrong to show support for those on strike against that company... then continued on to Bay Street and the stock exchange. 
<hr>
<b>School Closures</b><p>
This is one of the reasons for todays protest: cuts to education front and centre in Halton last night...as the board of education released its hit list of schools slated for closure and the auction block... and as ian dovey reports.                                
<I><br>  Bob Williams the director of education says it's never an easy decision to close schools.<br>  But faced with a financial crisis, the Halton Board of Education says it must close facilities and sell property.<br>  A staff report recommends the following schools be closed: In Burlington; Fairfield, Lakeshore, Mohawk and Mountain Gardens.<br>  In Oakville, Oakwood...and in Milton Percy w. Merry Public School.<br>  Sale of the following schools is recommended; Elizabeth Gardens, Fairfield, H. Wrigglesworth, John A. Lockhart, Lakeshore, Mohawk, Mountain Gardens, Oakwood, Percey W. Merry, Speyside and Woodside. <br>     Some board staff members and parents were relieved...others were obviously disappointed. <br>     Halton's two vocational high schools, General Brock in Burlington and General Wolfe in Oakville will remain open and become adult education centres. <br>      The staff report is also recommending Aldershot, Central, Nelson and Lord Elgin High Schools implement grades seven to O.A.C. inorder to remain open.<br>  Teaching staff and class sizes are not expected to change.<br>  However, there could be principal, secretarial and custodial lay-offs.<br>  Further public input will be allowed before the board makes the closure and sales of these schools before December 19th.<br>  </I>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
For the second day in row the value of Canadian shares edged lower. the dollar and interest rates remained stable.<br>  Market watchers expect the Bank of Canada to lower the trend setting bank rate as early as next week. 
<hr>
<b>Booze Bust</b><p>
It could be a dry December, for those accustomed to tippling tax-free booze, in southern Ontario. The RCMP has moved in to smash a major bootlegging operation, that was smuggling truckloads of American liquor across the border. As Scot Urquhart reports; many of those arrested, live in the Hamilton area:
<i><br>  This, is just a fraction of the contraband seized in this region, over the last few months. In total ... some 16-hundred cases of illegal booze. ... half a million dollars worth ....  guns, drugs, money too, and the paraphenalia of sophisticated smugglers. <br>   Some 45 thousand trucks a month cross the border between the U.S. and Canada .... one percent of them, are carrying contraband. This ring preferred to bring booze in from Massena New York; using access points near Cornwall... but border crossings as far away as B.C., were also employed. Staff Sgt. Armstrong says, the work of the RCMP, has just begun: <br>  The criminal penalities are relatively insignificant ... fines of ten thousand dollars ... jail terms of 3 to 6 months in most cases; but police are able to seize assets from the proceeds of crime; and grabbing the toys and cash of the crooks, is what really hurts: <br>  Of the 12 arrests so far; 7 suspects are from the Hamilton area.<br>  Douglas Samson of Ancaster; Carl Kaarsemaker of Waterdown; Thomas Jacobs of Flamborough; Leslie, Robert and Brent Maxwell ... all of Stoney Creek ... and another Stoney Creek resident ... Mary Clark. All charged with a number of smuggling-related offences.<br>  Police also arrested suspects from Cornwall, and Massena New York, and are looking for two other Americans ... including 66 year old Richard Rancati of Las Vegas Nevada.<br>   The irony in all of this... the public complains about crime... and then promotes criminal activity... by buying smuggled booze.</i>
<hr>
<b>St. Kitts Fire</b><p>
One man suffered severe injuries to his hands in his attempt to put out a fire in a St. Catharines highrise apartment building last night.<br>  The building at 292 Oakdale Avenue was evacuated when a fire broke out in a sixth floor unit.<br>  The blaze caused about 50 thousand dollars damage.<br>  The fire is still under investigation by the fire marshall's office.
<hr>
<b>Catholics - 2000</b><p>
The Roman Catholic Diocese of Hamilton has launched its own Days of Action ... spiritual action as it prepares for the year 2,000.<br>  At 7:30 tonight the Diocese, which represents nearly 400-thousand catholics from across central Ontario, will hold a special celebration at Hamilton's Cathedral of Christ the King to launch a programme of spiritual renewal.<br>  Christians across the world are counting down to the anniversary of Christ's birth.
<hr>
<b>Jennya Leaves</b><p>
Nine months after arriving in Hamilton for hip surgery five year old Jennya Poluhovich is leaving for home in Belarus.<br>  Jennya and her father will depart for Kiev tonight.<br>  Last January doctors, nurses at St. Joseph's Hospital donated their time and services to perform the corrective surgery on Jennya.<br>  She returns home still wearing a brace, but now able to walk and run.




<P>
