<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, October 24, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>50 Rd. Pileup       
    <li>Traffic Fatals      
    <li>TTC
    <li>Fergus Murder       
    <li>Interest Rates      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Hamilton Compost    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>50 Rd. Pileup</b><p>
The Toronto bound Queen Elizabeth Way is still closed at this hour following a multi-car pile-up early this afternoon.<br>  Police are providing few details at this hour, however witnesses say the vehicles plowed into the back of a car that had slowed down, just east of the Fifty Road exit ramp.<br>  One man suffered serious injuries and was flown by air ambulance to the Hamilton General Hospital.  A woman received leg injuries and was treated in hospital.<br>  No names or other details have yet been released by OPP Burlington.<br>  However, we repeat the Toronto bound lanes at Fifty Road remain closed.  Traffic is being re-routed onto the service road at Casablanca Boulevard, returning to the QEW at Fruitland Road.
<hr>
<b>Traffic Fatals</b><p>
We now have an identity of the victim of yesterday's 403 Ancaster car crash. 30-year-old Scott Hands of Calidonia was driving a Toyota eastbound that crossed into the westbound lanes and struck two other vehicles. He was pronounced dead on arrival at Hamilton General Hospital.  And a Milton man died in a two-vehicle crash in Oakville early this morning. 29-year-old Dean Kruger was thrown from his jeep in the collision on the Third Line at the North Service Road.  Police are looking for witnesses.
<hr>
<b>TTCt</b><p>
It could be slow going if you're heading into Toronto tomorrow, day one of the Actions Days of Protest in that city. The Toronto Transit Commission won an injunction today to limit picketing around the transit system but TTC chairman Paul Christie says he cannot guarantee transit service. 
<hr>
<b>Fergus Murder</b><p>
It's believed to be the first homicide in Fergus in at least 50 years. Forty-year-old Patricia Abbott was found dead in her home yesterday by co-workers when she failed to return to work after lunch. Police are not saying how she died. The woman lived in the home with her boyfriend and teenaged daughter. Her slaying has shocked neighbors who describe abbott as a happy person who loved her daughter very much.  
<hr>
<b>Interest Rates</b><p>
Never say never. That seems to be the new slogan for mortgage lenders, real estate agents, and home buyers. The wildly unpredicatble state of interest rates, has almost everyone wondering, how low, can we go? Scot Urquhart reports
<i> <BR>It's happening so fast, and frequently, that not even the banks can seem to keep up.<br>  Mortgage rates, are coming down, again! <br>  Well, the last time we saw rates like these ... Hamilton looked like this.   and the beatles had a number one hit ..... <br>  Gorette da Silva says, the number of people looking for mortgage money is on the rise ... but despite record low rates, customers are still trying to squeeze the best possible deal they can, from the banks: <br>  Gord Majic is one of those who decide that now, is the time to jump: <br>  And Derek Carter says, he's having a record year ... but while lower interest rates are helping the real estate market ... there is still a down side to all of this: <br>  And as long as buyers remain uncertain; and the economy sluggish... no one is willing to predict just how low ... the rates can go. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br> Canadian stock prices took a pause today from four consecutive days of record highs.<br>  Interest rates and the dollar remained stable.<br>  A young Mississauga biopharmaceutical company is rapidly growing as it develops some important drugs. 
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Compost</b><p>
A bit of tax re-leaf could be coming to city of Hamilton residents by way of a new yard waste collection program.<br>  The city feels it can cut tipping fees by about half by diverting leaves and grass clippings from regular garbage to a new composting facility.<br>  Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  Beginning this week on Hamilton mountain, and next week in the lower city, there's a new way to handle your trash.<br>  If you're backyard composter can't handle the amount of leaves or grass clippings or other garden waste in your yard, you can now leave it out on the curb every other week on your regular garbage day.<br>  Just make sure it's bundled, in a clear plastic bag or in a container clearly marked for composting.<br>  Your yard waste will eventually end up part of a new composting facility in Glanbrook.  <br>  The compost collection will take place from now until the middle of December.  <br>  If you have any questions about leaf and yard waste recycling in Hamilton, you can call Public Works at 546-2785.<br>  </i>





