<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, October 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>









<ul>
    <li>CAW - GM Deal 
    <li>CUPE 1287 Vote 
    <li>Hamilton - Protest  
    <li>Hosp. Board Reps     
    <li>River Rescue        
    <li>Frumusa Trial       
    <li>Graffiti Kids       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Rally Recap         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>CAW - GM Deal </b><p>
Twenty six thousand striking General Motors workers in St. Catharines, Oshawa, Windsor and Quebec are poised to celebrate tonight. Ratification votes held today are being counted this hour.<br>  The tentative deal reached yesterday gives workers a 10 percent wage increase over three years, and protects jobs for the term of the contract.<br>  CAW president Buzz Hargrove spoke told more than 5 thousand GM workers in St. Catharnes this afternoon and called the job protection provisions a huge victory for the union.          <br>  
<hr>
<b>CUPE 1287 Cote </b><p>
Six hundred, fifty Niagara regional employees will be back on the job tomorrow.<br>  The workers ratified the latest contract offer by a margin of 72 percent.<br>  Niagara regional employees had been on strike since Labor Day weekend.<br>  They were demanding a contract that gave them job security.<br>  The 32 month contract they accepted today has job security provisions but the workers had to offer other concessions.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton - Protest</b><p>
 Organizers in Hamilton say, at least one thousand demonstrators from this city, will take part in the Toronto Days of Protest, this weekend. Some twenty buses have been lined up, to ferry demonstrators from this city to Toronto on Friday and Saturday. Scot Urquhart has more on those preparations:                             
<i><br>  The Coalition for Social Justice is ready. They will take five bus loads of people to Toronto to deliver a message to Mike Harris: <br>  Organizers hope that the Toronto Days of Protest this weekend will dwarf the rally that brought 100-thousand demonstrators to Hamilton, last February. At least 20 buses will roll out of Hamilton on either Friday, or Saturday ... about half of them sponsored, by the United Steelworkers. Union organizer Peter Leibovitch says the steelworkers will target existing picket lines ... like the strike at S.A. Armstrong, in Toronto: <br>  But are these rallies having any effect? It seems as though the Harris Tories have simply ignored the demonstrations and carried on. Not so, according to Catherine Hudson, of CUPE: <br>  And despite some increasingly heated rhetoric between labour leaders, and the government ... Hudson is confident that the Toronto Days of Protest will be both peaceful, and successful. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Hosp. Board Reps</b><p>
In the wake of a controversial severance package, Hamilton politicians will ask the province for a greater presence on a new hospital super-board.<br>  The board will run Hamilton Health Sciences Corporation, the product of a merger between the Hamilton Civic Hospitals and Chedoke-McMaster Hospitals.<br>  Hamilton's mayor and Hamilton- Wentworth's regional chairman will serve on the board.<br>  Now Hamilton's finance and administration committee has voted to ask the province to add two more politicians.<br>  Aldermen believe hospital boards must be more accountable to the public, especially after Chedoke-McMaster agreed to hand its outgoing CEO an 800-thousand dollar severance package.
<hr>
<b>River Rescue</b><p>
A New York state man is alive and well after he was rescued from the icy waters of the Niagara River by a Honduras boy living in Fort Erie. Police say 67-year-old Richard Urbanski of Williamsville, New York, was fishing from his 16-foot aluminum boat when it overturned and landed him in the drink. He was clinging to the side of the craft when 17-year-old Luis Rodriguez of Fort Erie swam out, battling strong currents, and rescued Urbanski. He was shaken and cold but otherwise uninjured.
<hr>
<b>Frumusa Trial</b><p>
Double murder convictions against a Niagara Falls man, who has spent eight years in jail, have been overturned by the Supreme Court of Ontario.<br>  37-year-old Peter Frumusa has been ordered a new trial. The reasons will be released later in a written judgement. Eight years ago 70-year-old Richard Wilson and his 48-year-old wife, Annie were clubbed to death in their Niagara Falls-area home. The court heard new evidence in the case, including a statement from a police informer who admitted making up a story that Frumusa confessed to the murders while in jail.
<hr>
<b>Graffiti Kids</b><p>
An alert Hamilton mountain resident, aware of a growing graffiti problem because of recent media reports, helped to catch two would-be artists in the act.<br>  Police say a 16 year old and a 14 year old were spray-painting a supply building at Bruce Park late yesterday when a neighbour spotted them.<br>  Both boys are charged with mischief.<br>  Although several other pockets of graffiti on the mountain are gang related, police say they don't believe the pair are gang members.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stock prices smashed through new record highs again today as investors anticipate another reduction in the bank rate.<br>  Canadian banks are anticipating lower interest rates and will cut mortgage rates tomorrow. <br>  
<hr>
<b>Rally Recap</b><p>
 Beyond the Grey Cup there's the 2001 Canada Summer Games. The cities of Hamilton and Brantford officially launched their joint bid to host the summer games last night. The rally at the convention centre followed a tour by the provincial site review committee, which will now whittle down the to three, 9 Ontario communities bidding to be host. 





