<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, October 22, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>G.M. - Tentative
    <li>Harris Protest      
    <li>State of Region     
    <li>Crystal Beach Renew 
    <li>Gretzky Road        
    <li>Bad Dad             
    <li>Blood Shortage      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M. - Tentative</b><p>
It's a deal, albeit a tentative one but it could see 26-thousand General Motors Canada workers back on the job by tomorrow night.
<br> Autoworkers boss Buzz Hargrove preedicts members will ratify the deal tomorrow. The deal includes a pledge by GM to limit contracting out and the sale of facilities. 
<hr>
<b>Harris Protest</b><p>
Picketers not celebrating but protesting at Hamilton City Hall this hour. They're target premier Mike Harris in town for a Tory fundraiser at the Sheraton Hamilton Hotel. 
<hr>
<b>State of Region</b><p>
The Harris government may soon have something to say about regional government in Hamilton- Wentworth. The region's chairman Terry Cooke believes the key to region's survival lies in it's ability is to follow the lead of the private sector.<br> That was the theme of his annual "state of the region" address this morning. Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  Handing over the Hamilton Airport to Trade Port International.<br>  It's a business-like move the region of Hamilton Wentworth felt it had to make because it couldn't run the airport as lean and mean as the private sector could.<br>  The same with establishing a private public partnership to deliver the region's sewage and water service.<br>  The regional chair feels getting out of the governing of business of into the business of governing is the best way to keep Hamilton Wentworth thriving.  <br>  Cooke especially wants to apply that aggressiveness to regional government itself.<br>  Taking a cue from successful businesses by getting rid of the fat.  <br> Cooke says it's imperative Hamilton Wentworth have a new municipal council in place before the next municipal election about a year from now.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Crystal Beach Renew</b><p>
In the region of Niagara, some local citizens feel they have the right prescription for the economic revival of the town of Crystal Beach, the one-time thriving summer resort on the shores of Lake Erie that became a ghost town when the amusement park shut down in 1989.  Lauran Sabourin reports.
<i><br>  In it's heydey Crystal Beach was a magnet for anybody looking for some fun in the summer.<br>  <br>  But after Labor Day in 1989 people didn't come back... <br>  The main streets are deserted...<br>  Graffitti covers walls...<br>  Business signs are disintegrating...<br>  Birds build nests in holes left by bricks that have fallen out...<br>  Most of the buildings are boarded up..<br>  This building was once the Ontario Hotel...<br>  But a group calling itself the Friends of Crystal Beach sees beauty where others see decay .. <br>  Paul Kassay and Stella Ziff want to put a stop the deterioration of Crystal Beach... <br>  Crystal Beach has history rooted in the early 1800's..an important site during the war of 1812.<br>  Local entrepreneurs want to transform this community into a centre of some cultural activity.. <br>  Look toward the glistening waters of Lake Erie and you see the dramatic transformation already taking place in Crystal Beach.<br>  A community of gleaming colonial houses is springing out of the sand where the amusement park once stood.<br>  A residential and recreational compound that community activiists will be the spark for economic recovery in the rest of the village. </i>
<hr>
<b>Gretzky Road</b><p>
A road leading into Brantford, will soon bear the name of that city's famous son and one of hockey's greatest players. City councillors have voted unanimously to rename it the Wayne Gretzky Parkway. The hockey superstar was born and raised in the city and his parents still live there.
<hr>
<b>Bad Dad</b><p>
A confrontation between a Hamilton mountain father, and his teenaged daughter; has resulted in an arrest, and several weapons-related charges. Police say the 45 year old man, enraged by the continual defiance of his 14 year old daughter ... grabbed a weapon in his home, and began to threaten the girl. the teen reported the incident to her school guidance counsellor; and last night, just after midnight, the emergency response unit of the regional police surrounded the man's home ... and negotiated his surrender. no names have been released.
<hr>
<b>Blood Shortage</b><p>
The situation is becoming critical at blood banks in the region. Red Cross blood centres in Toronto, Hamilton and the Waterloo region have issued an urgent appeal for donors. Reserves of group "O" positive have fallen drastically, but the Red Cross says they need all types of blood.  Some hospitals are talking about postponing elective surgery.





<P>
