<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, October 21, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>G.M. Niagara        
    <li>Niagara Deal        
    <li>Hamilton Docs       
    <li>Health Science Corp. 
    <li>Hamilton Homicide   
    <li>Reading Week        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M. Niagara</b><p>
There are significant developments on the labor front in southern Ontario this evening.<br>  Twenty six thousand General Motors workers are counting on a resolution to their strike by the end of the day.<br>  This afternoon Canadian Auto Workers president Buzz Hargrove said after 45 hours of marathon bargaining there are still issues to be settled.<br>  The hurdles include some local issues as well as some snags in outsourcing.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Deal</b><p>
Municipal workers in St. Catharines could be going back to work soon.  Six hundred and fifty members of CUPE local 12-87 will vote on a tentative deal Wednesday after a 60-hour marathon session all weekend. They've been on strike 49 days. The strike involved St. Catharines administrative and welfare workers as well as road, sewage and water-plant employees.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Docs</b><p>
It's a great deal. That's the line the health minister is taking. Jim Wilson has announced a new deal with doctors that would reduce government clawbacks, and restrict the ability of new physicians, to practice where they please. But will the agreement bring permanent peace to the medical community? According to reporter Scot Urquhart, many doctors say no:
<i> <br>  But just which doctors is the health minister talking about? <br>  Dr. Donna Fedorkow is an executive with the Ontario Society of Obstetricians and Gynecologists; one of the specialty groups threatening to withdraw services November 1st. <br>  Although she is hopeful, Dr. Fedorkow admits Jim Wilson's prescription may not be the medicine to suit all doctors: <br>  Certainly Dr. Lynn Nash, would agree. She's the president of the Ontario College of Family Physicians. She does not favour the deal announced by the province. One reason; she thinks forcing new doctors away from established areas; may be a mistake: <br>  In the end says Doctor Nash, pitting physicians one against the other; will damage the health care system: <br>  Doctor Gordon Guyatt, of the Medical Reform Group says; the government will have to de-list 50 million dollars in services from OHIP; to pay for the new agreement: <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Health Science Corp.</b><p>
When Jennifer Jackman and Pamela Reid left their executive posts at Chedoke -McMaster Hospitals, they were awarded more than a million dollars in severance.<br>    Its a payout that has created controversy and raised many questions.<br>  Now that the merger of Chedoke McMaster and the Civic Hospitals is official, the new board wants to see how it all happened...and why.<br>  Dwight Ryan with that.  
<i><br>  Its now official. Hamilton's Chedoke McMaster Hospitals will be merged with the Civic Hospitals.<br>  The amalgamation, known as the Hamilton Health Sciences Corporation will create one of the largest health care facilities in the province.<br>  Word of the approval came from Ontario health minister Jim Wilson.   <br>    The health minister expresssed his concern in a letter to the Chedoke McMaster board.   <br>      Norman Preece chairs the board of the new Health Sciences Corporation.  Now that the merger is official, his first priortiy is to see the severance paperwork.   <br>       Preece and his lawyers will not only look at Jackman's severance, but that of one of her closest colleagues, Pamela Reid.  The Vice-president of Corporate Development quit her job last month and got more than a quarter of a million in severance.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Homicide</b><p>
Her death has been ruled a homicide even though an autopsy could find no anatomical reason why she should have died.  72 year old Jean Lindsay of Hamilton was found dead in her apartment last week.  It was originally thought she had died of natural causes, until that is, an interview with Mrs. Lindsay's 45 year old son, who visited the central Hamilton Wentworth Police Station Saturday night.             <br>   45 year old John Lindsay of Hamilton is charged with second degree murder.   He'll appear in court on October 29th.
<hr>
<b>Reading Week</b><p>
It's library week and to start things off, a special story time for these students at Queen Mary School in Hamilton.  Hamilton Mayor Bob Morrow, read to a group of grade three students from the book, "Have You Seen Bugs?"<br>  Mayor Morrow is the first in a series of celebrity readers as Queen Mary School holds "Libraries: Let's Celebrate Week".<br>  The week, sponsored by the Hamilton Public Libraries, is meant to encourage kids to read.





