<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, October 18, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Region Restructure  
    <li>Severance Sit-in    
    <li>Mountain Gang       
    <li>Cops and Gays       
    <li>Sabia Obit          
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Jail & Bail         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Region Restructure</b><p>
Councillors who want to abolish Hamilton- Wentworth Region are pushing ahead with plans to dismantle it. <br>    Some of them met today, to decide who can do the best job of delivering services to taxpayers.
<br> But the meeting was boycotted by councillors who oppose the motion to disband Hamilton- Wentworth, passed by regional council earlier this month.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <BR>Whether it's busses, sidewalks, or recreational programs, this working group of Hamilton- Wentworth regional councillors wants to know who can best deliver the services taxpayers expect.  But even though all of these councillors support the abolition of Hamilton- Wentworth Region, they're not prepared yet to start drawing up contracts authorizing Hamilton to sell services to the suburbs.  <BR>But these councillors intend to prove to the municipal affairs minister they're just as serious about doing away with the region, as chairman Cooke is about saving it.  <BR>So despite the boycott by chairman Cooke and some Hamilton councillors, this working group intends to keep on working to divvy up the services now provided by the region.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Severance Sit-in</b><p>
This Hamilton woman doesn't like the politics at Chedoke-McMaster Hospital. Anne Marsden is disabled.  She was fired from Mac without a severance package three years ago and today turned up on the hospital doorstep, seeking what she believes is her share of the generous severance packages now being handed out as the health care facility restructures. Ms. Marsden was a quality assurance analyst when Mac discharged her after seventeen years service... for writing a letter to the editor of the Hamilton Spectator suggesting that the hospital's senior management was spending health care dollars unwisely.
<br>  In a letter she delivered today to hospital chairman Paul Southall... Mrs. Marsden requests a meeting to discuss her case. And if she doesn't get it ... she says she'll sue.
<hr>
<b>Mountain Gang</b><p>
Regional police are taking on the Pinstripes, a multi-racial male-dominated criminal youth gang. These are their symbols, the graffitti is showing up everywhere and in the latest incident, a 16 year old Hamilton boy has been arrested after a brutal assault on a student.  It happened at Barton High School earlier this month.<br> A 19 year old was punched and kicked by a group of teens on his way home from school.<br> Earlier that day, police say he had accidently hit the accused with a hackey-sack ball.<br> The teen appeared in court this morning.<br> Police are trying to identify other members of the gang, but say witnesses are reluctant to come forward for fear of reprisal.
<hr>
<b>Cops and Gays</b><p>
 Police in Hamilton have another issue to deal with right now. During a private meeting last night, members of the gay community accused chief Robert Middaugh and his force of being homophobic and insensitive. They want gay officers recruited, increased patrols in areas where gay bashing is common and above all, a change in attitude. 
<hr>
<b>Sabia Obit</b><p>
She fought for women's rights, Canada's feminist pioneer who founded the National Action Committee on the Status of Women. Long time St. Catharines resident Laura Sabia has died after a 19-year battle with Parkinson's Disease.  She was 80. Sabia was often described as a fiercely outspoken traditional feminist, not a politically correct `men are the enemy' feminist.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
More evidence today of Canada's strengthening economy.  Trade figures show Canada with a four billion dollar trade surplus.<br>  Meanwhile stock markets in Toronto and New York closed higher again today and the Canadian dollar is up over seventy four cents U.S.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Jail & Bail</b><p>
They were singing behind bars today.... the charges are bogus, the jail is a fake, the judge is an actor.  But, the cause is real.<br>  Some of Hamilton's finest were arrested and charged today. They were put behind bars and told to raise bail.  It was the annual Canadian Cancer Society Jail and Bail in aid of Cancer Research and Camp Trillium. Fund-raisers are hoping to realize $50-thousand from the event... snd they're already half-way there.





