<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, October 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Jackman Deal        
    <li>G.M. First 
    <li>Nia. Region Strike  
    <li>Municipal Act       
    <li>Hosp. Partners      
    <li>Niagara Jobs        
    <li>Business First        
    <li>401 Crash           
    <li>Stolen Crash        
    <li>Pawn Woman          
    <li>Crime Stopper Awards 
</ul>
<hr>
<b>jackman deal</b><p>
The controversial cat is out of the bag.... <br>    Former Chedoke McMaster Hospitals CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman was paid big dollars when she left her position at the beginning of September.
<br>  The word came through a hospital issued news release this afternoon.<br>  Jamie West who has been following this story has the latest.
<i><br>  818-thousand dollars,  a number lower than a rumoured 969-thousand but still a lot of money going to former Chedoke McMaster CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman...<br>  Dr. Jackman publicly announced last summer that she would not seek the job as CEO of the new merged McMaster Civics superhospital.<br> However she became eligable for severance because her former job was eliminated by the planned merger.<br>  Regional chairman Terry Cooke has been a vocal opponent of the hospital's recent refusal to disclose the figure...<br>  The hospital says the anger of the public has been minimal...<br>  Chedoke McMaster says no funds donated and designated for patient care has ever been used to pay salaries or severances.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>G.M. First </b><p>
The head of the Canadian Auto Workers Union is hopeful that a deal to end a strike with General Motors can be struck by Monday.<br>  Twenty five thousand GM workers in Canada have been walking the picket line for the last two weeks.<br>  Union leader Buzz Hargrove says both sides made some important moves on the contentious outsourcing issue.<br>  Picketers on the line in St. Catharines are hopeful that the break came during a meeting with General Motors chairman Jack Smith.         
<hr>
<b>Nia. Region Strike</b><p>
Contract talks resume today in the strike by unionized municipal workers with Niagara Region.<br> The 650 CUPE members have been on strike since September 3rd.<br> Major issues in the talks include job security and contracting out.<br> Both sides have agreed to a news blackout during talks at a hotel in Thorold.
<hr>
<b>Municipal Act</b><p>
Ontario municipalities will have more power to charge user fees and cut the size of their councils, under reforms proposed today by the provincial government.<br>  Changes to the Municipal Act, introduced in the Ontario legislature today, would also exempt towns and cities from lawsuits arising from road maintenance, and sewer and water-main back-ups.<br>  But as Deborah Walker reports, even more sweeping changes are on the horizon.
<i> <BR> Proposed changes to the Municipal Act are based on the recommendations of David Crombie's "who does what" panel.  <BR>But opposition members say the "who does what" panel should be re-named the "who pays what" panel.  <BR>However the chairman of Hamilton- Wentworth Region says change is inevitable.  But Terry Cooke says it is worth investigating whether municipalities could assume school building and maintenance, and the transportation of students.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Hosp. Partners</b><p>
Some restructuring of partnerships under between Hamilton-  Wentworth and Niagara. Hotel Dieu Hospital in St. Catharines is joining forces with McMaster University and the University of Western Ontario.<br>  The affiliation will see undergraduate medical students and interns from McMaster practising at Hotel Dieu.<br>  The arrangement also allows both institutions better opportunities to conduct medical research.<br>  And it's hoped that in the long run the students will return to the peninsula to practice.<br>  There is an acute shortage of family physicians and certain types of specialists in Niagara.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Jobs</b><p>
Meanwhile, in Niagara Falls, some 12-hundred people have new jobs today. Casino Niagara has hired almost half its workforce.<br> There are about 21-thousand applicants competing for the three-thousand positions at the new casino.<br> The interim Casino Niagara opens in December.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
In New York today, stock prices once again soared into record territory.<br>  Lower housing starts south of the border have investors confident that inflation fears may finally be put to rest.<br>  In Toronto, the TSE dropped by seven points on a day that one trader referred to as less than exciting.<br>   
<hr>
<b>401 Crash</b><p>
It was dicey business getting to work for motorists on Highway 401 near Guelph this morning. Rush hour turned into rush hours, when two tractor-trailers and 15 other vehicles were involved in a pileup along the eastbound lanes near Highway 6.<br> The accident happened shortly after 6:00 a-m just east of Guelph.<br> Police say thick fog is partly to blame for the pileup which played havoc with the morning rush hour commute.<br> There were a number of injuries, mostly minor.
<hr>
<b>Stolen Crash</b><p>
A Hamilton Wentworth police officer, acting on a hunch, turned out to be right about a suspicious looking vehicle last night.<br> He tried following the car as it sped through east Hamilton early this morning.<br> It eventually ran into another cruiser. The officer was hurt slightly.<br> Five people in the suspect vehicle, which turned out to be stolen, suffered cuts and broken bones.<br> 18 year old Michael White of Hamilton faces several theft and dangerous driving charges.
<hr>
<b>Pawn Woman</b><p>
Some Hamilton youths have been charged with possession of stolen property after a woman decided to take matters in her own hands.<br> The 34 year old had been scouring pawn shops looking for items stolen in a break-in when she spotted a group of five young people, one carrying a bag that belonged to her.<br> She ended up getting her possession back.<br> The kids ended up under arrest.
<hr>
<b>Crime Stopper Awards</b><p>
Crime Stoppers in Hamilton- Wentworth has a pretty good track record when it comes to capturing criminals.  Now it's captured a string of awards. <br>  At the International Crime Stoppers Convention in Alabama, the Hamilton Wentworth program picked up more awards than any other in the world.<br>  They're tops for money recovered from crime ... nearly 1-and-a-half million dollars, and for the most cases cleared for 1995.<br>  With 158 suspects apprehended, the program came in second for most arrests last year.<br>  CHCH shared in their achievement with a second place prize for a Crime Stoppers segment warning seniors about phone fraud.<br>  The chair for Hamilton Wentworth's Crime Stoppers program explains why he thinks it works so well.





<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

