<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, October 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Breast Cancer Follow 
    <li>Auditor Follow      
    <li>Lady Bandit         
    <li>Agg. Assault        
    <li>Homolka - Coroner     
    <li>Radar Message Board 
    <li>Partners / Education  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Breast Cancer Follow</b><p>
The Ontario government is bolstering its defences in the fight against breast cancer.  It's going to spend 24 million dollars to set-up 30 new breast screening programs over the next four years.
<br> Two of them will be located in Niagara:<br> One program at the Greater Niagara General Hospital in Niagara Falls. And the other at St. Catharines General Hospital.<br> Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i><br>  The target group for the breast screening program in Niagara is 43 thousand women between the ages of 50 and 69.<br>  Its a routine screening program designed to detect breast cancer in women who may not suspect there is a problem.<br>  With the older populaton in Niagara having easy access to a breast screening program is critical.<br>  The incidence of cancer in this area is high.<br>  Breast cancer is one of the two leading causes of cancer death in women. <br>  It's estimated that 71 hundred women in the province will develop breast cancer this year.  Two thousand will die.<br>  In 1993, 84 percent of women who died of breast cancer were over 50.<br>  Breast screening is the best way to lower those death rates.  <br>   The government is alloting more than 24 million dollars to establish 30 new breast screening programs over the next four years. <br>  While screening won't prevent cancer,  it will certainly give women a better chance at survival. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Auditor Follow</b><p>
As for the health of the air we breathe, yesterday the provincial auditor's report criticized a lack of air monitoring by the Ontario government.<br> However, in Hamilton, ministry of the environment officials are breathing easier knowing their equipment is state of the art ... <br> And after you hear this report from Jamie West maybe you will too...
<i><br>   If it looks and sounds a little complicated it probably is...<br>  But it's nice to know that the air that sometimes hangs thick over the steel city is being examined carefully on a daily basis and through some of the best equipment in the province.<br>  The cost of operating this station in Hamilton's Beasly Park is about 10-thousand dollars a year.<br>  A bargain considering the importance of monitoring particles in the air...<br>  The real good news is that Hamilton air quality is three times better now than 20 years ago.<br>  And the number of days that the pollution index has reached the danger point has dropped steadily since 1970.<br>  And that should allow all of us to breathe a collective sigh of relief.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Lady Bandit</b><p>
Halton's lady bandit has struck again.<br> It happened yesterday afternoon at a Royal Bank in the Milton Mall. After indicating she had a gun, she got away with an undisclosed amount of money.<br> She's described as white, 25 to 35 years old, 5'5" with a slim build and dark wavy hair pulled back in a pink hairbands.  She wore a light brown bomber jacket, dark track pants and white runners.<br> Police believe the same suspect is responsible for a number of hold-ups throughout the region.
<hr>
<b>Agg. Assault</b><p>
Police still trying to get to the bottom of an aggravated assault case last night in Hamilton.<br> A 42 year old woman was found lying in front of a home on Carrick Avenue in central Hamilton.<br> She is being treated in hospital for a facial fracture, and possible broken ribs and a broken collarbone.<br> But she's not co-operating with the investigation, by refusing to tell police who attacked her.
<hr>
<b>Homolka - Coroner</b><p>
The coroner who handled the investigation of Tammy Homolka's death didn't do the job properly.<br> And the reason, says Ontario's chief coroner, is that Dr. Joseph Rosloski didn't have the experience to look at the case properly.<br> Dr. James Young says Rosloski now understands where he went wrong and no disciplinary action will be taken against him.<br> Tammy Homolka apparently died after she was drugged and sexually assaulted by her sister Karla and Paul Bernardo in 1990.<br> An inquiry into the investigation of the Bernardo case criticized Rosloski for mislabelling Tammy Homolka's death.
<hr>
<b>Radar Message Board</b><p>
Burlington residents are getting the message across load and clear ... don't speed on their residential streets!<br> With help from a piece of technology on loan from Alberta, the city of Burlington is trying to slow down drivers enough to read the signs of speeding.<br> Annette Hamm explains.
<i><br>  Ever wonder how fast you're really going while zipping through town?<br>  These drivers along Headon Road in Burlington found out thanks to this radar message board.  <br>  The radar board is being tested throughout the city of Burlington to try and make residential areas safer, and to make drivers aware of their actual speeds.  <br>  No speeding tickets are handed out during the test runs, it's more of an awareness project than speed enforcement.<br>  Residents in this neighbourhood are also keeping a watch on speeders by jotting down licence plates and sending them to police.  <br>  The city of Burlington hopes to raise money through corporate sponsors to buy at least one of the 23-hundred dollar radar boards for permanent use.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Partners / Education</b><p>
Statistics Canada says high school drop-outs returned to class in droves during the early nineties, because they were unable to find work.<br>  If those students returned to school in Hamilton- Wentworth, they're in luck.<br>  A partnership between schools and businesses in the region, gives students a decisive edge when it comes time to enter the workplace.
<i>  Hamilton- Wentworth's Industry Education Council is the oldest in Canada.  It's a partnership between educators and employers, a partnerership that allowed this grade twelve student to spend a one-month summer work-term at Burlington's Genum Corporation.  <BR>Goodridge says you can complain about change, or you can learn to control it.  It's those who adapt who won't just survive in a changing economy ... they'll thrive in it. </i>





<P>
