<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/15/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, October 15, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Sex Videos          
    <li>Project Heat Update 
    <li>Daylight Robbery    
    <li>Robbers Caught      
    <li>Fatal Crash         
    <li>Att. Murder Caught  
    <li>Bat Neighbour       
    <li>Drugs in Mouth      
    <li>Aud. Report 
    <li>Baby Docs' Strike   
    <li>Talks Resume        
    <li>Consumer Clearout   
    <li>Goody Bags          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Sex Videos</b><p>
Informative or excessive? A controversy has erupted over a Hamilton and Wentworth school boards video series on human sexuality. <br>   They're too hot to handle ...especially for elementary school children.
<br>   That's the feeling of some parents who are against the Wentworth County board's use of the videos.<br> Jamie West went to see what the fuss is about and a word of warning ...his report contains some sexually explicit images taken from the videos in question.
<i><br>  And this is what the fuss is about ..<br>  Sexual health is one thing but sexually explicit video's cartoon's or not are too much for some parents...<br>  The seven year old video entitled Head Full of Questions isn't just about mechanics its also about relationships and how Fred and Anna live day to day and care for one another...<br>  The Wentworth County Board has heard screaming from some parents about the video but mostly applause, still they're taking a second look...<br>  The video remains available through both the Wentworth County and Hamilton Boards of Aducation... Jim Enos would like it banned from schools but...<br>  The Wentworth Board says that's just what might happen.<br>   </i>
<hr>
<b>Project Heat Update</b><p>
Keeping kids out of trouble was an objective throughout the summer, when Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police turned up the "heat" on specific crimes.<br> They focussed on car theft, teen hangouts and small scale, break and enters.<br> Now they've released the results of their focus and introduced their next initiative.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  The high enforcement action teams, or HEAT units were set up throughout Hamilton Wentworth to target specific problems.<br>  Mainly what police describe as quality of life crimes that residents had complained weren't getting enough attention.<br>  Crimes like loitering, car theft and neighbourhood break and enters.<br>  From May to September, police sent out three HEAT teams.<br>  "Project Joyride" focused on stolen autos.<br>  This team arrested 28 people, three quarters of them were young offenders.<br>  Regular patrols by officers involved with "Project Hangout" cut down on the number of teens hanging out in malls and parking lots.<br>  A smaller unit patrolled Hamilton's west mountain, trying to prevent house entries.<br> In many cases, suspects identified in one project turned up in another.  <BR>Police already have a jump start on their latest project, making a key arrest earlier this week.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Daylight Robbery</b><p>
The heat is on tonight as police in Hamilton search for a suspect following a daring, daylight armed robbery of a man on his way to the bank to deposit his employer's receipts.<br> Investigators say the victim had parked his van to make the deposit at the James Street North branch of CIBC. He was struck on the head with a semi-automatic hand gun and forced back into his vehicle by a man wearing a stocking mask. He is described as six feet tall with scarred hands.<br> The victim was forced from the vehicle a short distance away.<br> The suspect escaped with the van and the receipts. the van was later recovered.
<hr>
<b>Robbers Caught</b><p>
Two brothers are being commended by police for stopping two teenaged boys from robbing this Stoney Creek variety store.<br> One of the brothers went into "Smile Variety" just as the clerk shouted for help.<br> He nabbed them, with help from his brother waiting outside in the car.<br> A 16 year old and 17 year old face robbery charges.
<hr>
<b>Fatal Crash</b><p>
Police in Halton are looking for witnesses to a fatal single car crash in Milton last night. It happened late last night on Twenty Sideroad. A vehicle lost control, struck a tree and rolled over. A passerby called police. One of the occupants managed to crawl away and was taken to hospital.  The other was pronounced dead at the scene.
<hr>
<b>Att. Murder Caught</b><p>
Police in St. Catharines have arrested a man wanted for attempted murder in Oshawa.<br> A Niagara Region police officer who stopped a car yesterday afternoon became suspicious of the identification the driver offered to him.<br> A check showed the man was named in a warrant in connection with the attempted murder of a 57-year-old Oshawa man last month.<br> Twenty-four year-old John Hudson of Thorold is charged with attempted murder, theft, possession of stolen goods, obstructing police and personation.<br> Hudson appeared in an Oshawa court today.
<hr>
<b>Bat Neighbour</b><p>
A man on Hamilton mountain who couldn't stand the noise of his neighbour's car has himself been quieted with assault and weapons charges.<br> This after a 60 year old man was beaten with a baseball bat.<br> The victim was taken to hospital with non-life threatening injuries after a man approached him with a bat, telling him to be quiet.<br> 24 year old Corey Tenny is charged with assault with a weapon and possession of a dangerous weapon.
<hr>
<b>Drugs in Mouth</b><p>
A Hamilton man trying to hide crack cocaine from a detective found the whole effort hard to swallow.<br> 36 year old David Charles Guthrie is charged with possession for the purpose of trafficking.<br> Police say the detective had a man under surveillance outside Hanrahan's Tavern, and when he was approached the suspect put the drug in his mouth.<br> The detective reached in and grabbed it, then found more crack in the man's Jaguar.
<hr>
<b>Aud. Report </b><p>
Damage is in the millions of dollars as a result of government losses to welfare and business cheats. In his annual report released this afternoon, provincial auditor Erik Peters says the government needs more tax auditors and beefed-up welfare fraud investigators. On the environment, he says we need to update air pollution and ground water monitoring.
<hr>
<b>Baby Docs' Strike</b><p>
Pediatricians in niagara will meet tomorrow evening to decide whether to make good on their threat to withdraw their services from area hospitals.<br>  All 13 of Niagara's pediatricians threatened to resign from hospitals November 1st unless Queen's Park caved in on contentious issues involving doctors pay.<br>  If the doctors do withdraw their services it would mean children who need pediatric care in hospital would have to travel to Hamilton.<br>  Niagara pediatricians are seen to be among the most militant in the province.
<hr>
<b>Talks Resume</b><p>
And the two sides in the Niagara regional workers dispute are going back to the table. The region and the union agreed to a resumption of talks this morning.<br> Six hundred, fifty striking workers have been walking the picket line since September 3rd.<br> The main strumbling block in the negotiations is job security.
<hr>
<b>Consumer Clearout</b><p>
Inventory clearance sales at Consumers Distributing stores begin tomorrow, as the retailer prepares to close their doors for good.<br> Vancouver-based Maynards is conducting the liquidation, and says discounts will vary from 25 to 65 per cent off regular prices.  As recently as August, Consumers operated 206 stores with 37-hundred employees.
<hr>
<b>Goody Bags</b><p>
It's barely two weeks before tiny trick-or-treaters will be going door-to-door.<br> And Burlington's Joseph Brant Hospital wants to ensure none of those ghosts and goblins wind up in the emergency department.<br> The hospital is spear-heading a campaign to give away ten-thousand heavy-duty halloween goody bags.<br> The bags are highly reflective when streetlight of headlight beams bounce off them, so they'll make trick-or-treaters more visible to motorists.<br> Halton Regional Police and Ontario Provincial Police have volunteered to distribute the goody bags to all Burlington school-children in junior kindergarten through grade three.




<P>
