<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, October 14, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>










<ul>
    <li>Good Shepherd Dinner
    <li>Mario's Thanksgiving
    <li>Red Hill Walk       
    <li>Toronto Fatal       
    <li>Boy - Train           
    <li>Disguise B&E        
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Vineland Artfest    
    <li>Fire Open House     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Good Shepherd Dinner</b><p>
 Here in Hamilton weeks of planning by good samaritans resulted in a happier Thanksgiving for hundreds of people at the Good Shepherd Centre this afternoon.  The annual Thanksgiving Dinner gives hope to those who have been dealt a low blow by circumstance.<br>  They feel "thanksgiving" is just a word, rather than a day of celebration.<br>  Brother Richard and his dedicated corps of volunteers catered to over 600 visitors at the centre's Cannon Street facility.<br>  Mothers with children were more in evidence this year, which Brother Richard notes is a disturbing change from the past.
<hr>
<b>Mario's Thanksgiving</b><p>
Non-profit agencies weren't the only ones serving up turkey with all the trimmings today.<br>  Staff at the East Side Mario's restaurant on Queenston Road in Hamilton volunteered their time today, to provide Thanksgiving dinner for more than two-hundred people who might otherwise miss out on a holiday meal.<br>  The dinner was co-ordinated by the New Westminster Presbyterian Church, and six other charitable agenices pitched in to help.
<hr>
<b>Red Hill Walk</b><p>
 After the turkey dinner, the next item on the Thanksgiving tradition list is the walk. "Friends of Red Hill" enjoyed perfect weather for their annual Thanksgiving hike through the valley today.<br>  They found the jaunt was easier, now that work is under way on a nature trail.<br>  Alex Reynolds joined the group.
<i> A natural oasis, right in Hamilton's backyard, was the focal point, as supporters took to the trails on this Thanksgiving Day.<br>  The lobby group, dedicated to the preservation of the 16-hundred acre, 8 kilometre long nature preserve, explored the newest section of the Red Hill Valley Trail.<br>  It was a leisurely stroll, in unspoiled natural surroundings that in future could yield to a manmade concrete monolith, which for the "friends" is an abomination. <br>  Opposition to the expressway goes beyond environmental issues. <br>  With employment downsizing in the city's industrial core, the group feels future traffic volume doesn't justify a road through the valley. <br>  <br>  When told to go take a hike, "Friends of Red Hill Valley" just smile, because that's their mandate for this natural wonder in the east end of the city.<br>  As a matter of fact, it's been a great day for a walk...cameraman Nick Garbutt and I walked off our big thanksgiving meals from last night, but it's only anticipating another go at the turkey tonight.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Toronto Fatal</b><p>
It's been a tragic Thanksgiving weekend for some. OPP are investigating a crash on the QEW that killed a 42-year-old Hamilton woman. Police say Lori Ann Alleyne Millette's car struck another vehicle at Mississauga Road around 3 p-m yesterday and rolled as many as six times. Her four-year-old daughter is in serious condition with head injuries while her husband and their 18-year-old son were slightly hurt. No one in the other vehicle was injured. The mishap closed the eastbound QEW for more than four hours.
<hr>
<b>Boy - Train</b><p>
Police have now released the name of a young Beamsville teen struck and killed by a CN train early yesterday. Niagara Regional Police say 15-year-old Brook Everet Mackey was walking with three friends along the tracks when the train approached and they decided to stay on the tracks and wait until the last moment to jump out of the way. Brook was pronounced dead on arrival at Lincoln Memorial Gospital.<br> The four boys were all students at Blessed Trinity High School in Grimsby.
<hr>
<b>Disguise B&E</b><p>
It was a Thanksgiving weekend Jill Kaup won't ever forget.  The Niagara-on-the- Lake woman risked her life when she tackled a knife-wielding thief disguised with halloween make-up, she surprised in her bathroom early Sunday morning. The suspect got away but was tracked down by with the help of the niagara police K-9 unit. A 14-year-old niagara-on-the- lake boy will appear in court tomorrow charged with break, enter and theft, assault with a weapon and disguise with intent to commit. Our heroine received a small cut to her hand but is okay.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
 Banks, government offices and financial markets in Canada were closed today for Thanksgiving.<br>  It will be business as usual again tomorrow.<br>  However in the U.S. today, stock prices roared to new record highs helped by stronger than expected third quarter profits at Chrysler Corporation.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Vineland Artfest</b><p>
While most of us had our minds on Thanksgiving today, hundreds of crafty consumers were already thinking ahead to Christmas.<br>  The fifth annual Vineland Thanksgiving Artfest gave visitors a chance to get a head-start on their Christmas shopping.<br>  Craftsmen and artists from across Ontario displayed wares ranging from scultures and wood carvings, to furniture and baked goodies.<br>  Proceeds from the artfest will go to buy extras for students at the Vineland Public School.<br>  And although visitors did not have to pay any admission charge, they were asked to bring along food and clothing donations for the Lincoln Community Care agency.
<hr>
<b>Fire Open House</b><p>
Dozens of youngsters were thankful the Hamilton Fire Department opened its doors today.<br>  Every Thanksgiving Day, the department holds an open house for kids to come in and get acquainted.<br>  All eleven stations opened their doors so the little ones could explore the firefighting apparatus.<br>  They also get some tips on fire prevention and safety.




<P>
