<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, October 11, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Local School Boards 
    <li>Parkview - Legionaires
    <li>Mystery Stabbing    
    <li>Satans Choice       
    <li>Driveway Extortion  
    <li>Harnick - Victims 
    <li>Hamilton Wentworth Business Information Network 
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Fountain Draw       
    <li>C.W.P.H. Fighter    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Local School Boards</b><p>
They say it makes no sense at all ...this next big step in the Mike Harris commons sense revolution.
<br>   A published report says the province plans to scrap all 166 school boards in Ontario and replace them with as few as five regional school councils with restricted mandates.<br>  The Toronto Star says the government expects to save one billion dollars on non classroom administrative costs...<br> As Jamie West reports... in Hamilton... ...the idea is earning a failing grade.
<i><br>  The Star report says part of the rationale for abolishing school boards is that the government believes they're getting in the way of chopping administrative education costs, and would be too quick to raise local property taxes in response to provincial funding cuts.<br>   5 regional replacement councils would be structured to include the constitutional rights of Catholics to govern their own schools.  <BR>The chairman of Barton Secondary's School Council shudders at the plan...<br>  Under the changes the government is expected to impose province wide teacher bargaining.<br>  There are 294 wage contracts between teacher unions and 166 school boards.<br>  The Tories are said to believe it's a waste of time and money.<br>  Teachers argue different areas call for different agreements...<br>  The changes would likely come just in time for the November 1997 municipal elections. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Parkview - Legionaires</b><p>
From our youth to our seniors, there is concern tonight at a Hamilton senior's residence over a flu-like respiratory illness that has affected one-third of the 126 patients.<br>  Parkview Nursing Centre is collaborating with the Regional Public Health Department in the investigation and management of the outbreak, which surfaced three weeks ago.<br>  Of the 39 cases, eight seniors had pneumonia. all but four of those affected have recovered...two of these are in hospital.<br>  There was concern at the outset, the problem could be Legionnaires disease.
<hr>
<b>Mystery Stabbing</b><p>
Police not sure what to make of a stabbing in central Hamilton early this morning. A 40 year old man is in hospital with chest wounds; a 42 year old man suffered stab wounds to his leg.<br>  But neither will tell investigators what happened.
<hr>
<b>Satans Choice</b><p>
One of two men in custody after a weapons search at the Satan's Choice motorcycle club in Hamilton earlier this week now faces further charges.<br>  During a search of an east Hamilton home, police found a pair of brass knuckles, three pounds of marijuana, and evidence of cultivation and resin manufacturing.<br>  32 year old William Weir of Hamilton faces several new weapons and narcotics charges.
<hr>
<b>Driveway Extortion</b><p>
Two men have been arrested after an elderly Hamilton woman was forced to pay for a driveway repair she wasn't happy with.<br>  The 76 year old woman put a stop payment on the cheque for the repair back in September.<br>  Two men showed up at her door and forced her to go to her bank and withdraw the money.<br>  34 year old Donald Clark and 36 year old William Shellard, both of Brantford, face charges of exortion and forcible confinement.
<hr>
<b>Harnick - Victims </b><p>
More help on the way for victims of crime in St. Catharines. Victims rights advocates Priscilla Devilliers and Donna French applauded the announcement today by attorney general Charles Harnick. It invovles a new victim witness assistance program for the garden city and a dozen other new offices to be established over the next two years.<br>  The 160 thousand dollar investment will pay for experts tp help crime victims cope with the trauma of dealing with the justice system. A victim notificaton service will also help keep them informed on the status of their offencder. The attorney general admitted the moves are designed to make up for how the system has wronged crime victims in the past. 
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Wentworth Business Information Network </b><p>
With the national unemployment rate up again, more people need help finding work. The rate climbed a half a point to 9.9. per cent last month. The rate dropped in Hamilton and the golden horseshoe and is still below national and provincial rates. But with more and more full time jobs disappearing, the Hamilton Wentworth Business Information Network couldn't have come along at a better time. The service, officially launched today, is linked to the internet, and provides a community-wide service addressing employment, training, career planning and economic development needs.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
There is more speculation today that the Bank of Canada may once again reduce interest rates.<br>  Federal figures indicate Canada's jobless rate surged to 9.9 percent in September, up significantly from the month before.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Fountain Draw</b><p>
When the restored Gore Park fountain is officially turned on next Saturday, the ceremony itself will be flowing with tradition.<br>  Back in 1860, two students helped with the original opening ceremonies in downtown Hamilton's Gore Park.<br>  Today, some 136 years later, a grandson of one of them, Colin Gibson, drew the names of two youngsters of this generation who will with be a part of the opening ceremonies for the restored fountain. Matthew Ventura and Tanya Pimentel, both six, entered a colouring contest and each won the chance to participate in this historic event.<br>  The fountain will be dedicated Saturday, October 19th.
<hr>
<b>C.W.P.H. Fighter</b><p>
Finally tonight, a new addition has made its way to the Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum in Mount Hope.<br>  The last Cf-100 ever made will become an interactive display at the museum.<br>  The jet fighter interceptors were issued in 1946, and built by Avro in Malton, Ontario.<br>  The canucks, as they were nicknamed flew as defenders in northern Ontario, Quebec and BC until 1981.<br>  The two-seat all-weather fighters usually had a polished aluminum exterior, but the one at the museum, because it is the last one built, was painted black like its prototype.<br>  It will be ready for display in about three weeks.






<P>
