<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, October 10, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Jackman Bonanza     
    <li>Belly Buttons       
    <li>GM - St. Kitts        
    <li>Niagara Strike      
    <li>Halton Meeting 
    <li>Brantford Fatal     
    <li>St. Kitts Bomb Arrest 
    <li>Satan's Choice      
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Jackman Bonanza</b><p>
With a health care system teetering on bankrupcy, one Liberal MPP calls it an outrage. <br> A CEO's severance package, reported to be close to a million dollars.
<br> The hospital involved, Chedoke McMaster, remains mum on the deal they struck with Dr. Jennifer Jackman before she stepped down last month...<br> And as Jamie West reports tonight...the public may never find out the terms of the deal ...
<i><br>  Was there a back room deal struck here at Chedoke McMaster worth $969, 600 dollars?<br>  Hamilton MPP Dominic Agostino says the information came through two unnamed sources one of whom Agostino claims is a director with the new Hamilton Health Sciences Corporation.<br>   He's outraged and wants the hospital to fess up...<br>  The lump sum payment is said to be based on 80 percent of Dr. Jackman's salary over four years.  She earned 303-thousand dollars a year as CEO before stepping down last month just before Chedoke McMaster and the Hamilton Civics merged. Legally, it's the hospital's choice whether to publicly disclose the details...<br>  Employment lawyer Ed Canning says it's difficult to sort through without the specifics of the deal but...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Belly Buttons</b><p>
Some may call it just a bandaid solution but it could save the hospitals six-thousand dollars a year: a team of nurses at Chedoke McMaster have released the results of a year long study that shows the cords of newborns dry up and fall off faster, if left alone. Traditionally alcohol swabs have been used and prescribed to speed the process along. A randomized trial of 1811 babies in Hamilton and Kitchener showed that those whose cords were left alone...separated 20 percent faster. The nurses say it costs hospitals about a dollar seventy five per newborn for alcohol and swabs.
<hr>
<b>GM - St. Kitts</b><p>
The union representing striking General Motors workers in St. Catharines is calling on the mayor to apologize for remarks he made to two Toronto newspapers on Tuesday.<br>  Mayor Al Unwin said he feared the strike would push GM to move its St. Catharines operation to the U.S.<br>  The union is charging that the mayor is helping GM with comments like that.<br>  Despite the controvery morale was buoyant on the picket line today, the fourth day of the walkout in St. Catharines.<br>  Talks between GM Canada and the autoworkers union, meanwhile, have recessed for the Thanksgiving weekend.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Strike</b><p>
 Meanwhile striking regional workers in Niagara are accusing their employer of watering down the issue.  The union representing 650 striking Niagara Region employees claims Niagara Region is allowing bacteria laden drinking water into Niagara homes. CUPE is warning don't drink it, the region says it's okay.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more.
<i><br>  CUPE president Sid Ryan says he won't drink Niagara water because there's bateria in it.<br>  Ecoli and fecal coliform bateria.  The type that came make a person very sick. <br>  CUPE local 1287 says inspectors who test the drinking water have told them the bacteria levels in Fort Erie, Port Colborne and Lincoln are unacceptable.  And the reason they are unacceptable is because unqualified people have been running the water treatment plants during this five week strike. <br>  The union's calling on the environment minister to rescind the contingency plan drawn for the strike.  To conduct and independent investigation.  And to fully disclose test results. <br>  The region did show us some test results.  Results that indicate no amounts of bacteria in the drinking water.<br>  The union is saying that it's warning the public of a potential health hazard.<br>  The region is charging the union with fearmongering. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Halton Meeting </b><p>
Hundreds of parents jammed into school gyms in Oakville and Burlington last night to hear details of the Halton Board of Education's plans to close a dozen of their schools.<br> The director of education expxlained provincial cutbacks have placed the board in a desperate financial situation.<br>  Bob Williams says the sale of 12 schools, that have yet to identified will save the board 24-million dollars.<br> Some parents fear the board is moving too quickly.
<hr>
<b>Brantford Fatal</b><p>
<br>  Highway 403 near Cainsville Road in Brantford remains closed at this hour after an as yet unidentified motorist was killed this afternoon in a major car crash involving several vehicles. Details remain sketchy... it isn't clear if charges are pending. Provincial police officers remain on the scene, sorting out what actually happened.
<hr>
<b>St. Kitts Bomb Arrest</b><p>
A Stouffeville man has been arrested in connection with last week's bomb threat at St. Catharines General Hospital. 33 year old Myles Bentley Groulx is facing a number of charges, including possession of explosives. The incident forced the evacuation of a wing of the hospital. Police say Groulx had no connection to the hospital. They say the motive for the bomb threat is interesting, but they're not releasinge details of that motive, until the suspect's trial.
<hr>
<b>Satan's Choice</b><p>
And two members of the Satan's Choice motorcycle gang in Hamilton were arrested last night.<br> Police recovered a revolver and two sawed-off shot guns.<br> The revolver was found in the car of a gang member.<br> The shotguns were seized during a search of the Satan's Choice clubhouse on Lottridge and Biggar.<br> 35-year-old Peter Grigorovsky of Stoney Creek faces two weapons charges.<br> 32 year-old William Weir of Hamilton faces three weapons offences.<br> Bail has been opposed.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Get ready for another interest rate cut.<br>  The Canadian dollar has climbed to its strongest level so far this year, above 74 cents U.S.<br>  Investors have a renewed confidence in Canada because our government budget deficits are falling faster than expected. The experts say that should lead to lower interest rates.<br> 






<P>
