<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, October 9, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Sean O'Sullivan Lab 
    <li>Wayne Gretzky Way?  
    <li>Niagara Stunt          
    <li>Super City Vote     
    <li>Glendale Experiment 
    <li>Missing Person      
    <li>Most Wanted         
    <li>Connors Brewery     
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Cumis Apples        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>sean o'sullivan lab</b><p>
His name personified hope to many and now the Father Sean O'Sullivan Research Centre is keeping that hope alive.
<br>   Hope in the form of cures and treatments for patients, and hope in the form of expansion at St. Joseph's Hospital, as the centre reaches its fundraising goal.<br>  Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  Former Ticat Bernie Faloney quarter-backed the fundraising kickoff for the new research centre.<br>  In less than two years, they've raised more than 10 million dollars.<br>  The money won't be spent on bricks and mortar, the centre itself operates throughout St Joseph's Hospital.<br>  Instead, the funds will be spent on new researchers ... from graduate students to senior scientists.  <br>  Their work focuses on new approaches to clinical care and research on urinary, bone and joint and chest and lung diseases.<br>  The research centre is named after Father Sean O'Sullivan for the spirit of discovery and optimism he was known for.<br>  At the age of 20 he became the youngest member of parliament in Canadian history, then he left politics to enter the priesthood.<br>  Father O'Sullivan died in 1989 of leukemia.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Wayne Gretzky Way?</b><p>
Could it just be a Canadian thing? We just don't respect our heroes when they become too successful.<br> The managing editor of a Brantford weekly paper thinks so, after readers overwhelmingly opposed naming a street after Wayne Gretzky.<br> But, as Dwight Ryan reports, many Brantford residents heartily disagree.  <br> 
<i><br>  It was Alexander Graham Bell who first put the city of Brantford on the map.<br>  But a young hockey player soon turned the telephone city into the home of Wayne Gretzky.  <br>  A flap has developed in Brantford over the renaming of a street.  Should Park Avenue North become Wayne Gretzky Boulevard?<br>  Readers of a weekly newspaper overwhelmingly said no.  And managing editor Ron Kowalsky was surprised by their venom.   <br>    Since then the so-called controversy has taken on a life of its own.<br>  Kowalsky is even quoted in the current issue of Time Magazine.   <br>    Soon the daily newspaper was defending the great one.<br>  The local radio station decided to downplay the issue saying it wasn't news.   <br>    While the naysayers called the weekly newspaper,  they were hard to find on market square over the noon-hour.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Niagara Stunt</b><p>
Charles Blondin did it in 1860 and made quite a name for himself. Now over a century later, stuntman Jay Cochrane wants to try it too: walk a tight rope across Niagara Falls. Just last month, the Toronto native, who's been doing this kind of thing since 1971 thrilled thousands in Shanghai when he skywalked more than 200 yards between two skyscrapers without a safety net.  A year ago, he crossed the Yangtze River in one of the longest highest crossings ever attempted.  As for the Niagara feat, the queston is will he be allowed to?  At this time, Niagara Falls mayor Wayne Thompson and his American counterpart are enthousiastically endorsing the plan and city council has given it's approval in principle
<hr>
<b>Super City Vote</b><p>
It wasn't a difficult feat for Hamilton city council last night.  They voted 9-6 to replace the Hamilton-Wentworth Region with a super-city.  The vote essentially undoes from a city stand-point what the region did last week when the majority of councillors voted to disband the region in a bid to revert to single local governments.                 The city's actions last night are also seen an as invitation to the province to intervene and settle the long-standing squabble over regional government in time for next year's municipal election.
<hr>
<b>Glendale Experiment</b><p>
It turned out to be a science project. Students at Glendale Secondary were rushed into assemblies this morning after to learn that the subject of yesterday's bomb scare was a grade nine girl's science project, left behind when she moved lockers.<br> Glendale's principal called the assemblies to to talk about the dangers of calling in bomb scares, and playing with combustible materials.<br> As it turned out, the liquid in the 2 litre pop bottle was coloured water, not gasoline as originally suspected.
<hr>
<b>Missing Person</b><p>
Police in Niagara are seeking your help in finding a missing Welland woman. 43-year- old Audrey Desjardins was last seen almost a week ago driving a red wine coloured 1985 Ford LTD 4-door sedan, license OJM 741. She is described as white, five-three to five-four, 115 pounds, slim build, blonde hair, fair complexion. If you have any information that could help, calll Niagara Regional Police at 905-735-7811 extension 3300.
<hr>
<b>Most Wanted</b><p>
A Hamilton man wanted for almost a half-million dollars in income tax evasion has been named as most wanted by Hamilton- Wentworth Crime Stoppers.<br> Police say 55-year-old Herman Gebele also faces possession of stolen property charges in connection with numerous break and enters between 1989 and 1994.  Herman Gebele is a former Hamilton businesman. He is 55 years old, 5-foot-eleven, has thinning light brown hair and has been seen recently in the Hamilton area even though he is believed to reside in the U.S. now.
<hr>
<b>Connors Brewery</b><p>
The Brick Brewing Company is taking over Conners Micro-brewery of St. Catharines. Few financial details of the deal have been released but brick plans to move the Conners operations to its Waterloo facility by the end of the month. Only six Conners employees have been hired by Brick -- the other 20 people in St. Catharines will lose their jobs. Conners president Glen Dalzell says he's selling the brewery in the face of stiff competition and financial pressures.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
  Canada's major bank's announced today they are cutting mortgage rates for the second time in a week.<br>  Federal finance minister Paul Martin told a parliamentary committee the federal deficit is falling faster than the government expected because of low interest rates.<br>  K-Mart is chopping 150 jobs at its Canadian headquarters in Brampton.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Cumis Apples</b><p>
Finally tonight, for the fifth year in a row, a Burlington company is in the giving spirit.   The Cumis Group is donating its entire 225-apple tree orchard crop to charity. This morning volunteers from Cumis, were joined by an army of others from the Burlington Fire Department, Halton Regional Police, Hamilton Bulldogs, more than 15 social service agencies, even a team of celebrity volunteers for a picking fest at the Cumis head office. In previous year's the event has netted 800 bushels during the single day blitz, not to mention a few sore muscles.






<P>
