<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, October 8, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Glendale Evacuation 
    <li>Skyway Fatal        
    <li>Jeep Wheel          
    <li>Cannon St. Fire      
    <li>Stolen Van          
    <li>Boyle 
    <li>Downtown Plan       
    <li>Team Hamilton       
    <li>Housing Up          
    <li>G.M. Picket         
    <li>Jobs Poll           
    <li>Hands - Peace       
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Glendale Evacuation</b><p>
Classes were cancelled for hundred of Hamilton high school students today after two separate bomb threats.  And one turned out to be the real thing.
<br> Some tense hours for staff and students at Glendale Secondary School in east Hamilton this morning.<br>  A dangerous device was discovered in an empty locker prompting a full evacuation and a full police response...<br>  Jamie West has the story...
<i><br>Police were called about an hour after classes started at Glendale Secondary School.<br>  The school was immediately evacuated...and the Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police bomb squad called in...<br>  The device described by police as incindiary in nature as opposed to explosive was taken to a nearby quarry and destroyed.<br>  School officials say the finding came with no warning, and that there had been no trouble around Glendale in recent days.<br>  And police were barely finished clearing the scene... when at noon they were called to Winston Churchill School just a few miles away after an anonymous caller said a bomb would explode in 45 minutes.<br>  Again a full evacuation... students cheered, but daycare workers next door looked worried and upset.<br>  And again police did a full sweep of the building...<br>  No one was injured but classes at Churchill and all after school activities were cancelled.<br>  Glendale re-opened for afternoon classes but few students returned.<br>  Police are hoping to hear from anyone with information on either incident. </i>
<hr>
<b>Skyway Fatal</b><p>
And work crews fixing the highway over the Burlington Bay Skyway... watched in horror last night ... as a lone car pulled out past a group of escort vehicles, and slammed into the back of a paint truck. 27 year old Paul Boswell of York, Ontario, died immediately.<br> The driver of the paint truck, was not injured.
<hr>
<b>Jeep Wheel</b><p>
And police are continuing their investigation, into an accident on the QEW near Burlington Street yesterday.<br> A jeep travelling on the road, lost a wheel at high speed... the tire flew across the highway and slammed into an oncoming tour bus, injuring six people....one seriously. The jeep is being held, pending a full mechanical inspection of the vehicle.
<hr>
<b>Cannon St. Fire</b><p>
Yesterday we told you how an ambulance attendent rescued five people from a burning house in central Hamilton.<br> Well today we know what caused the 30-thousand dollar blaze ... a hydroponic marijuana growing operation.<br> A spokesman for the Hamilton Fire Department says makeshift wiring to the lamps, fans and pump to run the system sparked the fire.<br> Police recovered 60 plants from the attic, and have charged 26 year old Raymond Burns with cultivation of a narcotic.
<hr>
<b>Stolen Van</b><p>
Quite the surprise for a Hamilton man yesterday when he saw two teens driving around in his stolen van.<br> He called police who managed to stop the teens while they were stuck in traffic along Stonechurch Road on Hamilton mountain.<br> A pair of teenaged boys, aged 15 and 16 are charged with possession over 5-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Boyle </b><p>
Under intense pressure to resign over the Somalia Inquiry, Canada's chief of defence staff, General Jean Boyle quit today. His resignation, accepted by the prime minister follows David Collinette's departure as defence minister just four days ago.  
<hr>
<b>Downtown Plan</b><p>
City and regional councillors in Hamilton Wentworth are at this moment listening to plans for the rejuvenation of downtown Hamilton.<br>  At the urging of Mayor Bob Morrow, area homebuilders came up with a plan for renewal.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports, that for a modest investment of taxpayers money, the homebuilders say they can bring back life to the city's core.  <br>  
<i>The Hamilton Halton Homebuilders' Association has spent months preparing a renewal plan for downtown Hamilton.  It was an initiative that was started by Hamilton Mayor Bob Morrow several months ago.<br>  Many of the downtown buildings are in fact owned by members of the association, and it is in their interest too to see the downtown core revitalized.<br>  In an unusual meeting of city and regional councillors, the plan was unveiled, shrouded in secrecy.  <br>    It'll cost just over 400 thousand dollars to get the plan in motion.  The homebuilders want 90-thousand from the city, 90-thousand from the region.   <br>    Already apartments and offices above existing businesses are beginning to rent as people begin to sense an air of renewal.<br>  Condon says with downtown development fees already scrapped, no further concessions from the city are needed.   <br> City alderman and downtown businessman Marvin Caplan likes the plan.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Team Hamilton</b><p>
Meanwhile, fiery rhetoric is on the agenda for tonight's Hamilton city council meeting, when aldermen are asked to re-affirm their support for turning Hamilton- Wentworth region into a super-city.<br>  A slim majority of Hamilton councillors oppose last week's vote at Hamilton- Wentworth regional council to disband the region, and leave its six municipalities intact.<br>  Last June, Hamilton city council also voted to disband the region, but wanted Hamilton to gobble up its five suburban neighbours to create a super-city.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Housing Up</b><p>
The politics may be on shakey ground but the Hamilton housing market is sound.<br> Low mortgage rates and housing prices continue to spur new home construction.<br> Figures released today by Canada Mortgage and Housing show starts jumped to 265 units last month, up from 162 units in September of 1995.  That represents a 64 per cent increase.
<hr>
<b>G.M. Picket</b><p>
A real estate agent in St. Catharines meanwhile, says his phone has stopped ringing.<br> Michael Turner says it's been like a morgue since five-thousand autoworkers went on strike against General Motors a week ago, joining their counterparts in Oshawa and Ste. Therese, Quebec.<br> Mayor Al Unwin says he's worried for the five-thousand striking autoworkers, suppliers and the company.  Buzz Hargrove, head of the Canadian Auto Workers Union, says the prospects for a quick settlement still look dim because after four decades GM seems determined to scrap ``pattern bargaining,'' in which the union reaches a deal with one automaker and expects the other two to match it.<br> GM says it doesn't intend to copy the deal reached with Chysler last month.
<hr>
<b>Jobs Poll</b><p>
Don't ask the autoworkers but according to the latest Angus Reid survey, 9 out of 10 Canadians like their jobs.<br> The poll says pay is not the top factor. Instead job satisfaction, respect from bosses, and a feeling of control are the more important.<br> That's why, the survey says, the self-employed are the happiest workers, even though they work the longest hours. On the down side ... 22 percent of us worry that we will lose our jobs; a result of downsizing, and continued unemployment.
<hr>
<b>Hands - Peace</b><p>
Nearly one hundred and 50 young school children joined hands in Hamilton this morning to mark the YWCA's Week Without Violence.<br> As they walked around Whitehern Museum downtown, the children were raising their hands in support of the Y's initiative to promote practical alternatives to violence at home, at schoool and in their neighbourhoods.






<P>
