<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, October 7, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>St. Kitts Pickets
    <li>CAW - Ford       
    <li>Palladini - Highways  
    <li>Cannon St Fire      
    <li>Tennis Arrests      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Welland Food Fest   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>St. Kitts Pickets</b><p>
The latest word is the General Motors talks are going nowhere and there's little hope of averting a huge autoworkers strike as thousands more prepare to join the picket lines.  We have a number of stories on the autoworkers strike tonight, beginning with the domino effect. A Toronto area GM supplier has laid off 15-hundred workers and in the United States, a thousand workers were sent home today from a GM powertrain plant in Tonawanda near Buffalo and 800 will be laid-off from a transmission plant in the Detroit area tonight.  
<br>   More than five thousand GM workers in St. Catharines hit the picket lines midnight last night.<br>  The striking employees were joining their counterparts in Oshawa and Ste Therese, Quebec who walked off the job last week. All in all there are some 20-thousand out now in Ontario and Quebec. 46-hundred more are ready to go out in London, Woodstock and Windsor at midnight Wednesday. The main issue in the dispute remains outsourcing. The workers feel they will lose their jobs if GM contracts out work to other manufacturers who pay less.
<hr>
<b>CAW - Ford</b><p>
 And in another development, the head of the CAW, Buzz Hargrove is threatening to break-off negotiations with GM and start talks with Ford. 
<hr>
<b>Palladini - Highways</b><p>
While the automakers work to keep the industry going through all of this, Queen's Park is trying to keep the traffic moving smoothly through Ontario's highway system.<br>  But they need more money to do it.<br>  And as Dwight Ryan reports, the province's transportation minister is hoping some of it will come from the federal government.  <br>  
<i><br>  Ontario drivers pay the federal government two billion dollars a year in gas taxes.  None of that money is returned to the province for road maintenance, even though sixty percent of Ontario's roads are in need of repair.<br>  The province's transportation minister says its not fair..and today he went before a federal transporatation committee demanding cash.   <br>    Al Palladini wants two cents out of every ten cents a litre in tax returned to Ontario.  Asked by committee members what committment Queens Park was willing to make, he said 700 million dollars will be spent this year alone on highway repairs.   <br>    Some Liberal commitee members don't see it that way.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Cannon St Fire</b><p>
Hamilton firefighters say it will be some time before they know the extent of this damage. A three story home on Cannon Street near Wentworth went up in flames this morning. There is no word on what sparked the blaze.<br>  Five people escaped without injury thanks to the assistance of ambulance officer Tim Spence who arrived just before fire crews.
<hr>
<b>Tennis Arrests</b><p>
A tip to a school's liason officer has led the arrests of four teens.  The boys aged 14 to 17 have been charged in a break and enter at the Valley Park Tennis Club in Stoney Creek, we featured last week.<br>  The newly constructed club was nearly ready for use when vandals broke in two weeks ago, breaking windows, punching holes in walls and throwing paint throughout the building.<br>  The spree caused 15-thousand dollars in damage.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Interest rates paid on Government of Canada Bonds are falling while Canadian stock prices continuing smashing new records.<br>  A new wave of investors confidence is also strengthening the loonie, lifiting the dollar close to 74 cents U.S.
<hr>
<b>Welland Food Fest</b><p>
Finally tonight, another successful Niagara Food Festival has come and gone.  The 3rd Annual Welland Food Festival drew record crowds once again and while eveyone ended up a winner, three of them have ended up winners of a CHCH TV food festival draw. They are: first prize: Internet In  A Box goes to Maggie Joyce of Coquitlam, B.C., Norma Warner of St. Catharines wins a CHCH-TV shirt and basball cap, and Gary Dolan of Lowbanks, Ontario takes home a CHCH-TV T-shirt and baseball cap.






<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

