<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, October 4, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>St. Kitts Bomb      
    <li>Mountain Murder     
    <li>Bank Robbery        
    <li>Highway Six Crash      
    <li>Old Dumps           
    <li>Dundurn Delights    
    <li>Canine Demo         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>St. Kitts Bomb</b><p>
The emergency room at St. Catharines General Hospital became an emergency last night and was evacuated after police found what they are calling explosive materials inside the emergency room.  Lauran Sabourin has more.
<i><br>  Just before six last evening the switchboard at the St. Catharines General received an anonymous call that a suspicious package was left in the emergency room.<br>  Police found the package inside ceiling tiles in the men's washroom in the emergency room area.<br>  One report suggested that the explosives may have been sticks of dynamite but police will not confirm that.<br>  Within minutes of the package being located the emergency room was evacuated.<br>  One hundred, sixteen patients in the floors above the emergency room were moved to another building. <br>  The bomb squad removed the package from the building by tying and line to it and then pulled it out...<br>  The prodedure took quite a while.<br>  Patients and staff still in the building were left wondering what was going on .. <br>  The package was taken to an empty lot where it was destroyed. <br>  Police say at no time was the package a danger to the public. <br>  As a result of this incident the hospital is reviewing it's security measures. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Mountain Murder</b><p>
Yet another murder on the books for Hamilton Wentworth. Police are canvassing a neighbourhood on Hamilton's east mountain this morning, trying to locate witnesses after a man was found dead in his home. The body of 43 year old Gary Gatecliffe was discovered in his bed by his mother, who went the house because she hadn't heard from him for a couple of days. Police say there were obvious signs of trauma to Mr. Gatecliffe's head. An autopsy is to be performed later this afternoon.
<hr>
<b>Bank Robbery</b><p>
Police in Hamilton are looking for the bandit who made off with cash from a Bank of Montreal branch on Queenston Road this morning.<br> It happened just before ten oclock.  The suspect told the clerk he had a gun and demanded money.  He made off in what turned out to be a stolen Honda Civic.  By the time police recovered the abandoned car the thief had escaped in a second vehicle.<br> The suspect is described as being a white male with reddish hair.  He's 5-feet, eight inches tall and was wearing dark clothing.  The weapon he said he had wasn't seen.
<hr>
<b>Highway Six Crash</b><p>
An 11 year old Toronto girl remains in serious, but stable condition in McMaster Medical Centre, following a serious car crash, yesterday evening.<br> Limore Gutman received major injuries, when the van in which she was a passenger, was rear-ended by a second vehicle on Highway 6, near Safari Road. Gutman was flown by air ambulance to McMaster University Medical Centre, with neck and back injuries considered serious but not life threatening.<br> 4 other teens and the two adult drivers were treated and released from hospitals, with minor injuries.<br> Police have now charged the driver of the car, 57 year old Roger Hansell of Campbellville, with careless driving.
<hr>
<b>Old Dumps</b><p>
The cost of eliminating health and environmental risks at old dump sites in Hamilton- Wentworth, is a hefty one.<br>  Next week, a regional committee will consider a report that says it will cost thirteen-and-a- half million dollars to make the dumps safe.<br>  And in some cases, if the region fails to act immediately, it risks facing charges from the ministry of the environment.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i><BR>The prospect of spending millions to clean up old dump sites comes at a time when Hamilton- Wentworth region can ill afford it.  Hamilton- Wentworth inherited responsibility for ten old dump sites when the region was created in 1974. Six of them pose little or no risk to human health or the environment.  One of them, the former Brampton Street landfill site in Hamilton, has been given a medium priority for action. The remaining three have high priority, and staff recommend immediate action to correct problems, primarily with leachate.  <BR>The old Ancaster dump needs improvements to its leachate collection system, to ensure well water is not contaminated. Tests also show groundwater contamination has occurred south of the old Edgewood landfill site in Flamborough, which has no leachate collection system at all.  Mayor McMeeking has no fear that Hamilton councillors, upset by this week's vote to disband the region, will retaliate by refusing spend money on dump clean-ups in the suburbs.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Dundurn Delights</b><p>
Hamilton's Dundurn Castle will be fragrant with the scent of history this weekend.<br> This as the Garden Club of Hamilton holds its first ever juried flower show at the castle.<br> The show is a floral fundraiser to raise money to restore the castle grounds to their former splendour.<br> Annette Hamm gives us a preview.
<i><br>  These arrangements are bringing a dimension to Dundurn Castle not seen since the days of its first owner, Sir Allan McNab.<br>  His gardening staff would have seen to it the home was filled with beautiful floral designs all year round.<br>  Sir Allan himself was quite the flower enthusiast.  <br>  This weekend, Dundurn is filled with beautiful bouquets and arrangments to celebrate the castle's restoration and Hamilton's sesquicentennial.<br>  It's the club's first public show, a high end competition for both professional designers and an open class.  <br>  As judges in the flower show, co-chairs Elizabeth Pigott and Elizabeth Coons keep an eye out for specific elements of design.  <br>  Dundurn Delights, A Castle Revisited runs Friday until 8 o'clock, Saturday from 10 to 5 and Sunday from 12 to 4.<br>  Proceeds will go towards restoring the castle's landscape.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Canine Demo</b><p>
Police K-9 dogs in training were showing off their skills today at the Niagara Regional Police training facility in Niagara on the Lake.<br> Police dog Thunder is three weeks into his training. When he graduates in December, Thunder and his handler Constable Yancy Eddie will be serving on the Haldimand Norfork Police force.<br>  The Niagara Police Canine Training Program is recognized as one of the best in the country.  And has trained 27 dogs for various forces in tracking techniques.






<P>
