<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, October 3, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>G.M. - St. Kitts    
    <li>Niagara-CUPE Update 
    <li>H.W. Animosity      
    <li>Fatal Accident         
    <li>Harbourfront Fine   
    <li>Robberies           
    <li>Dangerous Offender  
    <li>Rolider Review      
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>G.M. - St. Kitts</b><p>
Autoworkers in St. Catharines are cobbling together picket signs and collecting steel barrels for fires to keep their hands warm as they prepare to strike. And it could happen within days if a deal isn't reached between G.M. and their union.
<br>  In Oshawa and St. Therese, Quebec, meanwhile, auto workers are already carrying picket signs. And those on the lines say there's a lot of support among members of the Canadian Auto Workers for the strike. So far, 15 thousand GM workers are on strike, and thousands... including those in St. Catharines ... more are set to join them next week. All of this as economists warn the GM strike will throw roadblocks in the way of economic recovery in Canada.
<hr>
<b>Niagara-CUPE Update</b><p>
A pep talk today for striking regional workers in Niagara. CUPE national president Judy Darcy congratulated workers on five differnet picket lines for what she described as their courageous stand. Union officials are anxious to get back to the negotiating table, and are awaiting a call from the region. The strike by 650 inside & outside workers is in its fifth week.
<hr>
<b>H.W. Animosity</b><p>
Back in the endangered region of Hamilton; Hamilton city councillors, who voted earlier this week to dismantle the region, today admit their support for the plan is conditional.<br>  And at least one of them is prepared to reverse his stand, unless Hamilton's suburbs are willing to share both their wealth and their land with the city.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> <BR>Some Hamilton councillors have their eye on lands to the south of the city.  They'd also like a piece of the suburban tax revenues generated by development, made possible through the expenditure of regional tax dollars.  And they figure it's a fair price for the suburbs to pay in exchange for their support of the motion to abolish Hamilton- Wentworth Region.  <BR>On Tuesday, Hamilton city council is expected to reaffirm its position in favour of creating a super city, encompassing the entire region. Morrow says municipal affairs minister Al Leach has agreed to take the city's position into account before reacting to the request to abolish Hamilton- Wentworth Region. </i>
<hr>
<b>Fatal Accident</b><p>
Police looking for witnesses to a fatal accident in Hamilton shortly after six o'clock last night.<br>  A man, stepped off the curb at the corner of Prospect and Main Street East, was struck by an oncoming car.<br>  39 year old Wayne Haylock of Hamilton died.<br>  Police are still investigating, and would appreciate a call from anyone who may have seen the crash.
<hr>
<b>Harbourfront Fine</b><p>
This east Hamilton recycling business has been fined 10-thousand dollars for endangering the environment. And the Hamilton Fire Department warns it could face up to 50-thousand more in fire code violation fines if these huge piles don't get a whole lot smaller. Harbour Front Properties on Burlington St. East pleaded guilty to the violations last November. The monstrous mounds contain combustible recycled building materials. It took weeks to locate and entinguish smouldering fires deep within the mounds that began last Christmas Day. At 10 meters in height, the piles of recycled building materials are more than three times higher and more than 30 times wider than allowed by law.
<hr>
<b>Robberies</b><p>
Police investigating a number of robberies in Hamilton overnight.<br>  Uncle Tommy's Variety and a 7-11, both in Hamilton's east end were hit early this morning.<br>  Just a few hours before, another gas bar, this one on Hamilton mountain, was robbed.<br>  The clerk refused a man's demands for cash and sent him on his way.<br>  The clerk called police with a description of the suspect's getaway car, noticing it had no licence plates.<br>  Police found the car, with the plates inside, and traced them back to the suspect's home.<br>  27 year old Mark Johnston of hamilton is charged with robbery.
<hr>
<b>Dangerous Offender</b><p>
 A Hamilton man; who cannot be named ... has been declared a dangerous offender.<br>  Mr. Justice Nick Borkovich handed down a harshly worded ruling yesterday; describing the 45 year old man as "a cancer on the public body" and seemed to suggest that a punishment of inderminate sentence in prison, was not harsh enough. The man's identity has not been released to protect the identity of his victims.
<hr>
<b>Rolider Review</b><p>
They claimed this man was a dangerous offender when it comes to the treatment of brain injured patients.....<br>  In 1989 Dr. Ahmos Rolider was hired to head up a new program to treat young people with brain injuries at Hamilton's Chedoke McMaster Hospitals.<br>  Early in 1995 several staff and former patients of Rolider came forward with allegations of abuse. The hospital told CHCH News in March of 1995 that they had done their own review of the program and that no staff complaints had been brought forward.<br>  Earlier this year the family of another former Rolider patient stepped forward with more allegations of abuse at Chedoke during Rolider's tenure and they've been calling for an investigation.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Financial markets took a rest today after setting record highs on stock markets over the past two days.<br>  There's new speculation that the Bank of Canada might cut interest rates further.<br>  






<P>
