<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, October 2, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Region Abolished?   
    <li>Bourassa      
    <li>Piccolo Funeral     
    <li>Car vs. Pedestrian  
    <li>Bikers Charged      
    <li>Gas Bar Arrest      
    <li>Design Network      
    <li>Business First        
</ul>

<hr>
<b>Region Abolished?</b><p>
Months of political bickering over the future of local government in Hamilton- Wentworth came to an abrupt end last night, as regional council voted to eliminate itself. <br> Nine suburban councillors and eight Hamilton councillors voted to abolish Hamilton- Wentworth Region, and to give the City of Hamilton responsibility for what are now regional services.<BR>
And the Ontario cabinet minister responsible for approving the abolition of Hamilton- Wentworth is surprisingly receptive to the idea.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i>The seventeen councillors who voted in favour of dismantling Hamilton- Wentworth Region have been branded as separatists, and accused of betrayal. Regional Chairman Terry Cooke condemns the vote as the product of an unholy alliance between suburban and Hamilton politicians, who are motivated only by the desire to protect their council seats.  <BR>Hamilton councillor Henry Merling introduced the motion, and lined up the votes necessary to give it a decisive victory. He says abolishing the region is preferable to the City of Hamilton's proposal to annex its five suburban neighbours.  <BR>Meanwhile, Cooke predicts the province will now be forced to step in.  But don't count on the province the rule out the elimination of Hamilton- Wentworth Region.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Bourassa</b><p>
Politicians at all levels of government were paying tribute to former Quebec premier Robert Bourassa today.<br> He died this morning after a lengthy battle with skin cancer at age 63. 
<hr>
<b>Piccolo Funeral</b><p>
They filled the pews of St. Francis Xavier Church, they filled the chairs in an ajoining hall.<br> More than 1200 people gathered today to say goodbye to three victims of violence.<br> A mother and her two young children were stabbed to death a week ago.<br> Today a preist referred to their deaths as an annihilation of innocense.<br> Dwight Ryan reports.   <br>  
<i>An air of profound sadness surrounded St. Francis Xavier Church in Stoney Creek.<br>  More than 1200 family and friends of Fran Piccolo, her ten year old son Jason and eight year old daughter Alisha came to say goodbye.<br>  The funeral mass was conducted in both english and italian.<br>  Father John Van Hees called their violent deaths an annihilation of innocense adding they are now at peace.  They are with their god and they can see the light of god. As the three white caskets were placed in three silver hearses, the tragedy seemed overwhelming. Father Van Hees said if someone could give us the reasons why this happened, then we could better deal with our grief, yet no matter how many answers we receive they do not take away from us the pain of loss that we feel.  We are still left in silence.<br>  In that silence,  the procession moved away from the church. Classmates of Jason and Alisha at Our Lady of Peace Catholic School formed an honour guard. Each held a single white carnation.<br>  Across the street, the students of St. Francis Xavier Catholic Elementary School lined the street to show their respect.<br>  Through their tears, they knew they were witnessing an enormous loss of innocense.  And they wondered why?</i>
<hr>
<b>Car vs. Pedestrian</b><p>
A serious accident over the noon hour on Hamilton mountain.  A car, making a turn off West Fifth onto Mohawk Road collided with another vehicle.<br> An unfortunate pedestrian was crossing the intersection at the same time.<br> She was struck and has been admitted to hospital with serious injuries.<br> No charges have yet been laid.<br> Police are still investigating.
<hr>
<b>Bikers Charged</b><p>
A Milton man is lucky to be alive tonight after after an attempt on his life in front of this industrial building on Lawson Road in Milton. It could have been the first bloodshed in the feared turf war between rival biker gangs in the golden horseshoe. Two members of the Satans Choice have been charged with attempted murder and a string of weapons offences after shots were fired at 31-year-old Rayne Doherty of Milton, the past president of the Lost Souls.<br> Doherty was able to run away and hide and call police on his cell phone.<br> Police stopped a vehicle fleeing from the scene. Charged are: 30-year-old Michael Peter O'Shaughnessy of Oakville and 29-year-old Kevin Eric Zita of Mississauga.
<hr>
<b>Gas Bar Arrest</b><p>
The arrest of a robbery suspect over the weekend has helped Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police solve five other gas bar hits.<br> A man arrested after a gas station was robbed Saturday night has been charged with five additional counts of robbery.<br> In less than one month, six Hamilton gas stations were robbed at knifepoint.<br> Charged is 28 year old Rade Maglov of Hamilton.
<hr>
<b>Design Network</b><p>
Take eight very talented women, all specialists in their own craft.<br> Put them together in the homey backyard setting of a restored carriage house.<br> What do you get?<br> A design network with a unique approach.<br> Annette Hamm explains.
<i><br> From this inviting carriage house in Waterdown, eight enterprising women hope to make the world of design a little less intimidating.<br>  They want to dispel the myth that asking a designer for help means spending a lot of money.  <br>  The design network was the brainchild of Deby Milford, an interior designer who's worked together with her seven colleagues for the last 10 or 15 years.<br>  Together, they cover the whole spectrum of what it takes to make your house a home.  <br>  Starting next week, the design network is offering classes in everything from Christmas decorations to faux finishes and wild and free floral arranging.<br>  An open house will be held this weekend from ten til 5 at the carriage house on John Street.<br> </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
The Bank of Canada has dropped the central bank rate by a quarter point.  The chartered banks are following suit lowering their prime rates.  Mortgage and loan rates are sure to follow.<br> All this on a day that the stock markets soared to new levels.<br> 






<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

