<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 10/01/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, October 1, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Hamilton / Niagara Housing 
    <li>Niagara Hospitals   
    <li>McCull./Reg. Motion 
    <li>Vanscoy Suspect     
    <li>Robbery Arrests     
    <li>Thieves Caught      
    <li>Crack Cash          
    <li>Fox 40 Suit         
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Hamilton / Niagara Housing</b><p>
Hot. hot. hot. The housing market in Hamilton Wentworth, and across the country, is experiencing a dramatic turnaround. <br> And delegates to a Hamilton conference heard today that the market is expected to remain strong.
<br> Dwight Ryan tells us, the main reason is low interest rates.
<i><br>Residential housing sales in Hamilton Wentworth are up 30 percent over a year ago.  And the market is expected to remain strong.<br>  Houses on the market are usually sold within 90 days and selling prices are 94 percent of the list.<br>  The market is so hot that Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation says there are housing shortages in some areas.    <br>  Not only is the resale market hot, new home construction starts are up 50 percent over a year ago.<br>  Helen Hutton is a senior market analyst with CMHC.  At a Hamilton conference she said first time buyers are driving the market, primarily due to low interest rates.   And the scenario is similar across the country.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Niagara Hospitals</b><p>
 The news isn't so bright when it comes to the health care industry.  With the announcement of the closing of two of Sudbury's three hospitals the ontario government is showing that it's serious about cutting health care spending.<br> Hamilton hospitals have been through a major restructuring and now Niagara is tackling the issue.<br>  Lauran Sabourin reports.
<i><br>  Niagara region has 430 thousand residents.<br>  Ten hospitals and about 900 hospital beds.<br> That's about 35 percent hospital beds than the region had just five years ago.<br>  But if the government has its way the region will do will even less.<br>  Fewer hospital beds.<br>  Possibly even fewer hositals. <br>  It's the goal of the Niagara District Health Council to come up with a savings plan for health care in Niagara. <br>   The District Health Council is looking for ways to save money.<br>  Individual hospitals are doing the same thing.<br>  This afternoon Hotel Dieu Hospital in St. Catharines announced plans for a partnership with Haldimand War Memorial Hospital in Dunnville.<br>  They're looking to share some technology and expertise.<br>  The hospitals are scrambling for ways to cut costs.<br>  The District Health Council is doing the same thing.<br>  Everyone wants to remain in the health care ministry's good books.<br> </i>
<hr>
<b>McCull./Reg. Motion</b><p>
From restructuring hospitals to regional government. It's a debate that's raged on in Hamilton-Wentworth since the early 70's. Vic Copps was the mayor then and he went as far as chaining himself to the gates of the legislation over the issue. In just about two hours time, Hamilton alderman Bill McCulloch will introduce a notice of motion at regional council that he hopes will once and for all end the impass. 
<hr>
<b>Vanscoy Suspect</b><p>
One day after the funeral of 14 year old Jasmine Vanscoy ... the young offender charged with her killing appeared in court. The 17 year old boy, charged with second degree murder made a brief appearance this morning. Police say Vanscoy was shot in the head with a.45 calibre pistol that was stolen from an Oshawa sporting goods shop, six years ago.
<hr>
<b>Robbery Arrests</b><p>
Two Brantford men are in custody tonight awaiting a bail hearing, nabbed by the Hamilton-Wentworth police bank robbery task force.  They've been charged in connection with a Royal Bank robbery in Dundas last Friday, but further charges are also pending. 24-year-old Neal Anthony McMullan and 28-year-old Wesley Earl Woodcock are both from Brantford.
<hr>
<b>Thieves Caught</b><p>
A man walking back to his van last night in downtown Hamilton managed to catch a thief red-handed.<br> Police say two men were breaking into the van when the owner approached.<br> One suspect took off, but the owner was able to tackle the other one, and hold him until police arrived.<br> 18 year old William James Charles Mason of Hamilton is charged with attempted theft and possession of burglary tools.
<hr>
<b>Crack Cash</b><p>
It might have paid just to sit still ... but a passenger in a car stopped by police bolted as the cops were questioning him and the driver.<br> On his way out the door, the suspect dropped several pieces of crack cocaine before police grabbed him.<br> They also found a large quantity of cash.<br> 29 year old Jason Grandville of Rexdale is charged with obstructing police, possession for the purpose of trafficking, and possession of property obtained by crime.
<hr>
<b>Fox 40 Suit</b><p>
The makers of the Fox 40 are blowing the whistle on a competitor. Hamilton businessman, entrepreneur Ron Foxcroft has filed a statement of claim in federal court against the makers of the Acme Tornado 2000, claiming their whistle is a copy of the famous Fox 40 pea-less whistle designed and manufactured here in Hamilton and shipped all over the world.  The Acme Tornado 2000 whistle is made by J. Hudson and Company  and is distributed in Canada by A. Conway Beacham Limited. Foxcroft, a basketball referee and an industrial designer unveiled the Fox 40 in 1987 originally for the professional referee market but now, it's used widely for safety and protection.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Low interest rates and renewed investor confidence setoff a buying spree of stocks in Toronto and New York today, sending share values in both Canada and the U.S. to new record highs.<br>  More improving forecasts for Canada's housing industry.  





<P>
