<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, September 30, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Mulcahy Remand      
    <li>Vanscoy Funeral     
    <li>Ancaster Fire       
    <li>Gas Bar Arrest      
    <li>Manufacturing       
    <li>Seaway Update       
</ul>
<HR>
<b>Mulcahy Remand</b>
<br> A Montreal native charged with three counts of first degree murder made a brief court appearance in Hamilton today.<br> 27 year-old Shane Mulcahy faces the charges following the stabbing deaths last week of a Stoney Creek mother and her two young children.<br> Mulcahy was not represented by a lawyer and was remanded in custody until next Monday morning.  Wearing a prison uniform and handcuffs, Mulcahy said little during his brief court appearance. <br>  A funeral mass for Fran Piccolo and her children Jason and Alisha will be held Wednesday morning at 10 o'clock at St. Francis Zavier Church on Highway Eight in Stoney Creek.
<hr>
<b>Vanscoy Funeral</b>
<br> A funeral service for 14 year old Jasmine Vanscoy was held in St. Catharines today.<br> The teenager died after being shot in the head with a .45 calibre weapon at her home Tuesday night.<br>  St. Alfred's Roman Catholic Church was filled to capacity this morning with people wanting to pay their respects.<br> The grade 9 student at Holy Cross High School had been on life support for two days before she died.<br> A 17 year old young offender has been charged with second degree murder in connection with her death and he will appear in St. Catharines court for a bail hearing tomorrow morning.
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Fire</b>
<br> Police and the Ontario Fire Marshall's Office are investigating a suspicious car and garage fire in Ancaster over the weekend that caused 120-thousand dollars in damage.<br> Witnesses say they heard a car speeding away shortly before the fire started early Sunday morning.<br> At least one other car in the residential neighbourhood was broken into and nearly set on fire.<br> Several other vehicles were broken into and ransacked.
<hr>
<b>Gas Bar Arrest</b>
<br> A police officer, suspicious of a car driving through downtown Hamilton without headlights on this weekend, helped to nab a suspect after a series of gas bar robberies.<br> The officer noted the description of the car and its occupant, then about 20 minutes later, responded to a robbery at a gas bar where the suspect matched the description.<br> 28 year old Rade Maglov of Hamilton is charged with robbery.<br> Police are now trying to link this latest robbery with five more at other gas stations.
<hr>
<b>Manufacturing</b>
<br> Canada's economy is on the rebound.  Figures from Statistics Canada indicate our economic pulse is getting stronger.<br>  Despite an increase in the gross domestic product, economists feel more must be done to turn the economy around.<br>  Dwight Wyan has that story.      
<i><br>  Canada's economy is humming along.<br>  The gross domestic product, a total of all the goods and services produced in the country, rose in July by 0.5 percent. Just about every sector increased meaning our economy is finally pulling out of the doldrums.  <br>    Slowly but surely however, those attitudes appear to be changing.   <br>  Federal economists feel the jump in the GDP will lead to a revival in consumer spending and job creation.<br>  This McMaster University economist says its great, but more has to be done.   </i>
<hr>
<b>Seaway Update</b>
<br>  By February of next year control of the St. Lawrence Seaway is going to be handed over to those who use it.<br>  As Lauran Sabourin reports, the federal government wants out of the shipping business, and it's trying to negotiate a deal with its U.S. counterpart to do the same.
<i><br>  Since 1959 the St. Lawrence Seaway Authority has been guiding ships down the river from the Atlantic Ocean to Thunder Bay.<br>  And since then the Seaway Authority has been an agency of the federal government.<br>  Subsidized by taxpayers.<br>  But with the mounting debt the government wants to get out of the shipping business.<br>  It wants to hand control of the system over to those who use it most: the shipping companies and the companies whose comodities are being shipped.<br>  But in the longer term the Seaway Authority is negotiating with its U.S. counterpart to have one agency running the system.<br>  As the government sees it, one agency will be more efficient.<br>  Commonality on the kinds of things such as ship inspections and regulations.<br>  More co-operation between the U.S. and Canada on navigational aids. <br>  The St. Lawrence Seaway isnt' a huge money making operation.<br>  Tolls have been lowered to lure more business to the system.<br>  But tonnage has remained flat in recent years.<br>  In 1995 it was just over 48 million tonnes moved on the system.<br>  Down from a peak in the late 70's of more than 70 million tonnes. <br>  The Seaway Authority is looking at handing over control of the system  to the Canadian users in the new year.<br>  But when exactly the U.S. and Canada will successfully negotiate the terms of a new cross border agency is still being explored. </i>





<P>
