<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, September 27, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>License Hike        
    <li>McCutcheon Deal     
    <li>Vanscoy Dies        
    <li>Student Hit         
    <li>Dundas Robbery      
    <li>Senior Warning      
    <li>Mental Health       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Habitat Update      
    <li>Fairclough Medal    
    <li>Wargames            
</ul>
<hr>
<b>License Hike</b><p>
 Downtown Hamilton business owners are crying foul over recently increased liscensing fees,<br>   But as Jamie West reports the city of Hamilton feels the increases are more than fair...
<i>They're close to wrapping up another year of business at Reardon's Meats where they see the city of Hamilton's liscense rate increase as a lot of baloney. Going from 50 dollars a year to 135 dollars annually.<br>  The same rate now applys to all establishments regardless of what they previously paid. <br>  And in fact because of the blanket rate of 135 dollars some businesses will actually see a decrease.  The city says reduced provincial transfer payments are the reason... and they'll rake in an additional 477 thousand  in revenue in 1997.<br>  Pub owner Ed Fisher says the city's double dipping.<br>  He isn't the only business owner crying in his beer, but can you fight city hall.<br>  It's not likely the city will be all ears when they come calling. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>McCutcheon Deal</b><p>
They were celebrating the Hamilton Civic Hospitals in the atrium of the Henderson this afternoon.<br>  Hospital staff, patients and guests joined in looking back at the shining moments of the civics as the organization gets ready to merge with Chedoke McMaster Hospitals on October first.<br>  Outgoing CEO Dr. David McCutcheon was honoured as he gets ready to start his new job as CEO of a major hospital in Ireland.<br>  His severance package worth 385-thousand dollars was made public this afternoon. Chedoke McMaster hospitals has refused to release details of the severance package given to their outgoing CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman.
<hr>
<b>Vanscoy Dies</b><p>
The 14-year-old St. Catharines girl who was shot in the head with a stolen handgun earlier this week has died. Jasmine Vanscoy had been on life support since the shooting in her home Tuesday.<br> police say she died late last night in McMaster Medical Centre in Hamilton.<br> A 17-year-old youth charged with attempted murder now faces a charge of second-degree murder.<br> Police confirm the victim knew her assailant, but they have yet to determine a motive for the slaying. It turns out the .45-calibre semi-automatic handgun used in the shooting was stolen six years ago from a gun shop in Oshawa.
<hr>
<b>Student Hit</b><p>
Police looking for witnesses to an accident in west Hamilton yesterday in which a student from Hong Kong was seriously injured.<br> The student was walking from Colombia College on Main Street when he stepped off the curb into the path of a dump truck.<br> It happened around 12:30 Thursday afternoon.<br> The 17 year old boy suffered a fractured skull and broken arm.
<hr>
<b>Dundas Robbery</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth police are looking for an armed bandit who made off with cash from the Royal Bank in Dundas this morning.<br> It happened just before 11 o'clock and he made his getaway on foot.<br> The suspect is described as being about 25 years old, five-feet, seven inches tall with a mustache, black t-shirt and black wraparound glasses.  He had a handgun.
<hr>
<b>Senior Warning</b><p>
A warning tonight for residents of seniors buildings in Hamilton's east end.<br> Seems a suspect is targetting a number of apartments, and stealing purses.<br> He's simply walking into units if no one answers the door.<br> Police warn residents to keep their doors locked and not to let anyone suspicious inside.<br> They're looking for a white man, about 20 to 30 years old with a medium build and dark brown hair.
<hr>
<b>Mental Health</b><p>
A top Hamilton criminal lawyer says cuts to legal aid are letting mentally ill people fall through the cracks of the justice system.<br>  Dean Paquette was among the featured speakers today at the national conference of the Canadian Mental Health Association.<br>  Mental health professionals and consumers have gathered in Hamilton this week to examine the interaction between the mentally ill, the media, and the criminal justice system.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> Panelists say an increasing number of mentally ill people have come in conflict with the law since legislative changes were enacted three years ago.  But criminal lawyer Dean Paquette says those charged with minor offences have little chance of finding a lawyer because of cuts to legal aid. And because of the Jonathan Yeo case, he says mentally ill people charged with violent crimes have little chance of getting out on bail.  <BR>Yeo was out on bail when he murdered two people, before killing himself. And Paquette says no one wants to run the risk of freeing another Jonathan Yeo.  Despite intense media coverage of cases like Jonathan Yeo's, Narozniak says that type of high risk offender is relatively rare.  <BR>The Canadian Mental Health Association national conference wraps up tomorrow.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stocks fell for a second day while interest yields on government bonds edged higher.<br>  The Canadian dollar strengthened by almost a quarter of a percentage point.<br>  Market watchers are expecting further dollar strength.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Habitat Update</b><p>
Now, an update on Hamilton's first ever Habitat for Humanity project. Tonight we meet the family who will call this labour of love home.<br> Annette Hamm introduces us to the Hernandez family and tells us what's ahead for them.
<i>This isn't how most families suit up for a new home.<br>  But Carlos and Maria Hernandez and their three sons are taking a definite hands-on approach to their four bedroom bungalow.<br>  They are Hamilton's first family to be housed by Habitat for Humanity.<br>  And under an agreement with the non profit building charity, have to put in 500 hours of sweat equity as a downpayment for their home.<br>  They've been working on it since day one.  <br>  In return, they'll get an interest free mortgage.<br> Habitant helps house families around the world who otherwise might never realize the dream of owning their own home.<br>  Nearly all of the materials are donated.<br>  Carlos Hernandez describes his families work as changing the little world around them.<br>  And while Maria Hernandez apologies for her english, it's easy to understand the gratitude in her eyes.  <br>  With three weeks to go before the house is finished, Hamilton Habitat for Humanity is still looking for help at the site.<br>  If you'd like to volunteer, just show up with your own tools at the corner of Loconder and Queen Victoria, just off Upper Gage on Hamilton's east mountain.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Fairclough Medal</b><p>
Hamilton's own Ellen Fairclough, Canada's first female cabinet minister has a new medal to add to the collection in her Stanley Avenue home. Last night she received the Order of Ontario. It's the highest honour conferred by the government of the province to citizens who have enriched the lives of others by attaining and setting high standards of excellence.  Mrs. Fairclough, now 91-years young has been honoured by every level of government for setting a role model for women in business and politics.  She made history in 1957 when prime minister John Diefenbaker named her to his cabinet.  Four other prominent citizens in the golden horshoe shared her honour:  Artist Trisha Romance of Niagara-on- the-lake, Astronaut colonel Chrias Hadfield of milton, Amber M. Foulkes of Oakville for her work with the disabld and union leader Clifford Russel Evans of Long Point.
<hr>
<b>Wargames</b><p>
<br> And finally tonight, if you see a few soldiers in full fighting gear engaged in some urban warfare downtown Hamilton tomorrow, don't worry.  It's just members of the Royal Hamilton Light Infantry practising. About 25 members of the rhli will be engaged in fibua training.  Fibua stands for fighting in build-up areas, a technique was used by rhli soldiers in peackeeping missions in Bosnia and Cyprus. Passersby will likely see and hear some activity around the James Street Armories around the noon hour ..it will last untl about 4. But rest assured only blank ammunition will be used.





