<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, September 26, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>








<ul>
    <li>Triple Killing Follow
    <li>Cops Re: Campbell    
    <li>School Closures     
    <li>Mac - Strike H.Q.     
    <li>Greyhound-hamilton  
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Bird Found          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Triple Killing Follow</b><p>
A shattered community is trying to come to grips with its worst nightmare tonight. <br>   Stoney Creek residents are still in disbelief following the slaying yesterday of a young mother and her two children.
<br>  The woman's boyfriend faces three first degree murder charges.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports tonight that the separate school board was quick to respond to the fears and questions of the victims' classmates.
<i><br>  It will be some time before this quiet Stoney Creek townhouse development returns to normal.<br>  The continued presence of police investigators is a reminder of the horrors of Wednesday... the violent deaths of a young mother and her two young children.<br>  Fran Piccolo, son Jason and daughter Alisha, whose lives were cut short by repeated stab wounds, underwent autopsies this morning.<br>  The man accused of murder, Fran's boyfriend, made a brief court appearance.<br> He'll return to court Monday morning. <br>  A few blocks away at Our Lady of Peace Catholic School, the process of healing begins. A crisis team counsels teary eyed children.    <br>    School board psychologist Dr. Clinton Davis says there are no easy answers.    <br>     Jason Piccolo was in grade 5, his sister Alisha in grade three.   <br>       A school memorial service is planned following the young victims' funerals.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cops Re: Campbell</b><p>
The long awaited review on the Campbell report into the Paul Bernardo investigation was released this afternoon by the Niagara Regional Police Services Board.<br>  The 29 page report has 16 recommendations that the force should implement in an effort to prevent another Bernardo from stalking and killing innocent victims.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more this report.
<i><br>  Among the key recommendations that all officers on the Niagara Regional Police Force be familiar and aware of the importance of the Viclas computer.<br>  The Viclas system tracks all relevent information involved in sexual assaults and homicides.<br>  A system that justice Campbell advised be used across the country.<br>  A system that the Niagara force is using now but was not widely used when Paul Bernardo was hunting, assaulting and killing young women in southern Ontario. <br>  The Niagara force was criticized by justice Campbell for it's handling of the Bernardo stalking complaints.<br>  In 1991 a young women complained twice to police about Bernardo following her.<br>  His license plate was given to police.<br>  Bernardo was never questioned in that incident.<br>  An incident that at the time may seem trivial to an officer.<br>  But an incident justice Campbell believe should have been taken more seriously. <br>  The chief is promsing a change in attitude. But it's also reinforcing that with a dispatch system that won't allow stalking complaints to be easily dismissed.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>School Closures</b><p>
In it's history the Halton Board of Education has closed 28 schools.<br>  With budget cutbacks hitting even harder in 1996, a consultant's report is calling for the closure of more schools by next September.<br>  As Jamie West reports...the moves will save the board millions of dollars.
<i>It's not only students who are sharpening their pencils but the bean counters at educational consulting services inc.<br>  Their report focusses on accomodation of students...part of the board's ongoing renewal and restructuring plan.<br>  Somewhere between 8 and 12 in total... both secondary including Aldershot High and Elementary, likely Fairfield School built in 1913.<br>  The board will host a series of public input meetings all start at 7:30 in the evening...  they are September 30th at Georgetown District High School.<br>  October 2 at Aldershot High.<br>  October 3 at Lord Elgin.<br>  October 7 at Iroquois Ridge.<br>  October 9 at T.A. Blakelock.<br>  and October 16 at Milton District High School.<br>  The bottom line is that the board will try to achieve a better balance of service between north and south Halton while eliminating surplus space and saving 2 million dollars annually.<br>  Their timetable is tight,,,with final decisions expected by December 19th. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Mac - Strike H.Q.</b><p>
As Ontario doctors continue their funding feud with the province, Chedoke-McMaster in Hamilton is gearing up to become the province's command central for 24-hour emergency referrals, if doctors carry out their threat to strike November 1st. The hospital will also serve as the information source for the area on the status of medical services available. Both sides are still on talking terms with negotiations to avert a strike set to resume next Tuesday.
<hr>
<b>Greyhound - Hamilton</b><p>
It's full speed ahead for Greyhound Air which launched national passenger service out of Hamilton International Airport July 1st.<br> Today the airline announced a special reduced flylow airfare for passengers flying in and out of Mount Hope.<br> Between September 29th and December 17th, it offering round trip fare to the west for 199-dollars. That represents a 23 per cent reduction in the airline's economy prices and it's aimed at raising the awareness of the advantages of using Hamilton International Airport.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stocks fell today led by gold producers, metal issues, and banks.<br>   That breaks a string of record highs.<br>  Interest yields paid on Canadian government bonds moved lower.<br>  The chairman of the Hongkong Bank of Canada was in Hamilton today to open the bank's newly renovated downtown branch.<br>  
<hr>
<b>Bird Found</b><p>
 And finally this afternoon, a happy conclusion to the woeful tale of Charlie the cockatoo who had been missing from his home at pet city in Hamilton's east end. <br>  He was located by one of our viewers whose children spotted the unusual bird in their back yard. aside from a little squawking, Charlie is reported to be just fine, in spite of his day in the wilds of Hamilton.





<P>
