<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, September 25, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Stoney Creek Homicide?
    <li>Niagara Shooting    
    <li>School Discipline?  
    <li>Welfare Fraud       
    <li>Phony 100's         
    <li>United Way - Workfare 
    <li>Business First        
    <li>King St. Crash      
    <li>10-Pound Mushroom   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Stoney Creek Homicide?</b><p>
Tragedy in Stoney Creek tonight. A triple homicide. Three people: a woman and two children are dead and a man is in custody.  It happened at a townhouse complex in Stoney Creek.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Shooting</b><p>
And in Hamilton General Hospital this hour, a fourteen year old St. Catharines girl lies this hour hooked up to life support systems.<br> The teenager was shot in the head last night in her home by a 17 year old young offender.<br> The accused has been charged with attempted murder and appeared this morning in a St. Catharines court.<br> Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i>The 911 call came in eighteen minutes after eight last night.<br>  When emergency crews arrived at 18 Sherbourne Street in the north end they found Jasmine Vanscoy unconscious with a gunshot wound to the forehead.<br>  A 17 year old young offender was taken into custody and charged with the shooting.<br>  Police scoured the backyard for an hour before they came upon what they believe to be the weapon.<br>  A 45 calibre handgun stolen from a gunstore in Durham region in 1990. <br>  Jasmine Vanscoy was a grade nine student at Holy Cross Highschool.<br>  Friends who know her say they are shocked that she would be the victim of a shooting.<br>  There have been reports that this shooting was gang related.<br>  But police are downplaying that rumor.  And people who knew both Jasmine and the accused say they dont' believe that's true.<br>  The accused will appear in St. Catharines court next Tuesday for a bail hearing. </i>
<hr>
<b>School Discipline?</b><p>
Parents say they want more discipline in the schools.<br> Teachers, on the other hand, are faced with tighter restrictions than ever before ... and students, in general, seem to be more defiant and unruly, every year.<br> What happens?  Well, staff and students in a central Hamilton school are finding out, first hand... as Scot Urquhart reports:
<i> This central Hamilton parent says, the difference in his child, is like night, and day: <br>  The problem, he says, is one particular teacher; at Robert Land School. A teacher he claims treated his son in such a fashion, that he filed a complaint with the Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police: <br>  But the story doesn't end there. This week, a second parent also filed charges with the police, saying the same teacher physically disciplined her child: <br>  That, she says, is unacceptable: <br>  She suggests the teacher should have taken some privileges, like recess, away ... or possibly have called her at home. Instead, when she complained, she says, she was offered a meeting, and a chance to transfer her child out of the school: <br>  At the Board of Education; no confirmation that any incident even happened. The board is standing behind the right to privacy act. But what can the board do, in these situations? <br>  And what would satisfy this parent? </i>
<hr>
<b>Welfare Fraud</b><p>
Three more cases of welfare fraud have been cracked in Hamilton Wentworth.<br> In all three cases, Hamilton men were charged with collecting welfare while they were working.<br> The amount collected illegally in these individual cases ranges from just over 12-thousand to more than 16-thousand dollars.<br> 32 year old Jerardo Dezayas-Camacho, 37 year old Mohammad Kiana and a male teen who can't be identified under the young offender's act are all charged with fraud over 5-thousand dollars.
<hr>
<b>Phony 100's</b><p>
The Better Business Bureau and regional police have issued a warning about counterfeit 100-dollar bills passed in Hamilton recently.  The quality is good but the optical security device, that's the gold seal on the upper left corner, is poor. Anyone with information on a suspected phoney bill should call police.
<hr>
<b>United Way - Workfare</b><p>
With two million dollars at stake, practicality overcame policy today at a meeting of the board of directors of the Burlington- Hamilton- Wentworth United Way.<br>  The board averted the threat of a labour boycott by voting to amend its donor policy.<br>  Now anyone who objects to the provincial workfare program can ensure their money won't be spent on United Way agencies who take part in workfare pilot projects.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> The United Way funds seventeen- hundred agencies in Ontario.  To date, few of them have expressed any interest in workfare.  But that hasn't stopped organized labour from threatening to boycott the United Way, a move that could have cost the Burlington- Hamilton- Wentworth campaign two-million dollars in lost donations. So the United Way's board of directors voted to give contributors the option of writing "no workfare" on their donor ballots.  The board insists its a practical move, not a political one.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Following yesterday's decision by the American Central Bank to leave U.S. interest rates unchanged, Canadian banks reacted today by cutting mortgage rates.<br>  Canadian stock prices roared to another record high .<br>  Brantford auto parts maker TRW announced it will close the Brantford plant, affecting 183 jobs.<br> 
<hr>
<b>King St. Crash</b><p>
In downtown Hamilton this morning, it was a case of backed up traffic creating more of a back-up.<br> Three vehicles were damaged, but no one was hurt, during a three vehicle pile-up.<br> The car at the end of the chain reaction actually ended up partially underneath the pickup truck ahead.<br> Officers tell us the first vehicle in the pileup had stopped at a green light because traffic was so heavy, and the other two didn't stop in time.
<hr>
<b>10-Pound Mushroom</b><p>
Finally, quite the find during a walk in the woods in Binbrook for Teresa Lach and Ursula (mare-oh-no-veech). They brought home a ten pound mushroom.<br> It turns out the fungus, which was the size of three soccer balls before it was sliced up for cooking, is an edible puffball.<br> The women checked with the Royal Botanical Gardens, to ensure that it was safe to eat.<br> But Chris Graham, the RBG's chief horticulturist warns people to use extreme caution in eating any wild mushroom they find, to avoid poisoning.<br> Puffball mushrooms are common in this area in damp, cool conditions.





