<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, September 24, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Ivor Wynne Zoning   
    <li>Bike lane           
    <li>Prentice dead       
    <li>GM - Axle Plant       
    <li>Inside Workers Vote 
    <li>New WIC Boss        
    <li>Bingo Stick-up      
    <li>Tassi Bravery 
    <li>Autism Cycle        
    <li>Cockatoo            
</ul>


<hr>
<b>Ivor Wynne Zoning</b><p>
Bureaucratic bungling could cost the Hamilton Grey Cup more than a million dollars, and leave some ticket-holders with no seats to sit in. <br> At stake are eleven-thousand temporary seats to be added to Ivor Wynne Stadium.<br>  At war are the City of Hamilton's building department and its culture and recreation department, which operates Ivor Wynne Stadium.<br>  Building inspectors say culture and recreation staff should draw an illegal procedure penalty, for erecting the temporary seats without the necessary building permit.<br>  Deborah Walker reports.
<i> With exactly two months to go to the Grey Cup kickoff, top bureaucrats huddle at Hamilton City Hall.  They're trying to figure out who fumbled the ball, by failing to obtain the zoning change necessary to erect eleven-thousand temporary seats at Ivor Wynne Stadium.  <BR>With no zoning change, there's no building permit.  So inspectors had no choice but to shut down work on the installation of the temporary seats.  <BR>That's because Grey Cup profits will be split between the CFL, the City of Hamilton, and Hamilton- Wentworth region, to pay back municipal money used to lure the Grey Cup to Hamilton.  </i>

<b>Bike Lane</b><p>
Another controversy brewing again at regional council over those infamous bicycle lanes in the city's west end. Two years after scrapping them, council may be revisiting or perhaps re-peddling the idea.<br> Council will vote October first on a transportation committee proposal to mark the lanes between Macklin and Dundurn Streets on Main and King Streets at a cost of 10 thousand dollars. The region put the brakes on the old bike lanes when chaos erupted with rush hour traffic.
<hr>
<b>Prentice Dead</b><p>
The Dundas man who was known as Mr. Public Works has died. John Prentice who served on Dundas council for 36 years and a number of years on regional council, collapsed at a committee meeting last night, of an apparent aneurism and died in hospital this morning. He was Dundas citizen of the year in 1986, past president of the Dundas Lions Club and was chair for many years of the Lions Homes, an alternative housing project for seniors. John Prentice is survived by his wife Dorothy, and four children and served with the Royal Canadian Navy during world war two.  He's resting at the J.B. Marlatt Funeral Home in Dundas.
<hr>
<b>GM - Axle Plant</b><p>
Negotiations between General Motors and the Canadian Auto Workers Union are underway.<br> The union has set next Wednesday at midnight as their strike deadline.<br> Even though both sides are talking, the union members we talked to in St. Catharines are preparing for the picket line.<br>  Lauran Sabourin reports.
<i>Fifty two hundred General Motors workers in St. Catharines have strike in the back of their minds.<br>  The last time GM Canada workers walked the picket line was in 1984.<br>  1996 could be another strike year. <br>  The union says hundreds of jobs have been lost in St. Catharines.<br>  Outsourcing is the main issue in the negotiations with GM.<br>  Three years ago the GM Axle Plant was sold to American Axle.<br>  The CAW negotiated a deal with the company to keep the 750 GM workers in the plant but production in St. Catharines is going to be phased out in 1998.<br>  Seven hundred fifty axle plant workers could be out on the street.<br>  Joining the 700 GM St. Kitts employees who lost their jobs when the foundry closed.<br>  Little by little the union says GM work is being contracted out to smaller and lesser paying manufacturers.<br>  The union fears the engine lines may be next. </i>
<hr>
<b>Inside Workers Vote</b><p>
  Our cameras were not allowed to show you but administrative and clerical workers were voting today on a tentative contract offer from the City of Hamilton.<br> 460 members of local 167 of the Canadian Union of Public Employees are eligible to vote.<br> Results are expected later this evening.<br> A week ago, Hamilton- Wentworth Region's inside workers, who are members of the same union local, voted overwhelmingly in favour of a new contract.
<hr>
<b>New WIC Boss</b><p>
As of November 1st, we have a new boss. John s. Lacey as been named the new president and CEO of WIC. WIC Western International Communications Ltd. is actually the parent company of CHCH-TV, along with numerous other broadcasting companies across Canada. <BR>Mr. Lacey, most recently an executive with Scott Hospitality Incorporated, brings with him many years of management experience in food services, transportation, hotels and the retail industry. This announcement concludes an extensive search that began in July when Douglas Holtby retired.
<hr>
<b>Bingo Stick-up</b><p>
Hamilton Wentworth Police are looking for a bingo hall bandit tonight.<br> A masked man walked into Centennial Bingo on Queenston Road around 10:30 last night, pointed a handgun at a cashier and demanded money.<br> The suspect is described as a white male, approximately five feet, ten inches tall.
<hr>
<b>Tassi Bravery </b><p>
A 67-year-old Hamilton man has been awarded the Governor- General's Medal of Bravery. First edition brought you the story of Philip Tassi in May of 1995.  He had confronted an armed masked bandit at a convenience store at Barton and Gage in Hamilton while paying for his gas fill-up. The man pointed a gun at his head and demanded his wallet.  Mr. Tassi grabbed the man's hand and after a struggle pinned him down until help arrived.  Two shots were fired narrowly missing our modest hero.     As a result of Mr. Tassi's actions, 42-year-old Peter Smyth was charged with three counts of robbery and firearms offences.  Mr. Tassi, the only ontario resident among nine Canadians to be awarded the Governor- General's Medal for Bravery, will be invited to a special reception in Ottawa on a date to be announced later.
<hr>
<b>Autism Cycle</b><p>
A team of wet and weary cyclists pedaled their way into Hamilton, this afternoon ... en route to Ottawa. The week long trip dubbed Cycle for Autism; is designed to raise public awareness about autism, and raise funds for research into the disorder. While in Hamilton, the group was joined by McMaster researcher Dr. Peter Zot- mah- ree ... who is internationally recognized for his work involving the neurologically based disorder. The ride organizer is Claudio Del Duca; a Windsor man who is the father of two autistic children.  October, is autism awareness month.
<hr>
<b>Cockatoo</b><p>
Finally tonight, workers at "Pet City" on Centennial Parkway in Hamilton's east end are on the lookout for a 13-week old cockatoo.  The large, white bird flew out the stores' front door this morning and hasn't been seen since.<br> The bird is still being hand fed and its owners are concerned that it might starve if not recovered. It's also the first time the cockatoo has been outdoors.<br> Despite being only 13-weeks old, the bird stands 26-inches from head to foot.




<P>
