<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, September 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>







<ul>
    <li>Palladini - Red Hill
    <li>Milton Fatal        
    <li>Ft. Erie Fatal      
    <li>Students Fatal      
    <li>Stoney Creek Crash  
    <li>Simcoe Body         
    <li>Scotia Robbery      
    <li>Fire Extinguishers  
    <li>Robert Pope Art     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>palladini - red hill</b><p>
Make that one highway down... one expressway still to go for Hamilton- Wentworth region. <br>  Today, the province of Ontario loosened its purse strings just enough to allow completion of the stretch of highway 403 linking Brantford and Ancaster.<br>  However construction of the north-south leg of Hamilton's Red Hill Creek Expressway remains stalled.
And as Deborah Walker reports tonight, the question of who's going to pay for it won't be resolved until December at the earliest.
<i> They came from Ancaster, Brantford and Brant County to cheer Ontario transportation minister Al Palladini, who delivered the sixteen-and-a- half million dollar contract that will finish highway 403. The project will get unwanted traffic off highways two and fifty-three, and pave the way for economic development.  <BR>The province and Hamilton- Wentworth have agreed to disagree over the cost of completing the Red Hill Creek Expressway, with the province accusing the region of inflating the bottom line.  On Monday, a regional committee voted to pay half the four-hundred- thousand dollar cost of hiring independent consultants to settle the dispute.  <BR>And if the region's estimates are right, will the province chip in more than the 100-million dollars already committed to the project?  We'll find out in December, when the consultants deliver their report.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Milton Fatal</b><p>
This first full day of autumn has been a tragic one on golden horseshoe roads.<br> An Acton man died just before 8 o'clock this morning when a pickup truck travelling along Steeles collided with a minivan driving through the intersection at Tremaine Road.<br> The van rolled over into a ditch, killing 49 year old Gerald Dick. Halton police closed a section of Steeles Avenue from Tremaine Road to Peru Road in Milton while they conducted their investigation and are now seeking witnesses.<br> The driver of the pickup was shaken but received only minor injuries.
<hr>
<b>Ft. Erie Fatal</b><p>
A Fort Erie man lost his life today when a car crashed into a tree on Lewis Avenue in Fort Erie.<br> Police say the driver lost control of the car, left the road, and smashed into a large tree. Police say 31-year-old Jeff Goy of Fort Erie died after he was rushed to a hospital in Buffalo after the accident.<br> Goy was a passenger.<br> Two other men from the Fort Erie area were hurt in the accident and are in stable condition in hospital.
<hr>
<b>Students Fatal</b><p>
Funeral services were held this morning for a Burlington teenager struck by a car last week while riding his bicycle.<br> Dean Palmer was hit on Wednesday, and died two days later.<br> Annette Hamm met with some friends of Palmer's this morning before the service.
<i>A makeshift memorial marks the spot on Burlington's Walker's Line where Dean Palmer was hit Wednesday night.<br>  He was crossing the street on his bicycle, not wearing a helmet.<br>  Palmer died of his injuries early Friday.<br>  Before his funeral this morning, friends of his from Nelson High School placed more flowers and tributes near the utility pole.  <br>  The memorial tells the story of a popular sixteen year old who played junior football at Nelson High.  <br>  Police have ruled Wednesday night's collision as accidental.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Stoney Creek Crash</b><p>
A man has been charged after a serious accident on the weekend that sent two women to Hamilton General Hospital. They're in critical condition.<br> The crash happened early Saturday morning on highway 20 on Stoney Creek mountain. Police say their car burst into flames after being hit from behind by a pick-up truck.<br> They've charged 33 year old Paul Katool with three counts of impaired driving causing bodily harm.
<hr>
<b>Simcoe Body</b><p>
OPP in Simcoe are investigating the discovery of human remains at a farm near Simcoe.  An apple picker discovered the remains while working in an orchard.   The body has been taken to the chief coroners lab in Toronto for a post mortem examination to determine the identity and cause of death.<br>  Foul play is not suspected.
<hr>
<b>Scotia Robbery</b><p>
Hamilton Regional Police are investigating yet another bank robbery.<br> Shortly after ten this morning a lone male walked into the bank of Nova Scotia on Mohawk Road East demanding money.<br> He escaped on foot with an undisclosed amount of cash.<br> Police say he was white, with dark brown hair and a goatee.  He had an earing in one ear and was wearing a black scarf over his face and sunglasses.
<hr>
<b>Fire Extinguishers</b><p>
The Better Business Bureau is warning Hamilton area businesses about a phony fire extinguisher inspector.<br>  Apparently the man wearing an uniform and badge asks to inspect fire extinguishers then returns five minutes later with a bill for twenty-five dollars.<br>  So far, eight businesses have fallen victim and Better Business Bureau and fire officials warn that written notices are required if fire extinguishers are faulty.
<hr>
<b>Robert Pope Art</b><p>
It's an unusual art exhibit in an unlikely setting and sadly, the artists is no longer here to read the reviews.  You see he died after a battle with cancer. But he recounted his journey with a paint brush in hopes of offering support to others. Matt Hayes has the story of Robert Pope.
<i>When Robert Pope died in 1992 after a ten year battle with cancer he left behind a rich legacy. The 35 year old painter depicted the struggles of a cancer victim on canvas. His 32 piece exhibit is called &quot;illness and healing&quot; and is currently on display at Hamilton's Henderson Hospital. It is an emotional experience.<br>  Its hard not to be affected by what these pictures say and they speak volumes. Touring the exhibit with William Pope, the artists father, is like flipping through a proud father's scrap book of his sons life. One picture shows William driving his son home after a session of difficult therapy. He says he was privliged to be there for him then and the privledge continues.<br>  William Pope takes pride in a body of work that gives us all a greater understanding of the dark and difficult road the cancer patient takes.<br>  Illness and Healing, The Art of Robert Pope is on dispay in the hospital auditorium at Henderson Hospital daily from 10 am until 8:30pm Friday. Admission is free to this exhbit that deserves to be seen. </i>




<P>
