<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, September 20, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>






<ul>
    <li>Ancaster Fair
    <li>Grape and Wine Festival
    <li>Chretien - Hamilton 
    <li>Oakville Parade     
    <li>High School Reform  
    <li>Niagara - CUPE
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Take Back The Night 
    <li>Cyclist Dies        
    <li>Gorge Body          
    <li>Pot Fire Charges    
    <li>Car PSA             
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Fair</b><p>
It's the last weekend of the summer of 96 and the roads are going to be busy. <br> There are fairs and celebrations gearing up throughout the golden horseshoe tonight and it looks like this beautiful weather is going to co-operate at least for a while. <BR>
Motorists are advised the 403 highway on the way to Ancaster between Mohawk Road and Main Street will be closed in both directions tomorrow morning between 10 and 10:15 while work crews do some blasting work in a rocky area of the escarpment known as the cascades.
<i>Now this is my idea of a day at school. Judging by the crowd everyone else had the same idea. 140 school buses carried kids out of the classroom for a day of farming and fun. Its the 146th year of the Ancaster Fair. The day can be an eye opener for kids of all ages. <br>    As for me I have other ideas.<br>  The word has traveled through the animal kingdom. The goats are very afraid. I'm back for my annual milking seminar.<br>  <br> We'll give the animals a rest and head to the midway for a little fishing and other games of chance along with food dizzying rides and death defying stunts.<br>  And there's still plenty more. Want to see for yourself? The Ancaster Fair continues through Sunday on Highway 53 at Southcoat Road.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Grape and Wine Festival</b><p>
Today marks the start of the 45th Annual Niagara Grape and Wine Festival.<br>  We take you to Lauran Sabourin in St. Catharines with more. 
<i>The Festival began with sausage and pancakes on the grill at the kickoff breakfast this morning in market square.  And over the next ten days there's so much more.<br>  But the reason this festival started was to celebrate the grape harvest and to showscase Niagara wines.<br>  Wine tastings, winery tours.<br>  Twenty one niagara wineries are involved in promoting this event.  The most number of wineries ever.<br>  Niagara grapes are at such a premium these days growers can't meet the demand.<br>  Not bad when predictions were just a few years ago that free trade would destroy the grape growing industry.<br>  The product is receiving world wide recognition and international awards.<br>  With fine wine goes fine food and this year many of the wineries are featuring gourmet dinners.<br>  trying to make the festival a more upscale attraction. <br>  But there are still some events that are tradition they will never change.<br>  This afternoon Howard staff was crowned the 1996 grape king.</i>
<hr>
<b>Chretien - Hamilton</b><p>
Enroute to the plowing match, the prime minister's plane landed at Hamilton International Airport.<br> The Canadair jet landed right on time and was greeted by a bevy of security officers.  The cavalcade was planned to quickly wisk the p.m. to the match.<br> But, office staff of the UPS terminal at the airport got an unexpected surprise when the cavalcade stopped abruptly and the prime minister got out.<br> Security officers quickly joined chretien as he went over to greet the flabbergasted workers.  He wouldn't stop however to talk to a CHCH-TV reporter but headed off to the plowing match.
<hr>
<b>Oakville Parade</b><p>
And some high profile visitors to Oakville this weekend as the city rolls out the red carpet to welcome home Donovan Bailey and its other Olympic heroes. A parade tomorrow morning at at 11:20 at Trafalgar Road and the QEW, proceeds south to Lakeshore Road, then west to Coronation Park for a noon civic reception.
<hr>
<b>High School Reform</b><p>
Yesterday it was getting rid of school boards, today it's changing the province's high schools.<br> Education minister John Snobelen says the current system is irrelevant.  He's proposing a massive jobs-oriented overhaul of Ontario's high school system.<br> Included are plans to let students decide if they'll pursue post secondary education before entering high school and establishing partnerships between schools and business.
<hr>
<b>Niagara - CUPE</b><p>
The union representing 650 striking Niagara region workers held a news conference today to explain why they rejected management's latest contract offer.<br> CUPE local 1287 also released the results of a survey that they say shows the striking employees do have support from taxpayers.<br> The union says even though the latest offer from management included provisions for job security it demanded other concessions.<br> And the union won't agree to concessions.<br> This morning union representatives rhymed off a litany of ways the region could save millions of dollars without asking its employees for concessions.           Niagara region says it needs to cut 8.7 million from its budget.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
For the fifth day in a row the value of Canadian stock prices in Toronto climbed to new all-time highs.<br>   The Canadian dollar also rose, closing above 73 cents US.<br>  Retail sales in Canada continue to improve. 
<hr>
<b>Take Back The Night</b><p>
A crowd of about 300 women and children walked through downtown Hamilton Thursday evening to "Take Back the Night."<br> This is the 15th year that women have reclaimed the streets in Hamilton.<br> The first Take Back the Night march was held in 1978 in San Francisco.<br> Since then the event has grown ...and now women around the world march in unison.
<hr>
<b>Cyclist Dies</b><p>
<br> Halton police are looking for witness to an accident that has claimed the life of a 16-year-old Burlington boy.<br> Dean Palmer of Elwood Road was hit by a car while riding his bicyle  Wednesday evening.  It happened on Walkers Line. The boy died from his injuries today at Hamilton General Hospital.
<hr>
<b>Gorge Body</b><p>
Police say the death of a woman in a fall in the Niagara Gorge was an accident.<br> 29 year-old Elaine McDermott of Niagara Falls died Monday when she fell 30 metres into the gorge near the falls.<br> A witness claimed the women lost her balance and fell after jumping on to a safety wall.<br> Police have ruled out foul play.
<hr>
<b>Pot Fire Charges</b><p>
A Hamilton man has been charged after a marijuana growing operation went up in smoke Wednesday morning.<br> Firefighters stumbled upon the hydroponic setup while trying to put out flames at this downtown duplex.<br> 42 marijuana plants, a vial of marijuana oil and a bag containing traces of cocaine were found inside one apartment.<br> 37 year old Ken Churm faces a several narcotics charges as a result.
<hr>
<b>Car PSA</b><p>
Last March, we told you about a group of federally funded students trying to drive home the message that car theft isn't a game.<br> The group of 15 teenagers focussed on the Hamilton mountain area, targetting other teens through a mentoring program.<br> It seems their efforts are paying off.<br> Police say car theft in the target area is down 10 per cent over last year.<br> The group's funding has now run out, but they're work is not completely finished.<br> They've put together a public service announcement which will be airing here on CHCH TV, trying to prevent kids from joyriding in stolen vehicles.




<P>
