<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, September 19, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>





<ul>
    <li>School Cuts    
    <li>Mac Career Day      
    <li>Niagara Vote        
    <li>AIC Booming         
    <li>Offender Watch      
    <li>Henkel Chemical     
    <li>Bailey Day          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>School Cuts</b><p>
Some startling words from eucation minister John Snobelen meeting with the Tory caucus in Vineland today. He says he's considering eliminating school boards.  <br>  He says people across the province have been telling him they'd feel more comfortable dealing with municipal councils than boards of education. And he's considering handing control over schools to municipally- appointed panels. The minister says it could help reduce school administration costs and give local politicians more control over educating children. Mr. Snobelen says he's waiting for recommendations this fall on changes to the education system from the so-called who does what committee.
<hr>
<b>Mac Career Day</b><p>
At the university level, aside from funding, a big problem is getting a job afterward. Today thousands of students at McMaster University tried to get a head start on their futures.<br>  47 companies set up displays to network with potential employees during the university's annual career day.<br>  Company reps talked with students about job opportunities, and how to prepare for the changing job market of the 21st century.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Vote</b><p>
In Niagara municipal workers have decided to stay off their jobs.  They'll be holding a news conference tomorrow morning to discuss the results of yesterdays vote to reject what the region calls its final offer. Region chairman Brian Merrett says he's disappointed and the region is not in a position to offer the union what it wants.<br> CUPE says it's willing to accept a wage freeze but is refusing to make any concessions.<br> The strike by 680 workers -- including social workers and garbage and maintenance crews -- began September 3rd.
<hr>
<b>AIC Booming</b><p>
 Concerns over job security and planning for the future has allowed one small Hamilton company to triple its business in the last year. Canadians have been pouring billions of dollars into mutual funds, and the AIC Group of funds, a money management firm has been a major benefactor.<br>  The other reason for its powerful growth is the performance of its investments.
<hr>
<b>Offender Watch</b><p>
Which part of the problem is the cause... and which part is the affect? Hamilton's Beasley Park has one of the highest reported crime rates in the city. It also has the largest concentration of social services in the province. is there a link between the two? That question will be the focus of a special neighbourhood meeting tonight; that will bring together residents, city staff, and social service agencies. Scot Urquhart has more:
<i> Hamilton's Beasley Park neighbourhood is said to have one of the highest concentrations of social service facilities, in the province. Half way houses, detox centers, shelters, counselling, and drop in centres. All within blocks of each other. It's believed that notorious pedophile Keith Legere; released in this area ... is still around. But if he is; no one has seen him, and he is certainly staying out of trouble. But that does not make area residents feel, any more secure: <br>  Rick took us on a walking tour of the area. past some of the facilites established within a four block radius of the park: <br>  Paul Johnson runs the Wesley Centre, one of the biggest targets of complaint, in the neighbourhood: <br>  And Linda Williams agrees. She lives in the building beside the Wesley Centre: <br>  And Rick says, it's not so much the daytime indigents at the centre ... as the gangs of youths at night time: <br>  How much is enough for one neighbourhood? And what responsiblities should agencies take; when they become residents of any neighbourhood? Those are just some of the questions that surround beasley park. The answers have yet to be found. </i>
<hr>
<b>Henkel Chemical</b><p>
In west Hamilton it's a bad smell that's become a major offender, at the site of an old chemical company.<br> Neighbours complained of nausea last night because of a smell eminating from the Henkel Chemical Company site.<br>  Henkel tore down the old Diamond Shamrock Company it purchased back in the late 80's, and is now trying to decommission the site for resale in a couple of years.<br>  The smell comes from a food preservative, BHT, which is decomposing in the soil and reacting with other chemicals.<br>  Henkel is issuing updates to residents living near the site, letting them know the smell may continue for the next couple of weeks, but there it doesn't pose a health risk.
<hr>
<b>Bailey Day</b><p>
A weekend of celebration is planned for Oakville as the town prepares to welcome its most famous citizen.<br>  Olympian Donovan Bailey returned home last night.<br>  And as Dwight Ryan reports, the town is all set to celebrate.  
<i><br>  At Donovan Bailey's Oakville watering hole, they're getting ready for a party. <br>  Another round of speeding bullets are served in honour of their most famous customer. <br>  The excitement began to build when the world's fastest man returned home Wednesday for the first time since winning double gold at the Olympics.  <br>    A whole weekend of events is planned to honour not only Donovan but three other Oakville Olympians.  <br>  Extra GO trains will be provided and free Oakville Transit will make it easier for the expected crowd.<br>  </i>




<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

