<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, September 18, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>





<ul>
    <li>Bailey Oakville
    <li>Hamilton Fire       
    <li>Roof Collapse       
    <li>Gorge ID/Oakville   
    <li>Marijuana Garden    
    <li>Welfare Fraud       
    <li>Young Driver        
    <li>Laidlaw Waste       
    <li>HW - Expressway       
    <li>Beamsville Jobs     
    <li>Thorold Jail        
    <li>Business First        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Bailey Oakville</b><p>
The city of Oakville is preparing to welcome Canada's newest hero tonight.  Sprinter Donovan Bailey, double gold medal Olympian arrives at Pearson International Airport in about two hours from now.
<BR> Oakville decided to postpone its Olympic athlete welcome until this weekend to accommodate Bailey's schedule. The red carpet treatment will include a motorcade through the downtown. 
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Fire</b><p>
A Hamilton woman is grateful to her heroes today. She was asleep when fire broke out in her downtown apartment. But firefighers were in for a surprise; as Dwight Ryan reports, the 40-thousand dollar blaze resulted in a collection of marijuana plants going up in smoke.   
<i><br> It was just after 9:30 in the morning that firefighters were called to this 2 and a half story home on Arthur Street South.<br> The second story apartment was fully involved.<br> Kristopher Urech called 911.  <br>  Darlene Barlow was asleep in the lower apartment when the fire broke out.    <br>      It didn't take firefighters long to realize that the blazing apartment was home to a marijuana growing operation.   <br>         Hamilton Regional Police and the Fire Marshal's office will be investigating.</i>
<hr>
<b>Roof Collapse</b><p>
A roof collapse on a construction site in Port Colborne this morning sent a man to hospital with undetermined injuries.<br>  Police say the 28 year old victim was working on the top of the building when the roof gave way.<br>  The man fell 15 feet to the ground.<br>  He was transported to Port Colborne General Hospital.<br>  A church is being constructed on the site at Westside and Barrick Roads.<br>  The Ministry of Labour is investigating.
<hr>
<b>Gorge ID/Oakville</b><p>
The woman who fell to her death into the Niagara Gorge early Monday, has now been identified. Police services personnel visited the scene today as part of the coroners investigation. 29-year-old Elaine McDermott was apparently jumping up onto a retaining wall when she lost her balance. <br> Police in Halton have released the name of the victim of that fatal car crash in north Oakville monday night.<br> 27-year-old Ronald Davidson of Mississauga was killed when his sports car struck the rear of a parked tractor trailer unit on Bristol Circle and burst into flames.
<hr>
<b>Marijuana Garden</b><p>
It's not your average garden greenery.<br> Maybe that's why an elderly Hamilton woman didn't recognize she'd picked a marijuana plant from her own backyard as part of a bouquet for a friend.<br> But the woman's daughter knew what it was and called police.<br> Turns out the plant had grown from seeds blown across the yard from the next door neighbours.<br> 32 year old Mark Rogers of Hamilton is now facing charges of marijuana possession.
<hr>
<b>Welfare Fraud</b><p>
In what they promise will be the first of many welfare fraud crackdowns, Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police have arrested a 41 year old Hamilton man.<br> Investigators say the suspect had been working from 1991 to 1995, and collecting welfare at the same time.<br> Over the four year period, nearly 12-thousand dollars in social benefits were cashed.<br> 41 year old Brian Allayne has been charged with fraud.
<hr>
<b>Young Driver</b><p>
A 12 year old boy has been arrested after a stolen car crashed in Hamilton's east end last night.<br> Police say he tried to run from the wreck, but was stopped by a nearby resident who saw him crash.<br> The boy pulled a knife on the resident and threatened to harm him, just as police arrived.<br> The 12 year old faces a list of theft and weapons charges, as well as failing to remain at the scene of an accident.
<hr>
<b>Laidlaw Waste</b><p>
 One man's trash is another man's treasure ... and perhaps no one understands that maxim better; than James Bullock. The president of Laidlaw Waste Systems has just completed a huge deal; that turns garbage into a mountain of gold, for the Burlington company. Scot Urquhart has more:
<i><br>  What does this ... have in common, with this: <br>  Laidlaw Inc. The company best known for its garbage trucks, is getting out of the solid waste business. Selling its company to Allied Waste Systems of Scottsdale Arizona ... for one point six billion dollars. <br>  Laidlaw thought it could spend its money in more profitable areas. That's why it bought a piece of Scott's Hospitality Ltd. not for the chicken ... but for the six thousand school buses owned by Scotts: <br>  And in the U.S. ambulance companies are the target of Laidlaw takeovers: <br>  And as for these trucks: Laidlaw is getting out of low tech hauling, and into high tech handling... of waste: <br>  In all three business interests Laidlaw retains ... they are the largest operators in the field. And even by selling their solid waste business to Allied, and retaining a 20 percent share of the company ... they will be number three in North America. The Burlington based company has positioned itself for the future, and the future, looks bright. </i>
<hr>
<b>HW-Expressway</b><p>
He's hoping some private business will sift the Red Hill Creek Expressway into gear. For now it's idling in neutral.  At Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Council last night, chairman Terry Cooke offered the assurance that the road is not dead yet... private sources of financing are still being researched and then the province will be approached again for funding.
<hr>
<b>Beamsville Jobs</b><p>
A company that makes spas and bathtubs plans to set up shop in Beamsville -- creating 60 jobs. Acryx is building an 80-thousand square-foot factory.<br> When it opens in January, it will be the largest plant in the town, west of St. Catharines.
<hr>
<b>Thorold Jail</b><p>
Mayor Mal Woodhouse of Thorold wants the provincial government to turn over the local jail to the city.<br> The Niagara Detention Centre in Thorold is one of 14 jails slated to close to make way for larger "super jails."<br> Woodhouse says he's not sure what use the jail would be put to by the city.<br> But he adds the government owes it to Thorold to transfer the jail to the city once it is closed.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Canadian stocks rose for the first time this week.<br> Interest rates remain stable while the dollar weakened a bit.<br> Most investors are still trying to guess how Canadian markets will perform if U.S. interest rates rise soon.<br> 




<P>
