<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, September 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Taxes - Expressway  
    <li>Hospital Shakeout   
    <li>HW Workers          
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Rosenthal Dead      
    <li>Oakville Fatal      
    <li>Kenilworth Crash    
    <li>Flasher Caught      
    <li>E.D. Smith - 115    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Taxes - Expressway</b><p>
Stop and go. That's the freeway situation in Hamilton and we're not talking about the traffic. <br> It's whether the Red Hill Creek Expressway will ever get built and when regional council meets in about two hours from now we may be a little closer to an answer.
<br> The latest sign of delay on the road... is a looming regional tax crunch, which has some councillors wondering whether we can now afford to build the road, or not.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Hospital Shakeout</b><p>
<br> With the amalgamation of the Civic Hospitals with Chedoke McMaster, personnel changes are a certainty.<br> Although the two hospitals have yet to merge, changes are already taking place.<br> Dwight Ryan has this update.  <br>  
<i>Fewer government dollars mean health care in Hamilton will change dramatically, and soon.<br>  Amongst the changes, an amalgamation of Chedoke McMaster Hospitals and the Civic Hospitals.<br>  McMaster's CEO Dr. Jennifer Jackman decided not to seek the new top administrative job.  She left Mac and is now out of the public eye.  Citizens have been kept in the dark over how much she got in severance.<br>  David McCutcheon of the Civic Hospitals applied for the new job but only got to the short list.  Yesterday he said he was off to Dublin for a new job.<br>  Taking the new job is R. Scott Rowand of Toronto.<br>  Civic officials can't say yet how much McCutcheon will get in severance. He had three years left in his contract.    <br>      Bienenstock says he'll take a few months to reflect and decide his options about the future.  He does say he'll remain in the community.  </i>
<hr>
<b>HW Workers</b><p>
Inside workers with the Region of Hamilton Wentworth have ratified a new collective agreement.<br> Members of CUPE Local 167 voted 83.5 percent to accept a deal that has been described as status quo.<br> Local 167 is also recommending Hamilton city workers accept their contract offer.<br> They'll be presented with a similar package Wednesday.
<hr>
<b>Business - First</b><p>
For the second day in a row, the value of stocks in Toronto closed at record high levels.<br>  Canada's biggest provider of funeral services, loewen group is being offered more than four billion dollars in a takeover bid.<br>  Auto industry watchers warn that new union contracts will lead to higher costs to consumers.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Rosenthal Dead</b><p>
A former Hamilton woman, murdered in New Jersey back in 1991, has been declared legally dead.<br> This even though Dede Rosenthal's body has not been found.<br> Rosenthal lived in Hamilton until six years ago, when she moved to New Jersey.<br> State prosectors there have obtained a court order for the death certificate so they can try to get a grand jury to indict the man who's confessed to killing Rosenthal.<br> Charles Reddish is also charged with the axe murder of a former girlfriend.
<hr>
<b>Oakville Fatal</b><p>
Halton Regional Police are looking for witnesses to an overnight car crash in Oakville that claimed one life. It happened on Bristol Circle east of Highway 5 and the 403. Officers say a vehicle slammed into a parked tractor trailer, and erupted in flames. The as yet unidentified driver was pronounced dead at the scene.
<hr>
<b>Kenilworth Crash</b><p>
A 39 year old man, up from Arizona for his father's funeral in Hamilton, remains in serious condition.<br>  This after a single vehicle crash overnight on the Kenilworth Access in east Hamilton.<br>  Police say Philip Kiley has severe head injuries and two broken legs.<br>  The car he was riding in went out of control, hitting a couple of medians at the bottom of the access.<br>  21 year old Angela Harris of Hamilton has been charged with impaired driving causing bodily harm.<br>  Harris was released from hospital with relatively minor injuries after the airbag on her side of the car deployed.
<hr>
<b>Flasher Caught</b><p>
Police have nabbed a man who exposed himself to two grade eight students this week on their way to school.<br> The girls were walking through an alleyway to Prince of Wales School in east Hamilton when they saw a man with his pants pulled down around his ankles.<br> 42 year old Daniel Ryan of no fixed address is charged with committing an indecent act, and breach of probation.
<hr>
<b>E.D. Smith - 115</b><p>
Back on this day in 1881, Ernest D'israeli Smith received his first income from the fruit business.<br> Now the Winona plant that bears his name is celebrating its one hundred and fifteenth birthday.<br> The business, still run by the Smith family, opened its doors to suppliers and employees' families for a special day of tours and activities.<br> The E.D. Smith plant, which supplies fruit and tomato-based products to companies across North America, now employs 350 full and 100 part time workers.<br> The Winona processing plant is also in the process of expanding, and by early next year will have added another manufacturing line.



<P>
