<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, September 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>YOA
    <li>HW Workers          
    <li>Niagara Negotiations
    <li>Gorge Body          
    <li>Apology             
    <li>Med student oath    
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Philip Zinc         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>YOA</b><p>
<br>   Hamilton- Wentworth police are recommending major changes to the Young Offenders Act.<br> Police Services Board members are meeting at downtown quarters right now.  <br> This all comes on the same day the case of a 15-year-old charged with second degree murder is put over until January for a transfer hearing. The teen is charged in the beating death of 18-year-old Roberto Oliveira at Lime Ridge Mall last May.<br> He died after being struck over the head with a baseball bat.<br> January's hearing will determine if the youth will be tried in adult court.
<hr>
<b>HW Workers</b><p>
While changes to the Young Offenders Act could dramatically affect regional police services, so could a strike by its administrative workers. 1200 members of CUPE local 167, inside regional workers employed by the region, are voting on a new contract offer today. The union is recommended acceptance of the deal which essentially maintains the status quo although more job cuts are expected.  Local 167 is also recommending Hamilton city workers accept their contract offer. They'll be presented with a similar package Wednesday.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Negotiations</b><p>
<br> Meanwhile the union representing striking regional workers in Niagara is urging members to reject what the region has called its final offer.<br> Union negotiator Jim High says if the membership follows the union's recommendation, the regional government could reconsider its position.<br> The offer will be presented to the employees this week, but no voting date has been set.<br> The 680 regional workers have been off the job since September 3rd.
<hr>
<b>gorge body</b><p>
A woman fell 30 metres to her death in the Niagara Gorge early today.<br> She was apparently sitting on a stone retaining wall a kilometre from the falls at about 2 a.m.<br> A male companion called for help but it took firefighters about two hours to find the body.<br> The woman's name won't be released until relatives are contacted. An autopsy is planned.
<hr>
<b>Apology</b><p>
<br> On August 22nd, 1996, CHCH Television aired a report on its 5:30 and 11:00 o'clock news broadcasts regarding upaid property taxes, which drew particular attention to a property owned by Frank Levy, a local businessman.<br> Unfortunately, we went to air with the reports without having given Mr. Levy an opportunity to explain the tax arrears situation concerning his property.  Had we done so we would have learned that Mr. Levy's company, Usarco Ltd., had financial difficulties in the late 1980's, the result of which left him without control over the property for some 3-1/2 years between 1990 and 1994.<br> Mr. Levy says that it is during this period that the extensive tax arrears accumulated on the property. Now that he is back in control of the property, Mr. Levy says that he is anxious to work out a reasonable solution with city officials.<br> Our report gave the impression Mr. Levy was trying to avoid speaking with our reporter.  We understand now from Mr. Levy that he was simply out of town when our reporter tried to contact him.  We apologize if our viewers received a different impression.  We also apologize for publishing Mr. Levy's phone number on the air during our reports.  CHCH is pleased to make this apology and sincerely regrets any inconvenience and embarrassment which may have been caused to Mr. Levy.
<hr>
<b>Med Student Oath</b><p>
<br>  Medical students at Hamilton's McMaster University are about to take an oath.<br>  The oath, in part, puts patients first.<br>  Its something they feel is necessary with more and more stories making news about doctors and their fight with the government.<br>  Dwight Ryan has this report.  <br>  sot
<i> They are future doctors.  And they are concerned about their pending profession.<br>  So the 23 year-old second year med students at Hamilton's McMaster University are about to take an oath..an oath that puts patients first.<br>  Media stories about physicians and their fight with Queens Park have them wondering what happened to the patient.    <br>  The medical students feel that they must re-affirm their dedication to patients early in their learning process.   <br>    Hamilton cardiologist Lorne Finkelstein says the students will soon learn that being political is a necessity if you're a doctor.    </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
Scientists at  the Hamilton Civic Hospitals Research Centre are getting a 20 million dollar investment from mutual fund investors to help develop a heart drug.<br>  The value of stocks in Toronto and New York closed at new record highs today as investors bet that interest rates will remain low for now.<br> <A HREF="../eveningnews/evngbusiness.htm">For further details see the Evening Business Report.</A> 
<hr>
<b>Philip Zinc</b><p>
<br> Turning waste into money.<br> It's something Hamilton-based Philip Environmental has been doing for years.<br> Now they've introduced a new system to recycle dust from the steel industry into metal and other reusable materials.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  It's being described as a breakthrough technology.<br>  This site will soon house the world's first zinc iron plasma process unit.<br>  It will also bring about a hundred jobs into the Hamilton area.<br>  Electric arc furnace dust is a hazardous byproduct of the steel industry.<br>  The dust has been recycled into the cement industry, but over the past few years it's changed in composition because of different steels being used in the auto industry.<br>  That means more metals can be recovered.<br>  At the new site, one hundred per cent of E.A.F. dust will be recycled, thanks to a unit which can quickly zap it using temperatures hotter than the sun's surface.  <br>  Philip's president and ceo, Allan Fracassi, says the pig iron will go back into the steel industry, and the zinc oxide could be used in everything from batteries to suntan lotion.  </i>



<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

