<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, September 10, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Housing Starts/Sales
    <li>Niagara Strike      
    <li>Education Cuts      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Sewage Blame        
    <li>Barton Stand-Off    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Housing Starts/Sales</b><p>
<br>  Housing starts in Hamilton have tripled over a year ago.  This combined with a surge in the resale market, has homebuilders and realtors smiling once again.<br>  As Dwight Ryan reports, low interest rates aren't the only reason people are finally taking the plunge.  
<br> <i>Hammers havn't been hammering and saws havn't been sawing like this since the summer of '88. <br>  Canada's housing market is experiencing a dramatic turnaround. Figures from coast to coast show that construction is up and resale homes are selling in record time.<br>  Hamilton is no exception.  <br>    A shortage of resale starter homes means more first time buyers are turning to townhouses. Homebulders are smiling now that consumer confidence is returning.   <br>  That confidence, combined with low interest rates and reasonable home prices means happy days are hear again for realtors.    <br>Realtors and homebuilders believe the slow, steady pace of today's housing market will continue at least until the end of the year.</i>
<hr>
<b>Niagara Strike</b><p>
<br>  The strike by 650 regional Niagara workers is going into its second week and no new talks are scheduled.<br>  The striking employees look after regional public services.<br>  But does the public even notice that the workers are off the job.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more in this report.
<i>Walk into Niagara Regional Headquarters and non union staff are manning the front desk.<br>  Management personnel are running the departments while 650 employees walk the picket lines. <br>  Two weeks into labor dispute is it having a noticiable impact on service.<br>  Niagara regional workers are responsible for operating water and sewage plants, looking after roads, some day care services and handling welfare cases. <br>  The welfare office was busy.<br>  People are being promised cheques. but they have to wait.<br>  These four young men go to high school. They live in the same apartment. Two were offered service cheques today. But they say that isn't enough.<br>  Meanwhile talks between both sides in this dispute have stalled. <br>  The question now at least for those affected by the walkout is how long is going to last.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Education Cuts</b><p>
 Hamilton school children may score an extra week's vacation this March break, according to a tentative calendar issued by the Board of Education.  Chair Bob Stewart says the board hopes to negotiate some unpaid leave days to help cover a five million dollar budget shortfall, when contract talks with elementary teachers resume september 16th.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br>  Financial markets in Canada were quiet today with little change in stock prices and the dollar.<br>   Canadian double gold Olympic medalist Donovan Bailey helped a Canadian company launch a stock listing on the New York Stock Exchange.<br>  Several area companies are being awarded by the Ontario Chamber of Commerce tonight for outstanding business achievement.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Sewage Blame</b><p>
And the dispute continues between taxpayers and regional government in Hamilton- Wentworth over last winter's pump shutdown at Hamilton's Woodware Avenue Sewage Treatment Plant.<br>  One hundred and 16 residents, most of them from Stoney Creek, have filed statements of claim with Hamilton Wentworth Region for damages as a result of the flood.<br>  Those claims could end up costing the region millions of dollars.<br>  Today, members of the region's Environmental Services Committee voted to request Philip Utilities Management Corporation help pay for those damages.<br>  Philip operates the sewage treatment plant, which is owned by the region.
<br>  Hamilton Wentworth Regional Council will vote on the committee's recommendation next Tuesday night.
<hr>
<b>Barton Stand-Off</b><p>
A Hamilton man is in jail tonight after a stand-off with police.<br>  Police surrounded an east end apartment building after getting a call from a man claiming his neighbour had threated him with a gun.<br>  About two hours later, the suspect was arrested outside the apartment.<br>  After conducting a search warrant, police found a 22 calibre rifle in his apartment.<br>  44 year old Fred Baranowski is charged with threatening death, pointing a firearm and breach of probation.



<P>
