<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, September 9, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Private Red Hill    
    <li>United Way          
    <li>Gas Robbery         
    <li>Mattress Fraud      
    <li>Driver/Air Ambulance
    <li>Habitat Hamilton    
    <li>Red Green - Unicef  
    <li>Regis-Kathie Lee    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Private Red Hill</b><p>
<br> Hamilton Wentworth politicians say that if the Red Hill Expressway is built with private funds, it will be built sooner and cheaper.<br> But at least one member of the committee still feels the controversial roadway isn't needed at all.<br> Dwight Ryan has that story..
<i><br>   Traffic could flow from Hamilton's new east/west expressway down the Red Hill Valley by the year 2000, if a plan to privately fund the controversial north/south route goes ahead.<br>  In what will amount to a lease to own arrangement, the Red Hill route would be designed and built by a privte consortium ..and the region will buy it back over the next twenty odd years.   <br>   Members of the Regional Transportation Committee vow to go ahead with the roadway, even though the harris government has failed to live up to election promises.  <br>  Since then, the province has reduced the amount of money promised and offered it in stages.  But area politicians say the Queen's Park door isn't closed.  <br>    Members of the Regional Transportation Committee will meet again in two weeks to further examine the idea of private funding for the controversial roadway.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>United Way</b><p>
<br> It was a special day for the Burlington- Hamilton Wentworth United Way campaign. About two thousand students, supporters, politicians, staff and campaign workers helped officially launch the 1996 campaign in the rain at Ivor Wynn Stadium.<br> This year the Ticats are onboard as supporters. Coach Don Sutherin and chairman John Fitzpatrick performed the ceremonial kickoff, students from the Prince of Wales School were on hand, as well as the United Way campaign team. Dofasco President and CEO John Mayberry presented a check for 850 thousand dollars. ---- combining all the pledges committed to this years campaign so far we are, on its first official day at the 1,223,990 dollar mark, well on the way to the 6.6 million needed to fund the United Ways 55 agencies and the 125 services they provide.
<hr>
<b>Gas Robbery</b><p>
<br>  A Burlington Petro Canada station is out a few toonies after an early morning robbery.  It happened at Guelph Line and Mountainside Drive just after midnight, when a lone male demanded money after revealing a knife under his shirt.  The suspect, last seen running southwest is white, about 20 years old, between 5-foot six and six feet with a husky build, dark complexion and moustache with a scruffy look.  He was wearing  a black and white flannel shirt and a dark blud fishermen's hat.
<hr>
<b>Mattress Fraud</b><p>
<br>  A Burlington man is to appear in court next month charged after a five month investigation involving Mattresses Unlimited. Police say customers were scammed out of thousand of dollars in a credit card altering scheme and switched label incidents. 36-year-old Michael P. Phillips of Burlington is charged with fraud over five-thousand dollars and five counts of passing off.
<hr>
<b>Driver/Air Ambulance</b><p>
Burlington Provincial Police are asking for witnesses to a serious two vehicle accident in Flamborough over the weekend. Three people were injured, when a car and van collided at Highway 6 and the 5th Concession yesterday afternoon. Fire crews were called into rescue the trapped occupants. An 18 year old Hamilton teenager was airlifted by helicopter to hospital with serious injuries. Charges are pending.
<hr>
<b>Habitat Hamilton</b><p>
<br>   Following the progress now of Hamilton's first Habitat for Humanity.  <br>    A couple of weeks ago, we told you how crews were clearing two lots at the corner of Queen Victoria and Locander Driver on Hamilton's east mountain.<br>  Well today, the building is underway, with the digging of the basement for a 13-hundred square feet bungalow.<br>  The adjoining lot has been cleared to accomodate tents for habitat volunteers.
<br>  As part of the habitat bargain, the family has to put in 500 hours of "sweat equity".<br> But the organization also needs some sweat from volunteers.<br> If you're interested in helping out, you can come out to the site, or call 528-6404 for more information.
<hr>
<b>Red Green - Unicef</b><p>
<br>  A green grand opening in Hamilton today,  as Hamilton's own handyman Red Green, alias Steve Smith, cut the ribbon officially opening the new Unicef store on King Street West in Hamilton. This year marks the 50th anniversary of Unicef sponsored relief projects around the world. Unicef is currently working with national governments and other international agencies to combat the sexual exploitation of children.  A portion of the proceeds from the sale of Red Green's new book is being donated to Unicef.  The Red Green Book: Wit and Wisdom of Possom Lodge Plus 100 Pages of Filler!
<hr>
<b>Regis-Kathie Lee</b><p>
They're no Connie and Dan but Regis and Kathie Lee brought their network morning show to Niagara Falls today, mingling with mounties and other guests, included singers Jann Arden and Anne Murray and actors Kevin Spacey and David Cassidy.



<P>
