<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, September 6, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Hamilton - Employment 
    <li>Labour Demo          
    <li>Cancer Office       
    <li>Robbery Arrests     
    <li>Blast Averted       
    <li>Business First        
    <li>City Colours        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>hamilton-employment</b><p>
We begin tonight with some good news to wrap up the week. The unemployment rate is down dramatically in Hamilton and across the country. <br>  After reaching ten percent just a few months ago, Canada's jobless rate now stands at 9.4 percent. And Hamilton, at seven percent, just about the lowest in the country, continues to help lead the way.<br>  Dwight Ryan has that story.  
<i><br>  Job creation in Canada is bouncing back.<br>  82 thousand new jobs were created in August, mostly full time, far exceeding those lost in May and June.  Most of the new jobs were created in Ontario and Quebec.<br>  Susan Martin watches the job market from the Michael G. Degroote School of Business at McMaster University.  And she believes Canada's job outlook is bright.   <br>    The national unemployment rate now stands at 9.4 percent, down sharply from 9.8 percent in July.<br>  Topping the list is Newfoundland at nearly 18 percent.  The lowest rate is in Regina at 6.3.<br>   Hamilton's next at seven percent.<br>   Its welcome news to the region's director of economic development. Nick Catalano credits area industries for their confidence.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Labour Demo</b><p>
<br> There may be more jobs available in Ontario. But union leaders fear those jobs won't be safe, if the Tory government pushes ahead with its agenda for labour reform.<br> Dozens of injured workers, social activists, and unionized employees marched on the Hamilton office of the Ministry of Labour today.<br> They say it's time Ontario's premier and labour minister stopped turning a deaf ear on workers' fears for their safety.<br> Deborah Walker reports.
<i> These workers predict more people will be hurt and killed on the job, if Ontario's government cuts enforcement of workplace safety standards, and curtails an employee's right to refuse to work in unsafe conditions.  And union leaders say those who are hurt on the job will be further penalized by proposed reforms to the Workers' Compensation system, and the possible closure of Occupational Health clinics for Ontario workers.  <BR>What most frustrates these workers is the Tories' failure to meet with them face-to-face.  And while there would be no meeting today with the premier or the labour minister, the director of the Ministry of Labour's western region did give them a hearing.  <BR>This is the seventh time workers have staged a ministry of labour sit-in in a major ontario city. And they vow to keep on doing it, until the Harris government starts listening.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cancer Office</b><p>
<br> Last night we told you about the frightening problem at a Hamilton Bell Canada office.<br> Word today that fifty workers have been cleared out of the third floor of the building.<br> The company and federal industry hygienists are trying to find out why employees on that floor have shown an alarmingly high cancer rate and are developing an action plan.<br> Company and union officials say at least 10 of 50 workers on the third floor have been diagnosed with breast cancer, colon cancer, brain tumors or uterine cancer.<br> Bell Canada spokesman Perry Blocher says tests of air quality, radiation and other emissions have all come back within acceptable industry standards.<br>  But the union representing some Bell workers believes there's a link between the incidence of cancer and electromagnetic fields emitted by computers in the workplace.
<hr>
<b>Robbery Arrests</b><p>
Two 17-year-olds from Mississauga have been charged with robbery and one with breach of probation after a robbery at a Shell gas station in east Oakville.  The male brandished a large knife, threatening the lone female attendant, demanding cash and cigarettes. The pair ran from the scene but were arrested a at a Mississauga home a short time later
<hr>
<b>Blast Averted</b><p>
<br> That file is closed but an investigation is still underway after a Georgetown resident found a pipe bomb wrapped in a towel in his driveway.  The Halton Police explosive disposal unit neutralized the device but say it was powerful enought to kill someone and cause extensive property damage.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br>  Financial markets accepted today's strong unemployment statistics with a positive tone.<br>  Stock prices in New York and Toronto rose.<br>  Interest yields on government bonds moved lower.<br>  Analysts are forecasting good things for Canada's economy. 
<hr>
<b>City Colours</b><p>
<br> Finally tonight, how would you colour Hamilton? <br> The majority of those involved in a Cantel Colour Your City survey saw red:  red was associated with exciting, emergetic, courageous and passionate.  Most Torontonians were serene blue for intelligent, and sincere, Barrie tested sunny yellow, warm and optimistic, Ottawa peaceful green. The August survey was part of a promotion for new colour cell phones but the researchers found it interesting to note why certain colours were more popular in different cities.


<P>
