<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, September 5, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Food Bank Woes      
    <li>Bell Cancer         
    <li>Sewage Spill        
    <li>Robber Caught       
    <li>Tickets - Buses       
    <li>Air Show Fiasco
    <li>The Morning Market  
</ul>
<hr>
<b>food bank woes</b><p>
Times are tough and getting tougher.  We've heard it all before.  <br>  But in this era of layoffs, and cutbacks, and funding problems; a disturbing new trend is beginning to emerge.

<br>   Not only are we as a society becoming leaner ... but in some ways it seems, we are becoming meaner, as well. Scot Urquhart has one example of what that means in Hamilton:<BR>
<i>Ester Benjamin is on her own, with three daughters. She is a client at the Neighbour to Neighbour Food Bank. The organization announced today, that it has put its staff on layoff notice; and could close its doors at the end of September. <br>  Originally; scores of churches on the mountain ran ad hoc food banks on a volunteer basis. Why is it then, that Neighbour to Neighbour needs full time staff? <br>  And what's more; Everest believes there is no need to apologize for the evolution of the organization. <br>  None of this matters, however, to Ester Benjamin. What matters in her life, is that when she was desperate; someone was there. <br>  But one day, may never come. Without government money to pay its staff, and 850 clients a month to feed; Neighbour to Neighbour says it is surviving month to month. It is clear the province will not carry the load any longer. the question is; who will? </i>
<hr>
<b>Bell Cancer</b><p>
Bell Canada officials have launched their own investigation, into a medical mystery at Bell Canada's Hamilton office. Workers on the third floor have been suffering from an alarmingly high cancer rate.<br>  Ten percent of the workers on the floor have developed cancer and there have also been several miscarriages.<br>  About 15 percent of the 150 employees have been affected. Union spokesman Gary Lloyd says people have developed breast cancer, brain tumours and colon and uterine cancer. The union suspects the cause is emissions from computers and fax machines. A Bell study found that radiations levels are within normal limits.
<hr>
<b>Sewage Spill</b><p>
Another health scare in Niagara. Almost two-million litres of raw sewage was flushed into Lake Ontario this week after a sewage plant was sabotaged. Niagara Region spokesman Michael Boggs says a piece of the plant's front gate was one of the objects found blocking the intakes to the Port Weller plant shortly before regional employees began a strike on Tuesday. By the time the two intake screens were cleared, an estimated 1.8-million litres of sewage had entered the Welland Canal and Lake Ontario.<br>   Ministry of Environment officials have visted the plant and agree someone "wilfully" blocked the intakes.
<hr>
<b>Robber Caught</b><p>
<br>  In Hamilton, police have made an arrest in a 4-month-old robbery.<br>  On May fifth, a male thief handed a note demanding money to a teller at an east Hamilton branch of the Royal Bank, claiming he had a gun. Today, police arrested a man on an unrelated matter who had a similar note in his possession. Charged with robbery is 45-year-old Richard Ernest Stanton of no fixed address.
<hr>
<b>Tickets - Buses</b><p>
<br>  Police in Hamilton have also been catching lots of speeders lately. A crackdown between August 18th and 31st netted 794 tickets.  Police tell us the high number shows too many of us are still driving too fast; people are just too aggressive.    <BR>And police are going to get agressive with drivers who fail to observe school bus laws. They've proclaimed next week school bus enforcement week. Aside from pushing education and awareness, they'll also be pushing fines of $265 and six demerit points. Watch out of you live near Mohawk Road and Upper Wellington, Highway 6 and Upper James.
<hr>
<b>Air Show Fiasco</b><p>
 And there's some turbulence in the skies over Hamilton right now...<br>  Hamilton- Wentworth regional politicians are flabbergasted at the news the Hamilton International Air Show lost nearly 200-thousand dollars this year, a loss that may have to be covered by regional tax dollars.<br>  As Deborah Walker reports, some of those politicians wonder whether taxpayers should keep footing the bill for a perennial money-loser.
<i> Hamilton- Wentworth regional politicians are used to bailing out the air show when bad weather grounds performers, and drowns attendance.  But this year, the weather was perfect.  <BR>Pat Sullivan is on the board of directors of the Hamilton International Air Show.  He blames poor attendance this year on the seniors PGA Golf Tournament held the same weekend.  To make matters worse, construction on Highway 403 backed up traffic for five kilometres, discouraging even people holding free air show tickets.  </i>

<b>The Morning Market</b><p>
 Starting Monday there's going to be a new early morning shift here at CHCH-TV when The Morning Market debuts at 6 a.m.<br>  Our new program will offer morning viewers an all-inclusive package of Canadian news and business from around the world.  <br>  
<P>
