<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, September 4, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Redevelopment Plan  
    <li>Art Gallery Woes    
    <li>Kocis Sentenced     
    <li>King St. Attack      
    <li>Musitano Cleared    
    <li>Villa Inquest       
    <li>Morison Dies        
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Junos-Hamilton      
    <li>Hamilton Music      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>redevelopment plan</b><p>
Don't count on out-of-towners to save downtown Hamilton.  And don't count on taxpayer financed mega projects to stop the core's decay. <br> That's the advice of a report presented today to political and business leaders, who've been meeting for a year to develop a strategy to halt the decline of the heart of Hamilton.


<br> The report, entitled "Strong Medicine", prescribes thirty-three recommendations to rejuventate the downtown.<br> Deborah Walker has details.
<i> The report concludes people are the key to revitalizing downtown Hamilton ... people living here, working here, shopping here, and spending leisure time here.  The report suggests a partnership between the public and private sector, led by a newly-hired, independent downtown co-ordinator, can lure people back to the core.  <BR> Right now, much of downtown Hamilton is not a people-friendly place, littered as it is with empty storefronts and boarded-up buildings.  <BR> There are no storefronts or sidewalk cafes to entice pedestrians to browse or linger. The report considers this a prime area for redevelopment.  The report also suggests returning two-way traffic to part of King Street, improving pedestrian links between Hess Village, the King and James area, the International Village and Theatre Aquarius, judicious recycling of some older buildings, and a more lenient parking policy.  <BR>And while municipal governments can help by supporting development projects and tax appeals, the report says they should get out of the business of building mega-projects like Copps Coliseum. Because if you can't lure your own citizens downtown, you can't expect to draw tourists either.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Art Gallery Woes</b><p>
<br> A vibrant arts community could have a large role to play in the revitalization of the downtown core; but at the moment ... that community is anything but vibrant. Theatre Aquarius is down; the HPO... is out. and now the art gallery says, it, is on shaky ground. More on that from Scot Urquhart:
<BR><i>  Beauty is in the eye of the beholder, they say .... but beauty of this magnitude, is expensive. <br>  The government taketh away, and the Art Gallery of Hamilton is about to make an impassioned plea to them, to give it back. <br>  But Ted Pietrzak insists, this will be a hand up ... and not a hand out: <br>  The irony in all of this, is that the art gallery admits, it's financial position is better than either of those organizations. They have no deficit. They own the building. They have a huge endowment generating substantial interest income. Heck, they have an art collection worth 44 million dollars. Why do they need more public money, and why wouldn't they resort to the obvious; and sell some of this work: <br>  But Ted Pietrzak does. Selling gallery stock he says, is tantamount to sacrilege: and that, says Pietrzak, is why the gallery needs more than 700-thousand dollars over three years, to help them stablize their short term debt load. But no matter how you package it, it's going to be a tough sell. But will taxpayers, and regional council agree? The answer will come, over the next few weeks. </i>
<hr>
<b>Kocis Sentenced</b><p>
A Grimsby man, who shot a friend and co-worker twelves times, was sentenced today to ten years in prison, on top of the fourteen months he has already spent in custody.<br>  The body of David Heagle of St. Catharines was found June twenty-first last year at the Stoney Creek Agricultural Airstrip.<br>  Just as his first-degree murder trial was about to begin, 25-year-old Christopher Kocis of Grimsby pleaded guilty to manslaughter.<br>  Kocis admitted he was acting as a back-up for heagle at a drug deal, when he panicked and shot his friend.<br>  Heagle died two days before his twenty-fifth birthday.<br>  In a victim impact statement read in court today, family members described Heagle as a kind, loving productive young man.<br>  Instead of buying him a birthday gift, they said they were forced to buy him a funeral plot.
<hr>
<b>King St. Attack</b><p>
A 50-year-old Hamilton man is recovering in hospital tonight after a brutal assault last night.  It happened during a confrontation between two people downtown Hamilton. The man was rushed to Hamilton General Hospital after he received he was beaten severely about the head, inside an apartment at 415 King Street West. Police took a thirty year old man into custody. He is believed to be a former tenant.
<hr>
<b>Musitano Cleared</b><p>
The former owners of a Dundas hotel have been acquitted of plotting a 1992 arson attempt that threatened to turn the downtown landmark Collins Hotel into ``a ball of fire.'' Noting that ``suspicion heaped upon suspicion'' doesn't add up to guilt, Justice Walter Stayshyn found 28 year old Pat Musitano, and his 34 year old brother-in-law, John Trigiani, not guilty of conspiracy to commit arson and arson for the purpose of insurance fraud.<br> A potentially disastrous fire was averted at the hotel on March 5th, 1992, when an upstairs resident smelled gasoline and called 911.<br> Police and firefighters found timer-rigged toasters stuffed with paper leading to a trail of gasoline-soaked paper placemats through the hotel's lower level.
<hr>
<b>Villa Inquest</b><p>
An inquest into the deaths of five residents of the St. Elizabeth Villa between January  1994 and April of 1995 will begin November 12th. The inquest follows an investigation into what regional coroner Dr. Bonnie Porter had called a high mortality rate. 42 people at the Hamilton home for seniors and the disabled over a 15-month periods. The Villa says the deaths were expected but a number of former staff members insisted residents were receiving sub-standard care.
<hr>
<b>Morison Dies</b><p>
 A memorial servie has been scheduled for former Hamilton MP John Morison, who died in Ottawa yesterday at the age of 73. He was the MP for Hamilton-Wentworth and Burlington from 1963 to 1972 and is pictured here during a Liberal rally at the Palace Theatre in 1965.  A member of the RCAF. during world war two and a prisoner of war from 1944 to 1945, Mr. Morison was also a prominent Hamilton businessman who operated a successful general insurance business.  He is survived by his second wife Deidre, and five of his six children. The memorial service will be held next Monday at Melrose United Church at 2:30, with a reception at the Royal Hamilton Military Institute.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br>  Canadian stocks rose for a second day led by shares of oil and gas companies.<br>  Interest rates on Canadian government bonds are stable. <BR>The dollar is higher closing above 73 cents US<br>  Economists are suggesting Canada's economy will strengthen noticably in the second half of this year.  <br>  
<hr>
<b>Junos-hamilton</b><p>
<br> Guess what's coming back to Hamilton?  The Canadian music industry will be showcasing excellence in music making with their major event of the year.<br>  Once again the honors will be taking place in the city.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Music</b><p>
<br> So as Hamilton prepares to host the Juno stars of today, Hamilton musicians aspire to be the stars of tommorrow. With a failed music career under his belt our Matt Hayes set out to find the secret to music success. He caught up to a young man whose music is about to take him a long way from home.
<i>And as Caras president Lee Silversides announced the March 9th date of the third straight Juno awards in Hamilton, down the street at Grant Avenue Studios a young hamilton man is mapping out his music career by a rather unusual route.<br>  Vincentis entering the music scene via Italy where he hopes his self penned album of Italian songs will top the charts. After winning a couple of Italian song competions he attracted the interest of Dig-it Records in Italy. Normaly the album would be recorded there but producer Vince Tempera came to Hamilton to capture what he calls the Canadian sound. <br>  So what's suddenly made Canadian music so hot. <br>  As for Vincent he plans an english version of the album to be released domestically.<br>  So it seems only fitting that as Hamilton prepares to play host to Canada's brightest stars at the Junos a young hamilton man launches a career that will take him around the world with the hopes that one day he will stand on this stage in his hometown for his moment of glory.<br>  </i>

<P>
