<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 09/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, September 3, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Back to School      
    <li>Niagara Strike 
    <li>OPSEU - Hamilton    
    <li>Mac - Civics        
    <li>Health Sciences 
    <li>Burlington Flood    
    <li>Police Auction      
</ul>
<hr>
<b>back to school</b><p>
More than 27-thousand public elementary students went back to school in Hamilton, this morning. <br>   ... but their back to school story, is not the only one. 15-hundred teachers spent their first day back in the classroom ...
<BR>
Many of them not knowing, whether they will have a teaching job at the end of the year. Scot Urquhart has the story, of one of those teachers:
<i><br>  It is back to school for Marlo Moore ... but unlike many of the students around her, who know they have many years of school in front of them... Marlo knows, this could be her last year. <br>  Marlo is teaching Special Ed this year. In a five year career, she's taught four different specialties, and been fired three times. Not because she's a bad teacher, but because education these days, is so uncertain. <br>  </i>
<br> The Hamilton Board of Education is still in contract talks with its elementary teachers. Those negotiations could end with further job cuts. Marlo Moore, is one of those who may once again face unemployment, come June.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Strike </b><p>
While teachers negotiate for their futures on the heels of Labour Day, hundreds of Ontario workers are now on strike. Six hundred, fifty employees with Niagara region walked off the job today at noon.<br> The members of CUPE Local 1287 have been in a legal strike position since Sunday.<br> The main issue in this dispute is job security.<br> To save 650 thousand dollars management says it may contract out certain jobs.<br> But the union charges that management hasn't done enough to cut costs in other areas.<br> Union members offered to take 8 days off without pay between now and the end of the year.<br>  The union represents welfare staff, sewage and water treatment workers, and those who manage the day care and seniors homes.
<hr>
<b>OPSEU - Hamilton</b><p>
And employees of one of Ontario's largest trade unions are on strike. In Hamilton, Ontario public service staff union workers picketed the Hamilton office of the Ontario Public Service Employees Union. The 250 member union of staff reps girevance officers and support staff are protesting over layoff notices, scheduled to take effect next week. OPSSU  members helped direct the strike by 46-thousand OPSEU members against the Harris government earlier this year.  
<hr>
<b>Mac - Civics</b><p>
<br>   The merger of Chedoke McMaster Hospitals and the Hamilton Civic Hospitals will create one of the largest health care organizations in Canada.<br>  And a 42 year-old Edmonton native will be at the helm.<br>  Dwight Ryan reports that after a lengthy and exhaustive cross Canada search, someone has been found to lead the Hamilton Health Sciences Corporation.  <br>  
<i><br>  The cat is finally out of the bag...   <br>    With 1350 beds, a budget of 400 million dollars and a staff of eight thousand the merger will create one of Canada's largest health care providers.<br>  42 year old Scott Rowand was one of hundreds of applicants from across Canada.  Just five made the short list.<br>   An impressive resume helps and Rowand's is just that.. <br>  Assistant professor in the faculty of medicine at U. of T. <br>  President of the Association of Canadian Teaching Hospitals, <br>   Past president of the Ontario Council of Teaching Hospitals and  past chair of the Toronto Academic Health Sciences Council. There's more. He's a member of the advisory council for the Centre for Health Economics at McMaster and the Hospital Management Research unit at U. of T.<br>  Its the kind of C.V. one needs to earn 339 thousand a year. Not the highest paid hospital CEO in the province ..and not the lowest.   <br>    Rowand told his Toronto colleagues that he's on his way.<br>  And he's says he's up to the challenge for his new job in Hamilton.  <br>  The target date for the merger is October 1st.<br>  Rowand will start his five year contract as CEO in early November.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Health Sciences </b><p>
<br>  Almost 26 million dollars in funding over the next three years was confirmed today for a McMaster University and Mohawk College Centre for Applied Sciences, to be constructed on the Mac campus. Hamilton West MPP Lillian Ross made the announcement. The facility will train as many as seven thousand full and part ime students in occupational therapy, physiotherapy, nursing, medical imaging, and pharmacy assisting, among other skills.
<hr>
<b>Burlington Flood</b><p>
<br> A flood emergency in Burlington today. The sun was shining so it wasn't the weather...  but a 50-year-old watermain that simply had deteriorated with age.<br> The old cast-iron main, under Queensway Drive ruptured early this morning, sending torrants of water gushing into a backyard on Brinell Street.<br> That yard ended up under two feet of water. A city of Burlington official says there's no damage inside the house.<br> Crews spent much of the day pumping and making repairs to the road.
<hr>
<b>Police Auction</b><p>
<br> Looking for a good used bicycle? Try the Halton Police Auction set for this Saturday.<br> They'll be selling off about 180 bikes... as well as a variety of other unclaimed merchandise... to the highest bidders. Viewing at 8:30 a.m... the auctions starts at 9:30 at the police HQ building at the QEW and Bronte Road in Oakville.


<P>
