<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, August 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Tax Bullies         
    <li>More Region Reform  
    <li>More Reform 
    <li>Murder Charge       
    <li>Pizza Attack        
    <li>Crack House         
    <li>Brantford Crime     
    <li>Grand Drowning      
    <li>Plane Crash         
    <li>Missing Boy         
    <li>Jr. Achievement   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>tax bullies</b><p>
<br> Few in number, large in debt. That's the story of a handful of delinquent taxpayers, who collectively owe the city of Hamilton millions of dollars in tax arrears.  All this week we've brought you their stories, or at least we've attempted to and have shared our efforts with you.
Tonight, the story of a disabled woman who also owes the city some money. She's been taken to court several times, and every day, she feels the burden of the taxman. Scot Urquhart has her story.
<i>Louise Lloyd, has not had an easy life. She's on her own. And she works hard. She was born with clubbed feet; and lost those seven years ago in an industrial accident. But she doesn't get a penny, in Workers' Compensation. Despite that, she want's to make it clear, she's not complaining: <br>  Louise owes about three thousand dollars, by her calculations; and she's trying to pay it back: <br>  She may be joking about it; but Louise admits she's: <br>  Louise says, she's tried and tried to strike a deal with the city: <br>  Louise knows that, only too well, and she vows to pay the money back. She says all she's looking for, is a chance, to survive. <br>  Bob Charters says, if she comes to see him ... she may get it. <br>  There are fifteen thousand cases of tax arrears in Hamilton ... and you can bet, there are two sides, to every story. </i>
<hr>
<b>More Region Reform</b><p>
<br>  Hamilton Wentworth Regional Council has agreed to disagree on the issue of regional reform.<br>   City councillors and suburban councillors will seek third party assistance in resolving the reform issues while keeping the region operating as usual...<br>  Jamie West reports...
<i>Finding the answer will likely be a much more difficult affair...<br>  To that end regional chairman Terry Cooke moved that a provincial mediator be brought in to help resolve the regional reform issues speciffically...a change in the political structure of regional government, consolidation of services and amalgamation of taxes...<br>  Flambourough's mayor is looking for a local voice of reason...<br>  Regional council in fact decided to go ahead with plans to seek a locally appointed facillitator...a person who unlike a mediator has no decision making authority...<br>  Councillor Dave Wilson says despite pressure from the province for municipal reform...in Hamilton Wentworth there are very few council members who really want change...<br>  Hamilton council wants a one tier supercity that would absorb all surrounding municipalities...<br>  The suburbs have proposed a modified two tier system that preserves local autonomy...<br>  Everyone agrees a resolution is going to be hard to achieve...<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>More Reform </b><p>
<br> One thing regional council did agree on today was to eliminate a fourteen year old upper tier tax discount for the suburbs. That means regional taxes in surrounding municipalities will increase, while city of Hamilton taxes will decrease.<br> No word yet on what it means to the bottom line of your regional tax bill.
<hr>
<b>Murder Charge</b><p>
<br> Police in Hamilton have cracked a two year old murder case.<br> They've charged 36 year  old Christopher Bank of Hamilton with first degree murder in the October 1994 death of Brother Daniel Morgan... a self-styled minister with the Church of the Universe. Bank is also charged with robbery. The break in the case came as the result of a Crime Stoppers tip allowing police to connect a car fire in Morgan's abandoned vehicle with another auto fire three weeks earlier in the same location. Bank is in custody awaiting a bail hearing.
<hr>
<b>Pizza Attack</b><p>
For the second summer in a row, an employee at this Pizza Pizza store in Hamilton has been attacked.<br> Overnight, he was trying to get three people out of the pizzeria when one of them cut his arm with a metal straw holder.<br> Police say he lost a considerable amount of blood, but is okay now.<br> 19 year old Jacob Kaloustian of Hamilton is charged with assault with a weapon.<br> Last summer, the Pizza Pizza employee was cut in the back of the head during an attack.
<hr>
<b>Crack House</b><p>
A winfall for Hamilton Wentworth Regional Oolice after they found a crack cocaine pipe in a car they'd stopped in east Hamilton.<br> They charged the driver, then traced the crack to this house on Holton Avenue North where they arrested seven more people on drug and weapon charges.<br> A ninth man was charged after he tried to trade six stolen football jerseys for crack cocaine while police were still there.
<hr>
<b>Brantford Crime</b><p>
<br> A five-month long investigation into a stolen-goods ring has come to a close with 24 arrests after raids in Brantford, Paris, Kitchener, Stoney Creek, St. Catharines, Mississauga, Pelham and Toronto. Police weren't surprised to find a large and varied haul of stolen goods including air conditioners, furnaces, computers, lawn mowers, weed-eaters, alcohol, blue jeans, sunglasses and baseball gloves.<br> But they didn't expect to find illegal cable television equipment: more than 1,200 so-called ``magic boxes,'' used to circumvent cable television systems.
<hr>
<b>Grand Drowning</b><p>
An autopsy scheduled today in Brantford after an apparent drowning in the Grand River. The body of 51-year-old Warren Pearce of Mount Hope was recovered just east of Mines Road in Caledonia, after a fisherman spotted someone in trouble in the water yesterday. By the time help arrived it was too late.  Police do not suspect foul play.
<hr>
<b>Plane Crash</b><p>
A 60-year-old Hagersville man is in serious condition in hospital in Hamilton after his ultra light aircraft crashed in a bean field in Springvale near Jarvis. David Rogers was testing his aircraft on a private airstrip when he encountered engine problems. He had reached an altitude of 100 feet when he nosedived to the ground and flipped over. Cayuga OPP are still investigating.
<hr>
<b>Missing Boy</b><p>
<br> A search is under way for an Hamilton teenager missing from a scout camp in Haliburton. Provincial police say 18 year old Jean Luc Renaut, who is autistic, disappeared from Camp Camac yesterday during a game of hide and seek. The search is being conducted by volunteers, police officers and scout leaders in an area just to the east of Haliburton village.
<hr>
<b>Jr. Achievement</b><p>
<br>  Canjac '96, an international conference of junior achievers is taking place at Hamilton's McMaster University.<br>  227 high school students from across Canada and ten other countries have gathered for the week to learn more about business and economics.  As well, they'll hone their entrepreneurial skills for future careers.<br>  Each of the delegates will get first hand advice from the corporations that are sponsoring the conference.


<P>
