<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, August 22, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>TD Robbery        
    <li>Bomb Threat         
    <li>Gorge Rescue        
    <li>Missing Kid Found   
    <li>Region HSR        
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Air Traffic         
    <li>Teletouch           
    <li>Thoroldnet          
</ul>
<hr>
<b>TD Robbery</b><p>
We don't know if he's paying his taxes but he seems to have changed his M.O. Hamilton's lunchtime bandit, is now behaving more like a brunch-time bandit.<br>  A suspect believed to be a serial bank robber has struck again in Hamilton.<br>  The latest hit, this morning at a Toronto Dominion branch downtown, is beleived to be his sixth in ten days.<br>  Yesterday, a suspect with the same description robbed a Bank of Montreal branch at almost exactly the same time of morning ... about twenty to eleven.<br>  Police have formed a serial bank holdup task force to find this bandit, and other repeat offenders.
<hr>
<b>Bomb Threat</b><p>
<br>    They're breathing sighs of relief on Hamilton's east mountain tonight after the police bomb squad converged on Stonechurch Square Plaza. A clerk in the Day- Night Pharmacy there had spotted someone leaing a suspicous looking black bag in the store. All of the usual precautions were taken... the pharmacy and adjoining stores were evacuated. After the bomb squad robot went it became clear that there was no bomb in the bag. It contained stolen audio CD's.
<hr>
<b>Gorge Rescue</b><p>
Two Toronto-area men face charges after a tumble into the Niagara Gorge early this morning. Niagara parks police say they were drinking and horsing around near the Rainbow Bridge and had climbed over a wall. The men lost their footing and fell 10 metres to a rock ledge. Niagara Falls firefighters rescued them using an aerial truck. The men were treated for minor injuries and then charged under the parks act.
<hr>
<b>Missing Kid Found</b><p>
  A happy ending to our story yesterday about the missing 11-year-old Hamilton boy. Christopher Hicks hadn't been seen since August 11th but police have located the boy. He is reported to be safe with relatives.
<hr>
<b>Region HSR</b><p>
 More busses will be running out to the suburbs.  A 15-to 10 vote today put the brakes on a hot debate over an extended urban transit area in Hamilton Wentworth.<br>  As Jamie West reports...the suburbs will pay more, but the city of Hamilton says the move will be more equitable for everyone concerned...
<i>And they were not alone...Ancaster, Stoney Creek, Dundas and Flamborough all gave thumbs down to a Regional Transportation Department recommendation calling for expansion of the HSR into their towns.<br>  The HSR now runs at a seventeen million dollar deficit, all of which in the past has been taken up by the city of Hamilton alone.<br>  Most suburbs including Ancaster have purchased service from the HSR on a pay as you play basis.<br>  After finally voting to approve the recommendation, the HSR will truly become a regionally operated service, that will cost each suburb more than 100-thousand dollars each over the next five years. </i>
<hr>
<b>Business - First</b><p>
  For the sixteenth time since may, interest rates in Canada are on their way down.<br>  The Bank of Canada dropped the central lending rate by a quarter point today leading the major banks to trim their prime lending rates.<br>  Mortgage rates are also on the way down again. The central bank hopes the move will help spur on our lagging economy which is already showing signs of recovery.<br>  Retail sales in Canada in June were up by 0.6%, their largest gain in nearly a year.  Economists now say the worst is behind us and the remainder of the year will bring more good news.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Air Traffic</b><p>
It seems more people are spending money to fly in and out of Hamilton International Airport.   In fact July was the busiest month for passenger service in almost six years.<br>  Air traffic last month, after Greyhound Air began service quadrupled over July of last year. Greyhound Air  is reporting strong business in its four daily flights in and out of Hamilton and USAir Express is also showing an increase in passenger traffic on its four flights between Hamilton and Pittsburg.
<hr>
<b>Teletouch</b><p>
<br>  A five minute phone call may be all it takes to make sure a senior citizen is safe and healthy, and to re-assure family members who can't be in touch every day. <br>  For the last 25 years in Hamilton and Halton, Tele-touch has been providing that service.<br>  As Annette Hamm tells us, the program needs more volunteers to meet the growing list of seniors who need a reassuring ring.
<i> Alone in her Hamilton apartment, 71 year old Mar looks forward to a phone call every morning from her Tele-touch volunteer.<br>  Mar signed up for the free service so that someone other than her cats would know if something went wrong.  <br>  Mar hasn't met her volunteer caller, and hasn't been told her last name or where she lives.<br>  The program likes to keep things on a first name basis only for security reasons.  <br>  Karli has spent her summer calling about thirty seniors a day from the Teletouch office.<br>  She's handling an overflow of clients and will be matched with her own client when she goes back to school.  <br>  It takes five minutes a day to become a Teletouch volunteer, and you can call from your home or office.<br>  If you're interested in helping out, or would like to be a Teletouch client, you can call 522-9567 in Hamilton or 875-0808 if you live in Halton.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Thoroldnet</b><p>
<br>   The city of Thorold, near St. Catharines, is about to become one of Canada's first "virtual" communities. "Thoroldnet" is set to go on line next week, allowing residents to use their computers to apply for things like building permits, dog licences and reserve library books. Thoroldnet is expected to help the city cut costs, eliminate red tape and best of all, eliminate lineups.


<P>
