<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, August 21, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Tax Cheats          
    <li>Kays Charges        
    <li>Missing Child       
    <li>Infanticide         
    <li>Break-in Arrest     
    <li>Falls Death         
    <li>Depot for Sale      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Wesley Neighbours   
    <li>CNE - Killjoys        
</ul>
<hr>
<b>tax cheats</b><p>
<br> Tonight more on our on-going coverage of Hamilton's tax delinquents who owe the city some 87-million dollars.  Last night reporter Scot Urquhart revealed the top 10 deadbeat taxpayer list, who alone account for 10 per cent of outstanding tax bills.
<BR>
Tonight Scot tells us more about these people and what they have to say for themselves.
<i><br>  It's no surprise really. if you owed this kind of money ... you wouldn't want to see the media either ...<br>  And so when we went to find out who was behind the 1.9 million dollar tax arrears on this property ... we had to speak to the tennants:<br>  Sam McKinlay rents space for his printing company here. He said they recently got a letter from the city:<br>  We also managed to get a phone number for Ed Palonek of Oakville ... the man who sam says, represents Rothwell, and acts as his landlord: <br>  So ... we went to check on number two on the list ... officially ... it's Theatre Aquarius. Just about a million dollars, in the hole. What about the grants they've been getting from the city: <br>  And Max Reimer says, they do have a plan to pay the money back. A plan to be unveiled to city council next month: <br>  Unofficially ... the real number two delinquent, is 1158929 Ontario Ltd. with two properties on Strathearne Ave. The combined tax arrears ... is in the order of 1.3 million dollars. We had trouble with the Ministry of Consumer and Corporate Affairs tracking down a principal for the numbered company ... so we went to the listed address. We didn't feel entirely welcomed: <br>  And what about those harbour commissioners? We asked them why they owed more than 800-thousand dollars.<br>  According to their annual report ... they made about 57 million dollars last year. How could they owe so much? We were told they were tax exempt... and while some of their tennants might be in arrears... they weren't.... we were'nt told much else <br>  There are more names on the list. More mysteries to solve. But for the most part it seems clear; that no one directly involved is in any kind of hurry; to clear things up. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Kays Charges</b><p>
Criminal charges have now been laid against the former owner of Kay's Pizzeria in Hamilton.<br> The charges stem from the failed operations of the restaurant and catering business.<br> 37 year old Jon Raffay of Stoney Creek will appear in court next monday on 3 counts of fraud and one of theft by conversion.<br> Police say the theft charge was laid after royalty payments were not made to a company which sold its recipes to Kays.
<hr>
<b>Missing Child</b><p>
<br> Police want your help in finding an 11-year-old Hamilton boy who has been missing for more than a week. Christopher Hicks was last seen on August 11th. He's described as five feet tall, weighing 91 pounds, with brown hair and blue eyes. If you've seen this boy or know where he might be, call Hamilton- Wenworth Regional Police at 546-4925.
<hr>
<b>Infanticide</b><p>
<br> A tragic story emerging out of a Hamilton courtroom. A 17 year old who gave birth to a baby girl while her family slept will be sentenced next month for infanticide.<br> Police and social workers were alerted to the case in January of 1995 when the teenager was brought to hospital bleeding badly. She denied having given birth but later relented. An autopsy revealed the newborn was full term and was alive and healthy but died of severe head injuries due to blunt force trauma.
<hr>
<b>Break-in Arrest</b><p>
<br> A Hamilton man appeared in court in Walkerton today after police siezed a carload of break-in tools. They included a police scanner, walkie-talkies, and crowbars. 23-year-old Jarem Corbett is charged with poseession of break-in instruments and breach of probation. A Woodstock man and two youths were also charged.
<hr>
<b>Falls Death</b><p>
<br> A crowd of horrified tourists looked on as a man was swept over Niagara Falls.<br> US state park police spokesman Peter Tarasow says the man went over the American falls at about 7:15 last night.<br> Tarasow says he's not sure if the man, in his 20s, fell in the water accidentally or if it was a suicide.<br> Witnesses say it appeared the man was in panic.<br> It's the fifth time this year a person has gone over the falls on either the American or Canadian side.
<hr>
<b>Depot for Sale</b><p>
<br> How often do you ride the bus? ...not enough according to the Hamilton Street Railway, so they're getting leaner while trying to find new ways to generate revenue.<br> As Jamie West reports the HSR is getting into the leasing business...
<i>The HSR's Wentworth Street garage has been home to most of it's operation since the end of June....<br>  That's when they pulled out of this 12 year old, 13 million dollar facility on Hwy 6....a facility that the region hopes to lease out...<br>  For the last five years the HSR has been stripping down it's operation ...after early eighties predictions of a booming Hamilton population failed to materialize...<br>  In 1996 about one in ten people ride the bus...<br>  The HSR will continue to service about 20 buses at a time at the Hwy 6 depot, including the new accesible low floor model that will hit the streets in late September.<br>  Those operations they say will not interfere with the business of their new tenant whoever it turns out to be. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br> More good news out of Burlington based Zenon Environmental today.  The international water treatment company has landed an eleven million dollar contract in Poland.  Company officials say the contract is a significant inroad into the Polish power plant market.<br> The news follows impressive second quarter profits for Zenon announced earlier this week.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Wesley Neighbours</b><p>
<br> Usually it's cries of "not in my backyard!" ... but for some residents of a Hamilton apartment co-op it's more like not in our front yard, or anywhere near our building. <br> They're complaining about clients from the Wesley Urban Ministries Drop in Centre next door.<br> Clients who sometimes use drugs or pass out on the grass nearby.<br> And while the ministry is trying to stem the problem, they say there's only so much they can do.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i> In other words, Richard Gillespie wants Wesley Urban Ministries to clean up the area outside their new location.<br>  Since the centre opened a few months ago, neighbours, especially those next door at the meridian co-op have complained about seeing clients sleeping on the grass, urinating in their garden, or shooting up drugs.  <br>  Some co-op members want a fence between their building and Wesley's, others see this as a problem in society, not just in their neighbourhood.  <br>  Wesley Urban Ministries would like keep the drop in centre open 24 hours a day, not just from midnight til noon... so these guys would have a place to sleep inside during the day.  But they don't have the money to do it.<br>  They have, however, banned two trouble makers from the centre.  <br>  Wesley Urban also runs the apartments above the drop in centre and townhouses behind it, so Johnson says they also want to keep things under control for their own tenants.  </i>
<hr>
<b>CNE - Killjoys</b><p>
 Two Hamilton area bands will be performing at the CNE ExMusicFest tonight.  The Killjoys of Hamilton, and the Rainbow Butt Monkeys of Burlington join Halifax artists Sandbox and Tempe and The Refreshments from Arizona.  The show starts at the bandshell at 6:30 and is free with your CNE admission.


<P>
