<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, August 20, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Crime Patterns      
    <li>Hit and Run         
    <li>Olson Parole        
    <li>Bill 49 Hamilton    
    <li>MTO Mobile Unit   
    <li>Oakville Fire       
    <li>Turkstra - MD     
    <li>Fastest Man         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Crime Patterns</b><p>
<br> Get ready for another round of bank heists.<br> It looks like there's a serial robber at work in the Hamilton area.<br> The four most recent robberies, two yesterday within the span of a three hours, bear striking similarities.<br> Annette Hamm reports.
<i><br>  As soon as there's a bank robbery in Hamilton Wentworth, crime analyst Nancy Kaneva gets a call.<br>  The officers on the scene provide her with the robbery details, she tells them if it matches any others.  <br>  Often, suspects become comfortable with a certain style of robbery; they fall into a habit.<br>  That makes a crime analysts task of identifying patterns much easier.<br>  Then police can put bank branches on notice, even put undercover officers in place to protect employees and customers.  <br>  Now Kaneva's job is to try and pinpoint where and when this latest suspect might strike next.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Hit and Run</b><p>
 A 38-year-old Buffalo man was released on bail in Niagara Falls on our side of the river today. Glen Root will be back before the courts on September 11th. He's facing charges related to a tragic accident in which three teen-agers on bicycles were run down by a car, which fled the scene. A 13-year-old boy was killed in the mishap.
<hr>
<b>Olson Parole</b><p>
A victim's rights group is outraged that Clifford Olson has applied for a review of his parole eligibility.<br> Olson has served 15 years of a minimum 25-year term for the sex slayings of 11 British Columbia children.<br> But, under the criminal code's so-called "faint hope" clause he's applied for a review to see if his earliest parole date can be moved up.<br> The group CAVEAT founded by Priscilla Devilliers, mother of Burlington murder victim Nina Devilliers, says the review is a show for Olson, who has become notorious for exploits involving challenges to the justice system, not to mention emotional torture for the families of his victims.
<hr>
<b>Bill 49 Hamilton</b><p>
<br> Ontario's Employment Standards Act has been changed more than 20 times since it was introduced 22 years ago.  <br> And now the Harris government wants to make more changes.<br> In Hamilton today, a standing committee began a 13 city tour for hearings on its proposed amendments.<br> Among them: putting a 10-thousand dollar cap on the amount workers can be awarded from the Ministry of Labour as the result of a claim.<br> Labour groups worry the changes may erode minimum work standards.
<hr>
<b>MTO Mobile Unit</b><p>
And a little bit of Queen's Park came to Duff's Corners today, that's the corner of Highways two and 53, to try out a weigh station on wheels.<br>  The Ontario Ministry of Transportation is testing its new mobile truck inspection station, in its ongoing campaign to keep unsafe trucks off the road.<br>  Inspectors say the mobile unit can do almost everything a permanent weigh station can do, with the added advantage that it can be moved to routes used by truckers trying to evade inspection stations on major highways.
<hr>
<b>Oakville Fire</b><p>
It's back to the drawing board for six small Oakville businesses after a million dollar fire gutted a strip mall.<br> Firefighters were called to the River Oaks Malls late yesterday afternoon to battle the blaze. However all six stores in the strip mall were gutted. A neighbouring senior's residence was evacuated as a precaution. The fire marshall has been called in to investigate the cause of the inferno. Fire officials say the flames started in a garbage bin outside the mall and spread engulfing the entire structure.<br> Luckily, no one was injured.
<hr>
<b>Turkstra - MD</b><p>
<br> It's a cross-Canada caravan, that's a cross between "home improvement" and good works.<br> The Dewalt Canada National Tour stopped at Turkstra Lumber on Hamilton mountain today.<br> The tour, sponsored by the popular power tool-maker, delivers expert home improvement tips.<br> At the same time, Dewalt holds contests and challenges to raise money for Muscular Dystrophy.<br> Seven specially- equipped Dewalt vans set out from Halifax earlier this month, on a cross-country odyssey that will end in Vancouver late in September.
<hr>
<b>Fastest Man</b><p>
Finally tonight, a Niagara Falls man is fed up with American claims that Michael Johnson -- and not Oakville's Donovan Bailey -- is the world's fastest man.<br> The last straw for Mike Leskiw was last night, when a US television magazine show claimed Johnson was the fastest man in the world.<br> Both Bailey and Johnson set world records at the Atlanta Olympics -- Bailey in the 100 metres and Johnson in the 200 and 400.<br>   Leskiw says he is going to spend 600 dollars US for an ad in the New York Times to explain to the Americans that Bailey is number one.


<P>
