<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, August 19, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Tax Arrears         
    <li>Action Day Bill     
    <li>Royal Robbery       
    <li>Galley Shoot        
    <li>Bernardo girlfriend 
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Mac Code         
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Tax Arrears</b><p>
 We hear it again, and again. The city, is caught in a money crunch. Budgets are squeezed, and cash-flow, is tight. But there is a huge pool of money that could be... and should be pumped into the city treasury, to make sure the well doesn't run dry. How big a pool? 
<hr>
<b>Action Day Bill</b><p>
<br> It's been half a year since thousands of labour activists vented their frustration in Hamilton during a weekend of protest. And the bill still isn't settled. Annette Hamm tells us that may change tomorrow.
<i> The Hamilton and District Labour Council didn't call the Days of Action protest back in February.<br>  But now they're footing the bill.<br>  Several other unions planned to protest in Hamilton while the Tories held a convention, and the Ontario Federation of Labour asked the council to help organize things.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Royal Robbery</b><p>
The rash of lunch-time bank robberies in Hamilton continues, with the latest target the Royal Bank branch at Main and Sherman.<br>  A man walked into the bank just after one-thirty this afternoon, told the teller he had a gun, and stuffed cash into a beige plastic bag before making his getaway.<br>  The suspect is described as white, five-foot eight, and about twenty-eight- years-old.<br>  He was unshaven, and had dirty blond hair.<br>  This is the third lunch-time robbery in Hamilton in eight days.
<hr>
<b>Galley Shoot</b><p>
Two men have been charged after a weekend shootout outside a central Hamilton bar.<br>  It all started Saturday night after a man shot a semi automatic handgun into the air in the parking lot at the Galley Pump.<br>  One of the two men he was trying to scare retaliated by trashing his jeep.<br>  53 year old John Bothman of Wasago is charged with possessing a dangerous weapon.<br>  47 year old Thomas Grecko of Newbury is charged with mischief and uttering threats.
<hr>
<b>Bernardo Girlfriend</b><p>
<br> Convicted double murderer and serial rapist Paul Bernardo may be living in a segregated jail cell but he has a girlfriend, actually an old girlfriend. The latest issue of Macleans Magazine interviews an unidentified woman in her late 20's about her "strong emotional attachment" to Bernardo. She says she can't explain why she remains fond of a man found guilty of horrendous murders. And when she thinks about what Bernardo did she sometimes just "blocks it out." She and Bernardo had a relationship in the late 1980's, and she met him again shortly before his arrest in 1993 for the murders of teens Kristen French and Leslie Mahaffy.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br>  Canadian manufacturing shipments in June were down following two months of growth.  Taking the big hit: cars, car parts and electronics.<br>  And the U.S. Federal Reserve meets tomorrow.  Most analysts on both sides of the border believe the feds will leave interest rates alone. A hike in rates would probably lead to investors fleeing the stock markets.<br>   
<hr>
<b>Mac Code</b><p>
<br>  At university campuses everywhere students are gearing up for a new school year and for many, part of that involves the ritual of frosh. In recent years campuses in southern Ontario have seen an increase in more violent and objectionable behaviour like hazing. Over the past couple of years, students at McMaster University have taken the lead and tamed welcome week activities but this year new rules have been carved into stone. In May, following more than two years of studying policies across Canada and the U.S., the McMaster University Senate approved a code of conduct, setting out penalties for breaking clearly defined rules and that code comes into effect this fall.


<P>
