<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, August 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Macnab Apt. Fire     
    <li>Wainfleet Body      
    <li>Worker Pinned       
    <li>Ancaster Speeder    
    <li>Paling Air          
    <li>Cabinet 
    <li>Young Builders      
    <li>Business First        
    <li>Business Thrives    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Macnab Apt. Fire</b><p>
   <br>  A dramatic high-rise fire in Hamilton this afternoon. Two people including a firefighter were rushed to hospital this aftenoon after a fire broke out in a north end Hamilton highrise.<br>  All of the tenants in the seniors building had to be evacuated.<br>  Lauran Sabourin has more..
<i><br>  Just after one this afternoon a fire broke out in unit 1105 at the Ken Soble Towers on Burlington Street.<br>  Smoke billowed from the 11th floor unit.<br>  Firefighters were battling the blaze from the inside.<br>  Most of the 11th floor sustained major smoke damage. <br>  The tenant of 1105 was rushed to hospital suffering burns and smoke inhalation. <br>  A firefighter who was overcome by smoke was also taken to hospital by ambulance.<br>  Three other people were treated for smoke inhalation on the scene. <br>  The buildings tenants, most of them seniors were herded into a transit bus so officials could take a head count. <br>  The Fire Marshall had been called to the scene.<br>  They are still not sure how the blaze started. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Wainfleet Body</b><p>
<br>  Niagara Regional Police are appealing to the public tonight in their search for a suspect in a fatal hit and run.  It happened sometime in the early morning hours in Wainfleet on Lakeshore Road near the golf course.  The body of a man in his late teens or early 20's was found around 5:30 this morning.<br>  He had suffered massive injuries after being hit by a vehicle.
<hr>
<b>Worker Pinned</b><p>
A city of Hamilton worker is in hospital tonight with serious leg and foot injuries after an accident on Barton Street just before the noon hour.  57 year old Dave McManus, was removing a concrete saw from a trailer, when it broke loose from a braking mechanism. The 15-hundred pound saw rolled over top of McManus and pinned him to the street. He was conscious when taken to hospital. Investigators are trying to find out why it happened.
<hr>
<b>Ancaster Speeder</b><p>
<br> A few months ago we told you how the town of Ancaster together with Brantford OPP and Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police are cracking down on speeders through its speeder of the month.  The winner for July clocked in at 122 in a 60 zone on Carluke Road. That motorist has been fined 450-dollars. First runner-up got nailed with a 365-dollar fine for doing 110 in a 60 and told the officer the speedometer was broken.
<hr>
<b>Paling Air</b><p>
<br> A new study, indicating an unusually high incidence of asthma in children living near the industrial core, has divided residents in a Hamilton neighbourhood. Some say the pollution-laden air is killing them.  Others say the air's fine, and they're sick of having people trash their neighbourhood.<br> Reporter Scot Urquhart went to Paling Avenue, and found both the issue, and the study, to be hotly contested items:
<i><br>  There are two sides to every story ... and these women say, no one is hearing theirs: <br>  The women are infuriated by a series of newspaper articles claiming that their street is an area with poor air quality, and serious health problems: <br>  Karen Bedard, was quoted in the paper, as a mom concerned about the health of her asthmatic son: <br>  In fact, the women even took issue with the picture that was printed with the article: <br>  These neighbours say, their street is as green and healthy as any other in Hamilton, and they are concerned about their property values being driven down, by false information ... but there's no doubt, the issue is a controversial one on Paling Avenue. This woman says; she's been harassed by her neighbours, for speaking out about air quality: <br>  In fact, says Hunter, asthma in general is on the rise ... for reasons yet unknown. And he cautions that the homeside health study is not definitive, by any means: <br>  Hunter cites diet, and dust mites in air- tight homes ... as other significant factors contributing to the rise in asthma. The neighbours on Paling Avenue say, that just goes to prove ... that you can't believe everything you read. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Cabinet</b><p>
A new minister is in charge of the air we breathe down at Queen's Park. Environment minister Brenda Elliot's out as environment and energy minister and Norm Sterling, the former consumer minister has her job, with the consumer portfolio going to controversial social services minister David Tsubouchi. It's all part of premier Mike Harris' first cabinet shuffle. Burlington MPP Cam Jackson is now the minister without portfolio in charge of seniors issues.            
<hr>
<b>Young Builders</b><p>
<br>  They were learning how to build their own cabinets in ancaster today.  You're never too young to learn a little self-sufficiency.<br>  That's the philosophy behind "Community Day", held at Ancaster's Home Depot today.<br>  Home Depot staff showed members of the boys and girls clubs the nuts and bolts of carpentry.<br>  By the end of the day, using materials provided by the store, the fledgling builders had constructed two picnic tables and a sand box.<br>  Home Depot says the program fosters a sense of team-work and accomplishment, and also gives kids the know-how to build items needed by their clubs.
<hr>
<b>Business First</b><p>
<br> The Bank of Canada today lowered its trend setting bank rate by a quarter of a percentage point. That triggered a reduction in the prime lending rate. <BR> Chartered banks dropped their prime rates by a quarter of a percent to six per cent.<br> That translates into lower interest payments on investments and on consumer loans.<br> 
<hr>
<b>Business Thrives</b><p>
<br> The construction equipment is gone and Ottawa Street is again open for business.<br> A special ceremony was held today to signify a new beginning for one of Hamilton's most thriving business areas.<br> Dwight Ryan was there...  <br>  
<i> Tony DiTomasso has been fixing cars on Ottawa Street for 42 years.<br>  He was in the crowd as the mayor unveiled two stunning murals signalling an end to constuction and the beginning of a refurbished business area.  <br>  Often referred to as the unofficial mayor of Ottawa Street, Tony takes pride in the service he and his neighbours offer.  <br>       Working on his mural, artist Cameron Mahy was overwhelmed by the friendliness of Ottawa Street merchants.   <br>      Sixteen thousand cars a day travel down the newly paved Ottawa Street.  New sidewalks and a stoplight make it safe for pedestrians.  <br>    A visit to Ottawa Street is like an international tour.    <br>  But if you want croation specialties, like lamb, pork and streudel, you'd better call ahead.   <br>  Whether its smoked meat, cakes or textiles, the newly refurbished Ottawa Street is open for business.<br> </i>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

