<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, August 14, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Niagara Labor Strike
    <li>Blue Box Update     
    <li>Hunter St. Fire      
    <li>Bank Hit            
    <li>Home Invasion       
    <li>Child Porn Arrest   
    <li>Boy Assault         
    <li>Booze Bust          
</ul>

<hr>
<b>Niagara Labor Strike</b><p>
 It's showdown time between municipal governments and their workers across the province. <br>  For the workers it's catch-up time, now that the ndp government's social contracts have expired. It all begins in Niagara, where the region thought it had a deal.<br> But union heavyweights from Toronto had a look at a proposed contract and told the employees it should be rejected.<BR>
 So six hundred, fifty employees there are taking a strike vote today and now, as Lauran Sabourin reports, CUPE national reps and bureaucrats are locked in a war of words.
<i><br>  On the one side Mike Stokes, veteran union negotiator. The man who along with CUPE Ontario President Sid Ryan is accused of trying to scuttle this deal. <br>  The most contentious issue in this dispute is a proposal to contract out jobs.<br>  Regional administrators admit that to save some some jobs may be contracted out. But employees will be guaranteed employment. <br>    The union is using radio ads to get its message across. <br>  The region is countering with a campaign over the fax machine..  The employees to which the messages are directed don't know what to do. <br>  In the end both sides say the interest of the taxpayer should be paramount. The union says providing less service is a disservice to the taxpayer. Regional politicians say asking ratepayers for more money is a disservice to the taxpayer. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Blue Box Update</b><p>
  Published reports today indicate that metro Toronto stands to lose millions in its blue box program.<br> For most people, recylcing is now a way of life. As Dwight Ryan reports, the Hamilton Wentworth region put the process in private hands ..and may even make money on its blue box program.  <br>
<i><br>  Ontario residents are conscious of dangers to our environment and they're doing something about it. <br>  In fact two thirds of the population regularly uses blue boxes.<br>  Papers, bottles, cardboard and cans no longer fill our landfill sites, they go in the box to be recylcled.  What used to be waste is now a valuable commodity.<br>  Still metro Toronto stands to lose about five and a half million dollars with its recylcing program. Taxpayers will cover the loss.  <br>  The front-runners were Phillip Enviornmental and Third Sector Recycling...a non-profit firm.<br>  They teamed up and now handle the tons of reclyclables that people in the region put out in their boxes...   <br>    Alderman Dave Wilson chairs the region's environmental services committee.   <br>    </i>
<hr>
<b>Hunter St. Fire</b><p>
A Hamilton man repeatedly braved flames and smoke this afternoon, to drag his unconscious wife from their burning basement apartment.<br> 38-year-old James West was in the backyard of his Hunter Street West home just before three this afternoon, when he noticed smoke pouring out of the basement windows.<br> His 38-year-old wife Rebecca was inside.      
<br> Paramedics and firefighters revived Rebecca West, who was rushed to hospital suffering from smoke inhalation.<br> Damage to the house is estimated at fifty to seventy-five thousand dollars.<br> The Wests had just moved into their new apartment on the first of August.
<hr>
<b>Bank Hit</b><p>
Police are investigating another lunch-hour bank robbery in Hamilton, the second one this week.<br> A white man, between thirty and forty, walked into the Bank of Nova Scotia branch at King and Sherman just before noon today.<br> He handed a teller a note, saying he had a gun, although no gun was seen.<br> The robber fled on a ten-speed bike, and a witness followed him in a car.<br> Police also gave chase, and although they found the shirt, hat and sunglasses the man was wearing, they failed to nab the robber himself.
<hr>
<b>Home Invasion</b><p>
Police are looking for two gunmen after a home invasion in a downtown apartment yesterday. It happened at the Hess Village Towers on Market Street around 4 o'clock in the afternoon.  Three women and a seven year old girl were bound with duct tape and forced to the floor by the robbers. One woman was pistol whipped but not injured seriously. The tenant, while bound managed to open the door and get to the lobby for help.  The suspects escaped with cash and jewellry. They're described as two black males in their mid-20's, one about 5- foot-seven , wearing black jeans, a green t-shirt baseball cap and black and red running shoes; the other 5-foot-four,, wearing a green t-shirt and pants, white baseball cap and green and beige running shoes.
<hr>
<b>Child Porn Arrest</b><p>
<br>  Police have charged a 35-year-old Hamilton man with three counts of possession of child pornography.<br>  Police initially responded to complaints about a man loitering around the Gage Park wading pool, and video-taping activities in the park.<br>  They later searched an east Hamilton apartment, and seized eighty videotapes.<br>  Charged is thirty-five-year- old Daniel Patrik Gunn of King Street East.
<hr>
<b>Boy Assault</b><p>
<br> In St. Catharines, a 13 year old boy is facing two counts of sexual assault.  His arrest followed compliants from the boy's two female cousins, aged 11 and 8. No further information is being released to protect the identities of the accused and his alleged victims. The boy has been released from custody and is to appear in court September 9th.
<hr>
<b>Booze Bust</b><p>
Canada Customs officers at the Peace Bridge in Fort Erie pulled over a cattle car this afternoon with more than 21 hundred bottles of alcohol stashed in a compartment.<br> The booze was under an adjustable floor in the trailer.<br> The 361 cases had an estimated street value of more than one hundred, six thousand dollars.<br> Charged is 50 year old George Blancke of Moorefield Ontario.

<P>
