<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, August 13, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Regional Structure  
    <li>QEW Truck Fire   
    <li>Double Fatal        
    <li>Explosive Promo     
    <li>Stelwire Vote    
    <li>Yacht Close         
    <li>Nia. Workfare       
    <li>Business First        
</ul>

<hr>
<b>Regional Structure</b>
<p>
The endless debate over regional government reform, plodded forward in a new direction, today. <br>  The first of three working- groups designed to help streamline local government, began deliberations over a new structure for the six area municipalities today.
<br> While no agreement seems to be in sight; reporter Scot Urquhart discovered that the easiest way out of this mess might be, to give the people what they want:
<i><br>  The city wants to do away with the region ...<br>  The region wants to do away with half a dozen municipalities.... <br>  And the municipalities just want the city and the region, to leave them alone, and go away. <br>  Somehow, this working group of regional politicians, must decide how to reconcile those wildly different visions: <br>  And that's the key ... although we are tied together by geography; suburban residents aren't prepared to let big city politicians gang up on them; and take their towns away: <br>  And so there is no mileage in pedalling the big city concept, in small towns like Ancaster. Just ask Enid Macdonald, who runs the local laundromat, and has lived in Ancaster for 43 years: <br>  And so the issue of government reform, goes 'round and 'round .... and in the end, says councillor Morelli, we might be better to drop the idea of a super city ... and concentrate on the things we can all agree upon: <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>QEW Truck Fire</b><p>
<br> The Toronto bound lanes of the QEW just east of the Garden City Skyway were closed for hours today after a tractor trailer exploded into flames this morning.<br>  The truck was burning noxious plastics.<br>  And as Lauran Sabourin reports if the wind had been blowing the other way hundreds of residents would have been evacuated.
<i> <br>  The flames lit up the night sky as the tractor trailer sat burning on the Glendale ramp off the QEW. <br>  The driver of the truck had pulled onto the ramp after he could smell his brakes getting hot. <br>  He got out of his truck and saw smoke coming from the second axle brake drum which was glowing red. Authorities believe a tire had blown. <br>  Then an explosion. <br>  An explosion on a truck that was carrying more than 17 thousand kilograms of polystyrene beads.  <br>  When the fire was extinguished half of the truck was gone.<br>  Nothing was left but a charred wreck that was still smoldering hours later.  <br>  The firefighters were hosed down. That's because  polystyrene residue carries toxic fumes with it. The Niagara on the Lake  fire chief Bruce Little says if the wind hadn't been blowing north they would have had to evacutate nearby residents.  <br>  But the Toronto bound lanes of the QEW were closed for hours.<br>  The Glendale ramp was finally opened around three this afternoon. <br> </i>
<hr>
<b>Double Fatal</b><p>
<br> Two people are dead and three others are in hospital following a two-vehicle crash near Waterford, just north of Simcoe.<br> Police say a car driven by 45-year-old Vladimir Minic of London pulled into the path of a van driven by 47-year-old Robert Archer of Port Dover last night.<br> Minic and his 19-year-old daughter, Stella Minic, were killed.<br> An unidentified passenger in the car is in serious condition in Hamilton General Hospital.<br> Archer and his 16-year-old son, Joseph, are in a Simcoe hospital with non-life threatening injuries.
<hr>
<b>Explosive Promo</b><p>
<br>  Fears of a mail bomb resulted in a number of calls to police in Hamilton-Wentworth today.  The suspicious packages were plain white cardboard tubes. The tubes turned out to be a promotional campaign for a Stoney Creek furniture company. Stoney Creek Furniture sent out the tubes containing a pamphlets and keys to a 10 thousand-dollar treasure chest. The company says it will identify itself in its next promotional mailing.
<hr>
<b>Stelwire Vote</b><p>
<br>  Three hundred, fifty striking Stelwire workers in Hamilton will be back on the job beginning tomorrow morning.<br>  Today members of Local 5328 voted 91 percent in favor of accepting the company's offer.<br>  The four year deal includes increased pensions, a better profit sharing plan and a shorter work week.<br>  The union feels that carrying out their strike threat gave them significant leverage with the company.
<hr>
<b>Yacht Close</b><p>
A well-known Canadian yacht maker is about to sail into the sunset apparently for the last time. C and C Yachts of Niagara on the Lake will be closing at the end of the month, leaving 20 people out of work. Officials at the 30-year-old company say they haven't been able to recover from a devastating multi million-dollar fire two years ago. The company says it will do all it can to help the workers find new jobs.
<hr>
<b>Nia. Workfare</b><p>
  Meanwhile,  Niagara is doing what it can to find jobs for scores of welfare recipients.<br> Four-thousand people in the region have been deemed qualified for workfare.<br> Of those, an undetermined number are considered the most employable.<br> The region is considering turning welfare offices into employment agencies for those people.<br> The proposal will be debated by regional council on Thursday as it considers how to implement workfare.<br> If it passes, it will affect the entire niagara region.
<hr>
<b>Business - First</b><p>
 <br> Canadian stock prices opened the week moving higher along with the value of the dollar. <BR>The number of building permits issued to build new homes is on the increase in Canada, but corporate profits are lower than they were a year ago. 

<P>
