<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, August 12, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>





<ul>
    <li>Olympic Welcome     
    <li>Missing Man         
    <li>TD Robbery         
    <li>401 Fire            
    <li>51 Tisdale Arson    
    <li>Child Abandoned     
    <li>Olson Parole        
    <li>Most Wanted         
    <li>Shipping Death      
    <li>Hamilton Doctors    
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Olympic Welcome</b><p>
 They gave us all they had. years of training, for a few thrilling moments, in Atlanta. And today it was time to say thank you, to the young men and women, who were the pride of Hamilton, in the Olympics. Scot Urquhart has more:
<i><br>  Who says, you can't go home again? Whatever these athletes may have done in Atlanta ... they are number one in the world, in the hearts of Hamiltonians. Even recent transplants; like cyclist Clara Hughes say their lives have taken root, and blossomed in Hamilton: <br>  Hughes ... who gave one of her bronze medals to her grandmother ... dedicated the second, in a moving tribute to the recently deceased Eddie Higgins; a major force in Hamilton's running community: <br>  From long-time veteran gymnast Alan Nolet, to the shining new star of swimmer Joanne Malar ... Hamilton had much to be proud of in Atlanta. And that Canadian pride came out in surprising fashion when runner Paula Schnurr told the crowd that her proudest moment of the Olympics, was watching the men's 4x100 relay team : quote: "kick some american butt" ... a remark that drew applause and laughter from the crowd, and her parents: <br>  But the true spirit of the Olympic challenge was perhaps best summed up by the mayor Bob Morrow's brother ... Al Morrow... coach of the national rowing team; who says the win at all cost attitude; has no place in his program, or in the world of sport: <br>  But losing, wasn't an issue here. For the people of Hamilton, these athletes, are worth their weight, in gold. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Missing Man</b><p>
<br> Halton Regional Police believe a Burlington man, missing for over a month, may be living or working in the Hamilton-area.<br> 34-year-old William Marr left his north Burlington home June twenty-eighth after arguing with his parents.<br> Marr has gone missing in the past, but always returned home within a few days.<br> He is white, five-foot-nine, with a medium build, short brown hair and blue eyes.<br> Police do not suspect foul play in William Marr's disappearance, but his family is anxious to know if he's all right.<br> Anyone who may have seen marr since June twenty-eighth is urged to contact Halton Regional Police.
<hr>
<b>TD Robbery</b><p>
<br> The search is on tonight for  a lone robber who held up the Toronto Dominion Bank branch at King and Wentworth streets in Hamilton over the lunch-hour today.<br> Just after one o'clock, the robber handed a teller a note, saying he was armed with a gun.<br> The suspect is described as a slim, unsavoury-looking white man in his twenties.<br> He was wearing a black baseball cap and a t-shirt with faded lettering.<br> he was also carrying a grey plastic bag.
<hr>
<b>401 Fire</b><p>
<br> OPP looking for witnesses to a tractor trailer crash on the 401 near Milton this morning.  It happened in the middle of rush hour near Trafalgar Road, when the truck, was cut off by a car, struck a guardrail and flipped over before bursting into flames.<br> Both people in the tractor trailer managed to escape with only minor injuries. But eastbound traffic was backed up for miles as only part of one lane was opened for rush hour commuters.
<hr>
<b>51 Tisdale Arson</b><p>
<br>  Damage was extensive when a house on Tisdale Avenue in Hamilton went up in flames overnight. Fire swept through the vacant duplex just before one a.m.  Arson is suspected.<br> Representatives of the fire marshalls office spent the day going over debris.
<hr>
<b>Child Abandoned</b><p>
<br> A 30-year-old woman is facing charges after a six-year-old child was found abandoned in Niagara Falls. Police say the girl was left home alone yesterday by her mother.<br> The child called 9-1-1 and police found her on the street in front of her home when they arrived.<br> The girl has been handed over to family and children's services.
<hr>
<b>Olson Parole</b><p>
<br> Infamous child killer Clifford Olson is now eligible to apply for a parole review and that's reopening the nightmare that began 15 years ago for the families of his 11 victims.<br> Olson hasn't publicly announced his plans, but it's expected he'll apply under criminal code section 7-45 -- the "faint hope clause."<br> It allows convicted killers to apply for early parole 15 years into their minimum 25-year prison sentences.<br> The faint hope clause is a huge issue right now with victims rights groups like caveat saying life should mean life with.
<hr>
<b>Most Wanted</b><p>
<br> A Canada-wide warrant has been issued for the man who tops the Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police service's most wanted list.<br> After serving time for crimes ranging from impaired driving to uttering forged documents, thirty-year-old Darrel Cranston was released on parole in May of this year.<br> He is now wanted for violating his parole conditions.<br> Darrel Cranston is white, six-foot-two, weighs 166 pounds, and has long brown hair and hazel eyes.<br> He also has numerous tattoos on his upper arms and abdomen.<br> Anyone with information on Darrel Cranston's whereabouts is asked to call Crime Stoppers at 522-TIPS.
<hr>
<b>Shipping Death</b><p>
<br> An investigation is underway into the death of a St. Catharines shipping company employee last week in Detroit.<br> Obidiah Blackwood, 35, was killed instantly when he fell about six metres into system rollers aboard "the enterprise."<br> There were no witnesses.<br> Blackwood had been an employee of Upper Lake Shipping since last June.  He was buried yesterday in his native province of Newfoundland.
<hr>
<b>Hamilton Doctors</b><p>
<br> It's no secret that doctors across Ontario are angry over government cutbacks that they say have effectively cut their pay over the last decade by one third.<br> In Niagara, and southwestern Ontario there have been threats of service withdrawal. But in Hamilton most doctors are saying the show must go on... Jamie West reports....
<i><br> And who would know better than Dr. Murray Enkin, a retired, 72 year old Hamilton obstetrician and member of the medical reform group who's helped deliver thousands of babies and written several books on the subject since 1947....<br>  Enter government health insurance and that number rose to 90 percent...<br>  The problem says Dr. Enkin is with the system itself...<br>  Family physician Dr. Walter (oh-sean-ik) says Hamilton doctors have a better line to the government than their Niagara and southwestern Ontario counterparts...<br>  He believe's that the rhetoric of of angry doctors is just that...<br>  </i>

<P>
