<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, August 9, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Greyhound Close Call
    <li>Mac/No OPSEU        
    <li>Pregnant Complaints 
    <li>Festival of Friends 
    <li>Local Jobs & Homes  
    <li>Dermawand           
    <li>Kitchener Raccoon   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Greyhound Close Call</b><p>
 There was more anger than fear ... for passengers on board a Greyhound Airlines jet, forced to make an emergency landing at Mount Hope Airport this morning. A relatively minor technical problem grounded the plane ... but as Scot Urquhart reports, the airline's handling of the issue ... was a public relations fiasco:
<i> After only a few minutes in the air, the troubled Greyhound 727 limped back into Hamilton Airport ... with fire crews trailing cautiously behind. 110 passengers were herded off the plane and into a flight lounge where they were then sequestered for several hours .... while this harried Greyhound representative tried to figure out what to do. What she was told by head office not to do, however, was speak to the media. <br>  
While mechanics tried to trace the problem ... the general manager of Ontario Flight-Craft came forward to answer a few questions. His company is a subsidiary of Greyhound's parent company, and services their planes. <br>  
It turned out an electrical malfunction caused a wiring harness to overheat. The pilot followed safety procedures, shut the engine down, and came home... making sure that no one got hurt. But there was still no information about what Greyhound intended to do with its flight schedule, or passengers. <br>  
We did find at least one, philosophical passenger. <br>  
In the end; Greyhound flew urgent priority passengers out of Toronto, on other airlines; set up alternative flights in the evening for some others, and arrange hotel accomodations for those who would have to wait until Saturday; to get to Kelowna. But none of that information, came out of Hamilton.  </i>
<hr>
<b>Mac/No OPSEU</b><p>
<br> Clerical workers at McMaster University have voted against being represented by the Ontario Public Service Employees Union.<br> Union organizers had said OPSEU representation would bring fairness to the workplace, but workers didn't buy their argument.  Less than 900 of the eligible employees voted on the certification. Of them, more than half said no.<br> David Wartman, McMaster's director of human resources says he's both surprised and pleased at the vote.  He adds contract talks with the staff association members will resume.
<hr>
<b>Pregnant Complaints</b><p>
<br> Hundreds of pregnant women in Ontario are scrambling to find doctors who will deliver their babies.<br> Dozens of obstetricians and other specialists are refusing to take on new patients in an escalating battle between doctors and the harris government over compensation.<br> Most of the calls are coming from southern Ontario especially the Toronto, Peel and Niagara regions.
<hr>
<b>Festival of Friends</b><p>
<br> At Gage Park, a musical extravaganza.<br> The annual Festival of Friends is underway and Dwight Ryan went to have a look.  <br> 
<i><br>  The magical sounds of taxi chain waft through the air of Hamilton's Gage Park.<br>  Scattered about, fans set to hear a full weekend of free entertainment.<br>  Hamilton's premier summer festival is underway again and runs through until Sunday night.<br>  The Festival of Friends offers something for everyone, especially kids.   <br>    But there's more...  <br>   The Festival of Friends continues through the weekend at Gage Park in Hamilton ..and its free.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Local Jobs & Homes</b><p>
<br> More people found work in Ontario last month. But the July unemployment figures do not show the dramatic drop that was hoped for by job seekers and economy watchers.<br> The unemployment rate in the province fell to 9.2 per cent from 9.5 per cent. <br>  In the past 13 months, 89-thousand new jobs have appeared in Ontario. <br>  Throughout the golden horseshoe the numbers look like this, in Hamilton the unemployment rate dropped to 7.4 from 7.9, St. Catharines and Niagara also fell 9.5 from 9.7 ....Toronto's unemployment rate bucked the trend and went up from 9.7 from 9.5. <br>   And another positive economic indicator today from Central Mortgage and Housing.  Their figures released this morning for Hamilton indicate starts of single family homes jumped 75 percent from 113 in 1995 ...to 198 in 1996, and thier best July for existing homes since July of 1988, analysts believe the housing market will stay healthy until at least the fall, even though housing starts nationwide are down.
<hr>
<b>Dermawand</b><p>
<br> A kitchener woman and her partner have engineered the latest in beauty care...<br> The technology has been around for years but is now finding a place in the consumer market ...<br>  And if you're looking to get an edge on acne or freshen up that tired looking face then this new product might be for you...<br>  Jamie West reports...
<i><br>  Lori South is treating her skin... and no this wand isn't from the starship enterprise....<br>  
Just take it from Dermawand president Christina Boves ...<br>  
Ozone...is electrified oxygen and is also thought to help slow down the aging process namely wrinkles. ....<br>  
Leslee Ferguson sells wrinkle cream and is a believer...<br>  
Dermawand is manufactured by Hamilton's Omega 5 Technologies for the consumer market...there's been a similar machine in use in estetics clinics for over two decades...<br>  
Heather Bridges trains estiticians and works with clients at Westdale's Luba Mera spa...she says the Dermawand is for real...<br>  Dermawand is CSA approved and is being distributed across Canada and the U.S.  In Canada it will retail for 119 dollars. <br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Kitchener Raccoon</b><p>
<br> A raccoon in Kitchener has learned a hard lesson about rummaging through people's garbage.<br> The furry little critter has been spotted running around town with a peanut butter jar stuck over his head.<br> Humane Society officials say they'd like to help, but they can't track the raccoon down.<br> They say the animal will likely lose weight because it can't eat, and hopefully the jar will fall off.<br> But if you should spot Rocky with a jar on his head, please report him to the authorities just in case.


<P>
