<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/08/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, August 8, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>




<ul>
    <li>Tennant Woes        
    <li>Clerk Shot Update   
    <li>Morgan Arrest       
    <li>Charlton Stabbing   
    <li>Body Recovered      
    <li>Brantford Drowning  
    <li>Quebec Relief       
    <li>Car Over            
    <li>Hiway Rangers       
    <li>Morrow re: Olympics 
    <li>Glad Days     
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Tennant Woes</b><p>
 Get ready for the hard times to come. That's the message being preparte for a tenants forum at the Rotary Self Help Centre in Hamilton tonight ... area housing groups say a package of new provincial legislation will bring nothing but bad news to renters in Ontario ... but landlords, and some analysts say, the picture may not be as bleak as it seems. Scot Urquhart reports:
<i> Andrea Horvath is preparing to go to battle. She is a housing advocate who says new provincial legislation on rent control and tenants rights will bring renters the worst of all worlds, in Ontario.
<br>  Andrea says the rental market in Hamilton is already too tight ... with vacancy rates slipping below two percent.
<br>  But this man disagrees. He is Arthur Weisz chairman of Effort Trust; with more than 10-thousand units, they are by far, the largest landlord in the region. <br>
Weisz points to the renters news where some landlords are offering incentives like one month free rent ... or no security deposit. He says half of his buildings are not even charging the maximum rent allowed by law ... because tenants simply won't pay it.
<br>  And this building superintendant agrees. Madeleine Castonguay says, she's got five vacant apartments at the moment.
<br>  Helen Hutton is a market analyst with CMHC. <br>  Hutton sees a slight rise in rents, and tighter vacancy rates ... but nothing like the late 80's ... when Hamilton had a vacancy rate approaching zero. </i>
<hr>
<b>Clerk Shot Update</b><p>
<br> And a Dundas variety store clerk is facing an uncertain future today.<br>  This after a botched robbery tuesday left 28 year old Khaled Mugber with a bullet in his chest and paralysed below the waist. Police say a masked robber probably armed with a powerful .357 magnum revolver shot the Farah Food Mart clerk. Four teenage boys have been charged with robbery after they were stopped in a stolen vehicle in downtown Hamilton a short time after the shooting. Police have now laid further charges, including attempted murder and weapons offences today. Doctors at Hamilton General Hospital are waiting for the victim's condition to improve before they can consider surgery to remove the bullet.
<hr>
<b>Morgan Arrest</b><p>
<br> Hamilton police have made an arrest into part of their investigation of the murder of Daniel Morgan. The Church of the Universe minister was found dead in his Wentworth Street apartment on October 19th, 1994. Detectives have determined that Morgan's apartment was broken into and that he was beaten and robbed. Investigators have now charged 37 year old Willaim Edward Davies of Hamilton with break and enter and theft in connection with the incident.
<hr>
<b>Charlton Stabbing</b><p>
<br> Hamilton Regional Police have taken one man into custody following a stabbing incident this afternoon.<br> Police say two men got into a drunken argument on the balcony of this apartment building at Charleton and Walnut streets.<br> In the ensuing fracas, both men suffered minor stab wounds.<br> Both were treated at the scene...one was taken into custody.  No charges have yet been laid.
<hr>
<b>Body Recovered</b><p>
<br> A body recovered from the lower Niagara River has been identified as that of 25 year old Salvatore Palmeri.<br> The Hamilton resident fell into the fast-flowing river last weekend while hiking with a friend.<br>  Palmeri's body was recovered near Queenston.<br>  An autopsy conducted in St. Catharines revealed that the victim died from accidental drowning.
<hr>
<b>Brantford Drowning</b><p>
<br> A 24-year-old Brantford man has drowned following a boating accident in the Simcoe area.<br> Provincial police say Allan Hoyt was tossed out of an inflatable boat last night on Rainbow Lake near Waterford.<br> Hoyt was pulled from the water and rushed to a hospital in Simcoe.<br> He was later transfered to Hamilton General, where he died.
<hr>
<b>Quebec Relief</b><p>
<br> Hamilton is still responding to the victims of the devastating floods in Quebec.<br> This morning more than 300 boxes of clothes and household items were loaded up to be transported to the Saugenay region.<br> The depot at Jackson Square began collecting donations two weeks ago.<br> The goods will be delivered to the flood victims by Laidlaw free of charge.
<hr>
<b>Car Over</b><p>
<br> Authorities are mulling over how to raise a car that had plunged into Tewes Falls near Dundas.<br> The license plates on the car were stolen from Burlington.<br> Police are looking for the vehicle's owner.<br> They say it could cost thousands to tow the car up the gorge.
<hr>
<b>Hiway Rangers</b><p>
<br> Accidents as a result of careless and innattentive driving are down.<br> The OPP's special Highway Rangers Unit is claiming a growing victory against the carnage on the golden horseshoe's busiest highways.<br> All this after photo radar was mothballed over a year ago...<br> Jamie West reports...
<i><br>  Senior constable Al Boyce isn't the lone ranger, and that's all right with him. He's happy to have 17 other partners helping to keep the highways of southern Ontario safe...<br>  
In the past year nearly 59-thousand motorists have been stopped after seeing the OPP cruiser in their rear view mirror..<br> 
Hundreds of charges have been laid for various infractions... 
<br>  Success to be sure even without photo radar...<br>  Other tools like in car video have cut down on not guilty pleas, which means more cash in the can for Mike Harris... And speed is still the number one problem... and that will cost a hundred and five...and 3 demerit points...<br>   
Meri Oliver operates the general store on Hwy 2 near Alberton. A regular stake out point for the highway rangers ... and if the rangers have it their way, there'll be a lot more peace and quiet on the highways. </i>
<hr>
<b>Morrow re: Olympics</b><p>
<br> And today at Hamilton City Hall mayor Morrow announced plans for a civic reception for area athletes who have just returned from competing in the '96 Centennial Olympics in Atlanta. The mayor hoped to have all athletes in attendence and invited everyone to participate by showing up at City Hall at 1pm Monday afternoon.
<hr>
<b>Glad Days </b><p>
<br> Glad Days are back in southern Ontario.<br> August 15, 16 and 17th a small army of volunteers will be hitting the malls in Hamilton and Burlington selling gladioli flowers to raise money for epilepsy.<br>  For three dollars a bunch or two for five dollars people can take home a bunch of gladness in aid of research for epilepsy.


<P>
