<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, August 7, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>



<ul>
    <li>Shooting Heroes     
    <li>Heat - Water Quality
    <li>Dhaliwal Found      
    <li>Niagara Rescue      
    <li>SIU Probe           
    <li>Lake Swim Update    
    <li>Labor Woes          
    <li>Mars                
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Shooting Heroes</b><p>
 The victim survived. Arrests have been made; and today, Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are crediting the actions of ordinary citizens for helping them to apprehend four suspects wanted in connection with a convenience store shooting in Dundas, last night. Scot Urquhart has more on that story:
<i><br>  The shooting of a convenience store clerk in this quiet Dundas location ... has shaken employees and neighbours alike. Although there are obvious efforts to make the store more secure ... the surveillance cameras inside were not running at the time of the shooting, according to store owner Aiman Ahboonewaruh,  he visited the 28 year old victim; Kahlid Mogber... in hospital this morning. <br>  But there may be reason to worry. Sources say Mogber is still carrying the bullet, and is paralysed from the waist down. Doctors don't know whether those injuries are permanent, or not. <br>  
Witnesses saw the gunman flee the store and head up this embankment to a waiting getaway car. Other neighbours had already taken the licence number, and called police. <br>  
That taxi driver was Rick Ritchie. He happened to be stopped for a light at the corner of King and Main in Dundas; just as the suspect vehicle turned the corner in front of him. He called in the location; and trailed the car into Hamilton; all the while providing police, with a steady stream of information.<br>  
Does he feel like a hero? <br>  
In what police describe as a high risk take down at Hunter and James; the suspect vehicle collided with a police cruiser. Four young offenders were then taken into custody without further incident.</i>
<hr>
<b>Heat - Water Quality</b><p>
<br>  Its the hottest day of the year and many people are taking to area beaches to cool off.<br>  But, the humid conditions can cause high bacteria levels making the lake unsafe for swimming.<br>  As Dwight Ryan reports, regional officials are keeping a close eye on the water quality and so far its A-okay.  <br>  
<i><br>  Hot, hazy and humid.  Its weather like this that can make this great lake not so great.<br>  
Its weather like this that brings Mike Brady to the shore of Lake Ontario to see if its safe to swim.<br>  Brady from the Hamilton Regional Health Unit takes samples from the beach for study at the lab. They're looking for e-coli bacteria...a product of human waste.<br>  
Its just as disgusting as it sounds and it can make you feel rotten...      <br>  
Surprisingly warnings have not been posted this year at Hamilton beaches.  Though the water's cold, its reasonably clean.<br>  But not everyone likes the idea of swimming in it.      Just remember, it can make you sick.<br>  </i>
<hr>
<b>Dhaliwal Found</b><p>
<br>  Yesterday we reported on a missing 14 year old boy.  Nirmal Dhaliwal hadn't been seen since saturday when he was dropped off in the Guelph Line - Driftwood Drive area of Burlington to canvass for newspaper subscriptions. Halton Police today announced the boy has been found in Montreal and has been returned to his home.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Rescue</b><p>
<br> A tourist from Ohio is lucky to be alive after he tumbled down the gorge in Niagara Falls Monday night.<br> Twenty year old Mathew Shears and a companion had fallen asleep near Hubbard's Point when he rolled over and fell 20 metres down the rock face.<br> He had been lying there more than 12 hours before somebody on the US side of the river noticed him and called police.<br> Shear's in hospital with undetermined injuries.
<hr>
<b>SIU Probe</b><p>
<br> The province's special investigations unit will probe the death of a man who struggled with police in St. Catharines.<br> Police went to a home early sunday morning where a semi-conscious person had reportedly overdosed on drugs.<br> Niagara Region Police say the man struggled with police officers before being transported to hospital where he was later pronounced dead.<br> An autopsy suggested 34-year-old Beverly Ingraham died of a pulmonary edema, a condition in which excess fluid accumulates in body tissues.<br> The SIU is called in on any death or serious injury involving police.
<hr>
<b>Lake Swim Update</b><p>
<br> In spite of the near perfect conditions, Toronto detective John Munro has failed in his bid to swim Lake Ontario. Swim spokesman Dave Haggith says Munro developed a sore shoulder early today and was pulled from the water around 5:15 this morning -- just five kilometres short of his goal. The Toronto cop left Niagara On-the-Lake early yesterday, in a bid to raise money for an anti-youth violence program called chill-power.
<hr>
<b>Labor Woes</b><p>
<br> Provincial cutbacks may soon take a toll on labor relations in both Hamilton- Wentworth and Niagara.<br> 
Municipal employees in both regions and in the city of Hamilton are on the verge of striking against proposed contract concessions.<br> 
Concilliation efforts in Niagara have broken down and CUPE members there are awaiting a "no board" report that could put them in a 
legal strike position before the end of the month.<br> Civic workers in Hamilton- Wentworth and the city of Hamilton plan their own strike vote next Friday.  They're expected to take a hard line against proposed wage cuts reported to be in the five percent range.
<hr>
<b>Mars</b><p>
<br> For centuries earthlings have tried to find life on Mars, but the first study to present serious evidence of microbes on the red planet is being denounced quickly by other scientists.<br> A group of scientists with NASA claim to have found in a rock from Mars, organic compounds they say were deposited by primitive life forms, before the rock was blasted into space and sent on a 15-million year voyage to Earth.<br> The rock apparently landed in the antarctic about 13-thousand years ago and was discovered in 1984.<br> Interestingly enough, Hamilton's McMaster University holds one of only twelve samples of that original martian rock.<br> But reaction to the findings in the scientific community, ranges from cautious optimism to outright disbelief.<br> NASA says it plans several more mars projects for further study.


<P>
