<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, August 6, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>


<ul>
    <li>Neighborhood Safety 
    <li>Air Quality - Heat  
    <li>Stolen Explosives   
    <li>Boy Missing         
    <li>Baby Pool           
    <li>Niagara Gorge       
    <li>Lincoln Crash Update
    <li>Stelco Erie         
    <li>Munro Swim          
    <li>CNIB- Japanese   
</ul>
<hr>
<b>Neighborhood Safety</b><p>
<br> Its national "night out" day. Across the nation, tens of thousands of people will gather in neigbourhoods to give a "going away party" to crime and drugs.<br> Dwight Ryan has the story.  <br>  sot
<i><br>  At Carter Park in Hamilton's Stinson neighbourhood, there is not much to fear.<br>  A neighbourhood that was once plagued with drugs, crime and prostitution is on the mend. Residents don't mind walking the streets.  Their parks are safe.<br>  Like many other areas, the Stinson neighbourhood is working hand in hand with police to clean up its image.  And residents welcome the sight of police cruising their streets.  <br>  The Stinson neighbourhood in Hamilton is one of thousands across the country that will hold night out festivals this week.<br>  A going-away part for crime and drugs.  <br>  While the night out festivals will be held this week, the work to clean up canada's crime ridden communities continues throughout the year.<br> </i>
<hr>
<b>Air Quality - Heat</b><p>
<br> This is day two of what is expected to be at least four days of poor air quality in southern Ontario.<br> The first summer heatwave of 96, is making breathing difficult for those with on- going respiratory problems, and it's at very least a source of aggravation for people considered to be in good health.  Jamie West reports...

<i><br>  Hot enough to fry an egg on the road.... maybe not quite ... but in fact still cool enough for these seasoned heat handlers to be hard at it...<br>   A thick layer of ground level ozone has topped the 50 level on the official scale...in short that's bad...<br>  For most people in good health... a good hankerchief and lots of water will get you through...but a strong heat and pollution cocktail mixed from a lot of gas powered motors, can be deadly to the very young and the not so young...<br> But despite increased numbers of asthma cases in Hamilton ...there's very little evidence that points directly to air pollution as a cause.</I>

<hr>
<b>Stolen Explosives</b><p>
<br> Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are asking for your help in solving an overnight break-in at a Dundas construction site.<br> As Dwight Ryan reports, explosives were stolen...and police say they are extemely lethal.  <br>  
<i><br>  Sometime during the early morning hours, thieves raided this dundas construction site. <br>  
Taken in the heist, a number of cylinders containing a potentially dangerous substance.   <br>    
If you have any information concerning the theft, call Hamilton Regional Police at 522-4925 or Crime Stoppers at 522-TIPS.</i>
<hr>
<b>Boy Missing</b><p>
<br> Halton Police are stymied by the disappearance of a 14-year old.<br>  Nirmal Dhaliwal hasn't been seen since Saturday when he was dropped off in the Guelph Line - Driftwood Drive area of Burlington to canvass for newspaper subscriptions.<br>  Dhaliwal, who lives on Derry Road in Mississauga, is described as an east indian male with short black hair and black eyes.  He's 5-feet, six inches tall and weighs 125 pounds.  When last seen, dhaliwal was wearing a grey t-shirt and light-colored pants.<br>  Anyone with information concerning this missing youth is asked to call Halton Police.
<hr>
<b>Baby Pool</b><p>
A 14-month-old Burlington boy is in critical condition in hospital after nearly drowning in a backyard pool. Jordan Belisaro was unconscious yesterday when he was pulled from the water. A neighbor, James Dring, responded to cries for help from the family and vaulted over a fence. He applied CPR until paramedics arrived. Police say Jordan is now breathing on his own, but remains unconscious.
<hr>
<b>Niagara Gorge</b><p>
<br> The condition of a Romanian man, injured while trying to climb down into the Niagara Gorge, has improved. Nicolae (krow-kan-ess-kue) is now listed in serious condition at the Erie County Medical Centre.  He suffered severe head and internal injuries Sunday after falling to the bottom of the US side of the gorge.<br> Officials say he fell after coming to the end of a clothes-line-like rope he was using.<br> US police say they are not sure if they will be laying charges or turning (krow-ken-ess-kue) over to immigration officials.
<hr>
<b>Lincoln Crash Update</b><p>
An early morning accident in the town of Lincoln yesterday has now claimed a life. Niagara Regional Police say 24 year old Phyllis Andrews, a visitor from Trinidad, succumbed to her injuries on Monday. She was one of six people taken to area hospitals as a result of the two car collision on 15th Street in lincoln. Police are continuing their investigation.
<hr>
<b>Stelco Erie</b><p>
<br>   Nearly one-thousand steelworkers employed at Stelco's Lake Erie Steel in Nanticoke have ratified a new contract. Eighty-two per cent of the workers who voted yesterday cast their ballots in favor of the tentative deal, reached last week. The new contract provides a two dollar-an-hour raise and pension improvements. Stelco has also promised to expand the Nanticoke plant, creating 30 new jobs.
<hr>
<b>Munro Swim</b><p>
<br> A toronto police detective is attempting to swim across Lake Ontario.<br> John Munro, 45, the husband of marathon swimmer Vicki Keith, stepped into Lake Ontario at Niagara on the Lake early this morning.<br> Munro says conditions are perfect. He says he is expecting a sunny day with calm water. Munro says it will take up to 24 hours to finish his swim at Vicki Keith Point on Toronto's waterfront.<br> The Toronto cop is raising money for chill-power, an education program aimed at preventing youth violence.  
<hr>
<b>CNIB - Japanese</b><p>
<br> Some special visitors for the CNIB in Hamilton this afternoon.<br> A group of university students from our twin city, Fukuyama, Japan, toured the facility and its transitional training centre.<br> The centre is in the midst of a capital campaign trying to raise 1.8 million dollars for much-needed renovations.


<P>
