<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 08/02/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, August 2, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Nanticoke Expansion 
<LI>Seniors Spat 
<LI>Stabbed Boy 
<LI>Drowning 
<LI>St. Kitts Fire 
<LI>Caribana Niagara 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Nanticoke Expansion </H3>

<P>
A ten percent increase in wages and a thirty five percent hike
in pension benefits. These are just two aspects of a labour agreement
reached between the United Steelworkers Union and Stelco's Lake
Erie Works. As Dwight Ryan reports, the historic agreement could
lead Stelco to go ahead with a massive expansion of its Nanticoke
plant. 
<P>
<I>Its a deal. A thousand steelworkers at Stelco's Lake Erie Works
will vote Monday on a contract that offers better wages, pensions
and bonuses. As well new jobs will be created as part of the four
year pact. </I>
<P>
<I>The trend-setting agreement follows more than a year of negotiations
in which the union says Stelco was more interested in taking than
giving. </I>
<P>
<I>In a small town, good news travels fast. The mayor is delighted.
Retailers in the city of Nanticoke, which includes Port Dover,
have seen some tough times. Times they hope are behind them for
good. </I>
<P>
<I>Steelworkers are expected to overwhelmingly accept the new
contract agreement. Word on the plant expansion is expected soon
after.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Seniors Spat </H3>

<P>
Call it grey power ... a wrinkled revolution is underway, at a
Burlington seniors' centre where some members are refusing to
pay a user fee, for the use of the facility. Scot Urquhart has
more on that: 
<P>
<I>A buck a day to play.. may not seem like much ... but it's
got these seniors fighting mad. It was the first day on the job
for Centre Director Cathy Lamb ... she says the euchre players
are the only group that refuses to pay the user fee. </I>
<P>
<I>But Cathy says the seniors are not helping to keep costs down.
But this angry senior points to a prison system where recreation
is free ..... and where will the seniors go ... if they lose?
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Stabbed Boy </H3>

<P>
A four-year-old Collingwood boy who was stabbed last weekend has
been released from a St. Catharines hospital. The child, whose
identity is being withheld, was treated for a punctured lung.
He's still suffering from breathing problems but is expected to
make a full recovery. 
<P>
The boy was visiting St. Catharines when he was attacked by a
seven year-old. The attacker is too young to face charges and
family and child services is forbidden to discuss the case. The
four year old is expected to get psychological counseling to deal
with the trauma. 
<HR>

<H3>Drowning </H3>

<P>
A 37 year old man is missing and presumed drowned after falling
into the Welland Canal in Port Colborne. Police say two men were
fishing off a dam last night when one of them tripped and fell
about three metres into the water. His friend ran for help. 
<P>
Emergency officials searched but found no trace. His name has
not yet been released. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Fire </H3>

<P>
Three people are in hospital after a suspicious fire in St. Catharines
last night. Niagara's arson task force and the Ontario Fire Marshall's
Office are probing the cause of the fire, that completely engulfed
the house. 
<P>
56 year old Sheila Mitchell and 26 year old Ian Page were sent
to Hamilton General Hospital in serious condition. 25 year old
Scott Page is also listed in serious condition. 
<HR>

<H3>Caribana Niagara </H3>

<P>
Niagara Falls is hoping the main event of Toronto's annual Caribana
Festival will help them out. Tomorrow's 10-hour street party which
includes a parade featuring elaborate and colorful costumes, is
drawing hundreds of American tourist and Niagara Falls officials
hope the Caribana visitors will also boost what has been a disappointing
tourist season so far in the city. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian financial markets have changed dramatically because of
yet more economic data from the U.S. that indicates American interest
rates will remain stable. 
<P>
Investors aggressively bought Canadian stocks and bonds today
as interest rates on government bonds dropped sharply. 
<P>
Mortgage rates will fall tomorrow. 

<P>
