<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/31/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, July 31, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Welfare Reasons 
<LI>Crop Losses 
<LI>Squeegee Kids 
<LI>Huge Shipment 
<LI>Steelworkers Deal 
<LI>Canoe Race 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Welfare Reasons </H3>

<P>
Where have they gone? Thousands of welfare recipients have left
the system since the Tory government cut benefits last fall ...
but no one seems to know exactly what happened to them. A Hamilton
study now gives at least part of the answer ... as Scot Urquhart
reports: 
<P>
<I>The exodus is on. More than two thousand recipients left the
welfare system in Hamilton Wentworth between October 1995, and
January 1996 ... but where did they go? The Social Planning and
Research Council survey says that roughly 80 percent of those
who left welfare did so, because they, or someone in their family
found work; or went back to school. And most said their lives
were marginally better ... without welfare. </I>
<P>
<I>Why does the food bank see things differently than the planning
council does? Well one reason ... may be the relatively small
size of the study sample. Susan West admits that it was tough
to track former welfare recipients ... and some of them couldn't
be found at all: and although recipients who are working now may
be saving the system money in the short run ... the longer term
indicated a disturbing trend.</I>
<P>
<I>Susan West agrees the study is not the final answer on welfare.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Crop Losses </H3>

<P>
Farmers in Ontario are taking a big financial hit thanks to the
weather. A cold, rainy spring is resulting in smaller crop yields.
and a fungus is destroying much of the province's wheat crop.
Dwight Ryan reports from Guelph. 
<P>
<I>A dark cloud hangs over Ontario's agricultural industry. Losses
to farmers could total 90 million dollars and the weather is to
blame. </I>
<P>
<I>Peter Hannam is a partner in Woodrill Farms near Guelph. He
says prices will remain high because of the cold wet weather.
</I>
<P>
<I>Professor Rick Upfold is with the University of Guelph. Fusarium
causes toxins which result in vomiting in humans and reproductive
problems in animals. With wheat harvesting about to begin, its
clear the fungus is widespread. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Squeegee Kids </H3>

<P>
They're on the streets and they're looking for you....more precisely
your car and it's dirty windshield. They're called <I>squeegee
kids </I>and have been a fixture on the streets of Toronto, Vancouver,
Montreal and Ottawa. Now they're hitting the streets of downtown
Hamilton as we hear in this report from Jamie West... 
<P>
<I>This occupation came out of New York City and has become a
regular part of the downtown landscape in several Canadian cities.
Jean Paul is sixteen and lives at the Good Shepherd Centre ...
he and his partners work together...and share the earnings...to
buy things like pizza and cigarettes ... and personal items like
soap, deodorant and toothbrushes.</I>
<P>
<I>The police are trying to find a way to reasonably deal with
the situation.... but just 30 minutes after we arrived so did
the police.</I>
<P>
<I>Jean-Paul told us he thinks about his future, he wants to go
back to school and one day become a carpenter.... but for now
he says he will continue to sponge a living off the windshields
of downtown motorists. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Huge Shipment </H3>

<P>
A huge shipment made it's way into Hamilton harbour this afternoon.
The sight of a 5 storey high storage tank, caught the eyes of
a lot of people near the Burlington Canal and lift-bridge. 
<P>
The tank was being towed from Oshawa en route to Pier 23 for delivery
to Canada-West Indies Molasses. The company will use the tank
to store canola oil. 
<P>
McKeo Marine says it took nearly 12 hours to make the journey.

<HR>

<H3>Steelworkers Deal </H3>

<P>
A tentative settlement was reached earlier today between the United
Steelworkers Local 8782 and Lake Erie Steel Co. Local 8782's president
said details of the agreement will not be released until union
members have had an opportunity to review terms of the deal, that
will be Friday at 11am in the Port Dover Community Centre, with
a vote scheduled for Monday, Aug. 5th. 
<HR>

<H3>Canoe Race </H3>

<P>
It's no secret that tensions have been simmering at times between
police and members of the native community. But as Lauran Sabourin
reports this afternoon members of both sides took a paddle and
canoe into the Grand River in hopes of smoothing these troubled
waters. 
<P>
<I>Their paddling their way to a better understanding. One hundred
twenty five law enforcement officers. One hundred twenty five
members of southern Ontario's native communities. </I>
<P>
<I>Constable Brian Urie is paired up with Jackie Samush. While
relations between natives and police officers have improved she
still remembers the stinging racist remarks. And the only contact
many native youth have had with police is over the hood of a car.
</I>
<P>
<I>For two hours this afternoon the canoeists meandered down the
Grand River from Paris to Brantford. The race may look more like
a recreational outing, but to the participants it means much more.
In the last four years the canoe race has grown from 40 participants
to this year's 250. </I>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

