<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, July 30, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Rolider Follow
<LI>University Enrollment 
<LI>Selkirk Fire I.D. 
<LI>More Mall Murder 
<LI>Native Artifacts 
<LI>Shift Work Pt. 2 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Rolider Follow </H3>

<P>
The program is gone, but the controversy continues over a defunct
aversive therapy program for brain injured patients, at Chedoke
McMaster Hospital. The family of one former patient says, they
will now pursue criminal charges because their son may have been
treated without proper consent. Scot Urquhart reports: 
<P>
<I>It's not just what they did to him ... but whether they had
the right to do it ... at all. Diana Martin is Robbie Thompson's
mother. She says she's had power of attorney over Robbie since
1989 ... and had to produce that document to get Robbie admitted
to the brain injury clinic at Chedoke McMaster in 1991. She says
she never signed a consent form for Robbie's treatment. And the
only document produced by the hospital to show consent so far
... is one signed by Robbie; that is missing at least four signatures.
</I>
<P>
<I>Diana Martin says, that issue of informed consent has now led
her to the police. </I>
<HR>

<H3>University Enrollment </H3>

<P>
Many Ontario universities are increasing enrollments, despite
the fact that fewer students are applying. With increased tuition
fees, many high school students are opting for college, or just
looking for a job. 
<P>
But, universities have to make up for lower funding from Queen's
Park. Reporter Dwight Ryan wondered if standards are being lowered
in order to accept more applicants. 
<P>
<I>Across Ontario the number of applicants for full time first
year studies is down about one and a half percent. That follows
a sharp drop of more than five percent just a year ago. </I>
<P>
<I>Still acceptances are up.. about four percent. At Hamilton's
McMaster University, president Peter George says applications
are off by about seven percent. Enrollments however are up marginally.
</I>
<P>
<I>With higher tuition fees, some universities are accepting more
students just to cover cuts from Queens Park. Dr. George feels
tuition fees will increase for a few more years, then level off.
But do students feel they're getting their money's worth? </I>
<P>
<I>While some feel a university education is just for the rich,
McMaster hopes to help struggling students by raising money in
the community. Through the new student opportunity trust fund,
moneys raised by the school will be matched by the province.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Selkirk Fire I.D. </H3>

<P>
The victim of a fatal cottage fire in Selkirk Sunday night has
identified. A post mortem shows 69 year old Lorraine Robertson
of Stoney Creek died of smoke inhalation. 
<P>
The retired accountant was alone in the cottage when it was engulfed
in flames. The Ontario Fire Marshall's office is still investigating,
trying to pin down a cause. 
<HR>

<H3>More Mall Murder </H3>

<P>
Two more arrests have been made in the murder of a Hamilton teenager
at Limeridge Mall back in May. 18 year old Roberto Oliveira died
from injuries after an attack at the mall's theatre entrance.

<P>
A 15 year old was charged with second degree murder shortly after
the incident. Now, 18 year old Deel Yelda of Hamilton and a 17
year old face the same charge. 
<HR>

<H3>Native Artifacts </H3>

<P>
An important archaeological find has been announced in Brantford.
Archaeologists have discovered artifacts from an Indian settlement
said to be 1200 years old. Dwight Ryan has that. 
<P>
<I>Archaeologists work in the woods just metres away from the
Grand River. Their routine sight check next to the Brantford Water
Treatment Plant has turned up amazing treasures from Ontario's
past.</I>
<P>
<I>Brantford's PUC director Bob Patrick commissioned the archaeological
study. Topsoil examinations now will lead to a full archaeological
dig in the weeks ahead. Artifacts will then probably go on display
at the Woodland Indian Cultural Centre. Once they're removed,
it will no longer be considered an archaeological site and construction
on the water treatment plant can continue. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Shift Work Pt. 2 </H3>

<P>
Yesterday on First Edition, we began a two part look at shift-work.
While the time off may be great, the pitfalls of working around
the clock are many. Today we look at the role good nutrition and
exercise play in helping your body keep up. Annette Hamm reports.

<P>
<I>That's a trap many shift workers fall into. If you don't work
when everyone else does, you tend not to eat at regular times.
Tom and Maggie McKittrick, both HW Regional Police officers, know
the nutritional pitfalls of working unusual hours. </I>
<P>
<I>Many shift-workers tend to develop gastrointestinal and digestive
problems. A cup of coffee may be the energy boost most shift workers
reach for, but nutritionists warn not to go overboard. Limit yourself
to no more than four cups a day. </I>
<P>
<I>Maintaining a regular eating schedule is also important. For
example, it's recommended shift workers eat breakfast-type foods
upon waking, no matter what time of day it is. </I>
<P>
<I>As police officers, the McKittricks are expected to keep up
an exercise routine. They find it helps them sleep better and
gives them a chance to catch up with each other. Fitness experts
say any shift worker can benefit from exercise. more and more
employers, like Proctor and Gamble in Hamilton, are holding information
sessions to help shift-workers and their families. They realize
fit, well rested and well adjusted employees are more productive
and may be better able to make decisions.</I> 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

