<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, July 29, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Fatal Fires 
<LI>Mac Staff Vote 
<LI>St. Kitts Stabbing 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Shift Work 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Fatal Fires </H3>

<P>
Two people have died as the result of weekend house fires. Crews
were called to a Brantford home early this morning where the body
of a man was discovered. 
<P>
Hours earlier, a woman perished when her Lake Erie cottage went
up in flames. Dwight Ryan has the story. 
<P>
<I>Investigators have yet to determine what caused an early morning
fire that claimed the life of a Brantford man. Emergency crews
were called to the house just after four o'clock Monday morning...
family and friends gathered as investigators went about their
work. </I>
<P>
<I>40 year-old Bob Allison has been identified as the victim.
Allison and his family were in the process of moving at the time
of the inferno. A family cat also perished. </I>
<P>
<I>Hours earlier, firefighters from Fisherville and Selkirk were
called to an inferno on the Lake Erie shoreline. A 69 year-old
Stoney Creek woman perished. No cause for the blaze has yet been
determined. </I>
<P>
<I>Fisherville volunteer firefighter Fred Elfner was the first
on the scene. Homeowner Sheila Yates has nothing but praise for
the volunteer firefighters. </I>
<P>
<I>Family members of the victim have not yet all been notified.
Her name has not yet been released</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Mac Staff Vote </H3>

<P>
The union says it wants to bring fairness to the workplace ...
but at least one staff member at McMaster University, is crying
foul. A certification drive to unionize clerical workers at Mac
will probably come to a ballot later this week... at a time when
many staff members won't even be around to vote on their own future.
Scot Urquhart reports: 
<P>
<I>Summertime at Mac. A time when there are probably more flowers
than students on campus ... a time when staff crawls out of the
ivory tower ... and takes off, for summer vacation. And that's
what worries this woman. Anne Taylor is an administrative secretary
who will be asked later this week, to vote for a union, that she
doesn't want. Anne says the fix is in ... OPSEU is trying to pull
a fast one; when staff members are on vacation.</I>
<P>
<I>David Wartman is the director of human resources at Mac. </I>
<P>
<I>Connie Huziak is the OPSEU organizer heading the union drive
at Mac.</I>
<P>
<I>Then why are they holding the vote now? Provincial legislation
requires a certification vote to be held within five days of an
application; and despite the questions about this vote; David
Wartman says, it will probably take place on Thursday August first,
as planned.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Stabbing </H3>

<P>
A four-year-old St. Catharines boy, stabbed in the back during
the weekend, is recovering in hospital. Officials at the Chedoke-McMaster
Medical Centre in Hamilton say the boy's condition has been upgraded
to good. 
<P>
He was rushed to the hospital with life-threatening injuries on
Saturday after being attacked with a knife. A seven-year-old boy,
not related to the victim, is the prime suspect in the case. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Philip Environmental of Hamilton today announced it plans to accept
an offer to sell its solid waste business for 118 million dollars
U.S. 
<P>
Stock prices in Canada and the U.S. moved lower, the dollar strengthened,
interest yields on Canadian government bonds moved higher. 
<HR>

<H3>Shift Work </H3>

<P>
According to recent statistics, about 20 percent of Canadian jobs
require workers to work odd hours ....shifts of 8 to twelve hours
that start at all hours of the day and night. Its called shift-work
and shift-work has been linked with a variety of health problems
and safety issues. But there are steps you can take to lessen
the impact of working around the clock. Annette Hamm has this
report. 
<P>
<I>Like one out of every 5 Canadian workers, Tom McKittrick doesn't
have a 9 to 5 job. Neither does his wife, Maggie. Tom works ten
hour shifts with the Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police canine
unit ... half a week days, half a week nights. </I>
<P>
<I>Maggie McKittrick is also a police officer. She works ten hour
shifts, afternoons and nights every other week. Both agree the
key to keeping their schedules, and themselves, sane is to not
let the effects of shift-work get the best of them. Getting enough
sleep is the first hurdle most workers like Tom and Maggie have
to get over. </I>
<P>
<I>Dr. Jamie MacFarlane runs the sleep disorders clinic at the
University of Toronto. He says the first rule of sleeping on shift
is that there are no rules. You have to experiment which type
of sleep makes you feel best ... whether you nap or not, whether
you go to bed right after you come home or wait a few hours. Just
make sure sleep doesn't consume your life. </I>
<P>
<I>For most night workers, that low point hits between 3 and 5
in the morning. The corporate nurse at Hamilton's Proctor and
Gamble plant agrees that's a time many workers there complain
about. </I>
<P>
<I>Tom and Maggie McKittrick have managed to work out their sleep
schedules, largely through family co-operation. </I>
<P>
<I>Coming up tomorrow, we'll tell you how proper exercise and
nutrition can help your body cope with shift-work. </I>

<P>
