<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, July 26, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Mike Strange Fight 
<LI>Golf Ball Divers 
<LI>Housing Help Centre 
<LI>Drowning I.D. 
<LI>Jewelry Robbery 
<LI>Sub Shop Heist 
<LI>Musk Sniffs 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Mike Strange Fight </H3>

<P>
They're celebrating in Niagara Falls tonight. And it's a strange
one. Boxer Mike Strange made it to the quarter finals at the Olympic
games in Atlanta this afternoon. He won a second round bout handily
over his Armenian opponent. 
<P>
Strange now advances to the quarter finals, and as Lauran Sabourin
reports his friends and family back in Niagara Falls were savoring
the victory at Mike's neighbourhood bar. 
<P>
<I>The songs came easily once this crowd realized that Mike Strange
was going to win his second bout. But only minutes earlier Strange's
friends couldn't bare to watch the start of this fight. A fight
that initially put Strange's Armenian opponent in the lead. </I>
<P>
<I>Mike's brother Jim watched the nine minute battle holding his
breath. Strange won gold at the Commonwealth Games last year.
This was expected to be an early victory. Late into the second
round Strange came back. landing clean blows that scored points
with the judges. </I>
<P>
<I>Derek McLatchie is a long time friend of Mike's and co-owner
of the bar. He knows Mike Strange as a determined and disciplined
fighter. A young man who has the confidence to win. </I>
<P>
<I>The round was over in minutes. But the partying at the Highland
Tap Bar will continue at least until Strange's next bout. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Golf Ball Divers </H3>

<P>
It's no secret that the business of golf is very lucrative and
the sport continues to grow in popularity, but questions about
recycling golf balls from water traps are being raised after the
second death in a month, of a trained scuba diver at a Toronto
area course. 
<P>
As Jamie west reports...there's a big demand for used golf balls
but some retrieval companies may be getting in over their heads...

<P>
<I>It's all about making a buck and saving a buck. Golfers gobble
up experienced balls by the dozen. </I>
<P>
<I>The Ministry of Labour has now requested that retrieval companies
only use machines to retrieve balls at least for the time being...
Jim Sara is an experienced diver and the course superintendent
at Carlisle Golf and Country Club...he says the looks of these
ponds can be deceiving. </I>
<P>
<I>Carlisle contracts out the retrieval of golf balls to an independent
Toronto area company called Nearly New...in exchange for balls
to re-sell in their pro shop. At the moment there are no regulations
governing who retrieval companies can and cannot hire to dive.</I>
<P>
<I>Yesterday's tragic death of experienced diver Murray Alcock
in less than two metres of water has surprised course operators
but not Rick Bullas a dive master who has strapped on the tank
over one hundred and fifty times. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Housing Help Centre </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Centre's Dave Christopherson is calling for an inquest
into the death earlier this month of a homeless man in a July
third fire that engulfed a downtown abandoned building. 
<P>
He also had some choice words today for the Harris government's
decision to yank the funding rug from beneath the Housing Help
Centre. Anthony Pooley has the details. 
<P>
<I>Dave Christopherson's provincial riding takes in Hamilton's
downtown... where by far the largest number of the city's homeless
find temporary refuge from the elements wherever they can. Abandoned
buildings are favored by those with nowhere else to go... and
it was in this such structure that 29-year-old transient Donald
Dupuis met his death in a fire three weeks ago. </I>
<P>
<I>So today... the Hamilton Centre MPP called for an inquest into
his death. Earlier this week, a local organization that helps
those who need it find housing fell victim to the Harris government's
cost-cutting ax ... as Hamilton's Housing Help Centre announced
it was closing it's doors in the face of lost provincial funding...
representing about 80-percent of its operating budget... a major
slap in the collective face of the homeless.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Drowning I.D. </H3>

<P>
An autopsy performed at Welland Country General Hospital has confirmed
that man who was found dead in a Welland backyard swimming pool
earlier this week did drown and his death has been ruled accidental.
48-year-old Kenneth Roland was from grand bend. 
<HR>

<H3>Jewelry Robbery </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police are looking for two thugs who
held up a mountain jewelry store. Police say two white males scooped
two cases from Hummingbird Jewelers on Upper James over the dinner
hour. A large amount of gold was stolen. 
<P>
Store staff were unable to provide any further description of
the robbers. They escaped in a stolen car that was later recovered.

<HR>

<H3>Sub Shop Heist </H3>

<P>
And police are seeking a lone black male who held up a mountain
submarine shop last night. Police say the thief entered the Mr.
Submarine shop on Upper Gage shortly before ten o'clock demanding
cash. He indicated he had a gun, although no weapon was seen.

<P>
He's described as a male, black, in his late 20's ...about five
feet, 11 inches tall. At the time of the heist, he was wearing
a green and orange jacket with a black scarf over his face. The
suspect escaped with an undetermined amount of cash. 
<HR>

<H3>Musk Sniffs </H3>

<P>
Last week it was police dog Rocky. This week's canine hero is
Musk. The Revenue Canada detector dog sniffed out a haul of marijuana
during a search of a vehicle trying to enter Canada at the Fort
Erie border. It was contained in a number of heavily-packaged
bundles, two taped to the driver's ankles, five others inside
the vehicle. Estimated street value of the cache: almost 11-thousand
dollars. 
<P>
Richard Alfonso, 25 of Toronto is charged with importing a narcotic
into Canada and possession for the purpose of trafficking. Last
year, Revenue Canada's 29 detector dogs helped find more than
46 million dollars worth of illicit drugs. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

