<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, July 25, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton - Floods 
<LI>Welland Drowning 
<LI>Nusca - Fatal 
<LI>Pyro Punks 
<LI>Condom Bomber 
<LI>Tainted Appeal 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>GO - Business 
<LI>Keyes - Marine 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton - Floods </H3>

<P>
The city of Hamilton has launched an Olympic effort to help flood
victims in Quebec. Mayor Bob Morrow this morning announced an
initial fundraising target of 150 thousand dollars, significant
in that this is the city's 150th birthday. Lauran Sabourin has
more. 
<P>
<I>The province of Quebec has established a 200 million dollar
fund to help the devastated communities rebuild. But it's expected
the damage figure will be much higher. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton wants to send more than good wishes. The city has
set an initial fund raising goal of 150 thousand dollars. In the
last 48 hours the Hamilton Red Cross has been overwhelmed with
calls to help. All of the major banks have set up flood assistance
accounts. </I>
<P>
<I>Other companies are also doing their part. Mobile Cartage is
collecting clothing and other goods that will be transported to
the affected area. If you want to drop items off you can bring
it to their warehouse at 354 Nash Road north in Hamilton. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Welland Drowning </H3>

<P>
An autopsy was scheduled today to try to determine how and why
a man died in a pool at a home in Welland. The 48 year old man,
who had been visiting the Edgar Street house, was found in the
backyard pool yesterday afternoon, floating face down. 
<HR>

<H3>Nusca-Fatal </H3>

<P>
A car truck crash early this morning has claimed the life of a
Hamilton man: 31-year-old Joseph Nusca. It happened at King and
Sanford in east Hamilton when a pickup truck ran a red light colliding
with a car. The truck then flipped onto its side and slid into
a Hydro pole. 
<HR>

<H3>Pyro Punks </H3>

<P>
Police and fire officials in Hamilton are investigating a number
of overnight arson fires. The blazes in garbage containers and
construction equipment caused little damage but kept firefighters
in north-central Hamilton hopping. In all, eight fires were set.

<P>
Witnesses say a group of teenagers, six boys and three girls,
were seen fleeing from the fires. 
<HR>

<H3>Condom Bomber </H3>

<P>
A late night prank has resulted in serious charges against a Hamilton
girl: mischief endangering life and assault with a weapon. Police
say the teenager was throwing water filled condoms from a 12th
floor balcony in Hamilton's northeast end. One of the projectiles
struck a woman on the hip and soaked her 18 month old daughter.

<HR>

<H3>Tainted Appeal </H3>

<P>
Hamilton AIDS activists say they are simply running out of time.
Disappointment and outrage tonight over the actions of the Canadian
Red Cross. It wants the supreme court to overturn a ruling that
the Krever Inquiry can name names in its final report on how thousands
of Canadians got HIV or Hepatitis C through blood transfusions.

<P>
The Red Cross contends the report could expose it -- and its workers
-- to criminal or civil court cases, and could suggest they were
responsible for the tainted blood scandal. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Stock markets made some strong gains today after better than expected
earnings at IBM helped revive dozens of technology stocks. 
<P>
Analysts are still bullish about many technology companies. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar lost almost a quarter of a penny against the
u-s dollar. 
<HR>

<H3>GO - Business </H3>

<P>
New businesses surrounding Hamilton's new downtown GO Centre are
finding it a tough go...just months after the station's grand
opening. As Jamie West reports their economic field of dreams
is turning out to be more like a field of broken dreams... 
<P>
<I>The battle cry was heard for years in downtown Hamilton...
if we build it they will come... new business owners a stone's
throw from the new GO Centre are stymied... even the cab drivers
are idle promises of big money circulating around the GO station...
so far have turned out to be nothing more than a lot of baloney.</I>
<P>
<I>Tucker Plus has been in business for fifty years over twenty
of them on John Street...but no longer are they giving the city
of Hamilton their rubber stamp of approval.</I>
<P>
<I>Three trains a day go in and out of Hamilton ...buses run all
day long... nearly 3000 passengers a day ...the equation doesn't
make sense to businesses that would rather be rolling in dough
than rolling it out at this slow rate.</I>
<P>
<I>Some have already packed it in ...but most remain hopeful that
time will once again get the til ringing.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Keys - Marine </H3>

<P>
The federal government is looking at ways to improve the country's
marine transportation system. Harbors and other waterways will
have to improve the way they do business in order to remain competitive
in the 21st century. 
<P>
The Canada Marine Act, or Bill C-44, will seriously reduce the
involvement of the federal government in the operation of the
marine transportation system. But those who use the system are
being given a say in how the changes will be made. Today they
met with federal officials in Hamilton to have their say. 

<P>
