<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, July 24, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>H.W. Marine Search 
<LI>Machine Fire 
<LI>403 - Brantford 
<LI>Hamilton Steel 
<LI>Body Image 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>H.W. Marine Search </H3>

<P>
A group of young rowers who apparently set out to cross Lake Ontario
overnight has prompted an air and water search of Lake Ontario.
This afternoon the Hamilton- Wentworth police marine unit joined
other police and military rescue units in the search. They're
covering the section from Hamilton to Mississauga. We're expecting
results of their efforts anytime. 
<P>
While police have no reports of anyone missing, a white rowboat
with more than one person on board was seen early today about
100 metres from the east Toronto shoreline just after one was
reported stolen from woodbine beach. In addition to the lake search,
a ground search of the lake shoreline is also underway from Toronto
to Pickering in case the teens returned to shore. 
<P>
In March of 1995, six teens vanished without a trace in a boat
stolen from a marina in Pickering.
<HR>

<H3>Machine Fire </H3>

<P>
Damage estimated at close to a million dollars after an early
morning fire in Hamilton's industrial core. It happened at Central
Welding and Machine Knife at Depew and Beach road. The company
makes cutting blades for industry. 
<P>
It's believed the fire was started by a malfunctioning furnace
control. Falling debris from the gutted structure sent five firefighters
to hospital with minor neck and back injuries. All five have been
treated and released. 
<HR>

<H3>403 - Brantford </H3>

<P>
The provincial government is now saying the highway 403 link between
Ancaster and Brantford will be open to traffic late next year.
Tendering for the final leg of the roadway was announced today.
The project will include a new bridge at Shaver Road, interchange
improvements at highway two and 13-kilometres of new driving lanes.

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Steel </H3>

<P>
Good news from the Hamilton steel industry today. Word late this
afternoon that Stelco earned 30 million dollars during the second
quarter of this year. That's down from the same time last year,
but still a sign on continuing promise. The results, however,
were even more promising for Dofasco. Anthony Pooley has more.

<P>
<I>This is what the nickname &quot;steel town&quot; is all about...
and even with all of the job cuts over the years, the steel industry
remains the backbone of Hamilton's economy... more or less. </I>
<P>
<I>Today, it looks like more as Dofasco posted second quarter
earnings, showing huge increases in both sales and profits for
the second quarter. Specifically, second quarter sales jumped
21.3-percent over the same period last year to 787.7-million dollars.
Profits are up a whopping 31.6-percent to 54.6-million. </I>
<P>
<I>The challenge, says president and CEO John Mayberry, is to
sustain the good results for as long as possible ... tough sometimes
in a cyclical industry. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Body Image </H3>

<P>
Yesterday we told you about the growing problem of childhood obesity.
Today, reporter Jamie West takes a look at another North American
trend...our obsession with body image.
<P>
<I>Experts say we put too much pressure on ourselves to measure
up to impossible standards set by the media...and it's high time
we learned to relax and accept different body images... </I>
<P>
<I>They're everywhere, and lately they're of Olympic proportions
body images, attractive, athletic, fit, slim and trim... for the
average person...a nearly impossible goal to achieve but one that
is placed centre stage by the media. And that often leads to medically
dangerous yo-yo dieting.</I>
<P>
<I>Marnie Wilson now 24 has felt the pressure since she was 16..
Experts say the pressure is far greater on women but men are not
immune... 42 year old stand up comedian Scot Harris buffed up
five years ago</I>
<P>
<I>But nutritionist's and doctor's say it's time to accept our
often genetically programmed and varied physical forms, take off
the pressure and find some peace ...because it's not likely we'll
ever find the perfect body.</I>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

