<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, July 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Henley Newser 
<LI>Flood Assistance 
<LI>QEW Rollover 
<LI>Carjacking Arrest 
<LI>Drunken Conductor 
<LI>GM Engine Shutdown 
<LI>Santa - July 
<LI>Obesity 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Henley Newser </H3>

<P>
The city of St. Catharines, home of the renowned Henley Regatta
is rowing its way to gold....in the form of the 1999 World Rowing
Championships and perhaps the 2001 Canada Games. 
<P>
The Ontario government today agreed to contribute 1.5 million
dollars in a partnership with the city and Ottawa for a major
upgrade of the Henley course. It's all part of the Martindale
Pond Henley Course Eco-system Management Plan. 
<P>
Serious problems with respect to water depth and movement had
threatened to end any future world class events including the
six annual regattas. That's a dollar value alone of about three-quarters
of a million dollars or 40 full-time jobs. 
<P>
The economic impact of the &quot;Worlds&quot; in 1999 is estimated
at more than 15-million dollars and a minimum of 804 full-time
jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Flood Assistance </H3>

<P>
The French community in Hamilton is responding to an appeal for
funds, relief funds following the devastating weekend floods in
the Saguenay region of Quebec. 
<P>
This morning the national office of the Red Cross issued a country
wide appeal on behalf of the thousands of flood victims. They're
asking for two million dollars to help them rebuild. And as Lauran
Sabourin reports a local relief effort has begun to mobilize.

<P>
<I>The rest of Canada watched with horror as the first pictures
of the of the devastating flood were shown on television. Torrents
of water ripped through buildings. Waters poured through a local
church as if it was a sieve. As the waters receded it left vehicles,
debris buried in mud. </I>
<P>
<I>At the local branches of the Canadian Red Cross calls for assistance
are beginning to come in. People offering assistance. A lot of
calls are offering clothing. The Red Cross would rather have money.
With money the relief workers can help victims more effectively.
They can buy the goods to begin the massive rebuilding project.
Others more sympathetic to the victims see the relief effort as
a way to help reunite the country. </I>
<P>
<I>If you do want to help the flood victims in Quebec you can
make a donation at any branch of the Toronto Dominion, Royal,
CIBC or Scotiabank or you can bring cash, cheque or visa to any
branch of the Canadian Red Cross. The national goal is to raise
2 million dollars toward the flood relief effort. </I>
<HR>

<H3>QEW Rollover </H3>

<P>
A Mississauga transport driver has been charged with careless
driving after the rig he was in rolled over on the QEW at the
junction of highway 403 in Burlington last night. The 18-wheeler
blocked both southbound lanes of the QEW for seven-and-a-half
hours, during which traffic was re-routed onto the 403. 
<P>
Police say further charges are pending against 47-year-old Amaritt
Singh bath, who sustained only minor injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Carjacking Arrest </H3>

<P>
A Niagara police dog is being credited for nabbing two suspects
from a carjacking in Toronto. Last night, two people were seen
running from a car that had rolled over on highway 406 in St.
Catharines. Police dog &quot;rocky&quot; and his handler quickly
caught up with the pair. 
<P>
19 year old Dennis hertz of Hamilton and 20 year old Monique Jamotte
of Toronto are charged with possession of stolen property. 
<HR>

<H3>Drunken Conductor </H3>

<P>
And Hamilton- Wentworth police have now charged a 37 year-old
Niagara Falls man with the impaired operation of railway equipment
after a weekend incident. It happened at the CN railroad yard
in the city's Northend. Police were called over complaints of
a drunken driver. Police say the conductor of a train was under
the influence of alcohol. 
<P>
Co-workers managed to get him out of the locomotive before calling
police. 
<HR>

<H3>GM Engine Shutdown </H3>

<P>
Another engine line at the General Motors St. Catharines plant
will be shut down. The 3.4 litre v-6 engine line will stop production
at the end of 1997. The line employs about 200 people but it hasn't
been determined just how many people will lose their jobs. 
<HR>

<H3>Santa - July </H3>

<P>
What's Santa Claus doing out at this time of year? The jolly old
elf made a special summer trip from the north pole just to see
all of the kids in the &quot;Supie&quot; program at Hamilton's
Woolverton Park. 
<P>
So it was Christmas in July for these kids as they spent an enjoyable
day doing fun things with saint nick. About 50 kids showed up
for the event... and naturally, they were glad they did. 
<HR>

<H3>Obesity </H3>

<P>
Some of North America's top experts on childhood obesity say watching
television may be a bigger culprit than diet in contributing to
an alarming increase in overweight north American children. But
as Jamie West reports ...that's not all. There's a new factor
that's keeping our children from getting fit... 
<P>
<I>The American college of sports medicine says the news is not
good ... one in 5 kids between the ages of 6 and seventeen is
obese...experts say it's an epidemic. </I>
<P>
<I>Chedoke McMaster hospitals Dr. Oded (bar-or) was one of two
Hamilton doctors out of nine in north America invited to share
research on the subject, at a meeting last week in Indianapolis.
But interestingly enough, during the last decade consumption of
fatty foods has decreased.</I>
<P>
<I>Public parks ...that used to be the gathering place of kids
in the summer have become deserted. And why is that? ... well,
it's due to a factor that virtually didn't exist in north America
a decade ago... that factor is parental fear... and that trend
is costly... in the U.S. it's estimated that the psychological,
social and medical costs of raising obese children into obese
adults is in the 10's of billions of dollars. And Canada isn't
far off the pace. </I>


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

