<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, July 22, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Olympics 
<LI>Orchestra Limbo 
<LI>House Centre Close 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Ancaster Livestock 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Olympics</H3>

<P>
A disappointing day for a Burlington gymnast at the summer Olympic
games in Atlanta. It wasn't Alan Nolet's day but what a weekend
for Hamilton's Clara Hughes. 
<P>
Lets take a look at the medal board on this day 3 of the Olympics.
The Americans top the medal board with 10 while the Germans remain
close just 1 back. Canada with 2 bronze thanks to Claire Hughes
and Curtis Myden. 
<HR>

<H3>Orchestra Limbo </H3>

<P>
It's been a marathon, albeit a slow one to try to bring music
back to the city of Hamilton. Competing interests in the race
to rebuild the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra met behind closed
doors today. 
<P>
<I>Community leaders came up with a twelve point plan to revive
classical music in Hamilton after the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra
collapsed in a sea of debt in January. But the plan came too late
for organizers to apply for Canada Council funding. The process
dragged on and on and the sound of music seemed further and further
away. </I>
<P>
<I>Former artistic director Boris Brott made it on time.. but
his application for funding appears doomed. </I>
<P>
<I>Today, after an hour long meeting, Hamilton mayor Bob Morrow
said both groups will now work together. What role Boris Brott
will play is unclear. Many former musicians feel it was Brott
who started the orchestra's downfall during his final days at
the helm. Today he wasn't talking. </I>
<P>
<I>Musician representative Paula Elliott is cautiously optimistic
about the future of a Hamilton orchestra.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>House Centre Close </H3>

<P>
It was a year ago that Jackie Gordon participated in this demonstration
against Harris government cuts to previously approved non- profit
housing projects. And today, with very little fanfare, the executive
director of the Housing Help Centre for Hamilton Wentworth announced
in a written release that the centre will close August second...
another casualty of cutbacks from Queen's park, which picks up
80-percent of the tab for the HHC's activities. 
<P>
She also says that the centre will re-open at some future date
when and if it finds alternate funding. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Interest rates in Canada are moving lower tomorrow. 
<P>
Canada's major banks will be cutting their prime lending rates
by a quarter of a percentage point to six and a quarter per cent.

<P>
Inco and Southam posted 2nd quarter earnings today. 
<HR>

<H3>Ancaster Livestock </H3>

<P>
A 67 year tradition has come to an end in a part of the Hamilton
Wentworth region that just 20 years ago was mostly farmland. 
<P>
The Ancaster Livestock Exchange has offered up it's last sale
to local farmers who as Jamie West reports tonight will now have
to travel a little further to buy and sell... 
<P>
<I>Monday morning at the Ancaster Livestock Exchange.... farmers
buying and selling livestock... a weekly tradition for 67 years,
and although the cattle don't seem to feel all that sentimental
the farmers do.</I>
<P>
<I>Bob Williams and Bill Walker both lawyers have owned the exchange
for 12 years. They say rapid land development is pushing farms
out of the area.... some farmers have been with the exchange since
day one, friendly people like 81-year old Les Gundy.</I>
<P>
<I>Local farmers will now have to buy and sell at stockyards in
Hagersville, Norwich, Wainfleet or Kitchener.</I>


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

