<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/19/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, July 19, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Taro Okay 
<LI>Mt. Hope-Tradeport 
<LI>Ruthven Search 
<LI>Cormorant Tour 
<LI>Brott Summerfest 
<LI>Olympic Well Wishers 
<LI>Seniors Lock-Out 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Taro Okay</H3>

<P>
A four year battle in Stoney Creek ended this afternoon when a
company called Taro Aggregates was declared the winner. The winner
of an often emotional and bitter struggle with residents to keep
a state of the art landfill operation out of their community.

<P>
The Ministry of Environment and Energy has approved a proposal
by Taro to establish another landfill at Taro's east quarry. That's
off highway 20 in Mud Street, across the road from Taro's west
quarry which reached capacity late last year. 
<P>
The new industrial landfill for solid, non hazardous waste, will
have a capacity of 10-million tonnes. Residents who live near
the site have opposed Taro's proposal, saying a leak in the landfill
would spell disaster for the Niagara escarpment. 
<HR>

<H3>Mt. Hope-Tradeport </H3>

<P>
The deal is done. The documents are signed. Now it's time to get
on with business. Today, Hamilton International Airport officially
passed from municipal control to private hands, as Tradeport International
Corporation took over operations at the airport. 
<P>
By relinquishing control, Hamilton- Wentworth is counting on the
private sector to make the airport the heart of economic activity
in the region by the next century. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>With the kind of fanfare that normally accompanies the signing
of international trade agreements, Hamilton- Wentworth regional
chairman Terry Cooke, and Tradeport president Tony Battaglia signed
the documents that transfer the operation of Hamilton International
Airport from the region to private hands. </I>
<P>
<I>Tradeport has promised to lengthen runways, to entice businesses
to industrial lands around the airport, to expand cargo handling,
and to eventually attract a million passengers a year to Hamilton
International Airport. </I>
<P>
<I>To cap off today's ceremony, Tradeport also unveiled the new
logo that will carry the airport into a new era of privatization.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Ruthven Search </H3>

<P>
From the skies over Mt. Hope to below the waters of Lake Ontario.
The renewed search for a missing pilot and his rented plane in
Lake Ontario came to an abrupt halt last night. During a final
approach of the search area, the sonar unit from the HMCS Cormorant
hit something 8 metres off the lake bottom, disabling the unit.

<P>
Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police had requested assistance from
the ship in their attempt to find 63 year old Bill Ruthven. The
veteran pilot was returning to Hamilton from Brampton when he
disappeared mysteriously in February of 1994. 
<P>
Police are now trying to locate other vessels with side scan sonar
that will be passing through Lake Ontario so they can continue
their search. 
<HR>

<H3>Cormorant Tour </H3>

<P>
The HMCS Cormorant is in Hamilton to help celebrate Aquafest,
the Sesqui-centennial edition. The Canadian navy diving support
ship has been conducting research in the great lakes on everything
from shipwrecks to zebra mussels. 
<P>
The HMCS Cormorant is docked at the foot of Catherine Street and
will be open to public tours all weekend from 2 to 4 in the afternoon,
and 6 to 8 at night. 
<HR>

<H3>Brott Summerfest </H3>

<P>
The jazz festival is not the only musical game in town this weekend.
The Boris Brott Summer Music Festival opens Sunday, with a sold-out
performance by Ancaster pianist Valerie Tryon. 
<P>
This is the festival's ninth season, with thirty-two performances
planned between Sunday and August eighteenth. 
<HR>

<H3>Olympic Well Wishers </H3>

<P>
3.5 billion people around the world will be glued to their TV
sets tonight for the opening of the centennial Olympics in Atlanta.

<P>
Hamilton swimmer Joanne Malar is there, cyclists' Sue Palmer and
Clara Hughes, Burlington runners Graham Hood and Paula Schnurr,
Oakville's Donovan Bailey, gymnast Alan Nolet...the list goes
on. 
<P>
Atlanta is a long way from home, but starting today, anyone can
walk into one of the nineteen Mail Boxes Etc. stores, and fax
a free &quot;good luck&quot; message to our Canadian Olympians
in Atlanta. There are Mail Boxes Etc. centres in Hamilton, Stoney
Creek, Ancaster, Dundas, Waterdown, Burlington, Oakville, Milton
and St. Catharines. 
<HR>

<H3>Seniors Lock-Out </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton mountain seniors home locked out sixty-three health
care aides and service staff today, just as the workers prepared
to vote on what the company calls its final contract offer. 
<P>
Members of local 175 of the United Food and Commercial Workers
picketed outside the Wellington Retirement Community on Upper
Wellington at Stonechurch today. A union spokesman condemns the
lock-out as nothing more than an attempt to intimidate workers
into voting in favour of the contract offer. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

