<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, July 18, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>TWA Crash
<LI>Ruthven Search 
<LI>Cartworld Reopens 
<LI>Drugs/Guns 
<LI>Young Thief 
<LI>BB Gun Shots 
<LI>Good Grief 
<LI>Orchestra Future? 
<LI>Deadbeats Local 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>TWA Crash</H3>

<P>
We begin tonight with a brief update on last night's TWA crash
off Long Island New York. We can tell you that rescue workers
have now pulled more than 100 bodies from the waters of the Atlantic.
All were among the 228 people aboard flight the 747 jumbo jet
that exploded into a fireball shortly after take-off. 
<P>
No survivors found, an FBI terrorism team is taking part in the
investigation. 
<HR>

<H3>Ruthven Search </H3>

<P>
And on this side of the border another search will begin tonight
in the waters of Lake Ontario for Bill Ruthven. The 63-year-old
veteran pilot was returned to Hamilton from Brampton in a rented
single-engine piper Cherokee in February of 1994 when he simply
vanished, somewhere near the Burlington Skyway Bridge. 
<P>
His last words described something hitting his windshield. No
sign of a wreckage was ever found. 
<P>
Exactly one year ago the HMCS Cormorant assisted Hamilton- Wentworth
police in the most recent search for any sign of Ruthven or his
plane. It turned up nothing. 
<P>
It's a mystery complicated by theories that he had faked his own
death. Shortly before he disappeared he had been accused of sexually
assaulting a friend's daughter in Muskoka in the early 70's. Bala
OPP even issued a Canada-wide warrant for his arrest. 
<HR>

<H3>Cartworld Reopens </H3>

<P>
Provincial inspectors gave a Mount Hope go-kart track permission
to re-open to the public today. Cartworld has been closed for
the past three days, while inspectors from the Ministry of Consumer
and Commercial Relations investigated a go-kart collision that
killed 26-year-old Dion Desterke of Hamilton. 
<P>
Because the victim was taller than average, inspectors believe
the go-kart's seat belt harness crossed Desterke's upper arms
instead of his shoulders, allowing him to hit the steering wheel
during the collision. 
<P>
Preliminary autopsy results show Desterke died of internal chest
and abdominal injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Drugs/Guns </H3>

<P>
Two Oakville men face weapons and drug charges after police stopped
a car in Burlington for a traffic offense. In the vehicle, they
found a loaded hand gun, four rifles, a thousand rounds of ammunition
as well as narcotics and drug paraphernalia. 
<P>
25-year-old Nicola Radin faces two weapons charges, while 23-year-old
Ryan Schick is charged with possession of a narcotic. 
<HR>

<H3>Young Thief </H3>

<P>
A 17-year-old Hamilton youth faces several charges in connection
with the theft of a Mercedes. 
<P>
Police in Halton say they spotted the stolen car traveling along
Lakeshore Road in Burlington. They pursued it to a house on Beach
Boulevard in Hamilton into which the driver fled. He later surrendered
to police without incident. 
<HR>

<H3>BB Gun Shots </H3>

<P>
An unusual drive-by shooting on Hamilton mountain last night ...
unusual because the victim didn't know he'd been shot at. 
<P>
A 45 year old man was gardening in his front yard on Mountain
Brow Boulevard when he was hit in the back with a B-B from a passing
truck. He didn't realize what had happened until the truck's driver
came back to apologize. 
<P>
A passenger in the truck, 24 year old Lawrence Assiginack of Hamilton,
faces weapon and assault charges. 
<HR>

<H3>Good Grief </H3>

<P>
It was one of those days. Police near St. Catharines, called in
the canine unit after a wanted man was spotted in an orchard in
Fonthill. 
<P>
A police dog named &quot;Grief&quot; and an officer located the
suspect on a highway Monday night but he fled, and &quot;Grief&quot;
was sent in. Four times Grief clamped his jaws around the suspect's
leg. Four times police moved in to subdue the man. And four times
the 320-pound suspect got up and kept running. 
<P>
Police say the suspect, identified as Larry Pagee, was last seen
running naked through dense bush. 
<HR>

<H3>Orchestra Future? </H3>

<P>
Key players from Hamilton's music scene have been summoned to
a private meeting with top politicians, in order to harmonize
efforts to resurrect an orchestra in the city. 
<P>
Hamilton Mayor Bob Morrow and Hamilton- Wentworth regional chairman
Terry Cooke have scheduled the meeting for Monday morning. And
the invitation list includes musicians from the defunct Hamilton
Philharmonic Orchestra, and two men leading the drive to keep
symphonic music alive. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>The debt-induced death of the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra
last January, galvanized community leaders, who drew up a twelve-step
plan for a musical revival, a plan that called for a million dollars
in the bank, wage concessions from musicians, and zero tolerance
for deficits. Four months later, the vision for the new Hamilton
Orchestra has achieved little substance. </I>
<P>
<I>The task force recommendations came too late for orchestra
boosters to apply for provincial and federal grants. But the man
who conducted the HPO for twenty-one years did meet the deadline,
filing an application for funding for the New Academy Orchestra.
</I>
<P>
<I>Any day now, the Canada council will tell Boris Brott if he
was successful in winning funding for his proposal. If he does,
it's pointless to pursue plans to mount a second orchestra, in
a community that has already failed to support one. But if Brott
is unsuccessful, then the mayor and the regional chairman will
make it clear at Monday's meeting that only compromise, co-operation
and a unified front.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Deadbeats Local </H3>

<P>
The Harris government is stepping up its campaign to insure child
support payments are maintained. In a program aimed at deadbeat
parents...failure to make regular payments will mean driver's
licenses won't be renewed. Alex Reynolds reports. 
<P>
<I>It's one measure in a plan that isn't getting full marks. Ignoring
support payments is costly to the province, as mothers and children
frequently end up on the welfare rolls. </I>
<P>
<I>The family support plan, a mechanism designed to insure obligations
are met, is overloaded because of provincial cutbacks... the case
load is too heavy for the structure. </I>
<P>
<I>Statistics project child-support payments will be $1 billion
in arrears by the winter, thereby placing a greater financial
burden on the province.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Some disappointing 2nd quarter earnings spook investors into selling
stocks today. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar drops below 73 cents U.S. 
<P>
Canada's biggest gold mining company announces a big takeover
today. And Canadians increase their buying of light trucks and
vans in may. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

