<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, July 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Heat Crime Units 
<LI>Stabbing 
<LI>Purse Snatching 
<LI>Pistol Packer 
<LI>Mountain Molotov 
<LI>Go-cart Update 
<LI>Niagara Docs Update 
<LI>Simcoe Storm Damage 
<LI>NIA. Airport 
<LI>Downtown Boost 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Heat Crime Units</H3>

<P>
The heat is on in Hamilton- Wentworth and the target: neighbourhood
hang-outs that spawn youth crime. Last night we told you how Ancaster
has imposed a curfew in municipal parks. Tonight, Operation Hangout:
in about 90 minutes from now, police and community groups will
meet in a special session aimed at stemming this escalating problem.

<P>
Twenty parks and malls in Ancaster, Dundas, Waterdown, Glanbrook,
Flamborough and Hamilton mountain have been identified as problem
areas for loitering and disorderly conduct. &quot;Operation Hangout&quot;
will examine alternative places for teens to congregate. 
<P>
And on another front, more than a dozen officers have been assigned
to special heat units, setting up surveillance in hotspot neighborhoods.
For residents of Hamilton- Wentworth, it's all part of a grass-roots
movement to take back their neighborhoods. Annette Hamm tells
us how it works. 
<P>
<I>Constable John Ross is one of several officers giving Hamilton
Wentworth neighborhoods the heat treatment. Heat Units are special
units designed to target crime hot spots. Modeled on a New York
City program, they're designed for officers to focus strictly
on a problem at hand, freeing up other officers for beat duty.
That in turn gets officers on the street talking to residents
about what's wrong with their neighbourhood. </I>
<P>
<I>In Ross' unit, the big focus over the past several weeks has
been prostitution and car theft. On any given night, Constable
Ross tells us a heat unit will recover at least two stolen vehicles.
Most of the time heat unit officers are in plainclothes and unmarked
cars, sometimes they're out walking the streets, trying to stem
a variety of problems. </I>
<P>
<I>The Heat Unit is designed to make residents more at ease, and
if criminals know the special teams may be out there watching,
it's hoped their activity may be deterred.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Stabbing </H3>

<P>
A slashing victim in the Dunsmure and Cope area of Hamilton's
east end, is lucky to be alive, but police say he's not co-operating
with their investigation. 
<P>
Blood dripping from his throat, 45 year old David Birdsell ran
six blocks, refusing help from police or ambulance attendants.
Finally, they were able to get him to hospital, where he's listed
this morning in serious condition. Birdsell told police he was
jumped by people he didn't know, but is supplying very few details.

<HR>

<H3>Purse Snatching </H3>

<P>
And in Halton tonight, police are looking for two men after a
purse-snatching just after midnight in Oakville last night. They're
both black, one is 5 foot-three with a medium build, wearing a
white hat. The other, 5 foot-five, thin, wearing a dark hat and
baggy pants. 
<P>
Two women were approached at the corner of Chisholm and Lakeshore
road. One suspect grabbed a purse and when the women screamed
he kicked one of them and the pair ran off in different directions.
Two citizens tried to help but lost them. 
<HR>

<H3>Pistol Packer </H3>

<P>
A St. Catharines woman obviously couldn't take it anymore. Last
night five teens were standing in the parking lot of a variety
store on Rockwood Avenue, listening to a car stereo. 
<P>
Police say a woman pulled up in an older black car and pointed
a chrome, semi-automatic pistol at them and told them to take
off. They did. Police are looking for the woman, described as
about 30 years old with shoulder length brown hair. 
<HR>

<H3>Mountain Molotov </H3>

<P>
You never know what you might find in your own backyard. Last
night, a Hamilton mountain couple walking through a field behind
their house found a Molotov cocktail. They carried the bottle
back to their house, but bomb technicians moved it away to a safer
area to defuse it. 
<HR>

<H3>Go-cart Update </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton man, killed in a weekend go-kart crash, may have died
because he was taller than average. Investigators from the Ministry
of Consumer and Commercial Relations were back at Cartworld in
Mount Hope today, re-enacting the accident that killed 26-year-old
Dion Desterke. And as Deborah Walker reports, provincial inspectors
have now broadened the scope of their investigation to include
an earlier accident at Cartworld, that seriously injured a Burlington
man. 
<P>
<I>Exactly seven weeks before Dion Desterke died, 26-year-old
Kirk Ryder of Burlington was circling the Cartworld track, when
he was bumped from behind by another driver, just like Dion Desterke
was. Ryder, who still suffers from back and neck injuries, says
he was devastated when he learned someone had died in a similar
accident, in the same spot below the bridge on the Cartworld track.
</I>
<P>
<I>Using a go-kart similar to the one Dion Desterke was driving,
inspectors worked with private consultants and representatives
of the Go-kart Track Association to re-enact the fatal accident.
Although they were initially baffled, inspectors now believe they
know why Desterke died. </I>
<P>
<I>Benn says Cartworld's safety standards are actually higher
than those required by the province. With the investigation nearly
complete, Benn says Cartworld could re-open to the public as early
as tomorrow.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Docs. Update </H3>

<P>
If you're expecting a baby and live in Niagara, let's hope you
already have an obstetrician. Baby doctors there have carried
out their threat to stop accepting new patients July 15th to protest
Ontario government cutbacks. What many thought to be the major
issue -- government subsidies of doctors' malpractice insurance
-- has already been resolved after the province reinstated the
subsidies. 
<P>
But obstetricians are still upset over fee clawbacks. And they
say over the last ten years government cutbacks of one sort or
another have effectively cut their pay by about one third. 
<P>
St. Catharines General Hospital says despite the move, an obstetrician
will be available in emergency situations. 
<HR>

<H3>Simcoe Storm Damage </H3>

<P>
Tobacco farmers north of Simcoe are adding up the damage following
a severe thunder storm. A government adjuster says wind and rain
damage from last night's storm is severe, but no one will lose
a full crop. The storm hit about 30 farms in the area. 
<HR>

<H3>Niag. Airport </H3>

<P>
The Niagara and District Airport will officially change hands
to local authorities on Friday. It's being taken over by a group
called Tradeport International, which represents St. Catharines,
Thorold, Niagara-on-the Lake and Niagara Falls. 
<P>
Ottawa announced two years ago that it wanted to privatize regional
airports.
<HR>

<H3>Downtown Boost </H3>

<P>
The latest bid to boost Hamilton's stagnant downtown core is a
three month trial that will leave you with more money in your
pocket. Free parking is coming to most downtown parking lots on
evenings heading into the weekends. As Jamie West reports tonight
..the city hopes the move will be a positive step in right direction...

<P>
<I>Soon this Hamilton parking lot cash register won't be ringing
at all at least on Thursdays Fridays and all day on Saturdays.
The idea?... instead of putting your money in the meter.... you
can spend it on downtown business.</I>
<P>
<I>The three month free parking trial was agreed to at a Parking
Authority Board meeting yesterday ... and this man will have to
wave a lot harder just to earn a living ... Earl McAusland, general
manager of six privately owned downtown parking lots says he'll
feel the pinch.</I>
<P>
<I>But parking is just a small part of a much bigger issue ...
the experiment will cost the Parking Authority about 200-thousand
dollars in lost revenue, but that will not translate into staff
reductions or layoffs. </I>
<P>
<I>Fourteen lots in the downtown core are affected freeing up
997 parking spaces. Including the Convention Centre and Eaton
Centre Parkade.</I> 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

