<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, July 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Bailey - Racism 
<LI>Stelwire 
<LI>Joe Brant Chronics 
<LI>Greyhound-Add 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Go-kart Follow
<LI>Bank Robbery 
<LI>Ancaster Curfew 
<LI>Mystery Woman 
<LI>Pantless Driver 
<LI>Non-body St. Kitts 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bailey - Racism</H3>

<P>
Are Canadians racist? That's the question around the office water
coolers and in the coffee shops today. It all began with a line
in a magazine article about Canadian sprinter and Olympic hopeful
Donovan Bailey. Bailey said Canadians are as blatantly racist
as Americans. As Jamie West reports tonight, he is also disappointed
by Canadian's apparent apathy to his sport.
<P>
<I>In an article written by American sports journalist Michael
Farber... Bailey says &quot;people who don't appear to be Canadian,
people of color, don't get the same treatment. They associate
you with your parents birthplace or your birthplace.&quot;</I>
<P>
<I>Marauder basketball star Keegan Johnson remembers the Ben Johnson
scandal.</I>
<P>
<I>Bailey believes Canadians haven't yet recovered ...as witnessed
by a race at Copps Coliseum last January ...even though the race
was just a twenty minute drive from Bailey's Oakville condo...with
the gold and silver medalists from the world championships running...only
6000 showed up in an arena that holds 18-thousand. </I>
<P>
<I>Michael Farber says &quot;it was if the world's fastest man
were running next door and his neighbors drew the drapes.&quot;
--a big change since 88.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Stelwire </H3>

<P>
As the strike of '46 is remembered, 67 steelworkers in Burlington
are celebrating a new contract. Members of local 8460 have agreed
to a new six-year deal with Stelwire, a subsidiary of Stelco and
Canada's largest producer of steel wire products. 
<HR>

<H3>Joe Brant Chronics </H3>

<P>
Twenty five new jobs will be created at Burlington's Joseph Brant
Memorial Hospital next spring. Patient care attendants are needed
for a new nursing home operating within the hospital. Annette
Hamm tells us the restructuring will fill a need within the hospital
and within the community. 
<P>
<I>Halton region has had a shortage of nursing home beds for several
years. Currently, there are more than 5-hundred people waiting
for placement in a long term care facilities. Within a few months,
about a tenth of those people may be housed at Joseph Brant Memorial
Hospital. </I>
<P>
<I>The hospital is renovating two wards to accommodate 48 nursing
home beds. Hospital nursing homes aren't new in Ontario... Norfolk
General, West Lincoln and Welland Hospitals have had them for
years. Joseph Brant's president and CEO sees it as a trend for
urban hospitals. </I>
<P>
<I>Oakville Memorial is leasing space to a private nursing home
chain. Private or public, the cost of a nursing home room is the
same, set by the Ontario government. A spokesperson for another
private chain says the hospital is to be commended for keeping
Halton nursing home residents close to their families. Pending
provincial approval, the 48 beds should be ready next March.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Greyhound-Add </H3>

<P>
And private enterprise appears prospering in our skies: just a
week after its launch, Greyhound Air has announced a second daily
jet flight out of Mt. Hope Airport. 
<P>
As of today passengers can take an early morning plane in addition
to the early evening flight to five western destinations: Winnipeg,
Calgary Edmonton Kelowna and Vancouver. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Yesterday's big correction in stock markets re-ignited today with
dramatically sharp drops in stock prices. However by the time
markets closed, prices in New York made a recovery while losses
in Toronto moderated. The experts are calling this a healthy correction.
<HR>

<H3>Go-kart Follow</H3>

<P>
Preliminary findings indicate a Hamilton man, killed in a weekend
go-kart accident, died of internal chest and abdominal injuries.

<P>
26-year-old Dion Desterke was bumped by another go-kart, and crashed
into a barrier at Cartworld in Mount Hope on Sunday. Inspectors
from the Ministry of Consumer and Commercial Relations have examined
the Cartworld track and the kart Desterke was driving, to see
if safety problems played any role in his death. 
<P>
The coroner's office will await the results of the government
investigation before deciding if an inquest should be called.

<P>
Cartworld will remain closed until the investigation is completed.

<HR>

<H3>Bank Robbery </H3>

<P>
Police are investigating a noon-hour holdup at a Bank of Nova
Scotia branch in Stoney Creek. A robber walked into the bank on
Barton Street at Green Road, showed a teller what looked like
a handgun, and handed her a note demanding cash. He fled on foot
with the money. 
<P>
The suspect is described as a black male in his thirties, five-foot-six,
with a thin build. He was wearing black sunglasses, a blue baseball
cap, a blue jacket, and a blue nylon track suit. He was last seen
running south on Green Road towards highway eight. 
<HR>

<H3>Ancaster Curfew </H3>

<P>
They're trying to crack down on crime in Ancaster, especially
youth crime... vandalism, a growing problem in the town. U.S.
president Bill Clinton thinks curfews are the answer and now Ancaster
council agrees. Ian Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>A fire three weeks ago destroyed two thirds of Barbara Smith's
business. The late night blaze behind the Ancaster Bakery was
deliberately set. The same suspected group of young teens struck
again last Friday night. </I>
<P>
<I>Barbara Smith says the vandalism has gone beyond the thrill
of childhood pranks and has turned to fear. Town council agrees
these isolated incidents are beginning to dangerously add up and
has imposed a ten p-m to 6 a-m curfew. A restriction these young
kids scoff at. Even Barbara Smith has doubts about the effectiveness
of a nighttime curfew.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Mystery Woman </H3>

<P>
A mystery woman whose identity has puzzled police since she was
found last night in a remote section of Ancaster has been identified.
Her name won't be released until her family is contacted. The
young woman was discovered ankle deep in mud by hikers along the
rail trail just before dark. She's currently under doctor's care.

<HR>

<H3>Pantless Driver </H3>

<P>
Somewhere in Dundas there's a man driving around without any pants
on ... and police need help finding him. Two women saw the man
driving out of University Plaza early last evening. They told
police he saw them, and smiled as he masturbated in the car. 
<P>
The man was wearing a brown shirt, no pants, and had brown and
grey hair greased back. He was driving a late 1980's maroon Buick
Regal, without licence plates. Anyone with information is asked
to call Crime Stoppers. 
<HR>

<H3>Non-Body St. Kitts </H3>

<P>
Emergency officials in St. Catharines were led on a wild goose
chase today. Firefighters, ambulance crews and police were called
around 8:30 this morning by people seeing what they thought was
a body floating in Twelve Mile Creek. The waterway runs through
the city. 
<P>
It turned out to be a scuba diver taking his own unique tour of
St. Catharines. Even though he entered restricted water near a
Hydro dam, no charges have been laid. 


<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

