<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, July 15, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Cartworld Follow
<LI>Apt. Fire Fatal 
<LI>Gulliver's Drowning 
<LI>Pool Drowning 
<LI>Niagara Fatal 
<LI>Cottage Stabbing 
<LI>Domestic Stab 
<LI>Restaurant Robbery 
<LI>Business First
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Cartworld Follow</H3>

<P>
Government inspectors were back on the job today, investigating
a fatal crash at a Hamilton-area go-kart track. Both the coroner's
office, and the Ministry of Consumer and Commercial Relations
are probing the death of 26-year-old Dion Desterke of Hamilton.
He died yesterday after he was forced into a barrier, by a collision
with another go-kart at Cartworld on Highway Six south near Mount
Hope. 
<P>
Despite the tragedy, go-kart operators insist the industry is
safe and well-regulated. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>It's business as usual at Lakeland Go-karts in Hamilton's Confederation
Park. The Firmi family has run this track for thirty-seven years
without serious incident. Lew Firmi says go-carting is safe. Despite
those regulations, the gates at Cartworld near Mount Hope are
locked, opened only to employees and a team of government inspectors
investigating the fatal go-kart collision that killed a Hamilton
man. </I>
<P>
<I>This novice driver recently joined a private club at Cartworld,
and has nothing but praise for its safety standards. Government
inspectors will make their findings public once they've decided
whether driver error of safety infractions caused the Cartworld
crash.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Apt. Fire Fatal </H3>

<P>
Police have now released the name of a Hamilton man killed in
an early morning fire. Firefighters arrived just before five to
find the flames from a burning chesterfield extinguished but the
body of 72-year-old Christopher Leonard in the kitchen area. The
fire marshall is investigating. 
<P>
So far officials say careless smoking is suspected, and the apartment's
smoke detector was not working. It's the region's fifth fire fatality
this year. Damage has been listed at 15 thousand dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Gulliver's Drowning </H3>

<P>
Deaths by drownings in the golden horseshoe this weekend... in
Flamborough, 26 year old Mohammed Abdul Waheed of Mississauga
drowned at Gulliver's Lake yesterday while trying to save his
younger brother. 
<P>
The 19 year old man was later pulled to safety from an unsupervised
swimming area. And Niagara Region Police are investigating the
death of a man in a swimming pool at a Niagara falls motel. A
man in his 40's was pulled from the pool at the Queen Elizabeth
Motel Saturday afternoon. 
<HR>

<H3>Pool Drowning </H3>

<P>
Niagara Region Police are investigating the death of a man after
a swimming pool accident at a Niagara Falls motel. A man in his
40's was pulled from the pool at the Queen Elizabeth Motel around
4:15 Saturday afternoon. 
<P>
He died yesterday morning at greater Niagara general hospital.
The man's name is being withheld until relatives can be notified.

<HR>

<H3>Niagara Fatal </H3>

<P>
And a Guelph man slipped off the edge of the Niagara escarpment,
plunging to his death in the Niagara gorge Sunday. It all began
when Niagara Parks Police received a complaint from a pair of
tourists who had surprised a suspect during a theft from a car.
The suspect fled the scene but was not pursued. 
<P>
23 year old David Kucman died after falling about 11 metres on
to an Ontario Hydro access road near the Botanical Gardens. 
<HR>

<H3>Cottage Stabbing </H3>

<P>
Three Hamilton men have been charged following a knife fight at
a cottage near Sturgeon Falls that sent five people to hospital.

<P>
Charged with aggravated assault are 21-year-old George Koutsokeris
and 28-year-old Johnny Pantanella. A charge of assault with a
weapon has been laid against 30-year-old Daniel Pantanella. 
<P>
Four men suffered knife wounds in the disturbance, while another
received wounds to the face. OPP haven't said what caused the
disturbance, which broke out early yesterday. 
<HR>

<H3>Domestic Stab </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton woman is in hospital after being terrorized by her
boyfriend for two days. Police say the woman has been treated
for non life threatening stab wounds. 
<P>
40 year old Charles Martin of Hamilton is charged with assault
with a weapon and two counts of assault threaten death. 
<HR>

<H3>Restaurant Rob </H3>

<P>
A quick take out at a Hamilton restaurant has netted a suspect
one wallet and a diamond ring. Police say he grabbed the goods
off a man as he walked into the Del Mar Restaurant. The restaurant
is just a few steps away from the Hamilton Wentworth central police
station. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First</H3>

<P>
A massive stock market correction sent stock prices on a nose-dive.
Most of the selloff was fueled by disappointing earnings results
among technology companies. 
<P>
Despite the falling stock prices, TD Bank released an upbeat prediction
on Canada's economy. 


<P>
