<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, July 11, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Niagara Response 
<LI>Bevan Reaction
<LI>Rolider Inquiry 
<LI>Ecstasy Bust 
<LI>Girl Hit 
<LI>Creek Crash 
<LI>Farm Accident 
<LI>Shed Arson 
<LI>Cuba Crisis 
<LI>Carters Honeymoon 
<LI>Sesqui Super Home 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Niagara Response </H3>

<P>
An Ontario court judge has handed down a scathing indictment of
the police forces who investigated the Paul Bernardo case. 
<P>
Mr. Justice Archie Campbell says the system failed and because
of that, a rapist slipped through their fingers and went on to
commit murder. 
<HR>

<H3>Bevan Reaction </H3>

<P>
The chiefs of police in Niagara, Halton and metro Toronto are
not talking tonight but they have issued a joint statement. They
say Campbell's recommendations will improve the way in which police
services manage complicated investigations, that they will take
steps to prevent a recurrence of systemic or specific errors identified
in Campbell's report. But they are asking for more time to go
through the document. 
<HR>

<H3>Rolider Inquiry </H3>

<P>
And now the latest on a call for another inquiry. Chedoke-McMaster
Hospital is holding out an olive branch to families who say their
children were abused by the staff of a controversial brain injury
clinic. But those same families do not appear anxious to accept
the peace offering. Scot Urquhart has more on that story: 
<P>
<I>Chedoke McMaster says, it's just trying to clear the air. The
Martins, John and Diana, along with Wendy Littlejohn, have accused
the hospital of turning a blind eye to alleged abuse ... carried
out by Amos Rolider; the director of the Chedoke McMaster Centre
for Behavioral Rehabilitation, in 1991. </I>
<P>
<I>In light of the controversy, the hospital says it will appoint
an independent investigator to conduct an external review of patient
records during the Rolider years, of 1989 to 1993. The hospital
has already had one such review. It was called &quot;The Wood
Report&quot;. It was conducted by Dr. Roger Wood early in 1994,
soon after Rolider left the hospital. The original draft of the
report was so harshly critical of Rolider, and his methods, that
horrified hospital officials asked Dr. Wood to re-write his report
and tone it down.  But Cynthia Janzen insists, that comparing
the Wood Report to the review they are now proposing would be
apples and oranges.</I>
<P>
<I>Indeed, nine months after his signature appeared on the revised
edition of the Wood Report, hospital vice president Jay Graydon
had this to say about Amos Rolider.</I>
<P>
<I>And so the Littlejohns and Martins will press their demands
for a full public inquiry into the Rolider affair.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Ecstasy Bust </H3>

<P>
It's called ecstacy and it's a drug that's hitting it big with
young people across southern Ontario. But a raid last night at
a home in Stoney Creek has put a big dent in the supply. 
<P>
Drug officers from Halton and Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police
have made what could be the biggest bust yet of ecstacy in southern
Ontario. The two men who live in the house, 40 year old Anthony
Williams and 28 year old Robert Williams face a number of drug
and weapons charges. 
<P>
Police estimate the street value of their haul to be worth 150-thousand
dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Girl Hit </H3>

<P>
Some serious motor vehicle accidents over the past 24 hours...
police investigating one in which a 12 year old girl was hit by
a car on Hamilton mountain last night. She is recovering from
severe head injuries. 
<P>
Police say the girl was playing ball on East 24th street when
she was struck. 
<HR>

<H3>Creek Crash </H3>

<P>
Investigators also looking into a two car crash on Stoney Creek
mountain that sent a young man to hospital with severe head and
chest injuries. The 23 year old is listed in serious condition.

<P>
It happened around midnight when a car ran a stop sign hitting
an oncoming vehicle. 
<HR>

<H3>Farm Accident </H3>

<P>
And a Beamsville farmer has died of his injuries after being thrown
from his tractor when it left Tufford road yesterday and struck
a culvert. A passing motorist found 83 year-old Amedeo Dionis
and took him to hospital. 
<P>
Police believe he suffered an asthma attack. 
<HR>

<H3>Shed Arson </H3>

<P>
Another fire bug at work in downtown Hamilton. Overnight someone
set fire to a shed on Birge Street by lighting a gasoline trail
from a fence to the shed. damage is estimated at about 5-thousand
dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Cuba Crisis </H3>

<P>
A U.S. government decision to ban executives of a Toronto mining
company with dealing in Cuba has some golden horseshoe businesses
nervous. Sherritt International says it will stay in Cuba and
foreign affairs minister Lloyd Axworthy says he wouldn't be surprised
if Canadians boycott the U.S. over its anti-Cuba measures. Ian
Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>With the blacklisting of Sherritt International Corporation,
Canadian companies doing business in Cuba are looking over their
shoulders. </I>
<P>
<I>Ron Foxcroft of Fluke Transport and the manufacturer of the
Fox 40 whistle does business with the Cubans. Following up on
a threat Washington has impose sanctions on the executives, shareholders
and families of Sherritt International of Toronto, for mining
confiscated American property in Cuba. </I>
<P>
<I>Ottawa says the U.S. action is outrageous. </I>
<P>
<I>Hotz Recycling of Hamilton deals directly with the Cubans.
For five years Hotz has been selling recycled paints to Havana.
Despite the Helms Burton Act and harassing calls from Miami based
anti Castro groups, a Hotz executive says it will live up to its
contract with the Cubans. </I>
<P>
<I>Foxcroft, on the other hand doesn't want to upset uncle Sam,
but at the same time fears Canadian retaliatory action. What action,
if any the Canadian government takes remains to be seen. But what
is known is that the Helms-Burton legislation is far reaching,
beyond trade. Case in point, last month's Hamilton international
airshow. One week before the event, the Americans pulled 13 exhibits
because of Canada's trade relations with Fidel Castro.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Carters Honeymoon </H3>

<P>
Niagara Falls has always served as a magnet for romantics. And
it appears former U.S. presidents are not immune to its attraction.

<P>
One-time U.S. president Jimmy Carter and his wife Rosalynn decided
to celebrate their fiftieth wedding anniversary in the honeymoon
capital. While there, they did what most tourist do. They took
a ride on the maid of the mist, ventured into the rock tunnels
behind the falls, and visited nearby Niagara-on-the-Lake. 
<P>
The city of Niagara Falls even issued the Carters an official
honeymoon certificate. No word on whether there was a heart-shaped
tub in their hotel suite. 
<HR>

<H3>Sesqui Super Home </H3>

<P>
And finally it's being built as part of Hamilton's 150th birthday
celebrations, and it's guaranteed to remain a modern marvel even
by the time the city turns 200. Today, business and community
leaders signed the cornerstone of Hamilton's sesquicentennial
super home on Upper Paradise Road, near Rymal. 
<P>
More than eighty Hamilton-area businesses have co-operated in
the construction of a state-of-the-art home, that will be raffled
off in a lottery later this summer. The Sesqui Super Home Lottery
will benefit numerous charities, including Hamilton's four hospitals.


<P>
