<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, July 10, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Bernardo - Campbell Report
<LI>Rolider Petition 
<LI>Cop Charged 
<LI>Lottery Fraud 
<LI>Skinny Robber 
<LI>Canine-Marine 
<LI>Niagara Safety 
<LI>Food Banks 
<LI>Casting Jobs 
<LI>Kwiklynx 
<LI>Wine Shortage 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Bernardo - Campbell Report</H3>

<P>
The long awaited Campbell report will be released tomorrow ..
it is the government's examination of the handling of the Paul
Bernardo murder investigation... and it is touted to be a document
that will name names and change the way murder investigations
are conducted all across North America. We will have extensive
coverage of the story throughout the day tomorrow.
<HR>

<H3>Rolider Petition</H3>

<P>
A new development tonight in the story we brought you yesterday
about allegations of abuse of brain injured patients at Chedoke
- McMaster Hospital. The call for a public inquiry over a so-called
aversive therapy program gained momentum today, as parents of
these patients brought their plea forward, to the public. 
<P>
John and Diana Martin claim their son, Robby Thompson, was abused
by Amos Rolider; the man who headed the Chedoke - McMaster program
from 1989, to 1991. They went public with their case because they
say; they couldn't get satisfaction from the hospital. Scot Urquhart
has more: 
<P>
<I>John Martin was stoic... as his son Robby Thompson, screamed
in pain. Robby's mother couldn't bear it. Robby received this
treatment as a patient of the Chedoke - McMaster brain injury
program in 1991. The Martins are taking aim at the hospital, with
a definite agenda in mind.</I>
<P>
<I>Former crown attorney Tony Skarica is now a Tory MPP.  But
John Martin has no faith left, in the hospital, or the system.
</I>
<P>
<I>A provincially appointed body known as PABIAC and headed by
Chedoke - McMaster staffers ... is currently working on a package
of standards for the province. At the moment, they are leaning
toward a system of voluntary compliance, voluntary reporting,
and voluntary inspections.</I> 
<P>
And, in the last hour, Chedoke McMaster Hospital announced that
it will initiate an independent third party review of all patient
records from the behavioral brain injury program, from 1989 to
1993. The hospital says it will announce the independent body
appointed to conduct the review; within the next few days. 
<P>
Hospital spokesperson Cynthia Janzen says the hospital believes
that it has been open and accountable all the way along, and they
intend to share the results of the review with the public, when
they become available. 
<HR>

<H3>Cop Charged </H3>

<P>
A metro Toronto police officer was arrested this morning over
a domestic dispute in Burlington last month. The 30-year-old man
whose name is not being released to protect the identity of the
victim was released but is due to appear in court July 31st. 
<HR>

<H3>Lottery Fraud </H3>

<P>
Dreams of winning the big one have netted a Dunnville man with
a fraud charge. Police say over the period of a week, the suspect
purchased 85-thousand dollars worth of &quot;Keno&quot; and &quot;Lotto
649&quot; tickets with NSF cheques. 
<P>
All of the purchases were made at a Target Food store on Hamilton
mountain. 33 year old John Horton of Dunnville is charged with
fraud over five-thousand dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>Skinny Robber</H3>

<P>
A tall, skinny bandit with long blond hair has had a busy week
so far in Hamilton. Last night within an hour police believe the
same suspect robbed a 2-for-1 Pizzeria on Hamilton mountain and
the Journey's Inn in Stoney Creek. 
<P>
On Monday night, it's believed the same guy hit a variety store
in downtown Hamilton. In all three cases, he produced a handgun
and made off with a small amount of cash. 
<HR>

<H3>Canine-Marine </H3>

<P>
They've had an informal agreement for years to help each other
out. But now officers from both Halton and Hamilton Wentworth
regions are on the same team. The police services have announced
a formal amalgamation effective immediately. Annette Hamm tells
us what that means for residents in both regions. 
<P>
<I>Halton region's lone police canine unit is about to get some
neighbourhood backup. Hamilton Wentworth's four canine teams will
join forces with Halton as part of a formal amalgamation. The
dog deal means Halton will have more units on duty, and Hamilton
Wentworth will save on the cost of training a new dog. </I>
<P>
<I>There are also savings on board for both police services marine
units. Halton Regional Police will also add their polygraph services
to sweeten the pot. Up until this deal, Hamilton Wentworth has
had to borrow a lie detector. </I>
<P>
<I>Both police services will record the costs of all three joint
programs, and split them at the end of the year. Although a savings
is expected, there's no firm figure attached yet. </I>
<P>
<I>Halton and Hamilton Wentworth are also looking at joining their
emergency response units, bomb squads and major crime units.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Niagara Safety </H3>

<P>
Niagara Region Police are appealing to motorists, cyclists and
pedestrians to be more careful. At this time last year the number
of traffic fatalities in the region was eight. So far this year
13 people have died on Niagara's roads. 
<P>
Police Chief Grant Waddell says lack of judgment, excessive speed
and alcohol have all been contributing factors. 
<HR>

<H3>Food Banks </H3>

<P>
Effects of last October's Harris government spending cuts are
now being analyzed. And in Hamilton- Wentworth it meant more people
turned to the food banks. 
<P>
Jackie Gordon of the Housing Help Centre says the number of families
in Hamilton- Wentworth relying on emergency food programs jumped
more than 37 per cent from September to November of last year.

<HR>

<H3>Casting Jobs </H3>

<P>
Things could be looking up now though: at least one local company
is actually creating jobs. Booming auto-parts sales are driving
Amcan Castings to generate up to 50 jobs in the Hamilton- Burlington
area. 
<P>
The Burlington-based subsidiary of Tritech Precision of Toronto
has been hiring over the past two years and vice president Kris
Nowers says it will continue to do so to catch up on a 500-million
dollar backlog. 
<HR>

<H3>Kwiklynx </H3>

<P>
And from car parts to computer parts, the latest Internet technology
came to Hamilton this afternoon. Weslink Datalink, through a consortium
of Hamilton cable companies, unveiled it's new Kwiklynx to patrons
at the Bean Bar restaurant. 
<P>
With speeds 100 times faster than current modems, Kwiklynx will
make full motion, like Channel 11 News updates and animation,
like Disney movie previews, feasible on the Internet. 
<P>
Kwiklynx is currently being tested in field trials with selected
homes, businesses and libraries. 
<HR>

<H3>Wine Shortage </H3>

<P>
A grape shortage in Ontario's Niagara region may leave European
wine connoisseurs with few opportunities to sample the province's
vintages. Four consecutive wet and cool springs have produced
below-average grape harvests. 
<P>
Wine makers are scrambling to find enough grapes to meet the growing
demand for and meanwhile Niagara strawberry growers continue to
cash in on the American berry scare. 

<P>
