<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 07/09/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, July 9, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Rolider Update 
<LI>Breast Cancer Clinic 
<LI>Youth Charged 
<LI>Seniors Sick 
<LI>Housing Starts 
<LI>No Smoking Response 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Rolider Update</H3>

<P>
We begin tonight with an update on a disturbing story that we
first brought you 16 months ago. It is a story of pain, and denial.

<P>
The pain, was inflicted upon brain injured patients at Chedoke
McMaster Hospital, between 1989 ... and 1993 ... in the name of
treatment. 
<P>
The denial; comes from hospital officials who refuse to acknowledge
any impropriety. Scot Urquhart has the latest on this story and
we warn you that the pictures you are about to see may bother
sensitive viewers. 
<P>
<I>What exactly happened here between 1989, and 1993? That is
the question posed by a petition, calling for a public inquiry
into the operation of the Centre for Behavioral Rehabilitation
during the tenure of Amos Rolider. </I>
<P>
<I>Wentworth North MPP Tony Skarica says, he will take the petition
to Queen's Park and promises to get to the bottom of things.</I>
<P>
<I>So just what are these disturbing allegations? Families of
former patients say, their brain-injured children were abused
by Rolider and his staff.</I>
<P>
<I>The young man in the chair is Robby Thompson ... a patient
with a brain injury. He was in Rolider's care back in 1991. The
procedure is called aversive therapy and was supported by the
hospital at the time. Although the techniques are not used in
the brain injury program now, Chedoke-McMaster has never made
any apologies concerning their prior practices. In fact they have
been so reluctant to do so, a Hamilton alderman quoted in stories
by Christine Hahn of the Hamilton Mountain News ... has accused
them of covering up the abuse.</I>
<P>
<I>But is the hospital responsible? Yes; according to doctor Allan
Hopewell ... an internationally renowned expert, on brain injury
treatment.  In fact, Doctor Hopewell says that Rolider was grossly
underqualified for the position he held, as head of the rehab
clinic.  Hopewell says the infliction of pain does nothing to
help; but simply terrorizes patients into compliance.  </I>
<P>
<I>None of these allegations are new. Channel Eleven broke the
story 16 months ago. What is new, is the call for a public inquiry.
What do Chedoke officials say now? Councilor D'amico says, he
too will support a call for a public inquiry; and he is also calling
on former patients and their families to come forward.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Breast Cancer Clinic </H3>

<P>
Hamilton will become home to Canada's second one-stop breast health
centre. A facility where women suffering breast cancer will find
all of expertise and support they need. As Lauran Sabourin reports
this facility will become a reality in part because of a million
dollar fundraising effort by the Junior League of Hamilton Burlington.

<P>
<I>The centre will provide everything from surgery to support
groups for women diagnosed with breast cancer. All of the necessary
services under one roof. </I>
<P>
<I>The Junior League is making a commitment to raise more than
a million dollars for cancer detection equipment. And for what
cancer specialists call a healing garden. A place where medicinal
herbs will be grown. A hospital garden where cancer patients can
go to have peace of mind. To feel better. </I>
<P>
<I>Adele Chetec knows the anguish of being diagnosed with cancer.
Two months ago Adele was told that she had breast cancer. Weeks
of chemotherapy has temporary robbed Adele of her hair. </I>
<P>
<I>A naturally optimistic person Adele finds solace in positive
attitude visual therapy. In talking to other women who are going
through the same thing. And she's hopeful that support groups
that will be more readily available at Hamilton's Breast Health
Centre will help other breast cancer victims through this traumatic
time.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Youth Charged </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton youth has been charged with lighting up a school. Police
say an incendiary device was thrown through a window at Cardinal
Heights School on Bobolink Road July 1st. The resulting fire caused
100-thousand dollars in damage. 
<HR>

<H3>Seniors Sick </H3>

<P>
A mysterious respiratory illness has struck a nursing home in
Welland. The 23 residents at Sunset Haven have been moved into
the gym while the seniors home is given a thorough cleaning. The
virus may be linked to birds nesting in the attic. 
<P>
An official of the region's seniors department says the move is
a precautionary measure. 
<HR>

<H3>Housing Starts </H3>

<P>
More signs of consumer confidence showing up in the latest figures
from Canada Mortgage and Housing. 
<P>
Housing starts in Hamilton were up in June with 272 housing starts
compared to only 102 starts in June of 95. 
<P>
Year to year housing construction figures remain virtually the
same. However a CMHC spokesperson says with constant mortgage
rates predicted throughout the summer, home construction should
remain strong over the coming months. 
<HR>

<H3>No Smoking Response </H3>

<P>
The air is clearing. The first domino has now fallen in Waterloo
Region's race to ban butts from bars and restaurants. Waterloo
city councilors have the become the first to approve the region's
new smoking bylaw, which would prohibit smoking in food courts
and malls, then restaurants and bars by the year 2-thousand. 
<P>
In light of this decision, and the uproar over Toronto's smoking
ban still burning, Hamilton Wentworth is taking a slower approach.
Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>It was an experiment that could turn into a lifestyle change.
Seventeen restaurants in Hamilton Wentworth voluntarily banned
smoking for one day in June. The region's Public Health Department
says 70 per cent of those volunteers report no negative economic
impact. </I>
<P>
<I>The owner of this &quot;Just Desserts&quot; franchise in west
Hamilton didn't lose money that day because she only imposed the
ban until 6 PM, when the majority of her customers are non smoking
anyway. A permanent ban she says could slice profits by 25 per
cent. </I>
<P>
<I>&quot;Chagall's&quot; restaurant at the Sheraton Hamilton Hotel
also imposed the smoking ban until 6 PM during the experiment,
but the food and beverage manager feels a permanent ban shouldn't
be a government decision.</I> 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

