<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, July 8, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Greyhound Launch 
<LI>Traffic Lights 
<LI>Wheelchair Busses 
<LI>Victoria Crash 
<LI>Niagara Fall 
<LI>Mtn. Heroes 
<LI>Most Wanted 
<LI>Hydrofoil Launch 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Greyhound Launch </H3>

<P>
Canada's airline industry has officially gone to the dogs. A new
experiment in integrated travel began this morning ads the country's
newest airline, Greyhound Air, took wing. 
<P>
Greyhound plans to base its eastern operations right here at Hamilton's
Mt. Hope Airport. Its inaugural flight takes off for Winnipeg
and Vancouver at 7:20 tonight. 
<HR>

<H3>Traffic Lights </H3>

<P>
Back on the ground, what does it take to stop traffic? Just ask
a group of residents on Hamilton mountain. They've successfully
lobbied Hamilton Wentworth councilors to change their mind over
the placement of a traffic light, at a cost of several thousand
dollars. Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>Traffic engineers tell us they work a fine balance between
what's best for pedestrians and what's best for drivers. This
time, the scale tipped to favour pedestrians. </I>
<P>
<I>Joan McGraw had some weight behind making the change here on
Hamilton mountain's Fennell Avenue. Gathering names in her neighbourhood,
she's convinced Hamilton Wentworth's Transportation Services Committee
to move a light one block east to accommodate school kids. The
move comes with a hefty price tag. </I>
<P>
<I>While a new traffic light may pacify some pedestrians, many
drivers we spoke with wonder if it's really necessary. </I>
<P>
<I>Traffic engineers say new signs or lights usually stem from
complaints. But they don't want to stop traffic at every block,
for fear of sending angry drivers away from main arteries and
onto secondary streets. </I>
<P>
<I>If Hamilton Wentworth council approves changing the light at
the centre of this dispute, it could take a couple of weeks before
the move is officially made.</I> 
<P>
Hamilton Wentworth regional council will vote on moving the Fennell
avenue traffic light on July 16th. 
<HR>

<H3>Wheelchair Busses </H3>

<P>
Come September, people in wheelchairs may become free passengers
aboard the Hamilton Street Railway. The HSR has introduced one
of 25 new accessible low floor buses into its fleet. 
<P>
The &quot;Alf&quot; buses are designed to supplement, not replace
the current disabled and aged regional transport system. Starting
September first, every other bus on the city's four busiest routes
... the King, Barton, Upper Wentworth and Upper Wellington, will
be wheelchair accessible. 
<P>
In a proposal to Hamilton city council, the HSR is recommending
wheelchair passengers and their escorts board the buses for free.
The HSR will be introducing 25 such busses each year for the next
three years. 
<HR>

<H3>Victoria Crash </H3>

<P>
Three people are in hospital tonight, after a two vehicle crash
in downtown Hamilton. A man standing at the corner of King William
and Victoria was hit after two cars collided in the intersection.
He and both female drivers of the cars are being treated for non-life
threatening injuries. One of the drivers has been charged with
failing to stop for a red light. 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Fall </H3>

<P>
A 13-year-old Niagara Falls girl is in hospital with broken bones
after falling from a third-floor balcony. 
<P>
Police say Amanda Lawrence was trying to climb from one balcony
to another yesterday morning when she slipped and fell about eight
metres to the ground. The teen suffered two broken wrists and
minor facial and leg abrasions. Lawrence had successfully made
the dangerous climb several times in the past. 
<HR>

<H3>Mtn. Heroes </H3>

<P>
Two men with a keen eye on their Hamilton mountain neighbourhood
are being commended by police for their actions this weekend.

<P>
On Saturday, they spotted three suspects trying to break into
a house on their block... a house the pair knew was empty because
the owners were on holidays. They managed to tackle one of the
suspects, and held him until police arrived. 
<P>
19 year old Michael Belmont of Hamilton is charged with attempted
break and enter. 
<HR>

<H3>Most Wanted </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police are asking the public to help
them find a man wanted on a string of charges, including criminal
harassment, forcible confinement, making death threats, and assault
causing bodily harm. 
<P>
34-year-old Harry James Staats is this month's most wanted man.
He is white, five-foot-eleven, weighs 173 pounds, and has green
eyes, a moustache and shoulder-length brown hair. Staats wears
an earring, and has a tattoo of skulls on his upper right arm.

<P>
The charges stem from an incident in March, when a woman on James
Street North in Hamilton was choked, threatened and forcibly confined.
Anyone with information on Staat's whereabouts is urged to call
Crime Stoppers at 522-8477. 
<HR>

<H3>Hydrofoil Launch </H3>

<P>
Finally tonight, the &quot;Sunrise Six&quot; is headed south.
The refurbished hydrofoil was officially launched in St. Catharines
today after spending the last three years in dry-dock and will
make its new home along the Detroit river. 
<P>
Its operator, the Mississauga based Jackpot Express Lines is hoping
the gamble will pay off . The 20-tonne, 68-passenger vessel along
with its sister ship will ferry people between Windsor and Detroit
in hopes of cashing in on customers of the Windsor casino. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

