<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/26/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, June 26, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton Poverty 
<LI>Medical Reform 
<LI>Butt Out 
<LI>QEW Crash 
<LI>Blind Disposal 
<LI>Mother Mourns 
<LI>Niagara Strike 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Poverty </H3>

<P>
Montreal is home to a lot of poor people. A national survey indicates
that 22 percent of Montreal's population lives below the poverty
line. Hamilton was about half way down the list of 25 cities surveyed
with 15 percent of the population considered poor. As Dwight Ryan
reports, the outlook for the future of the poor isn't very bright.

<P>
<I>Kathy Bass is considered poor. The mother of three receives
nearly $1600 a month in government cheques, but rent and utilities
consume nearly 1200 of that. She's not alone. </I>
<P>
<I>The Canadian Council on Social Development says 15 percent
of the Hamilton population lives below the poverty line. Kathy
Bass fears for her daughter Casey's future. </I>
<P>
<I>At Family Services of Hamilton Wentworth, counselor Mary Mills
says the nation's poor need to be educated. With fewer government
dollars available, agencies like the Northend Children's Centre
find it more and more difficult to help those in need. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Medical Reform </H3>

<P>
Promised reforms to Ontario's medical system have been put on
hold, again. Health minister Jim Wilson says, the long awaited
package has been held up, while the government makes a decision
on new fees for proposed pilot projects. 
<P>
The reform package was supposed to be unveiled in April ... but
the announcement has now been put off until the middle of July.

<P>
Although no definite details of the plan have yet been released;
at least one group is already taking shots at the package. The
medical reform group says the government plan is little more than
window dressing; designed to appease the OMA. 
<HR>

<H3>Butt Out </H3>

<P>
The city of Hamilton has decided not to pursue an apology from
the Toronto Sun over a cartoon depicting east Hamiltonians as
&quot;buttheads.&quot; 
<P>
The cartoon appeared in last Wednesday's edition, two days after
constituents in the east Hamilton riding re-elected Sheila Copps
to parliament. The cartoonist responsible, Andy Donato says it
was a comment on those who voted for Sheila Copps in a recent
by-election. Ian Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>Councilor Chad Collins brought the motion forward demanding
an apology from the Toronto Sun for this cartoon portraying residents
of east Hamilton as butt heads. But not many heeded call. A bummed
out Chad Collins sat and listened. </I>
<P>
<I>Geraldine Copps whose daughter Sheila prompted the cartoon
opted to sit this one out. Taking it all in was a Toronto Sun
reporter. </I>
<P>
<I>Council defeated the motion demanding an apology and or an
investigation by the Ontario Press Council. Collins says he just
wanted to stand up to the Toronto media for its Hamilton bashing.
</I>
<P>
<I>In the end city council voted to butt out, turn the other cheek
if you will perhaps avoiding bigger stink. </I>
<HR>

<H3>QEW Crash </H3>

<P>
It was a spectacular accident, but the OPP say, the driver of
the car that rolled over on the QEW near Burlington Street this
morning, was not seriously injured. 
<P>
Police are still investigating the cause of the single car crash;
and have not made a decision about possible charges in the case.
While injuries and damages may have been minor ... the accident
caused major headaches, for morning drivers. 
<HR>

<H3>Blind Disposal </H3>

<P>
In response to Health Canada's warning regarding plastic PVC mini
blinds and the possible dangers associated with exposure to the
lead content, the region of Hamilton Wentworth is recommending
the blinds be taken back to the place of purchase or; take them
to one of three regional transfer stations beginning no later
than July first. 
<P>
The region's solid waste stations are open from eight in the morning
to 6 p-m Monday to Saturday. Residents of Hamilton Wentworth are
being asked not to dispose of polyvinyl chloride mini blinds with
their regular household garbage. 
<P>
Health Canada has set up a toll-free hotline for those concerned
with disposal or questions about the blinds. The number is 1-800-693-3131.

<HR>

<H3>Mother Mourns </H3>

<P>
The mother of four children who died in a fire in their Kitchener
home blames herself for not being able to rescue them. 
<P>
Leanne Dombroskie says &quot;I hate myself when I think about
it because I'm their mother. I'm supposed to protect them.&quot;

<P>
Eight-year-old Angela Dombroskie, four-year-old David Dombroskie,
four-year-old Jamie Burns and two-year-old Devin Burns died June
11th. Leanne Dombroskie says her fatal mistake was misjudging
the ferocity of the fire and how quickly it would spread.
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Strike </H3>

<P>
A strike by 146 members of the United Steelworkers' local 4151
against Washington Mills Electro Minerals has started after rejection
of the company's offer of a 3.5-per-cent wage-and-benefit increase
over two years. 
<P>
The union, representing both production and office-and-technical
employees, says the overwhelming rejection was also based on proposed
changes in the company's hiring practice and over-use of temporary
help. 
<P>
The company makes crude abrasives for use on sand paper, grinding
wheels and other applications. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
A renewed fear that interest rates might rise soon, contributed
to a selloff of stocks in New York and Toronto today. 
<P>
Interest yields on Canadian government bonds edged lower. 
<P>
Economists at Scotiabank are forecasting higher interest rates
later this year. 

<P>
