<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/25/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, June 25, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Hamilton Teachers 
<LI>Tobacco Control 
<LI>Missing Dad 
<LI>Niagara Body ID 
<LI>Hire A Student 
<LI>Macdonald Westcom 
<LI>Business First
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Teachers</H3>

<P>
The Hamilton Board of Education is faced with trimming millions
from its 1996 budget. Much of the money will have to come from
contract talks with eleven bargaining units. 
<P>
Elementary teachers will go back to the bargaining table tomorrow,
but high school talks remain at an impasse. Dwight Ryan reports
tonight that the province has appointed a fact-finder in an attempt
to get those negotiations underway. 
<P>
<I>For school boards across Ontario, times are tough. Transfer
payments from Queen's Park have been slashed since the Tories
took power a year ago. </I>
<P>
<I>In Hamilton, board of education trustees have come up with
a budget that includes more than 11 million dollars in reductions.
And they say five million will come from contract negotiations.
A plan to chop 72 jobs from elementary schools has been put aside..
at least for the time being. Library services, design and technology,
guidance and family studies programs would be trimmed and the
jobs would be lost. But both sides will return to the bargaining
table Wednesday. </I>
<P>
<I>Board trustee and negotiator Ray Mulholland says the high school
teachers must realize that the pie is now much smaller. That the
amount of money available is smaller. The high school teachers
meanwhile, have charged the board with bad faith bargaining. </I>
<P>
<I>Ray Mulholland says the teachers and the board together are
like a family.. and that right now the family is in dispute. He's
optimistic the dispute will be resolved before school returns
in September. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Tobacco Control </H3>

<P>
The use of tobacco by adults is declining, but young people are
picking up the habit in increasing numbers. Attempting to put
the brakes on the problem, alarmed Hamilton Wentworth public health
officials today unveiled a tobacco prevention program. Alex Reynolds
reports. 
<P>
<I>The campaign is aimed at retailers who defy the tobacco control
act and continue to sell smokes to minors. A concentrated five
week blitz, beginning July 1st, includes bus ads, print, radio
and television announcements. </I>
<P>
<I>However, the good news has turned to bad. Regional public health
department staff conduct compliance surveys in which an adult
chaperone and a visibly underage minor visit random retail establishments
that sell tobacco. We tagged along as 15-year-old Nicole shopped
for cigarettes. The clerk claimed Nicole looked over 19, while
the manager told us store policy forbids sales to minors. Across
the street, Nicole was questioned about her age. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Missing Dad </H3>

<P>
Hamilton police are asking for the public's help in finding a
missing east end resident. Police say 33 year old Stephen Kelly
dropped his children off at school yesterday morning and failed
to show up for work. His car was found locked at the Centre Mall.

<P>
Police say Kelly was depressed over personal problems. Anyone
with information should call detectives at 546-2957. 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Body ID </H3>

<P>
Police have identified a body found in the Niagara River near
Fort Erie as that of 35-year-old Jose Defrias Junior. 
<P>
Defrias had been missing since June 17th when he decided to go
for a swim while fishing with family and friends. He dove off
a nearby bridge and never resurfaced. His body was discovered
yesterday afternoon by a fisherman. 
<HR>

<H3>Hire A Student </H3>

<P>
It was a party atmosphere this noon hour at Burlington's Civic
Square. The Canada Employment Centre for Students held a free
barbecue for Burlington business people to draw attention to the
services they provide during hire a student week. 
<P>
Unemployed students also provided a fashion show hoping to grab
the attention of potential employers. And the Student Employment
Centre will provide a free car wash tomorrow at the Canadian Tire
store at Fairview and Cumberland in Burlington. 
<HR>

<H3>Macdonald Westcom </H3>

<P>
News from the executive offices here at CHCH. Channel 11 President
and C.E.O., Jim Macdonald has been named President of Westcom
TV Group - the entire television division of our parent company
WIC Western International Communications. 
<P>
Jim takes over for Donald Smith who is retiring after 45 years
of outstanding service in broadcasting. Jim will also stay on
here at CHCH. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Not much change in stock prices today but the interest yield on
Canadian government bonds moved lower again. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened to its highest level in two months.

<P>
Dofasco's joint-venture mini mill in Kentucky is facing pollution
charges. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

