<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, June 21, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Fruit Fatal 
<LI>Burlington Fatal 
<LI>Niagara Falls Fatal 
<LI>Stabbings 
<LI>Herbie Sex Charges 
<LI>Welland Fraud 
<LI>NDP Convention
<LI>Hamilton Ideas 
<LI>Berry Illness 
<LI>Hamilton Teachers 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Fruit Fatal </H3>

<P>
A freak farm accident has claimed the life of a young Greensville
boy. At about two thirty this afternoon a three year old boy was
crushed when a table fell on top him. The table was located inside
a roadside fruit stand on a family farm at the intersection of
Sydenham and Fallsview roads. 
<P>
According to the police the young lad was playing around the table
and accidentally pulled it over on top of himself. The boy was
taken to Chedoke-McMaster hospitals were he was pronounced dead.

<HR>

<H3>Burlington Fatal </H3>

<P>
Burlington OPP are looking for witnesses to a fatal accident at
the plains road exit and the QEW overnight. It happened when a
northbound car crashed head-on into a southbound car traveling
in the same passing lane. 
<P>
60 year-old Bernard Ansel of North York was killed; the other,
31-year-old Samuel Hill of Fort Erie, was taken to Hamilton General
with serious injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Falls Fatal </H3>

<P>
Police in Niagara are also looking for witnesses after an elderly
Niagara Falls man was hit by a car this morning. Tonight he is
fighting for his life in a Hamilton hospital. 
<P>
The victim who's name still hasn't been released was struck while
crossing Montrose Road in Niagara Falls. He is suffering a broken
neck and severe head injuries. Police are asking any witnesses
to this accident to contact the traffic unit. 
<HR>

<H3>Stabbings </H3>

<P>
Police are trying to sort out a double stabbing that took place
in Hamilton last night. According to the police, the two men in
their early twenties were stabbed when they jumped another man
inside an Eastbourne Avenue apartment. None of the injuries was
life threatening. 
<HR>

<H3>Herbie Sex Charges </H3>

<P>
&quot;Herbie the clown&quot; a popular children's entertainer
is facing numerous sex assault charges involving two teenage boys.

<P>
Herbie, also known as Donald Edward Herbert of Fort Erie was charged
in connection with assaults that took place over 15 years ago.
The 59 year old has entertained kids across the province. He will
appear in a Fort Erie court July 7th. 
<HR>

<H3>Welland Fraud </H3>

<P>
A Port Colborne insurance agent will appear in court July 17th,
charged with bilking numerous people out of 900 thousand dollars
from 1982 to 1995. 
<P>
Forty eight year old Frank John Pizzati has been charged with
defrauding the public over five thousand dollars. 
<HR>

<H3>NDP Convention</H3>

<P>
Never again. Ontario's New Democrats admit the social contract
was a mistake. At their leadership convention in Hamilton today,
delegates overwhelmingly approved a resolution that would ban
any legislation that doesn't respect collective agreements. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Ideas </H3>

<P>
Another group of politicians were huddling in Hamilton over the
future of the city's stagnant downtown core. It's been the subject
of debate for years, but today a braintrust of architects, business
people, bankers and residents put their heads together to develop
a serious vision of a new downtown that will one day thrive. Jamie
West has the story... 
<P>
<I>Can a new Gore Park fountain translate into a fountain of economic
activity for downtown Hamilton... these people ..think so but
only as part of a bigger plan... ...one that will create less
of this and more of this. </I>
<P>
<I>The Hamilton Society of Architects has brought together architects,
business people, developers, politicians and the general public...
their two day brainstorming session will result in a new vision
for downtown on paper ... out of date tax levees and absentee
landlords continue to plague the core.</I>
<P>
<I>Michael Stearn is from Pittsburgh. another city moving from
a manufacturing base to a technology driven economy... </I>
<P>
<I>The Hamilton downtown ideas charette wraps up Saturday evening.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Berry Illness </H3>

<P>
A 51-year-old Hamilton man has been diagnosed as a victim of a
parasite linked to American-grown strawberries. He's the first
person outside the Toronto area known to have been infected with
the parasite. The man had been ill for about a month before tests
confirmed he was suffering from a cyclospora parasitic infection.

<P>
Cyclospora, which is treated with antibiotics, can cause diarrhea,
stomach cramps, nausea, vomiting and fatigue for several weeks.
Health officials in Ontario are asking the public to thoroughly
wash all American-grown strawberries before eating them. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Teachers </H3>

<P>
Some members of the Hamilton Board of Education may be spending
the weekend working ...trying to negotiate a deal with the union
representing 73 teaching positions with the Hamilton Board of
Education has been placed in the hands of its bargaining unit.

<P>
The board could have axed the non mandated teachers last night,
but decided to table the motion to try and reach a negotiated
solution with the elementary branch affiliates. 
<P>
The 73 teaching positions are in the areas of guidance, library,
design and tech, and family studies. The two sides are expected
to get together today and if necessary over the weekend. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stocks dropped again today. However US share prices made
a big recovery. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened while interest yields on Canadian
government bonds moved lower. 

<P>
