<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/18/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, June 18, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Ham. East Follow
<LI>Two Year Old Drowns 
<LI>Grieving Mother 
<LI>School Guard 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Berries - Rain 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Ham. East Follow</H3>

<P>
Sheila Copps is on her way back to Ottawa tonight after kicking
butt in Hamilton East. The reborn MP for Hamilton East has been
invited to attend the weekly Liberal caucus meeting tomorrow where
she could be re-appointed to the Jean Chretien cabinet. 
<P>
Copps, who has represented Hamilton East riding for 12 years,
took more than 12-thousand votes in last night's by-election.
That's nearly twice the number of her nearest rival, NDP candidate
Wayne Marston. The Reform Party came in fourth after the Tories.
Scot Urquhart reports. 
<P>
<I>It was over in a hurry: less than 40 minutes after the polls
closed; Sheila Copps knew she was going back to Ottawa. </I>
<P>
<I>In her victory speech, the master politician knew exactly what
to do... accused of breaking promises; she sounded properly chastised:
she hit all the right notes: and she allowed herself to gloat,
just a little.</I>
<P>
<I>Even though she won by a two to one margin ... Copps majority
was considerably reduced from the last general election. NDP candidate
Wayne Marston for example got nearly four times the number of
votes, and NDP leader Alexa Mcdonough says, that should give Jean
Chretien pause to think.</I>
<P>
<I>But according to Copps, that is exactly what it means: and
with a phone call from the prime minister only moments after the
polls closed; it is likely that Copps will be leading the harmonization
fight; from cabinet.</I>
<P>
<I>Copps took the biggest gamble a politician can take ... and
won handily: but having survived this, Copps cachet in Ottawa
will be virtually, unmatched. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Two Year Old Drowns </H3>

<P>
A two year old Niagara on the Lake boy is dead after he fell into
his a pond behind his family's concession 7 home. 
<P>
The body of James Schrubba was pulled from the water by his distraught
mother. He had been outside with his mother and grandmother when
they noticed he was missing. The child was pronounced dead at
hospital.
<HR>

<H3>Grieving Mother </H3>

<P>
The mother of a murdered two year old St. Catharines boy has broken
her silence. Last month, Timothy Jackson's lifeless body was found
inside the home he shared with his father. His mother Laura Jackson
had given custody of Timothy to his father two months before.

<P>
Paul Dunn is still behind bars charged with the baby's murder.
As Lauran Sabourin reports Laura Jackson wants to answer accusations
that she didn't care about her baby's welfare. 
<P>
<I>The evening of May 24th. Police and paramedics were called
to 18 Oakdale Avenue where the saw the lifeless body of two year
old Timothy Jackson. Laura Jackson is Timothy's mother. </I>
<P>
<I>She had given temporary custody of timothy to his father. Two
and half months later the child was dead. Those who saw him say
they were shocked. He had cigarette burns on his body. Razor marks
across his chest. Chunks of his hair were pulled out. He was beaten
and bruised. So many people are asking why his mother wasn't around.
</I>
<P>
<I>Laura has two other children who live with her parents. She
said she left Timothy with his dad because she believed the child
would be cared for. Since Timothy's death his mother has created
a shrine in his memory. His stuffed toys. Pieces of clothing.
His running shoes hang on the wall. </I>
<HR>

<H3>School Guard </H3>

<P>
Parents in a northend Hamilton neighbourhood are calling it a
recipe for disaster. Students of Robert Land School will have
to learn to operate a new stoplight to cross Wentworth Avenue
North. 
<P>
The veteran crossing guard is being moved to another street, but
parents say she should stay where she is. And they're petitioning
city hall to keep her there. the story tonight from Dwight Ryan.

<P>
<I>For twelve years, Diane Smith has been helping kids cross Wentworth
Street North outside Robert Land School. Morning, noon and after
school, Diane has been there to make sure the youngsters safely
get to the other side of the busy northend roadway. </I>
<P>
<I>But a traffic light will soon replace her. Diane won't lose
her job, she'll go to a less busy street at the back of the school.
On Wentworth Street, the kids will learn to push a button and
then cross on their own. </I>
<P>
<I>Youngsters have been hit before at the corner, and school principal
Wanda Lane says the guard should stay. </I>
<P>
<I>Area residents have started a petition demanding that City
Hall leave Diane Smith at her post. Otherwise, the kids will be
on their own come September. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
For the second day in a row stock prices rose in Toronto. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar continued to weaken. 
<P>
Interest yields on Canadian government bonds edged slightly higher.

<P>
Laidlaw of Burlington, is proposing a new offer in its quest to
buy a fleet of six thousand school buses from Scott's Hospitality.

<HR>

<H3>Berries-Rain </H3>

<P>
The southern Ontario berry business has had a rough grow of it
lately. First a cold wet spring delayed the season a couple of
weeks, then concerns over use of a pesticide on California berries
prompted public health concerns....now local growers are wait
it out as the raindrops fall once again. 

<P>
