<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, June 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Votes- First 
<LI>Ammonia Leak 
<LI>Pool Tragedy 
<LI>Attacker Task Force 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Marci Award 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Votes - First </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton name dominates the national political landscape once
again. Will the Copps name regain its luster after the polls close
at eight o'clock? That's when the former Hamilton east MP will
learn the cards dealt to her by the constituents after resigning
over a promise to quit if her government failed to scrap the GST.

<P>
Ms. Copps, who says she is keeping her fingers crossed, took a
stroll with her husband this morning. She'll be casting her ballot
later this evening so she can vote with her mother. Alderman Geraldine
Copps had committee meetings all day. 
<P>
A Spectator poll last week showed support for the former deputy
prime minister had dropped but still stood at over 52 per cent,
New Democrat Wayne Marston was a distant second with just over
16 per cent, followed by Tory Angie Tomasic at 14 per cent and
Reformer Andy Sweck at just under 9 per cent. 
<P>
Today, in an informal exit poll, a majority of voters told Channel
11 News they'd voted NDP. As voters headed for the polls, all
13 candidates remained optimistic. 
<HR>

<H3>Ammonia Leak </H3>

<P>
Some tense moments this morning on Hamilton mountain. Fire fighters
were called out to contain an ammonia leak at a poultry processing
plant. The gas leak prompted the fire department to deploy its
decontamination unit, and forced firefighters to stay on the scene
for over three hours, while they dealt with a faulty pump system.

<P>
Luckily no one was hurt, but surrounding businesses were forced
to evacuate the area until the dangerous vapors dissipated. 
<HR>

<H3>Pool Tragedy </H3>

<P>
A sober warning about the dangers of pool parties as another school
year winds down: an unidentified Milton girl remains in serious
condition in Hamilton General Hospital tonight after a pool party
turned tragic over the weekend. 
<P>
The 18-year-old struck her head on the bottom of the shallow end
of a backyard pool. The young woman remained conscious but unable
to feel her lower body. Police say she sustained serious injuries
to her spine and neck.
<HR>

<H3>Attacker Task Force </H3>

<P>
The task force that was formed last year to try to catch a vicious
serial rapist who had attacked three children in southern Ontario
is being disbanded. And police won't say why. 
<P>
Lauran Sabourin reports, the team comprised of members of Halton
Peel and Waterloo Regional Police officers will wind down at he
end of the month. 
<P>
<I>Police know they are looking for the same attacker in all three
incidents because they are linked by the suspects DNA. </I>
<P>
<I>The first incident occurred in August of 1992 at a Kitchener
park. And eight year old boy was lured into a heavily wooded area
and raped. Two years later a 10 year old boy was attacked in broad
daylight in a park in Brampton. And then last august a 15 year
old girl was dragged into Burlington's Wildewood Park at gunpoint.
She was viscously raped over a three hour period. </I>
<P>
<I>Since the task force began it's probe they've investigated
over one thousand tips. They've investigated and have eliminated
over 700 suspects.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Investors ended a 10-day string of selling Canadian stocks sending
share values in Toronto higher. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar weakened, while interest yields on government
bonds remained stable. 
<P>
The United States and China reached a last minute deal to avoid
a multi billion dollar trade war. 
<HR>

<H3>Marci Award </H3>

<P>
And finally tonight, the Radio-Television News Directors Association
honored the best in broadcast journalism, in Brockville over the
weekend. 
<P>
The winner of the Dave Rogers Award for feature story coverage
went to Marci Ien, a former Channel 11 reporter. The award was
for her four part feature called, &quot;Journey to Freedom: The
Underground Railway,&quot; about the dangerous route taken by
many American slaves who escaped over the border to live free
in Canada. 

<P>
