<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/14/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, June 14, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Air Show - Traffic 
<LI>Ham. East Campaign 
<LI>Civics - Grievances 
<LI>Hill Park Fight 
<LI>Edgar Stabbing 
<LI>Skyway Crash 
<LI>Stelco Update 
<LI>Wesley Project 
<LI>Attempt Murder 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Air Show - Traffic</H3>

<P>
It's Friday. It's been a long cold winter in the golden horseshoe
but today the sun is shining for tens of thousands of visitors.

<P>
The Hamilton area is in the international spotlight for the air
show at Mount Hope, the Seniors PGA in Ancaster and the Burlington
Sound of Music Festival. Now, to reporter Dwight Ryan standing
by live at Mt. Hope with the air show. What's happening now? 
<P>
<I>It was a mini air show for volunteers and officials setting
up for the 1996 Hamilton International Air Show. Warbirds sat
majestically on the runways, part of the statis display for the
weekend event. Overhead, the thunderous roar of jet fighters practicing
for one of Canada's premiere events. </I>
<P>
<I>Gigantic military planes arriving including the stealth bomber..
a crowd pleaser that makes few Canadian appearances. </I>
<P>
<I>This year, the air show is a three day event with a nighttime
show tonight lighting up the sky. An fm radio station at 99.1
on the dial will provide visitors to the show with up to date
traffic information. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Ham. East Campaign </H3>

<P>
Never say never. Those words have taken on new meaning, in the
riding of Hamilton East. Despite polls to the contrary; there
are signs that not all is well for former deputy prime minister
Sheila Copps. And the riding once thought to be the safest Liberal
seat in Canada; has suddenly become very dangerous. Scot Urquhart
reports: 
<P>
<I>You are seeing something that is extremely rare ... the wife
of the prime minister on the campaign trail: and it may be a signal
that what was unthinkable seven weeks ago, is now suddenly possible.
</I>
<P>
<I>Sheila Copps could be, in trouble. Wayne Marston isn't talking
like someone who is running nearly 36 points behind in the polls.
Conservative candidate Angie Tomasic is convinced that Sheila
can be beaten; and despite the polls in the morning paper that
predict a landslide ... even Sheila Copps concedes, that the by-election
portrayed as a walk, has suddenly become a race.</I>
<P>
<I>Could the impossible happen? the voters of Hamilton East, have
two days, to decide. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Civics - Grievances </H3>

<P>
The union that represents nearly fourteen-hundred support staff
at the Hamilton Civic Hospitals filed 250 grievances today, to
protest layoff notices issued last week. 134 members of local
7-9-4 of the Canadian Union of Public Employees received the layoff
notices. As Deborah Walker reports, that represents nearly ten
per cent of the union's membership. 
<P>
<I>At the headquarters of CUPE local 7-9-4, they're counting up
the grievances. Another 250, bringing the total number of grievances
filed since the layoff notification procedure began to nearly
four-hundred. </I>
<P>
<I>The Civic Hospitals were close to eliminating a 20-million
dollar shortfall, when the province announced its was cutting
four-million dollars more than the administration expected. </I>
<P>
<I>Back at the CUPE office, Walters says the only positive thing
about the layoffs is that registered practical nurses, who are
represented by his union, are finally getting the recognition
they deserve. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Hill Park Fight </H3>

<P>
Another incidence of violence in a Hamilton high school. Charges
are pending against a 16 year old boy after another 16 year old
had his head stepped on during a fight inside Hill Park High School
on the mountain. 
<P>
The boy was taken to hospital, but his injuries are not serious.

<HR>

<H3>Edgar Stabbing </H3>

<P>
A fight at a house party near Centre Mall in Hamilton early this
morning has left two men injured and one charged. Police were
called to the home to find one man slashed in the arm, another
stabbed in the back, and yet another man hiding outside the house.
Both injured men have been treated in hospital. 
<P>
The third man, 26 year old Jose Chavez of no fixed address faces
two counts of aggravated assault and a count each of obstructing
police and failing to comply.
<HR>

<H3>Skyway Crash </H3>

<P>
A Niagara Falls man is sure to be counting his lucky stars tonight.
30 year old Brian Regle escaped, unharmed, even though a tractor
trailer flipped onto his car. The back of the car was completely
crushed. 
<P>
The tractor trailer, carrying auto parts, flipped as its driver,
38 year old Margaret Anderson of Burlington, was turning onto
the QEW from Burlington Street in east Hamilton. Police are still
investigating the crash, which closed at least one Toronto bound
lane of the QEW for six hours. 
<HR>

<H3>Stelco Update </H3>

<P>
Stelco's Hilton Works is back in business, and its employees are
back on the job today. On Tuesday evening, the Hamilton steel
plant shut down all production, after a power interruption caused
a malfunction in the system that provides air, steam and cooling
water. 
<P>
Some of the plant's units are already back in action, while its
two blast furnaces are gradually returning to full production.
The plant's general manager says the procedures employees followed
to safely idle the plant Tuesday evening have resulted in no permanent
damage to the facilities. 
<HR>

<H3>Wesley Project </H3>

<P>
It's been nine years in the making, but Wesley Urban Ministries
feels their new home in downtown Hamilton is worth the wait. Today,
they unveiled their new facilities to the public. 
<P>
The project was started when a need developed for affordable housing
in the downtown core. Wesley has closed its old drop in centre
and moved a few blocks over to a site where they can house singles
and families, and still supply hot meals in a beautiful new setting.

<HR>

<H3>Attempt Murder </H3>

<P>
Things not so safe this morning in another of Wesley's locations.
A man walked into the Kirkendall Strathcona neighbourhood house
with a semi automatic handgun, and tried to fire two shots at
a Wesley employee. Both times the gun wouldn't fire, and the worker
managed to jump the gunman and keep him under control until police
arrived. 
<P>
45 year old Horacio Alexandre of Hamilton faces several charges,
including attempted murder. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

