<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/13/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, June 13, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>McMaster Reactor 
<LI>Stelco Update 
<LI>St. Joe's/Civics 
<LI>Stabbing Arrests 
<LI>Robbery Roundup 
<LI>Citizens Arrest 
<LI>Most Wanted 
<LI>Palleta Cleared 
<LI>Austin Fired 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>McMaster Reactor</H3>

<P>
As government funding dwindles, or disappears, public institutions
like Hamilton's McMaster University, are being forced to reassess
the way they do business. And business is exactly what will turn
a one-time McMaster University liability, into a potential money-maker.

<P>
McMaster announced today that instead of decommissioning its research
nuclear reactor, it will keep the reactor operating, and operating
at a profit. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>One year ago, McMaster University decided to decommission its
nuclear reactor, because the million-dollar cost of running it
outweighed its research and educational value. But after reviewing
the reactor's sales potential in the private sector, McMaster
has developed a four-year business plan that will allow the reactor
to pay its own way. </I>
<P>
<I>McMaster projects the reactor can generate revenues of two-million
dollars a year, largely through sales of radioisotopes like iodine
125. The reactor is also valuable in measuring trace elements,
for instance in samples being assessed by the mining industry.
</I>
<P>
<I>Faced with cutbacks in government funding, McMaster University
will be looking at other areas of its operation to see if they,
like the reactor, can be turned into money-makers. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Stelco Update </H3>

<P>
Stelco still hopes to have full production restored at Hilton
Works by noon tomorrow. On Tuesday evening, the Hamilton steel
plant's central boiler station failed because of a power interruption,
and one of the boilers burst. As a result, the plant was unable
to provide steam for power, and water for cooling purposes. 
<P>
While repairs are underway, Stelco is trying to keep as many employees
as possible on the job by reassigning them to shipping and maintenance
work. Those who are not required have the option of taking a vacation
day, or a day off without pay. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Joe's/Civics </H3>

<P>
Another partnership day for Hamilton Civic Hospitals. Late yesterday,
more details of the merger between the Civics and Chedoke McMaster
hospitals were announced. 
<P>
Today, the Hamilton General and Henderson Hospitals have signed
a collaboration agreement with St. Joseph's Hospital. Annette
Hamm tells us what that deal will mean for patients. 
<P>
<I>It may be a few months before patients see the side effects
of this collaboration deal between St. Joseph's and Hamilton Civic
Hospitals. But both sides agree the effects will be healthy. That
means looking at both the support and clinical structures at all
three hospitals involved. </I>
<P>
<I>Examining housekeeping, and purchasing as well as medical specialties
before deciding which areas may move from one hospital to another.
No layoffs are expected because of the collaboration, but that
doesn't mean staff won't be cut from the Henderson, General and
St. Joseph's Hospitals. They still have to deal with provincial
cuts, but with the collaboration, any layoffs will be made across
the board, not just at one facility. </I>
<P>
<I>It's expected patients may see the effects of this latest partnership
next spring. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Stabbing Arrests </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police interrupted a basketball game
last night, and arrested four teenagers in connection with the
stabbing of a Hamilton high school student earlier this week.

<P>
Nineteen-year- old Long Dang is recovering from a punctured lung
in hospital. He was beaten with a table leg and stabbed after
being lured out of Sir John A. Macdonald High School Monday afternoon.

<P>
Last night, police surrounded a basketball court near Bay and
Cannon Streets where about thirty people were playing. They arrested
20-year-old Binh Quoc Pham, 18-year-old Dinh Khal Vuu, 18-year-old
Dung Quoc Huynh, and a 17-year-old young offender. All four have
been charged with aggravated assault. 
<HR>

<H3>Robbery Roundup </H3>

<P>
And police are now investigating another case of youth violence
in Hamilton. A teenager was assaulted and robbed of his ghetto
blaster while walking on King Street near Wellington around seven-thirty
last night. 
<P>
The robber is described as a white male in his late teens, with
shoulder-length black hair. 
<P>
About ninety minutes later, police were called to another robbery
scene. Someone tried to hold up Caesar's two-for-one pizza on
Upper Wellington Street just before ten o'clock. But the bandit
left empty-handed when the clerk failed to immediately hand over
cash from the till. 
<P>
The suspect was a black male, five-foot-seven, and in his mid-twenties.
He was wearing a green track suit with white stripes, a baseball
cap, and used a black scarf to cover his face. 
<HR>

<H3>Citizens Arrest </H3>

<P>
Some Burlington residents witnessing a break and enter in progress
last night called police and helped nab two would-be thieves.
Police say the pair had gained entry into garden city motors on
plains road intending to steal over a hundred thousand dollars
worth of computers and tools. 
<P>
Two Hamilton men are charged: 30 year-old Michael Sakins and 31
year-old Robert Uruski. 
<HR>

<H3>Most Wanted </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police are looking for a man accused
of trashing a Hamilton home. Late last month, a suspect damaged
the house and its furnishings while demanding to know the whereabouts
of a woman. 
<P>
42-year-old Peter Miles Stargratt is Crime Stoppers most wanted
man this month. He is five-foot-ten, weighs two-hundred pounds,
and has short brown hair, blue eyes, and a tattoo of a wolf on
his right arm. Police believe Stargratt, who's wanted on break-and-enter
and mischief charges, is staying in the Hamilton-Toronto area.
Anyone with information on his whereabouts is urged to call Crime
Stoppers at 522-TIPS. 
<HR>

<H3>Palleta Cleared </H3>

<P>
Four employees of a Burlington based food company have had criminal
charges against them thrown out of court. Pat Palleta, president
of Qualico Foods, his son Paul and nephew Vince Palleta and Daniel
Mullins were all discharged yesterday of 50 counts of conspiracy
during a preliminary hearing. 
<P>
The men were charged last year following a joint investigation
into complaints that Qualico was fraudulently exporting Australian
beef to the United States as a Canadian product to avoid high
tariffs. 
<HR>

<H3>Austin Fired </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Spectator editor Rob Austin has been fired. Publisher
Pat Collins says the firing is not a change in direction of the
newspaper, it's a change in the leadership of the newsroom. 
<P>
The 52-year-old Austin became editor in 1991. Managing editor
John Gibson will be acting editor until Austin's replacement is
found. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

