<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/12/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, June 11, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Tsubouchi
<LI>Hamilton Workfare 
<LI>Hospital Mergers 
<LI>Board Layoffs 
<LI>Youth Beating 
<LI>Young Stalker 
<LI>Stelco Update 
<LI>Tire Fire 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Charest-Hamilton 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Tsubouchi</H3>

<P>
Workfare has landed. It came to 20 Ontario communities today,
including Hamilton Wentworth. Social Services minister David Tsubouchi
made it official in Niagara Falls this morning and organized labour
was there to voice their displeasure about the controversial government
scheme to require able-bodied welfare recipients to work for their
money. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Workfare </H3>

<P>
There is no middle ground. Workfare is a love or hate it proposition.
And, as Scot Urquhart reports, reviews are mixed, before the program
even starts: 
<P>
<I>When Workfare landed in Hamilton Wentworth, the welcome was
less than warm. A group of demonstrators distributed pamphlets
outside the region's Joblink Resource Center ... panning Workfare
as something just short of forced labour. </I>
<P>
<I>So what's wrong with Workfare? Susan West knows a lot about
Workfare. She's writing a study for the Social Planning and Research
Council of Hamilton Wentworth. And rather than saving taxpayers
money ... Susan believes; we'll pay more in the end ... even though
the region attached a list of conditions to its Workfare agreement,
with the province.</I>
<P>
<I>But Alf Spencer swears, that the region will be keeping a sharp
eye on the bottom line. And the director of Direct Services says
the region will ensure that Workfare jobs supply meaningful experience,
without taking work away, from those who already have it.</I>
<P>
<I>The truth is that no one knows just how this great social experiment
will pan out ... but even if fails ... in social terms the Tory
government will succeed, in keeping a campaign promise.</I> 
<P>
About 85-hundred welfare recipients in Hamilton Wentworth are
potentially eligible for Workfare. It is anticipated that only
a few hundred at a time will be actively participating in the
scheme; due to a shortage of qualified placements.
<HR>

<H3>Hospital Mergers </H3>

<P>
At this hour, board members with both Chedoke McMaster and Hamilton
Civic Hospitals are pouring over recommendations for their merger.

<P>
They received the recommendation package late this afternoon on
how the new hospital, one of the largest in Canada, will be governed.
Annette Hamm reports. 
<P>
<I>In this closed door meeting, board members from both Chedoke
McMaster and Hamilton Civic Hospitals received the blueprint for
their future. The hospitals are merging into one hospital with
one board and one chief executive officer. </I>
<P>
<I>The Transition Committee overseeing the merger sought public
input in March. That input is included in the recommendations
presented to both boards. Staffing and budget levels won't be
decided by the transition committee, but rather by the new hospital's
chief executive officer. The committee is still interviewing for
that position, and should have an announcement later in the summer.
</I>
<P>
<I>The hospital merger is expected to be complete by December.
On Thursday, Hamilton Civic Hospitals will sign a collaboration
agreement with St. Joseph's Hospital. It's not another merger,
more a partnership to cut down on duplication of services and
improve on patient care.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Board Layoffs </H3>

<P>
And the financial juggling act continues at the school boards.
A Hamilton Board of Education committee has voted to eliminate
the equivalent of another seventy-three full-time elementary teaching
jobs. All the teaching positions are in non-mandated programs...
family studies, design and technology, guidance and the library
program. 
<P>
The decision was taken in light of the board's failure so far
to achieve five-million dollars in savings through negotiations
with its various employee groups. 
<P>
On a more positive note, another board committee, which is meeting
tonight, is expected to recall 134 of the more than two-hundred
elementary teachers who received layoff notices earlier this year.

<HR>

<H3>Youth Beating </H3>

<P>
An eyewitness to the murder of a Hamilton teenager was beaten
in the weight room of a Hamilton high school this week. 
<P>
The eighteen year - old, who attends Sir John A. Macdonald Secondary
School, was approached by a group of six or seven Asian students
from another high school Monday afternoon. They asked him if he
had seen the attack on 18-year-old Roberto Oliviera, who died
two weeks ago after he was beaten with a baseball bat at Lime
Ridge Mall. When the student confirmed he was a witness, he was
punched, kicked and hit over the head with a garbage can. The
victim broke free and ran for help, but teachers were unable to
catch his assailants. 
<P>
About an hour later, another student at Sir John A. Macdonald
was beaten and stabbed near the school, but police don't believe
there's any connection between the two assaults. 
<HR>

<H3>Young Stalker </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton elementary school student, who showered one of his
teachers with flowers and love notes, has been charged with criminal
harassment and threatening death. 
<P>
Police say the fourteen-year-old was infatuated with the 36-year-old
teacher, and left notes on her car, sent roses to her home, and
telephoned her repeatedly. His unwanted attentions came to an
end when he wrote her a lengthy letter, professing his love, and
threatening to kill another female teacher at the same school.
The youngster was arrested and charged yesterday. 
<HR>

<H3>Stelco Update </H3>

<P>
It will take up to two days to fix a problem that has brought
steel production at Stelco's Hilton Works to a standstill. 
<P>
Last night, the steel plant's boilers failed because of a power
interruption. That in turn caused a malfunction of the system
that draws water from Hamilton Harbour to cool production equipment.
More than 15-hundred steelworkers were on the job when all major
production units were forced to shut down. No one was hurt. 
<P>
Stelco says it will take twenty-four to forty-eight hours to restore
full operations. 
<HR>

<H3>Tire Fire </H3>

<P>
Five years later, the ashes are about to be buried after 1990
Hagersville tire fire. The New Credit Native Band will get a 450-thousand
dollar trust fund in return for letting Haldimand-Norfolk region
dump the waste in a landfill site next door to their reserve.
The band will also gain access to the region's water supply system.

<P>
For years, reserve residents have had to use bottled water or
poor quality water from wells. The fire, fed by a mountain of
14-million used tires broke out at Straza's Tyre King. It burned
for 17 days, spewing toxic chemicals and fouling the water. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
New economic data from the United States shows prices and inflation
edging higher. That contributes to widespread expectations that
interest rates might rise. Those conditions sent interest yields
on Canadian bonds higher today while stock prices dropped for
the eighth day in a row. 
<HR>

<H3>Charest-Hamilton </H3>

<P>
Federal Conservative leader Jean Charest is in Hamilton today
on by-election business. He's campaigning for Angie Tomasic, running
for the Tories in Monday's Hamilton east by-election. 
<P>
Tonight, Charest will meet with Hamilton high school students
who want tougher punishment for young offenders. He will also
campaign with Tomasic in Sam Manson park. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

