<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/11/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, June 11, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Kitchener Fire 
<LI>Apt. Fire - Baby 
<LI>Electrocution 
<LI>Stabbing Follow 
<LI>Hospital Cuts 
<LI>Workfare-Hamilton 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Welland Storm Damage 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Kitchener Fire </H3>

<P>
Tragedy in Kitchener. Four children -- who may have been playing
with a lighter -- died in a house fire early this morning, while
their frantic mother watched in helpless horror. The children
-- all under the age of 10 -- were trapped in the semi-detached
home about 7:30. 
<P>
The dead children have been identified as nine-year-old Angela
Dumbroskie, four-year-old David Dumbroskie, three-year-old Jamie
Burns, and two-year-old Devin Burns. Their mother, 27-year-old
Leanne Dumbroskie, had to be restrained by neighbors from going
back into the house. She was taken to hospital suffering from
first-degree burns to her face, smoke inhalation and shock. 
<P>
A firefighter was also taken to hospital, after he fell through
a burned out floor. 
<HR>

<H3>Apt. Fire - Baby </H3>

<P>
And, in Hamilton just before the noon hour, firefighters were
called to a small kitchen fire on Sanford North. An unattended
pot on a stove filled an apartment unit with smoke. 
<P>
An infant was taken to hospital as a precautionary measure. Damage
from the grease fire was minimal.
<HR>

<H3>Electrocution </H3>

<P>
And tragedy struck in Welland when a 25-year-old man electrocuted
himself while doing some home repairs. 
<P>
Police say Michael Stewart Levinski was installing an electrical
plug in his kitchen last night. He was found unconscious and rushed
to hospital where he was pronounced dead less than an hour later.
<HR>

<H3>Stabbing Follow </H3>

<P>
Police are still looking for four oriental male suspects after
an attack on two Sir John A. Macdonald High School students yesterday.
One was stabbed, the other was beaten with a table leg. 
<P>
As Ian Dovey reports the police are looking a motive and four
suspects. 
<P>
<I>Police have recovered the knife and the wooden table leg used
in the parking lot attack of two Sir John A. Macdonald High School
students. The victims in their late teens were ambushed after
school by four individuals. The police have no suspects...and
are not ruling out if this incident is related to another call
they received earlier in the day. </I>
<P>
<I>This incident is certainly disturbing, but some student we
spoke to say they're not surprised by the attack, saying violence
is almost a daily occurrence here. </I>
<P>
<I>The attack on these two young men occurred within hours of
a noisy student demonstration calling for tougher penalties against
young violent offenders. Students in Hamilton have been protesting
and circulating petitions since a 15 year old was charged with
murder after a teen was beaten to death with a baseball bat at
Limeridge Mall two weeks ago.</I>
<P>
<I>The victims of the Sir John A. Macdonald attack were taken
to the General Hospital. Police their injuries are not life threatening.</I>

<HR>

<H3>Hospital Cuts </H3>

<P>
Two hundred, twenty jobs are being eliminated at the St. Catharines
General Hospital. That's 20 percent of the General's workforce.
As Lauran Sabourin reports 100 people are taking early retirement,
120 employees will be laid off. 
<P>
<I>The layoffs will be phased in over the next 12 months. Every
group of employees from cleaning staff to hospital administrators
will be affected. Eighteen managers have lost their jobs. The
unions are still sorting out the numbers. </I>
<P>
<I>The General needed to cut 12 million dollars from it's budget.
The hospital had to look for ways to lower its costs. At the same
time it's urging the public to lower its expectations. The hospital
insists the quality of patient care wont' be compromised. But
the extras will be gone. As they put it's not a hotel.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Workfare-Hamilton </H3>

<P>
Details of the Ontario government's long-awaited Workfare program
will be unveiled at a news conference in Niagara Falls tomorrow
morning. At the same time, Hamilton- Wentworth region will find
out if it is one of the Ontario communities chosen as a test site
for the first phase of Workfare. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Billed as &quot;Ontario Works&quot;, the Tories' Workfare program
will require single, able-bodied welfare recipients to work for
their benefits. If Hamilton- Wentworth is chosen as one of the
first communities to institute Workfare, the region will begin
by consolidating existing services that help people find work.
After four months, recipients who have not found work on their
own, will have to take part in community projects or volunteer
work, or risk losing their benefits. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton- Wentworth will also work with the private and non-profit
sector to find jobs for welfare recipients.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stocks fell for the seventh day in a row. 
<P>
Interest yields on Canadian government bonds edged higher while
the dollar moved lower. 
<P>
Wescam, of Flamborough reported a big jump in its second quarter
profits today. 
<P>
Zenon environmental of Burlington has landed a six million dollar
contract in Taiwan.
<HR>

<H3>Welland Storm Damage </H3>

<P>
Parts of Niagara are still cleaning up after a series of powerful
thunderstorms rolled through the peninsula last night. In rural
areas of Welland and Wainfleet strong winds uprooted trees. Tree
limbs snapped, and power lines were downed. 
<P>
In St. Catharines power was out in sections of the city after
Hydro lines were downed there. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

