<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/10/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, June 10, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Region - Options 
<LI>Hamilton East Campaign 
<LI>Students-Demo 
<LI>Oakville Assault 
<LI>Simcoe Assault 
<LI>HSR Assault 
<LI>Pimps Busted 
<LI>Horton's Robbery 
<LI>Dundas Accident 
<LI>Suicide Threat 
<LI>Housing Starts 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Region - Options </H3>

<P>
Now that they've staked out positions on opposite sides of the
municipal government reform debate, the City of Hamilton and its
suburbs are willing to explore the possibility of finding some
middle ground. 
<P>
Today, city and suburban councilors faced each other for the first
time since Hamilton council proposed annexing its neighbours.
But instead of being confrontational, the atmosphere in the council
chamber was decidedly conciliatory. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Technically, there are now four options for municipal government
reform on Hamilton- Wentworth regional council's table. Every
one realizes the status quo is no longer acceptable, because of
provincial pressure for change. And there's little political support
for the constituent assembly's recommended model for a one-tier
regional government. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton proposes the creation of a super city, while the suburbs
want a modified two-tier system. In the interests of presenting
a unified front to the province, councilors have agreed to meet
in July to try to find a compromise between Hamilton and its suburbs.
</I>
<P>
<I>Even though all six local councils have rejected the constituent
assembly's recommendations, the group's co-chairman considers
its efforts worthwhile, if only because politicians were forced
to confront the need for change.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton East Campaign</H3>

<P>
And the politics of change will leave its mark on the federal
riding of Hamilton East one week from today. As the race heads
down to the wire, Dwight Ryan reports, at least one candidate
feels its a race between just two of the thirteen candidates.

<P>
<I>Sheila Copps is in the political race of her life. Running
for the seat in the commons that she resigned after the liberals
failed to can the GST. Liberal polling indicated she'd easily
retain the seat ..even though by-elections cost about half a million
dollars. </I>
<P>
<I>Even though there are thirteen candidates running in Hamilton
East, New Democrat Wayne Marston says only two are in the race.
</I>
<P>
<I>Heavy hitters from the Progressive Conservative party gathered
for breakfast at a downtown hotel in support of Angie Tomasic.
The guest speaker.. former prime minister Joe Clark. </I>
<P>
<I>Reform candidate Andy Sweck says the weekend endorsement of
Preston Manning shows the internal party turmoil is over. With
a week to go until voting day, he's confident. Copps meanwhile
says outside taxpayer groups won't be successful in their bid
to discredit her.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Students-Demo </H3>

<P>
Earlier today Hamilton high school students staged another noisy
demonstration downtown Hamilton to support their demands for changes
to the Young Offenders Act. 
<P>
The placard-carrying students rallied in front of Hamilton City
Hall, then marched to Gore Park, urging passing motorists to honk
in support. 
<P>
Students have been protesting and circulating petitions since
a teenager was beaten to death with a baseball bat at Limeridge
Mall two weeks ago today. A fifteen-year-old is in custody, charged
with his murder. 
<HR>

<H3>Oakville Assault </H3>

<P>
A nineteen-year-old woman was repeatedly beaten and raped in a
field in Oakville over the weekend. The woman walked into Hamilton
General hospital early Saturday morning and told medical personnel
she had been forcibly confined, sexually assaulted and beaten
in the field. 
<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth regional police later arrested a 23-year-old
man and turned him over to Halton Regional Police. 
<HR>

<H3>Simcoe Assault</H3>

<P>
A man is wanted for mischief after making a false claim that he
was confined and sexually assaulted in Simcoe. Haldimand-Norfolk
Regional Police say a man reported last Thursday that he had escaped
from a home where he had been kept against his will for several
days. Investigators say the allegations are false. 
<P>
Police have issued a warrant for 21-year-old Stephen Alexander
Bowman of the Toronto area. 
<HR>

<H3>HSR Assault </H3>

<P>
A 44-year-old Hamilton man has been charged with sexually assaulting
two women on Hamilton busses. 
<P>
Last night, a fifteen-year-old girl told her bus driver another
passenger had fondled her. Another woman aboard the bus complained
the same man had assaulted her last January. 
<P>
Police are urging any other women with similar complaints to contact
them. The suspect is five-foot-eleven, weighs 230 pounds, and
has graying brown hair with long sideburns. 
<HR>

<H3>Pimps Busted </H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police arrested two men over the
weekend, and charged them with running a ring of prostitutes.
Police say the women ranged in age from fourteen to twenty-four,
and were working in the area of Barton and Emerald streets. 
<P>
20-year-old John William Savage of Hamilton, and 21-year-old Douglas
Robert Smith of no fixed address are charged with extortion, procuring
for the purposes of prostitution, and living off the avails of
prostitution. 
<HR>

<H3>Horton's Robbery </H3>

<P>
A robber, armed with a handgun, held up a Tim Horton's doughnut
shop in Hamilton over the weekend. The man walked into the Tim
Horton's at Main and Wellington Streets, threatened the waitress
with a handgun, then fled on a bicycle. 
<P>
The suspect is described as five-foot-eight, in his early twenties,
and deeply-tanned, with black hair, green eyes, a round face and
a pot belly. 
<HR>

<H3>Dundas Accident </H3>

<P>
A Dundas man is fighting for his live after a single-car accident
early yesterday morning. Residents in the neighbourhood of Hatt
and Foundry Streets awoke to the sound of a loud bang, and discovered
a Camaro crushed around a Hydro pole. 
<P>
Rescue workers had to use the jaws of life to free the man from
the wreckage. He was taken to Hamilton General Hospital with life-threatening
injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Suicide Threat </H3>

<P>
A Hamilton- Wentworth Regional Police dispatcher is credited with
saving a man's life, and averting the evacuation of a Hamilton
neighbourhood. 
<P>
A suicidal man turned the gas on in his Fairholt South apartment
Saturday evening. While police prepared to evacuate the area,
a dispatcher spoke to the man by telephone. After twenty minutes
or so, the dispatcher had calmed the man down and talked him out
of his suicide plans. 
<HR>

<H3>Housing Starts </H3>

<P>
Good news today on housing construction and real estate in Hamilton.
Canada Mortgage and Housing says housing starts last month were
up 16 per cent over the month before. 
<P>
A CMHC analyst says continued strength in the market for existing
homes is helping potential buyers sell their current homes. 
<P>
Existing home sales so far this year are up more than 50 per cent
over last year. Construction is expected to remain strong with
stable mortgage rates. 

<P>
