<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/07/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, June 7, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Sesqui Celebrations
<LI>Supercity Reaction 
<LI>Hamilton GO 
<LI>Smoking Survey 
<LI>CIBC Diversity 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Sesqui Celebrations</H3>

<P>
The final plans have been put into place for the biggest birthday
party Hamilton has ever seen. The city celebrates its Sesquicentennial
this weekend but it comes at a time when the future of the city
and its suburban neighbours has once again become shrouded in
controversy. 
<HR>

<H3>Supercity Reaction</H3>

<P>
Hamilton- Wentworth's suburban mayors are not about to sit idly
by and watch the city of Hamilton swallow up their communities.

<P>
Yesterday, Hamilton city council rejected the local government
reforms recommended by the constituent assembly, and voted instead
to disband Hamilton- Wentworth region, and annex Hamilton's five
suburban neighbours. As Deborah Walker reports, suburban mayors
plan to fight what they consider Hamilton's self-serving proposal.

<P>
<I>The mayor of Flamborough finds it ironic that what started
as an exercise to improve local government in Hamilton- Wentworth,
has ended with the city of Hamilton trying to take over its neighbours.
</I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton councilors may outnumber suburban councilors, but
any regional council vote requires the presence of at least two
communities other than Hamilton. Without them, council business
grinds to a halt. </I>
<P>
<I>Both mayors believe it's better to compromise, perhaps by allowing
Hamilton to take over regional services, and sell them back to
the suburbs.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton GO </H3>

<P>
It was a no go for residents of the region trying to commute eastward
this morning and the disruption will likely last through the weekend.

<P>
All GO transit service west of Port Credit was canceled after
a train derailment just before five this morning. It involved
four cars of a CN freight train at an overpass in on Mississauga
Rd. The cars weren't carrying any hazardous material, and no was
one hurt but passengers at several stations, including Oakville,
Burlington, Hamilton and Aldershot had to find other ways to get
to work. 
<P>
It happened while engineers were trying to slow the train down
after a detector indicated there was a piece of equipment dragging.

<HR>

<H3>Smoking Survey </H3>

<P>
A survey on smoking trends shows smoking is becoming more unacceptable
in Hamilton Wentworth. The public opinion poll of just over a
thousand people was commissioned by the region and found that
71 and 72 percent of adult respondents respectively support stricter
bylaws to ban smoking in all enclosed public places and in the
workplace. 
<P>
And to the region's surprise the survey found that a majority
of smokers and non smokers would visit public places as often
or more if they became smoke free.
<HR>

<H3>CIBC Diversity </H3>

<P>
The CIBC in Hamilton has tied its employee diversity celebrations
into the city's sesquicentennial. The bank and its guests, including
the Sesqui mascot, shared a huge cake over the noon hour. It was
decorated with the flags of the 26 countries of origin of the
bank's employees. 
<P>
The bank says today's event shows its commitment to the diversity
of the bank and the community. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

