<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/06/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, June 6, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Ham. - Assembly 
<LI>Promotion Fraud? 
<LI>Apt. Fire 
<LI>Halton - Choice 
<LI>Cemetery Costs 
<LI>Child Found 
<LI>Nurses Jobs 
<LI>Jackman Quits 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Learned Societies 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Ham. - Assembly </H3>

<P>
Hamilton city council drew a line in the sand today... a line
that encircles all of Hamilton- Wentworth, and eliminates the
region, and its five suburbs. 
<P>
Confronted with conflicting recommendations on municipal government
reform from the suburbs and the constituent assembly, Hamilton
city council came out swinging today. At a special meeting, council
voted unanimously to disband Hamilton- Wentworth region, and to
swallow up Stoney Creek, Glanbrook, Flamborough, Ancaster and
Dundas. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>For more than twenty years, the City of Hamilton has paid seventy
per cent of the cost of running Hamilton- Wentworth Region. After
a day-long session, Hamilton city council decided the buck stops
here. Council voted unanimously to eliminate Hamilton- Wentworth
region, to absorb all regional staff, and to take over all regional
services. </I>
<P>
<I>By the year two-thousand, the city wants to expand its borders
to encompass the entire region, with one city council, one councilor
for each twenty-thousand people, and an amalgamated tax base.
</I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton city council's position is at odds with its suburbs,
who are willing to keep the region on a probationary basis. And
Hamilton city council rejected the report of the constituent assembly,
after a consultant told aldermen many of the report's assumptions
have no basis in fact.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Promotion Fraud? </H3>

<P>
It's not illegal. But it lives in the house next door, to that
neighbourhood. It's a telemarketing promotion that preys on the
good will of average citizens; and takes advantage of legitimate
charities. Scot Urquhart has the story: 
<P>
<I>They are out there, and they want your money. Regional police
are looking in to a number of questionable fund-raising schemes
... currently being used to part you ... from your cash. </I>
<P>
<I>One involves a so-called charity baseball tournament ... where
companies and individuals are asked to buy advertising space in
a program. Although Hamilton is listed on the flyer... Sgt. Bob
Wright says the regional police force is not involved.</I>
<P>
<I>A similar sort of promotion ... involves so-called newspapers
promoting ... fire safety, drug awareness ... or some other worthwhile
cause. Individuals are asked for donations, and sponsors again
are asked to buy advertising; the papers are delivered ... but
most of the money; is pocketed.</I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton Firefighters ... are among the organizations that
feel they've been burned by questionable fund-raisers... they
say they have nothing to do, with the fire safety newspaper. </I>
<P>
<I>Legitimate organizations say the telemarketers are taking advantage
of the good will of average people ... Rick Entwistle of Bowling
for the Disabled says it's tough enough trying to raise money
without phony fund-raisers taking scarce dollars out of the fundraising
kitty.</I>
<P>
<I>Sgt. Bob Wright says do some research, before you write the
cheque.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Apt. Fire </H3>

<P>
Careless smoking is the culprit in an afternoon fire that gutted
an apartment in a west Hamilton building. Tenants were evacuated
as firefighters wrestled with the problem of clearing smoke from
the structure's hallways and stairwells. 
<P>
The tenant in the affected apartment was treated at hospital for
smoke inhalation. Damage is estimated at 20- thousand dollars.

<HR>

<H3>Halton - Choice </H3>

<P>
Members of the Lost Souls motor cycle club in Milton have flipped
colours and joined the province-wide Satan's Choice gang. 
<P>
Halton Regional Police say the new club members have rented this
fortified clubhouse in a Milton industrial mall. Security cameras
keep an eye on the secure doors of the clubhouse. Police say the
club is frequented regularly by other club members and that they
too are watching what's going on. 
<HR>

<H3>Cemetery Costs </H3>

<P>
They've finally tallied up the damage at the Drummond Hill Cemetery
in Niagara Falls. Two hundred and eight historical monuments were
damaged or destroyed by vandals earlier this week. The damage
estimate is about 32 thousand dollars but will likely rise once
restoration work begins. 
<P>
Two fourteen year old boys are facing mischief charges in connection
with the vandalism spree. 
<HR>

<H3>Child Found </H3>

<P>
A 10 year old Hamilton boy missing since late yesterday afternoon
is back home tonight. Bradley McLean apparently left his fathers
home with plans of going to his mother's home in Windsor. He was
found unharmed but unhappy by a woman on Delaware Street, crying
as he pushed a box of clothing along the sidewalk. 
<HR>

<H3>Nurses Jobs </H3>

<P>
More than 100 registered nurses at the Hamilton Civil Hospitals
are receiving layoff notices this week. Connie Ross is head of
the union local representing nurses from both Hamilton General
and Henderson hospitals. She says patient care will suffer as
a result of the layoffs. 
<HR>

<H3>Jackman Quits </H3>

<P>
Dr. Jennifer Jackman, who made headlines as the top paid public
sector executive in Hamilton, has bowed out of the race for super
C.E.O. of a merged Hamilton Civic and Chedoke - McMaster Hospitals.

<P>
The Chedoke - McMaster C.E.O. since 1991 says her decision is
based on a lifestyle change. The merger plans were announced last
December and the decision on a new chief executive officer will
be made this summer. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Falling gold prices continued to trigger more selling of Canadian
gold mining shares today. That pulled the overall value of the
Toronto Stock Exchange lower for the fourth day in a row. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened. 
<P>
Interest yields on Canadian bonds edged lower. 
<P>
Trimark expanded its ownership of Dofasco shares to 12 per cent.

<HR>

<H3>Learned Societies </H3>

<P>
For the last two weeks Brock University in St. Catharines has
been hosting the 1996 Learned Societies Congress. 
<P>
Seven thousand professors have gathered at the campus to present
the latest research in their field. The Learned Societies event
is significant because it puts Brock University on the academic
map. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

