<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/05/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, June 5, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Waxman - Region 
<LI>Halton Middle School 
<LI>Kid Crime 
<LI>Cemetery Arrests 
<LI>Bank Hit 
<LI>Hydro Pole Down 
<LI>All Candidates 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Waxman - Region </H3>

<P>
The co-chairmen of the Constituent Assembly charged with re-shaping
municipal government in Hamilton- Wentworth, lashed out today
at the political response to their recommendations. 
<P>
In separate speeches, Don Granger and Chester Waxman accused the
region's six municipal councils of essentially dismissing the
constituent assembly's final report, which recommended the creation
of a single, stream-lined level of government. And both men say
the local councils seem more inclined to listen to consultants,
than to the citizens who elected them. Deborah Walker reports.

<P>
<I>Constituent Assembly co-chairman Chester Waxman told the Metropolitan
Hamilton Real Estate Board any talk of reforming government evokes
a strong emotional response. And he warns elected politicians
are not above inciting those emotions to protect their own turf.
</I>
<P>
<I>Waxman points out the Constituent Assembly spent a year talking
with citizens, before tabling its recommendations. In response,
he says the city of Hamilton and five suburban councils chose
to hire consultants, at taxpayers' expense. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Halton Middle School </H3>

<P>
And a restructuring is underway at the Halton School Board. In
an attempt to save millions of dollars, schools will be closed
and staff will be layed off. Included in the renewal plan is an
option to scrap middle schools. As Dwight Ryan reports, not everyone
is in favour. 
<P>
<I>Students in Miss Brook's high school music class. But they're
only in grades seven and eight. Its an idea trustees with the
Halton School Board are giving considerable thought to. </I>
<P>
<I>Skip the middle school, go from grade six in elementary school
to grade seven in high school. The Halton board has to save at
least 40 million over the next few years. </I>
<P>
<I>And it works according to Central High School principal Greg
Macpherson. </I>
<P>
<I>Bob Williams hopes trustees will approve the concept before
the end of June. If they do, middle schools will be a thing of
the past in Halton. </I>
<P>
<I>Teacher rep Erica Andrew says its a big mistake. If Williams
has his way, school closures can begin this fall. And students
in grade seven and eight will be in high school. Trustees promise
though, that those opposed to the concept will be heard.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Kid Crime </H3>

<P>
Canadian schools are not the dangerous hellholes that many people
believe they've become. That according to Dr. Rod Dolmage a youth
crime expert from the University of Regina. 
<P>
As Lauran Sabourin reports Dr. Dolmage believes that reports of
youth violence are exaggerated and he has the evidence to prove
it. 
<P>
<I>If there is evidence that points to an increase in crime committed
by teenagers, it's not that more youth are breaking the law. It's
that the activities of young lawbreakers are being reported to
the police more often. </I>
<P>
<I>Take a look at the newspapers and almost daily you'll see something
on youth violence. Even if the public accepts that teenagers involved
in violent crime are the minority, that most are generally good
kids, there is still the perception that teenagers just have no
respect for authority.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Cemetery Arrests </H3>

<P>
Police in Niagara Falls have arrested two teenagers and charged
them in connection with the rampage in Drummond Hill Cemetery.

<P>
More than 100 headstones at the 1812 historical site were knocked
over or destroyed. The graveyard was the site of the battle of
Lundy's Lane. American and British soldiers are buried at this
cemetery. 
<P>
The two teens are charged with mischief over five thousand dollars.
They will appear for a bail hearing in St. Catharines court tomorrow.

<HR>

<H3>Bank Hit </H3>

<P>
Two armed bandits robbed a west Hamilton bank branch today ...
the T.D at Aberdeen and Dundurn. Police say they wielded hand-guns
and ordered an elderly customer and staff members to the floor.
One of the robbers held a gun, while the other scooped the tills.
The pair fled with an undisclosed amount of cash in a stolen vehicle
which was recovered a short distance away. 
<P>
They were seen getting into a blue car. The men are described
as white, 30-to-35, five-eight. One has black hair... the other
has brown. If you have any information that could help, call police.

<HR>

<H3>Hydro Pole Down </H3>

<P>
Police in St. Catharines are searching for a hit and run driver
after a Hydro pole was knocked down this morning. A car skidded
out of control and rammed the pole which then fell across the
residential street. 
<P>
Hydro crews were on the scene and quickly removed the obstruction.

<HR>

<H3>All Candidates </H3>

<P>
It was a warmer reception for former deputy prime minister Sheila
Copps last night. After jeers and boos at an all candidates meeting
on Monday night, Copps was greeted with applause at a Beach Boulevard
debate last night. 
<P>
Candidates parachuted in from other cities were given a rough
ride, though, by some of the Hamilton east citizens. Many of them
say they don't want a stranger representing them in the house
of commons. 
<P>
13 candidates are running in the federal by-election, called when
Copps resigned over a GST promise. Hamilton east residents will
vote June 17th. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Gold prices fell sharply for the second day in a row. That caused
another steep drop in the value of shares on the Toronto stock
exchange. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened while interest yields on Canadian
government bonds remained stable. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

