<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/04/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, June 4, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Cemetery Vandalism 
<LI>Tolton Robbery 
<LI>Roy Missing 
<LI>Fire Death Follow
<LI>University Openings 
<LI>Superfresh Closure 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Cemetery Vandalism</H3>

<P>
Laura Secord is buried there and so are a number of military leaders
from the war of 1812. But the historic Lundy's Lane Cemetery in
Niagara Falls has been trashed by vandals. 
<P>
More than a hundred tombstones at the site of the battle of Lundy's
Lane were destroyed in a vandalism spree overnight. Lauran Sabourin
has more. 
<P>
<I>They were just beginning to assess the extent of damage this
morning. This graveyard was the site of the battle of Lundy's
Lane. Scores of American and British soldiers died here. The remains
of Laura Secord are buried in this cemetery. </I>
<P>
<I>The monument to Laura Secord was spared. But others around
her were destroyed. Granite stones pushed off their base. Tipped
over. Stones broken in pieces. </I>
<P>
<I>The police believe this was the work of vandals. Punks who
had nothing better to do. But the question people are asking now
how do you protect a public historical site.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Tolton Robbery </H3>

<P>
Police in Hamilton are looking for a 20 year old after a robbery
at the Tolton Food Market this afternoon. 
<P>
The suspect, believed to have had a gun stuffed in his pants,
demanded money from a female employee before putting the woman
in a back room and making his getaway on a white mountain bike.

<P>
He's described as 20-years old, 5-feet, 8-inches tall with a slim
build and short hair. 
<HR>

<H3>Roy Missing </H3>

<P>
And police are asking for help in locating a man who hasn't been
seen since April 1st. 65 year old George Roy of Main Street West
left for the west coast for a three or four week visit after leaving
his dog in the care of a friend. He hasn't been heard from since.

<P>
Roy is described as 5-feet, 10-inches tall, 185 pounds with brown
eyes and short receding brown hair. Anyone with information is
asked to call police. 
<HR>

<H3>Fire Death Follow </H3>

<P>
Counselors awaited the return today of students and staff to Hamilton
mountain's largest public elementary school. They were there to
console those shaken by yesterday's death of 13-year-old Steven
Pardiac. 
<P>
The grade seven student died of severe burns, after he was engulfed
in flames while playing with paint thinner during a weekend camp-out
in his family's backyard. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Outside, the flag at George L. Armstrong School on Hamilton
mountain flies at half-staff. Inside, eight members of the Hamilton
Board of Education's crisis response team are ready to help parents,
staff and students cope with the death of Steven Pardiac. </I>
<P>
<I>Professional counseling is also available to neighbours who
tried to help Steven, to the friends who were with him, and to
the firefighters who responded to the emergency call</I>. 
<HR>

<H3>University Openings </H3>

<P>
2800 students of McMaster University are to graduate this week.
For many, further education beckons. For others, its time to join
the work force....if there is a job. Dwight Ryan has our story.

<P>
<I>Words of wisdom and of hope from noted Canadian novelist Margaret
Atwood as McMaster's spring convocations begin. Atwood and noted
CBC journalist Margaret Lyons received honorary doctorate degrees.
They were among 2800 students who will graduate over the next
three days. </I>
<P>
<I>Graduation ceremonies for science and business degrees take
place Wednesday. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Superfresh Closure </H3>

<P>
A &amp; P is slashing about 600 jobs and shutting six of its 200
Ontario supermarkets by the end of August. All of the affected
stores are in southern Ontario including a Superfresh store in
St. Catharines. An Ancaster store has already closed. 
<P>
The 600 full and part time employees will be out of work. The
Canadian division of A &amp; P made a marginal profit last year
after losing money for three consecutive years. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stock prices were pulled lower by a sharp drop in the
price of gold. 
<P>
Interest yields on Canadian government bonds moved lower. 
<P>
New house building permits in Canada during may were weaker than
expected. 
<P>
Computer experts are advising companies to get their identity
on the Internet in order to keep up with the competition. 

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

