<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 06/03/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, June 3, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Regional Reform 
<LI>Burn Victim 
<LI>Dover Fatal 
<LI>Outlaws Arrest 
<LI>Falls Rescue 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Aspiring Model 
<LI>Hike for Health 
<LI>Model T - Shriners 
<LI>Big Bike 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Regional Reform</H3>

<P>
It's a new month and time is now running out for regional government.
The Harris government is determined to reform the regional government
system in Ontario. 
<P>
In Hamilton Wentworth, the constituent assembly recommended scrapping
local governments and going ahead with a leaner super region.
Surrounding municipalities were outraged and formed a common front.

<P>
Hamilton councilors have yet to formally respond and the deadline
is looming. Dwight Ryan has more. 
<P>
<I>It was two months ago that the constituent assembly presented
its final report on regional reform. A leaner super government
without duplication of services was their answer. Not unexpectedly,
surrounding municipalities were aghast. </I>
<P>
<I>What would happen to the identity of Ancaster, Stoney creek,
Dundas Flamborough and Glanbrook. They presented a common front.
Keep the local in local government said their response. Unofficially,
stay out of our back yard. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Burn Victim </H3>

<P>
A 13-year old Hamilton boy died this morning from injuries suffered
during a backyard weekend camp-out on Hamilton's east mountain.

<P>
Police say Steven Pardiac and three friends were trying to set
fire to some items when lighter fluid splashed on him. The flames
got out of control ... fully engulfing the boy. A neighbour used
a sleeping bag to try to smother the fire but not before he sustained
2nd and 3rd degree burns to more than 80-per cent of his body.

<HR>

<H3>Dover Fatal </H3>

<P>
Police in Port Dover began the week with an investigation into
the cause of a car crash that killed a Dunnville woman and injured
her 8 year-old-son. 
<P>
33 year-old- Margaret Bush died last night when her car went off
the road and hit a Hydro pole, just east of port Dover 8 year
old Dylan Bush is expected to recover from his injuries. 
<HR>

<H3>Outlaws Arrest </H3>

<P>
In a continuing crackdown on motorcycle gangs Niagara police have
laid additional charges against an outlaws gang member. 
<P>
Thirty eight year old Claude Longval is facing two prostitution
related charges. Longval was arrested last month during a police
sweep of biker hangouts. 
<HR>

<H3>Falls Rescue </H3>

<P>
A mystery man can thank rescue workers for saving his life after
he changed his mind about taking his own. A helicopter lifted
a man off a tiny island at the brink of the falls where he apparently
had planned to commit suicide. A passerby called police after
spotting the him stranded on gull island, about 100 metres from
the Canadian shore. 
<P>
Police won't reveal his identity other than to say he is a Canadian
citizen. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Stock prices in the US and Canada moved lower today. 
<P>
Analysts say investors are nervous that a strengthening American
economy might force interest rates higher. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar rose slightly. Canadian interest rates remained
stable. 
<HR>

<H3>Aspiring Model </H3>

<P>
Appearances can be deceiving. In a business where cosmetics, and
glamour are everything; there is a shooting star, with her feet
planted firmly on the ground. Scot Urquhart discovered her in
Burlington, today: 
<P>
<I>Walking through the halls of Burlington Nelson High School,
you might not notice anything unusual about Samantha Martin ...
other than she tends to stand a little bit above the crowd ...
but if you think that basketball is the passion of this six foot
one, grade nine student ... you'd be wrong ... modeling, is the
game that turns Samantha's head. </I>
<P>
<I>Samantha is doing more than passingly well, at the game ...
she is one of ten finalists ... picked from more than 10-thousand
new faces from across North America; in a talent search sponsored
by Cover Girl Cosmetics, and y/m magazine.</I>
<P>
<I>For someone with such a bright future, in such a glamorous
business ... she is amazingly down to earth: and those friends
quite obviously look up to her, in more ways than one</I>
<P>
<I>Although she's excited about the June 16th competition ...
Samantha martin is keeping things in perspective; and says she
won't be disappointed, if she doesn't win. For now, in many ways
she's just a typical teenager. But for Samantha Martin, the future
may soon be anything but typical.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Hike for Health</H3>

<P>
Hamilton hospitals say, it's an emergency ... health care is on
the critical list, and you can do something about it. 
<P>
Four regional hospitals: Chedoke McMaster, Hamilton Civics, St.
Joe's and St. Peter's have teamed up once again... to raise money
for regional hospitals with the annual Hike for Health. 
<P>
The hike takes place June 9th; on Hamilton's official sesquicentennial
birthday, and will actually cover four different routes; each
of varying length and difficulty. All routes will converge on
Macassa Park ... for a special Sesqui picnic:
<HR>

<H3>Model T - Shriners </H3>

<P>
There were wheels turning for charity today. Jack Harvey and Rod
Mizener set off from Hamilton City Hall this morning in a 66-year-old
model A Ford Roadster, for a 35-hundred mile round trip to Halifax.
Along the way, the motoring duo will raise money for the Shriners
Hospital for crippled and burned children. 
<HR>

<H3>Big Bike </H3>

<P>
And finally, it took a little longer to get this set of wheels
in motion. A bicycle built for, well 30, one of the biggest in
Canada. And the people pedaling it around Hamilton's Westdale
neighbourhood today, have some pretty big hearts. 
<P>
Seven teams of thirty people rode to raise money for Ontario's
Heart and Stroke Foundation. A team from the Hamilton- Wentworth
Regional Police force kicked off the first circuit. 
<P>
So far, over five-hundred teams in Ontario have taken a spin on
the bike, raising more than a million dollars for stroke research.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

