<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/31/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, May 31, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Students - YOA
<LI>Bikers Crackdown 
<LI>Copps Barbecue
<LI>Hamilton Clean 
<LI>HSR Hike 
<LI>Milton Jobs 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Team Mohawk 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Students - YOA</H3>

<P>
It was the sound of anger... it was the sound of fear... it was
an out-pouring of frustration. A rally by Hamilton high school
students who say they are sick of violence; and want changes to
the Young Offenders Act ... rattled the downtown core throughout
the noon-hour. 
<P>
The hastily planned demonstration was sparked by the brutal murder
of 18 year old Roberto Oliviera ..and the charges laid against
a 15 year old suspect, under the Young Offender's Act. Scot Urquhart
has that story: 
<P>
<I>They were determined to be heard ... the murder of Roberto
Oliviera has galvanized the anger of hundreds of Hamilton students
... and the object of their wrath is the Young Offender's Act.</I>
<P>
<I>The students called for Mayor Bob Morrow, to address them,
and get involved. He did. Promising to help organize a meeting
with federal and provincial politicians, to discuss the issue.
But the students didn't stop there ... they took their message
to the streets of Hamilton ... and staged another demonstration,
at Gore Park.</I>
<P>
<I>Clearly, these kids were angry about what they see as a rising
tide of violence in society ... and they say, lenient penalties
are to blame. But when pressed on the deeper issues, of what spurs
violence in the first place; there were no real answers.</I>
<P>
<I>If the rally was intended to draw attention ... it did ...
bordering at times on bedlam; drivers honked in agreement as the
students chanted, and pedestrians on the street voiced support,
with few exceptions. </I>
<P>
<I>The students plan another rally June 10th ... they are hoping
that demonstration against violence will be larger, and will involve
people of all ages... who oppose violence in society.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Bikers Crackdown </H3>

<P>
Police across Canada are preparing for war against outlaw motorcycle
gangs this summer. Niagara police have already begun a crackdown
on bikers with the arrests last month of several Outlaws members.
And now the Canadian Association of Chiefs of Police has developed
a campaign with other forces and the Criminal Intelligence Service
of Canada to curtail the illegal activities of biker gangs. 
<P>
Association president Tom O'Grady says the law enforcement community
is united in serving notice that public safety will not be compromised
by ruthless gangs intent on profiting from illegal activities.

<HR>

<H3>Copps Barbecue</H3>

<P>
In Hamilton- Wentworth, police hope the community-based approach
will help prevent crime, especially among young people, by developing
good relationships with the cops on the beat. Police are targeting
high-crime neighborhoods specifically, like the Lansdale - Stinson
neighbourhood. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Clean </H3>

<P>
There were few surprises today as members of the Keep Hamilton
Clean Committee embarked on their annual tour of the city's worst
litter spots. 
<P>
This mess belongs to the back yard of an abandoned home on West
Avenue North. Committee members could only say 'wow' as they first
laid eyes on the trash. 
<P>
Committee chair Ron Volterman says the annual tour draws attention
to homeowners and companies that don't clean up. He adds they
usually do after they're approached by City Hall. 
<HR>

<H3>HSR Hike </H3>

<P>
Hamilton transit riders will be paying a nickel more to ride the
bus. Starting tomorrow the cash fare for adults, seniors and students
will be a dollar, seventy five. The cash fare for children will
be a dollar, five. Monthly passes increase one dollar to 56 dollars
for adults and 41 dollars for seniors, students and children.

<P>
This is the first fare increase in more than two years. 
<HR>

<H3>Milton Jobs </H3>

<P>
There's still enough people buying cars to create some new jobs
in Milton. 
<P>
Johnson Controls has decided to build a new automobile seat manufacturing
plant in the town. The 10-and-a-half million-dollar facility will
be supplying seats for Corolla cars at the Toyota plant in Cambridge.

<P>
The new plant will mean the creation of 120 jobs in Milton. 
<HR>

<H3>Business - First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stocks rose to their 30th record high today. 
<P>
Rising prices for Canadian gold mining companies helped the rally.

<P>
The Canadian dollar also strengthened. 
<P>
New data released today shows Canada's economy continues to crawl
foreword at a slow pace. 
<HR>

<H3>Team Mohawk </H3>

<P>
After months of painstaking preparations, six pretty excited Mohawk
College students are on their way to Marshall, Michigan to race
in an event known as the Mileage Car Competition. This is a race
where distance determines the winner. 
<P>
Reporter Ian Dovey caught up with the pit crew before their departure.

<P>
<I>She rolls like a charm, but is the Tomahawk Five, a sixty pound
super mileage car, good enough to win the Society of Automotive
Engineers Competition?</I>
<P>
<I>Since January a garage on Hamilton's west mountain has been
the design and workshop of the Tomahawk Five, the brainchild of
six Mohawk College students. </I>
<P>
<I>The aluminum cockpit, and super modified Briggs and Stratton
engine are surrounded by a fibreglass shell. </I>
<P>
<I>Last year this group of industrial and mechanical students
placed 6th in north America, but the key to this year success
may lie in the rubber, wheelchair racing wheels. </I>
<P>
<I>The Tomahawk Five will go as fast as fifty miles per hour,
but speed is not important - it's the distance. The winners will
receive a thousand dollars.</I>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

