<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/30/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, May 30, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Youth Crime Follow
<LI>Oliviera Fund 
<LI>Extortion Plea 
<LI>Bain - Bernardo 
<LI>Simcoe Fatals 
<LI>Mcdonough - Hamilton 
<LI>Anti-Copps Signs 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Skilled Labor 
<LI>Experience Canada 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Youth Crime Follow</H3>

<P>
Two shocking cases of kids, killing kids have rocked the region
over the last week; and many parents are wondering whether youth
crime is out of control. 
<P>
There is even greater concern, when rumored plans for retaliatory
crimes circulate through area high schools. Scot Urquhart checked
into those rumours today; and reports that according to the authorities,
reports of runaway youth crime, are greatly exaggerated: 
<P>
<I>The fallout from the tragic beating death of 18 year old Roberto
Oliviera ... continues to unsettle the students of St. Jean de
Brebeuf High School.... according to principal Chris Fox. He says,
kids are wondering whether it's safe anymore, to go to the mall
... or come to school. ... his job, he says, is to assure both
the students, and their parents, that it is.</I>
<P>
<I>Despite rumours of an escalating feud between students of Brebeuf,
and nearby Barton Secondary School ... rumours so extreme... that
even a drive-by shooting has been suggested ... youth branch co-ordinator
Jorge Lasso says, there is no need to panic.</I>
<P>
<I>And do the police believe that kids are more violent than ever?
And doctor Clint Davis agrees .... he is the staff psychologist
for the Hamilton Wentworth Roman Catholic Separate School Board:
and part of the reason it rarely occurs in schools ... is due
to the intense focus on the issue; and the success of anti-violence
programs throughout the system. Programs where the message about
retaliatory violence; is made perfectly clear.</I>
<HR>

<H3>Oliviera Fund </H3>

<P>
The Portuguese Information Centre in Hamilton has opened a bank
account to help the Oliviera family with some financial difficulties.
They're welcoming donations from the community at the James and
Barton branch of the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce. Account
number 45-00814 
<HR>

<H3>Extortion Plea </H3>

<P>
Last week we told you about two teen aged girls from Simcoe charged
with extortion. The 16-year-old has now pleaded guilty to extortion.

<P>
Police say the pair threatened men by saying they'd claim to have
been sexually assaulted unless they handed over money. She'll
be sentenced next Wednesday. 
<P>
The other girl charged with extortion in the case, a 13-year-old,
has been released on bail. She'll be back in court June 12th.
<HR>

<H3>Bain - Bernardo </H3>

<P>
Convicted murderer Paul Bernardo's in the news again. A Toronto
man who has spent five years in prison for a murder he says he
didn't commit, is now pointing a finger at Bernardo. 
<P>
Papers filed with the Ontario Court of Appeal include fresh evidence
in the case of Robert Baltovich who was convicted of second-degree
murder in the presumed death of his girlfriend. 
<P>
Elizabeth Bain vanished in 1990 and her body was never found.
The new evidence submitted last week does not name Bernardo, who
was convicted of killing two Niagara-area teens. But it makes
reference to evidence presented at a trial concerning the Scarborough
rapist. 
<P>
Bernardo has admitted to a string of assaults blamed on the Scarborough
rapist -- the last, about the time Bain vanished. 
<HR>

<H3>Simcoe Fatals </H3>

<P>
A two car collision south of Simcoe claimed the lives to two people
today. The names of the occupants have not been released pending
notification of next of kin. 
<P>
Ontario Provincial Police say the accident happened before the
noon hour on east quarter line road south of Highway 24. 
<HR>

<H3>Mcdonough - Hamilton </H3>

<P>
There is a by-election in the federal riding of Hamilton east
because of Sheila Copps' stand on the GST. She admits her government
hasn't done anything about scrapping the tax and has put her career
and reputation on the line seeking a new mandate from voters.
But New Democrats say a vote for Sheila is a another vote for
the hated tax. 
<P>
And today, federal leader Alexa Mcdonough joined candidate Wayne
Marston in unveiling the New Democrats' view of taxation. Mcdonough
says the Copps name is not enough to ensure electoral victory
in Hamilton east. 
<HR>

<H3>Anti-Copps Signs </H3>

<P>
Here's the latest in the anti-Sheila equals anti-government sign
war. This billboard by the National Citizens Coalition is just
one of many that have popped up over the last few days in east
Hamilton. 
<P>
The coalition has launched a 20-thousand dollar campaign against
the former deputy p.m. The campaign includes radio spots along
with the billboard suggesting Copps lied to voters about scrapping
the GST when she ran for election in 1993. 
<P>
Copps resigned last month to keep a promise to quit if the GST
was not scrapped. 
<HR>

<H3>Business-First </H3>

<P>
Stock prices and the Canadian dollar strengthened today as interest
yields in bond markets edged lower. 
<P>
Toronto Dominion Bank reported a big increase in its latest financial
results. Many of Canada's leading financial advisors have contributed
their advice to a money planning guide. 
<HR>

<H3>Skilled Labor </H3>

<P>
The dawning of a new century may turn out to be the beginning
of a skilled labour crisis in Hamilton Wentworth. A new report
warns that as baby boomers begin to retire the area's employment
scene will face a shortage of skilled laborers ...Jamie West reports...

<P>
<I>A regular breakfast meeting at the Hamilton and District Chamber
of Commerce was the place to unveil Skillscape 96 a report produced
by local training broker TranSkills. </I>
<P>
<I>The report says that businesses have been too slow to ensure
they employ the type of multifaceted and flexible workers required
in today's marketplace. The report says government and the education
system have only paid lip service to training students in the
skill they need to compete.</I>
<P>
<I>Ron Wallace helps teach business operators and entrepreneurs
to adapt to the new world... simply put, in a world where the
technological innovation cycle has shrunk from five years a decade
ago to six months today, the workforce wants people who are skilled
at acquiring skills ... </I>
<HR>

<H3>Experience Canada </H3>

<P>
An employment outlook survey for this summer says jobs will be
hard to find in Hamilton. The Manpower Temporary Services report
says none of the area employers interviewed plans to hire any
workers over the next few months. 
<P>
But at least 500 unemployed or underemployed Canadians will get
a chance to learn some job skills and see another part of the
country under a new federal program. <I>Experience Canada </I>is
a joint venture of the Liberal government and the Council of Canadian
Unity. Participants from all parts of the country will take part
in a 10 month program aimed at helping them launch their careers.

<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

