<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/29/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, May 29, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Murder Update 
<LI>Manning-Hamilton 
<LI>Niagara Teachers 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Smoke Free 
<LI>Council-Beer 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Murder Update</H3>

<P>
We begin tonight with the question why? Why did a young Hamilton
man end up dead after a school yard spat? 
<P>
Yesterday we told you about the 15-year-old charged with second-degree
murder after 18-year-old Roberto Oliveira was beaten to death
with a baseball bat. Tonight why and how could this happen. Lauran
Sabourin reports that the violence that killed young Roberto earlier
this week is frighteningly more common than any of us would like
to think. 
<P>
<I>A crowd of students were gathered outside St. Jean Brebeuf
High School this morning. The only topic of conversation was the
battle that ended with the death of one friend. The incarceration
of another. </I>
<P>
<I>One teen who didn't want to be identified witnessed the fight
at Limeridge Monday night. Killed was 18 year old Roberto Oliveira.
A 15 year old has been charged with his murder. </I>
<P>
<I>These students say that solving disputes with weapons is more
common than you think. Students use weapons as tools of intimidation.
</I>
<P>
<I>The school board has sent crisis counselors to the school.
Counselors who are seeing tensions spilling over into violence
more often.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Manning-Hamilton </H3>

<P>
At Scott Park Secondary School, students are advocating a get-tough
approach to teen-aged criminals. Reform party leader Preston Manning
made a stop there today while campaigning for local candidate
Andy Sweck, who's running in the Hamilton east by-election. Anthony
Pooley reports. 
<P>
<I>The one thing that Reform party leader Preston Manning likes
to point out when he's talking about youth crime is that the victims
of teen-aged criminals are usually teenagers themselves. This
assembly at Scott Park Secondary School is a good case in point...
the vast majority of these kids support the notion of a Young
Offenders Act that's much tougher on teen-aged criminals. </I>
<P>
<I>Earlier, he took a giant step onto traditionally Liberal turf...
as he met with polish business leaders at a Barton Street restaurant.
At both venues, he said that the by-election is about jobs, crime,
and most importantly, political accountability. He also said that
there is virtually no possibility of Reformers and Tories formally
uniting... but he told reporters later that he'll give consideration
to the situation in Brant, where the two parties have decided
to nominate a single candidate. </I>
<P>
<I>This is Manning's second trip thus far in this by-election
campaign.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Niagara Teachers </H3>

<P>
Last-ditch talks continue in a bid to avoid a strike by separate
school teachers in Lincoln County. More than 500 teachers are
poised to walk off the job Saturday. 
<P>
Board spokesman Pat Pacecca says if there is a strike they would
be forced to close all of the board's schools because they couldn't
guarantee the safety of the students. Pacecca also says letters
are being prepared for parents explaining what will happen with
final exams, marks and graduation exercises if the teachers do
walk out. 
<P>
A strike would affect 91-hundred students. 
<P>
Meanwhile, teachers at the Lincoln County Public School Board
have ratified a new contract that calls for a continued salary
freeze. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Stock prices moved lower again today after interest yields on
government bonds moved higher. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar strengthened. 
<P>
Royal Bank became the third big Canadian bank to report another
strong quarter of improving profits. 
<P>
And the wireless communications industry in Canada is booming
with a shortage of engineers to fill existing job openings. 
<HR>

<H3>Smoke Free </H3>

<P>
You may find it a little bit harder to light up at lunch time
on Friday. Sixteen Hamilton restaurants are set to go smoke free
for the whole day or part of the day. 
<P>
As Jamie west reports...health services officials and restauranteurs
are viewing the exercise as an experiment... 
<P>
<I>The Regional Health Department may be fanning the flames of
the always smoldering smoke versus non smoke debate...but sixteen
Hamilton restaurants are ready to take part. Health officials
say breathing for one hour in a smoky room can equal as much as
smoking 35 cigarettes. </I>
<P>
<I>At the Portable Feast cafe on Queen Street... owner Misty Ingrahm
thinks her restaurant might go completely non smoking in a few
years... six of her best customers get together here once a month
to ash out the issues of the day ...they're all close cousins,
but sit miles apart on the smoking issue.</I>
<P>
<I>Some restaurants that have traditionally catered to smokers
have butt completely out ...with little pain to their owners pocketbooks.
Lee McBrides in Westdale ...will also take part &quot;in world
no-tobacco day&quot; and the owners say they'd go non smoking
completely if they were confident the patrons would fill the restaurant...
but for now smokers are welcome...</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Council-Beer</H3>

<P>
You may not be able to smoke in restaurants in Hamilton forever,
but you will be able to drink on the links. Last night city council
voted to allow beer and liquor sales on its municipal golf courses.
Ian Dovey reports. 
<P>
<I>Whether it's in celebration or despair golfers at Chedoke and
Kings Forest courses can enjoy a cold beer out in the open and
that pleases some golfers. Council approved a motion to allow
for the sales of beer and alcohol at its city owned courses but
by the narrowest of margins 9 to 8. </I>
<P>
<I>But there are limitations. Sales and consumption of alcoholic
beverages will only be allowed between the ninth and tenth holes,
which is about one hundred feet from the club house. Still, dissenters
say it's too risky.</I>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

