<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/27/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, May 27, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Health Council 
<LI>St. Kitts Strike 
<LI>Teacher Recall 
<LI>Dead Teacher 
<LI>Dunn - Court 
<LI>Regal Death 
<LI>Business First
<LI>Truck Inspections 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Health Council</H3>

<P>
The 79 recommendations that comprise the Health Action Task Force
studying the future of Hamilton hospitals went to the vote this
afternoon, it's been a long drawn out process that hasn't ended
yet. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Strike </H3>

<P>
And the numbers game continues on the education front tonight.
Catholic teachers in Lincoln have scheduled a new round of contract
talks with the board for Thursday, with a strike deadline set
for Saturday. 
<P>
The 550 elementary and secondary teachers agreed to strike after
the board imposed an almost five per cent pay cut. The Ontario
English Catholic Teachers Association says recent board decisions
will result in the loss of seniority rights and the possibility
of layoffs. The teachers have been without a contract since last
August. 
<HR>

<H3>Dead Teacher </H3>

<P>
A memorial service has been held at the Oakville school which
employed a teacher found dead in Quebec last Friday. 
<P>
After searching for the better part of a month, the body of Diane
Cross was found on the balcony of a chalet in the Laurentian Mountains,
north of Montreal. Police do not suspect foul play. 
<P>
She disappeared May first and her family thinks she may have died
of exposure while in a diabetic coma. It's near a summer camp
where she once worked as a counselor and contracted the virus
that led to her diabetic condition. Autopsy results could be released
tomorrow. 
<HR>

<H3>Dunn - Court </H3>

<P>
26-year-old William Paul Dunn of St. Catharines was remanded in
custody until June 14th for a bail hearing when he appeared in
court today. 
<P>
He is accused of second-degree murder in the beating death of
two-year-old Timothy Jackson. The toddler was rushed to hospital
late Friday night after a 9-1-1 call said he had drowned in a
bathtub. An autopsy revealed the boy had suffered severe head
injuries. Dunn was the boy's official guardian. 
<HR>

<H3>Regal Death </H3>

<P>
The name of a man found dead outside the Regal Hotel in downtown
Hamilton early yesterday has been released. 
<P>
Police say 25-year-old Christopher Paquet was laying on the sidewalk
below a window to his third floor room. Foul play is not suspect.
The police, however, are trying to determine Paquet's whereabouts
prior to his death. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First</H3>

<P>
It was a quiet day on Canadian financial markets because banks,
government offices, and markets in the United States were closed
for Memorial Day. 
<P>
Canadian share prices and our dollar strengthened slightly. 
<P>
More and more investors are getting their stock picks from the
Internet, but experts warn it might not be very reliable. 
<HR>

<H3>Truck Inspections </H3>

<P>
Transportation minister Al Palladini is cracking down on unsafe
trucks. Truck drivers and owners will face hefty fines and demerit
points for operating defective rigs. As Lauran Sabourin reports
inspection teams are out on the highways pulling over suspect
transports. 
<P>
<I>For the next two days truckers driving the QEW through Niagara
may be pulled over for a random inspection. Lights that don't
work. Tires that don't have enough tread. Defective brake lines.
Inspectors are looking for anything that may impair the operation
of vehicle. </I>
<P>
<I>At the spot check in Vineland this morning, thirty percent
of the trucks stopped had defects. At another check up the road
60 percent of trucks failed inspection. </I>
<P>
<I>OPP officers were ordering suspect transports in for inspection.
Everything was being looked at. Chains that weren't secure. Logs
that don't' add up. Truckers are being targeted for inspections
because of a series of fatal mishaps two years ago. It's hoped
that these random spot-checks will encourage truckers to more
diligent about safety.</I> 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

