<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/24/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, May 24, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Allergy Season 
<LI>Hamilton East 
<LI>Youth Threats 
<LI>Teen Extortion 
<LI>Stalker Charged 
<LI>St. Kitts Police 
<LI>Hamilton Rescue 
<LI>High School Hooky 
<LI>Commission Closes 
<LI>Scout Parade 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Allergy Season </H3>

<P>
Now that we've chalked up one of the longest winters in history,
get ready for one of the worst allergy seasons ever. 
<P>
Golden horseshoe allergists are warning hay fever sufferers to
shut their doors and windows and run for the medicine cabinet.
So if your eyes are watering and itchy, and your nose running,
and the sneezing is driving you crazy, it could be the trees and
plants playing catch up. They're releasing twice the normal amount
of pollen into the air while they do it. Jamie West reports. 
<P>
<I>For most of us the on-set of spring is a walk in the park yet
for others it can be blooming miserable. This year's allergy season
promises to be a bad one. </I>
<P>
<I>Allergic rhinitis or hay fever is a more prevalent chronic
disease, outranking even heart disease. And it appears that allergies
are on the rise, increasing 25 percent each decade. </I>
<P>
<I>Research shows that hay fever is responsible for half a million
lost work days in Canada and an equal number of missed school
days. And the use of over the counter nasal sprays for long periods
of time can do more harm than good. </I>
<P>
<I>And look on the bright side, the first frost is only about
5 months away.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton East </H3>

<P>
For the first time in two and a half years, Canadians appear to
be losing their confidence in prime minister Chretien. The PM's
approval rating has dropped to 47 percent, compared to 36 percent
who disapprove. Seventeen percent had no feeling one way or the
other. But, as Dwight Ryan reports, the true test of the liberals'
popularity comes on June 17th. 
<P>
<I>Prime minister Chretien says he doesn't work around polls,
he just does his job. He adds his government is doing reasonably
well. Still its the first time since 1993 that Chretien's approval
rating has fallen below fifty percent. </I>
<P>
<I>Sheila Copps gave up her post as deputy prime minister saying
she'd broken her promise on the GST. The Gallup poll results don't
phase her and many believe her return to parliament will be a
cake walk. </I>
<P>
<I>12 candidates will face Copps in the June vote. New democrat
Wayne Marston has lost to Copps before. This time he says its
a horse race. Hamilton East voters will determine who wins the
battle June 17th.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Youth Threats </H3>

<P>
Just yesterday we told you about a 14-year-old Oakville teen who
stands accused of murdering another 14-year-old and comes amid
reports of a general increase in crime among the young. Now word
that a 17-year-old Oakville youth has been convicted of phoning
bomb threats to the Atlantic City International Airport. 
<P>
The teen and a 16-year-old accomplice were charged after calls
to the busy New Jersey Airport were traced to pay phones in Oakville
last May. The calls were made just after the bombing of the federal
building in Oklahoma City that killed 168 people. One flight was
canceled because of the threats. 
<P>
The 16-year-old pleaded guilty last year and was sentenced to
four months in prison. The 17-year-old is to be sentenced July
13th. 
<HR>

<H3>Teen Extortion </H3>

<P>
In Simcoe two teenage girls are facing extortion charges. Haldimand-Norfolk
Region police say two victims were told that if they didn't give
the girls money, the teens would go to police and tell them they
had been sexually assaulted. 
<P>
The girls are aged 13 and 16. Police say one of the victims had
already made several payments. The accused, who can't be identified
because of their ages, go before a judge today for a bail hearing.

<HR>

<H3>Stalker Charged </H3>

<P>
And a 30-year-old Burlington man will appear in court next Wednesday,
after children were stalked on their way home from school. 
<P>
Halton Regional Police say they were followed by a man in a green
car last month. There were no attempts to abduct or harm the students.
Steven Andrew Dikens has been charged with five counts of criminal
harassment. 
<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Police </H3>

<P>
A crackdown on biker gangs and five murder investigations have
eaten up the entire overtime budget for the Niagara region police
force. The force set aside only 188-thousand dollars for overtime
this year -- about half of last year's total. 
<P>
The biker raids and subsequent investigations used up 70-thousand
dollars of the overtime kitty. The murder cases burned up the
rest. There was only one killing in Niagara last year. 
<HR>

<H3>Hamilton Rescue </H3>

<P>
It was an unusual rescue operation for some Hamilton firefighters.
An eight-year-old boy, stuck in a washing machine. 
<P>
Captain Wayne Hammond says the boy climbed into the machine last
night while his mother was doing laundry in their apartment building
and wrapped himself in a circle around the agitator. 
<P>
Hammond says it took a few minutes to get him out by &quot;helping
him bend the proper way.&quot; The boy was unhurt. 
<HR>

<H3>High School Hooky </H3>

<P>
And about 500 Hamilton high school students had a little explaining
to do. Half the students at Sir Allan MacNab High School played
hooky yesterday, skipping a day-long conference on multiculturalism
and anti-racism. 
<P>
Principal Trish Fulton says parents will be asked to explain the
students' absence. She says a number of parents did call to say
they didn't want their children attending a mandatory multicultural
conference. Fulton says it seems there's a backlash against racial
equity. 
<HR>

<H3>Commission Closes </H3>

<P>
Ontario's Human Rights Commission is closing five offices across
the province, including one in St. Catharines. The commission
also intends to freeze hiring and set up four 1-800 numbers across
Ontario to handle all complaints about discrimination and racism.

<P>
Offices will also be closing in Kitchener, Kenora, Sault Ste.
Marie and Toronto all to make up for a 700 thousand dollar funding
cut from the Tory government. 
<HR>

<H3>Scout Parade </H3>

<P>
If you're planning a trip to downtown Hamilton tomorrow be prepared
for gridlock around Main Street. About eight thousand boy and
girl scouts will flood the downtown for their 58th annual parade.

<P>
The group assembles at Victoria Park at 8:45 a.m., travels south
on Locke to Main and then past the reviewing stand at Hamilton
City Hall. 
<P>
Scouts Canada expects a record number of bands and floats. All
participants donate items to the good turn food drive. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

