<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/23/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, May 23, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman Verdict 2 
<LI>Burloak Murder Follow
<LI>Most Wanted 
<LI>Camper Burns 
<LI>Triplex Fire 
<LI>RPN's / Generics 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman Verdict 2 </H3>

<P>
Every day for the past month, they have driven from the tiny village
of Clifford, Ontario, to Hamilton, to hear testimony at the trial
of the man accused of killing one of their own. And today, the
friends and family of Joan Heimbecker wept and embraced each other,
as 25-year-old Rory Foreman was found guilty of first-degree murder.

<P>
Foreman himself showed no emotion as the jury delivered its verdict.
But he apologized to everyone in the courtroom for taking Joan's
life, and for the ordeal he put her friends and family through.
Deborah Walker reports.
<P>
<I>25-year-old Joan Heimbecker, a bright and beautiful McMaster
University graduate student, died of multiple gunshot wounds in
her university residence two years ago. Her ex-boyfriend, 25-year-old
Rory Foreman, remained impassive as the jury foreman rose and
pronounced him guilty of first-degree murder. </I>
<P>
<I>Before he was sentenced, Foreman apologized to Joan's parents
and sister. He told the court: &quot;it was a selfish, cruel and
cowardly act ... and I'm sorry for what I've done.&quot; &quot;I
guess it's true... you only hurt the ones you love.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Outside the court, Joan's room-mate, Nicki Hodges, said she
was relieved at the verdict, but unmoved by Foreman's apology.
During the trial, Nicki delivered a harrowing eyewitness account
of the night she watched Rory Foreman pump six shotgun blasts
at Joan Heimbecker. </I>
<P>
<I>It took the jury twelve hours to reach a verdict, although
many had expected a much quicker decision. Lawyers on both side
believe jurors struggled with the question of whether Foreman
really intended to kill Joan. Foreman's lawyer remains convinced
his client is not as evil as the deed he executed, and that Foreman
did not intend to kill Joan Heimbecker.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Burloak Murder Follow</H3>

<P>
And in Burlington today a 14 year old has been charged with the
first degree murder of another 14 year old. 
<P>
Police say it appears Lee Doherty was beaten to death with a blunt
object. His body was found yesterday in a wooded section of a
Burlington park. Kathy Renwald reports. 
<P>
<I>Friends of 14 year old Lee Doherty of Burlington made a tearful
visit looking for the place he was murdered. At the same time
at the Milton Courthouse another 14 year old Burlington boy faced
first degree murder charges in Doherty's death. </I>
<P>
<I>The shocking crime was the talk of the housing complex where
Lee Doherty lived. The park where Lee Doherty's body was found
is well known to kids in the housing complex. </I>
<P>
<I>16 year old Skip Tuck was a friend of Lee Doherty's.  He led
us to the place where kids party by the fire pit ..a few steps
away from where Doherty's beaten body was found in a cement culvert.
</I>
<P>
<I>Across from where the victim and his father lived.. neighbours
gathered. </I>
<P>
<I>The 14 year old charged with first degree murder was remanded
until May 29th.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Most Wanted </H3>

<P>
Crime Stoppers in Hamilton- Wentworth is looking for a man wanted
for breaching conditions of his parole. 
<P>
27-year-old David Gillan was serving time for 24 counts of break
and enter charges and was released in December. Gillan is 6-feet
tall, weighs about 200 pounds, with short brown hair, hazel eyes
and a pale complexion. 
<P>
If you have any information or have seen this man, you are asked
to call police or Crime Stoppers. 
<HR>

<H3>Camper Burns </H3>

<P>
Residents of a St. Catharines neighbourhood fled their homes last
night as police tried to negotiate with a man who wanted to set
fire to a camper trailer, parked beside a house. 
<P>
At one point, the man turned on a propane cylinder, filling the
camper with gas. It exploded, throwing him out of the trailer.
He's being treated in Hamilton for serious burns to his arms and
legs. 
<P>
The Ontario fire Marshall's office is investigating the incident.

<HR>

<H3>Triplex Fire </H3>

<P>
And another St. Catharines man is in the burn unit at Hamilton
General Hospital after fire broke out in a triplex early this
morning. 
<P>
23 year old Ted Marks suffered serious burns to much of his body,
and cuts after smashing through a back window to safety. His 21
year old roommate managed to escape without injury. 
<P>
Niagara Regional Police were called in after firefighters found
80 marijuana plants in an upper apartment. Investigators are still
trying to figure out what sparked the fire, which caused 57-thousand
dollars in damage. 
<HR>

<H3>RPN's / Generics </H3>

<P>
Unregulated assistive personnel,... clinical associates,... patient
care &quot;partners...&quot; they all mean the same thing. ...generic
health care workers that will replace some skilled registered
nurses in hospitals all over Hamilton Wentworth. they're coming
to save money, but not everyone welcomes them, as we hear from
Jamie West... 
<P>
<I>That's how many nurses feel about being teamed up with unskilled
underlings, who will be paid about a third of what nurses earn.
</I>
<P>
<I>Generic workers will be trained intensively for about 8 weeks,
in very specific duties... nurses complain that having to manage
generics will take them away from the bedside too often and could
cause them to miss the subtle signs of a patient who may be close
to crisis. </I>
<P>
<I>Hospital managers think the opposite will happen.. another
sore spot with RN's is the fear of being laid off and then being
hired back as a generic worker for a lot less money.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
The Canadian dollar lost a bit of value today along with stocks
as Canadian government bonds fell. 
<P>
Some retail analysts say toy prices could drop because of a US
government investigation into alleged price fixing by Toys &quot;r&quot;
Us. 
<P>
A new forecast suggests house construction in Canada will increase
this year. 
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

