<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/22/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Wednesday, May 22, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman Verdict? 
<LI>Hospitals Update 
<LI>Highway Six Stats 
<LI>Grand Flooding 
<LI>Tornado Update 
<LI>Bedtime Birdies 
<LI>Kitchen Garden 
<LI>Shaw - Niagara 
<LI>Trike a Thon 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman Verdict? </H3>

<P>
Did he intend to kill Joan Heimbecker or was it unplanned and
in the heat of passion? The jury is still out in the Rory Foreman
murder trial. they retired to reach a verdict late this morning.

<HR>

<H3>Hospitals Update </H3>

<P>
Hamilton's future health care system is also on trial right now.

<P>
Forget the Health Action Task Force report and adopt the Academic
Health Care Network report ... that sentiment is growing in Hamilton
less than a week before the District Health Council sends its
final recommendations for healthcare reform to Queen's Park. 
<P>
Doctor's and CEO's have been lobbying council members and as Jamie
West reports...., now the business community is jumping on board
as well... 
<P>
<I>A full page add appearing in the first section of the Hamilton
Spectator boldly shouts out ...Hamilton Wentworth deserves better.
It's referring to healthcare reform. and is signed by over 150
business and community leaders. While one section over an ad appears
seeking a C.E.O. for a merged Hamilton Civics and Chedoke McMaster
hospital. </I>
<P>
<I>Healthcare reform has been a hot topic for months but now the
community led by well known philanthropist Morgan Firestone is
stepping forward...they say the only report worth considering
is the one drafted by the Academic Health Care Network, one that
keeps all of Hamilton's hospitals open while still meeting the
fiscal goals of a reduced provincial healthcare budget. </I>
<P>
<I>The Health Action Task Force reports calls for the closure
of one unspecified acute care hospital. That move would leave
Hamilton with 16 percent less acute care funding than Toronto...14
percent less than London... even though Hamiltonians would be
taxed just as much. </I>
<P>
<I>Hamilton Wentworth regional council last night passed a resolution
to endorse the C.E.O.' s report and it's amendments to keep the
Henderson's ER open and provide adequate beds for cancer patients.
</I>
<P>
<I>The District Health Council will vote Monday on whether to
accept the Health Action Task Force recommendations, the Academic
Health Care Network report or a combination of both.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Highway Six Stats </H3>

<P>
Forget about calling highway six the killer highway. An OPP officer
says it's no more dangerous than any other highway. 
<P>
Instead, constable Glenn Bell says driver error is to blame for
nearly all of the crashes on highway 6. His comment comes after
another fatal crash, the sixth death this year, on the stretch
between highways 401 and 403. 
<HR>

<H3>Grand Flooding </H3>

<P>
Police and conservation officials say no fishing no canoeing...in
fact don't go near the grand river or its waterways right now.

<P>
A flood warning remains in effect for areas along the river, from
Kitchener right through to Lake Erie. Recent storms have elevated
water levels. Some flooding is expected in some of the low-lying
areas near the river which is expected to crest in and around
Caledonia tonight, Dunnville tomorrow. 
<HR>

<H3>Tornado Update </H3>

<P>
Power is still out in parts of Nanticoke after Monday's severe
storm. The worst hit area is an industrial park. Ontario Hydro
says it may be Friday before power is restored to all the plants
in the area. 
<P>
Meanwhile, Environment Canada officials are still trying to determine
whether it was a tornado that touched down in east Hamilton Monday
night. Officials say the damage may have been caused by a downburst
of strong winds which descend from a thunderstorm and spread across
an area. 
<P>
Dumpsters by the dozens are being filled as cleanup and repairs
continue to a number of homes and businesses struck by the Victoria
Day storm. 
<HR>

<H3>Bedtime Birdies </H3>

<P>
Even inside every storm cloud there's a silver lining...at least
for a pair of baby birds in Dundas. Their whose home was blown
from a backyard birch tree and they appeared to be abandoned and
destined for certain death, from starvation. But a quick thinking
good Samaritan moved their nest ...next to that of another robin
in the neighbourhood. Her maternal instincts took over and now
her newly adopted babies, are doing fine. 
<HR>

<H3>Kitchen Garden </H3>

<P>
By now, most of us have been out dabbling in the dirt, trying
to create a piece of garden magic. But imagine trying to recreate
a piece of history. That's what members of the Garden Club of
Hamilton are doing at Dundurn Castle. Annette Hamm explains. 
<P>
<I>Now that the outside of Hamilton's Dundurn Castle is restored,
work has started to put the former home of Sir Allan MacNab in
a proper setting. Two ornamental gardens on the north lawn of
the castle mimic what might have grown there decades ago. MacNab
was a garden enthusiast; one of the first people he hired upon
building the home was a master gardener from Scotland. </I>
<P>
<I>Now volunteers from the Garden Club of Hamilton carry on the
work, under the guidance of Dr. Leslie Laking, a former director
of the Royal Botanical Gardens. He drew up the plans for the ornamental
beds and for this miniature version of MacNab's kitchen garden.
The original filled an acre and a half ... this one will supply
the castle with dried flowers for winter arrangements, and vegetables
for their kitchen program. </I>
<P>
<I>The plants were started back in February at the Gage Park greenhouses,
from historical seeds purchased in Pennsylvania. Eventually, the
grounds will feature more of the plants enjoyed during a gardening
boom one hundred and 40 years ago. </I>
<P>
<I>The gardens will be weeded and watered over the summer by junior
volunteers at Dundurn Castle.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Shaw - Niagara </H3>

<P>
Tonight is the grand opening of the Shaw Festival's 1996 season.
Every summer the Shaw brings about 300 thousand theatre goers
to historic Niagara-on-the -Lake. And as Lauran Sabourin reports
they leave about 70 million dollars behind after the final curtain.

<P>
<I>Some last minute housecleaning in the old town before the grand
opening. Local hotels are booked. Lunch hour at the Prince of
Wales greenhouse dining room was busy. </I>
<P>
<I>There are three theatres at Shaw. . combined they put on 733
performances each year. The Shaw not only lures tourists who want
to spend money, it's also the largest single employer in the town.
</I>
<HR>

<H3>Trike a Thon </H3>

<P>
And finally tonight we bet there are a lot of tired little ones
from St. Marks pre-school in Dundas. This after they spent the
day wheeling their way around their pre school to raise money
for Ronald McDonald House. 
<P>
This is the sixth year for their trike-a-thon, and with a rough
estimate including today's total they've raised about 85-hundred
dollars to date. The money will be used to provide a comfortable
place to stay for families of sick children. 
<P>
