<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/21/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Tuesday, May 21, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Tornado Follow
<LI>Foreman Summations 
<LI>Stabbing 
<LI>Kempling Obit 
<LI>Taro-Council 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Debit Card 
<LI>Waterdown Fireworks 
<LI>Red Cross Appeal 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Tornado Follow</H3>

<P>
Was it or wasn't it.... a tornado that is. Which ever the case...
mother nature's fury has left a path of destruction and debris
spread across a wide area of southern Ontario. And she even included
a touch of irony when those watching the movie &quot;Twister&quot;
at a drive-in watched in disbelief as the screen was sucked away
before their very eyes. 
<P>
The violent storms that whipped through the region in less than
an hour last night, left many unprepared and today those who were
hit with the blast were calculating the cost of damage, counting
their blessings and cleaning up.. Jamie West reports... 
<P>
<I>City cleanup crews from Hamilton down through Niagara spent
the day restoring the aesthetics of normally quiet neighborhoods.
Evidence of a tornado...maybe, or maybe not. </I>
<P>
<I>Environment Canada says storms like this one can generate winds
just as damaging as a tornado...in this case, officials say winds
easily topped 115 kilometres an hour, and ironically ripped apart
a drive in movie screen in Thorold that was due to show the hit
movie &quot;Twister&quot;. </I>
<P>
<I>Charles Harbon was shocked to see three of his maple trees
topple over into his young neighbor's yard ...he's grateful no
one was hurt. His neighbors are assessing the damage. </I>
<P>
<I>According to Environment Canada, Hamilton sits right on the
edge of a southwestern Ontario tornado belt that has about 25
twister sightings every year. The average is about 85 sightings
across Canada. </I>
<P>
<I>Shelly Dugas's car window blew apart as she drove right into
the storm. South of Hamilton in rural areas... barn's selected
by the storm looked like they'd been bombed. This chicken farm
in Grassie is salvaging live birds after nearly 8000 perished
in the fury.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Foreman Summations </H3>

<P>
The defence calls it a crime of passion, unintentional, unplanned,
and committed while the accused was in a blind rage. But prosecutors
say Rory Foreman was concentrating, and counting when he pumped
six shotgun blasts at his ex-girlfriend, a McMaster University
graduate student. 
<P>
At the outset of his trial in Hamilton, Foreman pleaded guilty
to manslaughter. But the crown insists he's guilty of first-degree
murder. Today, jurors heard closing arguments from both sides.
and tomorrow, they'll begin deliberating their verdict. Deborah
Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Defence lawyer Peter Bawden approached the jury with a warning.
He said: &quot;However distasteful you may find Rory Foreman,
and however much you may hate him... it cannot be proven that
he intended to kill Joan Heimbecker.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Bawden says at some point, everybody has felt a rage so great
that they lost control of themselves, and said or did something
they never intended to do. Bawden says that's what happened to
Rory Foreman the night of March 30th, 1994, when Joan Heimbecker
rebuffed his attempts at a reconciliation. Bawden says for Foreman,
it was a crisis of confidence, as he lost not just a girlfriend,
but a way of life he aspired to. </I>
<P>
<I>Bawden says Foreman never intended, or planned to kill Joan.
He asked the jury: &quot;If you were stupid enough to plan to
kill someone in their own apartment with witnesses present, do
you suppose you'd waste ten to fifteen minutes terrorizing her
when you could just get the job done and get out?&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>But assistant crown attorney Alexandra Paparella insists Foreman
did have a plan when he packed two duffel bags, gifts for Joan,
and a loaded shotgun in the rented car he drove to McMaster University.
Paparella says the plan was a simple one. &quot;She was going
to take him back, or die.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>And Paparella says the very fact Joan's room-mate watched Foreman
fire six shotgun blasts at her friend, is proof he knew what he
was doing. Paparella says Foreman... &quot;chose not to shoot
Nicki Hodges. The reason he did not is that he was in control,
concentrating his actions on Joan Heimbecker.... his every movement
was deliberate and calculated...&quot; requiring fifteen separate
actions to fire five more rounds after the first shot missed.
</I>
<P>
<I>Defence lawyer Peter Bawden suggested if someone intends to
kill, they must have a reason to kill. Bawden says Foreman didn't
attain a single thing by killing Joan Heimbecker. But Alexandra
Paparella told the jury Foreman's objective was simple. She said:
&quot;Joan Heimbecker was a beautiful, attractive, very intelligent,
outgoing woman with lots of friends. She was as close to perfect
as Rory Foreman was going to get. On the other hand, Rory Foreman
was a possessive, controlling man. And if he couldn't have her,
no one would.&quot;</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Stabbing </H3>

<P>
Hamilton police have laid charges against a 30 year old man after
a 36 year old woman was stabbed in a Wellington Street North apartment
building elevator. She was taken to hospital for treatment. her
wounds are not serious.
<HR>

<H3>Kempling Obit </H3>

<P>
The man who represented Burlington in the house of commons for
21 years died yesterday. Bill Kempling was 76. 
<P>
He was first elected as a Progressive Conservative in 1972, leaving
politics in 1993. 
<P>
Bill Kempling is resting at Dodsworth and Brown Funeral Home in
Burlington. Funeral services will be conducted at St. Paul's United
Church in Dundas Friday afternoon. 
<HR>

<H3>Taro-Council </H3>

<P>
Four members of Stoney Creek city council have stated their opposition
to the proposed Taro landfill site. 
<P>
Councilors Georgina Beattie, Doug Conley, Paul Miller and deputy
mayor Grant Shaw have requested the environment minister refer
the east quarry plan to the Environmental Assessment Board for
a full hearing. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Canadian stock prices soared to new record highs again today.
However the dollar weakened, falling below 73 cents US. 
<P>
These latest developments stem from today's policy committee meeting
of the American Central Bank which decided not to change US interest
rates. That is leading to speculation that Canadian interest rates
could drop further. 
<HR>

<H3>Debit Card </H3>

<P>
New statistics show the popularity of debit cards is skyrocketing
in Canada. As more consumers use them, more merchants are offering
the direct payment service. 
<P>
The use of Interac direct payment almost doubled in the first
quarter of 1996 to 130 million transactions. 
<HR>

<H3>Waterdown Fireworks </H3>

<P>
Bad weather put a damper on Victoria Day celebrations in Waterdown
last night. So the Optimist Club of Waterdown has rescheduled
their fireworks display for this evening. 
<P>
The show begins at dusk at Memorial Park in Waterdown. The Optimist
Club tells us the carnival will also be set up again tonight.

<HR>

<H3>Red Cross Appeal </H3>

<P>
Well after the long weekend, blood banks are getting dangerously
low. 
<P>
Aside from the permanent clinic on King Street, the Hamilton Red
Cross has scheduled two mobile clinics tomorrow at the Grimsby
Senior Citizen's Centre from 1:30 to 8 PM and Thursday at the
Dundas Community Centre from 2 to 8. 
<P>
They're especially low in &quot;o rh+&quot;, &quot;o rh-&quot;
and &quot;b rh-&quot;. 
<P>
