<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/20/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Monday, May 20, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Victoria Day 
<LI>Fireworks Fire 
<LI>St. Kitts Storm 
<LI>York/403 Mishap 
<LI>Gypsy Arrest 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Turmel Runs 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Victoria Day </H3>

<P>
A day once simply known as &quot;firecracker day&quot;. May 24th
is the birthday of the long-reigning Queen Victoria ...a monarch
who became identified with an era. 
<P>
For convenience, the holiday has been moved to the third Monday
in May, and as Alex Reynolds reports, we are involved in a wide
variety of activities. 
<P>
<I>It isn't necessarily a do-nothing day. As the first long-weekend
of the young summer, people were very active....cottage opening
time ....planting the garden...opening the swimming pool ...yard
cleanup ...and purchasing fireworks. </I>
<P>
<I>As well as stores, the tightly regulated pyro materials were
on sale in large trailers favored by service clubs. </I>
<P>
<I>The area's major organized fireworks display was postponed.
Scheduled for Dundas Driving Park, officials feared the soggy
ground would have turned into a muddy quagmire with the thousands
expected to attend. Canada Day or the Cactus Festival is an alternative
consideration. Weather permitting, a pyrotechnics display was
listed for Memorial Park in Waterdown. </I>
<P>
<I>Gardening and sprucing up the property is top-of-the-agenda
on Victoria Day weekend, particularly this year. </I>
<P>
<I>For refreshment, most had stocked up, as government outlets
are closed, but one suds store was doing business on this holiday.
</I>
<P>
<I>It's been a full weekend, good and bad weather, much to do...but
as always, Victoria Day signals the start of &quot;the good ol'
summertime.&quot;</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Fireworks Fire </H3>

<P>
Fireworks sparked a fire in a Hamilton apartment building last
night. 
<P>
Two girls, aged 13 and 16, had ignited sparklers in the Oxford
Street apartment. Assuming they were fully extinguished, the youngsters
went out to the balcony, later to discover a major blaze had started
inside. 
<P>
Damage is estimated at sixty thousand dollars. There were no injuries.

<HR>

<H3>St. Kitts Storm </H3>

<P>
Mother Nature provided her own fireworks on this Victoria Day
holiday. Violent thunderstorms rolled across the province this
weekend. Lighting strikes knocked power in St. Catharines this
morning. Lauran Sabourin has more. 
<P>
<I>St. Catharines Hydro crews were working overtime today. Just
after seven this morning lighting struck a power line on Glendale
Avenue and knocked out electricity to the south end of the city.</I>
<P>
<I>Fortunately this was a holiday: traffic signals weren't functioning.
Crews had the power restored to the neighborhoods within four
hours.</I> 
<P>
Meanwhile, residents in east Hamilton were coping with sporadic
power outages this morning as well. Lightning from the storm hit
transformers around the Mount Albion Road area and power was off
for about two hours.
<HR>

<H3>York/403 Mishap</H3>

<P>
Believe it or not, no one was seriously injured this afternoon
when a car spun out of control and flipped on Highway 403 near
York Boulevard in Hamilton. 
<P>
The car landed on its roof... and two occupants were rushed to
hospital with non-life threatening injuries. Provincial police
are investigating. No word on why the driver may have lost control.

<HR>

<H3>Gypsy Arrest </H3>

<P>
Last week we told you about how tourists are being targeted by
professional pickpockets in Niagara Falls. This afternoon police
arrested two women and a man believed to be involved in a pick-pocketing
ring. 
<P>
The suspects were apprehended near the Brock Hotel. Police say
professional thieves are so good at what they do they can steal
a wallet out of a bag before the tourist is even aware that they've
been victimized. 
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Banks, government offices, and financial markets were closed in
Canada for Victoria Day. 
<P>
In New York, the value of stocks roared to new record highs as
American interest rates look like they are not increasing right
now. 
<P>
Iraq and the United Nations signed a deal to allow Iraq to sell
oil to the rest of the world again. 
<HR>

<H3>Turmel Runs </H3>

<P>
A couple of parachute fringe candidates in the Hamilton East federal
by- election filed nomination papers today. 
<P>
One of them is John &quot;the engineer&quot; Turmel ... a man
who has made a second career out of running for public office.
This will be his forty-first independent candidacy... and he's
seeking his place in the Guinness Book of World Records for that
milestone. 
<P>
The other is Charles Olito... a Woodville man contesting the race
on behalf of the Canada Party. Both candidates advocate different
brands of monetary and fiscal reform. 
<P>
