<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/17/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Friday, May 17, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman Legal 
<LI>Bar Fight 
<LI>Donut Fight 
<LI>Stolen Van 
<LI>School Theft 
<LI>Heat On Crime 
<LI>Reform Taro 
<LI>Academic Health 
<LI>Business First 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman Legal</H3>

<P>
A jury is expected to begin deliberating the fate of 25-year-old
Rory Foreman next Wednesday. Foreman is on trial in Hamilton for
the first-degree murder of his ex-girlfriend, a McMaster University
graduate student. 
<P>
Today, the judge informed the jury lawyers have now finished presenting
their evidence. And as Deborah Walker reports, the judge also
gave jurors a warning about testimony they heard yesterday. 
<P>
<I>At the outset of his trial, Rory Foreman pleaded guilty to
manslaughter, admitting he killed Joan Heimbecker by shooting
her repeatedly with a shotgun in her McMaster University residence.
But the crown rejected the plea, and the defence claim that the
shooting was unintentional. </I>
<P>
<I>Instead, prosecutors elected to proceed with a first-degree
murder case against Rory Foreman. The seven-man, five-woman jury
heard three weeks of testimony, including an eyewitness account
from Joan Heimbecker's room-mate, who watched Foreman fire six
shotgun blasts at her friend. Four of them hit Joan. Jurors also
watched graphic autopsy photographs projected onto a large screen,
and listened to Foreman himself for a day-and-a-half, as he took
the witness stand in his own defence. </I>
<P>
<I>This morning, mister justice Paul Philip called jurors into
the courtroom to issue a warning about a defence witness who testified
yesterday. During cross-examination by assistant crown attorney
Alexandra Paparella, the witness said his friend Foreman could
not obtain a firearms acquisition certificate, because he would
need a clean record. Today, justice Philip told the jury Rory
Foreman pleaded guilty to a minor criminal offense in 1993, and
was granted a conditional discharge, which is not the same as
a criminal conviction, and does not result in a criminal record.
</I>
<P>
<I>The judge warned the jury: &quot;this is the only occasion
mister Foreman has been before the courts prior to this case,
and you must ignore the comment made by the witness during your
deliberations.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>Before sending them home for the long weekend, justice Philip
told the jurors all the evidence is now in. They will hear closing
arguments from defence and crown lawyers on Tuesday, followed
by legal instructions from the judge. And sometime on Wednesday,
the jurors will retire to consider their verdict.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Bar Fight </H3>

<P>
Two men have been treated in hospital after an early morning bar-room
brawl at the Embassy Club in downtown Hamilton. 
<P>
One needed 10 stitches on his face, the other suffered bruises
to his face and upper body. The pair say they were assaulted by
four or five other men who punched, kicked and hit them with beer
bottles. Police are still investigating. 
<HR>

<H3>Donut Fight </H3>

<P>
Police also looking for a suspect after a slashing in a donut
shop parking lot. A patrol sergeant noticed two men fighting at
a downtown Hamilton Tim Horton's, then saw one of them take off
in a white van. The other man needed 16 stitches to his forehead
from a knife wound. 
<HR>

<H3>Stolen Van </H3>

<P>
A rough ride for two suspects after police tried to pull them
over early this morning in Hamilton for erratic driving. They
sped away, and ended up snapping the front axle of their van when
they tried to turn a corner too quickly. 
<P>
An 18 year old passenger was found hiding in the parking garage
at St. Joseph's Hospital. He's been charged with breach of probation.
The 17 year old driver, found hiding behind a nearby house, faces
charges of dangerous driving and theft over 5-thousand dollars.

<HR>

<H3>School Theft </H3>

<P>
A 15 year old has been charged after a break in at Lincoln Alexander
School on Hamilton mountain. 
<P>
After an alarm, police arrived to find a window smashed and teenager
running from the building. They found him hiding behind a nearby
car with some audio visual equipment. the teen has been charged
with break, enter and theft. 
<HR>

<H3>Heat on Crime </H3>

<P>
Hamilton Wentworth Regional Police together with community partners
are putting the heat on crime. 
<P>
A new initiative was unveiled today to deal with the ever-growing
problem of youth crime and crimes identified with diminishing
the community's quality of life. Things like auto theft, property
theft, vandalism and abuse of the elderly. 
<P>
Three teams of eight officers have been deployed as &quot;divisional
action teams.&quot; Those teams will target specific problems
identified as priorities by the local community. Early results
already show a decrease in car thefts by more than forty percent....

<HR>

<H3>Reform Taro </H3>

<P>
Today is the deadline for public review into the hotly debated
proposal for a Stoney Creek landfill site. It's now up to Ontario
environment minister Brenda Elliot to determine whether or not
a hearing should be called. 
<P>
Taro, owned by Philip Environmental, wants to open a landfill
for non-hazardous industrial waste. The Hamilton Region Conservation
Authority and two citizens groups have requested a hearing under
the Environmental Assessment Act. 
<P>
The Taro proposal has also become a political issue in Ottawa.
It was brought up in the House of Commons this afternoon. 
<HR>

<H3>Academic Health </H3>

<P>
The latest... and maybe the last... volume in the ever- expanding
series on the future of health care in Hamilton was unveiled today.
It breathes new life into Henderson hospital while staying within
tough new provincial spending guidelines. Anthony Pooley reports.

<P>
<I>This is not something one sees every day... or any day for
that matter. Politicians of all stripes gathering at the same
table... and actually agreeing on a plan of action... tight fisted
Tories and free spending socialists of the same mind. </I>
<P>
<I>And on those minds is a plan to keep all of Hamilton's hospitals
open and functioning, within tight fiscal guidelines' with a proposal
hammered out this morning that would see Henderson Hospital operate
a full-fledged emergency facility and 163 acute care beds. </I>
<P>
<I>All here... and some who aren't... are pushing the amended
plan of the Academic Health Care Network... a collaboration among
all of Hamilton's hospitals as well as Mac Health Sciences and
the Victorian Order of Nurses. </I>
<P>
<I>And they're hoping all of that goes a long way toward convincing
the District Health Council to accept the plan. All of this is
understandably confusing... there seems to be a new vision of
the future of health care in Hamilton almost every week. But if
this latest chapter in what is becoming a very large book is accepted,
all of Hamilton's hospitals will remain open and functioning...
with Henderson and St. Joe's off the critical list. </I>
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Prospects of lower Canadian interest rates injected another dose
of confidence into financial markets today. 
<P>
Stocks in Toronto rose to new record highs for the 27th time this
year. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar is stable while interest rates in bond markets
moved lower. 
<P>
