<TITLE>First Edition News: 05/16/96</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../../images/bkgd.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="../../../images/feicon.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>On-Line Archive</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>Thursday, May 16, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=585 HEIGHT=30 SRC="../../../images/bar.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>Foreman Cross 
<LI>Attempt Murder - Biker 
<LI>Thief Nabbed 
<LI>Home Invasion 
<LI>Riel Leg Irons 
<LI>Youth Crime 
<LI>Business First 
<LI>Lions Market 
</UL>

<HR>

<H3>Foreman Cross </H3>

<P>
An assistant crown attorney today ridiculed Rory Foreman's claim
that he did not intend to kill his ex-girlfriend, even though
he pumped four shotgun blasts into her body. 
<P>
25-year-old Joan Heimbecker, a McMaster University graduate student,
died March 30th, 1994 in her university residence. 
<P>
Foreman, who's now twenty-five, is on trial in Hamilton for first-degree
murder. Deborah Walker reports. 
<P>
<I>Rory Foreman testified yesterday that the first shot he fired
missed Joan Heimbecker, and after that, he lost control and kept
firing, but never intended to kill his ex-girlfriend. </I>
<P>
<I>But under cross- examination, assistant crown attorney Alexandra
Papparella reminded Foreman of what was physically required for
him to fire five more shots. Paparella said: &quot;eject, load,
fire. eject, load, fire. Fifteen movements. Fifteen deliberate
actions to fire off five more rounds. Do you agree to that?&quot;
&quot;Yes I do&quot; answered Foreman. </I>
<P>
<I>Paparella also wanted to know how Foreman could remember what
position Joan Heimbecker was in when he shot her, if he didn't
intend shoot her. Foreman answered: &quot;there was no intent.
I was caught up...out of control...I snapped...I kept firing...
I can just see it in my mind that's all. Everybody's been angry.
It happens.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>When Foreman repeated he was just out of control, Paparella
retorted: &quot;not so out of control sir that you didn't know
when you had fired the last shot.&quot; Because the sixth shell
was never ejected from the shotgun, Paparella suggested: &quot;you
knew you had six rounds. You fired off six rounds, and there was
no reason to eject the sixth shell because you knew you were out
of ammunition.&quot; </I>
<P>
<I>During the afternoon, the defence called Foreman's friends,
who said he lived in poverty in the slums of Kitchener. His first
girlfriend, testified Foreman threatened to kill himself when
she ended their relationship. </I>
<P>
<I>An acquaintance says Foreman called her twice in the hours
before Joan Heimbecker died. She was under the impression he wanted
to go out with her that evening.</I> 
<HR>

<H3>Attempt Murder - Biker </H3>

<P>
An Outlaws motorcycle gang member in St. Catharines has been charged
with attempt murder. 
<P>
Thirty nine year old Thomas Rae Culliton was arrested yesterday
morning as he was exiting a car wash in Welland. 
<P>
The charges relate to an incident last January where a 24 year
old woman was shot in the neck at the home of another Outlaws
gang member Jay Deming. Deming's house was torched two weeks ago,
a day after police announced their crackdown on bikers in the
peninsula. 
<HR>

<H3>Thief Nabbed </H3>

<P>
An elderly couple surprised an intruder in their Hamilton mountain
home yesterday afternoon when they returned to find a man in their
hallway. They tried to nab the man, but he ran out of the house,
carrying a bag. 
<P>
Police caught up with suspect, and recovered a jewelry box belonging
to the couple. Investigators are trying to see if this break and
enter is connected to two similar entries in the area just moments
before. 
<P>
22 year old Louis Joseph Roy of no fixed address is charged with
break and enter, and theft. 
<HR>

<H3>Home Invasion </H3>

<P>
And police are still investigating a home intrusion last night,
in east Hamilton. 
<P>
A man says he was knocked to ground and kicked repeatedly after
opening his apartment door to three masked suspects. A number
of electronic and clothing items were reported stolen. 
<HR>

<H3>Riel Leg Irons </H3>

<P>
A piece of Canadian history is back in the hands of Hamilton Wentworth
Regional Police. 
<P>
Last October at the Rockton Fair, these leg irons, which Louis
Riel wore to the gallows back in the 1880's, were stolen from
a police museum trailer. And yesterday, detectives found them
were they were least expecting them. 
<P>
The historic leg irons are just a small part of the haul police
took in from that raid yesterday. They seized several weapons
from a shed in Hamilton's east end, and from the house in Ancaster
where the irons were found. 15-hundred marijuana plants were also
seized from a hydroponic lab in Flamborough. 
<P>
49 year old Paul Gravelle of Ancaster and 52 year old Stan Jones
of Hamilton face several drug and weapons charges. 67 year old
Donald Hartin of Flamborough also faces drug charges. 
<HR>

<H3>Youth Crime </H3>

<P>
Meanwhile, critics of the Young Offenders Act have more ammunition
to press for changes. 
<P>
A police report says more than four of every 10 people charged
with robbery in metro Toronto last year were between 12 and 17
years old. The Globe and Mail says the statistics will be published
in a report next month. It says that's a big reversal from 1985,
when juveniles accounted for just 21 per cent of robbery suspects.

<P>
And the police figures show it's not a blip. They show a steady
shift toward younger perpetrators of certain types of crime, especially
theft with violence or a threat of violence. The report says the
figures are worrisome because they buck a trend toward lower overall
crime rates.
<HR>

<H3>Business First </H3>

<P>
Rising Canadian stock prices took a breath today, falling in value
for the first time in six days. 
<P>
The Canadian dollar and interest rates remained stable. 
<P>
Inflation in Canada during April was unchanged from March. 
<HR>

<H3>Lions Market </H3>

<P>
A new farmers market has cropped up in Stoney Creek. 
<P>
The town's Lions Club has renovated Stoney Creek's old post office
building to make way for fresh produce and other products. Vendors
are also set up in outdoor stalls in the municipal parking lot
beside the building. 
<P>
The Stoney Creek Lions Farmers Market officially opened today
and will be open for business every Thursday and Saturday from
8 am to 5 PM. 
<P>
